<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NO TIME FOR UCLA TO BACK DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ ``This year the Final Four, at least,'' the UCLA
basketball player said, ``and next year, the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   If only it were a quote from the 15th-ranked Bruins' press
conference Wednesday at the RCA Dome. In fact, that was freshman
JaRon Rush speaking in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of their NCAA Tournament opener today against
Detroit, the Bruins had nothing more brazen to say than this, from
sophomore Baron Davis: ``It's no time for babies. You've got to be
a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush, an integral part of the YOUNGEST TEAM IN SCHOOL HISTORY _
surely it bears emphasizing or why would head coach Steve Lavin
have mentioned it four times in a 15-minute session with reporters?
_ has backed off his earlier bravado.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the courage of one's convictions. ``We're just
trying to come out and play hard,'' he said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   That rustling sound you just heard was the 11 NCAA championship
banners shuddering.
</P>
<P>
   After 22 wins and a regular season ensconced in the top 20, the
Bruins, Lavin would have you believe, are in trouble. They're young
and wounded and going up against ``the most dangerous team in the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Detroit and Duke do sound sort of the same.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, more than patience and an extra pass or 10, what
the Bruins need to get by a very good Titans team is courage. We're
not talking about the kind of courage that pushes a player out the
door of his home for a school thousands of miles away or propels
him to stay on an airplane after a white-knuckle flight.
</P>
<P>
   The bravery of which we speak is only indirectly about hurling
one's body in the path of an opponent slashing into the paint or
diving for every loose ball or shaking off a throbbing big toe, an
ornery hip, an aching back, tender arches.
</P>
<P>
   The courage the Bruins have got to muster is all about boxing
out one's fears of failing, of falling short of the
banner-in-the-sky expectations that come with the jersey. It's
about swatting away every last excuse and absorbing Detroit's best
charge and getting knocked down but not out.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, UCLA would be better equipped for battle if Ray Young
(bruised hip), Davis (bruised right toe) and Jerome Moiso
(tendinitis in his arches) were pain-free and Dan Gadzuric hadn't
been lost for the season with an injury to his knee.
</P>
<P>
   That said, neither injuries nor indisposition should factor into
today's final score. The Bruins ought to beat Detroit because they
are U-C-L-A and in this combat zone that's a badge of honor, to be
proudly worn and roundly defended.
</P>
<P>
   Excuses are the last thing you'd expect to be lobbed like
grenades by a program that won its last national championship just
four years ago, boasts the second-best overall winning percentage
in the NCAA Tournament behind Duke and has more NCAA appearances
(35) than the 34-year-old Lavin has had birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   And yet there Lavin sat on Wednesday, emphasizing UCLA's
inexperience and playing up its injuries. He spun things until it
got dizzying. Does he really expect us to believe it is a small
miracle the Bruins got even this far?
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point in the season,'' Lavin said with a straight face,
``I didn't even think we'd be in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and did you know that the Bruins are the youngest team in
the history of the school?
</P>
<P>
   Detroit coach Perry Watson could tell Lavin a thing or two about
young teams. After all, one of his high school players, Jalen Rose,
was among the five freshmen who led Michigan to the NCAA title in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Inexperience doesn't have to be a team's undoing and neither do
injuries (see this year's Stanford squad). It does the players a
disservice to fashion either one into a crutch because then what's
to keep them from limping?
</P>
<P>
   Pride, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   UCLA senior Brandon Loyd has made one fewer NCAA Tournament
appearance than Detroit. You'd think the mere fact the Titans are
being widely hailed as the 12th seed most likely to succeed in this
year's tournament would have the blue-blood Bruins royally peeved.
</P>
<P>
   And yet on Wednesday the players seemed OK with being the
underdog. They sure didn't act like pit bulls who have been
provoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're the underdog, we play a whole lot better,'' Davis
said. ``People are writing us off now so we have something to
prove.''
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it, the Bruins' real crisis in a nutshell.
It's not injuries, it's not youth. It's that they are driven more
by other peoples' low expectations of them than their own lofty
intentions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
