<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARKANSASS-NCAA-WEST-TEX </SLUG>
 
Razorbacks finally have right side up 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Never one to sit idle or silent during a crisis,
Arkansas coach Nolan Richardson felt the 1998-99 basketball season
slipping away from him.
</P>
<P>
   So he responded with a fiery pep talk to energize his team. When
that failed, Richardson opted for the unconventional route.
</P>
<P>
   He benched Pat Bradley, his leading scorer, for three games. He
sat down Kareem Reid, his playmaker and floor general, for five
games. He even abandoned his signature, ``40 minutes of hell''
pressure defense for nine games after a 30-point loss to Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Anything, Richardson said, to get the attention of a young
Razorbacks' team that staggered into mid-February with eight losses
and faced consecutive games against the No. 6 and No. 2 teams in
The Associated Press rankings.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Reid said, even Arkansas players questioned their
pedigree as an NCAA Tournament participant. Then, the Hogs defeated
No. 6 Kentucky and No. 2 Auburn within a five-day stretch, creating
an about-face in the attitude of a team that has progressed, since
Feb. 20, from tournament bubble rider to No. 4 seed in the West
Region.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas (22-10) meets Siena (25-5) at approximately 2:15 p.m.
today at McNichols Sports Arena. Richardson said he is unsure what
to expect from a Razorbacks group that lists seven freshmen among
its top 14 scorers and has only three seniors on its roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matchups are really tough for us because this team doesn't
match up with anybody,'' said Richardson, whose top seven players
include no one taller than 6-foot-8 forward Derek Hood. ``A lot of
times, I'll have four guys out there who are 6-1 or 6-2. I call our
guys the PT boats because they're supposed to get in there, shoot,
and get out. I keep reminding them that a lot of things in small
packages blow up loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they blow up prematurely, creating self-inflicted
wounds. Witness the 87-57 loss to Oklahoma on Dec. 5, when the
Razorbacks suffered 17 turnovers and shot 39.3 percent from the
field. The contest convinced Richardson to put his pressure defense
in cold storage. It did not resurface for nine games, when the
Razorbacks used it to surprise Providence and hand the Friars the
most lopsided loss in school history, 118-79.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got eight freshmen ... and the type of defense I teach
is very difficult,'' Richardson said. ``Traps must come. But they
can happen anywhere. I tell them to `read and recover,' which is
very unorthodox. Early on, they didn't get it. So, we'd drop it and
come back to it, drop it and come back to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I decided it was like handling a racehorse.
Eventually, you give it its head and turn it loose. By the end of
the year, we were doing a good job. Not an outstanding job, but a
good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Good enough to record victories over Kentucky (74-70) and Auburn
(104-88) that set the stage for Arkansas to reach the final of last
week's Southeastern Conference tournament. Good enough that Reid,
who once wondered about his team's postseason destination,
considers the Razorbacks capable of a nice, long ride in the NCAA
field.
</P>
<P>
   His senior season, he said, has been salvaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so good or nice in the beginning. But it's been a
smooth ride lately,'' said Reid, who leads the team in assists
(160) and ranks third in scoring, at 10.2 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't always been consistent, but we've found a way to
get it done when it really mattered,'' said Bradley, who leads the
team in scoring (14.4 average) and owns the SEC record for career
3-pointers, with 361. ``I guess we play our best when our back's to
the wall. And we're definitely there now. You never know if your
next tournament game will be your last.''
</P>
<P>
   In a season filled with mixed results, Richardson figures the
only thing he can count on today is that his PT boats will sink
someone _ themselves or Siena _ with all guns blazing.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
