<HEADLINE>
NFL MIGHT PLAY WAITING GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Greater Los Angeles may have to put its plans to regain a NFL
franchise on hold for a little while longer.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among NFL execs and owners for two months has been
that the league was headed back to Los Angeles, that next week's
annual league meetings in Phoenix would likely produce a vote to
put a 32nd franchise in L.A. by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The league's expansion committee will meet Sunday morning and is
expected to make a recommendation to the membership on expanding to
either Houston or Los Angeles. A simple majority of those 14 owners
is required for any recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   But sources close to ownership say there are enough factions
within the entire membership to render any recommendation moot. The
league requires 24 of 31 votes to approve any expansion decision,
and expansion is on Tuesday's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the league) will try to convey the impression that
they are doing something,'' said a source. ``But when everything is
done, you'll see things are no further along than they were before
the meetings began. If they do say they're coming back to L.A.,
there will be enough conditions to keep Houston's bid alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Several sources, speaking on background only, said the owners
are separated by a variety of issues:
</P>
<P>
   Several feel the league is rushing a decision on adding a 32nd
franchise. Another new team, the owners feel, will eventually cut
into each team's national TV revenue and further dilute the
product.
</P>
<P>
   The league expanded from 28 to 30 teams in 1995 and will add a
31st in Cleveland this fall as settlement over Art Modell moving
the Browns to Baltimore in 1996. NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue
acknowledged last week that several owners dislike the formula for
stocking expansion teams, in particular the awarding of multiple
draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is some sentiment to do nothing,'' said one
source. ``And even if enough owners want to expand, there are
enough on either side (of the L.A. vs. Houston debate) to prevent a
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Several owners are still not sold on either of the two groups
seeking an L.A. expansion team, Carson/Michael Ovitz and the New
Coliseum/Ed Roski/Eli Broad.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz's latest financial presentation, said one source, was
``flimsy,'' featuring too much debt and not enough hard information
on equity involvement by other partners. And while the New Coliseum
bid has ``made a lot of progress,'' league execs have a problem
with the public money contribution and several owners are still
reticent to return to the original Coliseum site.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue has said any action to return to Los Angeles next week
would likely not specify a particular site or ownership group. It
would just establish an eventual return to L.A., with those
decisions determined at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, who hosted a visit to Carson by Tagliabue last week, said
he preferred a decision sooner than later, but understood the
league's decision-making process. New Coliseum spokesman John
Semcken said Roski and Broad would like a decision as much as
anyone, but understand the nature of the NFL's dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Houston businessman Robert McNair has been aggressively seeking
support among owners to keep his Houston bid alive after next
week's meetings. He recently broached league execs about expanding
to Houston (set ital) and (end ital) Los Angeles, and also sent
letters to several owners expressing an interest in buying their
teams if they were for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always been in favor of franchise stability,'' said
NFL spokesman Joe Browne Wednesday, adding that there's sentiment
to expand beyond 32 teams. ``McNair and Houston are still in the
running for the 32nd team. It's possible he's covering his bets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be a clear recommendation by the committee,
either L.A. or Houston, but we may not get beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair has his supporters among the membership, most notably Bud
Adams, who moved the Oilers from Houston to Tennessee. Adams is a
member of expansion committee and said in October that several
fellow owners in the AFC Central will support Houston's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Semcken said this week that while he expects the league ``will
do something,'' he now believes Houston will still be an option
when the meetings end. Neither L.A. group has been asked to make
any additional presentation or even attend the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   There are indications that the league wants some of the men
behind the two L.A. bids to combine forces in returning the NFL to
the city. One source said the league likes the marketing potential
of Ovitz and the financial resources of Broad, and would be willing
to consider either site if the two were part of the same team.
</P>
<P>
   Broad came onto the Coliseum project late at the request of Los
Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan after the NFL expressed concern about
Roski's resources. He has been an active participant in the
redevelopment of downtown Los Angeles, so he would be unlikely to
be part of any deal in Carson. Ovitz, meanwhile, might be unwilling
to give up top billing as the man who returned the NFL to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Where Roski, who has been the private party championing L.A.'s
cause for four years, sits in this suggested alliance remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Last and hardly least, there is always money to consider, and
each day a decision is delayed potentially increases the size of
the franchise fee for a 32nd team.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns' franchise fee was $476 million, but sources said
several owners -- Dallas' Jerry Jones, Tampa's Malcolm Glazer, new
Vikings owner Red McCombs and the Raiders' Al Davis -- felt the
league left at least $100 million on the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   All three groups seeking a franchise have been operating on the
assumption of a $500 million franchise fee. But the (set ital) very
low end (end ital), sources said, for a team in L.A. may be $650
million.
</P>
<P>
   When a price tag of $1 billion was mentioned to Tagliabue last
week, he did not shrug the number off.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion committee is made up of the members of the stadium
committee, chairman Jerry Richardson (Carolina), Wayne Huizenga
(Miami), David Modell (Baltimore), Mike McCaskey (Chicago), Wayne
Weaver (Jacksonville) and Bob Whitsitt (Seattle); and the finance
committee, chairman Bob Kraft (New England), Bud Adams (Tennessee),
Tom Benson (New Orleans), Bill Ford (Detroit), Glazer (Tampa Bay),
Jeff Lurie (Philadelphia) and Robert Tisch (New York Giants).
</P>
</TEXT>
