<HEADLINE>
RICHARDSON HAILS COURT'S ELIGIBILITY RULING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Arkansas basketball coach Nolan Richardson smiled
broadly and borrowed from the words of Martin Luther King as he
hailed Monday's court ruling that stripped the NCAA of its
eligibility standards for freshmen athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free at last! Free at last!,'' Richardson said yesterday,
parroting King's famous ``I Have a Dream'' speech in 1963. ``I'm
the happiest man in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, long an opponent of using college entrance exam
scores as a means of determining freshman eligibility because he
considers the tests culturally biased, said he shared his joy with
fellow African-American coaches after learning that U.S. District
Judge Ronald Buckwalter nullified NCAA rules requiring a minimum
score of 820 on the SAT to compete as freshmen. In his ruling,
Buckwalter said the standardized tests violated federal civil
rights laws because they had an ``unjustified disparate impact
against African-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   After learning of the ruling, Richardson said he immediately
placed celebratory phone calls to Temple coach John Chaney and
former Georgetown coach John Thompson. Like Richardson, Chaney and
Thompson are black. Like Richardson, both spoke out against using
these exam scores to determine freshmen eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   But no coach became more of a lightning rod for the topic than
Richardson, who raised the issue at every news conference during
Arkansas' march to the 1994 NCAA championship and the championship
game of the 1995 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a victory for me, per se,'' Richardson said. ``But
it's gratifying ... the work and time we put in, trying to tell
people \Rthe NCAA\S was wrong has been vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public's perception of Nolan Richardson changed because of
this. At this time in '94, I was angry. But I had reason to be
angry. Now, Nolan's happy. ... Looking back on what I did, it was
worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   NCAA officials have announced plans to appeal Buckwalter's
ruling.
LONG, HARD RIDE
</P>
<P>
   Siena guard Marcus Faison, who played his high school ball in El
Paso, has endured a long road to his first NCAA Tournament
appearance. And it has nothing to do with the Saints' needing 36
hours to travel from Albany, N.Y., to Denver for today's meeting
with Arkansas because of heavy snow in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Faison's father, Lamont, died less than a week after he enrolled
for his freshman year, in 1996-97. Lamont Faison, 38, suffered a
stroke brought on by a rare genetic ailment that riddles the body
with tumors. By the end of Faison's freshman season, Siena had lost
by 40 points in its conference tournament and school officials
fired the coach who recruited him, Bob Beyer.
</P>
<P>
   Incoming coach Paul Hewitt had to convince Faison to scrap plans
to transfer to another school. Two years later, the junior from El
Paso's Irvin High School has emerged as the leading scorer (14.6)
on a team making its first NCAA Tournament appearance since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just getting to the NCAA Tournament is special in itself. But
after everything I've been through at Siena, that makes this even
sweeter,'' Faison said.
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Iowa point guard Dean Oliver, who leads the Hawkeyes in scoring
(11.9 points per game) and assists (4.6 per game), is doubtful for
today's game against Alabama-Birmingham because of a respiratory
infection that worsened yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico coach Dave Bliss said forward Kenny Thomas, who
missed two games in last week's Western Athletic Conference
tournament because of a groin injury, will play today against
Missouri.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
