<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS WILL TRY NO. 2 SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ He's not the typical No. 2 hitter you'd find
in the National League, the bunt-the-man-over,
take-a-pitch-so-the-baserunner-can-run type of guy. But Jim Edmonds
will hit second in the Angels' lineup this year, right after
leadoff man Darin Erstad and right before No. 3 man Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy likes hitting there,'' Angels manager Terry Collins
said. ``He scored 100-some-odd runs (115) last year. There will
always be situations (to bunt or take pitches), but we don't have a
prototypical leadoff hitter either. If Darin Erstad is on base a
lot, which I anticipate, I think Jim Edmonds will get a lot of
fastballs to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds has always said he prefers to hit in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   __ New look: Attention American League: Closer Troy Percival has
added a weapon to his repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   Percival is working on a change-up this spring to go along with
his 95-mph fastball and his curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no better place to work on stuff than here,'' Collins
said. ``He worked on a change-up all winter, he worked on his
curveball all winter. The minute you get hitters not looking for
his fastball, the fastball becomes almost unhittable. This adds a
couple more weapons to his arsenal. It'll make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The good and bad: Three of the four innings Omar Olivares
pitched Wednesday for the Angels were perfect. It was the other
inning _ the third _ that seemed to irk Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares gave up a three-run double to the Giants' Barry Bonds
in the inning, but that's not what bothered Collins. With two out
and two on, Olivares walked Bill Mueller to get to Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing he's got to do if we're going to win is cut down
the bases on balls,'' Collins said. ``You can't walk Bill Mueller
to get to Barry Bonds. You cannot do that. Not when you've got
stuff as good as he (Olivares) has.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares seems to have an edge over Jarrod Washburn and Jason
Dickson in the battle for the No. 5 spot in the starting rotation,
but Collins won't admit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to rank them,'' he said. ``(Olivares) did a good
job for us last year, but one thing about the fifth spot _ you just
can't give away runs in any spot. Today was the perfect example.
You have to put that guy away.''
</P>
<P>
   __ On the mend: Shortstop Gary DiSarcina had his forearm X-rayed
Wednesday and it revealed the broken bone is healing. The
full-sized cast was removed and he was fitted with a short cast.
</P>
<P>
   He was given the OK to increase his activity but can't
participate in field work. He'll be re-examined in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   __ Moves: The Angels reduced the number of players in
major-league camp by 11 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Infielder Nelson Castro was optioned to Double-A Erie; pitchers
Ramon Ortiz and Mark Harriger and catcher Bret Hemphill were
assigned to Gene Autry Park for work purposes; and catcher Fausto
Tejero and pitchers Mike Bovee, Mike Butcher, Brian Cooper, Seth
Etherton, Lou Pote and Keith Troutman were returned to minor-league
camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
