</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU WANT 'EM TO READ, WRITE AND WIN, TOO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The NCAA places way too great a burden on college
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   You begin with the fact that for a kid even to get into college
today he actually has to have a high school diploma!
</P>
<P>
   No ifs, ands or buts.
</P>
<P>
   It's an NCAA rule.
</P>
<P>
   And a sheepskin only gets him in the front door. A freshman who
wants to score touchdowns or shoot buckets for the institution of
higher learning that recruited him also must demonstrate he can
read and write and is adequately prepared to do college-level work.
</P>
<P>
   Or that's how it was. This week a judge struck down the NCAA's
test-score requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 16 is out.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge's ruling stands, the 302 Division I schools will
decide which of their freshmen are eligible for sports and which
are not.
</P>
<P>
   I say if a young man wants to play for (fill in your NCAA
Tournament office pool pick) and can knock down the three-point
shot blindfolded, why on Earth should university administrators
concern themselves with peripheral issues like education?
</P>
<P>
   Why let academics hold him back?
</P>
<P>
   High school dropout?
</P>
<P>
   No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Give the young man a full scholarship and point him toward the
gym. It shouldn't matter whether a kid can find the ``x'' in
algebra if he can take his team to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Education?
</P>
<P>
   How about ``winning''.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not lose sight of what today's society ``really'' values.
</P>
<P>
   Is it fair to expect a 6-10 kid who can bring fans out of their
seats with a 360-degree reverse jam to concern himself with the
dual responsibilities of being a full-time student? If he's as good
as the coach says, the kid's probably going to leave school early
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   This week the kid is earning big bucks for the university.
</P>
<P>
   He's ``focused'' on basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Why ask him to risk losing his concentration by making him read
Shakespeare?
</P>
<P>
   A free throw during March Madness can be worth millions. Isn't
that enough pressure on a student athlete without demanding he
finish writing an outline for a term paper and turn it in next
Monday?
</P>
<P>
   Filling the hoop, baby.
</P>
<P>
   That's what matters. That's what it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball is a full-time job. Ask Minnesota Coach Clem Haskins,
who was confronted Wednesday with allegations of academic fraud at
his school. ``All I'm trying to do is win a game,'' Haskins
replied. His Gophers open the NCAAs against Gonzaga. ``It's all I'm
concentrating on.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Minnesota (motto: ``HOMEWORK? IT'S A SLAM
DUNK!'') understands what the NCAA doesn't. Being a student ``and''
an athlete is unrealistic. A kid shouldn't have to do both.
</P>
<P>
   A former office manager at Minnesota said she did research
papers and exams over a five-year period for at least 20 men's
basketball players, including four now on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Gangelhoff told the ``St''.``'' ``Paul Pioneer Press'' that
different players turned in the same paper she wrote for different
classes. Gangelhoff said players would come to her home where they
either would sit next to her as she typed the course work or be in
an adjacent room.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was a (homework) assignment and they had been to class,
we would talk about what happened in class and what they heard and
what they thought about the assignment,'' she said. ``Then they
would grab the remote and go watch TV, and I would type (the
assignment) up.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the research papers, we would rarely meet. They would just
give me the assignment and I would do it and then they would pick
it up. Sometimes I would read the papers to them and explain them
to them just in case they got asked in class about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine actually being singled out and questioned in class.
</P>
<P>
   What do you ``say''?
</P>
<P>
   It's just not fair to put a young man in that situation, not
when his mind is on Gonzaga. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
