<HEADLINE>
LIONS' FREDRICKSON TO VISIT CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cardinals' search for an outside linebacker doesn't begin
and end with trying to re-sign Jamir Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent Rob Fredrickson, a first-round pick of the Oakland
Raiders in 1994, is scheduled to visit the Cardinals' Tempe
training facility today.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials said that Fredrickson's visit doesn't mean
their interest in re-signing Miller has diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrickson, who lives in Scottsdale in the off-season, is the
first free agent from another team to visit the Cardinals since the
free-agency period began on Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   He is coming off his best statistical season: a career-high 86
tackles, 70 solo; 2{ sacks; and one interception for the Detroit
Lions in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions acquired him for a fourth-round draft pick in a trade
with the Raiders during the last off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrickson, who earned $1.3 million last year, has attracted
much interest in free agency. He already has visited the New York
Giants, Washington Redskins and New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cardinals strong safety Tommy Bennett, a restricted
free agent, returned from his visit to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers had discussions with Bennett's agent, Mitch
Frankel, but haven't decided whether to make him an offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals can match any offer for Bennett. But if they chose
not to match it, they would get no compensation.
</P>
</TEXT>
