<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-3COM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3COM-MICROSOFT VENTURE TO DEVELOP PC PRODUCTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Microsoft Corp. and the 3Com Corp. Thursday intend to
announce an alliance to jointly develop products to connect
personal computers and computer peripherals within homes,
executives from the two companies said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The concept behind the venture is that consumers could save
money by sharing modems, printers, scanners and removable storage
devices like zip disks by linking PCs into in-home networks rather
than buy multiple peripherals to cover each computer in a home. The
technology would also ease the playing of head-to-head computer
games.
</P>
<P>
   The companies intend to make the products, which would be
co-branded by 3Com and Microsoft, available in two stages. This
summer big personal computer manufacturers would begin to include
the new product in machines for customers willing to pay extra for
them.
</P>
<P>
   Then this fall 3Com and Microsoft will begin to distribute
add-on products through retail channels, including stores and
Internet shops.
</P>
<P>
   The companies do not intend to announce specific PC partners
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   3Com and Microsoft said Wednesday night that they planned to
charge less than $100 a computer for the new networking product.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Eagan, director for business development at Microsoft's
hardware group, said the deal with 3Com was the first time
Microsoft had agreed to co-brand a networking product.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance between Microsoft, the No. 1 developer of PC
software, and 3Com, the maker of data networking equipment,
represents a bet that consumers are as eager to link PCs at high
speed in their homes as they are in connecting to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The cable television and local telephone industries are locked
in a battle to be the first to deliver widespread high speed
Internet access to United States customers.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from the companies said that while they would
consider expanding into cable modems and high-speed phone line
modems, the venture would initially focus on in-home networking
using phone lines.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 0016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6005 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-SPRING-PREVU-     03-11 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-SPRING-PREVU-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEALY TAKES LEADERSHIP MANTLE  
 QB TURNS SILENT AS SPRING BALL GETS UNDER WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Ryan Kealy, a man of few words, has become a man
of no words.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona State quarterback has put a temporary embargo on
media interviews so he can focus on academics. Kealy's attitude is
part of an off-season maturation that includes trying to be a
better leader for the Sun Devils, his coaches say.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's blossoming,'' quarterbacks coach John Pettas said. ``He's
now realizing it's his turn to step forward. He's taking more of an
active role than a passive one.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Bruce Snyder said, ``He doesn't want to be singled
out. He has done a lot in the off-season to benefit the team, and
I'm proud of him. He's in great shape. He's focusing on academics.
He wants to do what's best for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils, who begin the first of an NCAA-allowed 15 spring
practices today, hope to regroup after a disappointing 5-6 season.
Although Kealy's inconsistencies were only a small part of ASU's
problems, Snyder said the junior took the finish to heart and has
joined defensive players Erik Flowers, Eric Fields and Junior Ioane
as vocal off-season leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we've had meetings in the off-season about leadership,
there's been a lot of passion,'' Snyder said. ``Has it been the
whole team? No. But are we advanced from where we were a year ago?
Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Leadership was a concern last season. Several players suggested
there was too much finger-pointing by other players, and some
veterans' work habits were questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Players have met several times in the off-season to discuss the
topic. Kealy, consciously or not, is integrating himself with the
rest of the team by lifting with the linemen and running with the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said he has three priorities for the spring:
</P>
<P>
   See what kind of impact the five enrolled junior college
transfers and 14 former redshirts can make.
</P>
<P>
   Redefine practice habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the veterans of last year's club lost the ability or
knowledge of truly how to practice, and they became a little less
focused,'' Snyder said. ``We want this group to understand what a
hard practice is and make sure they do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Develop leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to define what it is, who it is and what form does it
take,'' Snyder said. ``A lot of things have taken place over the
winter dealing with the players providing leadership the coaches
can't provide.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils will spend part of the spring returning to
fundamentals. A missed tackle here and a bad pursuit there probably
equated to several losses last season.
</P>
<P>
   But Snyder said he will not dramatically alter his offensive and
defensive schemes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of semi-prepared to go in and tear this thing
apart,'' Snyder said. ``But after we examined everything, it really
doesn't need that. It just needs a little tweaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The most tweaking will come in August, when the Sun Devils open
Camp Tontozona with 29 new players.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some story lines that could unfold: &QL; 
A new-look backfield &QL; 
Fullback Jeff Paulk's departure is significant. His blocking was
key to the success of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils will give redshirt freshman Jake Each a look
(redshirt freshman Darrel Turner is out with a hernia) but might
consider other options to join tailback J.R. Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility might feature Redmond with two tight ends such
as Todd Heap and Brian Jennings. Heap's receiving abilities will
allow for some offensive creativity. &QL; 
Player movement &QL; 
Several players will be at new positions in the spring because of
experimentation as well as necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Christon Rance, who started eight games at strong safety,
and sophomore Courtney Palmore, who played in 10 games as a backup
safety, will get looks at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Terrelle Smith, who began his ASU career on the defensive
line before moving to linebacker, will get a shot at fullback.
Smith was a high school All-America by several recruiting services.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils, who will be thin at offensive line during the
spring, also will do some shifting there.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Scott Peters, who earned freshman All-America honors his
first season, is expected to take over Grey Ruegamer's spot at
center. Snyder said he will move junior Victor Leyva to right
tackle and put senior Thomas Schmidt at right guard to compete with
sophomore Levi Jones, who has moved from the defensive line. &QL; 
Defensive changes? &QL; 
Two of the five junior college transfers who already have enrolled
_ Craig Koontz and Monte Franks _ are safeties and one, Adam Tanke,
is a linebacker. With the loss of free safety Mitchell Freedman and
the shuffling of several players, some new faces could make their
way into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secondary is absolutely a priority,'' Snyder said. ``If
you look at our recruiting, it pretty strongly states we need to
improve our defensive skills. The two new safeties have done a real
nice job of dove-tailing in (with the players), although they
haven't played a snap here yet.'' &QL; 
Health issues &QL; 
Don't expect to see starting cornerback Courtney Jackson practice
much, if at all, during the spring. He still has not recovered from
a hit during the regular-season finale against Arizona, an apparent
uncalled clip the Sun Devils privately are still seething about.
</P>
<P>
   How severe is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a medical person telling me he would have been
better off breaking his ankle,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Courtney Hysaw, who is still recovering from a severe
knee injury suffered at Camp Tontozona last year, won't be ready.
Running back J.R. Peroulis will be limited because of a lingering
knee injury. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
