<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS LOSE, BUT IS MARBURY ON WAY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Before the New Jersey Nets lost their fifth game
in a row Wednesday night, to the Indiana Pacers at Market Square
Arena, the team's officials were attempting to secure a deal that
would not only resurrect this lifeless season but also turn the
club into a league powerhouse in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In what would perhaps be the biggest trade of the season if
consummated, the Nets were trying to acquire Stephon Marbury, the
Minnesota Timberwolves' point guard who grew up in New York City.
The Nets offered Sam Cassell and a first-round draft pick, a league
official with knowledge of the discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's about an 80 percent chance that it could happen,'' the
official said, hours before the Nets (3-15) were beaten, 93-82, by
the Indiana Pacers (13-5).
</P>
<P>
   The Nets are likely to trade the disgruntled forward Chris
Gatling to the Milwaukee Bucks in exchange for center Ervin Johnson
and the backup point guard Elliot Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's game was further evidence that the Nets need
to make changes as they lost for the 11th time in 12 contests.
Their faint playoff hopes are now gone. In the traditional 82-game
season, their unsightly record is the equivalent of being 5-25.
</P>
<P>
   Rik Smits (20 points) led a contingent of five Pacers who scored
in double figures. Chris Mullin followed with 17.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Gill scored 25 points to lead the Nets, who lowered
their league-worst shooting percentage by making just 35 percent of
their shots. Keith Van Horn added 22 points for New Jersey while
Jayson Williams scored 13 and grabbed a game-high 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   After playing Indiana tough in the first half, the Nets crumbled
slowly over the third and fourth quarters, being outscored by 44-36
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Coach John Calipari, whose job security seems to dwindle with
every defeat, started his ``big lineup'' for the first time this
season. In search of a cure for his club's horrible play, he
started Jim McIlvaine at center, along with Williams, Van Horn,
Gill and Kerry Kittles.
</P>
<P>
   Gill, playing point guard, responded best to the change, scoring
18 points in the first half. He headed into the contest on the
heels of a four-game slump in which he totaled only 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   With Gill hitting jumpers and posting up, the Nets rallied from
an 11-point first-quarter deficit to pull within 49-46 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana outscored the Nets by 19-9 over the first eight minutes
of the third quarter to take a commanding 68-55 lead that never
again dropped below double digits.
</P>
<P>
   With the league's trading deadline of Thursday at 6 p.m.
approaching, the Nets do not have long to inject some energy into
their insipid lineup. A more drastic move for the club would have
them sending Kittles to Minnesota for Marbury. But the Nets hope to
avoid parting with their third-year shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota, off to a 12-6 start behind Marbury and Kevin Garnett,
is only entertaining a possible deal for Marbury because of his
refusal to sign a long-term deal with the Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota has offered him a contract extension worth $70.875
million over six years, the maximum amount allowable, but his
distaste for the state's climate and lifestyle has led him to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury plans to become a free agent after the season. Faced
with the probability of losing Marbury and getting nothing in
return, the Timberwolves, who lost All-Star forward Tom Gugliotta
as a free agent before this season, is looking for the best deal
available.
</P>
<P>
   While numerous teams would offer more than Cassell for Marbury,
who is averaging 18 points and 9.3 assists, league rules require
that players' salaries be within 15 percent of one another for a
trade to take place. With Marbury making $2.56 million and Cassell
$3 million, the deal is possible. Not many other top-notch players
make only about $3 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Cassell is not on Marbury's level, but he averaged 19.6 points
and 8 assists last season, and he is arguably one of the top point
guards in the Eastern Conference. His missing 14 games this season
because of a sprained right ankle is one of the major reasons for
the Nets' decline.
</P>
<P>
   If the trade happens, the Nets will sign Marbury to a six-year,
$67.5 million contract extension, the maximum amount allowable,
before Saturday's deadline for extending the contracts of
third-year players. Though the Nets are floundering, Marbury would
perhaps choose to sign an extended deal with them because of his
desire to live near New York City and the club's strong nucleus of
Keith Van Horn, Jayson Williams and Kittles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
