<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-OLYMPICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDD'S WEDDING PRESENT  
 NUPTIALS GIVE SUN SPOT ON U.S. TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's a safe bet that Detroit star Grant Hill is going
to get a nice wedding gift from Suns guard Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   Hill informed USA Basketball officials that he won't be able to
participate with the U.S. Men's Senior National Team this summer
that will try to qualify for the 2000 Olympics Games at Sydney,
Australia. Hill is getting married in July, and the tournament runs
July 14-25 in San Juan, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   It was Kidd's ticket to the qualifying tournament, and if the
U.S. team finishes first or second _ and anything less than first
would be regarded as a monumental upset _ Kidd and Suns teammate
Tom Gugliotta will represent their country at the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to call his mom and find out where he's
registered,'' Kidd said. ``And it won't be Target.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta had been told earlier that he would be among the nine
NBA players selected for the team that will compete in Puerto Rico.
The 12-man team for Puerto Rico also will include three players
selected from the collegiate ranks, the Continental Basketball
Association or from Americans playing in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd wasn't among the first nine, but the announcement was
delayed until Hill's replacement was selected. Three NBA players
will be added for the 2000 Games to the original nine, meaning Hill
could, and probably will, wind up on the squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to have the opportunity to represent my
country,'' Kidd said. ``It's a kid's dream and an ultimate goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta said Kidd's selection was ``obviously well deserved''
and Kidd's style of play will complement the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get to play with a player like Jason who can
literally dominate a game without scoring a point with rebounding,
passing . . . you love to play with guys like that,'' Gugliotta
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd's play in the first month of the NBA season, which included
four triple-double games _ double figures in scoring, rebounds and
assists _ no doubt opened eyes at USA Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to do anything to get on the team,'' Kidd
said. ``They told me I was having a great season, maybe it was a
turning point. Maybe they saw I could hit a couple of jump shots.
That's the thing that's usually the negative. The game is not
totally about shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd is among three point guards chosen for the first nine.
Miami's Tim Hardaway and Seattle's Gary Payton are the other point
guards. Atlanta's Steve Smith and New York's Allan Houston are
shooting guards. Gugliotta, his former Minnesota teammate, Kevin
Garnett, and Seattle's Vin Baker are the forwards. And San
Antonio's Tim Duncan is the only center named.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jason would have been picked the first time around,
but he has similarities to Gary Payton, who they were building the
team around,'' Suns Coach Danny Ainge said. ``He's been fantastic
for us. He's one of the premier players in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   USA Basketball is likely to add another small forward, a
shooting guard and another center. Shaquille O'Neal of the Los
Angeles Lakers, Hill and the Lakers' Kobe Bryant are likely
candidates for the remaining spots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
