<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUNK-DRIVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT FILED AGAINST NEW YORK CITY OVER CAR SEIZURES IN DRUNK
DRIVING CASES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Civil Liberties Union filed a class
action lawsuit Wednesday, asking a Manhattan state Supreme Court
justice to halt the Giuliani administration's new policy of seizing
the cars of people arrested for drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed on behalf of Pavel Grinberg, a 28-year-old
Staten Island man who the police said tested just over the legal
blood alcohol limit on the first night of the crackdown, is the
first to challenge the legality and constitutionality of the
policy. As of Wednesday afternoon, 79 cars had been seized in the
two-week-old initiative, which city officials are calling the
toughest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's filing was the first step in what is likely to be a
pitched legal battle that could drag on for months. The first
skirmish may occur Thursday morning when Justice Michael D.
Stallman is expected to hold a hearing in state Supreme Court in
Manhattan on the lawsuit's demand that Grinberg's car be
immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome will most likely draw interest from across the state
and the nation. Officials in Nassau and Suffolk Counties have
adopted similar car seizure policies, and Mayor Richard M. Daley of
Chicago has said he may try a similar approach.
</P>
<P>
   City officials predicted that the seizure initiative would
stand. ``We are extremely confident of the legal basis for this
initiative,'' said Daniel S. Connolly, a special counsel in the
city's Law Department. ``We will address all of the concerns
raised.''
</P>
<P>
   But Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, predicted that the policy would be struck down,
calling it ``unfair and excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The government should not be in the business of seizing
people's cars without the requisite legal authority,'' he said.
``And, even if authorized, it should not do so prior to trial and
conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit focuses only on those charged with drunken driving
for the first time, like Grinberg, a custodian at the New York
Public Library, and argues that taking away their cars is an
``excessive and grossly disproportionate punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the 4,970 people charged with drunken driving last
year in the city had never been charged with it before, court
records show.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, the civil liberties group argued that the new
city policy was unconstitutional because only the legislative
branch of the government _ in this case the New York state
Legislature _ can determine the punishment for a crime.
</P>
<P>
   It also argued that the seizures were illegal because state law
authorizes the taking of property used in the commission of
felonies, not misdemeanors. Offenders are charged with misdemeanor
drunken driving if they have no prior record. Repeat offenders are
charged with felony drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   Grinberg's 1988 Acura is his family's only car. The lawsuit says
his family is enduring ``great hardship'' as they struggle to get
around without a car in their neighborhoo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 0020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
