<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-LEE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE FINALLY SIGNS UP FOR YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Diamondbacks have all their roster players under
contract with the signing of first baseman  &UR; Travis Lee to a
one-year deal Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola Jr. downplayed Lee's signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to be last, and it worked out he was last,''
Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   The club had until today to have Lee under contract. Financial
terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, one of the top National League rookies last season, hit
.269 and had 22 home runs and 72 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed Lee, who didn't play Wednesday against the
Oakland Athletics, never ceases to amaze Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travis could play shortstop,'' Showalter said. ``He was an
all-state quarterback right-handed. It's weird that he throws the
baseball left-handed.'' &QL; 
Hot bat &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Greg Colbrunn filled in at first for Lee and had four hits,
including three doubles, and four RBIs. He also made a couple of
nice plays defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Colbrunn had only one hit in 10 previous at-bats this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel good coming in,'' Colbrunn said. ``I mean, it's
spring training. Some days, you're going to feel good. Some days,
you're going to feel bad.'' &QL; 
Seeing triple &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder  &UR; Luis Gonzalez, who had a triple in Wednesday's game,
is the father of 9-month-old triplets. He said his wife brings them
to the ballpark, but only one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll bring them up to the press box and see how these guys do
with them crawling all over their papers,'' Gonzalez said. &QL; 
Eager to play &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tony Womack, making the transition from second base to the
outfield, is ready to get back on the field after suffering a
broken bone in his right wrist when hit by a pitch in a game
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He is back on the field, working out, at least. Showalter said
that earlier in the week, despite wearing a cast on his right arm,
Womack was catching fly balls and taking short toss with his left
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Womack will be back this week, Showalter said,
``He'd like to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Womack won't likely be ready to play in a game for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't think the diagnosis was right at first,'' Showalter
said. ``He said, `It can't be right. It feels too good.' '' &QL; 
Short stops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks won their seventh straight game Wednesday,
collecting 21 hits in a 13-2 rout of Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said he'll likely make two more player cuts either
today or Friday, likely in the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder  &UR; Jason Conti, the organization's minor league
Player of the Year last summer, said he is enjoying seeing the
Valley this spring. Conti was raised in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``This beats the cold weather,'' he said. ``They're probably not
even playing baseball right now where I'm from.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Randy Johnson will take the mound today at Tucson Electric Park
against the Chicago Cubs and possibly  &UR; Sammy Sosa, if Sosa makes
the trip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
