<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-FOX-AZR &LR;      03-11 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-FOX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMELEON MELDS INTO DIAMONDBACKS PLAN  
 FOX EASILY ADAPTS TO MANY POSITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Andy Fox is making the rounds. He fields grounders at
second. He grabs his first-basemen's mitt and takes throws. He goes
into the outfield for some flies.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate utility man again is ready to plug in at any
position _ well, maybe not pitcher _ for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Andy have a way of finding at-bats,'' Manager Buck
Showalter said. ``They find a way of getting into the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, listed as an infielder, started at six positions for
Arizona last season: second, first, third, and all three outfield
spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, coming in, you've got to be ready to play every
position,'' Fox said. ``If something happens to somebody, there
aren't any big surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter wasn't surprised at how versatile the 6-foot-4,
left-handed-hitting Fox was last year when he played in 139 games
and had 502 plate appearances. He hit leadoff and third, at times,
and hit .277 with 21 doubles. He was second on the team with six
triples. He also had nine homers and drove in 44 runs and scored 67
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will have more competition with more versatility added to
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Backup first baseman Greg Colbrunn can also play outfield and
third base and, right now, is the third catcher in camp. Second
baseman Tony Womack is being turned into an outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   And there is Jay Bell, who moved from shortstop to second base
late last season for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest improvements I think in our club,
potentially, is some of our support players, guys who have
versatility,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   So where does Fox fit in? Try everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy will always fit in,'' Showalter said. ``He'll fit in on
any club until he decides to quit playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Fox is just trying to get over the flu that kept him
out for three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' he said. ``You don't ever want to miss any
time. Hopefully, I've got this stuff out of my system now. I'm just
glad it happened now instead of later.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who got married in the off-season, worked out Wednesday at
Municipal Stadium before the Diamondbacks played the Oakland
Athletics in a Cactus League game.
</P>
<P>
   He said he doesn't expect his role to diminish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the competition,'' he said. ``With competition, you've
got to be ready every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see myself on the bench all the time. I'll have my
at-bats. I'll get my chances. If you hit, you're going to find
places to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox filled in so well that third baseman Matt Williams thought
Fox was the Diamondbacks' most valuable player last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he didn't do was pitch and catch,'' Williams said. ``A lot
of teams aren't blessed with a guy that valuable. He can fill in
anywhere, not only when there are injuries but when a guy needs a
day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not be a starting player, but there is no reason why he
can't be out there at least three days a week. He's willing and
able to play any position. He's a pretty valuable guy.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Travis Lee, whose locker sits next to Fox's,
appreciates not only Fox's work ethic and versatility but his
clubhouse manners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taught me to clean up my locker,'' Lee said. ``I know how
to hang up my shorts and shirts now. He's a good guy to have
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
