<HEADLINE>
WEIGHT LOSS MAY HAVE COST WAITE  
 BACKUP GOALIE DROPS 22 POUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Coyotes backup goalie Jimmy Waite has lost 10 percent
of his body weight since the start of the season, which might have
led to his mid-season slump and caused the team to place him on
waivers for the purpose of reassigning him to Springfield in the
AHL.
</P>
<P>
   Waite, who was listed at 180 pounds entering last year's
playoffs, had bulked up to 202 when he reported for training camp
but has lost 22 pounds and weighed 180 when the Coyotes placed him
on waivers Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The weight loss wasn't lost on goaltending coach Benoit Allaire
and Coach Jim Schoenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bulked up in the summer and could afford to lose a little
bit,'' Schoenfeld said. ``But you can't be mentally or physically
sharp when you lose that much weight. It's something we addressed
for a month now with Jimmy and the training staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's about preparation and taking care of yourself. It's
a situation where you have to take your nourishment. If somebody
gained 20 pounds we would be all over them. You'll have to talk to
Jimmy, maybe he has a nervous disorder where he says he can't eat.
But he just weakens himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Waite confirmed he has lost weight, but thinks it's only part of
the wear and tear of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have,'' said Waite, who had not been claimed by another
NHL team through Wednesday evening. ``But I always lose weight
during the season. I don't have as much chance to work out with
weights during the season. I also tend to dehydrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he think the weight loss contributed to his ineffectiveness
of late?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Waite said. ``There were a few games when I
didn't feel as strong as normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Allaire said he talked to Waite after he lost 10 pounds, and
several more times about the importance of taking dietary
supplements and fluids to maintain his weight. Waite is often
nervous before games, and Allaire said he sometimes forgets to
ingest enough fluids during a game, which can effect his strength
as a game proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm trying to do right now,'' Waite said. ``I'm
trying to get my weight up, and I'm taking more vitamins.''
</P>
<P>
   Waite became dehydrated and required intravenous fluids after
winning his first start for the Coyotes last season, a 3-2 win at
San Jose on Nov. 13, 1997, after being obtained on waivers from
Chicago on Sept. 28, 1997. He hasn't had the problem since.
</P>
<P>
   Waite, 29, was the stingiest goalie in the NHL at this season's
start, bolting to a 6-0-2 record with a goals against average of
less than 2.00 per game. But he has not won since, posting an 0-5-2
record since his last win, a 4-2 victory over Montreal on Dec. 9.
</P>
<P>
   His save percentage has steadily dropped from 96 percent in
October and November, to 87.4 percent in December, to 86.7 in
January and finally to 82 percent during February, caused, in part,
by steadily decreasing appearances and missing some time with a
hand injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes reassigned him to Springfield for six games to work
on his game and confidence from Feb. 16 through March 1. He
returned March 2 against Detroit and gave up four goals on 10 shots
in a 7-2 loss that he said is the reason why he's being reassigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how fair it was,'' he said Monday. ``I mean, I
had just come back up from Springfield and I was thrown in right
away against one of the better teams in the league and we had
something like seven guys out. If I had won that game everything
would have been all right. I wouldn't be going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Waite, an unrestricted free agent at season's end, refused to
accept reassignment to Springfield, forcing the team to place him
on waivers, where he could be claimed first by other NHL teams. If
he clears waivers by noon (Phoenix time) today, he will remain
Coyotes' property and said he will accept the reassignment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
