A6016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NCAA-RULES-NYT &LR;      03-11 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NCAA-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FAIRNESS FOR BLACK COLLEGE ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, March 12:
</P>
<P>
   The National Collegiate Athletic Association will need to devise
new eligibility requirements for student athletes that preserve
academic values without at the same time discriminating against
African-Americans. That is the practical meaning of District Judge
Ronald L. Buckwalter's ruling on Monday that the NCAA's system of
basing eligibility largely on standardized test scores is unfair to
blacks. The ruling does not mean that colleges should abandon their
worthwhile and necessary efforts to improve graduation rates among
athletes. It does mean finding fairer ways to measure academic
potential.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the case, brought by four black student athletes who
were ruled ineligible to play sports in their freshman year because
of low admissions scores, was a rule known as Proposition 16.
Instituted by the NCAA in 1996, Proposition 16 tried to address
well-documented charges that the aggressive competition to enroll
athletic talent had created a universe of students who were badly
prepared for academic life and stood little chance of graduating.
</P>
<P>
   The rule requires a minimum score of 820 on the SAT's for
students with a 2.5 or higher grade point average in a ``core''
high school curriculum of 13 courses. A higher SAT score is
required of students with lower grades. The rule gives twice as
much weight to the SAT score as it does the grade point average.
</P>
<P>
   According to NCAA figures, 26.6 percent of the black students
who applied for eligibility in 1996 did not meet Proposition 16
standards, compared with 6.4 percent of white student athletes. The
main reason for their not meeting the standards was a failure to
achieve the minimum SAT score. The plaintiffs' lawyers also argued
that the test score was a flawed predictor of academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial piece of evidence, plucked from the NCAA's own data,
showed that student athletes who fell just below the 820 cutoff
point _ and were admitted but were denied athletic eligibility in
their freshman year _ wound up getting the same or even better
grades than those who barely met the 820 minimum. Those below the
line were mostly black, those above were mostly white.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs did not deny that efforts to raise entrance
standards for student athletes had led to a modest improvement in
graduation rates. But they argued that this improvement had been
achieved at the expense of denying eligibility, and in many cases
athletic scholarships, to a disproportionate percentage of blacks.
A supposedly neutral standard had in fact imposed an unfair burden
_ a ``disparate impact,'' in the judge's words _ on black student
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA, warning of chaos now that colleges have been left
without any guidance at all, says it will ask for a stay of the
ruling while it reviews Proposition 16 and seeks ways to change it.
It should not have to look far. Last year a special NCAA
subcommittee recommended alternatives to the present system,
including one that would base eligibility on an equally weighted
combination of high school grades and test scores.
</P>
<P>
   These recommendations should now be reconsidered. Given the
hotly competitive nature of college sports, it would be foolish to
return to a system where each school sets its own rules. Minimum
standards make sense for everyone, most of all the student athletes
who should be expected to value a degree as much as they do playing
time. But the standards should not deny black athletes a fair shot
at obtaining both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
