<HEADER>
A6018 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-HUSCROFT-     03-11 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-HUSCROFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSCROFT HAPPY WITH `PROMOTION'  
 DEFENSEMAN ADDS TOUGHNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Jamie Huscroft couldn't help but overhear the
conversation between the two men behind him on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran NHL defenseman had just been traded from the
Vancouver Canucks to the Coyotes, and on the flight to San Jose to
join his new team, his ears were burning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know who these guys were, and they didn't know who I
was,'' Huscroft said, starting to smile. ``I was just sitting there
reading a book when they came on, and I wasn't eavesdropping on
them or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   So what did they say?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Huscroft said, ``I overheard one of them say, `Did you
hear some guy from the Canucks got promoted today?' And his buddy
goes, `Don't you mean he got traded?' And the guy says, `No, he got
promoted!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, just getting out of a Canucks sweater is a step up
in employment to disillusioned Vancouver fans. Little did the two
fellows know who was sitting directly in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just smiled,'' the mustachioed Huscroft said, ``but that was
definitely a slap in the face for Vancouver. The team is
struggling, yeah, but I'm a huge Vancouver fan. They've got a great
organization there, and (General Manager) Brian Burke is
first-class. I'd never say anything to hurt him in any way, shape
or form.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I kind of laughed a little bit and shook my head,
too, at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Huscroft, 32, won't have any problem trying to stick it to the
woeful Canucks tonight, however, when they visit the Coyotes
(31-23-10) at America West Arena. He wasn't particularly pleased
with the way Coach Marc Crawford viewed or utilized his abilities
after stepping behind the bench at the All-Star break to replace
the fired Mike Keenan.
</P>
<P>
   Huscroft said Crawford felt the Canucks (19-35-10 entering
Wednesday's game at Anaheim) were overloaded with toughness and
grit, so players like himself, a physical, 6-foot-2, 212-pound
wrecking ball, slowly got played out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happens when a new sheriff comes to town, but what
can you do?'' said Huscroft, who was made an on-again, off-again
healthy scratch by Crawford. ``I have total respect for his
decisions. He's the coach, not me.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop the nine-year NHL pro from seeking a trade,
however, which Burke granted Tuesday after he swung a deal with the
Coyotes' Bobby Smith for a conditional draft pick in this year's
draft. Getting a chance to play his brand of punishing hockey
against Crawford and the Canucks just three days afterward
undoubtably will give Huscroft an extra jump.
</P>
<P>
   He showed plenty of that in his Phoenix debut Tuesday night
against the Sharks, shoving, slamming and steamrolling several San
Jose players. He was so excited, he literally hurdled over the
bench on his way ``back'' from shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had a very spirited game,'' said Coyotes Coach
Jim Schoenfeld, who coached Huscroft for parts of two seasons with
the New Jersey Devils. ``He played his position well. He was
abrasive out there. It was pretty much everything we expected. It's
too bad some other guys weren't what we expected them to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks overwhelmed the Coyotes in the third period for a 4-2
victory, handing Phoenix its 10th loss in 12 games, further
loosening the team's grip on the No. 4 playoff spot in the Western
Conference. Suddenly, that punch line on the plane about being
``promoted'' from the Canucks doesn't seem so funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a way better team than them,'' Huscroft said of
the Sharks, who are trying to hang on to the eighth and final
playoff seed. ``I don't know if that's a little too premature to
say, but I felt we should have beat those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Huscroft might not have the hands of a scorer or the skating
maneuvers of a top-four defenseman, but he has the heart and the
hustle. He's a hockey player, plain and simple. What you see is
what you get. And it's what the Coyotes' desperately needed.
</P>
<P>
   He illustrated the point perfectly Tuesday night, when a slice
of post-game pizza slipped out of his hands and fell to the locker
room floor while he chatted with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He picked it up and took another bite. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
