<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-DENVER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD GUARD STANDS PROUD AT WEST SUBRE GIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ They were there in the days when lapels were as wide as
the three-second lane, when players wore their hair long and
uniform trunks short, and before every true American began ponying
up $5 each March to enter the NCAA Basketball Tournament pool at
the office.
</P>
<P>
   Other than off-season golf tournaments and vacations sponsored
by shoe companies, there won't be many larger gatherings of
experienced, successful basketball coaches than there is this week
during the West Regional's first and second rounds at McNichols
Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's Norm Stewart, 63, is in his 38th season of college
coaching. Iowa's Tom Davis, 60, is in his 28th. Connecticut's Jim
Calhoun, 56, has 27 seasons of experience. New Mexico's Dave Bliss,
55, is in his 24th year, and Arkansas' Nolan Richardson, 57, is in
his 19th.
</P>
<P>
   That's a combined 136 seasons and an average season record of
20-10. Only one of the five, Richardson, has won a national
championship, but longevity should also count for something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how you define (success),'' Stewart said.
``Surviving is one. Winning a national championship is another.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the five entered coaching with winning an NCAA title in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us from that era, we were trained as teachers,'' said
Davis, who is in his last season at Iowa. ``Most of us figured we
were going to be high school coaches. That's how I started out.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, Calhoun and Richardson started their careers coaching in
high school. Stewart spent a year playing pro basketball and
baseball before returning to Missouri, his alma mater, as an
assistant. Bliss worked for IBM and Proctor and Gamble after
graduating from Cornell and before returning there for his
master's.
</P>
<P>
   He was then drafted into the Army and became an assistant for
Bob Knight at West Point.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss and Stewart will renew their old rivalry today when
Missouri, the eighth seed, plays New Mexico, the ninth seed, at
5:50 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss, formerly at Oklahoma, coached against Stewart in the days
of the old Big Eight Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norm Stewart's been there since Moses came down,'' Bliss said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, the top seed, plays 16th-seeded Texas-San Antonio
in the final game of the day at 8:20 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas, the fourth seed, plays 13th-seeded Siena at 1:10 p.m.
But the most intriguing story of the day could come in the first
game, when fifth-seeded Iowa plays 12th-seeded Alabama-Birmingham
at 10:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly a year ago that Davis announced this would be his
last season at Iowa after Athletic Director Bob Bowlsby declined to
extend his contract.
</P>
<P>
   It placed Bowlsby, and Davis's critics, in an uncomfortable
situation. There is no classier coach than Davis. He's run a clean
program in his 13 seasons in Iowa City, and has won more games in a
shorter time span than any other Iowa coach. His Hawkeye teams have
won 20 games nine times and have earned 9 NCAA tournament bids.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a feeling that the Hawkeyes could do better. While
Davis has never lost a first-round game in the NCAA Tournament, he
hasn't won a Big Ten championship either.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 60, has handled the messy situation with dignity all year
long, deflecting questions about the end of a career that began at
a high school in Milledgeville, Ill. If he is growing sentimental
about his last season at Iowa, he's keeping it well hidden. At
Wednesday's press conference his most controversial comment was:
`It's not been the easiest conditions in which to work under.``
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Calhoun pulled Davis aside and told the Iowa coach
that he served as a role model for other coaches. ``The thing most
memorable to me is the way he handled it,`` Calhoun said. ``Not an
ounce of gloat or anything, except for coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and his players talk of staying in the moment and focusing
only on today's game against Alabama-Birmingham. It's not going to
be easy, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing for coach has been the greatest basketball experience
of my life,'' said guard Kent McCausland, a senior from Waterloo,
Iowa. ``It was more than wanting to be a Hawkeye growing up, it was
wanting to play for Coach Davis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 0027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
