<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6021 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-SEATTLE-AZR &LR;      03-11 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-SEATTLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH STOCKTON IN CORNER, GONZAGA PACKING PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Gonzaga's most famous student was booted out of
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rumor has it that Bing Crosby got kicked out for throwing a
piano off the third floor of a dormitory,'' Gonzaga guard Richie
Frahm said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that Bing Crosby, the crooner who made ``White Christmas''
the No. 1 best-selling record of all time.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't leave the Spokane, Wash., school in the mid-1930s with
any hard feelings. The Crosby House, an alumni center, is named for
him.
</P>
<P>
   The second-most famous Gonzaga student got teary-eyed and hoarse
as he sat in his hotel room in Portland and watched on TV the West
Coast Conference final between the Bulldogs and Santa Clara on
March 1. Gonzaga won, 91-66, at Santa Clara to advance to the NCAA
Tournament for only the second time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th-seeded Bulldogs (25-6) meet seventh-seeded Minnesota
(17-10) in a West Regional first-round game this afternoon at
KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Utah Jazz guard John Stockton, a Gonzaga product, made sure he
was the first to call the players and congratulate them.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga guard Matt Santangelo said ``Mr. Stockton'' has been a
great friend of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Stockton?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't call him that to his face,'' Gonzaga guard Matt
Santangelo said. ``I call him John. But when I talk about him to
anyone else, it's Mr. Stockton. I just have a tremendous amount of
respect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga has gained a tremendous amount of respect around the
nation by winning 49 games the past two seasons, many at their home
court, the Kennel.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Bulldogs beat Washington and Washington State
of the Pac-10, the first time they've defeated both in the same
season in 55 years.
</P>
<P>
   They also led Kansas, ranked eighth in the country at the time,
for a half on the road before losing; beat Memphis and played at
Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we can play with anybody,'' Frahm said. ``I think
we're going to be an overachiever in the NCAA Tournament starting
with (today).''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs win because of their hot-shooting guards _ Frahm
(14.2 scoring average) and Santangelo (12.7).
</P>
<P>
   In the conference tournament title game, Gonzaga hit 18
three-point field goals, eight by Santangelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last two years, Mr. Stockton has taken me aside to
work out with him,'' said Santangelo, a 6-foot-1 junior from
Portland. ``It consists of basically a shooting routine and maybe
some one-on-one. The lessons I've learned after playing with him
are competitiveness, scrap, desire and the know-how to win. Those
are the things I've most tried to copy from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of the Bulldogs were highly recruited. Center Jeremy Eaton,
6-9, is known as much for his calf roping than he is for his
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   He could be the tallest team roper in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I do (in the summer) instead of working,'' Eaton
said. ``Most of the (ropers) call me, `Stretch.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga has done so well, it could lose its second-year coach,
Dan Monson, son of former Oregon Coach Don Monson.
</P>
<P>
   Monson, 38, is expected to be a candidate to replace Kevin
Eastman at Washington State. Eastman resigned under pressure
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach is going to be a hot commodity,'' Frahm said. ``It's
interesting to see what he does, where he goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Monson said he isn't thinking about going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for Kevin Eastman,'' Monson said. ``He's a good
coach. He does it the right way. My family went through the same
situation at Oregon, so I have compassion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any interest in any other job. I love it at
Gonzaga. My parents live there. I'm marrying a girl from there.
I've preached to the kids that team comes first. It would be
selfish of me to say that and to be worrying about other jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Monson and the Bulldogs enter the tournament loose. They ended
practice Wednesday with the coach hitting two half-court shots, one
on each end of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been on fire all year,'' Santangelo said. ``We (shoot
half-court shots) before every game. It doesn't surprise me that he
steps up before the big games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
