<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6023 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SOUTH-ARIZONA-AZR     03-11 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDCATS GIVE CREDIT TO `COACH O' FOR ONGOING SUC CESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Even the premier basketball programs like Duke,
Kentucky, UCLA and Kansas have slip-ups. Somewhere along the way a
subpar season that puts them either into the NIT or in front of a
television to watch the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   With more top players bolting for the pros early into their
college careers, maintaining continuity is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly what's happened at Arizona, which this season
has extended the second-longest streak in NCAA Tournament history
to 15 consecutive appearances. Record-holder North Carolina made
the field for the 25th straight year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats (22-6, fourth seed in the Midwest Region) meet
Oklahoma (20-10, 13th seed) Friday afternoon at approximately 1
p.m. Arizona time.
</P>
<P>
   If the Wildcats were going to falter, this might have been the
year. They had to replace four starters who won the NCAA title two
years ago and won 30 games last year.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to astute judgment four years ago, the Wildcats held
their ground. It was then, a year before he signed Mike Bibby, that
UA Coach Lute Olson recruited Jason Terry. Olson wouldn't have
gotten a player like Terry if Bibby were already in the program.
But even after Bibby arrived, Terry stayed with the program,
content as sixth man while Bibby started at point guard for two
seasons before bailing for the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to dodge the bullet this year because of the
great play of these seniors,'' Olson said, referring not only to
Terry, a first-team All-American, but also all-conference center
A.J. Bramlett.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine this UA team if freshmen Ruben Douglas and Traves Wilson
had manned the backcourt spots alone. Terry led the Pac-10 in
scoring, assists and steals and made critical shots time after time
in close games. In the process, he has claimed every national
player of the year award announced thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Olson handed the ball to Terry in October, and he's been in
nearly every minute of every game since. And Arizona's long
tournament streak lives another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's been a strength of this program it's been the
ability to get the pieces to fit,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no secret why we're in the tournament 15 years in a
row,'' said power forward Michael Wright, the Pac-10 Freshman of
the Year. ``It's Coach O. He teaches us how to play, and he gets us
to work hard at it. That's why there are no downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry said it goes beyond that, to Olson recognizing the impact
of guards on the college game, and placing an importance there in
recruiting. Terry said the family atmosphere that permeates the
program, in which Olson gives veteran players blackball authority
on prospective recruits, is equally important.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've just got to credit Coach O and his recruiting style and
how the program is set up,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives guards a lot of freedom. Guards dictate the style of
play you have. That's why he has had so many great guards in the
past and why he'll continue to have them.''
</P>
<P>
   The progression of guards began with Steve Kerr, followed by
Khalid Reeves, Damon Stoudamire, Bibby, and Terry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always prided ourselves here as being a teaching
staff,'' Olson said. ``It's not a case of us rolling the ball out
and screaming and hollering and not going about teaching things in
a normal progression. That's part of the reason we've had guys go
out of the program and do very well overseas or in the NBA because
they've been taught the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's working. With this 15th straight NCAA Tournament
appearance, Olson passes John Thompson, who stepped down this
season at Georgetown, for the second place all-time. Former North
Carolina Coach Dean Smith, who retired two years ago, holds the
record with 23 in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, Olson likely will break another milestone record.
With 395 wins at Arizona, Olson is eight away from passing
legendary Fred Enke for coaching victories at the school. It took
Enke 29 years. Next year will be Olson's 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he's the best coach in America,'' freshman Richard
Jefferson said. ``He's a great coach, he recruits great players, he
has great assistant coaches, and he's in a great place. That's why
he has a winning tradition. It's not rocket science. It's just a
matter of doing what he needs to to to be successful.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
