r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-ARIZONA-SHOOTING-     03-11 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-SHOOTING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A THEORY: BIG GUN, BIG BANG  
 50-CALIBER RIFLE RE VERBERATES WITH POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The .50-caliber rifle has been reborn, and that has
sparked some controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Big cartridge rifles have been around for a long time, spawned
by the British .55-caliber rifles that were used as anti-tank
weapons in the world wars.
</P>
<P>
   The .50-caliber variety was used in the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Rock McMillan, president of the McMillan Brothers Rifle Co. in
north Phoenix, said the sporting use of the 50s began in the early
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan also manufactures what generally are considered to be
the best fiberglass rifle stocks anywhere. The custom rifles
themselves aren't too shabby.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan said the development of effective muzzle breaks, which
redirect muzzle blast to the rear and thus lessen the recoil,
helped make the .50-caliber rifle ``more feasible,'' according to
McMillan, whose company makes 50s.
</P>
<P>
   The .50 is a huge gun. Target shooting models weigh somewhere
near 50 pounds. Some of the hunting varieties weigh around 32
pounds. A standard hunting rifle weighs about nine pounds, and you
know how heavy they get when carrying them long distances.
</P>
<P>
   This obviously isn't a firearm you carry too far.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1986, Rock's father, the company's founder, was
approached by the military to build a .50-caliber rifle. The
25-pound gun was to be used mainly as a sniper rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the same quarters with McMillan is Arizona Ammunition,
owned by Jim Schmidt of Phoenix. It's a small company that builds
custom shells for various guns. Sixty percent of its business,
according to Schmidt, is ammunition for 50-caliber rifles. In fact,
his is the largest producer of 50-caliber rifle ammunition in the
world. There are no main-line companies making the shells in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   The gun is controversial because it's big, it's loud, and it's
becoming more and more popular. It is banned at Ben Avery Schooting
Facility in north Phoenix until a new range can be built to
accommodate the gun safely.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt is an interesting man. He was a top official in Phoenix
bus transit. He also was involved with transportation in the
Atlanta Olympics and head of transportation for Woodstock. He'll do
the same this year for Woodstock '99.
</P>
<P>
   There are larger projectiles than the .50-caliber. The so-called
elephant guns, usually with side-by-side barrels, have the size but
not the speed of a 50.
</P>
<P>
   The 577 nitro develops 10,000 foot pounds of energy at the
muzzle. The 700 nitro, a larger gun, develops 8,900 foot pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The .50-caliber yields 13,000 foot pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the speed and weight of the .50-caliber round, it is
far less effected by wind, a major cause of inaccuracy at long
ranges.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes it an excellent long-range gun,'' Schmidt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt makes ammunition for the military, law enforcement
agencies, hunters and target shooters. He also sells shells to the
U.S. Department of Energy and a number of foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a cheap game. Normal .50-caliber shells sell for $5
apiece. Specialty shells sell for more than twice that much.
</P>
<P>
   How far can the 50 shoot accurately? Buddy Clifton, who is a
three-time world champion with the 50, can hit a four-inch grouping
at 1,000 yards.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Army is testing Schmidt's loads that will be
accurate at 2,000 yards. Imagine what kind of scope it will take to
shoot at that distance.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters using the 50 don't exactly walk around in the forest
carrying the gun. It's too heavy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the hunters are real serious trophy hunters,'' Schmidt
said. ``They'll lie in the woods in the same spot all day for a
really big elk. They're looking for animals they can't get close
to. Most of their shots are under 1,000 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said one customer bought ammunition to kill feral pigs
in Texas. The man was a rancher south of Corpus Christi, and the
pigs were eating all his cattle food.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they even saw the dust from his pickup, they'd take off,''
Schmidt said. ``He needed to shoot them at 800 to 1,000 yards.
</P>
<P>
   One of the advantages Schmidt has in the market is that he has
several methods of coating bullets to perform better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a real leader in that,'' he said. ``We're also
constantly testing our ammunition in all kinds of guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers send them their guns, and Schmidt tests them with
various ammunition to see what works best.
</P>
<P>
   To allow a reporter to test various rifles, Schmidt took him to
a shooting range.
</P>
<P>
   The first gun was a 30-378 made by McMillan. This magnum gun was
developed in the 1950s by Weatherby. But it didn't perform well
until new propellants and bullets were developed, Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were three 50s: a McMillan bench rest for
competition, a Barrett semiautomatic for tactical use (such as
shooting criminals or enemies at long range) and an L.A.R. Grizzly
used for hunting.
</P>
<P>
   The McMillan, because of its competition stock, weighs 45 pounds
and sells for $5,000. You almost need a cart to move it. The
Barrett weighs about 35 pounds and sells for at least $6,000. But
SWAT teams and military snipers like it a lot. The L.A.R., which
has its bolt clear at the back, weighs 32 pounds and sells for
about $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan, Barrett, L.A.R., Armalight, A-Mac and ROBAR all
recommend Schmidt's ammunition for their rifles.
</P>
<P>
   All four rifles used at the range were equipped with muzzle
breaks. With the 50s at least it's necessary to keep the shooter
from lying on his back after a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-378, which moves at about 3,000 feet per second with
factory loads, was upgraded to 3,613 fps with Schmidt's ammunition.
The recoil wasn't uncomfortable from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The target 50 is so heavy it doesn't kick badly at all. But as
the weight decreased in the other two, the recoil was heavier but
not particularly uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   But as the rifle discharges, the shooter can't keep the gun
stationary. It moves back and the shooter with it.
</P>
<P>
   The muzzle break sends gases from the barrel around the shooter,
so you better stand directly behind or the discharge will cause
your hair to stand up. One round blew the carpet off the adjacent
bench and broke Schmidt's wind gauge.
</P>
<P>
   Some other shooters ask why anyone would buy a 50. The best
answer: because they want one. It's an expensive gun and expensive
to shoot. But hotrods are expensive and boats a black hole to throw
money into. But their owners want them.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt recommends only two brand name scopes for 50s: The
Leopold 16, 24 or 32 power and the Nightforce variable in the 24 or
32 power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 50 will tear up any other scope,'' he said. ``The 50 has
similar vibrations to an air gun, and most scope makers warn you
that their scopes can't be used on an air gun.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
