<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-CAVALIERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUMBLING SUNS CAN'T STOP CAVS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Suns need to hang one of those welcoming signs at
America West Arena that says: ``Mi Casa es su Casa''.
</P>
<P>
   ``My house is your house.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns made another guest feel right at home Wednesday night,
and they were booed off the floor for a second straight home game
after falling to the Cleveland Cavaliers, 86-73.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not taking care of our home court,'' said Suns guard
Jason Kidd. ``And it would be even worse if we weren't playing the
way we are on the road. We have to figure out how to play at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   They could start by figuring out how to score at home. The 73
points represents the club's lowest offensive output ever in a home
game _ America West or Veterans Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Only a 68-point effort against the Kansas City Kings in 1981 was
more pathetic than what the Suns accomplished against the
Cavaliers, and that was on the road. The Suns broke their previous
home worse of 74 set _ surprise _ earlier this season against Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns fell to 4-6 on their own floor.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't come out as flat as they did in an embarrassing
defeat to the Sacramento Kings in their last home game, but their
shots weren't falling and their patience wore thin as the game
progressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter where we play, we've got to make shots,''
forward Danny Manning said. ``It's rough to lose at home. It's
frustrating to see th e way we shot the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns shot just 35.4 percent, making 29 of 82 shots. They
turned the ball over 13 times, but it seemed as if the total might
be twice that. They were outrebounded 42-39, the seventh game in a
row they've been outrebounded.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cavaliers came into the game at the bottom of every
rebounding category in the league. The Cavaliers also had 10 steals
and the Suns three.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing the Suns are losing more often than the ball is
their followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't blame it on the crowd,'' Manning said. ``We get booed
on the road, too. We've just got to go out and make it better.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, nothing seems to have accomplished that.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Jason Kidd talked to the club after a loss to the Los
Angeles Lakers, and they responded for one game, beating Seattle.
General Manager Bryan Colangelo cut short a trip to Europe to
return to the Valley after hearing about the Sacramento debacle.
And club President Jerry Colangelo said he spoke with Coach Danny
Ainge and forward Tom Gugliotta within the past couple of days to
try to determine why the Suns are in such a malaise.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers emerged from an ugly first half leading, 45-38,
after the Suns went almost eight minutes without a field goal
during one second-quarter stretch. The Suns shot 39 percent, and
they only got 36 field-goal attempts against the Cavaliers'
plodding style. The Suns turned the ball over eight times.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cleveland forward Shawn Kemp had 14 first-quarter
points against the starting front line of Tom Gugliotta, Luc
Longley and Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said the Suns didn't even have time to get double-team
help to Kemp before he scored on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Suns reserve Clifford Robinson came off the bench to get Kemp
under control, and he scored only four more points the rest of the
way. But the Suns never could hit the important shots, and again
struggled to execute offensively in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a pattern,'' Ainge said. ``And that pattern is,
when we're struggling with our shooting, we're struggling to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not making enoughs shots right now. And we had some
breakdowns defensively in the fourth quarter that there is no
excuse for. I don't know if our team is suffering from a lack of
confidence right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a difficult time making baskets. There is no excuse for
those type of mistakes down the stretch. We're not focused, and
that's my job, to make sure guys are concentrating. If they're not,
I have to put guys out there that will. And it's very
discouraging.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
