<HEADLINE>
KILLER OF STUDENT TOOK PAINS TO CONCEAL CLUES, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kansas) (sw) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The killer of a 26-year-old graduate student in
Brooklyn on Monday night was careful to conceal clues to the fatal
stabbing, apparently going so far as to wrap the murder weapon in
plastic before plunging it into the woman's back, law enforcement
officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said that
the handle of the six-inch, smooth-edged kitchen knife used to kill
the victim, Amy Watkins, had been wrapped in a white shopping bag
before the attack and that there were no fingerprints. No blood was
found on the sidewalk near the body, a law enforcement official
said, and the knife was driven through Ms. Watkins's heavy winter
coat and wedged deeply into her back, indicating a killer of some
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins was killed shortly before 10 p.m. less than two
blocks from her home, as she was walking from a subway station.
Neighbors on the block said on Tuesday that they heard two distinct
screams, the first one of fear, the second in apparent pain. Ms.
Watkins was found clutching the bag of groceries she had bought
from a store on Flatbush Avenue, near the subway station.
</P>
<P>
   With little physical evidence and no apparent eyewitnesses to
the killing, detectives have continued combing the Prospect Heights
neighborhood, asking for help from residents and interviewing Ms.
Watkins' friends and neighbors. Police Commissioner Howard Safir
said on Wednesday that 25 homicide detectives were working on the
case but had yet to come up with any suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some leads that we are following but we could
certainly use help from anyone who has information relative to this
crime,'' Safir said. He added that although the police believe the
motive was robbery, ``we're not ruling anyone out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins, clad in a black overcoat, black wool cap, purple
gloves and a black and gold silk scarf, was found with no money,
purse or identification, the police said. An investigator who spoke
on the condition of anonymity said the police were trying to
determine whether she might have been killed by the same suspect
who robbed a pedestrian at knifepoint in the area a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The knife punctured one of Ms. Watkins's lungs and her aorta,
said Ellen Borakove, a spokeswoman for the city medical examiner's
office. She was pronounced dead at 10:45 p.m. at Interfaith Medical
Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 0042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
