r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-AZR &LR;      03-11 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL KEEPSAKES SHOT IN ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That bright blue background on your favorite player's baseball
card might be a dazzling Arizona sky.
</P>
<P>
   Once each spring, the players dutifully march before the hordes
of still and video photographers on picture day. The results grace
the ever-expanding variety of trading cards, and are also the ones
pulled later in the season for newspapers, ``plays of the day'' on
TV, and lineups on stadium jumbo screens.
</P>
<P>
   The rookies are the first ones out of the dugout, giving the
veterans a few more minutes of beauty sleep before they saunter
before the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The players sometimes clown around, pitchers posing with bats
and left-handers switching to the right side of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it's usually only the best and most accurate
shots that make it onto the shelves and into the shoe boxes of
kids' card collections.
</P>
<P>
   The days of the nickel pack of five cards _ and a piece of often
stale, crumbly bubble gum _ have been replaced with flashy ones
that routinely cost up to $2 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball trading cards now top $525 million in annual retail
sales. The cards not only are an important revenue stream for
baseball owners and players, they provide an essential advertising
link to new generations of fans, especially young boys.
</P>
<P>
   Today's cards feature thicker paper, foil-treated to resist
scratches and fading, bobbing heads and authenticating holograms,
just like credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   But no gum.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, some of the higher-end cards sport actual player
signatures, not just machine copies. And a few of the most
expensive cards even have minute pieces of jersey and bats _
actually used by the players _ embedded right in the card.
</P>
<P>
   Also gone are the patently faked poses and over-exposed flashes
of baseball yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cards have action shots on them,'' said Terry Melia, media
manager for Upper Deck Co. of Carlsbad, Calif., one of four trading
card companies officially licensed by Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Some players are photographed several times a year as they go
from team to team through trades or free-agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always trying to keep up with the players,'' said Melia,
a former editor of ``Trading Cards Magazine.'' ``With free agency,
these guys jump ship quick.''
</P>
<P>
   The value of each card depends on its condition, its scarcity,
the popularity of the player and that player's achievements.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a mint condition 1968 Topps rookie card for pitcher
Nolan Ryan had been valued at nearly $850. When Ryan was inducted
into the Baseball Hall of Fame this past year, the value of that
card soared overnight to more than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although baseball cards remain the most popular of all sports
trading cards, the most valuable card is that of recently retired
basketball superstar Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   An Upper Deck, personally autographed, limited edition,
sequentially numbered, Michael Jordan card with a swatch of one of
his jerseys, actually worn by during a game, is valued at nearly
$12,000, Melia said.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball trading cards originally were found in packs of cigars
and cigarettes. They made their real breakthrough when the Topps
Co. of New York started packing cards with gum in the 1950s, said
Colin Hagen, director of trading cards, collectibles and
memorabilia for Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1980s, Topps was synonymous with trading cards. By
the late '80s and early '90s, six companies were licensed to sell
the cards.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, two companies _ Pinnacle and Donruss _ have,
well, folded their cards.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Upper Deck and Topps, the industry shakeout still leaves
Pacific Trading Cards Co. of Seattle and Fleer/SkyBox International
of Mount Laurel, N.J. But the number of cards is proliferating,
thanks to a continuous demand for new and different cards,
especially those that incorporate new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Upper Deck, the only company licensed in five sports (baseball,
basketball, football, hockey and motor sports) carries six classes
of baseball cards, Melia said, and may have as many as 20 sets of
different cards issued each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's literally thousands of slides per sport, some of them
(thousands) per player, here at an extensive library,'' Melia said.
</P>
<P>
   Even for a relatively obscure player, such as Eddie Zosky, a
utility infielder for the Milwaukee Brewers, nearly 70 trading
cards have been issued.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest collectors are the players themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have one of each,'' said Zosky, who has played for half a
dozen clubs and minor-league teams in his 11-year career, including
a stint with the former Phoenix Firebirds. ``I have some kids at
home. When they get older, it will be a big thrill for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Zosky's favorite photo? A rookie-idol card shot when Zosky
played with the Toronto Blue Jays, in which he got to share the
limelight with the iron man of baseball, the Baltimore Orioles' Cal
Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   Zosky said he's never had a trading card photo he's ashamed of.
In fact, he said, ``It's an honor.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
