<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPP-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE CRASHES OUT IN BOULDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ One by one, the Pepperdine basketball players
walked out of the locker room. After a few minutes, it was apparent
the last guy out would be Jelani Gardner. His college career was
over, sooner than he and the rest of the Waves wanted. Gardner
missed a potential winning shot in the closing seconds of the
Waves' 65-61 loss to host Colorado in the first round of the
National Invitation Tournament on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I failed,'' Gardner said. ``I guess that's just part of the
game. Wherever I play next, I'll take that last shot again.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine finished 19-13. Colorado (18-14) advances to play
intrastate rival Colorado State in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Flash back to Feb. 28 in the semifinals of the West Coast
Conference Tournament. Gardner, a senior guard, takes a long
3-pointer that falls short with five seconds left and Pepperdine
goes on to lose to Santa Clara 58-54.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Gardner took a running 12-footer that banked off the
backboard and rolled off the side of the rim. The Buffaloes got the
rebound and held on to win for the seventh time in eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would like to see (Gardner) hit one of those,'' Pepperdine
head coach Lorenzo Romar said. ``We have no problem with who took
the shot. His feet didn't allow him to come to a complete stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was just 2 of 12 from the field, including 0 for 6 on
3-point attempts, and finished with six points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad way to go out, but I think I'll get the
message,'' said Gardner, a devout Christian. ``I believe everything
happens for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin Gibbs, a sophomore forward who becomes the Waves' top
player with the graduation of Gardner, said he was disappointed the
careers of Gardner and senior Marc McDowell were over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel for them right now,'' said Gibbs, who scored 10 points
and grabbed 10 rebounds despite an infected right knee.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves lost despite holding the Buffaloes without a
3-pointer; Kenny Price made nine 3's himself in CU's last game, a
loss to Texas in the Big 12 Tournament. The last time Colorado
didn't make a 3-pointer in a game was in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Colorado shot 51 percent for the game. In the contest's
first 10 minutes, the Buffaloes made many easy shots inside and in
transition. The Waves responded in the second half behind defensive
leader Tommie Prince, the WCC's Defender of the Year who held Price
to just four points.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Prince) is just phenomenal,'' Romar said. ``Ninety percent of
the time he has shut down the opposing team's top player.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the defensive pressure, Pepperdine held the Buffaloes
seven points under their season average.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves took a 61-60 lead with 1:40 seconds left on a basket
by Gibbs. The Buffaloes responded with a layup by Jamahl Mosley,
who was fouled on the play, to make it 62-61 with 1:27 remaining.
Mosley finished with a game-high 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves had a chance to take the lead with 20 seconds left,
but junior center Nick Sheppard fumbled the ball out of bounds as
he took a pass inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a layup,'' Romar said. ``We wanted to get the
ball inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
