r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ANALYSIS2-LADN-(S     03-11 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ANALYSIS2-LADN-(SLANG)CORRECTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE RAISES MORE QUESTIONS THAN ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 RICE CONTRACT STATUS (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A blockbuster trade for a team in the midst
of a nine-game winning streak? Even though four of those victories
are against the Clippers, it sounds like the type of move reserved
for the one of the NBA's knee-jerk franchises, like the Pistons,
Raptors or, yes, Hornets. Certainly not the Lakers, whose every
move seems to be thoughtfully calibrated. Or at least used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's trade that sent Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell to
Charlotte for Glen Rice, J.R. Reid and B.J. Armstrong was only the
latest example that the franchise is becoming the NBA's version of
the Fox-run Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The urgency to win a title, combined with the on-again,
off-again tension between owner Jerry Buss and executive vice
president Jerry West, is creating transactions that seem better
suited for teams in need of a major overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is considered heresy to criticize any decision West
makes, and the acquisition of Dennis Rodman has been brilliant, the
five-player trade with Charlotte raises plenty of questions. Rice,
one of the best pure shooters around, isn't completely healthy and
has yet to play a game this season. He's been sidelined with an
injury in his shooting elbow, and those injuries are tricky to deal
with.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Rice is 100 percent, he has to jell with the rest of
the lineup, not exactly ideal circumstances for a team trying to
ready itself for a title run with 30-odd games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Reid is essentially a throw-in to make the deal work under the
salary cap. Armstrong seemed like a valuable addition, a veteran
with championship experience to spell Derek Harper. So what did the
Lakers do? They waived him a few hours after the trade.
</P>
<P>
   From West's perspective, the trade made sense because the Lakers
add an outside shooter (if healthy) and become instantly older.
That's right, older. Neither Buss nor West wanted to wait until
Shaquille O'Neal or Kobe Bryant reached 30 to win another title.
</P>
<P>
   In order to compete against Utah or Indiana, the Lakers needed
to add some veterans, according to the conventional wisdom. But
didn't Rodman already take care of that void?
</P>
<P>
   This trade not only alters the roster, it demolishes team
chemistry. If Rice plays small forward, what happens to Rick Fox?
He's demonstrated loyalty by signing one-year deals the past two
seasons, and is now about to be buried on the bench. That's too
bad, since Fox is one of the few good influences in the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Robert Horry, who will never see minutes at his
natural position of small forward and continue to play out of
position at power forward. He'll now split time with Travis Knight
and Reid. Oh yeah, and Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Lakers are making moves, one wonders if Rice will be
back if they don't win the title this year. The Lakers have an
option to re-sign him for the 1999-2000 season, but he's a free
agent after that season, and even though the NBA now has a salary
scale, Rice is represented by mega-agent David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   There's another reason to dislike the trade. Falk is generally
detested by most NBA teams, and even though he's been diminished by
the current labor agreement, don't think he won't pester West about
trading for or signing some of his other clients, and use Rice as a
bargaining chip to do it.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of nuisance Washington and Miami have dealt
with, but not the Lakers. But the way the revolving door keeps
spinning, the Lakers are resembling those teams more every day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 0108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6049 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-NCAA-HNS &LR;      03-11 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-NCAA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
``Twenty-two hours, Bryce!''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shout came across the court after the Rockets' practice
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-two hours!''
</P>
<P>
   Bryce Drew's face lit up. He didn't have to ask what would
happen in less than one day. All he really needed was a television
with a broadcast of Valparaiso in the first round of the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets today will be completing their game-day shootaround
during the start of Valpo's first Tournament game since Drew became
an NBA rookie. But part of his heart remains behind. And when work
for the morning is over, Drew will waste no time in getting away
from Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   And though perhaps no Rockets player is as recognized as an NCAA
Tournament hero as Drew _ ``an icon,'' teammates Matt Maloney and
Brent Price called him _ each seemed as eager to see his alma mater
in the Big Dance.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about their own Tournament experiences, a few Rockets will
offer personal reflections. But most talk about glory days
hesitantly. Michael Dickerson, a member of Arizona's national
championship team in 1997, said he almost never thinks about the
title run.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Dickerson about Arizona this season, or Cuttino Mobley
about Rhode Island, Charles Barkley about Auburn or Pig Miller
about Michigan State, and eyes turn bright, predictions are made
and challenges are issued across the locker room. Being a college
fan is irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said he would join Auburn, the No. 1 seed in the South
Regional, at the Final Four in St. Petersburg, Fla., even if it
meant missing a Rockets game. Hearing this, Miller said he expects
his Spartans, the top seed in the Midwest, to be there and would do
anything he could _ perhaps short of missing a game _ to see them
chase a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most fun time of the year for basketball, in my
opinion,'' said Price, who played in two NCAA Tournaments with
South Carolina and Oklahoma. ``I think it's your best basketball.
Every game counts; every team is hyped. The excitement, the
upsets.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley will say little about leading Rhode Island within a game
of last year's Final Four, a run that included wins over No. 1
Kansas and Drew's Valpo team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice,'' the usually expansive Mobley said. ``If I sit
around and think about it, it's all right, but right now, I haven't
been able to think about it too much. The NBA is so busy.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Mobley considered the possibility of Rhode Island's
playing Arizona in the second round, the volume burst out of him
and toward Dickerson's quiet corner of the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rhode Island's going to be whipping them,'' Mobley shouted in
Dickerson's direction. ``Michael and I are going to watch that
together, and Lamar (Odom, the Rhode Island star) is going to be
whipping them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be fun. I'm not going to watch the first round,
because I don't want to jinx them. After that, it's going to be
fun. I'm happy they got in it, and I'm looking forward to watching
them.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Dickerson, he smiled happily at the mention of this
year's Wildcats and their chance for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy they got in, and I want (Arizona guard) Jason Terry
to do well,'' Dickerson said.
</P>
<P>
   And for Mobley's benefit, if not with his amplification,
Dickerson said, ``J.T.'s going to take care of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite not having enjoyed the same sort of Tournament success
personally, Miller had similar predictions for his school. Though
Mobley's Rams and Dickerson's Wildcats are in the Midwest with
Michigan State, Miller said the Spartans should face Duke in the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were put in the toughest bracket, but that's all right,''
Miller said. ``I like our chances. I'd love them to show everybody
how they're capable of playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The furthest we got when I was there was the (second round).
We were going to try to win it or at least see how far we could go.
It was tough (losing so early). But that won't happen this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, however, said he was not hoping to replace a lost
opportunity vicariously with a Spartans run this season. Barkley,
whose Auburn team lost in the first round in his lone Tournament
experience, said that also has nothing to do with his interest in
this season's Big Dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good time, but it wasn't a big deal like it is now,''
Barkley said. ``It wasn't March Madness back then. But everybody
wanted to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just support my alma mater. I support my school in whatever
it does.''
</P>
<P>
   If players are not interested in reliving past glory, or making
up for a lost opportunity, they can relate to the experiences to
come better than most. Forward Rodrick Rhodes went to the
Tournament three times with Kentucky and once with Southern
California and seemed to prefer the feeling that came with USC's
breakthrough to Kentucky's expected success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went for three years with Kentucky, and one year we only
went to the Sweet 16 and that was a bad year,'' Rhodes said. ``I
never really knew the madness of March Madness until I went to 'SC.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Kentucky (which has since won two national championships),
we just didn't know if we were a No. 1 or No. 2 seed. At 'SC, we
were a bubble team when we made it. It was total madness. I know
how the teams that were on the bubble and got in are feeling right
now. We knew we were going to make it at Kentucky. Getting in was a
big deal at 'SC.''
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon, who led Houston to the Final Four three times,
also thinks of the pressure of expectations that he said became
similar to NBA pressures. He did not, however, lament that burden
or the title that so narrowly eluded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the best, or some of the best, times,'' Olajuwon
said. ``Then, all I knew was the Final Four. It became like normal.
There was a lot of pressure. We have created the idea of the Final
Four and the NCAA championship, and the prospects for players with
the NBA with pro scouts. That was pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, the start of another Tournament could not help but
remind at least one last time of the previous one. Drew's
last-second 3-pointer lifted Valpo past Mississippi and made him a
symbol of the Tournament's ability to surprise and inspire, a story
made that much more complete when he celebrated in a hug with his
father Homer Drew, the Valparaiso coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great moment, not only for the school to make it to
the Sweet 16 but with my family,'' Drew said. ``March will always
be a blessed month to have in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But his time as an ``NCAA icon,'' Drew said, is almost over, and
he almost seemed to relish the idea of another great moment coming,
maybe even within 22 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am (an icon) for one more day,'' he said. ``Then someone
else will hit that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   And in 2{ weeks, Dickerson said from experience, ``Someone will
feel just great. It will be like a dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
