<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6052 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-TRADE-LADN-(SLANG     03-11 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TRADE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF RICE AND MEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Lake Show is dead. Long live the New
Millennium Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   A slow, sometimes painful retooling of one of the NBA's most
talented teams was completed Wednesday, when the Lakers traded
veterans Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell to Charlotte for forwards
Glen Rice and J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   The long-rumored swap took place after weeks of deliberation
within the walls of the Forum, and only after Rice's surgically
repaired right elbow passed muster three days ago. Now, with one of
the NBA's best pure shooters joining an already-potent lineup, the
Lakers believe they are primed for a run at their first
championship since the 1980s Showtime era.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have the best center in the league (Shaquille
O'Neal), we probably have the best rebounder in the league, in
Dennis Rodman, and maybe we'll have the best shooter and one of the
best small forwards (Rice),'' said Lakers executive vice president
Jerry West. ``We do think we have an attractive team, a team that
can compete in a playoff series against anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't necessarily the case before the trade, despite an
impressive eight-game winning streak, West said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You people look at wins like we're really playing well. I
don't necessarily (think so), nor do our coaches. . . . We've been
winning basketball games. To say they've been impressive, I would
say no,'' he said. Rice also filled a need. ``The bottom line is we
just didn't feel we had anyone here who could make shots on a
consistent basis, particularly when the game was on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade, which comes on the heels of the Rodman signing, cuts
the last significant ties to the post-Showtime, Del Harris-coached
``Lake Show'' era. Harris was fired two weeks ago, Nick Van Exel
was traded last June, and now Jones and Campbell, both Lakers draft
picks in the early 1990s, are gone. No Laker on the roster has been
here longer than three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lake Show has been buried, I guess,'' said Rick Fox.
``It's a totally different era, with new coaching . . . new
players. Hope we get new results, that'd be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate future could be bright. Rice has been one of the
NBA's top 3-point shooters, averaging 44 percent accuracy the last
three seasons and 20.8 points per game for his career. The only
concern was his surgically repaired elbow. Lakers scouts watched
him shoot Monday, and ``they called back with glowing reports,''
West said. ``He's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice and Reid will arrive today and could play Friday night
against Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte had been ready to deal for weeks, but the Lakers were
hesitant to trade Jones, a fan favorite and one of the best
defenders in the league. They had been trying to unload Campbell
and his $7 million-a-year salary for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very, very difficult decision, an agonizing
decision,'' West said. ``We wrestled with it for a long time. I
don't think we've ever had anything as difficult to do as this.''
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Armstrong was also obtained in the trade for salary cap
purposes, but was immediately waived. The Lakers also waived Corie
Blount and activated rookie forward Ruben Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Just another emotional day in an already tumultuous season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a day full of ups and downs,'' coach Kurt Rambis said.
``It was really tough to talk to Eddie and to Elden. . . . It's
tough to let those guys go. They were friends. It really hurt. But
I believe they are going to a situation where they are going to
prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   Few players had talked to Jones, who couldn't be reached for
comment. Jones issued a statement through his attorney, expressing
his ``gratitude and appreciation'' to fans and teammates. ``I am
thankful and relieved that there is now closure,'' said Jones, who
had been noticeably bothered by the trade rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a former starter relegated to backup minutes the last
two seasons, gets a new start in Charlotte, where he'll be the
starting center.
</P>
<P>
   With 30 games left, the Lakers make their own fresh start,
trying to again adjust to a reshuffled lineup that has seen four of
five starters change since last May. Kobe Bryant will shift to
shooting guard to accommodate Rice at small forward, while Reid
will compete with Travis Knight and Rodman for minutes. Rick Fox
and Robert Horry will fight for time behind Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sit around and moan over losing friends and
players,'' Derek Harper said. ``We have to get back to business
when those guys get here. We have to find a way to welcome those
guys and make this trade work, because it's a done deal now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
