<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE DATA TO BE SOUGHT ON HOME CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Medicare officials said on Wednesday night that
they had instructed home health agencies to start collecting
detailed information on the medical conditions and living
arrangements of millions of elderly and disabled people who receive
home health care services financed by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher H. Peacock, a spokesman for the Federal Health Care
Financing Administration, which runs Medicare, said the data were
needed to ``make sure patients get quality care'' and to develop a
new method of paying home health agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Some privacy advocates have expressed concern that the
government might intrude on the privacy of Medicare beneficiaries
by collecting and analyzing such personal data.
</P>
<P>
   But Peacock said the health care financing agency already
received huge amounts of sensitive information about beneficiaries,
including hundreds of thousands of claims filed each year by
doctors, hospitals and medical laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare already has confidential information about
beneficiaries,'' he said. ``The key is to make sure you safeguard
it. And Medicare does.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the change, reported on Thursday in The Washington Post,
home health agencies will be required to collect a standard set of
data on each Medicare patient they serve. The data will be used to
measure the results of the care and treatment provided to
home-bound patients.
</P>
<P>
   The government will also use the data to measure and improve how
home health agencies care for patients, Peacock said. Home health
agencies will send the data to state officials, who will compile
the information and send it to the federal government, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Providers of home care typically charge Medicare separately for
each home visit. Under the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, the
government is supposed to develop a new method of reimbursement,
perhaps by paying a fixed amount for several months of care.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said they assumed that Medicare would pay home
health agencies more for sicker patients, so the Government would
need detailed information about each patient's condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 0138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
