<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6058 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-HENRY-BOS &LR;      03-11 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-HENRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY BLASTS PAPPAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Players come, players go. Years pass. And one
of the constant themes in the Red Sox clubhouse is questionable
treatment by team physician and limited partner Arthur Pappas.
</P>
<P>
   This column has been written before. When second baseman Marty
Barrett sued the Red Sox in 1992, claiming Pappas misdiagnosed his
wounded knee, it was argued that the Sox should no longer have a
limited partner who doubles as team physician.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation never changed and now we have another ex-Sox
crying foul _ plus one or two players in the present clubhouse with
curious tales of misdiagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   From Peoria, Ariz., former Sox lefthander Butch Henry has hurled
some bombs onto the doorstep of the good doctor. Speaking with Bob
Finnigan of the Seattle Times, Henry, who pitched for the Red Sox
last year, unloaded on Boston's conflicted physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't go back to the Red Sox,'' Henry said. ``I'm
easygoing, and I get along with everyone. But I couldn't have
looked at those people without thinking they had tried to mess with
my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry claims Pappas last year told him he could pitch despite
having a tear in the anterior cruciate ligament of his left knee.
Henry didn't pitch in 1996 because of tendon-replacement surgery on
his left elbow. Pitching for the Sox during spring training last
year, he strained his left hamstring on a baserunning play. Henry
opened the season on the disabled list, then injured his left knee
on his second start and subsequently got into a disagreement with
Pappas and Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas gave Henry an MRI and an arthroscopic examination,
according to the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically said, `You have a partial tear of the ACL and we
think you can pitch on it,' '' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry said one of the Sox trainers advised him to have surgery
on the knee. Henry also said another Sox physician ``told me I had
a 90 percent tear, that I had only 5 to 10 percent left, and that I
was risking my career if I went out and pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Henry, he then met with Duquette, Pappas, and
assistant GM Mike Port and told them he decided to have surgery. He
said Duquette asked him to try pitching, but Henry refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his own way, Dan Duquette is one of the best baseball men
around,'' Henry said. ``But he isn't much of a people person. The
way he treats people leaves a lot to be desired. Dealing with him,
if the way he dealt with me is any indication, is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they held off on the surgery and made me questionable for
this spring, with my career in doubt, then he could offer me a
minor league contract at next to nothing, which he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be fair, Dan had taken care of me when I had injured my
elbow in 1995, signing me for 1996 when I couldn't pitch. But on
the knee, he hung me out to dry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe attempted to get responses from Duquette and Pappas
Wednesday night, but team publicist Kevin Shea said, ``I'm not
going to call them late at night on something like this. Dr. Pappas
always treats his patients as people first. And Butch Henry wanted
to come back to pitch for us this year, but he wanted a lot of
money. It sounds like sour grapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry was paid $1 million by the Red Sox in 1998 and pitched a
total of nine innings in two games. The Sox did not re-sign him for
1999, and the club can certainly say it paid Henry well for his
services. It's also easy to cite sour grapes with a disgruntled
ex-player.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Barrett? He sued the team and Pappas, claiming
his career was cut short because of misdiagnosis and a US District
Court jury awarded him $1.7 million. More recently, Sox youngsters
Brian Rose and Lou Merloni as well as veteran Reggie Jefferson had
difficulty navigating the waters in the Sox' murky medical ward.
</P>
<P>
   Highly-touted rookie Rose made only eight starts last year
because of a bone spur and fracture in his pitching elbow. Rose
hurt his elbow early last season, but the severity of his injury
went undetected by the ballclub. Duquette questioned his
willingness to pitch with pain until Rose finally went to get a
second opinion. Noted orthopedist James Andrews discovered Rose had
a stress fracture and bone spur that was tugging on the ligament in
his elbow every time he threw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know me,'' said Rose, ``and when I'm facing the same guys I
faced the year before and they're telling me I don't look the same,
I knew it had to be one of two things: My mechanics were really
messed up, or there was something wrong with me. And my mechanics
have always been good.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Merloni, a fan favorite, hurt himself running into a
tarp in Yankee Stadium last summer. Pappas initially diagnosed the
injury as inflammation in the knee, then a deep bone bruise. But it
never got better, and it wasn't until several frustrating weeks
later that Merloni found out he had a stress fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson's back injury was originally diagnosed as a strain
last summer and it wasn't until weeks later, when Jefferson visited
back specialist Robert Watkins, that a stress fracture was
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas is a genial fellow and for years pitchers on other teams
have sought his opinion for shoulder problems. He is highly
respected in the medical community and one couldn't expect to meet
a nicer man. But his dual role is a blatant conflict and the Sox
put their legal butts on the line every time he treats an injured
player. Pappas has a fiduciary responsibility that is in direct
conflict with his Hippocratic oath. And as long as the situation
exists, there are very likely to be more Butch Henrys tossing
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason a lot of players have a clause in their
contracts specifying no trades to Boston,'' said Henry. ``The Sox
are notorious for having differences of opinion with injured
players.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
