<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS (Washington) _ The battle over the
nation's scarcest medical resource, human organs, has moved from
Washington to the states, where a number of legislatures have begun
passing laws that would bar donated hearts, lungs, kidneys, livers
and pancreases from being shipped beyond their borders to sick
people elsewhere in the country. So far, the laws have not had a
large effect on the way organs are distributed. Rather, they are
intended to thwart an effort by the Clinton administration to force
organ recovery networks and transplant centers around the nation to
share their precious organs more liberally. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   VA-NY-TRASH (Sussex, Va.) _ In this quiet corner of southern
Virginia, the humans are few, the wildlife plentiful. But if the
county is rich in beauty, it has also been poor in resources. For
years, residents dumped their trash into the nearest hole in the
ground. No new schools had been built in 30 years. That was before
Sussex County discovered garbage. Five years ago, it embarked on a
controversial path that many people believed would improve their
struggling economy while jeopardizing their beloved environs:
accepting a private, state-of-the-art landfill that would import
thousands of tons of garbage a day, much of it from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DROUGHT (Houston) _ Texas is in a worse position than it
was last year at this time and there is fear that if there is
another drought things will be considerably worse. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-PRIZE (Undated) _ The world's largest monetary prize,
the Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion, will be awarded to
Ian G. Barbour, a physicist and theologian who has spent nearly
four decades working to foster a dialogue between science and
religion. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUBBLE-GYROS (Washington) _ Gyroscopes on the Hubble space
telescope are failing more quickly than expected. Rather than one
mission next year, NASA plans to fly a team in October to replace
the gyroscopes, then complete the repairs in 2001. By Warren Leary.
</P>
