<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAURENTS-JOLSON-THEATER-3TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECADES LATER, NAMING NAMES STILL MATTERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Four years ago, the Seattle Repertory Theater presented
the world premiere of ``Jolson Sings Again,'' a play about
informing during the McCarthy era in Hollywood and its toll on
individual lives. Arthur Laurents, the dramatist, director and
screenwriter who wrote the play, knew and worked with two major
artists who informed: the choreographer and director Jerome Robbins
and the stage and film director Elia Kazan. Laurents is the author
of the books for the landmark Broadway musicals ``West Side Story''
and ``Gypsy'' and screenplays for a number of films, including
``The Way We Were'' and ``The Turning Point.''
</P>
<P>
   In February 1995, during the first run of ``Jolson Sings
Again,'' Laurents met Frank Rich, an Op-Ed columnist for The New
York Times, when Rich interviewed him on the stage of the Seattle
Rep about his play.
</P>
<P>
   Laurents subsequently reworked the play, which is now being
presented at the George Street Playhouse in New Brunswick, N.J.,
through March 28. Directed by the theater's artistic chief, David
Saint, the four-member cast includes Betsy Aidem, Jonathan Hadary,
Robert Petkoff and Armand Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   As rehearsals began for the revised version, Rich and Laurents
met once more to talk about ``Jolson Sings Again,'' which describes
what happens among four friends when one of them informs, and about
several of the real-life models on which the characters are based.
Here are excerpts from the conversation.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRANK RICH. ``Jolson Sings Again'' happens to be extraordinarily
timely. This is a moment when people are talking about the
blacklist, when they have revisited Jerome Robbins' history during
the McCarthy period as a consequence of his death last summer and,
of course, when controversy surrounds the recent decision by the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences to grant the director
Elia Kazan an honorary Oscar. Yet you conceived this play when _
way before these events.
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR LAURENTS. In 1992.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. What prompted you to write it then?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. Because I had written ``The Way We Were'' (1973),
which deals with the same thing, and a lot of what I wanted to say
was cut, including the whole climax of the picture, where the
political story and the love story came together. What was terribly
disheartening to me was not only did nobody notice, nobody cared.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. So you wanted to revisit it?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. There was another reason. I was like Julian, the
character in ``Jolson Sings Again.'' I was very black and white. He
says in the play: there were good guys and bad guys. My own life
made me realize it wasn't that simple. I worked with Jerry Robbins
twice, knowing he was an informer.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. You worked with him on ``West Side Story'' and ``Gypsy.''
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. Yes. And then in the 60s, I did a screenplay for
Kazan. He had written a novel called ``The Arrangement'' and asked
me to write the screenplay. I was flattered, because I thought then
and still think that Kazan was the best theater director in my
lifetime, just wonderful. He was producing and directing the
picture. So I said, ``Why aren't you writing the screenplay?'' He
said, ``Because I want another eye.'' That made sense. He gave me
carte blanche: do whatever you want; give him 30 pages at a time.
Which I did. He said, ``Brilliant.'' And when I finished the whole
script, he gave me (italics)his(end italics) script. Which to me
says informers don't stop at informing.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Let's talk about ``Jolson Sings Again,'' which is mainly
set from 1947 to 1952 in Hollywood. Explain the title.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. The title came from a fact: Larry Parks, who was the
first person to testify before the House Un-American Activities
Committee, had played Al Jolson in a movie. When he testified, he
became an informer. And the newsboys on Hollywood Boulevard sang
out, ``Jolson sings again! Jolson sings again!'' To me, it
epitomized the whole period.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. In this play, there is a character named Andreas, who is a
director and an informer. But he couldn't be Kazan because Kazan is
referred to elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. There's another reason: Kazan and others said they
were doing it to save America from communism. Andreas ridicules
that.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Your first hit, ``Home of the Brave,'' about
anti-Semitism, opened on Broadway in 1946 right after the war and
was made into a movie__
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. About a Negro.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. It's one of the bitterly amusing moments in ``Jolson Sings
Again,'' when the audience learns how cavalierly a Hollywood studio
executive can change a writer's intent.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. That passage is absolutely true. I said to Stanley
Kramer, ``Why have you turned the Jew into a Negro?'' He said,
``Because Jews have been done.''
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Because of ``Gentleman's Agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. I said ``Gentleman's Agreement,'' he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. What were your own experiences during the McCarthy period?
You were not blacklisted__
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. Yes, I was blacklisted. I was not a member of the
party. You didn't have to be.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. This was after you wrote ``Rope'' for Hitchcock?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. Yes, and I wasn't mad about being in movies anyway. So
I came back to New York for a play that flopped.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. What was the period that you were blacklisted?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. The late 40s till the middle of the 50s. When I came
back to this country, (the agent) Swifty Lazar said, ``You have to
sign a piece of paper.'' I said, ``You didn't tell me that. What am
I supposed to write?'' He said, ``Anything you want.'' So I wrote,
literally, ``I am not now, nor have I ever been a member of the
Shoeshine Boys Union. Arthur Laurents.'' They took it. They had
something in writing. They didn't care.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. During the period that you were blacklisted, how did you
make a living? Did you write screenplays under a pseudonym?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. No, I went to Paris. People today don't realize how
cheap it was. I was young and it was marvelous. It's a terrible
thing to say about the blacklist, but that's the reason I got
there.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. So when you came back and it was really over, you were
always mainly a theater man__
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. I came back in 1953 for ``The Time of the Cuckoo,''
which may be revived by Lincoln Center Theater this fall.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Did you have any dealings with Kazan during the blacklist
period?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. I only knew him peripherally until ``The
Arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Explain how the blacklist played out on Broadway as
opposed to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. There was absolutely no blacklist in the theater. When
Jerry Robbins was called, he was choreographing ``The King and I,''
which was going to Broadway. They were still out of town. He went
to the producers and they said, ``Do whatever you want.'' The
difference to me was that Broadway producers were individuals, not
corporate producers.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. So someone like Zero Mostel, for instance, who was totally
blacklisted in movies and television, continued to work in the
theater. As for informers, in your play you draw a distinction
between Odets and Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. They informed about the same time. Clifford Odets _
this is my guess _ informed because he thought he was finished. He
was nothing in Hollywood. He had been unsuccessful. When you're
unsuccessful, you're a rat fink, whether you finked or not.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. The biggest crime in Hollywood is to be a failure. What
was it like to work with Robbins? When you worked with him on
``West Side Story'' that would have been '57. So all these wounds
were very fresh.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. Jerry Robbins and I were very, very close friends
earlier than that. There's a line in ``Jolson Sings Again'' that is
a quote from him. He said to me, ``I won't know for years from now
whether I did the right thing.'' And I said to him, ``I can tell
you now, you didn't.'' And he cried. But I couldn't turn my back.
He was my friend. What I found out later, as it says in the play,
was, ``You're not evil because you informed; you informed because
you're evil.'' The friendship ended pretty much with ``West Side
Story.'' When you do something like that, in this case I believe
for career, then you think, ``Well, what the hell.'' You've killed
one person. Now you may as well get the Uzi out and mow them down.
You don't care anymore. You have shut yourself off.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Yet people who were very vocal about the blacklist, for
instance Zero Mostel, worked with him as late as the mid-60s.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. You know the story. Someone said: ``Jerry Robbins is
directing. Would you work with him?'' And Zero said, ``Well, I
don't have to have lunch with him.'' That registered with me. Then
somebody said to me, ``But don't you think that's a cop-out?'' And
that's when I began thinking, ``Who is pristine? Aren't you cutting
your nose off not to work with him because you disapprove of what
he did?'' I worked with Jerry. Zero worked with Jerry, lunch or
not. Jerry was brilliant, there's no question about it.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. There are plenty of examples of people we consider to have
been important artists who were not wonderful people, whether it be
Frank Sinatra or Leni Riefenstahl__
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. Or Ezra Pound. Or T.S. Eliot.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Exactly. So you're saying it is possible, particularly in
a collaborative art form like the theater or the movies, to make
that distinction and go about your business.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. We're talking about famous people, about the arts and
big decisions like McCarthyism and the Hollywood witch hunt. But it
comes down to a daily decision. I think people face or commit
betrayal almost every day in their lives, in one form or another.
And what you have to do is decide what is the line you will or
won't cross. The issue that comes up in ``Jolson Sings Again'' is
very personal to me; it's about friendship, love and betrayal. It's
one thing to work with people like that. Can you really be a
friend? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. One reason you wrote the play was because you realized you
couldn't just say some people were morally reprehensible and some
were on the side of the angels. What are the events in your life
that made the gray start to appear?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. Despite everything, there were parts of Jerry I felt
affection for, but the other thing, that deep character flaw that
enabled him to inform, always kept cropping up.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Yet you retained a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. When he did ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,'' for a very
complicated reason I won't go into, he had to come to me. It had to
do with royalties on the ``West Side Story'' section. It must have
killed him to come to me. But he did. He walked into my house on
the beach _ he hadn't been there in 20 years _ and he said, ``It
hasn't really changed, has it?'' I said, ``No.'' And he said, ``Am
I still in the cigar box?'' Years before, I had a wall in my study
of photographs I took of people I cared about. If they fell from
favor I put them in the cigar box. So I said, ``No, Jerry, the
cigar box is long gone.''
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Reading ``Jolson Sings Again'' in the new version,
everything the informer character, Andreas, does is so slippery.
How he negotiated his way out of the draft in the war; his
extramarital affairs and, finally, his informing. They seem of a
piece. Over the last year in American politics, there have been
many analogies made, not all of them accurate, between McCarthyism
and the sexual witch hunt now. I also think there is something
almost Clintonesque about this character who is an informer. The
qualities that make him slippery make you wonder if someone like
Bill Clinton might have been__
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. When you see it in performance, Andreas has enormous
charm.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. While the standard analogy has been to liken Kenneth Starr
to Joseph McCarthy, there is also a case to be made that Starr's
antagonist, Clinton, in some ways has this kind of shifting moral
center, if there is a moral center, that recalls informers.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. In the case of the character in the play, I don't
think he has a shifting moral center. I think he is an honest
deceiver. He has the virtue of believing it when he does it. I
think they all do, up to a point. You read Kazan's autobiography;
so many times he says he would do it again. While Jerry absolutely
ignored the subject.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Which would lead you to think perhaps he was embarrassed
about it.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. No. I think _ again, it goes back to Clinton _ I think
they can compartmentalize very well.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Is it possible to compartmentalize in terms of Kazan, who
is receiving this honorary Oscar?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. My objection is: he has gotten two Oscars for his
work, but you don't honor the man. Not a man who has destroyed
lives.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Let me play devil's advocate. This isn't the Nobel Prize.
It isn't even the Jean Hersholt Humanitarian Award. It is an Oscar,
which is frequently bestowed on people in Hollywood who have
destroyed lots of lives.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. I think Kazan's motive is what is so awful. He
couldn't have worked in movies unless he testified.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. He's not the only one who had that motive, needless to
say. It still seems to me that this award, unless I'm
misunderstanding it, really isn't honoring him as a human being,
it's honoring his career.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. I think it's honoring him because the American Film
Institute wouldn't. He's 89, let's give him an award. And if you
want to know what I really think, I don't care who gets the Oscar
for anything.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. That's what I'm getting at. How does his receiving this
essentially valedictory award wipe out what he did in terms of
naming names?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. It says it was OK, we can forget about it now.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Let me argue the opposite for a moment. Every day since
the academy announced they were going to do this (at the Oscars
ceremonies next Sunday), there have been stories in the press
pointing out exactly what he did do. This is vividly bringing to
life what naming names meant, much as your play does. It brings
back a history that had been increasingly shrouded in memory since
the end of the Cold War. Everyone is talking about the McCarthy
period again. So can't you have Kazan receive a Hollywood award
that is essentially trivial, at the same time that there are going
to be very spirited protests and a huge public debate about
informing? I don't understand how the academy, simply by giving
this award, is invested with so much power that it can wipe out a
vivid, very well-documented historical record.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. But Kazan can think, ``They honored me. I did the
right thing.'' There is no one in the world who if you give them an
Oscar doesn't believe it's good. No matter what they say about it
before. I don't have much respect for any award, even the Nobel
Prize. They gave it to Pearl Buck.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. I agree.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. But that's the attitude that says: ``What difference
does it make after all? He's 89 years old. He made some good
pictures. Why make such a fuss?'' I do not want him honored as a
person for something he did that was despicable.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. Do you feel that the atmosphere in the country over the
last year has had any resemblance to the McCarthy period? Or is
that notion thrown around too loosely?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. Too casually. During that period you were really
frightened. Even when I came back from Europe and had a successful
play _ ``The Time of the Cuckoo'' _ I realized it vividly when
somebody asked me to sign something and I hesitated. The fact that
I hesitated appalled me, and I knew why. I was afraid. That fear
does not exist now. Even if they point a finger and say you're a
liberal.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. It's not going to affect your livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. It's not going to take away a job.
</P>
<P>
   RICH. You're working with young people on this play _ a young
director, young actors _ with a company that I suspect has a
younger audience than Broadway's. For those too young to remember
the McCarthy period, the fight over Kazan may seem hopelessly
arcane. Both for those involved with the production itself and the
audience, what do you hope another generation will take away from
your play?
</P>
<P>
   LAURENTS. I hope they will be moved. And I hope they will
realize that in your own life, you have to decide what lines you
will cross or won't cross. It has nothing to do with anything as
grandiose as McCarthy and informing. There are everyday betrayals.
The competition for success makes people do terrible things to one
another. I hope this play makes them conscious of that. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Singing at the `Circus' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)In the play ``Jolson Sings Again'' by Arthur Laurents,
the character Andreas, a director, explains why he informed. Here
are excerpts from the scene, set in 1951.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I named names. You have to name names. To prove you are a loyal
American, you have to repent and eat crow. You have to inform.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not going to follow the ex-party line and say I informed to
save the country from Russia and atomic war. That's rationalizing.
How does it justify becoming an informer? My ex-comrades confess
the sins of the American Communist Party at the drop of a
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   I can claim a legitimate beef. I got my cancer because 15 years
ago I was a member of a legal political party for one lousy year!
Most of which I spent arguing against the discipline! And when I
left, I was angrier than any of my fellow performers in the
congressional circus.
</P>
<P>
   But does that justify becoming an informer? They holler there
are card-carrying members sneaking subversive propaganda into the
movies. What movies? How? Are they insane? Even if they believe it,
does that justify naming the names of your friends and co-workers?
</P>
<P>
   There is no political justification for being an informer.
However, I did it. They had all been named before and couldn't be
hurt by me. Still, I named them. I informed. Why.
</P>
<P>
   Have you never wanted something so badly that you threw shame
out the window? That's what I did. Making films is everything to
me. It's my center, my identity, my reason for being. I don't claim
that's a justification. It's my explanation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
