<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6102 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOCKNEY-POSTER-ART-$A     03-11 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKNEY-POSTER-ART-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFORDABLE HOCKNEY, PLAYING THE PROMOTER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ If you have ever dreamed of owning a David Hockney but
haven't had $20,000 (or considerably more) to spend on a drawing,
oil painting or lithograph, Christie's South Kensington has come
along with the largest-ever sale of Hockney posters, to be held
here on March 25.
</P>
<P>
   And although one might argue that posters are not in the same
league as paintings and lithographs, the collection testifies to
precisely that dazzling breadth and wit that have made Hockney, now
61, one of the most popular and admired of contemporary artists.
</P>
<P>
   The collection belongs to Brian Baggott, 56, a onetime British
Airways employee who first met Hockney some 30 years ago and has
been collecting his posters (as well as silk screens) since the
early 70s. Working in group sales for the airline made it easy for
him to travel. ``I wrote to every gallery ever mentioned in the
back of a Hockney catalog to see if they'd done a poster,'' Baggott
explained from his south London home. And before long, he said of
his keen pursuit, ``it had become a bit of an obsession, rather
like schoolboys with stamps.''
</P>
<P>
   What exactly is a Hockney poster? The answer is as varied as the
artist's own output. Most of the 206 posters that make up the 132
lots for sale were produced by a gallery or institution or magazine
and use a Hockney image to promote an event or exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   But there are others, though many fewer of them, that were
specifically designed and overseen by Hockney himself, often with
tongue in cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 111, for example, is a poster for a Hockney show at the
Whitechapel Art Gallery in London in 1970 that features one image
in which Hockney has amusingly drawn himself. Some posters present
a detail of a much larger canvas; for example, the art chosen for
posters pertaining to Tivoli Gardens and the Strauss opera ``Die
Frau Ohne Schatten'' consists, in effect, of enlarged details from
pre-existing paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Others bear images unique to the poster _ like the geometric
faces announcing the 1976 edition of the Spoleto festival in Italy
_) and therefore to Hockney's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's every combination you can possibly think of,'' Baggott
said. ``That's very David; he likes to keep everybody on the hop.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it seems wasteful to purchase a Hockney poster, which
tends to be a reproduction, when his original works come up
frequently for auction. Indeed, at its 20th-century art auction on
March 26, Christie's has included a 1985 Hockney lithograph and
collage, ``An Image of Gregory,'' with a top estimate of $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the posters are estimated to sell for much more than
$1,000, and the prices are usually for lots of two or three items,
although a few posters are for sale on their own. (Ninety percent
of the lots, Baggott said, include at least one signed poster.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a way of buying a David Hockney affordably,'' said
Nicolette White, a 19th- and 20th-century poster specialist at
Christie's. ``OK, it's not the original, but there are only a
certain amount of them produced, and you've got David's signature
for a fraction of the price you would pay for an original work of
art.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall value of the sale has been estimated at $90,000 to
$100,000, although, Ms. White said, that figure is ``obviously
quite modest.'' And while it's the posters with signatures _ a few
with a scribbled ``for Brian,'' naming Baggott directly _ that will
command the higher prices, others are of note either because of
their scarcity or because of their images.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 131, for instance, contains Hockney's signed poster for a
1972 West End production of ``The Threepenny Opera,'' starring
Vanessa Redgrave, that is unusual because Hockney didn't in fact
design the show. More customary are posters for opera and ballet
productions that Hockney also designed, whether ``Turandot'' in
Chicago, ``Tristan und Isolde'' in Los Angeles, the triple bill
known as ``Parade'' in New York or ``The Rake's Progress'' in
Glyndebourne, England.
</P>
<P>
   Among the pricier items for sale, with a top estimate of some
$1,300, is a rare poster announcing Hockney's 1966 Royal Court
Theater production of the absurdist play ``Ubu Roi,'' by Alfred
Jarry; only one other known copy of that poster exists.
</P>
<P>
   Devotees of Hockney will find all the familiar images on view,
from a favorite model like Celia Birtwell, the fabric designer, to
his beloved dachsund, Stanley, as well as the languid young men who
have figured prominently in Hockney's depiction of life in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the 1988 Tate Gallery retrospective of his work, Hockney
came up with a poster that shows his 1987 canvas ``Little Stanley
Sleeping,'' now framed and nailed to a wall: the result is a droll
play on an extant painting. The Paris Review and the Young
Playwrights Festival Off Broadway are just two entities to make use
of Hockney images for posters.
</P>
<P>
   How does the artist himself feel about having posters expand the
audience for his work? In his 1993 autobiography, ``That's The Way
I See It,'' Hockney wrote: ``The poster can be a marvelous
reproduction, better than anything in a book, and if you print them
well and take the photographs of the paintings well, the posters
are worth keeping, people might like them; they can pin them on a
wall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
