<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-KANSAS-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
 
TCU outlasts Kansas State in NIT first round 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN, Kan. _ Delays usually send TCU coach Billy Tubbs into
a tizzy.
</P>
<P>
   He despises waiting.
</P>
<P>
   So when mechanical problems delayed TCU's departure from
Dallas/Fort Worth Airport to Kansas City, Mo., thus delaying TCU's
arrival in Manhattan until 2 1/2 hours before last night's game,
Horned Frogs players were expecting a Tubbs' tantrum.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Tubbs leaned back, relaxed and watched as TCU defeated
Kansas State, 72-71, in the first round of the National Invitation
Tournament last night at Bramlage Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handled that pretty well, considering'' said Frogs
preseason all-American Lee Nailon, his game-high 22 points also
helping Tubbs' mood considerably.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to use it as a positive,'' Tubbs said of TCU's travel
troubles. ``Hey, we didn't have to sit around and wait all day.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU jumped off a bus in Manhattan, taped and stretched and then
promptly jumped back on to go play.
</P>
<P>
   A long day had a chance to get even longer for Frogs players
when Wildcats guard Chris Griffin launched a wild, game-tying
attempt from a ways away with a couple of seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin's shot sailed wide, though, and a tip-in by Tony Kitt,
while good, was a point too little.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there was a little over three seconds left on the
clock,'' Griffin explained later. ``When Manny \RDies\S got the
rebound, he surveyed the court before he gave the ball to me. I
figured there was only one second left. I wasn't aware that they
had put time back on the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU (20-10) had grabbed its biggest lead of the game, 65-53,
with 7:57 remaining. Kansas State (20-13), however, refused to go
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats sneaked within sniffing distance a couple of times,
including 72-69 with 5.6 seconds remaining. Kansas State fouled
before the ball was inbounded, but two seconds had ticked off the
clock. The time was put back on before TCU missed the front end of
a one-and-one, giving K-State five seconds and one more chance. But
TCU played just good enough, just long enough to get to play again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to play our way to New York,'' Tubbs said of
the NIT finals March 23-25 in Madison Square Garden. ``I wouldn't
mind having a game at home, though.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU next faces Nebraska in the second round of the NIT either
Monday or Tuesday at a site and time yet to be determined. The
Cornhuskers defeated Nevada-Las Vegas, 68-55, last night.
</P>
<P>
   Frogs players seemed to seal their second-round berth during a
spurt midway through second-half play. It wasn't one thing, really,
just a number of things happening at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Frogs guard Ryan Carroll nailed a couple of critical 3-pointers
to finish with 16 points. Kansas State's Shawn Rhodes was whistled
for an intentional foul that allowed TCU to take a double-digit
lead with 8:59 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The size diminished considerably, but the lead never evaporated
for the Frogs despite their playing most of the second half without
Marquise Gainous. He was whistled for his fourth foul with 18:56
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The game, like the day, didn't start off well for TCU.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs were plagued by poor shooting early and trailed by as
many as nine points. They trailed 22-13 with 10:22 remaining in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   TCU went on an 18-2 run over the next 6:05, grabbing its first
lead of the game. The run was sparked by Nailon, who scored eight
of TCU's 13 points during the run. He credited the change to Tubbs'
decision to switch up so he was playing more facing the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get to play a lot freer,'' Nailon said of the switch.
``Coach didn't let me do that a lot this season. He kind of pulled
it out of his hat tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Nailon had started slowly, missing eight of his first 10 shots
from the field. It was a sluggish shooting night for both squads.
The Wildcats shot 42 percent from the field and were 3-for-23 on
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their zone made us shoot from the perimeter, and we just
couldn't make those shots,'' Wildcats coach Tom Asbury said.
``Great looks, wide-open shots, just wouldn't fall in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs weren't much better. They shot 43 percent, but were
7-of-23 on 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Just another little delay before they finally got on track.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
