<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6112 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     03-11 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST SQUEAK YOUR HIGHTOPS THREE TIMES...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN, Kan. _ This was about heart and wizards and
redemption, and TCU found some of all these things in Wednesday
night's 72-71 victory over Kansas State in the opening round of the
NIT.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough yet, mind you, but some.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs came to the Land of Oz as enigmatic as any team Billy
Tubbs has ever coached, disheartened by a first-round loss in the
Western Athletic Conference tournament last week in Las Vegas and
rightfully snubbed by the NCAA's 64-team tournament.
</P>
<P>
   This was a team that started the season ranked 24th in the
nation and found itself in the middle of a Kansas wheat field after
a late-season collapse that left Tubbs, who never met a notebook he
couldn't fill up, almost speechless with frustration.
</P>
<P>
   This was definitely about pride. The Frogs would not have been
able to look themselves in the mirror if they'd come here and lost
to the gritty but less-talented Wildcats, who end their season at
20-13.
</P>
<P>
   This was about starting fresh in a place nicknamed ``The Little
Apple'' with every intention of taking it all the way to ``The Big
Apple'' for the National Invitation Tournament final four.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky's the limit,'' said center Lee Nailon, who fueled the
Frogs' victory with 22 points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. Wasn't that what we were saying when this season began in
November?
</P>
<P>
   Nailon actually showed a flash or two of on-court leadership,
scowling at teammates for mistakes real or imagined, patting them
on the rump or offering words of encouragement for good plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach has been stressing that I need to do that more, stay
more focused and pick up the other guys, too,'' said Nailon, who
was more productive last night when he abandoned his patented
low-post moves and played facing the basket. He even stepped
outside and hit two key 3-point jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   If that seemed strange, imagine a Tubbs-coached team that never
_ I repeat, ``never'' _ pressed during the entire game and spent
much of it playing a 1-3-1 zone, inviting the 'Cats to bomb away
from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State responded by hitting three of 23 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their zone made us shoot from the perimeter, and we just
couldn't make those shots,'' Kansas State coach Tom Asbury said.
``Great looks, wide open shots, just wouldn't fall in.''
</P>
<P>
   So we have Nailon hitting 3-pointers and the Frogs abandoning
their trademark press. Want yet another
you're-not-going-to-believe-this observation?
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs never left his seat in anger, never yelled at the refs,
never seemed to break a sweat, much to the disappointment of a
small but vocal KSU crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the best officiated game I've seen all
season,'' Tubbs sniffed calmly after the victory.
</P>
<P>
   And here we were, expecting Billy to at least go off about the
Frogs' travel arrangements and problems getting here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   TCU made an economic decision not to charter a flight (an
$18,000 difference in cost), so the Frogs, after a 2 1/2-hour delay
at D/FW Airport because of mechanical problems, eventually flew to
Kansas City, Mo., then made the two-hour drive by bus, not arriving
at Bramlage Coliseum until 2 1/2 hours before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather walk in and play than sit around all day anyway,''
Tubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   Nailon fueled an 18-2 run that gave TCU a 38-33 halftime lead
after the Frogs trailed by up to nine in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the Wildcats could get in the second half was the
final score on a tip-in at the buzzer by Tony Kitt off a badly
missed 3-point prayer by Chris Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, we kind of got control of the game,''
Tubbs said, ``but we could never get in a comfort zone because of
their rebounding. They got a lot of baskets on put backs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats, one of the best rebounding and defensive teams in
the Big 12, dominated the boards, 49-34.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were a great rebounding team,'' Tubbs said, ``we'd be
playing in the `other' tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how far they can get in this one and that
may be as much a product of want-to as anything else. The Frogs are
like a stakes horse dropping down in class.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys seemed to find out that the game is fun again last
week during practice,'' Tubbs said. ``I've never accused our
players of quitting, and we've never come in and said we lost a
game because we didn't care enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, we may be too nice. We could probably stand to be
a little more nasty sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   They can be as nasty as they want to be in next week's
second-round game against Nebraska, probably in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the guys stay fired up,'' Nailon said, ``we can go all the
way to Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Manhattan is where the Frogs' new season began
Wednesday night. The other Manhattan is where they'd like for it to
end.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
