<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' PREQUEL TO ARRIVE TWO DAYS EARLY, LUCAS PROMISES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The world will get its latest ``Star Wars'' fix two
days early, director George Lucas announced late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace,'' the most
anticipated movie in decades, will open on May 19 rather than May
21, Lucas told the ShoWest convention of the nation's theater
owners in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work on the film has been going extremely well,'' Lucas said
in explaining the decision to move up the opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be able to release it on Wednesday, May 19, in
hopes that we can give the fans a head start and families can see
it on the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas said he loves the new film and was encouraged by the
reaction of his close friend, director Steven Spielberg, after
seeing the completed film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to see it again,'' Spielberg reportedly told
Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   The film, a ``prequel'' to the familiar ``Star Wars'' trilogy,
goes back in time to explain how Luke Skywalker's father, Anakin
Skywalker, became the evil Darth Vader. Lucas is planning to
release ``Episode II'' in 2002 and ``Episode III'' in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts believe ``Episode I'' can break the box-office
records set last year by James Cameron's ``Titanic'' for domestic
gross of $600 million and worldwide gross of $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after Lucas' announcement, 20th Century Fox, which has
distributed all the ``Star Wars'' movies, screened the second
two-minute trailer for the eagerly anticipated film.
</P>
<P>
   The clip, expected to debut in theaters Friday, opens with enemy
troops massing to attack as Natalie Portman, playing Queen Amidala,
Luke Skywalker's future mother, declares, ``I will not condone a
cause of action that will lead to war.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the remainder contains clips of the science fiction
series' trademark outer space battles along with light saber duels
involving Jedi Knights played by Liam Neeson and Ewan McGregor.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement also includes brief shots of robots R2-D2 and
C-3PO, Jedi master Yoda and arch-villan Jabba the Hutt.
</P>
<P>
   The trailer ends with the words, ``The saga begins May 19.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who created all the ``Star Wars'' movies and directed the
original 1977 film, also announced that the prequel will be
screened on June 18 with digital projectors at four undisclosed
locations.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, he disclosed that he expects to film all of
``Episode II'' with digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Long a strong proponent of using leading-edge technology to
improve moviemaking, Lucas said, ``I can't think of a better time
to be in the motion picture business.''
</P>
