A6125 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-PRESIDENCY-SFCHR     03-11 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-PRESIDENCY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA COULD MAKE OR BREAK ELIZABETH DOLE'S RUN
FOR  PRESIDENCY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Republican Elizabeth Hanford Dole came a step closer to
breaking the all-male hold on presidential politics Wednesday,
saying she will mount a ``people-to-people'' effort to explore a
run for the nation's highest office.
<P>
   ``What does a woman like me have to offer the country?'' asked
Dole, in announcing the formation of her exploratory committee at a
rally in Des Moines, Iowa. ``I'm not a politician and, frankly,
today I think that may be a plus.'' Bob Dole, her husband and the
GOP's 1996 presidential nominee, did not attend the event, where
she took the mike and wandered through the crowd with an energetic
address.
</P>
<P>
   With the California March 2000 primary just a year away, the
announcement by Dole _ who hit just about every hamlet and high
tech haven statewide while stumping for her husband in 1996 _ set
off a new round of political tremors in California.
</P>
<P>
   Political insiders say the nation's most populous state could be
a place where she has a big impact _ but faces more than a few
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is truly a historic opportunity for the country _ and more
important for the Republican Party,'' said GOP consultant Leslie
Goodman, also a friend to Texas governor and GOP front-runner
George W. Bush. ``The Dole candidacy is a signal to voters across
the country that Republicans are not taking women for granted. ...
and it's an opportunity to demonstrate the depth and breadth of the
GOP.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole's decision could also have state aftershocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly increases the chances that (Democratic U.S.
Senator) Dianne Feinstein will be vice presidential nominee,'' said
East Bay GOP campaign adviser and party activist Larry Molton.
``There will be tremendous pressure on Al Gore to keep up with the
Republicans ... and the better Elizabeth Dole does, the more
pressure there will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole's announcement comes the same week Bush formed his own
exploratory committee. But Bush has already done considerable work
in California, and Bush operatives were in Sacramento Wednesday
mining more support.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the wild card,'' said one veteran GOP insider of Dole.
``Nobody really knows who she is _ or how she'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   And state Democrats were already downplaying Dole's importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Oprah is retiring, she's got it hands down,'' said
California Democratic Party Chairman Art Torres. But ``we don't
need a television talk show host to be president. We need someone
with experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the possible candidacy of Dole _ the former secretary of
labor and secretary of transportation, and past president of the
American Red Cross _ is already historic. She is ``the first female
national political figure to emerge on her own professional and
political credentials,'' said GOP analyst Dan Schnur.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's strength and resume give her the status as a strong
``national political player'' that eluded two Democratic aspirants
for high office _ Pat Schroeder, who made a short-lived run for
president in 1988, and Geraldine Ferraro, a vice presidential
nominee on the Democratic ticket in 1984, he said.
</P>
<P>
   She also has proved her strength on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not, in 1996, see a better campaigner than Elizabeth
Dole,'' said former state GOP Chairman John Herrington, a longtime
friend of Dole's. ``She's smart and organized, and she comes across
as a very caring person _ not a hard-liner on any one issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Carroll, a Republican activist from Modesto, said Dole's
1996 campaigns on behalf of her husband were nothing short of
``phenomenal.'' She recalled how Dole spoke from the back of an old
train caboose in the middle of a feed lot to a tough crowd of
Central Valley farmers in 1996. ``It was over 100 degrees, hot and
sticky, and she looked cool as a breeze,'' said Carroll. ``I hope
she'll be able to win back a lot of those Republican women who
deserted the party or didn't vote at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a great following here, and she created it ... in the
campaign she did for Bob,'' said Los Angeles attorney Ken
Khachigian, the veteran GOP strategist who ran Bob Dole's 1996
California campaign. ``For the more conservative women, she has a
fairly conservative philosophy. And for moderates to liberals, she
has been a pioneer and pacesetter in issues that deal with women in
the workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dole faces new challenges in her quest for the
presidency,particularly in California.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, experts say:
</P>
<P>
   -- Defining the issues: Dole _ lacking a legislative record _
hasn't yet ``put meat on the bones'' and noted her stance on issues
like education, environment, trade and abortion, Khachigian said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her biggest challenge is going to be to fill in the policy
blanks, without sacrificing her potential support,'' said Schnur.
</P>
<P>
   -- Raising money: ``Dole has access to Bob Dole's contributors,
who are substantial. She will attract a lot of new money with
people wanting to cover bets,'' said Herrington. ``They want a good
Republican woman like her to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a lot of work to do to prove that ``she has the
table stakes to go,'' said Khachigian.
</P>
<P>
   -- Abortion: Dole is strongly anti-abortion, but Carroll said
her warm, engaging style will help her ``make the party more
inclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, does she believe in litmus tests?'' asked
Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   -- No elected office: ``In order to succeed, you have to have a
clear rationale for your candidacy and a clear vision of where you
want to take the country,'' said Goodman. ``The question is: Is
Elizabeth Dole the person who can outline that vision, having never
held elective office before?''
</P>
<P>
   -- Her husband's role: How often does Dole campaign in
California here  &LR; with her husband _ who got just 39 percent of the
1996 vote, compared to 51 percent for President Clinton? Bob Dole
is currently featured seen  &LR; in a nationwide in  &LR; TV ad, in which he
talks about erectile dysfunction and endorses the impotence drug
Viagra. If Elizabeth Dole becomes the subject of ribbing _ or the
dreaded ``Top Ten'' list of late night talk show host David
Letterman _ it could affect her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard for him (Bob Dole) to be a public
spokesman for a commercial product and a campaign surrogate at the
same time,'' said Khachigian.
</P>
<P>
   Said Schnur: ``Better those jokes, than the ones about Hillary
Clinton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
