<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 03:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6129 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-SCIENCE-SFCH     03-11 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-SCIENCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PHYSICIST WINS $1.24 MILLION RELIGION PRIZE  &HT;     By DON LATTIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ian Barbour, a physicist who has spent a career fostering
dialogue between scientists and people of faith, won the $1.24
million Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour, 75, announced that he would give $1 million of his
windfall to the Center for Theology and the Natural Sciences, an
institute in Berkeley, Calif., that is part of the Graduate
Theological Union, a consortium of seminaries in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Randolph, program director at the center, called
Barbour, a theologian and a nuclear physicist at Carleton College
in Northfield, Minn., ``a pioneer in the dialogue of religion and
science.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel unmitigated joy and happiness that Ian has been
recognized in this way,'' said Randolph. ``We intend to use the
money to continue the work that he has done.''
</P>
<P>
   The prize, awarded by an independent jury, was the latest gift
of Sir John M. Templeton, a Presbyterian layman and founder of
several successful investment funds. Previous winners of the award
_ the world's largest annual prize for achievement in any field _
include Mother Teresa, the Rev. Billy Graham and prison evangelist
and Watergate figure Charles Colson.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time the Center for Theology and the
Natural Sciences has benefited from Templeton's largesse.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Randolph said, the Templeton Foundation granted the
center $13 million to help professors and universities around the
world begin interdisciplinary courses in the study of science and
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of money going into this area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph said Barbour was the second J.K. Russell Research
Fellow at the center, just two years after its founding in 1981,
and has attended several conferences sponsored by the Berkeley
think thank.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, Barbour published ``Issues in Science and Religion,''
an early work in this increasingly popular _ and well-funded _
arena. His recent works include two books published by
HarperSanFrancisco, ``Ethics in an Age of Technology'' and
``Religion and Science: Historical and Contemporary Issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to think science has all the answers, because it's a
very powerful tool,'' Barbour said Wednesday. But scientists must
keep lines of communication open to the religious community, he
said, to help answer today's ethical and spiritual questions.
</P>
<P>
   John Cobb, a professor of theology at Claremont College in
Southern California, said Barbour deserved the prize. ``No
contemporary has made a more original, deep and lasting
contribution toward the needed integration of scientific and
religious knowledge and values,'' Cobb said.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph said Barbour, a member of the United Church of Christ
and a graduate of Yale Divinity School and the University of
Chicago, has helped foster understanding between ``those opposed to
technology and those who see salvation in technology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
