A6213 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-OSCAR-TABOOS-ART     03-11 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-OSCAR-TABOOS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT YOU WON'T SEE AT THIS YEAR'S OSCARS 
</HEADLINE>
  World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides of actor Tom Hanks in scenes from ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    When the 1 billion viewers in more than 90 countries tune in the
71st annual Academy Awards Ceremony on March 2l, they'll argue over
the same old stuff:
 &HT;    Can Tom Hanks' heroic officer in ``Saving Private Ryan'' go the
distance despite back-to-back Oscars in recent years? Will the best
actress be Australian Cate Blanchette playing a British queen in
``Elizabeth,'' or American Gwyneth Paltrow playing a British
gentlewoman in ``Shakespeare in Love''?
 &HT;    We'll see the usual parade of overdressed actresses and
over-choreographed dance numbers. But there's plenty we won't see:
Oscar taboos and precautions that go on behind the scenes. After
more than 25 years of covering the big night, I can list 10 things
you can bet you won't view when you tune in this year:
 &HT;    1. Demonstrations: At the slightest hint of disturbance in the
hall, producer Gilbert Cates and director Louis J. Horvitz will
order a cut to commercial or taped film clips. A ``silent
demonstration'' is being threatened by some guests who disapprove
of an honorary Oscar for Elia Kazan, who cooperated in 1951 with
the House Committee on Un-American Activites. If the demonstration
does occur, expect the show to go on with the cameras focused
determinedly elsewhere.
 &HT;    2. Empty Seats: During the long night many in the audience will
leave their assigned seats to present or accept awards. No sooner
does one of them spring to his feet than a 'sitter' jumps into the
empty spot. This is, after all, the hottest ticket in town and it
wouldn't do for it to look anything but jammed.
 &HT;    3. Freeway Gridlock: For the first time they've changed Oscar
night to Sunday. There will of course be some tight traffic outside
Dorothy Chandler Pavilion as limousines line up to unload the
glitterati.
 &HT;    4. Endless Verbiage: Cates and Horvitz will give the order to
``kill the mike'' of those who drone too long or make political
speeches when they should be thanking their mothers. (Mothers can
be thanked effusively provided it's done in 30 seconds or less.)
 &HT;    5. The War Chest: You won't hear a word about the $30 million
spent on newspaper ads and gifts by studios and producers lobbying
Academy members' votes. (The Los Angeles Times says Miramax alone
has spent in the $15-million range to tout ``Shakespeare in Love''
and ``Life is Beautiful.'') Everyone knows an Oscar can add
millions to a movie's box office take.
 &HT;    6. The Booty: Stashed at home, each of the 5,000 voting members
has a video cassette library of virtually every movie in the
contest. Behind the scenes are gift baskets for the presenters,
with perfume, champagne, and (in past years) $1,000-wristwatches,
leather goods and other trinkets from Rodeo Drive.
 &HT;    7. Security Guards: They'll be wearing tuxedo jackets like the
guests, but the guards' will have wires projecting from the back of
the collar. The radio-equipped team will occupy approximately 30
seats on two levels of the auditorium and outside the doors. In
addition is a contingent of 500 local cops_beefed up by Pinkertson
guards_under the direction of Jerry Moon, the former Los Angeles
policeman who has been keeping Oscar buttoned down for 20 years.
 &HT;    8. The Media: Most of the 1,000 reporters covering the event
(almost a third are foreign) are confined ``backstage'' and
interview the winners as they are paraded from one room to another.
But you won't see a press conference in which the losers lament
that the best man didn't win, the voting was rigged or the best
actress slept her way to the top. Instead they'll show up at
Miramax's Oscar bash or the Governors' Ball.
 &HT;    9) The Flacks: Call them press agents, handlers, publicity
types, hand holders: They outnumber the stars 2-1. They try to stay
in the background and make sure their clients display their best
side to the camera. Many of them have spent months devising Oscar
campaigns for their celebrity clients, and if they look more tense
than usual (and these are not the most laid-back people at the best
of times,) it's because if their client doesn't win they may get
fired.
 &HT;    10: Offensive Film: Clips with excessive nudity, racy or foul
language will not have made it past Susan Futterman, ABC's
standards and practices censor. One year she killed a clip of an
actress displaying three breasts from a scene in the sci-fi film
``Total Recall.'' ``Sorry,'' she said, ``that will have to go. I
can't even show women with two breasts.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480, or
by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) &QL;
</P>
