<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN14-CO     03-11 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Myopic GOP just might stimulate Gore
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, March 14, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Ronald Reagan was the Teflon president, then Bill Clinton is
the Velcro president _ everything sticks to him, not that he
doesn't deserve much of it.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican effort to attach blame to the Clinton White
House for an appalling breakdown in security during the Reagan and
Bush administrations is so off-base as to be laughable.
</P>
<P>
   This is one that won't cling to Clinton, and might just help Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott (R-Miss) had the audacity last week, after
allegations arose that the theft of nuclear secrets by China took
place during the Reagan/Bush years, to say he was not going to
dwell so much on the past, but wants to know what's being done
about correcting the problem.
</P>
<P>
   I would not expect much else from Lott. Why dwell on the past
when the past doesn't look good for the Republicans?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, GOPartisans are demanding to know why the alleged mole
managed to hang on to his job for nearly three (Clinton) years
while under investigation. It's a good question, but first I'd like
the primary question answered: How did a nuclear scientist manage
to pass secrets to the Communist Chinese for all those Reagan/Bush
years without being detected?
</P>
<P>
   I have another question that still has not been answered: How
did Reagan and Bush get away with their hear-no-evil, see-no-evil
roles in the Iran-Contra affair?
</P>
<P>
   And where was the deadly response from superpatriot Reagan after
terrorists blew up the U.S. Marine barracks in Beirut in 1983 _
killing 241 troops?
</P>
<P>
   Also, if we knew in advance that Bush would let Saddam Hussein
live to fight another day after Operation Desert Storm, would we
still have agreed to his boisterous buildup and attack?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, anyone can play partisan politics, but when does it
reach absurdity?
</P>
<P>
   For the Republicans to try to paint Clinton with responsibility
for this severe breach in U.S. security is stepping beyond the
line. To the good of Democrats, it can be an issue that might bring
Gore out of his self-inflicted obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Gore has jumped into the fight in a TV interview,
taking the reins away from Clinton by arguing back that this
administration inherited the Chinese nuclear mess from previous
administrations, namely Reagan's and Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   If there's something the Republicans don't want to do, it's to
wake up Al Gore. Already they've incurred national animosity over
the obstinate and bellicose way they handled the Clinton-Lewinsky
scandal; now they're intent on giving the Democrats another issue.
</P>
<P>
   To keep beating on Clinton is to beat a dead horse. While his
numbers may be high, he is still held in low-esteem by this nation
for his Monica dishonor. As a world leader, his prestige has
slumped, evidenced this past week by little Guatemala and El
Salvador telling him to take a hike over a joint resolution he
thought had been pre-approved.
</P>
<P>
   GOP presidential hopefuls don't need a fighting Al Gore on the
stump. Studies show that Gore ranks high in everything but emotion.
If he gets that, then George W. Bush and the other GOP contenders
will have a tougher opponent.
</P>
<P>
   (An earlier image of Gore and the younger Bush engaging in
debates carried with it the same prospect of watching two guys
fish.)
</P>
<P>
   It is time the Republicans ended their partisan siege. Trying to
paint over Reagan and Bush fiascos by smearing Clinton covers
nothing; it is transparent.
</P>
<P>
   There's enough blame to go around for quite a few of our present
and past presidents, Democrats and Republicans alike.
</P>
<P>
   Each, however, has his own mailbox _ self-addressed.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
