<HEADER>
A6223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN14-COX     03-11 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Gun control vs. lawsuit control
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If General Motors has a lick of sense, it will rush Congressman
Bob Barr onto its board. Just think: no more pesky lawsuits. A free
ticket through the courts. Trial lawyers, defendants, judgments,
damages _ all gone.
</P>
<P>
   Barr is the Georgia Republican who was booming impeachment long
before anyone had dug up even an excuse for that, apparently on the
general principle that, well, there's Bill Clinton and there's the
Constitution's impeachment option, so what are we waiting for?
</P>
<P>
   The hustle brought Barr, if not fame, at least notoriety and a
meteoric rise through the TV talk shows from after-hours gigs on
obscure cable channels to the glory of prime time network
interviews. But with impeachment a flop, how long can a poor fellow
survive on nothing better than speaking invitations from
organizations with political charters drawn up by guys who had
stared at the moon too long?
</P>
<P>
   Barr has soldiered into the breach in his own career with
federal legislation that, if passed, would forbid cities and states
to sue firearms manufacturers. As chance would have it, Barr is a
member of the National Rifle Association's board, which has been in
one of its patented swivets over lawsuits against the industry
filed by five cities.
</P>
<P>
   As it does in any attempt to contain the domestic arms race, the
NRA sees the suits as the first step in a plot to disarm American
yeomanry and submit the citizens to a tyranny of Nazis, Commies or
humanists. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Give Barr this: Most of us would agree that we've become a far
too litigious society and fear that some day the nation will come
to a complete stop because, as it turns out, everyone of us is in
court. And some of the lawsuits against the industry do seem a bit
of a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But so what? Mistaken, even goofy or malicious lawsuits are
filed all the time, and the courts have plenty of ways, and lot of
experience in using those ways, to dispose of them. There's no
stampede by other cities to follow the five that are testing these
legal waters. If the suits prove meritless, they will fail and that
will be the end of that.
</P>
<P>
   If, as Barr, the NRA and the manufacturers all say, these are
frivolous filings, what better, what more definitive, way to show
that than to have them publicly miscarry, rather than using
legislation of dubious constitutionality to prevent any ventilation
of the marketing and safety issues raised by the suits?
</P>
<P>
   Firearms policies are best set through the reconciling
negotiations of political give and take, but the gun lobby has used
its money and scare tactics effectively to prevent ordinary
political dialogue. The current, small bustle of lawsuits
represents less the core attack on firearms that the panicky
industry and lobby fear than a desperate resort to the courts in an
attempt to put legitimate public-safety concerns into play.
</P>
<P>
   The real message of Barr's legislation is that the gun lobby,
for all its contrary boasting, worries that the suing cities just
may have a legal point or two.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
