A6233 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOO-MUCH-HEALTH?-ADVI     03-11 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOO-MUCH-HEALTH?-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Below are summaries of the MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE stories
sent to subscribers so far this week. The service offers a daily
package of five or six health and medical articles prepared by the
finest medical writers and editors.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably more copy than you can use. But it's nice to know
it's there to help you provide your readers with the best possible
health report -- and it's very affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Our subscribers include newspapers, Web sites, TV stations and
major news publications around the world.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like sales information for your newspaper or Web site,
please call The New York Times Syndicate at 800-535-4425 or e-mail
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY, MARCH 10
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   HEART-TEST-MED -- Two studies presented Wednesday at the annual
meeting of the American College of Cardiology found that a test
known as electron beam computed tomography is an effective way to
predict heart-related deaths in people younger than 50. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   EXERCISE-TREAT-MED -- A rigorous exercise regimen may beat
standard drugs in strengthening the health of some heart patients,
Chinese researchers reported Wednesday. (350 words)
</P>
<P>
   LIVER-CANCER-MED -- During the first half of the 1990s, the rate
of the most common form of liver cancer in the United States
increased by more than 70 percent, a new study shows. And while the
disease remains relatively rare, the number of people with liver
cancer may continue to rise, experts say, as people who contracted
liver disease decades ago develop cancer. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   ATHLETE-DEATH-MED -- Even at relatively low speeds and forces,
blows sustained on the playing field can send young athletes into
cardiac arrest, according to two reports released Wednesday. (500
words)
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION-ADVICE-MED -- Karen Collins of the American Institute
for Cancer Research answers nutrition questions. This week:
</P>
<P>
   --What is the greenish glimmer I sometimes see on the surface of
meat? Is that a sign that it's unsafe to eat?
</P>
<P>
   --What is the latest news on diet's relationship to PMS?
</P>
<P>
   --Is it true that chromium supplements are helpful for people
with diabetes? (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   LYME-DISEASE-MED -- Satellite mapping to identify areas where
disease-carrying ticks gather, together with two new vaccinations,
may curtail the spread of Lyme disease, experts said at a national
conference on tick-borne diseases. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY, MARCH 9
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   CREATINE-MUSCLE-MED -- Creatine, a supplement that helps weight
lifters ``pump up'' may do the same for people with muscular
diseases, Canadian researchers report. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   FLU-SHOTS-MED -- Less than 30 percent of chronically sick women
under the age of 65 may be taking advantage of flu vaccines,
despite evidence suggesting the shots could save their lives,
according to a study published in the Journal of the American
Medical Association. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   ANTIOXIDANT-HEART-MED -- Italian researchers have released the
results of a large study on whether two widely used antioxidants --
Vitamin E and omega-3 fish-oil supplements -- cut heart-attack
risk. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   HEART-STRESS-MED -- A new study shows that heart disease
patients have an increased risk of sudden death when they
experience ischemia, a decrease in blood flow to the heart, during
times of increased psychological stress, researchers reported
Tuesday. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BAR-MED -- Vitamin-packed food bars designed to increase
athletes' endurance may give a boost to artery-disease patients as
well, researchers reported Tuesday at the annual meeting of the
American College of Cardiology. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-ADVICE-MED _ Dr. Eric Anderson answers health questions.
This week:
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while I develop a large lump under my skin that
seems to be a kind of subterranean pimple. Usually these go away on
their own. Should I be doing anything about them, or is benign
neglect the best treatment? (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   DENTAL-HEALTH-MED -- Dr. S. Timothy Rose, president of the
American Dental Association, writes about the importance of
flossing. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY, March 8
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   BIRTH-HELP-MED _ Expectant mothers who do not feel in control of
their labor are more prone to anxiety and a high level of pain, and
are also more likely to require intervention such as forceps and
C-section. A program at the Boston Medical Center pairs such women
with a ``birth sister,'' a woman who provides advice and support
during labor and in the first few months after delivery. (700
words)
</P>
<P>
   VITAMINS-HEART-MED -- Vitamin supplements may help people lower
their risk for heart disease, British researchers reported here
Monday at the annual meeting of the American College of Cardiology.
(500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SUPPLEMENT-RISK-MED _ Researchers at the annual meeting of the
American College of Cardiology have issued a warning about the
dangers of the nutritional supplement ma huang, also known as
ephedra, because it is a natural source of ephedrine. This
stimulant can cause serious heart complications, such as heart
attacks and irregular heartbeats. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   CIGAR-HEART-MED -- Cigar aficionados who think they're averting
the dangers of cigarette smoking actually may be slowly damaging
their blood vessels, according to researchers.
</P>
<P>
   TESTOSTERONE-HEART-MED -- Testosterone, the male sex hormone
thought to be a risk factor for heart disease, may not be so bad
after all. In fact, the hormone may hold promise as a future
treatment for some men whose clogged arteries impede blood flow to
the heart, according to findings presented at the annual meeting of
the American College of Cardiology. (350 words)
</P>
<P>
   LUPUS-ACNE-MED -- A common antibiotic used to treat acne may
cause side effects that resemble the disease lupus, British and
American researchers report. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   LUNG-CANCER-MED _ Men who drink large quantities of beer may be
increasing their risk of developing lung cancer, a new study shows.
</P>
<P>
   But those who drink wine may end up lowering their risk of
developing the disease, according to the study published in a
recent issue of the American Journal of Epidemiology. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate.)
</P>
