<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6243 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV14-C     03-11 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: SHOULD A VALET BE A HERO?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Mar. 14.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The senator pumped my hand and wished me luck. ``I
know you'll do the right thing,'' he said, looking me in the eye.
In this case, the ``right thing'' meant keeping mum about my life
and times as his top aide.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years I spent on Capitol Hill, before going back to
journalism, I learned more lore about the inner workings of the
Senate and the White House than I could ever hope to glean in a
lifetime of reporting. The president's national security adviser
(''everyone calls me Henry'') gladly gave me his personal phone
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly 30 years since I walked through the
``revolving door'' that divides media and politics _ the same door
that columnist Pat Buchanan recently turned as he began his third
run for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Working for a powerful pol can stir some strong emotions,
particularly if you're young and ambitious. The pink message slips
mount to impossible levels, forcing you to constantly choose whose
calls to return.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the perks. At the Kennedy Center, you sit in
the best seats _ for free. You ride in a limo to the flight line,
bypassing the ``civilians'' awaiting their boarding passes back at
the airport terminal.
</P>
<P>
   But then, sooner or later, it's time to go. And then you must
decide what to say about what you know.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti made such a choice when he left the White House in
1966 to become president of the Motion Picture Association of
America. Ever since the day John F. Kennedy was shot, and Lyndon B.
Johnson asked Valenti to leave his Houston ad agency to join the
inner circle, Valenti's code has been one of silence.
</P>
<P>
   While a staffer, Valenti was widely ridiculed for his fierce
loyalty. Once Valenti told an audience of advertising executives
that ``I sleep each night a little better, a little more
confidently, because Lyndon Johnson is my president.'' In the
Washington Post, Herblock lampooned him as a slave whose overseer
(LBJ) whipped him, ordering him to sleep better.
</P>
<P>
   George Stephanopoulos made such a choice, too, when he left the
White House in 1996 to become a commentator and a college
professor. After pocketing a huge advance, he wrote a tell-all
memoir about Bill Clinton that makes Clinton sorry he hired him. In
plugging his book, Stephanopoulos concludes that his former boss
isn't ``fit enough to be elected'' president.
</P>
<P>
   The book's ``All Too Human'' title refers to Clinton. But it
could just as easily refer to the author. Unlike Valenti,
Stephanopoulos soon had trouble sleeping as a staffer. He consulted
a psychiatrist, who prescribed Zoloft, an antidepressant that he
kept taking until after he had moved to a less pressured life in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   My own choice was to say nothing about what I'd heard and seen
while working for Republican Sen. Charles Percy of Illinois. In the
ensuing decade, until he left the Senate, Percy and I remained on
good terms. But never once did he feed me even a crumb of news.
</P>
<P>
   Having both dealt with flawed leaders, Valenti and
Stephanopoulos no doubt both buy into the adage that no man is a
hero to his valet. The real question is, how are valets to behave
when they leave service?
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
