<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6259 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-STOCK-TRADERS &LR;      03-11 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-STOCK-TRADERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK TRADING WITHOUT A NET 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired. (That's you, since you're reading this.)  
 By ERIK LINDEN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meet 15-year-old Alexis Neuhaus, online stock-trader. Every day,
Neuhaus, who lives in Washington, D.C., wakes up, boots up his
Pentium 200 computer and logs on to his preferred online broker,
Datek. But shhhh. Neuhaus's high school teachers don't know that he
checks stock prices from a computer lab between classes.
</P>
<P>
   Neuhaus is one of millions of small investors who are trading
stocks on the Internet. About 40 percent of all stock trades made
by individual investors are performed online, according to Gomez
Advisors, a firm based in Concord, Mass., that evaluates online
brokers. Two years ago, only a quarter of those trades were made
online.
</P>
<P>
   One of the big draws is that online trading is relatively cheap.
Trades online run from $5 to $30 _ less than half of what a typical
stockbroker charged before the advent of the Internet. Since then,
most have lowered their prices.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage is that online traders do not have to listen
to pesky brokers advising them about what might be a good bet.
These web traders like to fly solo, for better for worse.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how it works: You get a computer, some spare cash and an
online account. Do some research on stocks _ or don't _ and your
trading days have begun. No fee for signup. Just a small commission
for each trade.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of this new method say that the anarchistic nature
of online trading is dangerous for novices. Too many investors are
thinking short-term, they say, instead of investing for the
long-haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely risks,'' said Neuhaus, who is bullish on
the software giant Oracle Corporation. ``But I'm limited right now
because of my relatively low amount of capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Gerlach, who runs a website _ www.investorama.com _ that
gives advice to online investors, said that many armchair traders
needed to slow down. ``The process doesn't change just because you
can enter orders on your computer over the Internet as opposed to
calling up a broker or walking into his office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerlach, who wrote ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to Online
Investing'' last year, said that some people were drawn to online
trading because of the recent media hype and advertising exposure,
and because they could remain virtually anonymous. If you fail, no
one needs to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people figure that it's a way to not talk to anybody or
be embarrassed if they make mistakes,'' Gerlach said. ``A lot of
people would never walk into a broker's office, because they would
feel too intimidated by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Edwards, a homemaker in Chester, Penn., recently began
trading stocks online, and she said that she was comfortable doing
so. ``Trading online gives us the confidence to trade without being
pressured'' by stockbrokers, said Edwards, 48, who recently started
a trading club with nine other women in Chester.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards dismisses critics who say that online trading resembles
gambling. ``We're pretty close to Atlantic City,'' said Edwards,
who maintains that she researches each stock before she makes her
move. ``If we wanted to gamble, we'd go there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gennady Ladyzhinsky, a New York Police Department officer,
disagrees. As Ladyzhinsky works his street beat on the Lower East
Side of Manhattan, he does not only talk about nabbing the bad
guys. He talks stocks _ and about trading them online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very addictive,'' said Ladyzhinsky, who began trading
online when a bank he had money in launched a public offering.
After a successful spin with the stock, he caught the bug. ``It's
like gambling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In some quarters, the line between trading and gambling is
getting pretty thin. Take for example the increasingly popular
so-called fantasy, or play-money trading. Last month, E*Trade ran a
celebrity stock challenge, where online users played against Tom
Hanks and Meg Ryan from the movie ``You've Got Mail'' for pretend
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Both actors chose a fantasy portfolio of six stocks, and online
users went head-to-head with them. Over the period of one month,
Hanks _ whose portfolio included Yahoo! and America Online _ earned
more than $25,000, while Ryan earned $4,278, in fantasy money.
</P>
<P>
   While this all sounds like fun and games, Alan Alper, an analyst
with Gomez Advisors in Concord, Mass., worries that some investors
do not realize the financial risks associated with online trading.
Still, he concedes the method has made the stock market more
accessible. ``Almost anybody can be trading now,'' he said, ``and
that's probably a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers bear this out. In the last year, the number of
investors trading online jumped to 6.8 million from 4.1 million,
according to Gomez Advisors. In the coming year, that number is
expected to surge to more than 10 million people.
</P>
<P>
   But not all online brokerage services are created equal. Alper
recommends that consumers check out the differences between brokers
before signing up. In a recent evaluation, Gomez rated the popular
E*Trade service the highest overall. But when breaking down the
evaluation into categories, FarSight was judged the easiest service
to use, and DLJ Direct was rated the service most suited for
serious investors.
</P>
<P>
   Some naysayers predict outright doom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really about online speculating, not online
investing,'' said Paul Merriman, of Paul Merriman and Associates in
Seattle, who oversees mutual funds. ``And for people who wish to
speculate, online trading is nirvana.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, Merriman says only the patient few will end up
profiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people will do poorly,'' he said, ``because most
decisions will be made on emotions. Any time you allow emotions to
become part of the decision-making process, you're at high risk.''
</P>
<P>
   So people like teenage trader Alexis Neuhaus might want to take
note. As Merriman put it, ``With computer trades, all of a sudden
you think you're more powerful than you really are.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Eric Linden is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
