<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6265 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-SINATRA-MEMORIES &LR;      03-11 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-SINATRA-MEMORIES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER OF SINATRA SHRINE DOES IT HIS WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ERIK HOLM  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anthony Marinaro swears he is the illegitimate son of
Frank Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   He has no proof, but he does have Sinatra's swagger. He has
Sinatra's swing. And he has Sinatra's stuff. Lots and lots of
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bunch of junk, you know that?'' Marinaro said as he
surveyed the crowded walls of his Brooklyn
coffee-shop-cum-Sinatra-shrine. ``I'm a completist. I've got to
have it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Marinaro's coffee shop, Sinatra's Coo Coo Nest Caffe, is the
kind of establishment that probably wouldn't make it anywhere but
New York, New York. It's small, with just five tables. It's dingy,
with sporadic overhead lighting. It's hidden on the second floor of
a quiet Brooklyn neighborhood. And Marinaro, 36, has made only the
slightest accommodation for customers seeking solid food to go with
their coffee. Hostess cupcakes and small bags of potato chips are
available upon request.
</P>
<P>
   The Coo Coo Nest's only real attractions are the Sinatra
memorabilia, a creaky old jukebox, and Marinaro himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one believes me when I say I'm Frank Sinatra's son. But how
else do you explain this?'' he said as he dropped a quarter in the
jukebox and belted out an on-the-spot rendition of, ``Available,''
an obscure Sinatra ballad.
</P>
<P>
   A large brown-eyed man with a slight paunch, Marinaro's
mannerisms and lyrical command of the song invoke a vision of the
slight, blue-eyed pop icon.
</P>
<P>
   Marinaro even dresses the part on some nights, with a vintage
suit and vagabond shoes that could have been plucked right out of
the Chairman's closet from his Rat Pack days.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of the cafe are lined with dozens of framed photos of
Sinatra at every stage in his career. A picture of Ol' Blue Eyes in
a sailor suit with Gene Kelly. One with fellow Rat Packers in front
of the now demolished Sands Hotel. And then there's a fuzzy
photocopy of a picture of Marinaro and Sinatra singing a duet. The
Xerox job looks a little suspicious. But side-by-side, there is a
slight facial resemblance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they're cousins,'' allowed Nancy Sizemore, a
neighborhood resident who is more likely to be found in the bar
next door. In this little corner of Brooklyn, everyone feels like
they own a little bit of Frank Sinatra, Sizemore said.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra was born across the river, in Hoboken, N.J. He did not
make it over to Brooklyn much when he was growing up. But once he
had reached the top of the heap, Sinatra would order two sausage
pizzas from Grimaldi's, located just a mile up the road from the
Coo Coo Nest, whenever he was visiting the city that never sleeps.
Sinatra's presence is everywhere on that mile between the two
establishments. Many of the shops in Brooklyn's Little Italy have a
framed photo of the famous crooner on the wall behind the cash
register, and his voice occasionally floats out on the sidewalk
from open windows. Almost a year after Sinatra's death, people
still come to the neighborhood from all over to worship at
Marinaro's shrine to one of the most popular entertainers ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how they hear about the place,'' Marinaro said.
``We're a long way from any other stop on your standard New York
City tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of them catch the fact that ``Coo Coo'' is a reference to a
lyric in the Sinatra standard ``The Lady Is a Tramp.'' But fewer
still can swallow Marinaro's claim to the Sinatra throne. It might
be because Marinaro can't really back up the assertion. He says
that he learned of his heritage 10 years ago when his mother
confessed to him that he was adopted as part of a top secret
cover-up. The story is contrary to his birth certificate, and
Marinaro's mother has died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's understandable that people doubt me, of course,''
Marinaro said. ``There's so many people in the world out to lie to
you, so why should they believe me, right?''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, those who come to the Coo Coo Nest have
apparently decided that it does not matter. The Chairman went to
the great boardroom in the sky last May, and someone has to take
his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were happier back in the days when Sinatra was at his
peak,'' Marinaro said. ``Everyone thinks those days are gone.
They're not gone. They're still happening in this little room.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Frank Sinatra's not gone either. He's sitting right
here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Erik Holm is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
