<HEADER>
A6266 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-IMMIGRANT-NANNIES     03-11 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-IMMIGRANT-NANNIES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NANNIES: BEYOND MARY POPPINS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 BY FARNAZ FASSIHI  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three-year-old Miko Zalas, a chubby boy with curly
brown hair and big brown eyes looked up from his stroller and
smiled shyly at Grace Fuller, his 53-year-old Caribbean nanny.
``Come on Miko, sing along, A Deo Deo,'' she said. He hid his face
in the collar of his red snowsuit, but soon joined her in his
favorite tune, ``Banana Boat'' a Caribbean lullaby Grace sings to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Lipman, 7, goes to school on the Upper West Side but he
already favors Indian food over macaroni and cheese. ``He wants me
to make chicken curry and rice every night,'' said Jessie Desouza,
his 46-year-old Indian nanny.
</P>
<P>
   Friends tell Nigel Wingate's parents that their 8-year-old boy
speaks with
</P>
<P>
   ``an interesting accent.'' He calls his aunt ``ta ta'' which is
the Mexican word for ``aunt.'' Since he was born, Nigel has had
three nannies from three countries; one was from the West Indies,
one from Mexico and the last is Caribbean. These children, like
many in metropolitan cities, spend eight to 10 hours a day with
women from other countries and cultures. According to the records
of The International Nanny Association, an organization based in
Minneapolis that has members nationwide, the majority of nannies in
big cities like New York, Los Angeles and Miami come from other
countries. ``This is a big-city trend,'' Mary O'Conner, the
president of the association, said in a recent telephone interview.
``Around the Midwest and the Northwest they are a rare bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   In large fast-paced cities, affluent parents work long hours
outside the home, mothers return to work sooner after childbirth
and finding a satisfactory child-care arrangement within the family
is difficult. According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, nearly
one million children in the United States are being cared for by
child-care workers and child-care employment will increase faster
than the average of all occupations through the year 2006. In a
city like New York, which brims with people of all cultures,
growing up with diversity at home can be a good thing, said Henry's
mom, Janet Sabel, a lawyer who works full time and relies on Jessie
Desouza, the Indian nanny, to care for her two children. ``Being
with someone from a different country broadens my children's
perspectives on things, it opens their minds,'' Sabel added.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffery Garde, who has a doctorate in child psychology, says
that children who are exposed to cultural diversity in early stages
of life can adapt better to society and get along better with
people but there is an underlying risk. ``When, from a very early
age, a child is used to being served and praised by a person of
color and ethnicity, there is the danger that as an adult, he may
always feel superior to people of that race,'' he said. Dr. Garde
gave the example of his 5-year-old son, who has a Mexican nanny.
When the nanny asked his son to pick up his toys, his son told her
it was none of her business. ``It is clear that in his mind he
knows being a nanny she has to put up with his behavior,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Wingate, president of Best Domestic Agency, which is one
of the area's largest nanny agencies, said that up until recently
many American women never considered being a nanny as a career
option and this left the field open to an increasing number of
ethnic nannies. Among the 355 nannies placed through his agency, he
says 52 percent are from the Caribbean, 23 percent are classified
as ``Hispanic'' and the remaining are a mixture of Africans, Asians
and whites.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Fuller, Miko's nanny from the Caribbean, came to the
United States nine years ago and has worked as a nanny ever since.
She thinks a lot of American families prefer West Indian women
because child rearing is communal there. Families often have as
many as seven or eight children, with considerable age gaps, and it
is common to have the elder ones take care of the youngsters. That
gives the girls experience in caring for children. However, she
acknowledges that raising a child in America is different. ``I am
always aware of the differences and try to keep things in Miko's
own culture,'' she said. ``I don't want to influence him too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian Ivy, who holds a doctorate in psychology, said because
children chose parents as role models from a young age, their view
toward race is directly influenced by the parents' interaction with
the nanny. A child will form a bond with the nanny's culture when
the parents have a close relationship with the woman. But if the
parents treat the nanny in a subservient way, Ivy said, that child
is more likely to carry that through his adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, in the playgrounds of Riverside Park, the little
children lovingly follow their nannies around. Five-year-old Emma
pulled her Indian nanny's hand and says, ``Cholo'' in Hindi,
meaning, ``Let's go.'' Jessie, the nanny, beamed. Eunise Lee sat on
the bench next to Jessie and pushed the stroller back and forth.
The 3-month-old twin boys in her care had fallen asleep under the
winter sun. ``I wonder if when they grow up they will go to the
Islands and say I want to see how my nanny lived and what her
country was like,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Farnaz Fassihi is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
