<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-NUDE-MODELS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUDE MODELING: MORE THAN MEETS THE EYE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By SANDRA YIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She stands with one hand on a hip. An elbow juts. The
other hand touches the top of her head. She is nude from the waist
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you think you can hold this for 15 minutes?'' asked Gideon
Rubin, 25, a senior at the School for Visual Arts in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said the model, Marion Berg, 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You forgot to turn on the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, the heater buzzes on.
</P>
<P>
   Like Berg, Madonna posed in the buff. As long as artists need to
recreate the human body through drawing, painting or sculpture,
they will need nude models.
</P>
<P>
   Most models claim they don't do it just for the money. At hourly
rates that hover around $10, they could earn more waiting tables.
</P>
<P>
   There are perks though. Modeling is a chance to express
yourself. It can lead to other relationships, both professional and
personal. Sometimes through art, the model gains immortality.
</P>
<P>
   Most models say they do not feel naked when posing nude. They
get over any self-consciousness fast, they say. ``You become
essentially a bowl of fruit,'' said Laura Shrewsbury, 29, another
model. ``You're just a mass of light and shadow.''
</P>
<P>
   While some models find posing nude titillating or even erotic,
others, like Shrewsbury, don't. ``If I wanted to get naked, I would
be a stripper and earn a helluva lot more money,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Modeling can hurt. The body was not designed to be locked into
three-hour poses, with five minute breaks every 20 minutes. Some of
the more contorted poses are hard to hold for even a minute as
sketchers try to catch a slice of action. Those models that seem
happiest have backgrounds in dance, theater or art. They understand
their muscles and know how much their bodies can stand.
</P>
<P>
   For some figure classes, professors request specific poses. But
for others, models are more than a bowl of fruit. They often draw
on their knowledge of famous poses in art history, yoga, sports,
dance and theater to create new positions.
</P>
<P>
   Figure modeling, said Magnolia Santibanez, 29, is about giving
and emotions. The more she gives, putting her feelings into a pose,
the more comes back, she says. Modeling is a way of losing yourself
in something larger. You're not giving yourself, she said. ``You're
giving God, channeled through your body,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   In a city like New York, where getting to know other people can
be difficult, modeling can provide a real relationship. Santibanez,
an actress, said she was particularly pleased when a student
captured her thoughts through an expression or gesture. It confirms
what she projected _ someone else received and understood, she
said, adding the feedback is more precise than she could ever hope
for in theater.
</P>
<P>
   Berg, a theater director and teacher in New York City, says she
has become addicted to modeling because she likes the human
contact. Six months ago, the Paris native quit a job as an
executive assistant at a venture capital firm because she felt
``dead'' there. By contrast, making art is life-enhancing. When
someone draws her arm, she feels touched, although the touching was
pencil to paper or brush to canvas.
</P>
<P>
   There are perks. Some art schools offer free classes to models.
The students' use of color and texture in their art, as well as
what they wear, has inspired clothing designs for Shrewsbury's
4-year-old label, Underbelly, which offers sizes up to XL in what
she describes as ``Gothic, Glam, fetish, and cyberpunk.'' She has
also employed models from the School of Visual Arts for clothing
catalog shoots.
</P>
<P>
   For some, modeling is a way to live forever. ``When someone does
a painting and they don't throw it out, you're immortalized,'' said
Norma Jean Clark, 30, an actress.
</P>
<P>
   Clark considers those she meets at the art school as family. The
head of the model registry, Paolo Tanan, is like a brother. Another
model, an older woman, she considers a mother. She met her
boyfriend, an art teacher, through the school too: he hired her to
pose for his students. Clark collects paintings and drawings from
artists she knows. ``Maybe I'll retire on them if I don't make it
big as an actress,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Sandra Yin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
