<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6268 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-CARRIAGE-HORSES &LR;      03-11 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-CARRIAGE-HORSES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVISTS SAY 'NEIGH' TO CARRIAGE HORSE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By Douglas Steinke  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some say they are charming and romantic, others say
they are dirty and mistreated, but one thing is certain: Nearly all
New Yorkers have something to say about the carriage horses that
carry tourists and lovers around midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps none are more outspoken than the animal rights activists
who are trying to send the horses galloping out of the city and to
the farms where they say the horses belong.
</P>
<P>
   New York, which has six stables, isn't the only city that has a
carriage industry, and wherever carriage horses are found, animal
rights activists are not far behind. Atlanta, Boston, Chattanooga,
Tenn., Chicago, Indianapolis, Ind., and Kansas City, Mo., also have
carriage horses, although New York's industry is one of the biggest
and oldest.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, when several horses died of heat exhaustion
and other health conditions there, activists lobbied for stronger
laws. This year, a horse was electrocuted and died in a street
accident near Central Park. Activists are saying again that the
conditions for the horses have not improved and that the animals do
not belong in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would at least like to review this insane policy of having
the horses all over the city,'' said Susan Wagner of Equine
Advocates, a program that rescues abused horses nationwide and
places them with new owners.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1989 and 1994, a city law confined the horses to Central
Park. But when that law expired, a new one allowed the horses to
roam farther and later into the night. The horses are not allowed
all over the city, but they can travel through Central Park and
along a small stretch near the city's theater district.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner said that the horses had no place to graze and that at
night many are kept in tie stalls _ stalls so small that the horses
are unable to lie down or turn around in them. Some city stables
have the roomier quarters known as box stalls, although most do
not, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tie stalls, Michael Goodale of Pride of Kansas City Carriages in
Missouri acknowledges, are ``maybe a little small.'' But Goodale,
who keeps his 10 horses in the larger stalls, said activists are
comparing the living requirements of a horse to those of a human.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not that way,'' Goodale said. ``A horse is made for
strength and for pulling plows and carriages.''
</P>
<P>
   After the electrocution in New York, activists have been
``bearing down,'' said Henry Rogers of Chateau Stables in New York.
The horse that was killed was not owned by Chateau, he said, but
that has not kept the activists at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't care whose it was,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   No fewer than four different city agencies oversee the New York
carriage industry, including the consumer affairs and health
departments. Under city law, the Department of Consumer Affairs is
required to inspect the carriages at least once every four months,
and the humane law-enforcement division of the American Society for
the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals monitors the horses.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Holly Cheever, a veterinarian and consultant with the ASPCA from
1988 to 1994 whose duties included inspecting the stables, said the
conditions of the stables were narrow, dirty, and stiflingly hot in
the summer months. ``It was a narrow, black hole of Calcutta type
of thing,'' Cheever said, referring to conditions in the city in
India.
</P>
<P>
   The horses were watered only when they were working, she said,
and they were not often brushed or hosed down.
</P>
<P>
   While she said the condition of the horses seemed to be better
than it was during the 1980s, when there were few laws protecting
the horses, she's not confident that stable conditions have
improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have are the same stables that were used during the
days when carriages were the main form of transportation, archaic
stables that are in poor condition,'' Cheever said, referring to
19th-century stable conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau Stables, on Manhattan's West Side, provides horses for
theatrical productions in addition to the horses it uses for
carriage rides. Situated near a long string of car dealerships not
far from the Lincoln Tunnel, the two-story red brick building has a
ramp that the horses use to go to their stalls on the top floor.
</P>
<P>
   Four small Dumpsters filled with horse manure sat outside the
building on a recent afternoon, and the building itself is marked
by an old sign that reads, ``Chateau Stables/Chateau Theatrical
Animals.'' The company no longer raises the chickens and other
small animals it provided for Broadway shows, according to
Chateau's Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers declined to talk about the stables or the horses. ``We're
not looking for publicity right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Stagno of the New York chapter of In Defense of Animals,
a California-based group that is leading the charge against the
carriage industry in New York, said there was a different reason
why the carriage horse operators had little to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because they don't want people to know'' about the
conditions of the horses, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stagno said she did not think the carriage horses would ever
leave New York, but in St. Petersburg, Fla., Greta Bunting of the
Carriage Horse Action Committee of St. Petersburg hopes to push the
city's only carriage horse operator out of town.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, Mo., if animal rights activists were not
concerned about carriage horses there, at least one newspaper
editor was. Laura Scott, assistant editorial page editor of The
Kansas City Star, wrote in 1997 that ``much evidence points to the
reality that the horses don't belong on the Plaza.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goodale of Pride of Kansas City Carriages, a company that
has been in the carriage horse business for 20 years, disagrees.
``The ambience of the Plaza,'' he said, referring to an area of the
city that frequently hosts conventions, ``includes the horse-drawn
carriage. I don't know why these people think the horses are
abused.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cities, such as Sante Fe, N.M., Palm Beach, Fla. and Las
Vegas, have banned the carriage horse trade at the activists'
behest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing to do,'' Bunting said of the carriage
operators, ``is to try to stop them before they get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodale called the animal rights activists ``hate groups'' that
are more concerned with putting the carriage operators out of
business than with the safety of the horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the horses are your livelihood, then of course you're going
to take care of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Douglas Steinke is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
