<SLUG> BC-CNS-BOWERY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOWERY AIN'T WHAT IT USED TO BE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.   By KEVIN ROTHSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sitting in a wheelchair parked on the corner of
Bowery and Houston Street, Ed Caldwell pointed to his old haunts.
The Blue Moon bar was across the street. Now, it's a parking lot. A
cathouse, where the former merchant marine spent a few nights, is
on the intersection's southwest corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd get drunk like any other man, and when that run out you
get back to the ship or you go to jail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his left leg four years ago in a subway accident.
Caldwell, a bearded 53-year-old, is destitute and begs about $20 a
day. It is enough to rent a cubicle at the White House, a nearby
flophouse that used to cater to only white men. A black man,
Caldwell says it is integrated now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a mile from 14th Street south into the heart of
Chinatown, the Bowery was home to 7,000 people in the late 1960s,
twice as many in the 1940s. Many were homeless and penniless. The
Prohibition-era World League Against Alcoholism counted 200 bars on
the Bowery and 44 lodging houses, where rooms could be rented for
10 or 15 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowery, the country's most famous skid row, now sports a few
hot nightspots. Instead of being overwhelmed by the homeless, some
young people come here to live and play. Glimpses of the newcomers
remind long-time residents of how far the Bowery has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first moved here there were a lot of drunks,'' said
Sally Amato, who with her husband Anthony moved the tiny Amato
Opera Theatre to the Bowery nearly 50 years ago. She said the
Bowery's old denizens never gave her any problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just blow on them and they fall down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, Caldwell, and others who live and work on the Bowery say
the street began change about five years ago. On Bleeker Street and
Bowery, a block away from Caldwell's corner, Astor Restaurant &AMP;
Lounge opened two years ago. Owner Murat Bugdaycay put in high
ceilings and plenty of brass and wood for a look he called an
``American-French bistro combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Amatos, he is also asked why he chose the Bowery. But
he believes the street is gaining a cachet of its own, one he hopes
will match the surrounding neighborhoods. In a way, the street's
notoriety even works to his favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows where the Bowery is, for sure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greasy spoons along the Bowery used to specialize in pig snouts
and cabbage, the cheapest food around. Now that Astor has an
outdoor caf license, diners can enjoy house house specialties like
seared tuna with escarole to diners seated on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything has changed. Street preachers like Brother John
Callahan of the flapper-era Hadley Hall mission fertile ground for
their message of salvation. That tradition continues with the
Bowery Mission, run by the non-denominational Christian Herald
Association since 1878.
</P>
<P>
   New York City recognizes the mission as a historical landmark. A
grant to renovate the building's fade is in the works. It will
cover the cost to touch up the masonry and highlight the stained
glass. A neon cross is also planned. It would extend into the
street and serve as a beacon for those who need it.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowery Mission now feeds, clothes and shelters the men who
enroll in its program of bible study and and job training. By
appearances, the mission recalls this earlier era. Facing the
Bowery is a stained glass portrayal of the wayward Prodigal Son's
returning to his father. Inside is the chapel. But it hasn't run
out of customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a crowd for every meal,'' said Rod Malloy, the
mission's director of development.
</P>
<P>
   One enrollee is Lynn Thomas, a 54-year-old North Carolina native
with a crushing handshake. Thomas' last bout with drugs and alcohol
landed him in Harlem Hospital's psychiatric ward. Speaking as he
prepared trays of frozen hamburgers for lunch, Thomas said he
learned of the Mission through word of mouth and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like God led me here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Thomas, many men who have become unhinged find their way to
the Bowery. Not all choose the Bowery Mission's bible-based
program. But Malloy said he was constantly amazed to see that men
from all over the country still gravitate to the Bowery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get guys from all over the country that come to New York
for a new start, '' he said. ``Or to escape from whatever problems
they were having.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Kevin Rothstein is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
