<P>
   URBAN QUILTERS _ More and more New York men are finding a
traditional home art to be a source of expression.
</P>
<P>
   CARRIAGE HORSES _ Where horse &QC; drawn carriages are found so too
can be found animal rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   NUDE MODELS _ They bare all in the name of art, and few are in
it for the money.
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ _ Jazz composers come together to hear works in progress.
</P>
<P>
   BOWERY _ The Bowery, the country's most famous skid row, now
sports a few hot nightspots. Instead of being overwhelmed by the
homeless, some young people come here to live and play. Glimpses of
the newcomers remind long-time residents of how far the Bowery has
come.
</P>
<P>
   SINATRA MEMORIES _ He looks like Sinatro (sort of), walks like
Sinatra (sort of), sings like Sinatra (sort of) and claims to be
Sinatra's illegetimate son.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK TRADERS _ Smalltime investors are trading stocks on the
Internet. About 40 percent of all current stock trades made by
individual investors are performed online.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANT NANNIES _ They come from the Caribbean, Europe and
Africa and care for children, while adding a dash of diversity to
family life.
</P>
<P>
   BOXING GYMS _ The old boxing gyms fight to stay afloat as money
gets harder and harder to find.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKSTORE COMPETITION _ Small, specialty bookstores that managed
to survive the invasion of the superstore bookstores are having a
tougher time against online bookstores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6271 &Cx1f; tab-z
