<SLUG> BC-CNS-BOOKSTORE-COMPETITION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL BOOKSTORES FEEL THE SQUEEZE OF THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.   By KEN THOMAS  
 c.1999Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Diana Wells decided to close her wood-paneled
travel bookstore, she wanted to turn her misfortune into a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who specialized in obscure titles like the British
``Cadogan Guide'' and Peter Hathaway Capstick's ``Sands of Silence:
On Safari in Namibia,'' was shutting down her tiny shop after
months of fruitless marketing to her 65,000 globetrotting
customers. She sent newsletters, appealed to them on her new Web
site and spotlighted her veteran staff's knowledge about travel
tips in Tuscany and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   But by December, Wells knew her 17-year-old Traveller's
Bookstore was no match for Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that since we're struggling so much now, I would only
lose more money and more of my heart by continuing on,'' Wells
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's going to be that much worse during the next
year because it's growing so fast,'' she said of the popular online
bookseller. ``It's a brand new world that's opening up for so many
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells decided to make the best protest she could. In the window
of her store - nestled inside the lobby of the midtown Time Warner
building - she posted a New York City map showing 56 independent
bookstores, with a bold red X marking each of the 17 stores that
she says have closed in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Meg Ryan character in the movie ``You've Got Mail,''
Wells and other independent sellers have increasingly felt the
pinch of the behemoth bookstore chains and the unprecedented
Amazon.com online juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   In an industry that prides itself on service and expertise, many
independent stores are at a loss to compete with the convenience of
online shopping and discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Online book sales accounted for 2.4 percent of total sales in
1998, or $650 million, said Ken Cassar, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications, a New York-based Internet research firm. By 2002,
he projects, sales will be 11.3 percent of the market, or $3.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, the Web's largest book seller, raked in 1 million
new customers during the holiday season and peddled $250 million in
business in the fourth quarter, according to company figures.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the number of independent bookstores in the United
States has dropped 27 percent between 1991 and 1997, according to a
study last year by the American Booksellers Association. In the
same time, large chains have increased by 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The squeeze is not limited to New York. In October, the
family-owned Baxter's Books closed its doors in downtown
Minneapolis. In California, Gaya Books, a 12-year-old Berkeley
store specializing in New Age spirituality, and Printers Inc., a
Palo Alto store, also shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those bookstores would not be closing today if it was just the
Internet,'' said James McQuivey, an analyst with Forrester
Research, who contends chain stores also are choking the
independent. ``It's just a more difficult market than it ever has
been before.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells has accepted the inevitable. ``If you can sit in your
pajamas and order at 1 o'clock in the morning from the comfort of
your own home, I think people will,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many independent holdouts are clinging to the belief that
the big chains cannot match their service. Proprietors at the
Military Bookman on Manhattan's East Side and Murder Ink, featuring
rare murder mysteries, say their own Internet sales have actually
increased.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Seelen, an owner of the 75-year-old Drama Book Shop, said
his clientele was unflaggingly loyal. ``If they have anything to do
with the theater, they're a customer of ours,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Manhattan's Corner Bookstore, owner Lenny Golay insists
online customers have a different profile, often preferring books
about Web-related topics. ``They're not books that a literary
bookstore would carry,'' Golay said.
</P>
<P>
   A recent comparison showed that of the 25 top sellers on
Amazon.com, nine did not make The New York Times best seller list.
Many best selling books online deal with technology or the stock
market: Recent hot sellers on Amazon.com have been ``How to Get
Started in Electronic Day Trading'' and ``The Motley Fool's Rule
Breakers, Rule Makers: A Foolish Guide to Picking Stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Golay is concerned, this is a sign that independent
stores will continue to have a niche in a city full of bibliophiles
like New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be home with the flu on a weekend, you're
not going to go to Amazon.com,'' Golay said. ``You're going to go
to the local bookstore.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Ken Thomas is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
