<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6272 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-BOXING-GYMS &LR;      03-11 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-BOXING-GYMS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THERE WERE RINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ANDREAS TZORTZIS  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a small crime. Miguel Castillo did not rob
anybody, steal money or commit murder. But the one incident of
shoplifting was enough for Miguel's father and he pulled his
13-year-old son down to the West Side Boxing Gym for some
discipline and distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo couldn't stand the gym. He was more comfortable fitting
his 310-pound frame into the sofa in front of the television, or
spending his afternoons playing video games.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at 6 feet 2 inches and on the good side of 199 pounds,
Castillo, now 20, is a lithe, muscular shadow of his former self.
The video games have been given up for the speedball and punching
bag. In place of the shoplifting is the steady work West Side Gym's
owner, Arthemio Colon, gives him when he needs the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a pops, a grandfather to me,'' Castillo said. ``I
get a place to chill, and, when I was younger, stay out of
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   But trainers like Colon and gyms like the West Side are
beginning to vanish. Since 1994, New York City has lost 40 gyms,
leaving just 63 registered with USA Boxing, the national amateur
governing body. The annual Golden Gloves tournament in New York
City, open to all amateurs willing to brave the ring, had a 5
percent drop in the number of competitors this year, said John
Woluewich, the vice president of USA Boxing's local committee in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just teaching a fighter how to take a punch is not enough.
Today's boxing instructor and gym owner need to be able to write a
convincing grant proposal, present an attractive budget and hustle
for sponsorships. Most need to keep their flock from an even more
powerful lure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I think we're losing the kids to the streets, the
drug money, the flashiness,'' said Woluewich, who also trains young
fighters at Gleason's Gym on the shores of the East River in
Brooklyn. Last year, Woluewich lost one of his star fighters after
he was convicted of murder and sent to prison. ``The lure of the
streets gets them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Equally distressing is a lack of money to finance small,
neighborhood gyms. Money from the city and some agencies is not
enough to maintain the equipment needed to run a successful gym,
some gym owners say.
</P>
<P>
   Even USA Boxing can do little to help. The organization charges
each boxer $18 to register, a requirement if they want to compete
on the amateur level. In exchange, the gyms where the athletes
train receive a $1 million insurance policy to cover their
liability, but little else.
</P>
<P>
   The number of amateur boxers registered has stayed the same,
said Kevin Neuendorf, a USA Boxing spokesman, and 300 new gyms have
sprouted around the country over the past four years. But Woluewich
said high rents have caused the boom to skip New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The dearth of money has caused gyms to begin behaving like
struggling non-profit organizations. Recently, USA Boxing put out a
pamphlet for gym owners on the basics of grant proposal writing and
scripting endorsement letters to possible sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be out there on the front line pounding their
fist on the desk and asking for money, basically,'' Neuendorf said.
</P>
<P>
   In a city as awash in boxing history as New York, it's hard for
some to swallow that the gyms that spawned champions such as Sugar
Ray Robinson and Riddick Bowe and provided the training ground for
Muhammad Ali are vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   It makes veteran fighters like Woluewich, 42, pine for the days
of his youth, when disputes were settled in a ring, not the street.
Woluewich himself got into the sport after breaking a classmate's
nose 40 years ago. A local family court judge required him to
enroll in the neighborhood Police Athletic League and take his
right hook to the local ring.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Athletic League continues to provide boxing classes
on a $100,000 budget for New York City's youth population at six
sites in Brooklyn, the Bronx and Queens. But the 85-year-old
non-profit's focus has shifted over the years. Stressing exposure
to the fundamentals rather than serious competitiveness, the Police
Athletic League provides boxing instruction for children who may
not be interested in ever stepping into a ring, said to its sports
director, Jim Dolan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't discourage that, but our focus is on keeping kids off
the streets by showing them positive things to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Police Athletic League can only pay for its own
programs, and still jockeys for corporate and city grants with
other gyms. Gone are the days when the New York City Parks and
Recreation Department ran up to a total of 30 boxing programs in
all boroughs. Today, there are fewer than five sites in New York
that offer boxing instruction. ``It's too expensive,'' said Mike
Rosario, who runs a popular boxing program at the Thomas Jefferson
Recreation Center. ``They don't have the money to pay for the rent
or for equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Acevedo, the boxing instructor at St. Mary's Recreation
center in the Bronx considers himself a sort of public relations
executive. To raise enough money for the extra protective headgear
and gloves needed on a yearly basis, he goes to the Bronx borough
president, Fernando Ferrer, and other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all go through a little budget changing,'' Acevedo, a New
York City Park and Recreations Department employee, admitted. ``But
I've got good sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   Acevedo and others say the reason they hustle to keep the
programs around is simple. All agree the pride, discipline and
dedication instilled in the young fighters keeps them away from
less productive distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing for many kids is a way of expression, it's self-pride,
that you can do something, you can accomplish something,'' said
Bert Sugar, a popular boxing historian and author who edits Boxing
Illustrated magazine. The boxer ``is expending energy. He goes home
and he's tired as hell. He doesn't have time to go out and steal a
hubcap.''
</P>
<P>
   In the narrow, low-ceiling labyrinth of a gym in Washington
Heights, Castillo found the discipline, release and dedication
missing from his youth. In order to make it to class at La Guardia
Community College on time, he rises at 5 a.m. to jog in Riverside
Park or at a track near Yankee Stadium in the Bronx. After school,
Castillo will head straight to Colon's gym for an intense workout
and a few rounds of sparring in the tiny ring, then straight to
bed. ``I'm too tired to do anything else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Colon, 79, remembers the 40 fighters he had in the years after
he first opened the gym in 1960 on the advice of his friend Rocky
Marciano. The gym, with its sloppy, white plaster walls, tired old
iron machines and damp air became the testing ground for 18 Golden
Gloves champions over the years. Colon trained them as rigorously
as he does Castillo, and the weathered ring, now in a room closer
to the gym's entrance, was often filled with their blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps me here,'' Castillo said of Colon. ``I get to train
for free and work and you can't beat that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Andreas Tzortzis is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
