r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-JAZZ &LR;      03-11 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-JAZZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE 'PLAY'S' THE THING AT JAZZ COMPOSERS' WORKSHOP 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 Brad Foss  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jamie Begian has been fine-tuning his hauntingly
spare composition ``All Beans'' for two months. Nevertheless, the
35-year-old jazz musician is not sure if it has actually improved.
</P>
<P>
   On a morning after his jazz trio performs at a posh Upper East
Side cigar bar, Begian substituted his Gibson ES 335 guitar for a
No. 2 pencil. Seated at a short wooden desk, wearing faded jeans
and a gray crewneck sweater, he wrote meticulously on
lunchtray-sized score paper the musical notes swirling around his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that the first version was the best,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But that was not the message from peers and mentors at
New York's BMI Jazz Composers Workshop, a collection of
professional musicians who rely on feedback from one another to
help guide the creative process. With the next meeting just two
days away, Begian was anxious to hear BMI's 16-piece jazz ensemble
``read'' his piece. Only then would he know for sure whether his
minimalist creation was done.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988 scores of New York City's aspiring jazz composers
have participated in the workshop. The original members were mostly
players in the renowned Thad Jones-Mel Lewis Jazz Orchestra, which
thrived at the Village Vanguard until Jones' death in 1986. The
workshop remains a unique opportunity to have one's compositions
performed by top-notch Broadway and studio musicians, an expense
few novices could afford otherwise. But it is also a venue for
up-and-coming jazz writers to test their talent, meet informally
with their genre's legends and explore musical boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can fail or find out great things about yourself,'' said
Manny Albam, 76, one of three musical directors of the program.
Albam has been a composer, arranger and conductor for jazz notables
such as Dizzy Gillespie, Sarah Vaughn, Gerry Mulligan, Count Basie
and Woody Herman. He said the key was to write simply,
meaningfully, and quickly, all qualities that enabled him to create
the first jazz arrangement of Leonard Bernstein's ``West Side
Story'' in only five days.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being a haven for experimentation, the workshop
is useful for composers, Albam said, because it brings them
together and helps combat the ``aloneness'' of writing. That is not
to say the workshop is one big love fest.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hoffman, 43, who is earning a Ph.D. in music at New York
University, said fellow musicians were generally ``very
supportive'' of one another ``but that does not mean people don't
leave the workshop really bummed out sometimes.'' Indeed, neither
praise nor monetary success is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say that I have never once received a dime for
anything I've composed, except for a meager $14 in royalties,''
said Hoffman, who is flooding universities with his resume in
search of a teaching position. ``Hearing my stuff played is enough.
If it was never played, I don't think it would be worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Neumeister, a former trombone player in the Jones-Lewis jazz
band that performed regularly at the Village Vanguard, said he
became a ``serious writer'' the day he joined the workshop. Upon
the suggestion of the workshop's musical director, Neumeister began
arranging old jazz standards ``just as an exercise.'' In 1992,
however, one of these exercises _ Neumeister's arrangement of
Manning Sherwin's ``A Nightingale Sang in Berkeley Square'' _
earned him a Grammy award nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the benefits, as many as 1 in 3 of those who are
selected to join the workshop eventually drop out. ``Some of them
don't realize how hard they have to work,'' said Burt Korall, the
workshop's founder and director.
</P>
<P>
   Those who stick with it have limitless potential, said Jim
McNeely, composer-in-residence for the Village Vanguard Jazz
Orchestra and also a musical director for the workshop. ``Most of
them could certainly do what I've done'' for the Vanguard
orchestra, he said _ no small compliment considering their new
album, ``Lickety Split,'' was nominated for a Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   McNeely said he looked forward to hearing the ways in which
other musicians experiment with sounds. Of Begian, he says, ``He is
not afraid of taking some chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The workshop Begian had been anticipating began at 10 a.m., but
two hours passed before his piece was heard. A surreal and bluesy
composition by pianist Lisa DeSpain titled ``Dreaming in the Land
of Blue Oz'' was met with applause and nods of encouragement. She
even earned a peck on the cheek from Korall, whose jazz critiques
have appeared everywhere from Down Beat to The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   DeSpain, 34, said she had worked on the composition for nearly
two years before it became absolutely necessary to have it played
in front of her contemporaries. ``You get so involved when you are
composing that your ears get numb to what you're writing,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Begian's turn arrived, he eagerly arched his body forward
to listen as three flutists, a drummer and a bass player began the
opening lines of ``All Beans.'' The orchestra performed a few bars
from different sections of the composition before Begian abruptly
cut them off by waving his arms above his head.
</P>
<P>
   He had heard enough. He thanked the band, turned off his
recording device and sat down in the last row of folding chairs set
up in the small studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's done,'' he said. ``I think it's done.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Brad Foss is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
