<SLUG> BC-CNS-URBAN-QUILTERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL MEN DO QUILT, EVEN IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired. By RAMONA JENKIN
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Inside Bob Dawson's home on a tree-lined Brooklyn
street there are 27 traditional quilts in different sizes
meticulously pieced and hand-quilted.
</P>
<P>
   Each line of quilting _ the stitches that hold together the
sandwich of soft fluffy batting between two layers of cloth to make
up the quilt _ contains eight to 10 even stitches per inch, in
patterns that vary from straight lines to fancy ferns.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson has made them all.
</P>
<P>
   On a cold, clear Sunday afternoon, he settled into the big
stuffed blue chair in his living room and tightened a 16-inch
square white plastic quilting frame around a quilt of dark colored
squares within squares.
</P>
<P>
   He adjusted the black draftsman's lamp and started quilting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a quilt for when we moved into our new home,'' said
Dawson, 50, an engineer who took an early retirement package five
years ago after 24 years at NYNEX.
</P>
<P>
   He was about to get married to Evie Landry, 45, who has quilted
for the last 25 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While they were house-hunting they looked at a co-op that had an
Amish quilt hanging on a wall, he said. They didn't buy the co-op
but they liked the quilt so much they started looking for one just
like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't find what I wanted,'' Dawson said.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, who works for an international reproductive health
organization, did not have the time to make it. So Dawson read some
quilting books and made it himself.
</P>
<P>
   Now Dawson quilts almost every day, recreating historical quilts
he sees in books, stores or at shows, adding his own touches, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally he uses the computer to figure out dimensions, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he may have been influenced by his grandmother, who was
a quilter, Dawson said his master's degree in engineering has also
been helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it easy to figure out the geometry,'' Dawson said.
``It helps in piecing and quilting. It's about being precise and
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry said: ``I let him figure out my quilts now. I let him
engineer it and cut it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Horansky, 70, a retired pattern maker, and his wife, Ruby,
69, have attended the monthly meeting of the Empire Quilters' Guild
in Manhattan for almost three years.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent meeting, they pinned fabric together for a double
wedding ring quilt, a gift for a friend, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Horansky started quilting about five years ago after she
left her job as a mystery novelist, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife did it as a hobby and I watched,'' Horansky said. ''
'I could do that,' I said.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his retirement Horansky read a book on quilting and
made his first quilt, a crib-sized Irish chain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I got interested in log cabins,'' he said, referring to a
traditional pattern of strips sewn into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Horansky proudly displayed a photo of Clambake, his 4-by-4-foot
quilt _ a log cabin pattern in orange, green and tan _ in the book
``1999 Great American Quilts.'' It was named for the bright colors
in the center, like you would see in a fire at a clambake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Horansky and his wife machine piece, and unlike Dawson, they
machine quilt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Their styles are different and they usually work independently,
Mrs. Horansky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm not sure of something I'll ask him,'' she said.
``It's really very helpful to have another quilter there.''
</P>
<P>
   Horansky sees many benefits from his quilting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's given me new friends,'' he said. ``I like to show the
quilts. It gives me a sense of purpose and giving the quilts away
gives me great pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   His latest project was inspired by a large stone he saw in a
museum on a recent trip to Mexico City, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be forty inches round of the Aztec stone of the sun,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At another table at the guild meeting, Sam Novgorodoff, 45, sat
pinning and sewing hand-dyed pieces of fabric in the shape of apple
cores.
</P>
<P>
   He has been quilting for about six years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's virtually unappreciated in today's society,'' Novgodoroff
said of quilting. ``It's warm and is an expression of love.''
</P>
<P>
   The first quilt he made was a panel for the NAMES Project _
which commemorates the lives of people who have died from AIDS in
3-by-6-foot quilts _ in memory of his painting teacher, he said.
Then Novgodoroff helped friends make five other panels.
</P>
<P>
   His interest in quilting continued, he said, and he has made
about 30 bed- or wall-sized quilts since then. Most of them he has
given away.
</P>
<P>
   Novgodoroff said his techniques included machine and hand
piecing and quilting, photo transfer and trapunto, in which extra
batting, or stuffing, is sewn into small areas of the quilt
resulting in a raised effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's boring if you keep doing the same thing,'' he said. ``The
new techniques allow you to try new things all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Novgodoroff and Horansky are the only two men who belong to the
approximately 300-member guild, said its president, Susan Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But both men said they felt comfortable and enjoyed meeting
people at the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The guild does a lot of charity work, Novgodoroff said,
including quilts for children at places like the Ronald McDonald
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us like to quilt and don't know what to do with our
excesses,'' he said. ``If we don't see it ever again, we know that
it's been used for a good purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Horansky and Novgodoroff may be the only two men in the Empire
guild but Judy Doenias, 58, who has been teaching hand-quilting
classes in New York City since 1990, said that on average she
usually has one man in each group of 16 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of professional people who usually have a lot
of down time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Ritchey, 47, a computer programmer and one of two men in
Doenias' Tuesday evening class, recently bought his uncle's
farmhouse in Ohio and discovered a dozen quilts and quilt tops in
the attic, some in need of repair, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchey plans to move into the farmhouse in about three years,
he said, and he decided to work on the quilts himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea there was quilting in New York City,'' he said.
``Quilting is something I associated with the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Vogler, 40, a bank auditor and the other male student in
the class, said he was inspired by some Shakers' quilt work he saw
upstate in New York's Columbia County.
</P>
<P>
   A male friend of his brother-in-law also quilts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other men, Vogler said he was very comfortable with his
new hobby.
</P>
<P>
   His boss, a woman, knows that he quilts, he said, and although
he has not told co-workers, he thinks they would accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly,'' he said, ``I think it would raise a momentary
eyebrow and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Ramona Jenkin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
