<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
FAA COMPLETES FIRST STEP IN COMPUTER UPGRADE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
 PM-FAA-COMPUTERS-NYT  (gm) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Aviation Administration has finished
replacing a hulking, obsolete, trouble-prone mainframe computer at
its air traffic control center in Ronkonkoma, N.Y., the first step
in its nationwide modernization campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Air Route Traffic Control Center, on Long Island,
has been running the replacement computer full time since Feb. 24,
following last-minute changes insisted on by electronics
technicians for safety reasons. The FAA has suffered many setbacks
in its efforts to modernize but is pointing to Ronkonkoma as a
path-breaking success.
</P>
<P>
   The center handles mostly high-altitude, long-distance flights _
a total of 2 million in a typical year. The computer failed twice
in May 1996, delaying hundreds of flights by as much as an hour and
a quarter, among other failures.
</P>
<P>
   The device _ actually a computer and an identical backup _ fills
about 250 square feet, replacing an 1,800-square-foot IBM Model
3083 from the late 1980s. The replacement model, an IBM G-3, is not
new, but is still in wide use and, more important, is young enough
that replacement parts are widely available.
</P>
<P>
   When the younger models are installed at all 20 of the FAA's
high-altitude, long-distance centers nationwide in the next few
months, the agency expects to save $15.6 million in electricity
costs, about 95 percent of the bill, over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new machines are smarter, faster, more reliable and easier
to maintain, and that's going to have a positive impact on
safety,'' said Rodney E. Slater, the transportation secretary, in
an interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garvey said in a statement that the new computers are ``a
central element of our modernization program to build the air
traffic control system for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   The replacement computers are also certified as being able to
handle the rollover to the year 2000. The old one was not, and IBM
said it no longer had programmers who could read the outdated
computer code and correct it. The FAA eventually had to hire two
retired programmers to work on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was becoming desperate because the old machines,
installed from 1986 to 1988, were becoming impossible to service. A
recent report by the General Accounting Office said that a part
used to cool the old machine, called a CVLM, burned out regularly
and only about two-dozen spares remained nationally. Not only were
new cooling parts not available, but, according to the report,
nobody at the agency or IBM even remembered what CVLM stood for.
</P>
</TEXT>
