 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2526 - March 11, 1999   NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2526 -- March 11, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. MUST THE IRAQI PEOPLE BE PUNISHED FOR SADDAM'S EVIL? You have
probably heard of Scott Ritter, the UNSCOM weapons inspector and
former U.S. Marine, who resigned his post last August to protest
what he saw as the failure of the United States to act more
forcefully against Saddam Hussein's weapons of mass destruction.
But you may not have heard of Denis Halliday, who resigned his post
as head of the United Nations' Oil for Food Program in Iraq just
two weeks later to protest the humanitarian costs of the U.N.
sanctions. ``Four thousand to 5,000 children are dying
unnecessarily every month due to the impact of sanctions,'' he
said. ``We are in the process of destroying an entire society. It
is as simple and terrifying as that. It is illegal and immoral. By
Matthew Rothschild. From The Progressive. Full-length (3,000 words)
+ edited article available. 2. BIG NAME HUNTING Here is a
behind-the-scenes look at how TV stars Mike Wallace, Diane Sawyer,
Barbara Walters and Larry King go after big names such as Monica
Lewinsky. By Barbara Matusow. From Washingtonian magazine.
Full-length (3,500 words) + edited article available. 3. ELECTROBOY
``As far as manic-depressive tales go, my stories are typical. My
illness went undiagnosed for a decade, a period of euphoric highs
and desperate lows highlighted by $25,000 shopping trips, impetuous
trips to Tokyo, Paris and Milan, drug and alcohol binges, days
without sleep, sex with strangers and jail time. After seeing eight
psychiatrists, I finally received a diagnosis of bipolar disorder
on my 32nd birthday.'' By Andy Behrman. From The New York Times
Magazine. 1,500 words. 4. KUBRICK : THE RECLUSIVE MOVIEMAKING
GENIUS Stanley Kubrick died on Sunday at the age of 70 at his home
outside London, leaving a $100-million legacy - his latest film,
``Eyes Wide Shut,'' a psychological thriller starring Tom Cruise
and Nicole Kidman which is due to open in July, two years later
than expected. Steven Spielberg called Kubrick ``the grand master
of filmmaking. He copied no-one while we scrambled to catch up with
him.'' By Ivor Davis. 1,500 words.
