<HEADER>
A6320 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARCIA-COLUMN12-COX     03-11 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Please don't call him `Junior'
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ So, George W. Bush had a lineup of Republican
political superstars itching to tell an assembly of reporters _
representing media outlets from all over the Unites States, Japan,
Great Britain, Mexico, Texas and at least a couple from South
Austin _ what a great guy he is and what a great president he'd
make.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal. So, George W. Bush has won re-election as governor of
Texas _ something no governor since Dolph Briscoe in the 1970s had
managed to accomplish. Another big deal.
</P>
<P>
   So, George W. Bush delivered a nice piece of political rhetoric
that hit a nice tone of inclusiveness, self-reliance and the
importance of entrepreneurship, of owning something.
</P>
<P>
   Well, another big deal. Because if you listened to George
Stephanopoulos, George W. Bush doesn't even own his name. On the
Sunday morning talk show, ``This Week,'' Stephanopoulos referred to
the Texas governor and possible presidential candidate as ``George
Bush Jr.''
</P>
<P>
   And during the Sunday afternoon news conference convened to
introduce members of a committee that will explore the viability of
a George W. Bush presidential candidacy, the governor had to field
more than one question about his father.
</P>
<P>
   Some people say having a father who was once president gives
George W. Bush a big boost. That may be right, but if Sunday's
press conference is any indication, George W. may spend more time
than he really wants answering questions about his father, George
Herbert Walker Bush.
</P>
<P>
   We've been down this road before, but let's go down this road
again. The governor is not a Junior, in any sense. His friends
refer to him as ``W'' (or as ``Dubya'' as columnist Molly Ivins has
tagged him) when they want to make clear which George they are
talking about. But ``Junior'' the governor is not.
</P>
<P>
   After the governor and potential presidential contender laid out
his definition of a ``compassionate conservative'' and talked about
the importance of an America in which no one is left behind (I told
you those rhetorical touches were nice), one of the first questions
he was asked was about his dad and what part the elder Bush's brain
trust would play in the national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's George W. Bush who is going to be the candidate. I'm
going to have my own team,'' the governor responded, adding about
his father, ``I inherited half his friends and all of his
enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was also asked if his father's policies would be held
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any rival who criticizes my father makes a huge mistake. He's
not the candidate _ I am,'' the younger Bush responded. The
governor was just as quick to edit the remark to be more
conditional _ if he were to be the candidate, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Though having a famous namesake is no doubt a blessing, George
W. has had to accept the conscious and unconscious comparisons to
his dad. In his first run for governor, there were enough snide
comments made about ``Junior'' to paper the interior of the
mansion.
</P>
<P>
   And as recently as Sunday, George W. was answering questions
about what kind of advice he was getting from his dad. He said he
would listen to advice from both parents, but that he would have to
take advice from his mother because ``she's going to give it
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor handles questions about his pop with wit and class.
He makes clear that he reveres and loves his father, but makes
equally clear that he is an individual in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   Before this exploratory phase of the Bush presidential candidacy
is over _ and make no mistake, it is a candidacy _ you're probably
going to read a lot about George W. and his father's shadow. Maybe
those father-son comparisons are inevitable. We haven't had a son
follow a father into the presidency this century. The last two to
pull that off were the Adamses, John and John Quincy.
</P>
<P>
   At the minimum, however, you would think that people who get
paid a lot of money to dispense political analysis on national
television this century would at least get the Texas governor's
name right.
</P>
<P>
   Or do you think that I might be just a shade sensitive on this
particular issue?
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia, who has spent 51 years on this planet as a
``Junior,''is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
