<HEADER>
A6321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN12-COX     03-11 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate's freshman class of '99
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ One is an insurance defense attorney from
Beaumont. The other helps run a family-owned construction company
in LaPorte, between Houston and Galveston. Both are married with
two children.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two men _ Democrat David Bernsen and Republican
Mike Jackson _ make up the smallest freshman class in the Texas
Senate for as long as anyone can remember.
</P>
<P>
   Bernsen, 48, is the only actual newcomer to the Texas
Legislature. Jackson, 45, served in the Texas House for a decade
before his promotion to the Senate in last year's election.
</P>
<P>
   But Bernsen is no stranger to politics or state office. He got
involved in his first statewide race in 1978, helping the late
former House Speaker Price Daniel Jr. in his losing try for the
Democratic nomination for attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Bernsen's political work in Southeast Texas for some top
statewide Democrats, including former Gov. Ann Richards, was one
reason she appointed him to the Texas Highway Commission in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Bernsen got to the Senate by defeating incumbent Republican
Michael Galloway of The Woodlands, with 55 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bernsen, who attended Lamar University in Beaumont on a baseball
scholarship and got his law degree from St. Mary's University in
San Antonio, said the learning curve in the Senate is not a curve
at all, but ``straight up.'' His opposition to school vouchers,
Bernsen said, stiffened when a phone bank operation started
patching through telephone calls from district residents trying to
influence him to change his stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's explained to me how you take money away from public
education and make it better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson quit college in his native Louisiana to join his
father's fledgling industrial construction and maintenance company,
Force Corp., in 1973. After his dad died in 1994, Jackson became
president.
</P>
<P>
   He won his Senate seat almost by default. He took over a solidly
Republican district when the incumbent, Jerry Patterson of
Pasadena, made an unsuccessful run for the GOP nomination for land
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's pet project is legislation to require that when a
convicted sex offender is about to be released, neighbors in the
area where the offender will be moving be notified.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who with Bernsen also represents Galveston Island, said
he will be working with Bernsen and state Rep. Patricia Gray,
D-Galveston, on attempting to rebuild and control beaches
threatened by erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing our beaches at an alarming rate,'' Jackson said.
He hopes to get help from the federal government and the state land
office.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also is exploring establishing a regional port authority
to help the four ports in his district _ Freeport, Galveston, Texas
City and the Port of Houston _ cooperate more closely.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who overlapped in the House for one term with Lt. Gov.
Rick Perry, said he misses the easier camaraderie of the House but
has found veteran senators welcoming and helpful. The fact he
represents five times as many people, has a veto on gubernatorial
appointments in his district and is one of just 31 rather than of
150, has raised his profile with lobbyists and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a whole lot more new best friends than I had in the
House,'' he said. ``David Bernsen and I get along great, and I
think that he's going to be great in the Texas Senate,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
