<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This mama wishes Monica Lewinsky some nurturing, self-worth and
self-confidence
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Newspaper columns represent many points of
view. Whether written to disperse information, to dispel
information or to persuade, they all have a point of view. My point
of view has been and always will be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Mama's.
</P>
<P>
   Of my many roles: wife, daughter, sister, aunt, ``mama'' is the
one that will have the most far-reaching influence. Some may argue
that ``wife'' should be primary and they are right. But consider
that my husband's views, morals and personality were shaped long
before I met him. He never depended on me for food, shelter or
clothing. Our children depended on us both to meet those needs. And
it is he and I who will havehad the greatest role in shaping our
children's views, morals and personality. What we do and have done
to and for them will influence this world for many generations.
</P>
<P>
   Mama is not the same as ``mother.'' Mother can be strictly a
biological function. Mom is a nickname. Mama means someone who is
always there. Your No. 1 fan. Your biggest defender. The one who
loves you no matter what you do but the first one to cut the switch
when it is needed. ``Mama'' doesn't always have to be blood kin,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Today, this mama is sad.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I watched Monica on television last week.
</P>
<P>
   What a pitiful sight. She has the shape and the polish of a
woman, but she is a girl. Though she seemed not to lack for
material things throughout her life, she definitely missed out on
some intangibles. Nurturing. Self-image. Self-confidence.
Self-worth.
</P>
<P>
   When she grows up, she could be a fine adult but anyone,
especially a mama, knows that might never happen. Most kids make
mistakes, get past them, then make more, sometimes even the same
ones. Their families love them through it all. Then they generally
turn out OK. They do all this in relative anonymity. But this girl
fell onto the front page, in front of the TV cameras and smack dab
in the middle of the United States Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Will she survive?
</P>
<P>
   I hope so, but her mama, and the rest of her family, have much
nurturing to do so that she might gain self-image, self-confidence
and self-worth.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing.
</P>
<P>
   After generations of patting men on the back who abandoned their
mates of many years for younger trophy wives and merely tsk-tsking
when others chose to have extramarital affairs, why were we so
shocked when our president entered that arena?
</P>
<P>
   After all, the guy didn't come here from Mars. He grew up right
here in our midst, in our country, in our culture.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal. E-mail: awalker(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
