<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSTARICA-CATERPILLAR     03-11 1897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTARICA-CATERPILLAR12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Answering the crawl in Costa Rica
 &HT;    By Holly Hepp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ People are pretty jealous when I tell them I've
recently returned from a trip to Costa Rica. They immediately ask,
``Did you go to the beach?'' ``Did you stay at a resort?'' ``Did
you scuba dive?''
</P>
<P>
   I have to be honest and answer, ``No, I collected caterpillar
poop.''
</P>
<P>
   When their faces crinkle up in disgust, I add: ``And I can't
wait to go back!''
</P>
<P>
   While it may seem like a strange way to spend one's vacation, I
really did venture into the forests of Costa Rica this summer _
picking up the poop of exotic caterpillars, in the name of science,
for three weeks as part of an Earthwatch ``research'' trip. It was
one of the most exciting journeys I've ever taken.
</P>
<P>
   No, I'm not an entomologist. I took my last biology course
somewhere around the ninth grade _ and all I remember is the vats
of frogs in formaldehyde. I am, however, an amateur naturalist. I
love to hike Austin's nature trails with my binoculars. I've spent
hours poring over wildlife magazines and watching nature videos on
television. I'm deeply interested in ecology and conservation.
</P>
<P>
   When I sought out the perfect vacation, I not only wanted to
venture into a forest, I wanted to make some small difference in
preserving it. I also wanted a trip that was inexpensive. And safe
for a woman traveling alone. And populated with interesting people
who that could snatch me from a jaguar's jaws if need be ...
Luckily I found Earthwatch, an international organization that puts
interested volunteers into scientific research projects.
Participants share among themselves the costs of their food,
housing and transportation. No special skills or education
required. The only problem with Earthwatch is the multitude of
project choices. In my three-week block of time, I could study the
lemurs in Madagascar, the cultural heritage of Easter Island, the
elephants in Botswana or Neanderthal bones in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard choice, but I knew it had to be Costa Rica. I sent
in my money and forms and daydreamed all summer about walking
through the pristine forest.
</P>
<P>
   My friends and co-workers tried to dissuade me, but I laughed
them off _ how difficult could it be? I'm 34 years old and hike
Town Lake every day. With a little extra bug spray and sunscreen,
I'd be fine. To the forest!
</P>
<P>
   In the airplane, flying into the capital, San Jose(accent), I
had my first pangs of doubt. The clouds parted for a moment, and
when I looked out there was nothing but uninterrupted forest as far
as the eye could see.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God,'' I thought, ``I'm flying into the jungle!'' I knew
there was no way out then.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting up with the Earthwatch group, we set out in a
small bus for the Guanacaste Conservation Area in what was formerly
called Santa Rosa Park.
</P>
<P>
   Through the windows of the small bus, I watched the forest get
thicker and thicker. Coatis _ raccoon-like mammals with brown and
white fur _ ran across the road, holding their absurd striped tails
in the air. Rain came down in thundering torrents. We were all
relieved to finally reach the field station and move into our
dormitories. When I looked down at the other women laughing and
putting up mosquito netting, I felt like I was 9 years old and back
at sleep-away camp. There were 13 people on the team, and I
couldn't have asked for a greater bunch. They hailed from all over
the globe, and one Japanese woman said that the hardest part of the
whole trip was trying to understand English coming at her in so
many thick accents.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the project was Dr. Eric Olson, an enthusiastic
field biologist from Boston who never seemed to tire of sharing his
knowledge of the tropics. The first couple of days, we went on
orientation walks and learned the names and strange habits of the
creatures that buzzed us. Leaf cutter ants marching with their
green sails. Ant acacia trees with their ferocious red soldiers.
Black iguanas, striped iguanas and grasshoppers with green plate
faces. For me, though, the most magical were the night walks.
</P>
<P>
   No fear ... just move among the trees with your headlamp and see
what you can see. Brightly colored birds asleep in a tree. Lizards
asleep on leaves. A bat cave in constant motion. One night we
climbed a steep hill and set up a black light to attract moths. I
expected the usual small, brownish-gray flutterers, but instead
found myself standing in a swirl of infinite variety and color.
Some like little wood chips, some lacy and transparent, some green
like fungus. There was even one that resembled a bird dropping
until it spread its wings.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Olson picked up a sphinx moth with a 4-inch wingspan, and it
twittered its little abdomen nervously. Very gently, he took a twig
and gently poked it into the ``mouth'' of the moth, eventually
drawing out its amazing 6-inch tongue. When he let go, it curled
back like a tape measure and fit snugly into a little pouch beneath
its face.
</P>
<P>
   On our walks I learned that field biology is not just about
using your eyes. Dr. Olson stopped to touch, smell and handle each
insect. He put his ear to trees and once rubbed a soft caterpillar
across his lips. The quest for caterpillar poop
</P>
<P>
   By the third day, we had a good feel for the trails and started
collecting data. Dr. Olson's research consisted of examining the
detailed connections between tropical trees, the herbivorous
insects that are their major enemies and the enemies of the insects
themselves: birds, wasps and spiders.
</P>
<P>
   The Guanacaste Conservation Area is a tropical dry forest that
differs from a rain forest in that it is only wet during the rainy
season. It is similar to North American temperate hardwood forests
in that it has annual cycles of leaf flush and loss. We were there
in the middle of the wet season.
</P>
<P>
   One of our daily activities was to collect caterpillar droppings
(called ``frass'' by entomologists) from plastic sheets placed on
wire pegs throughout the forest. Frass pellets were then dried and
weighed to quantify whole forest herbivore activity.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for us to be excited about a plastic sheet
that was filled with frass. When we came back to the dormitories in
the evening, everyone had a story about the unique poop they had
found that day. Corkscrew and twisted, sculpted and spiral, each
piece was carefully picked up with tweezers while the plump
caterpillars munched overhead. ``Hey,'' we said, toasting ourselves
with plastic cups of rum, ``this is science!''
</P>
<P>
   My favorite activity though, was the beating and pooting.
</P>
<P>
   With my daily research partner, I would set out into the forest
armed with a beating stick, a meter-wide canvas sheet strung tight
on poles, and a glass vial with an attached plastic tube. Through
this tube I would suck _ or ``poot'' _ specimens into the vial.
</P>
<P>
   It's a two-person operation. One of us would whack the
vegetation with the stick and watch the rain of bugs fall onto the
sheet. Meanwhile, the other swished the plastic tube back and forth
like a vacuum cleaner and sucked them up for later identification.
Although we were only supposed to collect ants and spiders, our
whacks would bring down all sorts of strange creatures: dazzling
beetles, stick insects and huge praying mantises that would look up
with a curiously intelligent expression. The hunter and the hunted
</P>
<P>
   This was our research: what was eating what and who was eating
whom. Unfortunately, everything was eating us. Throughout our trip,
I felt like I was walking around with a sign that read ``free
lunch!'' No amount of bug repellent or protective clothing could
stop the feast.
</P>
<P>
   It began with the chiggers, poking their way through boots and
two pairs of socks; they left rings of fire around our ankles. When
there seemed to be no uninflamed skin left, they made their way
upward to the warmer, moister parts of our bodies. Chigger itch was
maddening, but it was reassuring to know that the mitedropped off
after its bite.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with ticks. They latched on to the most private, hidden
folds of the body, and the shrieks coming from the morning showers
let us all know a new one had been discovered.
</P>
<P>
   There were mystery critters, too. A 5-inch centipede that fell
down a shirt and left a white spiral sore. Scorpions that waited at
the bottom of backpacks and stung unwary fingers. Even the
mosquitoes seemed fiercer in the forest, buzzing and biting right
through the bug spray. We scratched and compared our bites in the
evening, but no matter how bad it was, no one wanted to leave. We
all knew this was a once-in-a-lifetime trip in a once-in-a-lifetime
forest.
</P>
<P>
   The insects, biting or not, were just one part of the incredible
diversity of life that we encountered in Guanacaste. In the
morning, as we first entered the forest to start our collections,
everything fled before us. But as we settled down, the animals
slowly returned. Birds of every size and color, skinks (a type of
lizard), agoutis (rabbit-sized nocturnal rodents), deer and, of
course, the innumerable monkeys. I don't know how many hours I sat
on the forest floor and watched the antics of the white-faced
capuchins or listened to the unearthly bellows of the howler
monkeys. I also discovered something else in the forest. Working on
the research or walking down the paths, I felt incredibly,
intensely awake. All of my senses were extremely acute and my mind
felt clear and alert. There seemed to be a sharpness and clarity to
everything I saw and heard. Other members of the team noticed it,
too. It was an incredible, energizing sensation that seemed to grow
as the trip went on.
</P>
<P>
   As well as feeling personally fulfilled, it was gratifying to
know that our basic research was going to further the understanding
of the dry forest and help with its conservation. For example, the
discovery that dry forest organisms may be relying on nearby
montane and rainforest areas as seasonal refuges was part of what
motivated the Costa Rican government and international donors to
pay for the Guanacaste Conservation Area.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Costa Rica has one of the world's best conservation
records; approximately one quarter of the country is under some
form of official protection. Much of this land is in the form of
national parks that, as well as being attractive to tourists,
sponsor research expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   Would I be a part of one of these research expeditions again?
You betcha. I just can't decide whether to study the dancing birds
in the Monteverde cloud forest, the sea turtles on Playa Grande or
the moths in La Selva rainforest. I only hope that it'll be half as
wonderful as the trip I spent in Costa Rica, picking up poop.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Hepp is the director of the Performing Arts School at
Zachary Scott Theatre. She teaches drama to all ages and directs a
popular youth group called the Earth Enforcers. In conjunction with
the school she also writes, directs and produces an original
children's play series called Playspace. As an actress, Holly has
appeared in more than20 local productions and with companies
including ``Shear Madness,'' the Capitol City Mystery Players and
Esther's Travelling Follies. She shares her South Austin home with
her husband and 16 exotic animals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
