<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, March 12,
1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-PARENTS _ The Rev. Chuck Meyer, vice president of
operations at St. David's and author of the Lucas Holt mystery
series set in Austin, has written a book of letters to his teen-age
daughter that focusses on the issues that come up between teens and
parents. We talk to teen and dad about the project. (Morris, Austin
American-Statesman). 22. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-TRAVEL 0312: I'm going to tell you my picks for the most
romantic cities in Europe. But before I do that, allow me to give
those of you contemplating a honeymoon a few pieces of advice:
First, stay in one place in Europe. Don't go driving all over the
continent in an effort to see everything. You'll just get tired and
cranky. Stay in one city, and it will become ``your'' city, the one
that will be foremost in your photo album. (Blackerby, Palm Beach
Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LIABILITY -- Issues of hotel liability may come as unwelcome
news to travelers. (Wade, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL BRIEFS _ A New York tour operator and airline-ticket
consolidator has opened a Web site to accept bids on domestic and
overseas tickets, and the owner says that no bid _ not even $1 _ is
too small to start. (Staff, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-VIENNA _ What a wedding cake of a city this is. Whether
it's the soaring 450-foot Gothic spire of Stephansdom cathedral or
row upon row of intricately ornate Baroque facades or the massive
overindulgent opulence of Schonbrunn Palace, this is a city that
looks like it was decked out by a cake decorator on a binge.
(Smith, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, MARCH 14.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-VENICE _ Riding the godolas _ everything you imagined and
more. (Crenshaw, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, MARCH 14.
</P>
<P>
   ROMANTIC-EUROPE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I'm going to tell you
my picks for the two most romantic cities in Europe. But before I
do that, allow me to give those of you contemplating a honeymoon a
few pieces of advice: First, stay put! Don't go driving all over
the continent in an effort to see everything. You'll just get tired
and cranky. Second: Go in spring or fall, even winter, but not
summer. Europe is too crowded, hot and expensive in summer, and
this tends to make people tired and cranky. And, I thought of a
third point: Don't worry about spending money. Budget enough for
the trip so that you're not fretting about every franc you're
spending on taxis and food. The wedding trip is not the time to
worry about money _ there's plenty of time for that later in the
marriage. And my No. 1 personal favorite city for romance?
.(Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   CRUISES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There are huge differences
between cruise lines and ships. Your choice will determine whether
you have a wonderful or disappointing cruise vacation. Which ship
is for you? With more than 24 cruise lines and more than 120 ships
serving North America, the choices are overwhelming. But never
fear. It is, in fact, easy to choose the right ship. We will help
guide you to the right ship. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ The AJC Travel ``Getaway'' feature is not available
this week.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-CENTERPIECE
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-PARIS _ PARIS _ A report from the Sonya Rykiel show.
(Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-BRAS _ What you wear underneath your outfit can make or
break the look. We pair four of the top styles this spring (sweater
sets, sphaghetti-strap outfits, halter-top dresses, tops) with the
bras that fit them best. Sidebar on shopping for a bra. (AHill,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 14.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-MAKEOVER _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ This is one of those
times when math is fun. From 211 pounds to 136. From size 18 to
size 8. After trying and failing with numerous diets, Jodie Conrad
moved from New York to Wellington, Fla. in 1996 and decided to make
a few ``lifestyle changes.'' She left a stressful job in retail
management. She joined Weight Watchers _ for the third time _ and
started walking every day. In a year and a half, she lost 75
pounds. And then the folks at Salon Margrit in Palm Beach took
over. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED MONDAY, MARCH 9.
</P>
<P>
   AGING-MODELS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The story goes like this:
Aging former model lives in Paris, making movies. Husband dies.
Seeking a change of scenery and the means to raise her daughter,
she moves to California, where she learns her European acting means
squat. Too old for modeling (so they said), she takes a job as a
receptionist in a tiny ad agency. She discovers that a coyote in
one photo shoot is making more than she earns in a month. That's
it, she decides. Grabs Rolodex. Visits cosmetics companies. Tries
to point out the potential of the aging Baby Boomer market. Doors
slam. Keeps trying. Starts a modeling agency for older models,
including herself. Gets picked by Clairol as a spokesperson. Then
Estee Lauder. Then L'Oreal. Then she writes a book. This is the
true story of Dayle Haddon. An interview. (Anna, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN 03011-- A teen takeover at the box office is
undeniable, with a flood of flicks targeting a younger, hipper,
smarter generation of movie lovers. (Vejnoska, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 3 color photographs taken from
films featuring young stars.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN -- A 2 column graphic ``Countdown to
`Star Wars''' outlining the number of days remaining until ``The
Phantom Menace'' opens.
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE -- People, ``the mother of all human interest
magazines,'' is celebrating its 25th anniversary by taking over the
world, or at least the newsstand. The celebrity-studded weekly,
which in 1974 invented ``personality journalism'' and changed the
definition of news, is the most lucrative weekly in the country,
earning, it says, even more than big brother Time. (Emerson,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS -- In Vincent Ward's maudlin melodrama ``What
Dreams May Come.'' Robin Williams plays a newly dead fellow who
finds himself in a lush afterlife resembling his wife's (Annabella
Sciorra) mock-Romantic paintings. His guide is Cuba Gooding Jr.,
who tries to keep Williams from venturing to hell when he learns
Sciorra has ended up there, a suicide. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) With 3 column color studio photograph from
the film.
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ What's Wilco without its twang? Maybe the finest
subversive pop act working the land right now. If the Midwestern
quartet, fronted by former Uncle Tupelo vocalist Jeff Tweedy, once
came across as fun but disposable, the band's steady artistic
growth now ensures that it's indispensable. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERACTIVE _ AUSTIN _ advancing the SXSW Interactive Festival,
which kicks off Saturday, March 13. Festival has found its niche
and focus _ it no longer is all over the map trying to cover video,
etc. The focus has been narrowed to just computers.w/sked of
highlights. (Kallenberg, Austin American-Statesman). 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   FERRIS-HUMANITIES _ Interview with William Ferris, Southern
folklorist appointed last year to head National Endowment for the
Humanities, who will be featured speaker Saturday, March 13 at the
25th anniversary day-long celebration at the University of Texas
for Texas Council of the Humanities. He will talk about his
experiences as a non-bureaucrat (he's an Elvis scholar among other
things) heading a Washington bureaucracy and address the
controversies of public funding as a political minefield. (McLeese,
Austin American-Statesman). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS/REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-LOCK _ Review of ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels,''
a twisty story about young English guys stuck with a gambling debt
and being chased by the mob. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   TRAILER-STARWARS _ A short on the new ``Star Wars: Phantom
Menace'' trailer hits movie theaters today, paired with fellow 20th
Century Fox release ``Wing Commander.'' (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-FANS _ Feature on Star Wars nuts who are anxiously
awaiting the release of the new movie. (Houck, Palm Beach Post).
40.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-WEB _ List of Star Wars Web sites. (Houck, Palm Beach
Post). 10.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-CORRUPTOR _ Review of ``The Corruptor.'' Grade: B-.
(StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-ROUNDUP _ Short review roundup of ``Wing Commander''
(Screens tuesday; Longino), ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' (Screens
tuesday; Vejnoska), ``The Rage: Carrie 2'' (Grade: D; St.Murray)
and ``Baby Geniuses'' (Grade: D+; Longino). (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-COMMANDER _ Review of ``Wing Commander.'' Based on the
popular video game, this film takes place in the year 2564, and the
battle is Earthlings vs. aliens. A product of Chris Roberts and
Austin's Digital Anvil. Stars Freddie Prinze Jr. and Matthew
Lillard. (Stuever, Austin American-Statesman). 15.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WING _ We sit down with Chris Roberts, the founder of Austin's
Digital Anvil, and are one of the first to see his new movie ``Wing
Commander''. Use screening as jumping off point for a story on
Roberts and his Austin company. While the movie supposed to not be
that good, the effects are expected to be tremendous. If so, this
could give Austin its first big effects house and add another
component to our city becoming the film city we claim to be. The
story would also touch on who Roberts is and why he is so gung ho
on making us a film town and how he intends achieve this arduous
task. (Kallenberg, Austin American-Statesman). 45. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   JACKHILL _ Interview with B-movie maestro Jack Hill, who's
getting the retrospective treatment from this year's SXSW Film
Festival. The Hill tribute is being hosted by Quentin Tarantino
(we're seeking a quote from QT re Hill) and will include such
titles as ``Switchblade Sisters'' and ``Swinging Cheerleaders,'' as
well as the blaxploitation classics ``Foxy Brown'' and ``Coffy.''
(Garcia, Austin American-Statesman). 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   TAYLOR _ Brief interview with Lili Taylor, star of the
Austin-shot ``A Slipping-Down Life,'' which screens Saturday at
SXSW. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman). 12-15.
</P>
<P>
   CAPSULE-REVIEWS _ Capsule review, tentative list: ``The Life and
Times of Hank Greenberg,'' ``Hill Stomp Hollar,'' ``The Perfect
Speciman,'' ``The Living Museum,'' ``The Accident,'' ``Abilene,''
``Fools Gold,'' ``American Chain Gang.'' (Garcia/Macor/Seaborn,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   THEATER NEWS/REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY-NEWSHOWS _ NEW YORK _ Reviews of the hottest new shows
on Broadway, leading off with ``Death of a Salesman'' and followed
by Fosse, Bright Lights/Big City, the Kenny/Phylicia Everybody's
Ruby and a brief recap of Annie/Gun/Bernadette. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 14
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC NEWS/REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   RENEEFLEMING _ Renee Fleming interview to advance for Spivey
Hall recital. Fleming is one of the hottest up-and-coming opera
singers we have these days. Story talks to her, and will include
other voices, as well. (Green, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CELLIST-HARRELL _ A visit with Lynn Harrell, the cellist for
this week's ASO concerts (more Rozsa). He had carpal tunnel surgery
last summer and had to take a six-month leave from playing. He also
had a good relationship with Robert Shaw. (Green, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMBERMUSIC _ Overview for a really interesting week in music
in Atlanta, which bounces between classical crossover, rock/pop and
improvisation. Shows are: Thamyris NextFest (at) Emory w/''The Mad
King'' (opera thing, I'll get more info) on 3/15; and NY's Bang On
a Can All-Stars doing Brian Eno's ``Music for Airports'' 3/20;
British guitar genius Derek Bailey, who's influenced everybody,
making a very rare US appearance 3/18 or 3/19 at the Existential
Church in Candler Park; and the Hilliard Ensemble (vocal chamber
outfit; pretty major in classical world). The idea is that it's one
of those unusual weeks in Atlanta when all this cool stuff
collides, and that it all says interesting things about music at
the end of the century, and that, though it's all ostensibly
high-brow a lot of it is wildly unconventional. (Dollar, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 14
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET _ BOOKS 0312: In ``Visions of Technology,'' Richard
Rhodes has compiled an anthology of more than 200 selections
tracing the development of technology through the 20th century. It
begins with the birth of radio, movies and airplanes, moves through
the era of television and satellites, and finally to the
development of the Internet and artificial intelligence as the
century closes. (Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW -- There is a point in some books when satire gives way
to outright meanness. Which means readers will recognize that ``Me:
By Jimmy (Big Boy) Valente,'' Garrison Keillor's supposed ``just
having a little fun'' mock-book about Jesse Ventura, the
pro-wrestler-turned-governor of Keillor's beloved home state of
Minnesota, is, frankly, nasty. (Guinn, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW -- You read a novel like ``Dreamland'' because you want
to get lost in the past. And where better to get lost than New York
City in 1910, with its millionaires and SKUBE ON BOOKS -- Who isn't
impressed by a two-ton sentence? You wouldn't want to diagram it,
and you certainly couldn't sing it. Either would ruin it. You only
behold its profundity, whatever its meaning. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The Skube column and reviews of 'Visions of Technology''
and ``Dreamland'' are available on the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's weekly Books page, which will be posted in
the Lifestyle folder on the Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SKUBE _ No one spins a sentence in postmodern criticism
like Judith Butler. A Judith Butler sentence is a timber truck
loaded with redwood. It is not for nothing that Butler, who teaches
philosophy at the University of California at Berkeley, is the
reigning Bad Writer of the year. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 14
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-VISIONS _ Review of Richard Rhodes' ``Visions of
Technology.'' (Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 14
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-DREAMLAND _ Review of Kevin Baker's ``Dreamland.''
(Drennen, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 14
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GODWIN _ When Gail Godwin was growing up in Asheville,
N.C., in a manless house, she had a choice between the stove and
the typewriter. Her grandmother aligned herself with the stove
while her mother pounded out newspaper articles and pulp romance
magazine stories on the typewriter. Godwin chose the more romantic
appliance. Some nine novels later, Godwin talks about the writing
life and the importance of faith and spirituality in her latest
book, ``Evensong,'' a sequel to ``Father Melancholy's Daughter.''
(O'Briant, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 14
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-EVENSONG _ Review of Gail Godwin's ``Evensong.''
(Friedman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for use by
NYT clients). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 14
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of new books by John LeCarre,
Ruth Rendell and Robert Parker. (O'Briant, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 14
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Shelley Fraser Mickle insists she simply writes
about ordinary people. She does, but she writes about them in an
extraordinary way. ``Real life is not necessarily great dramatic
happenings,'' she says. ``Life is lived in very quiet experiences
that are very important.'' We talk to the Florida author about her
novel, ``Replacing Dad,'' which will be aired as a CBS movie Sunday
night. Also in notes: Once again Robin Cook has tapped into the
headlines with ``Vector,'' a novel about anthrax and bio-terrorism;
and the literary magazine Brightleaf publishes a tribute issue to
Eudora Welty. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ONBOOKS (15 inches) _ Scott Eyman's books column. (Eyman,
Palm Beach Post). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-FAWCETT _ Review of `Embassy Row,' by Quinn Fawcett.
(Eyman, Palm Beach Post). 20.
</P>
