<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOOTH ABOUT IPANA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Sometime in the '40s when I was in the service, Ipana
toothpaste was taken out of stores. I have not seen it on the
market again. What happened to it?
</P>
<P>
   _ W.A.P., Grandview, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Ipana toothpaste has disappeared from the United States but
is being sold in Turkey, according to a Jan. 14 Christian Science
Monitor article.
</P>
<P>
   Ipana was the most popular U.S. toothpaste or powder from 1936
to 1945, but was abandoned by manufacturer Bristol-Meyers in 1968.
The brand was sold to new owners and revived twice, with limited
success.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble and a Turkish company restarted the brand in
1991 in a joint venture. ``Ipana is now a leading toothpaste in
Turkey,'' the Monitor reported.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to F. Lee Bailey?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.P., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to the defense attorney at 1400 Centerpark Blvd., Suite
909, West Palm Beach, FL 33401.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, whose past clients include O.J. Simpson and Patricia
Hearst, made the news recently when he was subpoenaed by Cleveland
prosecutors to produce any records he has pertaining to the late
Dr. Sam Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard was charged with the 1954 murder of his wife in a case
that inspired the ``Fugitive'' TV series and films. Bailey handled
the appeal that resulted in Sheppard's 1966 release.
</P>
<P>
   He has served as chairman of penal reform for the Association of
Trial Lawyers and co-chairman of the Foundation for the Advancement
of Inmate Rehabilitation and Recreation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a longtime fan of Tom K. Ryan, the creator of the
Tumbleweeds comic strip. Can you tell me where to write to him?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.M., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: You can contact Ryan at Box 446, Deerfield, FL 33443, or
through his Tumbleweeds World Wide Web site at www.tumbleweeds.com.
</P>
<P>
   Tumbleweeds, which appears in about 200 newspapers, was created
by Ryan in 1965. The 72-year-old cartoonist continues to produce it
from his Florida home.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan also sells autographed copies of his latest book,
``Presenting the Best of Tumbleweeds,'' for $15.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
