<HEADER>
A6390 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     03-11 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNERLY PUTS BUSH ON THE AFFIRMATIVE ACTION SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having received a chilly reception from Florida Gov. Jeb Bush a
few weeks ago, Ward Connerly has brought his anti-affirmative
action medicine show to George W. Bush's range.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, the African-American member of the University of
California board of regents who spearheaded the successful
referendum that terminated affirmative action in that state, came
to Austin to show support for proposed legislation that would
outlaw it in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He stood shoulder to shoulder with state Rep. Robert Talton,
R-Pasadena, who filed the bill, which is modeled after California'
Proposition 209 and Washington state's Initiative 200. Talton's
bill would prohibit state agencies from using affirmative action to
overcome the effects of past or continuing discrimination based on
race, color, gender, ethnicity or national origin.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is not the way Talton put it. He spoke of
prohibiting preferential treatment, the way affirmative action foes
always do to distort the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the economic pie becomes available to all people ... not
just one small sliver arbitrarily set aside by those in the
feel-good business,'' Talton said.
</P>
<P>
   And Connerly said, Amen.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be judged on the basis of their talents and
capabilities and not on their skin color, religion, national origin
or gender,'' Talton said.
</P>
<P>
   And Connerly said, Amen.
</P>
<P>
   Actually Connerly didn't say the word ``Amen.'' But that was the
gist of his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   What he actually said was:
</P>
<P>
   ``If this nation is ever going to live out its creed of equal
protection under the law, equal treatment for all people, it all
begins with the government treating everybody as equals.''
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that preferential treatment isn't the answer to
disparity of opportunity, Connerly declared: ``There is nothing
affirmative about treating people differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Give that man a Kewpie doll. He is absolutely right about that.
Treating people differently in the workplace and in public
institutions because they are female, because they belong to a
racial or ethnic minority or because of their religions is utterly
negative.
</P>
<P>
   Make that ``reprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   If that kind of negativism no longer happened to an appreciable
degree, there would be no need for affirmative action to give
minorities and women a fighting chance at a small portion of the
pie to which Talton so idiotically referred.
</P>
<P>
   Surely Talton does not really believe that because of
affirmative action, Hispanics, African-Americans and women are
gobbling up most of the Texas economic pie and leaving just a small
sliver for Anglo males.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, that's what he implied. But only an idiot wouldn't know
better. And there are no idiots in the Texas Legislature. Are
there?
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, of course, knows better, or should. He's been black a
long time. If he can't see that this society is a long way from
being colorblind, he must be really blind.
</P>
<P>
   Having brought his crusade to save the white majority from
affirmative action to Texas, Connerly has created a dilemma for the
Texas governor, the Bush who would be president. He may force
George W. to show his true colors on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   That's something that the Texas governor has shown some
reluctance to do because he's courting Hispanic voters. And some of
them think he's for affirmative action and that he might oppose the
bill that Talton is carrying for Connerly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, has insisted that he's for something called
``affirmative access,'' another of those phrases like
``compassionate conservatism'' that Dan Quayle and Lamar Alexander
refer to as ``weasel words.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the unavoidable fact of the matter is that Bush is
going to need the support of the hard conservative right in the
Republican Party to win the nomination, and ``affirmative access''
just might not be strong enough for them.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, George W. Bush's best course may be to give
the California crusader the Jeb Bush treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue won't go away. House Education Chairwoman Irma
Rangel, D-Kingsville, has filed a bill that would have the effect
of reinstating the affirmative action policies of public colleges
and universities that were voided by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals' controversial Hopwood ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush who would be president may wind up having to sign or
veto one or the other. And the whole nation will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1233EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6391 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     03-11 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERMINATED WORKERS ADVISED TO TAKE CHARGE, NEGOTIATE BETTER
SETTLEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you just got your pink slip or see it coming, don't despair _
get a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least get your hands on a copy of ``Getting Fired: What to
do if you're fired, downsized, laid off, restructured, discharged,
terminated, or forced to resign'' (Warner Books, 370 pages, $24).
</P>
<P>
   The book was written by Steven Mitchell Sack, a labor and
employment lawyer who has represented more than 12,000 fired
workers in his near 20 years of experience. He has also written
eight other popular books, including ``The Employee Rights
Handbook.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million workers are fired annually, Sack writes.
Hence the need for a book focused squarely on the rights of those
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to get past the emotion of being on the hit
list, and recognize that you often have a negotiating standpoint,
Sack says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are so disillusioned and shell-shocked after
receiving the news that they merely bow their heads and shuffle
their feet out the door,'' Sack writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, by questioning the firing and demanding more
benefits, or be anticipating a layoff and acting properly, you can
gain enhanced financial benefits and the confidence to look for and
find a new job.''
</P>
<P>
   Sack says that no matter what type of industry, no matter how
much you make and no matter what level of job you hold, you can
often reach a more amicable settlement than just clearing out your
desk and walking away from your employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, I have become convinced that the vast majority
of private employers fear the repercussions of most firings and are
willing to explore amicable solutions to avoid additional legal
expenses, bad publicity, and potential damages that sometimes
arise,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, employees lose millions of dollars each year
by taking too long or not trying at all to take action against
their firing, Sack writes.
</P>
<P>
   The book provides numerous strategies to follow based on court
rulings, regulations and labor law. Chapters including firing based
on gender, age, race, religion or handicap; and chapters on firing
to deprive workers of benefits or because of some action by the
employee, such as being a whistle-blower or having an office
romance.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the book discusses how to negotiate the best
severance package after you have been fired. The third section
talks about how to fight back using litigation or a related
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The book is peppered with interesting vignettes to illustrate
Sack's points. Also, Sack turns a great deal of legal material into
plain English that is easy to understand.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting trends to which Sack refers is
corporate America's firing of older workers instead of younger ones
to cut costs without cutting as many jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because younger workers were typically at the low end of the
wage scale, companies learned they would have to make substantial
cuts to achieve meaningful savings,'' he writes. ``They realized it
was more effective to offer early retirement and severance packages
to older workers at the top of the wage scale as the way to reduce
costs and stay competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two decades, employees have gained many more rights
through changes in law, Sack writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until twenty years ago, employees had few options when they
received a pink slip ... because of a legal principle called the
employment-at-will doctrine,'' Sack writes.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal laws have since been passed to protect
occupational health and safety, civil rights, freedom to complain
about unsafe working conditions and other related areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The net effect has been a gradual erosion of the
employment-at-will doctrine in many areas,'' Sack writes.
</P>
<P>
   Some states let fired workers sue in tort, as opposed to claims
based on a contract, and recover punitive damages for pain and
suffering brought on by the firing.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line, there's more to firing than just the pink slip. And
Sack's book may provide you with enough information to leave that
company with more dignity, and more money.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   ``Year 2000 Solutions for Dummies''
</P>
<P>
   By K.C. Bourne
</P>
<P>
   IDG Books, $29.99
</P>
<P>
   At least one software maker estimates that 5 percent of all U.S.
businesses will fail because of not fixing their Y2K problem in
time. A computer consultant estimates that 95 percent of all PCs
will fail a simple Year 2000 test. Author K.C. Bourne, a software
developer and consultant for more than 20 years, writes a thorough
and detailed discussion of how to fix the problem _ whether it's
your personal computer at home or a large business computer
network.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Harvard Entrepreneurs Club Guide to Starting Your Own
Business''
</P>
<P>
   By Poonam Sharma
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   This book focuses specifically on entrepreneurs or wannabes in
college now or those who have recently graduated. It provides an
overall business primer and shows how to combine your college
education with a business plan. As the authors are quick to point
out, Bill Gates left college to start his own company. At the very
least, the ambitious should be able to start their company while in
school or just out of it. The several authors of this book, all at
Harvard, write chapters on finance, legal protection, marketing,
ethics and other related topics.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Eating the Big Fish: How Challenger Brands Can Compete Against
Brand Leaders''
</P>
<P>
   By Adam Morgan
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   Many books are devoted to the No. 1 brand in any given category
of goods or services as a way to teach how to boost your own
brands. This book takes a slightly lower look, focusing on the No.
2 slot, the so-called challenger brand. After all, says Adam
Morgan, a planning director at one of the world's largest
advertising agencies, No. 1 is more the exception to the rule, and
all the brands under it are more the norm. This is a detailed and
interesting book on the amazing world of brand marketing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
