A6392 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-THECORRUPTOR-TEX     03-11 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THECORRUPTOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CORRUPTOR' A LITTLE TOO FAMILIAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even the name of the new action thriller, ``The Corruptor,''
sounds anemic. This story of cops who initially can't stand each
other when forced together and who learn to trust each other brings
together Chow Yun-Fat, the elegant Hong Kong movie icon, and Mark
Wahlberg, who did a credible job in last year's ``The Big Hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahlberg moves well, though his speaking voice makes him sound
like he's at least one latte short of being awake. He's the new kid
on the block, a novice detective who has been thrown into an
all-Asian task force. They couldn't be less happy with this white
addition. (Chow makes another obvious color joke _ he calls
Wahlberg ``green,'' because of the kid's inexperience. Of course,
after his career as an off-white hip-hop performer, Wahlberg should
be used to having his chops busted for being the token Caucasian.)
</P>
<P>
   They swing through the impenetrable crime world of Chinatown,
where Tong bosses have become skilled in playing both sides against
the middle. Chow has starred in roughly 70 films, and in what seems
like about 50 of them, he's played this exact same role: a
tough-as-nails rogue cop trying to winnow away mob influence on the
police force. In ``Corruptor,'' he is one of the cops who does
business with the mob.
</P>
<P>
   Revving up his trademark snarl and throwing his arms out with a
flourish, Chow steps from one side of the street to another, both
sides of which are in the dark. And when Wahlberg is targeted by
the mob bosses who want another cop in their pockets, Chow no
longer seems so alone.
</P>
<P>
   Except Wahlberg turns out to be an Internal Affairs operative
who's been sent to investigate Chow. This is supposed to add
another layer of complication to the story, which it does on the
most superficial level. Director James Foley gives some competence
to the routine proceedings, which are so shopworn that you'd swear
that Kim Chan, the actor who plays Tong kingpin Uncle Benny, has
not only played such a character before; he's actually played one
called Uncle Benny before. One car chase sequence that takes place
in downtown Manhattan is the best thing in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   But this kind of
guns-flying-and-glass-splintering-in-slow-motion is not Foley's
metier _ his previous work includes directing Wahlberg in the
potboiler ``Fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley also handled David Mamet's fragrant stew of a movie,
``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' where the real violence came from the
language. This kind of urban assault vehicle requires a devotion to
a craft he's indifferent to. Fans of the genre will dismiss it.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Mark Wahlberg will get the requisite thrill from his
dramatic display of pecs and tush. And fans of Chow Yun-Fat will
wonder if he'll ever get to star in an American picture that takes
advantage of his unique gifts in the action genre. Sure, you grade
those Hong Kong pictures in which he stars on a curve, because
they're outlandishly plotted. But they're full of snap and
wildness. In this area, that's a plus.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Corruptor''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: James Foley
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Chow Yun-Fat, Mark Wahlberg
</P>
<P>
   Length: 110 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence, nudity, adult content and language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
