<SLUG> BC-COYOTE-HUNTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVISTS BLAST LONGER COYOTE HUNTING SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Since the cartoon career of Wile E. Coyote and
his disaster-ridden pursuit of Road Runner, the lowly scavenger has
been the Rodney Dangerfield of the wild. Now the coyote isn't even
getting respect from the New York Department of Environmental
Conservation, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the agency is planning to extend by about month the
already lengthy hunting season on the reviled omnivore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is growing interest in coyote hunting in New York state
and we think we can provide some additional recreational hunting
with no danger whatsoever to the coyote population, which is
expanding,'' said Gerry Barnhart, director of wildlife and marine
resources. Barnhart said the proposed extension would standardize
the coyote hunting season throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   The season in the northern zone _ which includes the
Adirondacks, the St. Lawrence valley and the Lake Champlain valley
_ now begins the next to last Saturday and October and ends the
last Sunday in March.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern zone, which encompasses the rest of the state,
the season opens the last Saturday in October and closes the third
Sunday in March. The Department of Environmental Conservation
proposes a standard hunting season running from Oct. 1 to the last
Sunday in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``It provides an opportunity for some regulatory
simplification,'' Barnhart said. Barnhart said that with as many as
18,000 coyotes roaming every region of the state except Long Island
_ a pair was found in New York City a few years ago _ there's
hardly any risk of extinction. And with an animal that lacks the
cuddly qualities of, say, Bambi, and whose shyness is often
mistaken for treachery, no one would be likely to howl about an
extension in the hunting season _ or so it would seem.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fund for Animals is up in arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's purely recreational,'' Marion Stark of Albany, an
activist with the group, said of the proposed extension of coyote
hunting season. ``There is no biologically valid reason to kill
coyotes ... They (state regulators) are catering to the whim of
hunters.''
</P>
<P>
   Stark said the animals perform a useful function, eating rodents
and carrion (dead animals) and serving as ``sanitation workers of
the wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, she said that killing coyotes will, in the long
run, only result in more breeding; coyotes self-manage their
numbers by practicing a form of birth control when the population
gets too dense. ``The female will stop reproducing,'' Stark said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fund for Animals is attempting to fight the proposed hunting
extension. It is issuing press releases, encouraging constituents
to write to their representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Hope Ryden, author of 23 books on North American wildlife _
including one titled ``God's Dog'' in which she chronicles the
seven weeks she spent living near a den of coyotes to observe their
behavior _ has also joined the crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, coyotes have been scapegoated, but they are a
valuable part of our natural world,'' Stark said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
