<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVERSE-DIET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERSITY LEADS TO A HEALTHFUL DIET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phytochemicals. It's the latest buzzword in nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   To put it simply, phytochemicals are chemicals found in plants
that are suspected to have beneficial health effects. Some, such as
linoleic acid (pumpkins, melon, walnuts) are believed to block
biological processes that lead to cancer and prevent
arteriosclerosis. Others, like capsaicin (cayenne, chili, Tabasco,
bell peppers), may act as a pain reliever.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing new here is the terminology. The American Cancer
Society has been advocating a diet rich in fruits and vegetables
for years to help stave off certain cancers. Perhaps the biggest
news to come out is that the health benefits from phytochemicals
cannot be obtained from a pill.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement from the American Dietetic Association,
``the beneficial effects associated with a diet high in fruits and
vegetables may not be demonstrated when individual nutrients such
as vitamins E and C or beta carotene (which are also
phytochemicals) are consumed in supplement form.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem with phytochemicals becoming a food fad is that
information about how much of each chemical people need for optimal
health has yet to be determined, according to the American Council
on Science and Health. In addition, says the Agricultural Research
Service of the U.S. Department of Agriculture, scientists can't say
which phytochemicals are important; they probably work together.
</P>
<P>
   Though some plant products contain more phytochemicals than
others, health specialists say the best way to receive the likely
benefits of phytochemicals is to eat a large variety of fruits,
vegetables, whole grains, legumes and soy products. Here are a few
suggestions for adding more of these to your diet:
</P>
<P>
   _ Drink green tea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try tofu and tempeh. Soy products have image problems but
they're surprisingly easy to use and tasty.
</P>
<P>
   _ Substitute sorbet or juice bars for ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   _ Include red, green, orange and yellow fruits and vegetables in
your diet each day to ensure you are getting variety.
</P>
<P>
   _ Choose breads, cereals and pastas labeled ``whole-grain'' or
``whole-wheat.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Make plant-based foods the mainstay of your meals. Use meat as
a condiment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
