<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO BRING A PEACH TO RIPE PERFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISA STEVENS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question: I bought peaches at the supermarket because they were
a really good deal, or so I thought. They were as hard as rocks.
How can I get them ripe?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Ethylene gas speeds up the ripening process, so here's
what to do. Place the fruit in a paper bag with something that
gives off ethylene, such as an apple, and keep it at room
temperature for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are the pop-up temperature indicators on turkeys and chickens
reliable?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bessie Berry of the U.S. Department of Agriculture says the
pop-ups found in chickens and turkeys are reliable indicators that
the poultry is cooked to safe temperatures. She recommends,
however, to double check with a meat thermometer, just to be on the
safe side.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is dietary fiber and where is it found?
</P>
<P>
   A: Dietary fiber is made up of parts of plants the body cannot
digest, explains the National Barley Food Council. Foods rich in
dietary fiber include barley, dry beans, legumes, nuts, seeds,
fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tufts University Guide to Total Nutrition'' explains that
fiber does not have a nutritive value, but it is very useful in
digestion and is credited with helping lower cholesterol and cancer
rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6431 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DEEPEND-TEX     03-11 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DEEPEND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEEP END' SINKS UNDER ITS OWN EMOTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Beth Cappadora, Michelle Pfeiffer gets to suffer glamorously
in ``The Deep End of the Ocean.'' After she leaves her 3-year-old
boy, Ben, alone with Vincent, his 7-year-old brother, in a hotel
lobby, and Ben ends up missing, she falls into a puddle of shock.
</P>
<P>
   Not at first, though _ initially, this disorganized photographer
tries to tick off all the places he could be, and as it slowly
occurs to her that he's gone, she drops into a heaving heap. Her
husband, Pat, (Treat Williams) steps in to try to hold the family
together, but his wife devotes herself to trying a find a son who's
probably dead.
</P>
<P>
   It's a horror story from Jacquelyne Mitchard's novel that sends
a tremor of fear through audiences _ what if you were responsible
for your child's disappearance, instead of some leering,
yellow-toothed monster out of an episode of ``Hard Copy''? When,
during an argument, Pat screams, ``Kids don't just vanish up in
smoke,'' you feel her misery.
</P>
<P>
   And what would happen if you got a chance to be reunited with
the disappeared child, but he didn't know who you were? The boy,
now named Sam (Ryan Merriman), stumbles back into her life nine
years later _ he offers to mow her lawn. She pulls herself into
shape, whipping out her camera to get shots and compare them to
computer projections of what the boy might look like now.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has tried to get on with his, or her, life, but a scar
has been cut through this family. It turns out that the boy was
raised by a man (John Kapelos) who didn't know the child was
kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   The Cappadora misery is inflicted on everyone. It's one big,
unhappy family.
</P>
<P>
   The real misery comes in sitting through ``The Deep End of the
Ocean,'' which is all over the place. Michelle Pfeiffer is
undeniably the star, and she gets all of her close-ups. But ``Deep
End'' is also scrupulous in trying to get everybody's feelings into
the picture.
</P>
<P>
   It's so rigidly worked out that it doesn't seem to be about
anything _ it bends over backward in trying to be fair. Lacking a
point of view, the movie is a mawkish mess, a USA cable movie given
the emotional meandering of an Actor's Studio exercise. It's almost
impossible to take seriously, especially Whoopi Goldberg as a
detective who becomes Beth's friend.
</P>
<P>
   Except Pfeiffer has some fine moments, and Jonathan Jackson, as
the teen-age Vincent, has a quicksilver temperament _ his rage and
melancholy keep him at a distance from everyone. It's a stirring
piece of work that's too good for the picture.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Deep End of the Ocean''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Ulu Grosbard
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Michelle Pfeiffer, Treat Williams, Whoopi Goldberg
</P>
<P>
   Length: 148 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ adult language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
