<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET LESSON ON INTERNET'S POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a company gets taken over by another company and Wall
Street likes the deal, that's called a successful takeover. When a
company gets taken over by another company and Wall Street hates
the deal, that's called a ``take-under,'' because the acquisition
causes the acquired company's stock price to plummet.
</P>
<P>
   USA Networks' proposed acquisition of the Internet company Lycos
is a classic example of a ``take-under.'' Since the deal was
announced last month, Lycos's stock has lost one-third of its
value. Wall Street's reaction has been so negative, in fact, that
it now appears that the deal as proposed will collapse.
</P>
<P>
   David Wetherell, Lycos's largest investor, announced on Tuesday
that he was quitting the company's board and had hired the
investment firm of Morgan Stanley to help him line up another
buyer. This news was cheered by investors. Lycos's stock rose
smartly. The hope on Wall Street was that a bidding war for Lycos
would ensue.
</P>
<P>
   On one level that's what this story is about: people haggling
over the price of a stock. But on a more important level, it's
about the future of the Internet. Is the Internet just another
distribution channel? Or is it the mother of all distribution
channels? Is the Internet just another home shopping network? Or
does it touch every aspect of our lives?
</P>
<P>
   On one side are the traditionalists. Traditionalists, truth be
told, don't like the Internet. They don't understand it. Internet
culture makes them uncomfortable. Most traditionalists have missed
the run-up in Internet stocks. And most of them believe, in their
heart of hearts, that the whole Internet ``thing'' is basically a
speculative bubble waiting to burst.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are Internet enthusiasts. They believe that
the Internet is a transforming technology. They believe it is
capable of organic growth. They believe it erases boundaries and
rewrites the rules of business. They're long on Internet stocks.
They've made fortunes investing in the ``thing.'' And they believe
that when all is said and done, the future of commerce, education,
health care, entertainment, financial services, and a hundred other
business categories is on line.
</P>
<P>
   USA Networks' proposed acquisition of Lycos was structured with
traditionalists in mind. The chief executive of USA Networks, Barry
Diller (for whom I once worked briefly as a consultant), promised
investors that if the deal went through, he would deliver $1.2
billion in revenue in the first year. The traditionalists liked the
sound of that. They could imagine that some of that revenue might
become earnings. Traditionalists worship at the altar of earnings.
An Internet offering with real earnings made their hearts flutter.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasts hated the deal, since it narrowed the Lycos
platform. They saw it consigning Lycos to the role of alternate
distribution channel for Diller's Home Shopping Network zirconium.
There wasn't much value in that. That was all about the low end of
the market _ the demographics that least attracted their interest.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasts look at Lycos as a potentially immense platform,
capable of delivering all kinds of goods and services to an
expanding number of customers. For every joint venture that Lycos
enters into there will eventually be revenue. If it offers low-cost
long-distance telephone service in conjunction with a long-distance
reseller, there will be a penny earned on every other minute of
every call. If it offers low rate credit cards, there will be a
dollar earned on every $100 worth of transactions conducted with
that card. If it offers on-line banking services, there will be
fees earned with every new customer.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasts look at Lycos and see a hundred streams of future
revenue combining into a mighty river. They believe that in five
years, high-speed modems will be ubiquitous and that Pentium II
chip computers will retail for less than $400. Once that
infrastructure is in place, the entire world of commerce will
change. Those companies that have real Internet customers, like AOL
and Yahoo and Excite, will command a huge premium for access to
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   And the beauty of it is that Lycos already has those customers _
not in numbers anything like AOL, but in impressive numbers
nonetheless. The larger the number of customers, the larger the
value of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Diller's deal doesn't expand the customer base. It constricts
it. Which is why, in the end, the enthusiasts attacked the deal
with such ferocity. They were determined to win.
</P>
<P>
   Which they have done. The balance of power on Wall Street has
shifted. The enthusiasts have prevailed. On one level the Diller
deal was a miscalculation about price. But on a more important
level, it was emblematic of how the Internet changes perceptions of
value.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
(On Saturday, I wrote that Cambridge and Brookline do not offer
high-speed Internet access. Half-true. Cambridge does; Brookline
doesn't.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
