<HEADER>
A6440 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-DESIRE-BOS &LR;      03-11 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DESIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME FICTION WITH THE STAYING POWER OF ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DESIRE LINES 
By Christina Baker Kline 
Morrow, 343 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bright, popular, pretty Bangor girl disappears mysteriously on
the night of her high school graduation in 1986. Still haunted
powerfully by the incident 10 years later, her closest friend
returns to the Maine town and, at some risk, tries to fill in the
blanks and find her classmate, dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
   Any plot outline of ``Desire Lines'' would leave the impression
that Christina Baker Kline's fine novel, her second, is a work of
crime fiction. But accurate plot summaries offer little more
insight into books than their covers do. ``Desire Lines'' is
considerably more than genre fiction. The main distinctions are its
fuller embrace of the world and the psychological ripeness and
complex indelibility of its central characters _ the searching
Kathryn Campbell and her missing, magnetic friend, Jennifer
Pelletier.
</P>
<P>
   Recently divorced, Kline's protagonist returns reluctantly to
Bangor, dragging a sense of failure, to live with her mother. Kline
captures her melancholy homecoming with the same edgy truth that
makes the ensuing mother-daughter psychological warfare sourly
palpable. Feeding this turmoil and air of defeat is Kathryn's very
dimly understood, but almost overpowering, connection to her
long-lost friend.
</P>
<P>
   Kathyrn's search for the facts about Jennifer, which she digs up
while freelancing a series of stories for the local paper, provides
the skeletal, conventional mystery in ``Desire Lines.'' The feature
stories are to be published in connection with the 10th reunion of
Kathryn's high school class, which is also the anniversary of
Jennifer's disappearance. The sometimes wary interviews with aging,
changing classmates, and the reunion itself, have a bittersweet
``Big Chill'' tang. They also trigger the suspense.
</P>
<P>
   Purely by the standards of good popular mystery fiction,
``Desire Lines'' is fun but undistinguished, the suspense late in
developing and accompanied by some overobvious hints about the
villain of the piece.
</P>
<P>
   But the soul of the novel is the deeper and more engaging
mystery within Kathryn herself. Her unexamined past unnerves and
imprisons her, rendering her churlish and childish. She's obsessed
with her missing friend but unclear about the swirling feelings
aroused by her search _ an inchoate mixture of adolescent idolatry,
love, jealousy, and nagging guilt. As she better understands
herself, Kathryn ``distinctly remembers wishing she could jump
inside Jennifer's skin and inhabit her body, to see the world
through those light-blue eyes.'' And in further probing the truth
about Jennifer and clarifying their relationship, Kathryn emerges
almost as if from underwater, released from a kind of suffocatingly
protracted adolescence. Even her hometown, which originally seems
inhospitably provincial and raw, blushes with color and promise.
</P>
<P>
   We don't expect even the best crime fiction _ whether it's by
Elmore Leonard or Sara Paretsky _ to insinuate itself into mind and
heart or, certainly, to linger there long if it does. If their
narratives move and crackle stylishly as we read them, fine:
Ephemeral exhilaration is what we happily pay for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desire Lines'' has the staying power of art. I hesitate to
call Kline a ``serious novelist'' for fear of obscuring her easy
style and fluid metaphor-making, not to mention the simple
pleasures of her eventually suspenseful story _ but she's the real
deal. Kline dramatizes private life, from the charged crosscurrents
of broken families to the robust intimacies of sex, with a
generous, knowing appreciation of human nature. But what impresses
most about the author is the pulsing depth and ambiguity she brings
to her sometimes maddening but lovable main character, Kathryn, who
blooms into adulthood as she turns over the soil of her past and
exposes the hidden turnings of the human heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1324EST &QL; 
