<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6441 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-UCONN-BOS &LR;      03-11 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-UCONN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN'S CALHOUN LEAVING NOTHING TO CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Jim Calhoun wants to make certain he's covered
everything. There is so much you can't control in the NCAA
Tournament, so many elements that could sneak up on teams talented
enough to win it all.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the University of Connecticut coach, whose top-seeded
Huskies (28-2) meet 16th-seeded Texas-San Antonio (18-10) in the
West Regional first round, took care of the altitude factor by
bringing his team here a day early and altering the sprinting
drills. In addition, he said he will rotate more players in to
lessen the affects of the thinner air.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun saw two Texas-San Antonio game films and Monday lamented
he didn't know more about freshman guard Devin Brown, the
Roadrunners' leading scorer at 16.9 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun has allowed injured center Jake Voskuhl (foot) to
practice only sparingly, and after sophomore guard Albert Mouring
aggravated his right knee injury Wednesday, Calhoun said it is
doubtful he will play.
</P>
<P>
   Anything else?
</P>
<P>
   ``I always think you always get surprised by a number of
things,'' said Calhoun, who added that despite having taken seven
other UConn teams to the NCAAs, ``sometimes you get surprised by
how your team reacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or it could be officiating in the game, where you say, `Whoa,'
'' he added. ``Even though we've done a good job of nationalizing
officiating, there are still such variations. What I would
constitute as not even being a touch foul might be assault and
battery to some guy because that's how they play.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun, in his 13th season with the Huskies, knows this may be
his best shot yet at advancing to the Final Four. With all the
intangibles covered, he can focus on a Texas-San Antonio team that
scored 80 or more points 15 times this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They average 78 points a game,'' said Calhoun, ``and they
played a 3-2 zone against Southwest Texas State twice and
completely stymied them, and Southwest Texas was probably the best
team in their conference. I think we'll probably see zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. John's plays a 3-2 zone, but (coach) Mike Jarvis doesn't
believe in that. He did it because people have been slowing us down
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn is coming off two lopsided wins in the Big East tournament
_ including an 82-63 rout of St. John's in the final _ after a
57-56 nail-biter over Seton Hall in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies are led by Big East Co-Player of the Year Richard
Hamilton (21 ppg, 4.8 rebounds per game), the Big East tournament's
most outstanding player, Kevin Freeman (12.7 ppg, 7.1 rpg), and
All-Big East point guard Khalid El-Amin (13.8 ppg, 3.6 assists a
game).
</P>
<P>
   UConn, the third-winningest team in Division 1 over the last six
seasons (165-34), tied its 1995-96 school record for wins and the
senior class set a record for most wins in four seasons (108).
UConn was the last unbeaten men's Division 1 program this season,
starting 19-0, and the first team to go 9-0 in Big East road games.
</P>
<P>
   But Calhoun knows that in the eyes of many, the tournament is
the only thing that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's assume we lose a game and we only win 29 or 30 or 28,''
said Calhoun. ``We would lose three games this season and people
would say it's an unsuccessful season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to say that it would be an unsuccessful
season. I would feel the accomplishments of what we could have done
weren't met, because this team is good enough to advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday the Huskies placed basketball concerns aside.
Associate director of athletics/communications Tim Tolokan said the
team was mourning the death of former team manager (1992-95) Joe
McGinn, 26, of Bristol, Conn., who lost a battle with kidney
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The team has petitioned the NCAA for permission to wear uniform
patches honoring McGinn, who was a regular at games and joined the
Huskies in the locker room after their Big East championship last
Saturday night. ``He touched all of our lives,'' said Calhoun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
