</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CBC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA'S CBC HITS STATIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Since the 1930s, the Canadian Broadcasting Corp. has
been one of the strongest threads binding this vast but fragile
country, a nation still struggling for a cohesive identity and
greater cultural confidence.
</P>
<P>
   From Nova Scotia fishing hamlets to Inuit settlements of the
high Arctic to prairie wheat farms in Saskatchewan, CBC radio and,
later, television has been where most Canadians turned for news
about the world and about themselves, as well as an eclectic
mixture of sports and highbrow entertainment. Although audience
share has plunged precipitously in the era of cable and satellite
TV, the CBC remains a unifying force with its broadcasts in
English, French, and aboriginal languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It played a defining role for Canada, and still does,'' says
Vince Carlin, a former top news executive with CBC who today heads
the school of journalism at Toronto's Ryerson Polytechnic
University. ``No one else is doing the breadth of Canadian
programming that the CBC offers.''
</P>
<P>
   But these are dangerous days for Canada's national network,
which receives most of its funding from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Beset by labor unrest, fierce competition from private rivals in
Canada, and programming beamed from the United States, plus the
more or less open hostility of Prime Minister Jean Chretien, the
public broadcaster appears to be in a struggle for its life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different layers and levels of problems all
squeezing together at a bad time,'' Carlin says. ``A strike would
be disastrous. But just as dangerous is political interference. The
corporation's existence may be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, 2,000 CBC technicians launched a strike that has
turned top newscasts into comic operas, with anchors describing
massacres in Kosovo or plane crashes in India while the camera cuts
to footage of fashion models prancing in Paris, or the screen
simply goes blank.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has even disrupted broadcasts of ``Hockey Night in
Canada,'' a show that as a national symbol ranks right up there
with the Mounties and the Maple Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that could have far more serious consequences, the
CBC's 3,300 reporters, producers, and anchorpeople gave their union
a strike authorization last week in a vote that carried by a 5-to-1
margin. If they join the technicians on the picket line next week,
the CBC could be shut down for the first time since its founding in
1937.
</P>
<P>
   The risks are enormous. Already, fewer Canadians are tuning in
to the CBC, opting for proliferating specialty channels and popular
American programming.
</P>
<P>
   Despite CBC's long history and status as a national icon, the
network today captures only about 10 percent of viewers in English
Canada, although its French-language service _ watched mainly in
Quebec and New Brunswick _ attracts a substantially higher share
because it faces less competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real danger is that people will give up in our absence and
tune out the CBC for good,'' Eric Foss, a striking sound
technician, told Maclean's magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the broadcaster is sagging under budget cuts and what
appears to be political meddling by the Chretien government. The
prime minister's attitude toward CBC is said to fall between
annoyance and antipathy.
</P>
<P>
   According to Canadian press reports, he has been especially
incensed by the French-language arm of CBC, whose news broadcasts
are perceived to be pro-separatist _ in effect, favoring the
political unraveling of the country that feeds it.
</P>
<P>
   But officials have also been outraged by CBC news reports that
took hard, critical looks at actions and policies of the Chretien
government. In one case, the government forced the suspension of a
CBC reporter who swapped information with groups embroiled in a
dispute with the prime minister's office over alleged
heavy-handedness by the Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
</P>
<P>
   The correspondent did appear to have breached journalistic
ethics, but Chretien has the leverage to sway CBC's management. He
picks the head of the CBC, and its board is stacked with political
appointees, some of them described as hostile to the notion of
tax-supported broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the 1990s, the government slashed funding to the
network by hundreds of millions of dollars, and last month CBC was
forced to shutter foreign bureaus in Paris, Mexico City, and Cape
Town to control costs. That's an especially demoralizing blow since
the CBC is Canada's most important journalistic enterprise, and has
a reputation for foreign coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offer homegrown, highly trained eyes and ears on the rest
of the world for Canadians, and that sets us apart from others,''
says Peter Mansbridge, anchorman of the CBC's nightly national
newscast.
</P>
<P>
   Founded during the Great Depression, the CBC's mission has
always been more than to just inform or entertain. From the start,
the goal was to bind an immense, inchoate nation lying in the
cultural shadow of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The ties that bind Canada are still loosely woven, but there is
no question that the CBC has helped forge a stronger national
identity. Even today, roughly 90 percent of its prime-time
programming is made in Canada, ranging from TV dramas such as
``Emily of New Moon'' _ a series, based on books by Canadian author
Lucy Maud Montgomery, about two girls coming of age in rural Prince
Edward Island _ to hard-hitting news shows.
</P>
<P>
   Americans might not realize it, but CBC has shaped American
television and radio programming as well. National Public Radio's
``All Things Considered,'' for example, was closely modeled on CBC
Radio's ``As It Happens,'' while so-called TV news magazines, such
as ``60 Minutes,'' trace their genesis to similar CBC news
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Canadians, CBC has been a sort of CBS, NBC, CNN, and PBS
all rolled into one,'' says Carlin. ``It's allowed Canada to talk
to itself about its own issues, and my view is that Canadians need
and expect a public broadcaster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
