A6445 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-ELECTRIC-BOS &LR;      03-11 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ELECTRIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE SEEN LAGGING ON ELECTRIC CARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts state government, which once led the
national fight to force car makers to sell vehicles that run on
batteries, seems to be losing interest in the battle for
zero-emission cars under Governor Paul Cellucci, just when
activists say state leadership is needed more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires the sale of almost 20,000 zero-emission
vehicles in 2003, but the state has done little to prepare for the
coming upheaval. A program to test-drive cars using alternative
fuels has been cut, almost no one is building electric charging
stations, and the state is just beginning to buy electric vehicles
for official use.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, advocates of electric vehicles fear that
Massachusetts will be unprepared to enforce its hard-won law, which
requires 10 percent of new vehicles sold in 2003 to run on
batteries or a hybrid of batteries and gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're quite at the point where we don't have
enough time to do something, but we will be in a year or so,''
warned Michelle Robinson of the Union of Concerned Scientists. ``We
can't go from zero to 10 percent overnight, and it will give
industry a whole lot of ammunition to kill the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and other observers say it is too soon to blame
Cellucci for the lack of initiative. Problems such as convincing
skittish state agencies to buy electric cars date back to Governor
William Weld, while funding problems may reflect the transition
from one administration to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, Steve Skiffington, director of the state's
electric vehicle pilot program, estimates that he has lost almost
$1 million in funding for the program since last June and that the
number of vehicles under his control has dwindled from 20 to five.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Skiffington can't lend electric and hybrid vehicles
to all the public and private fleet managers who want to learn
about the new technology. And he has been unable to field test new
models in cold New England weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see more funding for more cars,'' said
Skiffington, who works in the Division of Energy Resources. ``We
want to be the Consumer Reports of state agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight for electric vehicles was a signature issue for Weld,
who went to court repeatedly to force car makers to offer
zero-emissions vehicles as part of the state effort to reduce
summertime smog. Because of a quirk in federal law, Massachusetts
had to abandon sales mandates for 1998 and 2001, but the 2003 sales
requirement is still on the books.
</P>
<P>
   Weld also signed a 1996 executive order committing the state to
buying large numbers of vehicles that run on fuels cleaner than
gasoline. By 2003, three-quarters of the new light-duty vehicles
must run on alternative fuels, and 10 percent of the total must be
electric.
</P>
<P>
   However, environmentalists say that, to succeed, these
initiatives require vast amounts of public education about the new
vehicles, as well as a fair amount of vehicle services. For
example, California businesses and government agencies have built
more than 300 public charging stations for electric vehicles, a
project that hasn't even begun here.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists also say that the state has been slow to set
an example by purchasing electric and other low-polluting vehicles.
``They're way behind'' in meeting the spirit of Weld's executive
order, said Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   So far, just 32 of the state's 2,700 light-duty vehicles run on
a fuel other than gas. All of them run on natural gas, though the
Metropolitan District Commission will soon get the state's first
electric vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But Herb Falconer, who oversees the purchase of light-duty
vehicles at the Executive Office of Administration and Finance,
promised there will be more purchases as older vehicles are
retired. ``This has a lot of potential for clean air,'' Falconer
said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the state's electric-vehicle testing program has
won praise from environmentalists for gathering information about
how electric vehicles with limited driving range can meet
commuters' needs. The program also identified the need for a
kerosene heater so that drivers of electric cars don't drain their
batteries providing heat in a typical New England winter.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Skiffington's program has five of the latest electric
vehicles, the Honda EV Plus model, equipped with batteries that can
go 100 miles before recharging. But Skiffington is still looking
for the money to acquire other state-of-the-art vehicles, such as
Toyota's hybrid version of the RAV 4, which has a longer driving
range because it runs on gas and batteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have access to money to test the vehicles that the
manufacturers will deliver in the future,'' said Sheila Lynch,
director of the Northeast Alternative Vehicle Consortium, a
Boston-based industry group.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists suspect that Cellucci, who took over from
Weld in July 1997, is less committed to electric and hybrid
vehicles than Weld was, in part because of Cellucci's ties to
former auto-industry lobbyist Andrew Card. Card lobbied hard
against the electric-vehicle law.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials Wednesday said there had been no
change in state policy. ``There has been no trickle down from
Cellucci'' suggesting that policy had changed, said Skiffington.
</P>
<P>
   And Newton Mayor David Cohen, who wrote the state's
electric-vehicle law when he was a state representative, said he
believes that Cellucci will rally to the cause once his
administrators grow comfortable in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have every hope,'' Cohen said, ``that the program will be
implemented successfully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
