r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-REVIEW-LEONARD-     03-11 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEW-LEONARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WESTERN IS BACK IN THE SADDLE, AND WHAT A RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 14)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Kid and The Big Hunt: Unabridged Stories from The Tonto
Woman and other Western Stories,'' by Elmore Leonard; read by Brian
Dennehy and Liev Schrieber; approximately 90 minutes; Simon &AMP;
Schuster Audio; $9.95.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who enjoys the talented Leonard probably knows that he
began his prolific-writing odyssey with westerns. More than three
decades before ``Get Shorty'' and other best-sellers, Leonard was
an accomplished writer of such classics as ``Hombre.''
</P>
<P>
   A Leonard-the-western-writer revival is taking place, and this
isn't a bad thing at all. These stories don't showcase his gift for
dialogue, but his lean and economic prose is evident, as is his
compassion for the people and places being written about.
</P>
<P>
   In both ``The Kid'' and ``The Big Hunt,'' men with resolve tough
their way through trying times. These aren't larger-than-life
creations, either. They are determined men of character, taking
their lumps but never losing their focus.
</P>
<P>
   The acclaimed horse trilogy by Cormac McCarthy did not breath
new life into the western genre, but it's possible the re-release
of Leonard's earliest works (1950s and early '60s) just might. They
are accessible stories that, once started, compel the listener to
take them to their conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``8.4,'' by Peter Hernon; read by Campbell Scott; abridged,
approximately 4.5 hours; Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio; $24.
</P>
<P>
   The title refers to the Richter scale, which may tell you all
you want to know about Hernon's second suspense novel in three
years.
</P>
<P>
   An explosive fault line has come alive in America's heartland,
near the confluence of the Mississippi and Ohio rivers. It has
erupted once, killing tens of thousands, and appears likely to
break loose at least one more time, much like the series of
earthquakes in 1811 and 1812 that devastated large portions of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   John Atkins and Elizabeth Holleran, seismologists who previously
did not know each other, discover love as they search for answers
to the trembling fault line's potential. We're not sure why she
finds him attractive. At the same time, there are devious men among
them, some working for the U.S. Geological Survey, who for reasons
that never become clear are undermining their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Hernon, a reporter with the St. Louis Post-Dispatch, should be
ready to quit his day job, thanks to ``8.4.'' NBC has purchased the
rights to turn it into a movie, and the book indeed has all the
makings of a big- or small-screen thriller. Which doesn't mean this
isn't a flawed work, despite the rumbling action.
</P>
<P>
   Hernon clearly knows science better than he knows character or
plot development. As a result, ``8.4'' in fact fails to register on
a literary scale.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunter,'' by James Byron Huggins; read by Boyd Gaines;
abridged, approximately 4.5 hours; Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio; $23.
</P>
<P>
   There is a comic-book quality to Huggins' latest thriller. The
protagonist, Hunter, the world's best tracker who has a massive
wolf as his loyal companion, is, if possible, more unbelievable
than Edgar Rice Burroughs' Tarzan. We don't know how Hunter came to
be such an amazing tracker, nor do we learn the origins of his
amazing physical strength. He just is, and he seems not a whit
real.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter is asked to assist a team of elite Army troops as they
search for a beast loose somewhere north of the Arctic Circle. The
beast is in fact a monster, created by a secret government agency.
The beast is hellbent on brutally killing and devouring every
person it encounters. It's not an exaggeration to say this creature
is every bit as believable as Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins pulled off an almost first-rate techo-thriller in 1997
with ``Cain,'' but ``Hunter'' misses the mark. Even a superb
reading by the always reliable Boyd Gaines can't keep ``Hunter'' on
track.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
