<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_CREATINE MAY SLOW LOSS OF MUSCLE TISSUE  
 _INCREASE IS TRACKED IN LIVER DISEASE RATES  
 _DRUG FOUND TO BENEFIT PARKINSON'S PATIENTS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 Creatine may slow loss of muscle tissue
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A popular food supplement used by athletes and body builders
shows promise of slowing the progressive muscle-wasting in people
with degenerative diseases like muscular dystrophy, according to a
new study.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine, an apparently safe and widely used amino acid,
produced an average 10 to 15 percent improvement in the exercise
ability of 81 patients with neuromuscular diseases, according to a
report published Wednesday in the journal Neurology. Dr. Mark
Tarnopolsky of McMaster University Medical Center in Ontario gave
the patients 10 days' worth of creatine, and found that their hand,
foot, and leg strength ``went up on every measurement.''
</P>
<P>
   The researcher said larger studies are needed, but he suggested
that taking creatine, which is relatively cheap, might delay for
weeks or months patients' loss of independence in various
activities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, researchers from Cornell and Harvard universities
recently reported that creatine benefited mice with a disease much
like amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, or Lou Gehrig's disease. The
mice moved and ate better and lived longer, said the report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Increase is tracked in liver disease rates
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More people are developing liver cancer and are dying from it
younger, according to a study that tracked rising rates of the
disease over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of 1.4 cases per 100,000 people in 1976 to 1980 rose to
2.4 per 100,000 in the period of 1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, liver cancer affects elderly people in developed
countries, said the researchers in a report in the current issue of
the New England Journal of Medicine. But younger people are
developing the disease from infections with hepatitis B and
hepatitis C, and those two diseases are primarily reponsible for
the increase in liver cancer incidence, according to the
researchers from the Veterans Affairs Medical Center in
Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   The authors say the increase in liver cancer rates may continue
for a number of years as some people who now have hepatitis B or C,
but haven't yet developed cancer, will later be diagnosed with it.
Liver cancer has a five-year survival rate of only about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, Drs. Nedim Ince and Jack R. Wandes
of Massachusetts General Hospital said aggressive treatment with
antiviral drugs may reduce the risk of hepatitis patients
developing liver cancer, but that larger studies are needed to show
how effective this strategy will be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Drug found to benefit Parkinson's patients
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Modern drugs can slow the decline of people with Parkinson's
disease, but at a heavy price _ the drugs may make the patient
psychotic. As many as 22 percent of patients with Parkinson's _ a
progressive loss of movement, flexibility and balance _ develop
delusions, hallucinations, and other severe mental problems, and
it's the single biggest reason such patients are put in nursing
homes.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, many antipsychotic drugs. But most of
them, ironically, make the Parkinson's symptoms worse.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome news from the research front, however, says that
clozapine, a relatively new drug normally used for schizophrenia,
benefited about 85 percent of Parkinson's patients with
drug-induced psychosis. In the study, reported in the current issue
of the New England Journal of Medicine, small doses of the drug
reduced the hallucinations and other psychotic symptoms by about 25
percent, and the drug even improved tremors caused by Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   The study was headed by Dr. Joseph H. Friedman at the Memorial
Hospital of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Jeffrey L. Cummings at the
University of California at Los Angeles Medical School said the
study suggests that use of clozapine ``may allow some patients to
continue living at home for longer periods and will facilitate the
care of many of those living in nursing homes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
