<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6452 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALAMOS-SPY-ART-BOS &LR;      03-11 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMOS-SPY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPYING ACCUSATION SHAKES SILENCE AT LOS ALAMOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. _ Even now, more than half a century after its
hush-hush creation, Los Alamos is not a town that talks much.
</P>
<P>
   Trained in science and silence, the elite research community
that developed the world's first atomic bomb still prides itself on
its secrets. Some husbands and wives know only the roughest
outlines of their spouse's assignments. Most neighbors know better
than to ask. Gossiping goes against instincts ingrained in the days
when residents were told not to talk to outsiders unless absolutely
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all trained not to talk about anything we were working
on, ever,'' said Lawry Mann, a retired physicist who is now vice
chairman of the Los Alamos County Council. ``So that certainly cuts
down on the rumor mill.''
</P>
<P>
   That certainty -- that silence must and will be maintained --
was challenged this week when a computer scientist at Los Alamos
National Laboratory was fired for allegedly handing nuclear warhead
secrets over to the Chinese. In a city where nearly every other
adult works at or for the Lab, as locals call the 43 square miles
of offices, explosive testing sites and laboratories, the
revelations were wounding. They were not, however, stunning.
</P>
<P>
   As Richard Perkins, who works for the Lab's largest
subcontractor, Johnson Controls, put it, ``I thought it was pretty
much inevitable.'' Added Mann, ``It's the type of thing that's
going to happen when you've got something other people want to
steal.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as they absorbed the potential magnitude of the scandal,
residents did tend to take the alleged betrayal professionally, if
not personally. Los Alamos, after all, was a town knit together by
a single purpose when the Manhattan Project was launched in 1943,
six secretive years before the city was formally established. The
18,500 or so people who live in the county are used to being blamed
for building the Bomb. Even as the Lab expands its work to the
other sciences, such as biomedical and environmental research, they
remain known for their first and most controversial success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get so much bad publicity and this isn't going to help,''
said Sandy Warnock, who lives across the street from the alleged
spy in their midst and whose husband is a project manager at the
Lab. ``The tree huggers in Santa Fe hate us. But I'm surprised at
my own reaction. I think they ought to put this guy on the end of a
nuclear weapon and send him to China.''
</P>
<P>
   Wen Ho Lee, the 59-year-old scientist who was just months shy of
retirement when he was fired, has not yet been arrested or charged
with any crime. Allen Marshall, a substitute teacher whose family
has lived next door to Lee for 16 years, said he finds it
impossible to believe Lee will be. Marshall, 25, grew up with the
Taiwanese-born Lee's two children and recalled him as a man who did
the cooking for the family and cooked the Marshall's a Peking Duck
every Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Lab you're told what to look for in case of spying and
none of those red flags came up,'' said Marshall, whose parents
work at the Lab. ``My parents are taking this hard. We just can't
see him doing something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Few, however, were surprised that Lee had the opportunity to do
so. Scientists from other countries regularly visit Los Alamos,
whose own scientists in turn make frequent trips abroad. Along with
9,242 others, Lee also had the highest security clearance awarded
by the Lab. Called Q clearance, it gave him access to every area,
no matter how sensitive the work being done there. Another 1,588
subcontractors, and Lab and US Department of Energy employees and
retirees, have more limited access, known as L clearance, said Lab
spokesman Jim Danneskiold, and 7,569 have Lab identification badges
but no security clearance at all.
</P>
<P>
   Those totals are far higher than the actual number of Lab
employees, 8,955 -- a number so large that the population of Los
Alamos doubles during the day and restaurants that are packed at
lunchtime are deserted by dinner. Located on a secluded mesa
surrounded by the Jemez Mountains about 35 miles northwest of Santa
Fe, and with the Lab requiring so much land, the city has nowhere
to grow. Even Wal-mart has been unable to find a spot for one of
its sprawling superstores.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, housing prices are higher than the national average
and the highest in New Mexico. According to Danneskiold, about half
of the employees live outside Los Alamos. Many of the people who
work at the Lab can't even afford to live nearby, not even down the
hill in White Rock where Lee has a burnt red, wood-and-brick house
in a pricey subdivision built in the late 1970s and early 1980s. He
and his wife Sylvia, a former Lab secretary, were in seclusion
there this week, their telephone disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably only 30 to 50 houses on the market at any
given time,'' said Suzie Havemann, a former president of the Los
Alamos County Chamber of Commerce who grew up in the city, left,
then returned about six years ago. ``I may be exaggerating, but
it's really bad. Everything is more expensive here: transportation,
housing, gas, food. But it's a great place to live if you can
afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the center for nuclear defense research, Los Alamos is in
essence a small town with a big brain. Architectually, it has a
1950s feel. Intellectually, it's already in the next millennium.
PhDs with seven syllable specialties abound, along with Nobel Prize
winners. A downtown street is named after J. Robert Oppenheimer,
the University of California physics professor who led the secret
effort to develop the first atomic weapons. Since World War II
ended, the university, rather than the US government, has run the
Lab as a federal contractor and signed its employees' paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Today Los Alamos is struggling to shed its status as a
one-company town. Last year, the county was given a $22.6 million
payment from the federal government, which discontinued the $2.8
million paid annually in lieu of local property taxes. Some of the
money has gone toward taking over the water system and the small
airport on the way into town, where the first commercial flight is
scheduled to take place later this month. A research park on land
that once belonged to the Lab is planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always surprised when they come into town and see
it's not a military base or a big, flat desert where nuclear
testing is done,'' said Kevin Holsapple, executive director of the
Los Alamos Economic Development Corp. ``There is a town that is a
very separate thing from the Lab, and we want even more of that.
We're not just about nuclear weapons anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs of change, in fact, are everywhere on the way into Los
Alamos. Unlike the early days, arrows now point the way for
visitors. Havemann, who never visited her father's office at the
Lab and could not recall a single father or mother who worked there
speaking at her school's career day, stressed that people are more
open today. Some could even joke about Lee's alleged betrayal of
the scientific community.
</P>
<P>
   ``In meetings today, people made some tongue in cheek comments
about spies and things,'' Havemann said. ``But we've always had a
controversial heritage. Maybe if I were a senior manager at the Lab
I'd see it differently, but absolutely I don't see it as a
reflection on me or Los Alamos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
