<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6455 &Cx1f; xxxxx
r g &Cx13;  &Cx11;  OPED-CHOOSE-LIFE-TAGS     03-11 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 OPED-CHOOSE-LIFE-TAGS 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Commentary
</P>
<P>
   By Waldo Proffitt
</P>
<P>
   NYT Regional Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   There is a big push in the Florida Legislature to authorize the
</P>
<P>
   state to issue auto license tags carrying the slogan ``Choose
</P>
<P>
   Life.''
</P>
<P>
   I expect there are enough votes in the Republican-controlled
</P>
<P>
   Legislature for the push to succeed. Which is unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   The state simply has no business taking sides in what may well
</P>
<P>
   be the most intractable dispute in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The proponents of adding this tag to the 43 vanity tags already
</P>
<P>
   available argue that ``choose life'' in this context only
indicates
</P>
<P>
   approval of child adoption.
</P>
<P>
   I think not. If that were the case, it would be a simple matter
to
</P>
<P>
   approve a tag reading, ``Adopt A Child,'' and you could get
</P>
<P>
   unanimous support from every legislator and every legislator's
</P>
<P>
   constituents.
</P>
<P>
   The words, ``Choose Life,'' as proposed in this usage, translate
</P>
<P>
   to ``Outlaw Abortion'' _ a perfectly legal public policy
objective,
</P>
<P>
   though not one I approve. More to the point, it is a policy most
</P>
<P>
   polls show is not supported by a majority of Floridians.
</P>
<P>
   To say that a ``Choose Life'' tag is intended only as a
</P>
<P>
   pro-adoption slogan is to engage in the sort of specious,
</P>
<P>
   evasive, less-than-the-whole-truth sophistry of which we have
</P>
<P>
   seen all too much in Washington during the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Those who may doubt that is a fair statement are invited to go
</P>
<P>
   forth and sign up legislative support for a license plate slogan
</P>
<P>
   reading, ``Choose Choice,'' or even ``Choose Freedom'' _
</P>
<P>
   certainly noble objectives almost universally approved by all
</P>
<P>
   Americans. But, you try to get those words on license plates
</P>
<P>
   under the sponsorship of men and women who support the
</P>
<P>
   freedom of women to make their own choice in matters of
</P>
<P>
   reproduction, and you will have a whale of a fight on your
hands.
</P>
<P>
   I think it would be just as wrong and stupid for the Legislature
to
</P>
<P>
   authorize ``Choose Choice'' tags as to approve ``Choose Life''
</P>
<P>
   tags. Either one would be seen for what it is _ a slogan
</P>
<P>
   expressing a point of view about abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Either one would be appropriate as a bumper sticker. Indeed,
</P>
<P>
   there are plenty of stickers using even stronger language
</P>
<P>
   already rolling down the highways.
</P>
<P>
   But, there is a big difference between an unofficial message
</P>
<P>
   pasted on a car and a message bearing the imprimatur of the
</P>
<P>
   state of Florida, unavoidably giving the impression that the
</P>
<P>
   sentiment expressed represents, if not the official view of the
</P>
<P>
   state, at least the view that it is appropriate for the
sentiment to
</P>
<P>
   appear under state auspices.
</P>
<P>
   This is not comparable to allowing Gators and Seminoles to
</P>
<P>
   taunt each other or encouraging the protection of universally
</P>
<P>
   valued species such as manatees and Florida panthers.
</P>
<P>
   It is more akin to pouring gasoline on a raging fire. It is
neither
</P>
<P>
   responsible nor proper for the state to reduce one of the most
</P>
<P>
   complex and divisive issues of our time to a battle of slogans.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that totally committed pro-life people and totally
</P>
<P>
   committed pro-choice people irritate each other by marching
</P>
<P>
   under banners which present their cause attract- ively.
</P>
<P>
   That they are both able to do so illustrates, I suggest, the
</P>
<P>
   complexity of the issue and the ambivalence it evokes. I don't
</P>
<P>
   know anyone who thinks an abortion is a truly joyous event which
</P>
<P>
   should be celebrated with toasts and merriment. On the other
</P>
<P>
   hand, I know few people who think no woman should ever be
</P>
<P>
   allowed to have an abortion under any circumstances
</P>
<P>
   whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   I think the views of most of us lie somewhere between these
</P>
<P>
   extremes, and probably not very far from the position of the
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court in Roe vs. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   I think, further, that, not many years hence, the abortion
debate
</P>
<P>
   will be mooted by advances in medicine which will prevent most
</P>
<P>
   unwanted conceptions and allow those which do happen to be
</P>
<P>
   ended by a woman without surgical intervention and without
</P>
<P>
   making her way through a wall of jeering pickets.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it is not wise to step up the level of intensity in a
</P>
<P>
   dispute for which there is no outcome that will satisfy
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   There are stories from Richmond indicating Virginia may follow
</P>
<P>
   Florida's venture in reproductive sloganeering, and I don't
think
</P>
<P>
   this is something for which we will get much credit by setting
an
</P>
<P>
   example.
</P>
<P>
   (Waldo Proffitt is the former editor of the Herald-Tribune in
Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
