<HEADLINE>
GUIDE DOG DROPOUT LANDS ON HIS FEET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's been employed by the Australian Protective Services three
months now, prowling the terminals of Sydney International Airport
searching for hidden firearms and explosives.
</P>
<P>
   His partner says he's a solid, earnest worker. And he'll be part
of the security force deployed next year to ensure the safety of
athletes and officials who will be arriving in the city for the
2000 Olympic summer games.
</P>
<P>
   He is Ocoee, a high-spirited 3-year-old black Labrador Retriever
who understands the angst of trying to find the right career.
</P>
<P>
   Born at the Guiding Eyes for the Blind's 30-acre breeding and
placement center in Patterson, N.Y., Ocoee was bred for specific
purpose of becoming a guide dog.
</P>
<P>
   But, like a Marine who washes out of basic training, he flunked
out of his first career. When the crucial moment came, at a test
for guide-dog certification, Ocoee cowered and slunk away, as the
family who adopted him brushed back tears.
</P>
<P>
   After a second, failed attempt at serving as a pet for a family
with an autistic son, Ocoee caught on with the US State
Department's anti-terrorism team, and it was the start of a
brilliant career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is doing very well,'' assures Doug Andrew, his partner,
housemate and senior canine detection trainer for the Australian
Protective Services, which is similar to the US Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, ``He still is playful.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocoee's triumph, after striving for success, may be dramatic
enough to warm the heart of any yuppie, but it carries special
meaning for the Norfolk, Mass. family that raised him, then let him
go after his dismal failure on the guide-dog proving ground.
</P>
<P>
   Aislynn Rodeghiero, a sophomore at the Rivers School in Weston,
Mass. three years ago, spent six months persuading her family to
help train a Guiding Eye puppy, to allow her to meet her school's
30-hour community service requirement.
</P>
<P>
   For 16 months, the Rodegheiros were responsible for raising
Ocoee in a safe and loving environment, teaching him obedience and
manners, and laying the basic foundation he would need for
guide-dog school.
</P>
<P>
   That meant frequently consulting an 81-page manual and calling
Guiding Eyes with questions. It also meant exposing him to a
variety of social environments: the Meadowbrook School in Weston,
Mass., where Linda teaches music, to weekly ``socialization''
classes in Kingston, Mass., and outings to malls, supermarkets and
busy city streets.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rodegheiros were prohibited from preparing Ocoee for his
biggest challenge: a half-hour temperament test he would have to
pass for admission to guide-dog training school.
</P>
<P>
   When that time came, the Rodegheiros personally delivered him to
the Guiding Eyes training center in Yorktown Heights, N.Y. As she
and her parents drove away in tears, Aislynn says, she looked back
and saw Ocoee, looking bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, really hard,'' she says. ``He was looking around
as if to say `What do I do now?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ocoee breezed through the obedience exercises, and barely
flinched when they fired gunshots to see if he'd panic. But when a
large umbrella suddenly sprung open in front of him, he cowered and
slinked away, flunking the test.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Gressle, a puppy evaluator at Guiding Eyes, said
confidence in a guide dog is crucial ``because they can't always
count on the person they are being teamed with being in the know.
The person . . . can't see what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rodegheiros took the news of Ocoee's failure hard, but
Gressle notes nearly half of the 520 puppies raised each year by
Guiding Eyes volunteers fail the test.
</P>
<P>
   Aislynn admits she wanted to adopt Ocoee, but talked it over
with her parents. They convinced her to see if he might have
another calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised him as a family and we made the decision as a family
to see how far he could go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ocohee was sent back to Guiding Eyes, his tail between his legs.
</P>
<P>
   Guiding Eyes placed Ocoee with a family that has an autistic
son, but he was returned within a week after he tore through the
garbage and accidentally knocked over the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad idea,'' said Kathy Kraft, director of Guiding
Eyes' adoption program. ``He's a big dog, 85 pounds, and very
exuberant. He was jumping on counters and stealing food. He wanted
a lot of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it made him unsuitable as a special needs dog, those same
qualities made Ocoee a hit with a scout for the US Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the bureau picks about two dozen dogs from Guiding
Eyes for training to detect explosives. Those dogs are then sent to
work abroad under a State Department anti-terrorism program.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Australian Protective Services was included in
that program, and Andrews personally selected Ocoee as his partner.
</P>
<P>
   The Rodegheiros, who keep a framed portrait of Ocoee in their
living room, remain attached to him. They saved his baby teeth,
quarterly puppy evaluations, collars, and toys as mementos, and
brought him $100 worth of his favorite treats when he graduated
from the ATF training center in Front Royal, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to see the cycle finish,'' says Aislynn. ``As
much as I wanted to keep him, I know he's over there for a
purpose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
