<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARPS-COLUMN-LADN     03-11 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIEND FONDLY REMEMBERS SPRINGFIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ She was constantly late, rarely sure of her talent
and never realized just how much loyalty she inspired, says Fred
Perry, the late Dusty Springfield's lighting designer and pal for
22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Perry joined Springfield's organization in 1964 as ``I Only Want
to Be With You'' was rising in the pop charts on both sides of the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I met with her, she was terribly glamorous,''
said Perry, a longtime Burbank resident. ``We talked about
everything but the lighting, and we clicked. That was the start of
a long and beautiful friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Springfield died March 2 at age 59 after a long battle with
cancer. Perry returned to Britain this week to attend today's
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always late,'' Perry recalled. ``She would arrive on
stage at the precise moment the orchestra would strike up. Once
after missing the tour bus, she'd hired a car and driver. They're
driving across the moors, and they see this yellow and brown bus
with instruments and costumes showing through the back window. So
she follows alongside, stops the bus to get on, and it turns out to
be Cilla Black and an entirely different tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Springfield retained her popularity at home and abroad because
listeners could identify with the emotions of songs like ``You
Don't Have to Say You Love Me,'' ``The Look of Love'' and
``Son-of-a Preacher Man,'' Perry believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she never thought she was any good,'' Perry said. ``She
was very shy, very closed, and you really had to be in her
confidence to get to know her well. She was very vulnerable and
never realized the loyalty she inspired in people.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry last saw Springfield, who spent about 15 years in Los
Angeles, about six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just very upsetting,'' he said. ``She was a wonderful
lady.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A life in Fulson: We were sad to hear of the death of West Coast
bluesman Lowell Fulson last weekend. Fulson, 77, died of heart
disease at his Lancaster, Calif., home.
</P>
<P>
   Best-known for his oft-covered hit ``Reconsider Baby,'' cut in
Dallas with David ``Fathead'' Newman on tenor sax and later
recorded by Elvis Presley, guitarist-singer Fulson was a mainstay
of Los Angeles' Central Avenue postwar music scene of the late '40s
and '50s.
</P>
<P>
   He also co-wrote ``Tramp,'' which was a hit on Stax Records for
Otis Redding and Carla Thomas. In 1993, Fulson received five W.C.
Handy Awards. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
