<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6462 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-TULIPS-BOS &LR;      03-11 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-TULIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TULIPS SPEAK THE LANGUAGE OF SPRING AND ITS RENEWAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tulips have a lot to say. They speak to us of the fullness of
spring, of private, individual glory and public ostentation in vast
numbers, of greed and human foible, and always of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Garden
</P>
<P>
   Pathways
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, they speak with quite a voice. The city plants 30,000
each year, 26,000 in alternating beds along the pathway in the
Public Garden from Arlington to Charles streets and 4,000 in front
of the visitors information center in the Common.
</P>
<P>
   These are classic public displays, usually in peak about
mid-April. The city plants seven kinds, mostly rugged Darwin
hybrids: ``Pink Impression,'' ``Elizabeth Arden,'' ``Jewel of
Spring,'' ``Apeldoorn''s Elite,'' ``White Emperor,'' ``Gordon
Cooper,'' and ``Diplomat.''
</P>
<P>
   After blooming, they are yanked to make way for bedding annuals
and shipped to a compost heap on MDC land. According to John
Slater, superintendent of the city greenhouse, city workers used to
dig them, store and dry them, then distribute them to the public,
but Boston Parks and Recreation no longer has the time and money to
do that. (After all, they do set out 150,000 bedding plants, and
that is after growing them in the first place.)
</P>
<P>
   In Marshfield, in my garden, tulips speak more softly. The
``Angelique'' double-petaled tulips (a wonderful soft pink)
whisper, ``Transplant us, you fool, because we're lost in that
shrub border you had to have.'' The red tulips (I have lost track
of what they are, but they may be ``Red Riding Hood,'' a brilliant,
long-lived Greigii) along the property line tell me I was smart to
plant them extra deep, as they have been reliable for 10 years now.
</P>
<P>
   The multiflowering ``Toronto'' tulips (a pleasing clump of
salmon) politely suggest the potential of tulips I have failed to
adequately pursue. And the dozens of carefree 4-inch-tall yellow
Tulipa dasystemons tell me I did all right in choosing these hardy
species tulips to carpet the dry yellow bed.
</P>
<P>
   For most of us, the first chat of the year with tulips comes at
the New England Spring Flower Show, where easily forced bulbs
always shout the cheerful news that spring is nigh.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's show, there will be another tulip voice, Anna
Pavord, gardening correspondent of Britain's Independent and
featured speaker at the show March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Pavord is the author of ``The Tulip,'' a painstaking 400-page
labor of love _ ``It was written entirely for me,'' she told me _
that she spent six years researching. She planted 2,500 in her own
garden last fall; she feels tulips are the flowers to give at
Valentine's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never know whom we're going to fall in love with,'' she
said, explaining her fascination with tulips and citing their
subtlety and versatility. ``They can do so many tricks, such a
staggering combination of colors.''
</P>
<P>
   And in staggering detail, ``The Tulip'' _ more a history than a
so-called garden book _ tells the tale over the centuries of a
flower that now comes in 120 species and 5,600 cultivars. They are
not native to western Europe (or the New World), arriving from the
East in the mid-1500s. Wherever they went, they created a
sensation, or, rather, people did.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, long, thin, pointed petals, a spidery effect, were
prized. Tulips were collected for the gardens of sultans and
portrayed in tile and on dishes. In the West, the English florists
(not flower sellers, but aficionados and growers of particular
flowers) valued tulips in a half-sphere, and tulips also were
well-portrayed in art, perhaps even more so because there was a
time when a painting of tulips was cheaper to purchase than the
bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   French tulip madness came first. In the early 17th century, one
grower exchanged a single bulb for a brewery worth 30,000 francs. A
miller traded a mill for a bulb of ``Mere Brune.''
</P>
<P>
   The famous Dutch tulipomania followed closely, then launched
itself to a new level, pure speculation for profit, not beauty. It
got entirely out of control, and it all came crashing down, of
course, and prices went into pretty much of a permanent recession.
But for a while, ``Semper Augustus'' sold for 1,000 florins a bulb,
more than six times the average annual income, and a price of
13,000 florins (more than the cost of a mansion) was quoted at the
height of the frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Tulip madness struck again, this time in, of all places, Turkey,
where the things grow wild. The Tulip Era peaked under Sultan Ahmed
III, who imported millions of tulip bulbs from Holland and spent
fortunes on extravagant tulip festivals. His 1730 overthrow
resulted.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, too, went a little crazy. Florists' societies
flourished and held feasts with bouts of drinking and eating and
bulb showing and trading.
</P>
<P>
   These evolved into shows, and, Pavord wrote, ``between 1750 and
1850, scarcely any town of importance in the north of England was
without its tulip show.''
</P>
<P>
   The great tulips were those that had ``broken,'' flowers that
arose one color one year and the next had multi-colored flames and
feathers. This was almost magical, and many recipes for it existed,
but in reality it was the result of a virus, which weakened but did
not kill the tulips, transmitted by aphids. Once a prized broken
tulip was selected, it could be reproduced exactly through the
bulb's offsets. This took time and labor and contributed to the
price, but with enough time and trouble, prices would and did fall,
along with the fortunes of speculators and collectors alike.
</P>
<P>
   For a variety of reasons, fashion being a big one, tulips
declined in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the great broken tulips are lost. (Growers want flames
and feathers but without virus.) Also, Pavord lamented, ``all those
wonderful Ottoman tulips are all gone.'' Istanbul is full of tulips
all right, but they're Dutch. Of the British tulip societies, only
one survives, and hereabouts you cannot find a tulip society,
though irises and day lilies and roses have organized worship.
Pavord's book tells us all this history, then concludes with
rundowns on the species and hybrids. The book is packed with
gorgeous color reproductions of rare tulip art, the closest you or
I will ever get to ``Semper Augustus'' or ``Louis XVI.''
</P>
<P>
   The tulip, once a ``jewel flower'' worn in hats and hair,
remains a potent flower of color and shape. ``I think we might be
on the verge of a revival,'' Pavord said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
