<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6463 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARING-COLUMN-BO     03-11 1670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHERS AND DAUGHTERS: HOW TO GET PAST THE SLAMMED DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Diane Aronson remembers most about her daughter Rachal's
preteen years is what a struggle they were. ``Often, I felt a very
deep, personal despair,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Rachal remembers being happiest when she shut herself in her
bedroom, with her mother on the other side of the door. ``Sometimes
I was so angry, I hated her,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this is a classic story of mother-daughter
conflict: stormy fights, shut doors, hurtful barbs. Yet it is also
a success story. Rachal, now 22, lives back home in Arlington,
Mass. with her parents and considers her mom a good friend. Last
week they went to Arizona together, just the two of them.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a mom who simply got lucky. Diane Aronson worked
hard. Her goal _ to respect Rachal's need for privacy but to also
stay connected _ seemed contradictory and downright impossible at
times. But it put her on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   Parents typically see the ages of 11 to 14 as a time when a
daughter's task is to separate and a mother's is to back off. But
researchers say that leads to a disconnect; a girl feels deserted
by her mother. They urge mothers to see this instead as a time of
change and renegotiation. Then daughters are more likely to feel
supported, and connections less likely to be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mistake to see this as `I'm losing my daughter.' That
prompts you to withdraw and causes real separation. Think of the
relationship as still intense, just different,'' says researcher
and psychologist Judith Jordan of the Stone Center at Wellesley
College. She specializes in the psychology of girls and women.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it is difficult. Instead of telling you secrets and
leaving hearts on your pillow, your daughter is sending mixed
messages, from ``Stay out of my life!'' to ``Will you make me
macaroni and cheese? No one does it as good as you, Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder mothers are confused.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in spite of their insistence at wanting distance, daughters
are confused, too. ``They are dying not to need you but the truth
is they do, so they get angry at themselves. That results in the
mixed messages,'' says psychologist Roni Cohen-Sandler, coauthor of
a new book, ``I'm Not Mad, I Just Hate You: A New Understanding of
Mother-Daughter Conflict'' (Viking).
</P>
<P>
   She says girls have a tremendous need to vent. Cognitive,
social, emotional, and physical changes cause girls enormous
stress, and, she adds, ``The hormonal surge of puberty leads to
less impulse control than they had at 8 or 9.''
</P>
<P>
   That Mom takes the brunt of this intensity and not Dad is
probably because her mother is the person a daughter feels safest
with. Most mothers recognize this for the backanded compliment it
is and can take the intensity when it's directed at peers, or
teachers, or issues in general. It's harder to take when you're the
focus of the intensity:
</P>
<P>
   You come downstairs in the morning dressed for work, your
12-year-old slowly looks you over from head to toe, then asks,
``You're not leaving the house like that, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   As mean as this sounds, it has more to do with
self-consciousness about her own appearance than anything else. The
more you can ignore it, the better. Even tougher to take, however,
is criticism of you as a person.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Rogers, a psychologist at the Harvard Graduate School of
Education who specializes in girls' development, tells of one
13-year-old who overheard an argument between her parents and told
her mother, ``He crushed you like an aluminum can.''
</P>
<P>
   This hurts to the quick, but so can your response hurt her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, mothers have encouraged girls to voice their
feelings. But when a girl turns her newfound observational
abilities on her mother's inner world, it's disturbing,'' says
Rogers. The typical mother responds in icy self-defense: ``This is
between me and your father; it's not your business.''
</P>
<P>
   The daughter is stunned. Why has Mom shut her down, closed her
out? ``Daughters feel deserted when mothers don't speak honestly
about their own lives,'' says psychologist Janet Surrey, codirector
of the Gender Relations Project at the Stone Center at Wellesley.
</P>
<P>
   A daughter is also confused, says Jordan: ``She's looking at
what it means to be an adult woman and she may not like the model
her mother presents.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a betrayed and angry mother and a betrayed and angry
daughter. Nasty, vindictive words are shouted, doors slammed,
relationships damaged.
</P>
<P>
   This is not inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can be authentic in your feelings, you can mitigate
conflict,'' says Rogers. Don't overdo, however. A good response
might be, ``You're right, that's a part of my relationship with
your father that I struggle with. I'm working on it.'' But don't
seek her advice or burden her with details.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even in the heat of angry moments, Diane Aronson never took
anything personally. ``I just didn't let myself,'' she says.
Cohen-Sandler applauds that strength. ``I tell mothers to take even
the meanest, most hateful thing a daughter says and translate it to
this: ``I'm upset right now and it may have nothing to do with you,
but I don't have words or thoughts for it, so it's coming out as
anger toward you.' '' Consider, she adds, that your daughter simply
can't help herself.
</P>
<P>
   She also suggests ways to keep arguments from escalating:
</P>
<P>
   --Stay focused. A 12-year-old can twist even the most
straightforward comment. Tell her, ``We're getting sidetracked
here. What I really need is help setting the table.''
</P>
<P>
   --Monitor the level of anger. When it's spiraling out of control
(it's a red flag if you're saying mean things to her), tell her,
``You know what? We're both too angry to continue. Let's take a
break and talk when we're calmer.''
</P>
<P>
   --Comment on feelings. A 13-year-old can get furious if you
misstate the tiniest fact of a complicated story, so don't bother
with them. Instead of saying, ``What did she say to you?'' try,
``That must have made you feel awful.''
</P>
<P>
   --Set limits on abusiveness. It's one thing to let her vent,
another to allow her to abuse you. Say, ``I'm happy to listen to
you but I can't do it until you stop calling me names.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most of all, don't consider the slammed door the end of
a discussion. ``It can mean anything from, `I had a bad day; leave
me alone,' to `I'm in trouble; come get me,' '' says Cohen-Sandler.
Rogers tells mothers to put this spin on a slammed door: ``Don't
give up on me!''
</P>
<P>
   ``A teenager slamming a door really wants you out of her face,''
she says. ``But a preteen wants you to notice something is wrong,
and what's wrong for her is being at an impasse with her mother. It
doesn't feel good to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Tread gently, though: Knock lightly on the door and say
something like, ``I just want you to know I'm here; I care. We can
talk if you want.'' That way, says Jordan, ``you open the
(figurative) door to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   When and if she walks in, validate her feelings: ``I know there
are a lot of pressures in your life right now.'' That alone is a
signal of respect that she will appreciate. Follow it up with, ``I
want to help, but I'm not sure how.''
</P>
<P>
   For many mothers, this process is hampered by their own fear of
conflict. ``There's a tendency to see it as destructive,'' says
Cohen-Sandler. But it's more destructive if a girl doesn't get the
anger out. ``They turn it inward and it leads to things like eating
disorders and depression,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan tells mothers that allowing the conflict to exist in an
appropriate way in the relationship is a critical learning model
for girls. ``They need to see they can handle conflict and not lose
the relationship,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   During the most difficult times, mothers need someone to talk
to. Aronson had her husband, but she also had the support of a
close friend who, happy coincidence for her, happened to be Janet
Surrey, the Stone Center researcher. ``Sometimes just being able to
say out loud what I was feeling was all I needed,'' Aronson says.
``It also helped that Jan could keep me focused on the big picture
_ keeping the connections alive _ rather than on all the little
disconnects.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly she did that. Rachal is not only a confident young
woman, but one who talks about her mother with respect and love.
When she looks back on those years, even though she remembers her
own anger and hate, she also talks about understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom never held a grudge,'' she says. ``When I was ready to
make up or to talk, she would be, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --When you tell her, ``Don't talk to me that way!'' she feels
misunderstood and controlled. Try instead, ``It's OK to be angry
with me, but not to voice it in such a hurtful way.'' Or lighten it
up by saying, ``Phew, that hurt,'' and move on.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't talk too much about your own preteen years. A
12-to14-year-old is too self-absorbed to imagine it's relevant.
</P>
<P>
   --What never to say: ``I know you're upset; it won't last.''
</P>
<P>
   --Most preteens shrink from public affection. Follow your
daughter's lead but don't be the first to withdraw. Keep in mind,
too, that she may still be OK about affection in private. Show
respect by asking first: ``I'm in the mood for a hug. Are you?''
</P>
<P>
   --Many girls are proud of their mothers. That doesn't mean
she'll tell you so or that she won't find something to criticize
you about. You might get less intensity, though.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ During cold weather, don't decide your infant
isn't warm enough by feeling her hands and feet. A baby's
extremities are normally cold. Feel around her belly instead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's first book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is now
available in bookstores. She welcomes letters and comments and can
be reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
