<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6465 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-CHINA-BOS &LR;      03-11 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PLACES TO GET OLD PLATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The table is set with starched linens, freshly polished silver,
and hand-washed crystal and china. When the candles are lighted,
the three-or-four-times-a-year ritual begins _ the family holiday
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   All the participants take their places at the table, unwrap
their embroidered linen napkins, and pass the plates piled with
food.
</P>
<P>
   The hostess holds her breath.
</P>
<P>
   Will Uncle Charlie, who has never met a glass of wine he didn't
enjoy, once again send a plate crashing to the floor? Will he put
yet another mortal dent in Grandma's original set of 14 place
settings, in a pattern that was discontinued 40 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   The hostess can relax. Whatever Uncle Charlie does, a dirge is
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Today there is a growing number of companies that specialize in
locating hard-to-find or discontinued china patterns. Aided by the
Internet, these firms work globally in tracking down a serving
dish, a teacup and saucer, or dinner and salad plates. There's only
one business in New England, but the others are easily reached by
phone, fax, or Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Abbott's in Canton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Corinne Raymond has been in the antiques and tableware
business for 30 years. She now concentrates on discontinued china.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we no longer have a retail room, we have a warehouse
filled with merchandise,'' says Raymond in a phone conversation
from Florida, where she and her husband were on a buying trip.
``Anything we don't have in stock, we can get from our other
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of her customers want to replace a broken piece of china,
fill out a place setting, or add place settings. Some are looking
for a gift, such as the husband who wanted to give his wife two
place settings for Valentine's Day in a pattern they chose when
they married.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's very easy to find what the customer wants and
other times it's not,'' says Raymond. ``Last year a woman called
and wanted 14 place settings in a discontinued pattern. It took
awhile, but we found them. She was so appreciative, which makes
this business so enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   Telephone: 781-828-0340
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Replacements Ltd. in Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   This is the granddaddy of replacement services and the largest
in the world. Founded in 1981 by Bob Page, Replacements has in
stock 83,000 china patterns from 2,286 manufacturers. The firm
draws from 1,000 suppliers nationally who regularly scout for
merchandise at flea markets, estate sales, and auctions. Sales rose
from $150,000 in 1984 to more than $64 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   As for the cost to the customer, prices vary and are based on
supply and demand, according to Mark Donahue, media placement
coordinator at Replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price varies because it depends on the pattern, how much
was manufactured, when it was discontinued, and how popular it
is,'' says Donahue. ``Most of our requests, 80 percent, are for
discontinued patterns. Prices for active patterns are competitive
with department stores, but ours are often cheaper because we buy
directly from the manufacturer. Plus, if a client just wants one
plate or one cup, we provide a single piece. Department stores sell
place settings,'' which include a dinner plate, salad plate, bread
and butter plate, and a teacup and saucer, ``not single pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most popular patterns, he says, are Desert Rose by
Franciscan and Rose Chintz by Johnson Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone: 800-737-5223
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Dishes From the Past in Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   This company, begun in 1993 by 70-year-old Ida May Fleet and now
co-run by her daughter, Jennifer Marcell, has an inventory of more
than 2,000 patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't the biggest, but we're growing,'' says Marcell.
``And we know dishes backward and forward. Plus, we aren't just a
replacement business. We have a retail store, a bridal registry,
and help people mix and match their china over the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   She says mixing patterns has become popular in the past two
years, ever since Martha Stewart gave it the nod. And some young
people still want older patterns because of the designs and
workmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone: 800-984-8801
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
China Trade Ltd. in Chicago
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Rickard started her business 15 years ago when her
stepdaughter inherited her great-grandmother's china and needed
pieces to fill out the place settings. She found the sleuthing
interesting and now concentrates on English and American china.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the smaller replacement dealers are more
knowledgeable,'' says Rickard. ``I've spent a lot of time in the
library.''
</P>
<P>
   She says her customers fall into three categories: a grandmother
or mother looking for replacements of a missing piece or pieces to
fill out place settings for a wedding gift; someone looking for a
piece like one broken at a party; or people with growing families
looking for more place settings to accommodate holiday feasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most young people today are buying cheaper china in the chain
stores,'' says Rickard. ``When a plate chips, they throw it away.
They move around a lot, and things get broken in transit, so they
don't want to be bothered with heirlooms. And nowadays working
couples don't have time to entertain elaborately with china and
crystal _ it's easier to meet friends in a restaurant. And it's a
very different world from when the man bought the car and the
dishwasher, etc. and the woman's domain was the china and
crystal.''
</P>
<P>
   Telephone: 800-295-4200
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Pattern Finders in Port Jefferson, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Stacy Davidson started her business 21 years ago after
leaving her job as an executive in Macy's dinnerware department.
She says many of her customers bought one place setting per year
after they married, and when the time came to add the serving
pieces, the pattern had been discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus husbands are infamous for breakage,'' says Davidson.
``They'll call up hysterical trying to locate a plate or teacup
before they have to tell their wives. There's a lot of sentimental
value attached to dinnerware that's handed down from generation to
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Her customers contact her from all over the country. She
recently found pieces in the same Lenox pattern for a woman on Park
Avenue and one in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman in Kansas told me she'd send me a check as soon as
she mailed her tractor payment.''
</P>
<P>
   Telephone: 800-216-2446
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Jaquelynn's China Matching Service in Milwaukee
</P>
<P>
   Jaquelynn Ives concentrates on 35 lines of English and American
dinnerware. She buys from estate sales, store closeouts, and
private individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think they can make a quick dollar in this business but
it takes a lot of knowledge and you have to have a large inventory
if you're going to fill people's requests and get the merchandise
out the day of a request,'' says Ives.
</P>
<P>
   She says she buys only items that are not chipped or scratched.
The top request from customers is for dinner plates, followed by
the serving pieces and soup and fruit bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone: 800-482-8287
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6467 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-SEX-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-AR     03-11 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-SEX-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... of STDs.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way Murphy, of Burlington, sees it, the numbers showing a
decline in the proportion of teenage boys having sex don't match
the world he lives in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't aware of circumstances in the past, but from what I
see I don't think there's been a decrease at all,'' he says. ``If
they can get it, they're going to do it. If a kid knows he can have
sex with his girlfriend, he's probably not going to turn her down.
Kids think it's better to be having sex than not to be having
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for all of Murphy's incredulity, polls of young people's
attitudes show shifting mores. The title character in the WB
network's prime-time teen drama ``Dawson's Creek'' is not the only
guy who says ``I have no problem being a virgin.'' Ask college
freshmen if they think casual sex is OK, and more of them _ 46
percent of men and 72 percent of women _ say ``no'' than at any
point in the quarter century that the University of California has
been polling on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the number of young adults, 18 to 24, who tell the
University of Chicago's General Social Survey that premarital sex
is always or almost always wrong is rising. It's 25 percent of
young men, up from 16 percent in the early 1970s, and 30 percent of
young women, up from 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I had sex, it was with a girl I loved,'' says
one 18-year-old. ``It was two years with the same girl before we
had sex. We talked about it. It was a mutual thing. It was not
something we regretted afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like more of a relationship first. Then you know the person,
how they are and know how they act afterwards,'' says McCaskill,
the Roxbury 18-year-old. ``If I'm going out, I'm not going to go
too quick. I'm going to take my time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I'm choosing to save myself for my wife is it's
more like a gift,'' says Dolan, the Nahant 17-year-old. ``I want to
be completely in love with her so I'm making love, not having
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   If love has something to do with it, then so does God. ``I'm
part of the Catholic Church, and that's a sin, and I don't want to
disobey God,'' says Matthew Murphy, Ray's 15-year-old brother
</P>
<P>
   ``God is the No. 1 thing in my life,'' says 17-year-old David
Ruff of Stoneham, a member of a charismatic Christian church. ``He
helps me make the right choices. Some guys might say you're a man
if you have sex before marriage, but I think a real man is someone
who waits until after marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   For teens who are having intercourse, the big news is the rise
in condom use. The Urban Institute says sexually experienced
teenage boys are using condoms 69 percent of the times they have
intercourse, up from 56 percent in 1988. And 45 percent are using
condoms with each encounter, up from 33 percent. Black youths use
condoms 73 percent of the time, up from 63 percent in 1988, the
study says. White youths, registering the biggest boost, use them
70 percent of the time, up from 54 percent in 1988. The smallest
change is among Latino youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get no resistance when I talk about condoms,'' says Eugene
Jones, a case manager at Boston High School's health clinic.
``Whether they do it or not, they know they should be using it. The
old reason for not using it _ that it doesn't feel as good _ you
don't hear as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask 16-year-old Darryl Barnes of Dorchester about condoms and he
reaches for the pouch in his backpack that he says he carries with
him ``twenty-four seven,'' 24 hours a day, seven days a week. ``You
never know,'' he says. ``I just keep them on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Murphy's mother gave him condoms to carry in his wallet,
even though she doesn't know, and hasn't asked, if he's ever had
occasion to use them. Most of his friends, he says, carry condoms,
too. ``There was an incident in my school, and it came out that a
kid had sex without using a condom,'' Murphy says. ``He really got
ragged on. If you're going to do it, do it the right way. Kids have
gotten smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Murphy thinks little else has changed among teenage
boys, he says he's not looking for notches on the bedpost. ``I
think there should be some kind of commitment, but it's not stay
together forever. You don't have to be in love to have sex,'' he
says. ``And I think it's bad if you give yourself away a lot before
finding that one person to be in love with.''
</P>
<P>
   In Swampscott, Greg Racki and his girlfriend have talked about
sex. ``We decided we're not ready,'' he says. ``Just being unsure
of where that would lead us. Maybe fear of regret.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TEENAGERS AND SEX &QL; 
(! used as column separator) &QL; 
