<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A KIND OF `HUSH' IN ROBERT PARKER'S WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
HUSH MONEY 
By Robert B. Parker 
Putnam, 309 pp., $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert B. Parker, then a professor at Northeastern University,
began his writing career by producing a novel, published in 1974,
about a private eye who gets involved in an academic matter. It has
been years since Parker has seen the inside of a classroom, but he
hasn't forgotten university politics, and periodically he arranges
for Spenser to return to campus to teach those pointy-headed
professors a thing or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``University politics is very odd,'' observes a good-hearted
professor of English. ``You get a lot of people gathered together
who, if they couldn't do this, really couldn't do anything. They
are given to think that they are both intelligent and important
because they have PhDs and most people don't. Often, though not
always, the PhD does indicate mastery over a subject. But that's
all it indicates, and, unfortunately, many people with PhDs think
it covers a wider area than it does. They think it empowers their
superior insight into government and foreign policy and race
relations and such. In addition these people are put into an
environment where daily, they judge themselves against a standard
set by 18- or 20-year-old kids who know little if anything about
the subject matter in which their professors are expert.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hush Money'' begins with a case of university politics. An
African-American professor, Robinson Nevins, has been denied
tenure, and the reason seems to be a rumor that he was sexually
involved with a male student who committed suicide after the affair
ended. Spenser's sidekick, Hawk (who is also black), was saved from
the streets by Nevins's father, and Hawk doesn't think that's what
happened. Once the sleuthing begins, neither does Spenser, whose
latest adventure turns into a sinister comedy of politics _ or of
political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   The deceased student was producing a publication called
OUTrageous, which was devoted to outing closeted homosexuals. He
was also making a sizable amount of hush money by blackmailing
closeted homosexuals who didn't care to appear in the columns of
OUTrageous.
</P>
<P>
   A second and virtually independent line of the plot concerns a
friend of Spenser's significant other, Susan. K. C. Roth is a
hot-to-trot divorcee who is being stalked. Spenser agrees to look
into the matter, but before long the divorcee has fixated her
attentions on him. Gallantly Spenser spurns her advances because
sex is one thing, and loving Susan is another. So now K. C. Roth
becomes the stalker and Spenser the stalkee.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way there's a defenestration, some double dealing, an
exploded car, and the bad guys' attempt to take Spenser out, which
is a mistake. Despite these pleasures, the plot, or the plots, are
not the strongest suit of this particular outing, and Parker helps
himself to situations, devices, and phenomena that have proved
helpful to him in the past (most recently in ``Night Passage,'' the
first novel featuring his new detective, Jesse Stone). There's an
unusual amount of sex this time, and Parker uses it to cause and
explain too much.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately Parker has long since conditioned his readers to
expect something more intresting than a plot from a Spenser novel.
There's character, for one thing. This book provides a privileged
glimpse into Hawk's youth, and brings back Lee Farrell, the
sympathetic gay cop with whom Spenser sustains a chapter-long campy
conversation. (They meet for a drink in the Limerick, and Spenser's
opening gambit is, ``I figured you'd order a pink lady.'') Susan's
professional psychologizing can sometimes be an irritant, but here
she sounds both sensitive and shrewd, particularly when compared
with a prominent feminist professor: ``There is no liberal agenda,
however goofy, that will not attract her attention. There is no
hypocrisy, however bald, that she will not endure if she can
convince herself that it is in the service of right thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the characters are acting on a skewed agenda, motivated
by political conviction and political correctness. Parker has no
use for this. He gives us Farrell, and also some thoroughly
unsympathetic gays; he gives us a man of conscience in Nevins, and
some very slimy African-American brothers. K. C. Roth is both a
wronged woman and a troublemaker. A dangerous right-winger becomes
almost likable when he risks and loses all for love. Spenser's
moral compass holds true, and every individual is judged on his or
her merits.
</P>
<P>
   With the kind of detail Parker's readers delight in, Spenser
whips up a decent supper out of unlikely ingredients including
linguine and canned black beans, samples some beer, pitches woo
with Susan, identifies a Carol Sloane record, laments the decline
in baseball broadcasting, walks around actual landscapes, and
patronizes real businesses. The university is unidentified, but the
student is named Prentice Lamont, which may provide a clue to
readers with detective instincts of their own.
</P>
<P>
   In one surprising moment, Spenser fancies himself as the movie
star of the '40s, Brian Donlevy. ``I could raise one eyebrow, like
Brian Donlevy, but I didn't very often, because most people didn't
know who Brian Donlevy was, or what I was doing with my face.''
Spenser apparently doesn't know (as film encyclopedist Leonard
Maltin does) that Donlevy wore platform shoes, a toupee, false
teeth, and a girdle. Or maybe he does, and doesn't care, because
that eyebrow trick has got to be worth something.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
