<HEADER>
A6471 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      03-11 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING YOU WANT TO KNOW ABOUT WINDOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Questions commonly heard at the Home Show: Where can I find
comparative information about windows? Which are best in new
construction? Which are best for replacements?
</P>
<P>
   Those are good questions, but there isn't much of an answer,
because most information on windows comes from the manufacturers,
who say, naturally, theirs is the best.
</P>
<P>
   So, what do you do? &QL; 
 &QL; 
New construction windows &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In houses under construction, the Big Three _ Andersen, Pella,
and Marvin _ all make a quality window. One reason all these
windows are quality windows is that they are made of wood. There
are many other companies that make windows; the list is almost
endless.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen uses vinyl to clad the sash (the movable part of the
windows, the frame that holds the glass). Pella uses enameled
aluminum to clad the sash. Each claims its type works best.
</P>
<P>
   There are many styles that use cladding of some kind on one or
both sides of the window. Cladding on the inside allows finishing
of wood on the interior.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever seen a window catalog, you've seen the huge and
bewildering selection of sizes, styles, cladding, and colors.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the windows have low-e double glazing, two layers of
glass with an interior film that increases resistance to heat loss
and gain.
</P>
<P>
   Double-glazed low-e glass is as good as you can get,
insulation-wise, without spending a lot more for the window.
</P>
<P>
   And, a quality wood window, double-glazed, is made by Brosco,
distributed by Brockway-Smith.
</P>
<P>
   If you like the idea of vinyl windows, check out those with a
steel or aluminum skeleton. It is this metal skeleton that gives
vinyl windows their ability to resist warping.
</P>
<P>
   Vinyl windows are built in two different ways: welded (no seams
or other fasteners) and mechanically assembled with screws or
bolts. The mechanical gurus think that mechanical assembly is best
because there are no welded seams to break, and such frames can be
disassembled to allow changing of glazing (glass).
</P>
<P>
   As for metal, it is this handyman's feeling that they should be
avoided, except for storms. Even though metal windows have a
thermal break between inner and outer surfaces to prevent loss of
heat and the dreaded sweating that so many metal windows get, metal
is just not the best of materials for a window in a house.
</P>
<P>
   As for styles, take a look at double hung (those that slide up
and down), casements (those hinged on one side and open like a
door), horizontal sliders (avoid them, they don't work very well),
awning (hinged at the top) and open outward; hopper (hinged at the
bottom and open inward), and the wide variety of picture windows,
bow windows, and bay windows.
</P>
<P>
   While double hungs are most popular, casements are good on
certain style housesand are fast gaining in popularity. For good
reason, too; casements close more tightly, casements can be opened
fully, (only half of the double hungs and horizontal sliders can be
opened), and casements, when open, act as baffles to draw fresh air
into the house. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Replacement windows &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What about the replacement windows? Americans seem hipped on
replacement window, probably because they have been convinced that
they need them.
</P>
<P>
   Before you consider replacement windows, ask yourself, do you
really need them, and if so, why?
</P>
<P>
   You might be surprised at the reasons people choose replacment
windows: 1. The old ones are leaky and drafty. 2. The old ones are
just tired looking, and I want a new look. 3. I'm tired of putting
up and taking down the storm windows. 4. I'm tired of washing four
surfaces of glass with my old windows and storms. 5. I don't like
the weights, ropes, and pulleys. 6. I'm tired of sweating windows.
7. This is the best one: I want tilt-outs for easy washing.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever turns you on, I suppose, but consider the possibility
that replacements are not needed unless the old windows are
actually broken beyond reasonable repair or are rotting. These are
legitimate reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Another good reason: The old windows are cheap and ineffective,
a common component of many houses built in the last 30 or 40 years.
Too often builders bought cheap windows as a way to save costs. It
was good for the builder, not good for the new homeowner.
</P>
<P>
   Still another good reason is if you have steel casements, which
not only don't insulate very well but also sweat like crazy in
winter because the metal is just as cold on the inside as on the
inside.
</P>
<P>
   But if your old windows are of reasonably good quality, close
well, and operate without huffing and puffing and breaking
fingernails, they can be weatherstripped to make them airtight and
weathertight, and equipped with a top-quality storm window that is
equally airtight, all of which will achieve close to what you would
get in a replacement window.
</P>
<P>
   The replacement-window business is huge, and the varieties of
styles and types, including vinyl cladding and other perks, are as
great as in the new construction window business.
</P>
<P>
   And a good thing about replacement windows is that most
companies manufacture and install just the sash, not the whole
window, at considerably less cost than a whole window. Besides,
entire windows seldom need replacing.
</P>
<P>
   The sash is the movable part of the window, the frame that holds
the glass. This applies to any style windows, including
double-hungs and casements. These replacement sash cost generally
from $150 to $200-plus per window, and installation is less
complicated and costly than removing and installing a whole new
window: casing, frame, sash, and all.
</P>
<P>
   Replacements come in vinyl clad wood, aluminum clad wood, plain
wood, and vinyl. They are all double-glazed, and some have the
low-e option. Most have the much-desired tilt-out feature.
</P>
<P>
   As with new construction windows, wood or vinyl-clad or
aluminum-clad wood are the best. If you choose vinyl, specify those
with an aluminum or steel skeleton to resist warping. And be aware
that the frames of vinyl windows are extra wide, and any storm you
may want to keep cannot easily be taken out and washed.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the reasons some window installers say you don't
need a storm with a double-glazed window, but if you already have
the storms, why not keep them; you will get triple glazing and the
insulative value of both windows will increase by about a third.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with double glazed windows, in both new construction
and replacement types, is that, up to now, the glass was difficult
or impossible to remove and replace in case of breakage or fogging.
</P>
<P>
   When that occurred, the movable sash (the frame that holds the
glass) had to be replaced, an expensive proposition unless the
window was in warranty.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, double-glazed windows cannot be fixed by the
homeowner, who used to do it easily on his single-glazed windows.
That was in a simpler time.
</P>
<P>
   It is fervently hoped that this can be corrected, so that the
homeowner, if he feels like it, can indeed replace just the glass,
not the sash, and certainy not the whole window. In a nutshell,
that is the lowdown on windows in new construction.
</P>
<P>
   Anything else? Yessir. Keep those old or new windows washed and
sparkling, and they will raise your morale summer and winter.
</P>
<P>
   And, admittedly, the tilt-outs make washing a breeze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
