<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6475 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STANDBY-FOOD-AZR &LR;      03-11 4570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANDBY-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVER-FAIL RECIPES ARE TRIED AND-TRUE FAVORITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Dependable. Tested. Tried and true.
</P>
<P>
   When we asked you to send in your favorite standby recipes, you
sent us the favorites you turn to again and again in a variety of
situations: for every day, for snacks, for entertaining. Some of
the recipes have been favorites for decades.
</P>
<P>
   They opened a window into pantries. The recipes show what real
people keep on hand. From this informal survey, we would have to
say that the frozen item that gets used most often is chicken
breasts. In pantries, the No. 1 item that sits on the shelf is _
yes, an old favorite _ canned, condensed ``cream of'' soups,
especially cream of mushroom soup. Packets of onion soup mix are
popular, too.
</P>
<P>
   By culinary coincidence, two of the first three recipes to
arrive were virtually the same dish: chicken breasts combined with
a can of whole cranberry sauce and a small bottle of French or
Catalina salad dressing. We tried it, and the results are a solid
``Wow!''
</P>
<P>
   We also received several versions of enchilada casseroles and
two near-identical recipes for a casserole of hamburger and
vegetables with a mashed-potato topping.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is soul food pure and simple!'' Betty Wikenhauser wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One warning: We didn't ask for low-fat recipes. Some are more
healthful than others. Some are one-dish meals. A few are
vegetarian, many are economical to make, almost all are versatile.
You can use your favorite fat-lowering techniques (such as
substituting reduced-fat cheeses) when you make your own versions
of these dishes.
</P>
<P>
   A sincere thank you to everyone who sent in recipes. More of
your recipes are available at www.azcentral.com/food/standby.shtml
_ ``The Arizona Republic's'' Web site.  &QL; 
RECIPES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Judy Wilson: ``Here is my favorite all-time standby recipe.
This is so easy to throw together. I have even put frozen chicken
breasts in the baking dish and just poured the sauce over them and
baked it without thawing the chicken _ and it turned out super!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
From Anna Fleetwood: ``This is fast, easy, delicious, and everyone
raves about it. Good for company or just about any time.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
CRANBERRY CHICKEN &QL; 
(From Judy Wilson and Anna Fleetwood)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 399 calories, 20 g fat, 81 mg
cholesterol, 35 g carbohydrates, 1.4 g fiber, 21 g protein, 523 mg
sodium, 44 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 to 2 pounds chicken pieces (can be skinless or skin-on,
boneless or bone-in)
</P>
<P>
   1 can (16 ounces) whole berry cranberry sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle (8 ounces) French or Catalina salad dressing
</P>
<P>
   1 package (1 1/2 ounces) dried onion soup mix (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange chicken in a 9- by 13-inch baking pan. In a medium bowl,
mix the rest of the ingredients. Pour mixture over the chicken and
bake, 45 minutes for boneless chicken or 1 hour for bone-in
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Note: One version of this recipe called for onion soup mix in
addition to the cranberries and salad dressing. Both were good. The
one with the soup mix is darker in color, tastes saltier, and has
1,067 mg of sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This recipe is a favorite with our family, from adults to
children. I always keep cooked chicken ready to put this together
quickly for guests,'' Mary Hart wrote. ``Also, you can make ahead,
refrigerate, and have ready to put into oven when entertaining.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN DIVAN &QL; 
(From Mary Hart)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 423 calories, 26 g fat, 75 mg
cholesterol, 21 g carbohydrates, 4 mg fiber, 28 g protein, 677 mg
sodium, 54 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 packages (10 ounces each) frozen broccoli, cooked but firm, OR
2 large stalks of fresh broccoli, steamed
</P>
<P>
   4 chicken breast halves, cooked and boned, cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 can (10.75 ounces) cream of chicken soup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded sharp Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bread crumbs or stuffing mix
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon margarine
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange cooked or steamed broccoli in greased 7- by 11-inch or
9- by 13-inch pan, with crowns facing edges of pan. Place chicken
on top.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine soup, mayonnaise, lemon juice and curry
powder and pour on top of chicken. Sprinkle with cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Combine bread crumbs and margarine and sprinkle over all. Bake
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This recipe was given to me by a friend in New Jersey. I like
to make it, as it is easy, and I serve it with an Italian salad and
Italian bread. It is very tasty,'' Rose DePalma wrote. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CASSEROLE ITALIANO &QL; 
(From Rose DePalma)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 472 calories, 35 g fat, 125 mg
cholesterol, 8 g carbohydrates, 1 g fiber, 30 g protein, 1,277 mg
sodium, 68 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds ground round
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon oregano
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce package elbow macaroni, cooked according to package
directions
</P>
<P>
   1 can (3 ounces) button mushrooms, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 can (8.75 ounces) tomato soup, undiluted
</P>
<P>
   1 medium tomato, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, saute onion and green pepper in butter over
medium heat until tender. Add ground round, cooking until brown.
Add salt, pepper, oregano and Worcestershire sauce. In a 2
1/2-quart casserole, combine cooked macaroni, ground round mixture,
mushrooms, soup and chopped tomato.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and bake for 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven, sprinkle cheese on top and bake 5 minutes
more, or until cheese is melted and brown.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``This is my favorite standby recipe,'' Kathy Cutler writes. ``You
can change the ingredients to suit your liking, like pork, beef or
veal for the chicken, and any kind of canned fruit for the peaches.
It's quick, easy and filling, and you can reduce the fat and
calories by substituting a vegetable spray to cook the meat and
using canned fruit in their own juices.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN WITH PEACHES AND RICE (with photo) &QL; 
(From Kathy Cutler)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 549 calories, 4 g fat, 96 mg
cholesterol, 82 g carbohydrates, 0.8 g fiber, 45 g protein, 128 mg
sodium, 6 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1 can (16 ounces) peaches in light syrup, cut into bite-size
pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 boneless, skinless chicken breasts, cooked
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked white rice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a small pot, simmer peaches with juice, uncovered, over
medium heat for 15 minutes, until slightly reduced. Slice prepared
chicken into bite-size pieces.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium serving dish, combine the chicken, rice and peaches.
Season as desired with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever I am, people normally have eggs and rice,'' Cynthia
Clements observes. ``For vegetables, I use whatever is available
and seems good, usually carrots and garlic, green onions if I have
it. The rice should be prepared and in the fridge for an hour or
two, but you don't have to if you don't have time. . . . The only
other thing you need to know is not to add soy sauce until it is
finished, and to have the oil be hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Clements adapted her recipe from ``Cooking Light'' magazine. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EGG FRIED RICE &QL; 
(From Cynthia Clements)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 395 calories, 9 g fat, 90 mg
cholesterol, 65 g carbohydrates, 3.4 g fiber, 13 g protein, 596 mg
sodium, 20 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cold, cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup green peas
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bean sprouts
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   Combine the sesame oil, eggs and egg whites in a small bowl;
stir well and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat vegetable oil in a large non-stick skillet or wok over
medium-high heat. Add egg mixture and stir-fry 2 minutes. Add rice;
stir-fry 3 minutes. Add green peas, salt and pepper; stir-fry 5
minutes. Add bean sprouts and green onions; stir-fry 2 minutes.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN ENCHILADA CASSEROLE &QL; 
(From Elaine Bell)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 1,105 calories, 57 g fat, 269 mg
cholesterol, 56 g carbohydrates, 3.8 g fiber, 87 g protein, 1,747
mg sodium, 47 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   4 chicken breasts, poached and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 can (4 ounces) chopped green chiles
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 chopped Italian or curly-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 jar (2 ounces) chopped pimento
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups shredded Jack or pepper-Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   8 flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   1 can (10.75 ounces) cream of chicken soup mixed with 1/2 can of
milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine the chicken with the chiles, onion,
garlic, parsley, pimento and 1 1/2 cups of the cheese. Divide the
chicken mixture among the 8 tortillas. Roll tortillas and place
seam-side down in a 9- by 13-inch pan. Spread soup mixture over
roll-ups and top with the remaining cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 30 minutes. Use lower-fat cheese in this recipe for fewer
calories and fats, Elaine Bell said. Also note that these are large
servings of two enchiladas each.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``This recipe was given to me years ago by my mother, who wasn't
one for spending hours in the kitchen,'' Roberta Dress writes.
``She relied often on this since we resided in a small town in
Illinois and getting fresh vegetables was nearly impossible. I've
since relied on it whenever I want a different vegetable to
serve.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
CELERY CASSEROLE (with photo) &QL; 
(From Roberta Dress)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 379 calories, 23 g fat, 43 mg
cholesterol, 38 g carbohydrates, 3.4 g fiber, 6 g protein, 918 mg
sodium, 55 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups celery, sliced 1/4-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can sliced water chestnuts
</P>
<P>
   1 can (10.75 ounces) cream of chicken soup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttery crackers (such as Ritz), crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces slivered or sliced almonds
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Cook celery in boiling, salted
water in a medium saucepan and heat to boiling. Cook for seven
minutes. Do not overcook. Drain. Combine in a large bowl with water
chestnuts and soup. Pour into greased, 1 1/2-quart casserole and
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium skillet, melt butter or margarine. Stir in cracker
crumbs and almonds. Pour over celery mixture. Bake, uncovered, for
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Original recipe calls for 2 cups of crushed Ritz crackers.
We tested the recipe with half the amount, with good results. To
further cut down on fat and calories, cut down on the amount of
butter.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 side-dish servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``I first made this recipe 25 years ago for my oldest daughter's
engagement dinner,'' Rosemarie Cuchna writes. ``I always serve it
with a wild rice blend and either asparagus or broccoli. Lately, I
have added dilled and buttered carrot slices. I make dinner rolls
and a spinach, mandarin-orange salad with a sweet-sour vinaigrette
to go with it. It is such a great dinner. Why change it?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN BREASTS IN WINE SAUCE &QL; 
(From Rosemarie Cuchna)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 161 calories, 6 g fat, 60 mg
cholesterol, 2 g carbohydrates, 0.1 g fiber, 21 g protein, 157 mg
sodium, 38 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   12 boneless, skinless chicken breast halves
</P>
<P>
   1 can (10.75 ounces) cream of mushroom soup
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   3-ounce can mushroom stems and pieces with juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   Paprika
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Place chicken breasts in one layer
in a large casserole dish coated with non-stick spray. Combine the
soup, sour cream, mushrooms and wine in a medium bowl. Pour over
chicken, dust with paprika, and bake for 1 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My Ham and Cheese Strata has never failed me,'' Linda Burgess
wrote. ``It's easy to make and gets rave reviews from family and
friends. I love the fact that you make it the night before and just
pop it in the oven the next morning.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
HAM AND CHEESE STRATA (with photo) &QL; 
(From Linda Burgess)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 406 calories, 25 g fat, 175 mg
cholesterol, 27 g carbohydrates, 0.9 g fiber, 18 g protein, 1,008
mg sodium, 55 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   16 slices white bread, crusts removed
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces extra sharp Cheddar cheese, shredded
</P>
<P>
   3 cups diced ham or turkey ham
</P>
<P>
   8 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   5 cups cornflakes, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 sticks (3/4 cup) melted butter
</P>
<P>
   Coat a 9- by- 13-inch pan with non-stick spray. Place 8 slices
of bread in single layer on bottom of the pan. Spread the cheese
and ham on top. Place remaining bread slices on top of cheese and
ham.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, beat the eggs. Add the milk, mustard and salt
and beat until combined. Pour mixture over the ingredients in the
pan. Cover and refrigerate 12 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   One hour before baking, combine the cornflakes and butter and
spread over top. Cover and place back in refrigerator for another
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Bake, uncovered, for 1 hour and 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Let stand 5 minutes before cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 to 15 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Hughes said she has been serving her version of this
recipe for 30 years: The original was in a ``What's Cooking in
Puerto Vallarta'' cookbook she bought at the airport there in 1969.
``It is so easy to prepare for 10 or 15 or more guests at breakfast
or brunch.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
BISCUITS WITH EGGS AND MUSHROOM SAUCE &QL; 
(From Margaret Hughes)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 551 calories, 35 g fat, 156 mg
cholesterol, 47 g carbohydrates, 0.2 mg fiber, 12 g protein, 1,083
mg sodium, 57 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1 can (10.75 ounces) cream of mushroom soup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 small can (4 or 4.25 ounces) mushroom pieces, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   6 hard-boiled eggs, sliced or chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 slices bacon, cooked to crispy, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   10 freshly baked canned or homemade biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Mix all ingredients except biscuits together in a large bowl.
Place in a casserole dish and bake for 30 minutes. Serve over
biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 10 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been a `count-on that one' in a pinch,''
Elaine Bell wrote. ``The ingredients are simple and I have them on
hand.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOMATO ZUCCHINI TART &QL; 
(From Elaine Bell)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 169 calories, 10 g fat, 52 mg
cholesterol, 11 g carbohydrates, 1.6 mg fiber, 10 g protein, 326 mg
sodium, 54 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
Crust:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups grated raw potato, squeezed of excess liquid
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unbleached flour
</P>
<P>
   Dash salt
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups grated cheese, such as Cheddar, Swiss, mozzarella or
provolone
</P>
<P>
   2 cups thinly sliced zucchini
</P>
<P>
   3 large tomatoes, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the potato, onion, egg, flour and salt. Pat mixture into
a well-greased 9-inch pie pan. Bake for 30 minutes, until edges are
brown. Remove from oven.
</P>
<P>
   Make a layer with half of the cheese in the crust. Arrange the
zucchini slices on top of the cheese, then a layer of tomatoes.
Sprinkle the basil, oregano, garlic powder, salt, pepper and onion
on top. Top with the remaining cheese. Bake for 45 minutes, until
golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``A tasty way to get your daily dose of fiber is to prepare a batch
of lentil puree to store in the refrigerator to have on hand for
quick and easy dishes,'' Maxine Lang writes. ``Delicious as a
filling for burritos and tacos, as a topping for quesadillas and
nachos, or as a dip for corn chips and veggies.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
LENTIL PUREE (with photo) &QL; 
(From Maxine Lang)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 102 calories, 1 g fat, 0
cholesterol, 18 g carbohydrates, 8.9 g fiber, 8 g protein, 107 mg
sodium, 3 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried lentils
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (4 ounces each) chopped green chiles
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dried cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Bring 5 cups of water to a boil in a large pot.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse and drain lentils, removing any stones that may be
present. Add lentils to water. Cover and simmer 40 minutes over
medium heat, until tender. Remove from heat and allow to cool
slightly in the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients in a food processor or blender. Divide
into two batches if necessary. Puree until smooth. If puree is too
thick, add 1/4 cup of water.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 16 1/2-cup servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Easiest dinner in the world,'' Judi Key writes. Her version of
this dish included a can of any kind of vegetables. Betty
Wikenhauser's recipe is ``soul food, pure and simple!'' she writes.
``This is my recipe I can count on when I have some hamburger in
the fridge and stand there wondering how to use it. This reminds me
of Depression days when my mother would give me two dimes and send
me to the little store at the end of the alley to buy a pound of
hamburger. This was one of her ways of using it, and it still
tastes good to me!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
DEPRESSION DINNER &QL; 
(From Betty Wikenhauser and Judi Key)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 333 calories, 27 g fat, 81 mg
cholesterol, 8 g carbohydrates, .9 g fiber, 14 g protein, 208 mg
sodium, 74 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Use leanest ground beef to reduce fat.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground beef
</P>
<P>
   2 cups well-drained canned or frozen vegetables, such as chopped
spinach (optional)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups prepared mashed potatoes (instant or homemade; recipe
follows for real ones)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   Mashed potatoes from scratch
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 large baking potatoes, peeled and cubed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   To prepare casserole: Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in skillet. Add onion and cook over medium heat until
tender. Remove onion and add meat, cooking until browned. Drain fat
well.
</P>
<P>
   In a greased 1 1/2 to 2-quart casserole dish or 8-inch square
pan, place the meat in a layer, followed by the onion, then the
vegetable (if using), then the mashed potatoes. Smooth the top of
the potatoes. Scatter bits of butter over the top. (Other optional
topping: Fresh-grated Parmesan or Romano cheese).
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 30 to 35 minutes, until heated through and edges are
lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare potatoes: Place potatoes in a medium saucepan. Add
enough cold water to cover by an inch. Bring to a boil. Cook for 15
minutes, or until potatoes are tender when pierced with a fork.
Drain potatoes and return to pot. Whip with a beater, or mash with
a potato masher for a chunky texture. Add remaining ingredients and
stir until combined.
</P>
<P>
   Casserole makes 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there ever a husband who doesn't want a full cookie jar!?''
wrote Barbara Wilson. ``Here is my standby, and even if I try a new
one, it doesn't work.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
SCHOOLHOUSE RANGER COOKIES  &QL; 
(From Barbara Wilson)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 46 calories, 2 g fat, 8 mg
cholesterol, 7 g carbohydrates, .2 g fiber, 1 g protein, 47 mg
sodium, 39 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 cups rolled oats
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cornflakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coconut
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup walnuts, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, beat together butter and sugars until mixture
looks creamy. Beat in eggs. In a separate bowl, sift flour, baking
powder, baking soda and salt. Stir into creamed mixture. Gently
stir in the vanilla, cereals, coconut and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Drop by rounded teaspoonfuls onto ungreased cookie sheet. Bake 8
to 10 minutes, until golden.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 9 dozen small cookies. Serving size: 1 cookie. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This recipe is a family favorite and is made often around our
house. It is a simple one-pot dish and everyone always goes back
for seconds. Recipe can easily be doubled,'' Melynn Reid wrote. &QL; 
 &QL; 
POTATO CHOWDER &QL; 
(From Melynn Reid)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 263 calories, 21 g fat, 49 mg
cholesterol, 16 g carbohydrates, 1.5 g fiber, 4 g protein, 792 mg
sodium, 70 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   4 cups potatoes, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup celery, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 chicken bouillon cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon parsley (optional)
</P>
<P>
   In large pot, combine potatoes, onion, celery, bouillon cubes,
garlic salt, salt and pepper and 3{ cups water. Stir well. Bring to
a boil. Reduce heat to medium and simmer for 15 minutes, or until
the vegetables are tender but not mushy. Stir in butter.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix sour cream and flour. Add to vegetable
mixture in pot. Use a potato masher to mash the mixture slightly.
Simmer over low heat a few more minutes, until heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with parsley, if desired. Serve with bread or crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I often make this fudge for bake sales and get frequent
requests for the recipe,'' Lillian Killian said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEVER-FAIL FUDGE &QL; 
(From Lillian Killian)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 53 calories, 2 g fat, 1 mg
cholesterol, 9 g carbohydrates, 0.4 g fiber, 1 g protein, 4 mg
sodium, 32 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1 2/3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped nuts (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   Combine the evaporated milk with sugar in a medium saucepan and
heat to boiling. Cook 5 minutes over medium heat, stirring
constantly. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Add remaining ingredients, stirring until the marshmallows are
melted. Pour into a buttered 8- or 9-inch square pan. Allow to cool
completely before cutting into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 64 1-inch squares. Serving size: 1 square. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a recipe we have had in the family for years and is
always a favorite when I serve it,'' Ruth Gasbarra wrote. ``Can be
served with all meats. I have tried this recipe with chicken broth,
but the beef broth remains our favorite. I usually double this
recipe for my family, as it is also very good left over.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
GASBARRA'S STANDBY &QL; 
(From Ruth Gasbarra)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 180 calories, 10 g fat, 25 mg
cholesterol, 18 g carbohydrates, 1.1 g fiber, 5 g protein, 515 mg
sodium, 5 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1 green pepper, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 can (4.25 ounces) sliced mushrooms with liquid
</P>
<P>
   1 can (8.75 ounces) beef broth
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup rice (NOT Minute Rice, but Uncle Ben's converted works
very well)
</P>
<P>
   In a casserole dish that can go on top of the stove and in the
oven, saute green pepper and onion in butter or margarine. Add
mushrooms, beef broth, and rice. Bake, uncovered, for 1 hour at 350
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 5 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is a recipe that is no problem to prepare and very
versatile,'' wrote Grace Goldstein-Roth. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SWEET AND SOUR MEATBALLS &QL; 
(From Grace Goldstein-Roth)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 544 calories, 40 g fat, 130 mg
cholesterol, 22 g carbohydrates, 1.2 g fiber, 24 g protein, 460 mg
sodium, 66 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper and/or Worcestershire sauce to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 can (10 3/4 ounces) tomato soup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Optional additions: Fresh sliced mushrooms, chopped green
pepper, pineapple chunks
</P>
<P>
   Combine beef, egg, water, bread crumbs, salt, pepper and/or
Worcestershire sauce, and onions in a large bowl. Roll mixture into
walnut-sized balls.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons oil over medium heat, and add a single layer
of meatballs. Cook on all sides until light brown. Continue until
all balls have been cooked, adding oil as necessary. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepot, combine soup, lemon juice, and brown sugar
and bring to a simmer. Taste and adjust with more lemon juice or
brown sugar if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Place meatballs in soup mixture and simmer for half an hour over
a low flame. If using any of the optional ingredients, add them,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Serve over rice, noodles or mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Standby favorite of my mother's kitchen and also mine,'' Lucile
Lay Kral writes. ``This cake can be adapted to coffee cake,
upside-down, etc.'' We think it also would make a great base for
strawberry shortcake. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOT MILK CAKE &QL; 
(From Lucile Lay Kral)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per piece: 104 calories, 3 g fat, 24 mg
cholesterol, 19 g carbohydrates, 0 fiber, 2 g protein, 100 mg
sodium, 21 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons shortening
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Lightly grease an 8- by 8-inch
square pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine flour, baking powder and salt. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, beat the eggs and sugar until slightly
thickened and creamy, about one minute. Add flour mixture and
continue to beat until combined.
</P>
<P>
   In a microwave-safe container, microwave shortening and milk
together until milk is hot and the shortening has melted, about one
minute. Add vanilla. Beat into the batter.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into prepared pan and bake 35 minutes, until golden brown
on top and toothpick inserted in center comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 pieces. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``My special favorite recipe is great to serve family and/or guests
because it can be prepared a day or two in advance,'' Wilda Lack
says. ``No last-minute fuss.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN SPECTACULAR  &QL; 
(From Wilda Lack)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 391 calories, 21 g fat, 74 mg
cholesterol, 24 g carbohydrates, 2.8 mg fiber, 27 g protein, 710 mg
sodium, 48 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cooked chicken (about 1 3/4 pounds boneless breasts),
cubed
</P>
<P>
   1 package seasoned long grain and wild rice, prepared
</P>
<P>
   14 1/2-ounce can French-style green beans, drained
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can sliced water chestnuts, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 can (10 3/4 ounces) condensed cream of mushroom soup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cheddar or cheddar-Jack cheese, shredded
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine all ingredients except cheese. Place in
greased 9- by 13-inch pan and top with the cheese. Bake, uncovered,
for 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   There are several sizes of packages of long grain and wild rice
mixes, generally ranging from 4 to 6 ounces. We tested this recipe
with a 5-ounce package.
</P>
<P>
   Original recipe called for 1 cup mayonnaise. We tested it with
1/2 cup and felt it was sufficiently moist.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 main-course portions. &QL;
</P>
