<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MOLONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEFTAINS' LATEST: OLD MUSIC, NEW FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chieftains have always aimed high. From the start, they
sought to bring Irish traditional music out of the pubs and into
theaters and opera houses around the world. They've done that with
style. They've also aimed high with their albums, which have
included guest shots by everyone from Sinead O'Connor to the
Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   Their latest disc, ``Tears of Stone,'' may be their most
ambitious yet in a 36-year career that has garnered seven Grammy
Awards. It sweetly marries many leading female singers _ including
Joni Mitchell, Bonnie Raitt, Natalie Merchant, Joan Osborne,
Loreena McKennitt, and O'Connor _ with Irish songs, most of them
love songs, some going back hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these songs I learned growing up. I learned them from
my mother and my grandmother,'' Paddy Moloney, the leader of the
Chieftains, said during lunch at the Ritz-Carlton this week, in
advance of a concert Sunday at Symphony Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is perfect. Female artists are making inroads like
never before _ witness the abundance of female winners at this
year's Grammy Awards _ and music insiders feel this could be the
best-selling Chieftains album in their history. That means it would
surpass the 500,000 sales of their 1995 CD, ``The Long Black
Veil,'' which paired them with the Stones, O'Connor, Mark Knopfler,
Tom Jones, and others.
</P>
<P>
   But while women are the focus of the new release (``I'm
fascinated by the sound of female voices with the Chieftains,''
says Moloney), he adds that this ``was not done for the money, but
is very much a friendship album.''
</P>
<P>
   Moloney has known some of these women for years. McKennitt, the
bewitching Canadian world-music phenomenon, once toured Japan with
the Chieftains. Raitt has been a supporter since Moloney popped
onstage with her two years ago, backing her on penny whistle.
O'Connor has sung with the Chieftains off and on for the last
decade, while Sissel (who sang on the ``Titanic'' soundtrack) has
toured with the group.
</P>
<P>
   The music _ chosen mostly from Moloney's suggestions _ is as
worthy as the concept. The sensuous, dusky-voiced Osborne sings the
classic ``Raglan Road.'' Merchant sings the haunting ``The Lowlands
of Holland.'' Mitchell adds her own ``Magdalene Laundries'' (a true
story about a convent where unwed mothers used to be cared for),
Mary Chapin Carpenter sings beautifully in Gaelic on her selection,
``Deserted Soldier,'' and Japanese singer Akiko Yano performs
``Sake in the Jar,'' a takeoff of the famed tune, ``Whiskey in the
Jar.''
</P>
<P>
   The album has its share of fun, but also has a poignant side.
Most laudably, the Chieftains do not crowd the guests, preferring
to add background embellishments rather than scream forth with ego.
``It's not us playing and them joining in,'' says Moloney of the
six-piece ensemble. ``It's them singing and us joining in. But
every track was an event. It was a big happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the respect that musicians have for the Chieftains that
Osborne, after she cut her track in New York, traveled to Ireland
to hang out with the band. While they were quaffing a few at the
Roundwood Inn in County Wicklow, Merchant walked in with her new
manager, Cambridge-based Gary Smith, co-founder of Fort Apache
studio. ``You know, Natalie, you should do a song on Paddy's
album,'' said Osborne. Merchant quickly complied, recording her
song in two takes.
</P>
<P>
   The most unusual number finds Brenda Fricker (who won an Oscar
for best supporting actress in the film ``My Left Foot'') reciting
the William Butler Yeats poem, ``Never Give All the Heart.'' Also
unusual is the inclusion of the overexposed Irish tune ``Danny
Boy'' by jazz vocalist Diana Krall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told people a hundred times that we wouldn't record
`Danny Boy,' '' says Moloney. ```Daniel Boone' is what I used to
call it. But Diana did an absolutely lovely job with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chieftains' current tour includes two guest performers:
fiddler Eileen Ivers, who played on the new CD, and singer Yvonne
McMahon, a member of the road crew.
</P>
<P>
   Old music and new friends _ a combination that has kept the
Grammy-winning Chieftains clicking for all these years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
