<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-11 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINING THE EAR TO HEAR THE SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was intrigued by a talk being given at the Waldorf School, a
private elementary school in Beverly. Its title was ``The Twelve
Senses.''
</P>
<P>
   We all know the usual five suspects _ touch, smell, taste,
sight, and hearing _ but what could the other seven possibly be? As
I drove to Beverly I turned over candidates in my mind. Intuition,
surely. It's often considered a sixth sense. Then a sense of humor,
and perhaps a sense of timing to describe what determines the
different pace at which each of us operates. I also came up with a
sense of empathy, our means of identifying with another person, and
a sense of sympathy, the process by which we feel compassion for
others.
</P>
<P>
   I was up to 10. I added a sense of excitement, the biological
source of our enthusiasm for life, and ended with a sense of self,
an inner compass that informs us that we're more than the sum of
messages from our culture. By the time I arrived, I figured I could
give the lecture.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, was I wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolf Steiner, the man upon whose philosophy the school is
based, was operating on an entirely different level. His 12 senses
included the basic five, and four more: a sense of balance, a sense
of movement, a sense of life, and a sense of temperature. But it
was the last three that captured my attention, what he considered
``higher, spiritual'' senses that we achieve with adulthood: a
sense of the word, the thought, the ego.
</P>
<P>
   We are born, of course, hearing all the sounds that surround us,
becoming more and more attuned to the spoken word as we grow older.
Then we learn to listen for the thought behind the words, the
larger meaning intended by the speaker. At this level, many of us
excel at picking up information and formulating it into concepts
and theories.
</P>
<P>
   Although our culture considers a rational understanding of what
we hear the goal of education, Steiner didn't stop there. He went
on to postulate ``a sense of ego,'' an awareness that beyond
particular words and thoughts dwells a being, a person with hopes
and dreams, a spirit, and a soul. At Steiner's highest level of
functioning, we attune ourselves to that reality, using words and
thoughts as a bridge between listener and speaker. We hear in such
a way that boundaries dissolve, creating an awareness and openness
to the depths of the other.
</P>
<P>
   I think we all reach that level of functioning in the early
throes of love, whether for a mate or a young child. The silliest
comment or the most trivial remark seems to illuminate the soul of
those we love passionately, as if every utterance were a pathway to
the core of the beloved. Yet we rarely manage to hold on to that
degree of responsiveness. We get so caught up in making judgments
or rehearsing our own replies that we're lucky if we even catch
another's meaning.
</P>
<P>
   I want to learn how to reverse that.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, I've just begun attending a Circle of Quiet at our
Unitarian-Universalist Church, which is held every other Monday
night. After a period of listening to music in silence,
participants are directed to talk to one another, without
interruption or eye contact, for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   We sit in pairs, side by side, and listen to each other. As the
first person speaks, the listener doesn't comfort or nod assent.
She needn't formulate advice or encourage the speaker with nods or
sympathetic noises. In fact, during those 10 minutes, the listener
is expressly forbidden to give any feedback at all. It's a strange
and unnerving experience for both parties, not only to speak and
listen without interruption, but not to worry about how the other
person might be feeling about the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Last time, I sat with a woman I hardly knew. As I listened, I
became intensely aware of her tone of voice, her moments of
hesitation, the places where she felt confident or uneasy. I could
hear her desire for understanding and connection as clear as a
bell. When our mutual sharing was completed, I felt as if I'd made
contact with the being who inhabited her depths and embraced her
spirit. The experience made me aware of how infrequently I reach
that level with my family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old concept, what our minister calls ``sacred
listening.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 13th-century poet Rumi described it: ``Out beyond ideas
of wrongdoing and rightdoing, there is a field. When the soul lies
down in that grass, the world is too full to talk about. Ideas,
language, even the phrase each other doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
