A6483 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-SEX-2TAKES-ART-B     03-11 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-SEX-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STD FEARS ARE CHANGING LIFE _ AND SEX _ FOR TEEN BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Includes statistics text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Gregory Racki plays wide receiver on Swampscott High
School's football team, and all the guys he hangs with are
athletes, too. A while back, one of his buddies confided that he
and his girlfriend had been having sex for six months. The friend
told nobody else.
</P>
<P>
   What's this? No locker room bragging about sex? No stereotypical
``jock'' out to ``score'' off the field as well as on? Well, not
the way 17-year-old Greg Racki tells it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one person that did it made it a total secret,'' Racki
says. ``Kids aren't in such a rush anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Racki's health teacher shakes his head as he listens to three
boys talking about sex. ``I'm thinking what it was like when I was
their age,'' says 46-year-old Buck Harris. ``It was the more
notches you got on your belt, the better. That was in the late
'60s. The norm was that having sex with lots of people was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But times are changing. Recent headlines alleging high school
rapes in Brookline and Falmouth may serve as grim reminders that
harassing girls and talking trash _ and, sometimes, much worse _
are still facts of teen life. But recent surveys reveal something
else, too: Fewer teenage boys report having had sexual intercourse,
and those who have done so report having fewer partners. As for
condom use, it's increasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generation has almost been tagged the sex generation, with
MTV and the music,'' says 17-year-old James Dolan of Nahant.
``Everything seems oriented around sex. It's kind of funny that
it's gone down.''
</P>
<P>
   The shifts, to be sure, are modest (and rates of teen sexual
activity are still higher than in the early 1970s), but the
declines show up on survey after survey. They jibe with polls that
find young people's social attitudes increasingly conservative.
They jibe with data recording decreases in teen pregnancy and most
major sexually transmitted diseases, albeit with some sobering
caveats. The American rate of teen pregnancy remains virtually the
highest in the Western world, and 4 million teens a year report new
cases of STDs.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the Youth Risk Behavior Survey of the Centers for
Disease Control, which asks high schoolers about everything from
sex to cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been a significant change over the course of the
'90s in the proportion of girls who say they've had intercourse or
who report having had four or more partners. But the number of high
school boys who say they've had intercourse dropped from 57 percent
in 1991 to 49 percent in 1997, roughly the same as the 48 percent
of high school girls who say they've had sex. Almost one fifth of
boys report at least four partners, but that's down from almost a
quarter in 1991. Almost 63 percent of sexually active boys used
condoms the last time they had intercourse, up from 55 percent in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Urban Institute's National Survey of Adolescent
Males, which looks at 15- to 19-year-olds, in school and out. In
1995, 55 percent said they'd had intercourse, down from 60 percent
in 1988, with the decrease concentrated almost entirely among white
males. Researcher Freya Sonenstein calls it ``primarily a suburban
phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   While condom use remains highest among black teens, the increase
in use is most dramatic among white youths. While comparable
surveys of teenage girls show an increase in the number of girls
having intercourse before age 15, from 11 percent in 1988 to 19
percent in 1995, the survey of adolescent males shows that the
level is stable at 21 percent. Only Latino youths register
significant increases in early sexual initiation.
</P>
<P>
   So what are teenage boys saying about sex these days?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, they're saying they're scared. Mention the topic
to a group of young men at Stoneham High School and they mention
``the book,'' a graphic, pictorial guide to sexually transmitted
diseases, that they perused in 10th-grade health class, the one
that 17-year-old John Curtis laughs ``is going to scar everyone for
life'' and lead them to monkhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am scared to death about STDs,'' says 18-year-old Robert
Hanley, who has seen a family friend die of AIDS. ``I am scared out
of my mind about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm way more worried about getting a girl pregnant,'' Curtis
interjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you serious?'' asks Hanley. ``I could deal with a baby but
not with dying of STDs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can prevent a baby,'' says 18-year-old Ryan Brown, ``but
you don't know if someone's clean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of four people have STDs,'' says Hanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' says 16-year-old Ryan Szloch as he surveys the eight
other classmates sitting around the table, ``is two of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a scare thing nowadays. You don't want people to
know you've had sex,'' Hanley says. ``Girls have the frame of mind
we have. We could have something goofy down there.''
</P>
<P>
   This, says Stoneham health teacher Sharon Chapman, is not a
conversation she would have heard a decade ago. ``It was all macho.
The guys who spoke up were the ones who knew everything and had
done everything,'' she says. ``You didn't hear them speak about
waiting. You didn't hear kids standing up for abstinence the way
they do now.''
</P>
<P>
   Abstinence, that is, from sexual intercourse. Adults may have
been surprised by the recent Kinsey Institute report that college
students don't consider oral sex ``having sex,'' but teenage boys
weren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had oral sex and they ask if you're still a virgin,
you'll say yes,'' says 17-year-old Brian O'Keefe of Stoneham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot to ask students to abstain from other things like
oral sex,'' says Racki of Swampscott. ``I think that's where most
kids draw the line. I think if they did the polls again and
included oral sex, the numbers would be way up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're still a virgin till you go to bed with her in the
womb,'' says 16-year-old Anthony Liriano of the South End.
</P>
<P>
   Oral sex, says 16-year-old Raymond Murphy of Burlington, ``is
one step above making out,''
</P>
<P>
   One major difference driving today's kids, of course, is AIDS.
The oldest among the teens of 1999 were babies when AIDS was
identified in 1981. The rest weren't even born. They're the
generation that grew up with sex education, not sexual revolution,
with consequences, not carefree loving.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you jump in a girl, and she's easy, you know she's got
something,'' says 18-year-old Sarnie McCaskill II of Roxbury. ``If
she's active, she might have something else active.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd have to look pretty hard to find a teen who hasn't learned
about AIDS in school. The CDC reports 92 percent have had some kind
of HIV curriculum. ``It's been 10 or 15 years since comprehensive
sex education,'' says Harris, the Swampscott health teacher.
``We've never had a generation that's better educated.''
</P>
<P>
   Walk into Swampscott High and the corridor is festooned in the
colorful paper pledges of students to forswear ``destructive
behavior.'' The most popular club on campus is the peer leaders
group, whose roster lists 150 of the school's 750 students. Walk
out of Stoneham High on a recent afternoon and the announcements
include an invitation to a session on AIDS and STDs. ``The thing
that helps us so much,'' says Stoneham's Hanley, ``is health class
in 10th grade.''
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of room, nevertheless, for concern in the latest
surveys. A majority of sexually active teenage boys, 55 percent,
don't use condoms each time they have intercourse. Roughly three of
every 10 say their last sexual encounter followed consumption of
alcohol or drugs _ a number that hasn't changed appreciably during
the '90s. Here in the Bay State one fifth of high school girls
report they've been hurt physically or sexually by someone they
dated. Three-quarters of 15- to 17-year-olds, according to a new
Kaiser Family Foundation national survey, underestimate the
incidence of STDs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
