<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOW THE SWEETENER AT SUGARLOAF REUNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARRABASSETT, Maine _ The two rather amazing events that
occurred in Carrabassett Valley last weekend probably have nothing
to do with each other, but somehow they cannot be separated.
</P>
<P>
   And it is particularly fitting that the Sugarloaf/USA ski area
is involved since, earlier in the season, the western Maine ski
area was victim of a snow drought the likes of which we had not
seen in about 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   And things were not improving. Every time there was snow, warm
rainy spells followed, creating an ice cap on every summit in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just down the road and across the river from the Sugarloaf
access road is a derelict building that looks a little like an old
country barn. The red paint is faded and the floor sags. The
cavernous rooms below have been dark for decades, with an
occasional faded poster on the wall recalling days long gone.
</P>
<P>
   The stage upon which Jud Strunk and the Sugarloafers once played
their semi-amazing eclectic rock is still in place, and the dance
floor is, like the rest of the interior, dark raw wood, including
the stout oaken posts that hold up the rest of the building. A few
booths where revelers once sat are still in place, and the bar in
the corner tilts with the sag of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The place may never have looked much better, but rarely was it
ever seen without a wall to wall crowd, and it may be significant
that few pictures exist of the most famous apres ski bar of its
era, the Red Stallion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of stories told about the Red Stallion
over the years,'' says founder Ed Rogers, who bought the club when
he was fresh out of University of Maine, ``wild stories, crazy
ones. But they're all true.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was speaking last Saturday night to about 400 graying
sixties kids who flocked to the Red Stallion for a one-time blast
down memory lane. A Founder's Night to raise money for the
Sugarloaf Ski Club brought back the hundreds of old-time
Sugarloafers who remember the Red Stallion as an emblem of youth
itself _ their own, and the wildly growing sport of skiing that was
never more popular, before or since.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always remember an era through a kind of memory haze and
romanticize it,'' said Bruce McLeod, who was drawn to the party by
word of mouth, its only advertising, ``but I hear these people talk
about the Red Stallion and I know I missed something pretty great.
I was about 10 at the time this place was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories include horses, lost skiers who took up residence in the
inn, and at least one New Year's Eve ski race down the roof of the
inn into one of the first heated pools north of Portland. Clothes
were optional.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an amazing place,'' said John Diller, who was a
bartender at the Stallion in the early '70s and is now general
manager of the mountain. ``It really was part of the identity of
the old Sugarloaf.''
</P>
<P>
   In those years, the area known as ``The Loaf'' had acquired an
identity that contained elements of wildness _ in part owing to its
location in the Great North Woods of Maine _ and fierce
independence outside the accepted skiing establishment. The quality
of terrain on the only lift-served area in the East with above
timberline skiing spoke for itself.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Globe managing editor Ian Menzies took a trip to the
area then considered an outpost among Boston skiers. He found Ed
Rogers at the Red Stallion, which in those days drew the likes of
Normal Mailer and IMG's Jim Watson. Said Rogers:
</P>
<P>
   ``A person can do what they damn well please here, what they're
most comfortable doing . . . that's the real Carrabassett
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Sugarloaf matured and the various corporate entities that
ran it sought to market the area's unmatchable New England terrain,
many sought to distance the mountain's image from the wild and
wooley days. The area became Sugarloaf/USA, and the beginning of a
village and several condo pods were designed to bring a family base
to the area.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering those days of the 1960s when skiing growth was at
its most vigorous, Rogers alluded to how ``homogenized'' the sport
and Sugarloaf had become. Fact is that few could have survived the
intensity of the Red Stallion days and ways for very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here tonight,'' said one middle-aged woman who asked
not to have her name appear, ``to find the bouncer who threw me out
of here and confiscated my fake ID. And he's right over there.''
The two shared a beer and a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   And just as the first light flickered in the old bar and the
first chords of rock 'n' roll heard in decades through the old
place were played by Uncle Al (an original), an amazing thing
happened besides the fact that the floor seemed to be sinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that snow,'' someone said, and sure enough, a blizzard
had started that would blanket the mountain in over 20 inches of
snow through the next 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, true to form, those who rocked the night away in
the Stallion were out for first tracks to ski in the deepest
lightest powder anyone in New England could remember. Some talked
of ``champagne powder,'' and early powder hounds had the snow
flowing off their chests and over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there were those who will always believe in
strange forces afoot. ``Finally, they figured out something that
pleased the snow gods,'' said a hotel operator. ``They opened up
the Stallion, and winter happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
