A6486 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-DOWNHILL-BOS &LR;      03-11 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-DOWNHILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIANS LIVE UP TO RAVE BILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the snow melts from the Alps and the Rockies this spring, and
as memories solidify of the World Cup ski season just winding up in
Sierra Nevada, Spain this week, two images will be lasting: an
Austrian ski team that has dominated the season like an
overwhelming red-and-white wave, and the pair of Norwegians who
stood up to the onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   With the downhill complete and three races to come for both men
and women, the overall season standings could change slightly, but
the Austrian men hold seven of top 10 spots and nine of the top 15.
That won't change.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will the standings of the Austrian women, who have four in
the top 10 spots _ including slots one and three _ and five in the
top 15. About a dozen countries compete regularly in World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegians Lasse Kjus and Kjetil Andre Aamodt stand 1-2 in the
overall standings, having knocked Austrian Hermann Maier into third
place overall after Wednesday's final downhill of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Since last summer when the team began working out earlier than
most on the glacial snow, word began trickling out of camp that the
Austrian team was special. And it didn't take them long to prove
the point.
</P>
<P>
   By midseason the Austrians were turning in history-making shows
_ like winning the top nine places in the Super-G at Innsbruck, a
feat never before accomplished. It also sent home the point that
this was a team effort rather than a star show, despite the
emergence of Maier, ``The Terminator,'' as the featured
personality. Austrian men took at least half the top 15 spots in
most races they entered.
</P>
<P>
   By the World Alpine Championships in Vail, Colo., last month,
the Austrian team was competing with itself _ kids against the
veterans, women against men _ and a headline in a Vienna newspaper
wondered: ``Where's the competition?''
</P>
<P>
   Historic Austrian names such as Karl Schranz and FranzKlammer
were being joined with new giants from the Tyrol, Maier and Thomas
Sangassinger. At the prominently located Austria House in Vail
Village, the old legends were mingling constantly with the younger
skiers, heightening the sense of national force, complete with its
own oompah band.
</P>
<P>
   And while most talk was once focused on the greatness of the
male team, it was suddenly apparent that the Austrian women had
also been developing into almost as dominant a force as their male
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   From Anita Wachter, a longtime queen of Austrian skiing, arose a
new generation of young women _ Michela Dorfmeister, Renate
Goetschl, and Alexandra Meissnitzer _ who congealed into a
well-sesoned team by the time of the Worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``All season we have been pushing each other really hard,'' said
24-year-old Meissnitzer on the day she won the giant slalom gold
medal at Vail, seeming to take the mantle of team leadership from
the bronze medalist, Wachter. ``We are a team. We support each
other, but when it is time to race, we compete hard against each
other. We have to be very competitive just to get to race.''
</P>
<P>
   Meissnitzer won Wednesday's final downhill of the season to give
her an unbeatable lock on the overall World Cup title with 1,640
points to Germany's Hilde Gerg at 1,163.
</P>
<P>
   To many observers, internal competition is part of the Austrian
secret. With strong state support in the nation's number one sport,
wave upon wave of rising young skiers compete for very few spots.
In some events, in fact, the toughest competition takes place in
the training runs that determine which Austrians will make the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we must race for a place on the team,'' said 21-year-old
phenom Ben Raich, who holds 10th place in overall World Cup
standings, ``there is very fierce rivalry between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranate Goetschl, who won the gold medal in women's downhill at
Vail, agrees, adding that ``you must understand that in our country
skiing is the number one sport, like football and basketball here.
Every little kid grows up dreaming about being a famous ski racer
on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on weekends, millions of Austrians are glued to their
television sets watching World Cup ski racing. But, beyond the fact
that the sport is a big moneymaker, the effort to raise a nation of
ski racers is a patriotic one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no team in the world that gets so much government
money and support,'' says Patrick Lange, a spokesman for the World
Cup tour that was started by his father, Serge, in the 1950s. ``You
look around at the race course: The Austrians have more coaches and
trainers, more skiers. They just do more than the other countries.
No one can touch them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
