<SLUG> BC-INTEL-PRIVACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL FACES ANOTHER FLAP OVER PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Intel Corp. faces a new round of criticism
from privacy advocates over a computer chip that identifies users
as they surf the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the privacy advocates objected to technology, known
as a Processor Serial Number, or PSN, contained in Intel's new
Pentium III chips. The PSN identifies individual machines connected
to the Internet by way of a unique number embedded in each chip.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, a French programmer notified Intel that one of
its chips found in new laptops inadvertently contained experimental
circuitry that was the forerunner to PSN. Intel spokesman Tom
Waldrup said the Santa Clara, Calif.-based company, the world
leader in microprocessor chips, had confirmed the flaw.
</P>
<P>
   According to Intel, the chips, which include some of the Pentium
II and Celeron lines, were part of a prototype that later led to
full-fledged installation of an identifying serial number feature
in the company's new Pentium III chips.
</P>
<P>
   The PSN feature is the subject of a formal complaint filed with
the Federal Trade Commission by Internet civil rights advocates,
who argue that the identifying feature violates user privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Waldrup said Wednesday that the experimental circuitry was
supposed to be erased from the chip during the manufacturing
process. However, an assembly line error allowed the prototypes to
remain enabled on the chips.
</P>
<P>
   Waldrup said Intel was releasing software that can turn off the
feature.
</P>
<P>
   The flaw was discovered by a French computer programmer, Pierre
Chassaing.
</P>
<P>
   Waldrup said inserting experimental features in existing
computer chips was part of a validation process that allowed Intel
to evaluate future manufacturing capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that most of these (chips) have been shipped into
the business market,'' Waldrup said. ``Only a small minority
would've been sold to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Waldrup, the flaw affects only chips made after
Jan. 5. He declined to say how many chips had been shipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is troubling,'' said Ari Schwartz, a privacy policy
analyst with the Washington, D.C.-based Center for Democracy and
Technology, a party to the FTC complaint. ``Intel throws this
technology out there, and then everyone else, customers, computer
makers and regulators, has to deal with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
