<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-MIAMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES WITHSTOOD HURRICANES' WORST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ He could have left. Lots of people told Tim James that
was the proper career choice to make.
</P>
<P>
   Stay in Miami? Play for a team that drew few fans, was seldom on
television, and was coming off a Big East season that was historic
_ 0-18 _ in the most negative kind of way?
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, that's why James chose to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I heard from people was how bad Miami was,'' said the
6-foot-7-inch orward who not only stayed but turned into the
brightest star a University of Miami team that _ can you believe
it? _ has a chance to be a legitimate player in the NCAA
Tournament, which begins for the Hurricanes Friday in Boston with
an East Regional game against Lafaytte. ``That just drove me.
People talked about all those empty seats at UM games, the fact
that the 'Canes weren't on TV, but all of the negative comments
motivated me. I looked at it as a challenge I wanted to meet
head-on. I wanted to come here with a few other guys and help make
this a respectable program.''
</P>
<P>
   Respectable?
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes are 22-6, seeded No. 2 in the East, and
considered by many a sleeper team that has an actual shot at the
title if the champion is destined to be a team other than Duke.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the Big East will argue with that.
</P>
<P>
   Not St. John's, which lost to Miami twice in the regular season
before finally nipping the Hurricanes, 62-59, in the semifinals of
the Big East tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Not Connecticut, the Big East tournament and regular-season
champion, which went all out to beat the Hurricanes in Miami,
winning by a basket in overtime in January, but then lost by a
basket in a rematch last month at UConn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are,'' said St. John's coach Mike Jarvis with as much
relief as satisfaction after last week's win, ``a very good team
that is going do well in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, James _ the Big East's Co-Player of the Year
(with UConn's Richard Hamilton) _ will most likely be the primary
reason.
</P>
<P>
   When James arrived in Miami as a freshman in 1995-96, the 'Canes
were looking for a cornerstone. He came out of Miami's Northwestern
High School and was a star from the start, leading the team in
offensive rebounds and blocked shots, while finishing second in
scoring on a 15-13 team (8-10 in the Big East) that was only two
years removed from that dreadful 0-18 stain.
</P>
<P>
   By his sophomore year he was the team leader, the catalyst for
teams that have made the NCAA field the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Milestone after milestone has been reached. This Miami team was
the first since 1964-65 to win 20 games. One more victory will tie
the school record.
</P>
<P>
   As for James, how many superlatives do you want to use? He is
the first Hurricane to score 1,500 points, grab 800 rebounds, and
block 200 shots. He leads the team in scoring (18.9 ppg), rebounds
(8.3), and blocks (2.2). He is fourth all-time in school history
with 1,685 points.
</P>
<P>
   And check this out. Before the last regular-season home game,
against Rutgers, his number, 40, was retired. The only other male
Hurricane player to be so honored was Rick Barry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what a joy Tim has been to work with,'' said
Miami coach Leonard Hamilton. ``He tries to do what is right all
the time. And it's always been that way.''
</P>
<P>
   James has done all of this in the most low-key fashion. You
don't hear a whole lot of trash talking from him, or see a lot of
showboating. But the fires within him are as stoked as anyone's.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't see it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you will see more in the next few weeks as James's
career at Miami winds down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have goals,'' said James, who still carries around the
disappointment of last year's first-round loss to UCLA. ``Last year
was a learning experience.''
</P>
<P>
   James began learning early. He came out of the tough James E.
Scott projects in Miami's Liberty City section. The realities of
the world intruded quickly. At 13, he saw a shooting victim
sprawled dead on the street.
</P>
<P>
   But his mother, Betty, wove a warm cocoon of safety around him.
It was a comfort zone that James stayed in when it came time to
pick a college.
</P>
<P>
   James figured, ``Why go somewhere else when you can play
big-time basketball right here in Miami?''
</P>
<P>
   He has played, and played as well as any Miami player since
Barry.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it makes no sense, all of this coming together in
such a short time.
</P>
<P>
   In other ways, it makes all the sense in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1358EST &QL; 
