<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPOCRISY IS STANDARD PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A word (three, actually) to all the moralists out
there:
</P>
<P>
   Take a hike.
</P>
<P>
   It's too late. The time to start clucking about graduation rates
and eligibility standards on our Division 1 men's basketball teams
has already come and gone. That time was, well, I don't know
exactly when it was because that, frankly, is the way we Americans
want it.
</P>
<P>
   You want pure ``student-athletes''? Good. Head to Hartford and
see Trinity. Go to Manchester (Indiana). Point the car toward
Hampden-Sydney, Va. They're all good Division 3 teams and they're
all at home in their own nice little tournament this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not putting them down. I love basketball at all levels. One
of those teams probably has a 6-3 inside man I'd adore. But that's
one level of competition, and what we've got going on in the
FleetCenter starting Friday is another. The 64 teams in the real
NCAA Tournament have better athletes than the teams playing in
lower levels, and those are the ones most sports fans want to see.
And if a few of them (aside from the Lafayettes and Penns who have
zero chance of winning it all) also happen to have a half-decent
student or two, that's a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   If Duke wins, you'll be reading and hearing about how coach Mike
Krzyzewski does it the ``right'' way, and there will be some truth
in that. Duke is a good, private (key word) school. But don't allow
people to sling too much bull. Absent their basketball skill, few
of Coach K's great players over the years would have gotten past
the Duke academic police. If Duke kids happen to have better board
scores than, oh, I don't know, Cincinnati's, it's still relative
because those scores won't match up to a random sampling of any
dozen Duke students. Duke has a double standard, all right. It just
isn't as pronounced as some others.
</P>
<P>
   Duke wins with Duke-like students, not by-the-numbers Duke
students. Moving right down the list of the remaining 309 Division
1 schools, there's not a scholarship-granting college among 'em
populated entirely by athletes who would have gotten into that
institution if subject to the same process as the nonathlete. Not
one. But no one wants to talk about that. We'd rather pretend that
Duke and Stanford are 100 percent virtuous and that Fresno State
and New Mexico are 100 percent evil.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just Us being Us. America is distinguished among all
nations for many reasons, not the least of which is a phenomenal
capacity for hypocrisy. Nowhere is this more evident than in our
love affair with big-time college sports.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the premise that no other country on earth does what
we do, and that includes America Lite, our neighbor to the
immediate north. There has never been an adequate justification for
our unique decision to include the full-blown business behemoths
known as major college football and basketball in our higher
education structure. What does having a great football team or
basketball team have to do with running a proper university? People
have been asking that question for the better part of this century.
Some have actually answered according to their conscience by
withdrawing from the process (see University of Chicago, circa
1939).
</P>
<P>
   The rest of them, and, yeah, us, have likewise come up with an
answer. Our public pronouncement is that there should be high
ethical and academic standards. You know, look at Whizzer White and
Bill Bradley. They are proof that one can have a full cake left on
the plate even after consuming a very large piece. They are the
shining examples that prove the system works.
</P>
<P>
   Hand me the hefty-sized barf bag.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is we really don't care if our favorite college teams
happen to be populated by semi-literate purse snatchers as long as
they win. Oh, we care about standards, all right, but not our
standards. The standards we really care about are the ones at some
other guy's school, usually one in direct competition with ours.
</P>
<P>
   We Americans want to think well of ourselves. We would like to
project an image of always taking the high road. Just don't judge
us by our actions. We deplore pornography, but it's a
multibillion-dollar industry. We preach nutrition, but we love our
Big Macs. And we'd like our school to win the ``right'' way, but
why won't Admissions let us have the 6-11 kid with the 610 boards
and the rap sheet? If we don't take him, Backcourt Tech down the
street will. Worse yet, they're on our schedule.
</P>
<P>
   So here we are, on the eve of another NCAA Tournament, and
what's the news? It seems that a former employee of the University
of Minnesota claims that she wrote papers and did take-home exams
for upwards of 20 Gophers basketball players, including members of
the 1997 Final Four team and four players on the current squad,
which is preparing to play Gonzaga in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling? I'm shocked!
</P>
<P>
   If true, it's regrettable and shameful. I'd also bet a weekly
NBA superstar paycheck that Minnesota just happens to be the one
that got caught _ this time _ and that the general reaction among
Gophers fans will be to string up the woman who couldn't keep her
mouth shut and go along with the program. This in itself isn't even
a new twist on the topic. What about the academic adviser down
there at the University of Georgia a few years back? It's all part
of the deal, because it's what we Americans want, and always have
wanted. We want to eat the sausage. How they make it is of no
concern.
</P>
<P>
   If we really wanted to see pure scholar-athletes in this
country, we'd have more of them. Real full-time students would play
and the others would perform for independent clubs or in
professional settings, the way they do everywhere else in the
world. But we don't want that; we want March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   If any members of the press are offended by it all, let them
phone in sick and allow the sports editor or news director to have
someone else cover the games. This is not the time to be crying
about graduation rates or eligibility standards. The rest of us
long ago made our peace with the system. We're good Americans. We
want it both ways, and we've got it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, then, you think Kent really has a shot at Temple?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-RUIZ-BOS &LR;      03-11 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RUIZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUIZ CLOSES IN ON A DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Norman Stone had his dream fulfilled not too long
ago. John Ruiz is still waiting on his.
</P>
<P>
   Stone is the local guy who bet everything _ his future, his
house, his dreams _ on a kid from Chelsea with nothing going for
him but a big heart and a willingness to fight for what he could
get. He hasn't quite won that bet yet but Wednesday he and Ruiz sat
in the last row of a three-tiered dais at Madison Square Garden
looking down at Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis knowing they are
only months away from fighting one of them for the biggest prize in
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   That has been Stone's dream all along, that somehow Ruiz would
become the No. 1 contender in the heavyweight division. If boxing
history is a barometer, that was about as farfetched an idea as
there could be. But it came true late last year, not long after
Stone signed Ruiz to a promotional deal with Don King and began to
get the kind of fights and connections that can put a fighter in
the rankings if he wins often enough.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz beat former International Boxing Federation heavyweight
champion Tony Tucker and steppingstone opponents such as Jimmy
Thunder and Ray Anis, and one day he woke up and learned his
manager's dream had come true even if his hadn't quite yet been
reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Johnny and told him he was No. 1 in the (World Boxing
Council) and he just said, `Yeah?,' '' Stone recalled. ``Then he
called me the next morning and says, `You sure?' Now look at us.''
</P>
<P>
   The sports world will be looking at them Saturday night when
Ruiz opens the Holyfield-Lewis pay-per-view show against Mario
Cawley, a kid he figures to knock stiff in a round or two. Cawley
comes in with a gaudy 21-1 record but he's been on what boxing guys
call ``the Nashville diet,'' meaning he's been fed a lot of kids
from Tennessee and Ohio who can't fight much so the only number
about him that's real is the number 1. That blemish came a year ago
in his last fight, when Hartford heavyweight Lawrence Clay-Bey
knocked him out. The consensus is whatever Clay-Bey can do, Ruiz
can do better.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is the point at this juncture. Ruiz is 33-3,
the North America Boxing Federation champion and holder of what the
No. 1 contender's spot brings _ a guaranteed title shot against the
WBC champion by October or thereabouts. When you're in that slot,
you're not looking for tough tuneups.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to John Ruiz's dream.
</P>
<P>
   He never dreamed of being the No. 1 contender, never thought
about it at all. He's happy to have the WBC's blessing but fighters
don't think about being a contender. If they really are fighters
they think about being a champion, something the kid from Chelsea
is now only two wins away from if he's lucky and boxing's gods
smile on him a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have believed that on all the nights Ruiz refused to
go out with his friends because he had to go to the gym or on all
the bitter cold, stone dark mornings when he ran through the empty
streets while his family slept? Who could believe a kid from New
England could become the No. 1 contender when no one had done it
since Rocky Marciano five decades ago?
</P>
<P>
   A kid could believe it. A kid with some talent and some will and
maybe not enough sense to know what is impossible in life. A kid
like John Ruiz could believe it and now he has done it. Now he has
given the man he calls Stoney his dream and is only one win away
from living his own dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was always to fight for the heavyweight
championship,'' Ruiz said softly as he sat 10 feet behind the boom
box voice of King.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think about it, it's been a lot of years to get to this
but in other ways it feels like only Wednesday when I was fighting
in the Olympic Trials (1992). I took the hard road. We didn't have
connections or a big promoter or anything when we started. There
were times where it looked like there were a lot of obstacles
between us and the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've had a lot of time to learn. I've had time to do a lot
of thinking. Now here I am, on the verge of fighting for the
heavyweight championship. That's not written in stone yet, but it's
my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a goal that looked distant after Ruiz tore the tendons in
his hand while losing a decision to cruiserweight Sergei Kobozev
Aug. 12, 1993. Ruiz's career was threatened and his goal seemed to
fade into the night after he finally got a shot on HBO and was
knocked out in 19 seconds by David Tua.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz walked out of his corner and into a crushing hook, the kind
of thing that happens to a professional fighter about as often as
lightning strikes him. But it happened and when it did many
dismissed Ruiz as just another kid who couldn't hold his hands up.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruiz looked at it for what it was _ an ill-prepared boxer
learning a hard lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that fight I sat down and thought about what I wanted to
do in my life,'' Ruiz said. ``The answer was I wanted to become
heavyweight champion. So I decided it was time to start training
harder, staying more focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame myself for the Tua fight. I wasn't serious enough. In
a way, I'm glad it happened because when something like that
happens either you quit or you go forward. It opened my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   He has gone forward ever since. At the start there were wins
over guys you never heard of again. But then came a shot to serve
as Lewis's sparring partner and a connection with his promoter,
Panos Eliados. Then came a shot at the NABF title against Thunder,
a big puncher who Ruiz knocked flat, then came wins over Anis and
Tucker, an 11th round TKO of the former champion just over a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter King stepped in and Ruiz won the World Boxing
Association North America title against journeyman Jerry Ballard.
Now here he is, the embodiment of Norman Stone's dream on the verge
of living his own.
</P>
<P>
   For a kid from Chelsea, for a kid from Anywhere, USA really,
it's a hell of a story. A story, Ruiz and Stone believe, that has a
chapter or two to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `In your wildest dreams did you ever think this
could happen?' '' Stone said as he looked around the Theatre at the
Garden Wednesday packed with so many of boxing's big names. ``I
tell them that's where it all started for Johnny and me. In our
wildest dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times we fought over the last hot dog in the arena
but the kid is here now. He made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Made it to Norman Stone's dream. One more win and John Ruiz will
have his dream, too. He'll have a title shot.
</P>
<P>
   In boxing, that's about as good as it gets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
