<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ECAC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE HOCKEY SET FOR SECOND SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The University of New Hampshire and Clarkson University won the
marathons.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's on to the sprints: A two-weekend dash to crown Hockey
East and ECAC tournament winners and another two-weekend race after
that to determine a national champion.
</P>
<P>
   UNH shut down Maine last weekend in a first-place showdown to
win its first outright Hockey East regular-season championship and
Clarkson beat Cornell Saturday night to hold off St. Lawrence and
win the ECAC title.
</P>
<P>
   Besides earning the top seeds for their league tournaments, UNH
and Clarkson each snatched one of the 12 guaranteed berths in the
NCAA Tournament that begins March 26-27. At least a couple of more
spots for Eastern teams are up for grabs the next couple of
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   While Maine and Boston College in Hockey East and probably St.
Lawrence in the ECAC are in great shape for at-large bids, the only
sure way into the NCAAs for most teams is to win the league
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The chase begins Thursday. No. 2 seed Maine hosts No. 7
UMass-Amherst for a best-of-three series and No. 3 BC has No. 6
UMass-Lowell, running through Saturday, if necessary. UNH hosts No.
8 Merrimack and No. 5 Boston University visits No. 4 Providence in
series that open Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard plays at RPI Friday and Saturday in a two-game,
first-to-three-points series. While the Hockey East teams play each
night until a winner is determined, in the ECAC the first game can
end in a tie after a five-minute overtime. If the first game is a
tie, the second game will be played until there is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty on the line this weekend and next, when Hockey
East moves on to the FleetCenter and the ECAC heads to Lake Placid,
N.Y., for the championship rounds.
</P>
<P>
   There is seeding order _ and first-round byes _ to be determined
for the national tournament. There is fine-tuning for the NCAAs.
There is the chance to regroup _ or to salvage a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just getting there, to Lake Placid,'' said Harvard
coach Ronn Tomassoni. ``We feel if we play well as a team we can
win this tournament. Now it's the playoffs and the slate is wiped
clean.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that Harvard started the season 2-8-1 overall
and 0-8-1 in the ECAC.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that BU also was 2-8-1 out of the gate. Or
that the Terriers, with some less-than-spectacular penalty killing,
lost all three of their games against Providence.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that BC, ranked No. 1 in the country when the
season began, has not quite lived up to expectations despite being
among the top seven teams in the nation all year.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't even matter that UNH and Maine went head-to-head
all season at the top of Hockey East, were among the leaders in the
nation, then did it again in a wild weekend in Durham last week.
</P>
<P>
   Any team can get hot and do some damage. Just as any other team
can falter now, or in the NCAA regionals, and see a glorious season
end in a quick 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard will try to ride the momentum from a strong finish that
included a pair of wins last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   BU will hope its penalty-killing unit plays more like the group
that allowed one power-play goal in its opponents' last 19 chances
than the unit that saw Providence score nine goals in 17 chances in
three losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we can beat anybody in this tournament,'' said BU
coach Jack Parker. ``No question about that. This is the only team
we haven't beaten, and in some ways it's nice to go down there in
that role.''
</P>
<P>
   BC, which lost in the national championship game to Michigan
last year, looks to keep one modest streak alive and end another.
The Eagles were the only Hockey East team that had home ice to
advance to the FleetCenter last year and UMass-Lowell has made it
to the semifinal round six straight times.
</P>
<P>
   Maine coach Shawn Walsh left Durham last week happy with the way
his team played, excited about the national tournament, and even
more excited that his team didn't have to play again on a rink as
wide as UNH's.
</P>
<P>
   UNH knocked off one of its demons last weekend and now takes aim
at another. The Wildcats have never won a Hockey East tournament
title and this year's group of seniors _ led by high-flying forward
Jason Krog and steady defenseman Steve O'Brien _ has only made it
to the FleetCenter once.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they were upset by Maine and sat out the Hockey East
championship round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pumped and we're looking forward to playing,'' said UNH
coach Dick Umile. ``We want to take the team and our fans and go to
the FleetCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the sprints begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
