<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SCHOOLOFFLESH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FLESH' IS CERTAINLY SKIN-DEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   French actress Isabelle Huppert's mystery _ even when she cries,
she's blank-faced _ is the center of director Benoit Jacquot's new
film, ``The School of Flesh.'' Jacquot seems her equal in terms of
enigma. They've created a low-blood-pressure tale about the dirty
magnetism of sex. Huppert plays a French fashion executive who
falls for the slinky young package played by Vincent Martinez. He's
younger and morally pliant _ a hustler who plays on both sides of
the sexual equator.
</P>
<P>
   Despite tumbling into sex with Huppert, which he finds so
satisfying that he refuses to charge her, Martinez treats her like
just another trick after they begin a relationship. She chases him
around to a bar where he once worked and grills his former lover
(Vincent Lindon) for information. And after Martinez abandons her,
she debases herself further by hounding him to a desolate part of
Paris where he's moodily turning tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's performance consists of posing his angelic figure as
if he's lost in dreams of starring in a Vogue spread. All the
chemistry from Huppert comes mainly when she's petty and grasping,
afraid of losing him and embarrassed about her obsession. Her
heart-shaped face takes on a mousy intensity at that point.
</P>
<P>
   Jacquot and his writer have adapted ``Flesh'' from a novel by
Yukio Mishima. I've not read this book, but based on my familiarity
with his other work, I'm sure that themes such as ambiguity, a
flirtation with humiliation and a tough scheming for dominance
resonate in it. They sort of do in ``Flesh,'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   You can feel the blood rushing through the temples of the
characters in Mishima's work, whereas Jacquot tends to be drier _
especially here, for reasons that don't make sense. It's a movie
about sexual politics that is neither sexy nor sexual. Jacquot has
conjured a reflective piece, despite a story line that sounds
quintessentially French, that doesn't really have a brain in its
head. But it sure acts as if it's smart.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The School of Flesh''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Benoit Jacquot
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Isabelle Huppert, Vincent Martinez
</P>
<P>
   Length: 105 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: Unrated _ in French with subtitles; contains nudity and
adult language and situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
