Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ Pressured by patient groups and
media leaks, researchers agree to move up their release of studies
of bone-marrow transplants as treatment for breast cancer. The
studies are the first large-scale tests of the expensive and
controversial treatment. Their early release, reported in The Wall
Street Journal, poses a difficult political issue for the American
Society of Clinical Oncology and the National Cancer Institute,
which is sponsoring two of the studies. By Denise Grady. (800
words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-MEETING (Undated) _ Oil ministers from six major producing
nations _ Saudi Arabia, Venezuela, Mexico, Iran, Algeria and Norway
_ meet in Amsterdam to renew attempts to cut production and bolster
oil prices. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 99
points, or 1 percent, at 9,872. The Nasdaq index was up 25 points,
or 1 percent. Elsewhere, prices rose 0.1 percent in Tokyo and fell
0.8 percent in Hong Kong. They rose 1.2 percent in Frankfurt, 1.5
percent in London, 1.4 percent in Brazil and 2.5 percent in Mexico.
On the American debt market, the long bond was flat, with the yield
at 5.56 percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   COLT-GUNS (West Hartford, Conn.) _ Colt's Manufacturing Company,
the gun maker, has been a symbol of American entrepreneurship and
expansionism for more than 150 years. Its financial history is
equally rich, a tale of lost patents and contracts, unhappy
workers, boom-and-bust cycles and, ultimately, a round trip through
bankruptcy court. Now, as it faces anti-handgun lawsuits and
legislation, Colt's future will be determined by a new owner, a
secretive billionaire family that was once among Baghdad's richest,
and a new chief executive, a man who helped build a Silicon Valley
company. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS (Detroit) _ Where the global auto business goes next.
Includes an interview with Schrempp and these developments: Moody's
lowers its credit ratings for Nissan and subsidiaries to below
investment grade. Nissan shares fall 11 percent in Tokyo, while the
stock of Nissan Diesel declines 14 percent. Renault shares are down
in Paris. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-BMW (Geneva) _ The outlook at Germany's BMW. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-MERGERS (Rome) _ Developments in the two big European
hostile takeover attempts. In Italy, Telecom Italia, launching a
takeover defense against Olivetti, proposes to buy out its cellular
arm for about $30 billion in stock and convert non-voting savings
shares into common shares. In France, shares of Societe Generale
rise as much as 15 percent and those of Paribas as much as 9
percent on their first day of trading since BNP announced its
surprise takeover offer. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   NATSEMI-EARNINGS (Undated) _ National Semiconductor posts
earnings. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (New York) _ Arminio Fraga, Brazil's new central
banker, comes to New York to try to convince financial firms to
make loans. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
