<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR TREK PLOTS YOU'LL NEVER SEE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if the news were not depressing enough, what with Bob Dole
shilling for Viagra while his wife considers running for president,
there is now talk of a 10th Star Trek movie.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Star Trek has ``matured'' over the years from the
drooling, hormone-addled Capt. Kirk to the cool, politically
correct Capt. Picard, the movies in many ways remain the same. The
infuriating Spock has been replaced by the equally infuriating Data
and the Enterprise is bigger and higher-tech, but much of what made
the show endearing (or annoying, depending on your point of view)
remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it be the first movie, the 10th movie or the 20th movie,
here are some of the things that have never happened and never will
happen on Star Trek.
</P>
<P>
   (Some of the material in this column was gleaned through a
Vulcan mind-meld with Peggy Robin, author of ``The Starfleet
Academy Entrance Exam'' and from the approximately 10,000 Star Trek
Web sites out there, a fact that, in its own way, is alarming.)
</P>
<P>
   1. The Enterprise runs into a mysterious energy field of a type
that it has encountered before.
</P>
<P>
   The Enterprise attracts mysterious energy fields the way
President Clinton attracts interns. And, like interns, these energy
fields are all capable of great destruction. It would be nice if
the Enterprise could, just once, pass through a mysterious energy
field that smoothed wrinkles, brightened teeth and gave Capt.
Picard a full head of hair.
</P>
<P>
   2. The Enterprise goes to check on a remote outpost of
scientists, all of whom are perfectly all right.
</P>
<P>
   If I were a scientist on a remote outpost, I would look forward
to a visit from the Enterprise with the same enthusiasm I would
look forward to an attack of shingles. Everything is fine until
these idiots in the funny shirts show up.
</P>
<P>
   3. The crew of the Enterprise is stricken by a strange alien
plague, the cure for which is found in the ship's well-stocked sick
bay.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of nine movies, there has been no evidence that
the staff of the Enterprise's sick bay could cure so much as a
hangnail, let alone a mysterious pox brought aboard by some alien
creature with two heads and six arms. The Enterprise may as well
convert the sick bay to shuffleboard courts for all the good it
does.
</P>
<P>
   4. A power surge on the bridge fails to electrocute the user of
the computer panel due to a highly sophisticated 24th-century surge
protection device called a ``fuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy from ``Home Improvement'' would feel right at home on
the Enterprise, where you can't even plug in your electric
toothbrush without causing a fire or electrocuting half the crew.
Perhaps the Enterprise's electronics were designed by the same
geniuses who wired the Mir.
</P>
<P>
   5. Somebody takes out a shuttle and it doesn't explode or crash.
As with the sick bay, I don't know why the Enterprise bothers with
shuttles. Just select the person or persons you want to ride in the
thing, then line them up against the wall and shoot them. It would
be cheaper, a lot less messy and allow more time for the users of
the computer panel to electrocute themselves.
</P>
<P>
   6. The crew of the Enterprise is captured by a vastly superior
alien intelligence that does NOT put them on trial.
</P>
<P>
   What is this thing that vastly superior alien life forms of the
24th century have with trials? Don't they have Court TV in the
future? Can't they just run down to Blockbuster and rent a copy of
the Simpson trial? Perhaps aliens in the future are all Republicans
and just like staging trials whether they have a good reason or
not.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
