<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE STILL DON'T GET BILL AND HIS WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday March 16)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yeah, I watched it. We learned that Monica is still afraid of
Ken Starr, that she feels sorry for hurting Hillary and Chelsea,
that at first she thought the blue dress was funny. But we still
don't know much more about the man she calls her sexual soulmate.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the others? I kept thinking about Juanita. Where
does unhappy Juanita fit in with the hundreds of women who Monica
says Bill Clinton had sex with.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, in those relatively naive days before Monica and
before Kathleen but long after Gennifer and right after Paula, I
was trying to sort out why many women were remaining loyal to Bill.
I decided that we had a sisterly relationship with him.
</P>
<P>
   He was the brother with the potential, and we were the sisters
who depended on him to make the family proud, even though he had
this one jerk tendency.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of the family and for the sake of Bill we tried to
emphasize his strong points and downplay, even rationalize, his
weak points. In the long run he was capable of doing so much good
that we felt it necessary to stand united behind him, although
privately, when we heard rumors, we wanted to hiss, ``Knock it
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it got worse, as things often do when you cross
your fingers and wish problems would just go away. Monica followed
Paula and Kathleen followed Monica. And we found it harder to think
of him as our hero. He was starting to embarrass the family.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were no other heroes, and we'd hung in with him
this far.
</P>
<P>
   And so we took Hillary's cue and held his hand and said this was
a private matter and had nothing to do with the presidency, even
though we were inwardly disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Juanita. She made it harder than ever for the sisters
because what she claims happened with Brother Bill goes way beyond
being a rogue, a skirt chaser, a crude make-out man and even an
adulterer.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita said he raped her.
</P>
<P>
   We may still get into debates on what is sexual harassment and
whether you can have an affair without intercourse, but we
understand rape.
</P>
<P>
   And that is what Juanita's story is about. She worked on his
campaign, and they were friendly. She said he asked to come up to
her hotel room. She didn't feel endangered. He tried to kiss her
and bit her lip. He pushed her on the bed and she said no. It was
not consentual.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the chilling end in Juanita's story. He goes to
leave, puts on his sunglasses and tells her she better do something
about that lip.
</P>
<P>
   The way she tells it makes Clinton sound so smug, so belittling
toward her that you can understand why she would stay angry and
humiliated for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some accused her of lying, but they were halfhearted critics and
sounded as practiced as a lawyer jumping up in court and yelling
``Objection.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work as well this time. In the past the woman who have
accused Bill Clinton have been more easily and readily varnished,
at least at first, as being a bimbo, gold digger, temptress, even
slightly disturbed. They could be lying or exaggerating or doing it
for the money. Maybe they just misinterpreted his warm, friendly
nature.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as you don't want to believe Juanita, she is
believable, especially given Clinton's record. Even if you have no
more energy to deal with another accusation, she can't be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Ireland, head of the National Organization for Women,
said she understands why Juanita would have resisted coming
forward. She also said she doesn't expect an explanation from
Clinton because his denials aren't worth the air it takes to say
them or the paper it takes to write them.'
</P>
<P>
   If Juanita had charged Bill Clinton with rape 21 years ago,
would that have made a difference? He was state attorney general
and running for governor, a high-powered man. And she let him into
her room. And she did go to a fund-raiser for him later on. They
would have barbecued her, but still it might have alerted someone,
maybe even Clinton himself, that there was a problem that could get
him into big trouble down the road, even kill the dreams he and
Hillary had taken such care to fashion. Maybe he would have gotten
some counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he has all of us armchair analysts taking one more
voyeuristic tour through the Oval Office to catch him if we can.
</P>
<P>
   Monica spoke well. She was poised, charming in a bright-eyed way
and believable, even when she says she's giving up married men.
</P>
<P>
   But her old boyfriend, our president, is still a worry.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
