<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV18-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE SEEKS TO ADOPT A BABY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday March 18)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martha notices babies everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the mall, sleeping so sweetly in strollers. In restaurant
booster seats. Cooing in their mom's arms.
</P>
<P>
   She can't wait to be one of those women pushing a stroller,
holding a bottle or patting a warm, wriggly bundle on their
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But the path to finding her baby has been frustrating and
arduous. A year of fertility treatment, including artificial
insemination and injectable drugs. Three shots a day. Frequent
visits to the fertility clinic for Martha and her husband, Mike.
Four failed attempts to coax a zygote from egg and sperm. A bill of
$3,000 each time.
</P>
<P>
   After the last treatment, all the signs were there: a maternal
glow, the camellia in the side yard bursting into bloom, an
intuitive feeling that this would be the time the miracle would
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the letdown and the mourning for the child that wasn't
to be.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the time had come for the question: Do we want to adopt?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always wanted to be pregnant, to have a baby and feel
her kick inside me. Letting go was hard. But at that point, I
thought, we can make our family in a different way. With adoption
you know at the end of that road there's a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciding to pursue adoption led to dozens of new questions:
Domestic or foreign? Older child or infant? Private lawyer or
agency?
</P>
<P>
   After research, including talks with several adoptive parents
and an adoption consultant, Martha and Mike decided on domestic
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a newborn,'' Martha says. ``Through international
adoptions, an infant can be up to 12 months old. And, in the U.S.,
there's a much greater chance of prenatal care and education.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, they found a few books that were particularly
helpful, such as ``Raising Adopted Children,'' by Lois Ruskai
Melina, and ``The Adoption Resource Book'' by Lois Gilman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one of the books, it said that when you adopt, people will
say to you, `Oh, you got your baby the easy way,' '' Martha said.
``But there's nothing easy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``birth mother letter'' was especially difficult to write.
</P>
<P>
   What image in their family photos, what reassuring words, would
convince a young, pregnant stranger that they were the couple to
raise her baby?
</P>
<P>
   They wrote about their house on a quiet street in suburban
Atlanta, their dog who was rescued from an animal shelter, shared
backpacking trips, family reunions at the beach and a vacation to
Australia, complete with kangaroo sightings.
</P>
<P>
   They wrote about why they wanted to bring a child into their
home, into their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Then, they mailed the letter to lawyers and agencies, to go in
files thick with other letters, other photos of smiling couples
hoping to be selected.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``At night sometimes, I'll see a real vivid picture in my mind
of our baby on the changing table with me doing raspberries on her
tummy, and she's giggling and kicking her feet,'' Martha says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fills me with warmth and happiness. And it keeps me from
getting too anxious about all the hurdles we still have to clear.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a New York Times Regional Newspapers feature
writer. She has master's and specialist degrees in marriage and
family counseling.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
