<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6573 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-GODSAID-TEX     03-11 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GODSAID-TEX </SLUG>
 
WELL-TOLD, JUST NOT SO WELL-FILMED (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In August 1994, former ``Saturday Night Live'' player Julia
Sweeney's life took a sudden downturn: Doctors discovered that her
brother Mike had advanced-stage lymphoma. Mike and Sweeney's
parents moved in with Sweeney during his chemotherapy, cramping
life at her dream house. And in March 1995 _ shortly before Mike's
death _ Sweeney found out that she had ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   From this year of hell, Sweeney developed the one-woman show,
``God Said, `Ha!' '' What started as a stage play evolved into a
book, a double-CD album and, now, a movie. It remains a funny,
moving piece, and happily, Sweeney steers clear of anything too
maudlin. But although Sweeney has said she likes the movie version
best, the film is a little odd.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney is attractive and articulate, and you could do worse
than spend an hour and a half with her. But ``God Said, `Ha!' ''
doesn't look as if it was ever meant to be on film (Sweeney's pal
Quentin Tarantino acted as executive producer), and it's often
awkward, as most photographed stage plays are. Sweeney moves around
on her mock-living-room set, and the camera moves almost
independently of her: Sometimes, she looks straight into the lens,
as if she were addressing her movie audience; other times, she's
shown in profile, looking dreamily off into space as if she were
blissfully unaware that anyone would be watching. This calls
attention to itself, as does a moment of rapid editing and another
moment when the camera draws back to show ... more cameras!
</P>
<P>
   The movements distract from Sweeney's words, which are full of
small gems about what it's like to be a single woman in your
mid-'30s living with your parents again, sneaking a forbidden
cigarette or trysting with a lover during one of those rare times
when the house is empty. The movie's advantage over all its other
source material is that it gives you some close-up views of
Sweeney's expressive face, which add to the amusement in her
anecdotes about her devoutly Catholic but somewhat daffy mother and
to the pathos when Sweeney tells of her brother's decline.
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with the earlier incarnations will notice that a
couple of humorous stories (about attending a Broadway show with
her parents and about being ignored at Starbucks) have been
excised. Although those portions are missed, their omission is
probably a good thing: The CD version of the show runs more than
two hours, which would be far too long for a one-person movie.
Sweeney directed herself, and that's a minor tactical error; if
someone like Jonathan Demme, who has shown a knack for filming
performance in ``Stop Making Sense'' and ``Swimming to Cambodia,''
had been behind the camera, this really could have come to life.
The words remain entertaining, and they make the film worthwhile _
even if, in the end, it doesn't amount to much of a movie.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``God Said, `Ha!'''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Julia Sweeney
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Julia Sweeney
</P>
<P>
   Length: 86 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ A couple of swear words, and frank talk about
sex, drug use and death
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
