<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6602 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PCBs-CANCER-HNS &LR;      03-11 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCBs-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GE STUDY ON PCB CONTAMINATION DRAWS SKEPTICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The New York attorney general's office and
environmentalists have questioned the validity of the latest study
on PCBs that showed no significant increase in cancer deaths among
workers who were exposed to the chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The study was financed by the General Electric Co., which stands
to lose hundreds of millions of dollars if found liable for
cleaning up the tons of PCBs that were discharged into the Hudson
River from its factories in Fort Edward and Hudson Falls between
1946 and 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency is weighing whether GE
should dredge the chemicals from the river or leave them untouched.
A decision is expected in early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   This latest study, released Wednesday, did not address the issue
of the Hudson River and won't settle the continuing debate between
environmentalists and GE, which is based in Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general is quite skeptical,'' said Marc Violette,
a spokesman for state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer. ``This report
appears to contradict scores of independent studies over the years
which show known health risks associated with PCB exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, the federal government has characterized
PCBs as probable human carcinogens, in part because of a 1975 study
by Dr. Renate Kimbrough that linked PCBs and cancer in laboratory
rats.
</P>
<P>
   Kimbrough, the lead researcher on the latest study, said there's
no evidence that the chemicals pose a similar risk to humans. The
study, the largest done to date, focused on 7,075 men and women who
worked at the plants between 1946 and 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers looked at the 1,195 workers in the group who
have since died and compared the causes of death to national and
regional averages. Among all workers, even those with the highest
exposures to PCBs, they found that the death rate attributable to
cancer was the same or lower than would be expected in the general
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is looking at all of these workers and doing
all of these analyses, we did not find any significant health
effects,'' Kimbrough said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are trying to determine why lab studies on rats don't
always translate into similar results in humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason you may have this discrepancy is that humans just
don't react to the same insults of PCBs as humans,'' Kimbrough
said.
</P>
<P>
   PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls, are man-made, non-flammable
chemicals that were used commercially by GE as the insulation in
large transformers and capacitors. They were also used as coolants,
lubricants and hydraulic fluids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do think this is a very significant study and needs to be
factored into the regulatory discussion on PCBs and on the public
discussion,'' GE spokesman Mark Behan said at a news conference in
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Behan declined to say how much the study cost, although he said
the company has spent ``millions'' on PCB research.
</P>
<P>
   State Health Department officials said they were in the middle
of reviewing the study.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists expressed skepticism as to how much weight the
study might carry with policymakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still hoping GE will be compelled to clean up the Hudson
River and do so quickly,'' said Larry Shapiro, the senior attorney
for the New York Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Lee, environmental director for Scenic Hudson in
Poughkeepsie, a river advocacy group, questioned the way the study
was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that when there's more analysis of this report, we're
going to find a lot of problems with the way this data was used,''
she said. ``Statistics can do whatever you want them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimbrough defended her scientific method, adding that an
independent panel of experts reviewed her work during the eight
years it took to complete the study. She said she used various
sources of information, from GE company records to Credit Bureau
reports. At one point, she hired private investigators to help her
locate workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like counting beans,'' she said. ``You get the death
certificates and compare them to the general population. There's
really no way to bias that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public should be skeptical about sources of information
and keep in mind that there are vested interests at work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
