<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     03-11 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP DEBATES ITS SOUL AND SUBSTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 14)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As roughly a dozen aspirants line up to challenge
one other for the Republican presidential nomination next year, the
most profound decision GOP voters may face is deciding which
philosophical route they plan to take into the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be the road of pragmatic progressivism and
internationalism or that of myopic nationalism and a return to
isolationist-protectionist policies of the distant past?
</P>
<P>
   With so many contenders, the Republicans have a choice among
candidates who represent a broad spectrum of ideas and values. All
of them talk of reduced government, less federal spending, tax cuts
and the return of more responsibilities to the local level.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Democrats, they promise to protect Social
Security and Medicare and boost funding for national defense.
</P>
<P>
   But they are divided on matters such as abortion, equal justice
for gays, shifting educational funds from public to private
schools, restoring prayer to the classroom and various other
policies advocated by the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over a party's soul and substance is not new to
either Republicans or Democrats. And it is the kind of debate both
should have almost constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Although a political party needs a philosophical base _ whether
it be right, left or center _ it also needs to be a living, dynamic
institution, not a petrified structure bound to the policies of
yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party was ripped asunder in the 1960s by the
Vietnam War, a revolutionary shift in moral values and violent
demonstrations in cities and on college campuses. But it struggled
back, with the help of Richard Nixon and Watergate and eventually
Bill Clinton's efforts to move the party from the left to the
center of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Now it must find its way into the future by trying to escape the
odor of the Clinton impeachment scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have faced internecine warfare repeatedly since
Theodore Roosevelt, in a dramatic break with the past, gave America
a new purpose and new vision at the beginning of the 20th century.
He made the United States a world power, won the Nobel Peace Prize
for mediating an end to the Russo-Japanese War of 1904-05, went
after monopolies as an aggressive trust-buster, built the Panama
Canal and decreed that the safest foreign policy for the United
States was to ``speak softly and carry a big stick.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP retreated into isolationism between World Wars I and II
but shed that tainted veil with the election of Dwight D.
Eisenhower as president in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ike 47 years ago, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, son of the
last Republican president, symbolizes the Republican establishment,
which has played a major role in setting America's foreign policy
agenda in the second half of this century.The symbol at the other
end of the spectrum _ the one that calls for trade protectionism, a
pullback of America's responsibilities abroad and a tough stance
against immigration _ is Patrick Buchanan, the one-time Nixon
speech writer who is making his third try for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The other contenders seem to be situated ideologically in
between.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who still must define his stands on crucial issues, has a
bounty of endorsements and attributes that should be the envy of
his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But no prize may be more vital to his future than the fact that
he is supported by half or more of the 31 Republican governors, the
men and women who direct the destinies of their states with an
admirable mixture of efficiency, pragmatism and political
perspicacity. They can help him win primaries and carry their
states on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Probably not since Eisenhower snatched the GOP nomination from
the conservative Sen. Robert A.Taft nearly a half century ago has a
Republican presidential hopeful's bid been bolstered by so many
sitting governors.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them find in Bush the kind of forward-looking moderate
who reflects their own approach to governmental problems and who
stands as a barrier to a total takeover of the party by the
right-wing militants. The governors also see him as a winner with
an ample bankroll at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, as the personification of the Republican
establishment, is exactly the kind of opponent Buchanan relishes.
Buchanan is at war with the establishment. He tried unsuccessfully
to snatch the GOP nomination from President George Bush in 1992 and
then from Bob Dole in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Ike, Governor Bush is not a war hero whose popularity
transcends partisanship. Nor are times as desperate as they were in
1952, when Ike was seen by Americans as the leader who could
extricate the nation from a bloody, stalemated conflict in Korea
while at the same time continuing to support war-ravaged Western
Europe with the Marshall Plan and NATO.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle for the soul of the Republican Party may be just
as intense in 2000 as it was 47 years ago. Buchanan, a politician
with street-brawler instincts and a certain appeal to industrial
workers and their families, will not be bound by Marquis of
Queensbury rules.
</P>
<P>
   That means Bush and other contenders for the GOP nomination had
better prepare to remove their gloves and get ready for a good
fight. The battle should be a lively one: compassionate
conservatism vs. a passionate return to Old Guardism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
