<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISION ON 2003 SUPER BOWL DUE SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The National Football League plans an
announcement soon on whether it will confirm or withdraw its
invitation to San Francisco to serve as host city for the Super
Bowl in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL withdraws the invitation at its annual meeting in
Phoenix next week, a regional task force will offer a plan to host
the game in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding to host Super Bowls is intense because the games
have been shown to generate revenues of $200 million to $300
million for their host cities.
</P>
<P>
   Staff-level discussions between the Oakland Coliseum and the NFL
have been held, according to Coliseum Commissioner Gail Steele.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco 49ers and San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown say
they expect to have a stadium built in time for Super Bowl XXXVII,
but the chairman of the Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum Commission,
Ignacio de la Fuente, said Wednesday he doubted that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an item of urgency,'' he said. ``We are going to be
ready and let the NFL know we have corporate backing.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Fuente said a 7,500-seat expansion of the coliseum's
capacity to 70,000 seats _ the minimum the NFL requires for Super
Bowls _ would cost $750,000 to $1 million. Corporate support would
be needed to make the host plan work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue expressed doubts in January
about San Francisco as the host city. A league spokesman said
Wednesday that a decision on San Francisco as site for the 2003
Super Bowl would be made public Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Citing problems with the 49ers' proposal to build a new stadium
and adjoining commercial center, at a cost of $525 million,
Tagliabue said in January that Super Bowl XXXVII would be moved to
another city if the project did not come together soon.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue mentioned San Diego, Oakland and Los Angeles as
alternative sites, singling out San Diego as the ``front-runner.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco stadium proposal has been dogged by delays,
rising estimates and management problems. The team's co-owner,
Edward DeBartolo Jr., has been suspended over his conviction in a
federal gambling and bribery case.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo was suspended provisionally through the end of the
1999 season, but the league has indicated that final action may be
taken next week.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown is still engaged in talks with Tagliabue in an
effort to keep the game in the city, there is no design yet for a
new stadium and the troubled project's environmental impact report
is overdue. Nor have club officials dealt with demands from public
officials that they provide up to $60 million to offset anticipated
effects on traffic, transportation and parks.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Singer, spokesman for the Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. of
Youngstown, Ohio, which controls the club and would build the
stadium, said this week that the corporation intends to meet NFL
requirements for the 2003 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing everything within our power to try to provide a
venue,'' Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   Design and financing proposals recently were presented to
corporate officials, he said, adding, ``They're looking at a
variety of options and opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The corporation has not officially backed away from the original
$525 million project that San Francisco voters approved in 1997,
but it also has said it was exploring all options.
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with DeBartolo Corp. deliberations said little
concrete detail was in place when the company's chairman and chief
executive officer, Denise DeBartolo York, took over club operations
from her brother, Eddie, late in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hampered by Eddie's having forged ahead without really
taking a look at how to make this thing work,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing that now _ talking to architects, banks and
planners. Their heart is in trying to make it work for 2003, but
they're also behind because Eddie left them holding the bag on
something he hadn't fleshed out.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo's spokesman, Rick Rice, denied the accusation, saying
that when DeBartolo voluntarily stepped down from club management,
``he felt the project was in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie remains committed to the stadium. He was diligently
pursuing that project,'' Rice said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
