<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WINGCOMMANDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WING COMMANDER' DOESN'T FLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The theater was abuzz at the promotional screening for ``Wing
Commander'' _ but not because of ``Wing Commander,'' which turns
out to be as interesting as dropping $6.50 in a video game and then
standing there staring at it with your hands in your pockets for an
hour and a half.
</P>
<P>
   No, the excitement had to do with ``Wing Commander's'' being a
20th Century Fox movie _ making it possible, just possible, that
there would be a new preview for the new ``Star Wars'' movie
attached. No such luck. Much of the crowd even sat through ``Wing
Commander's'' closing credits, in the hopes that the trailer would
appear after the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they were just asleep. Or maybe they thought that
``Wing Commander'' was the trailer, although that's unlikely,
because it's the kind of imagination-starved space opera that the
first ``Star Wars'' made obsolete. Freddie Prinze Jr. and Matthew
Lillard play hotshot pilots, ``Top Gun''-style: Prinze is the
maverick who inevitably falls for his female wing commander _ and
somewhat inexplicably, since Saffron Burrows plays her with all the
personality of a cantaloupe. Lillard plays the clown who you just
know will be a danger to himself and others; Jon Cryer's ``For some
reason, everybody calls me `Dead Meat''' refrain from ``Hot
Shots!'' kept springing to mind.
</P>
<P>
   This Freddie Prinze Jr. thing _ don't get it. Yes, the hot young
star is good-looking, and he has a pedigree replete with tragedy.
That doesn't mean he can act, although he is expanding his range:
In ``She's All That,'' he expressed emotions with a furrowed brow,
as if he were fighting off a migraine; in ``Wing Commander,'' he
expresses them with a gaping mouth, as if he were a goldfish
panicked about a lack of water. Lillard, probably the hammiest of
the current crop of young actors, is fun to watch for a while, but
then the screenplay forces him to ``think about what he's done,''
and he becomes serious and boring.
</P>
<P>
   The plot? It's something about humans battling aliens called the
Kilrathi, who are apparently terrifying because they recall bad
'50s sci-fi. There's also some blather about how Prinze's Blair is
a human/alien half-breed, which gives him intuitive navigational
skills but also makes all his allies suspicious of him. Director
Chris Roberts, who created the Wing Commander computer game,
doesn't make things clear with his muddled screenplay (it often
sounds like a game-play manual), although it is comforting to know
that in 2564, we'll still be drinking Johnny Walker Red and saying
things like ``It ain't no thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A particularly charitable audience member remarked after the
screening that the movie reminded him of the first ``Star Wars.''
Well, that's true, in that it does have (celestial) stars, and it
is about a war. It doesn't have ground-breaking special effects, a
myth-making story, interesting lead characters or any supporting
characters to speak of (fine actors such as David Suchet and Jurgen
Prochnow are wasted). Look, ``Star Wars'' fans, if you REALLY need
to see a ``Phantom Menace'' trailer all that badly, download it
from the Web site. But what's your hurry? It's not like ``Menace''
will go away any time soon. ``Wing Commander,'' however, mercifully
will.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Wing Commander''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Chris Roberts
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Freddie Prinze Jr., Matthew Lillard
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ violence, some strong language and sexual
situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
