<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THERAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE PALMA'S ORIGINAL SHAMES `CARRIE' UPDATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teen movies are to the late '90s what grunge music was to the
early '90s: A couple of hits, and suddenly everyone's playing
copycat, oblivious to the fact that such bandwagon-hopping leads to
a genre's self-destruction. With grunge, the success of Nirvana and
Pearl Jam left a trail of mediocrity in its wake; with movies,
``Scream'' and ``I Know What You Did Last Summer'' have led to such
losers as ``The Rage: Carrie 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Nominally a sequel to the 1976 Brian De Palma hit about a shy
and telekinetic teen girl, ``The Rage'' is more of a remake of
``Carrie'' _ and less a remake than a pastiche of the worst of
1999's ``other'' teen movies: ``She's All That'' (misfit heroine,
big party scene), ``Varsity Blues'' (sensitive jock hero, big
football game), ``Jawbreaker'' (conspiratorial vixens) and ``Cruel
Intentions'' (sexual games without thought of consequence).
``October Sky,'' a movie about teens that's not really a teen
movie, got left out, because no character in ``The Rage'' is a
rocket scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rage'' _ what a title _ doesn't even feature a character
named Carrie, unless you count the flashbacks featuring Sissy
Spacek from the '76 film. It's about Rachel Lang (newcomer Emily
Bergl), raised by trashy foster parents after her mother was
hospitalized for acute schizophrenia (seems Mom was unnerved by her
daughter's ability to move objects without touching them). Rachel
attracts the attention of the incurably romantic Jesse (Jason
London, twin brother of ``Party of Five's'' Jeremy), but she's
understandably suspicious of him, because Jesse's football-playing
buds are playing a game of sex-for-points, which led to the suicide
of Rachel's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief period, ``The Rage'' looks like it's going to
transcend its teen-movie conventions with its sensitive (albeit
contrived) treatment of Rachel, whom Bergl plays with far too much
confidence for such an outsider character (Spacek earned an Oscar
nomination with her finely observed portrayal of the original
Carrie's introversion).
</P>
<P>
   But as the movie turns toward horror, it lapses into
heavy-handed melodramatics and ludicrousness. In the original,
Carrie's telekinesis stemmed from her repression _ she kept
feelings bottled up so deeply that when she let them loose, things
around her exploded. Here, Rachel's ... er, condition ... is
explained as a genetic disorder (Amy Irving, the only link to the
original, is saddled with this speech).
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Varsity Blues'' and the marginally better ``Cruel
Intentions,'' ``The Rage'' is uncomfortably obsessed with teen sex
_ it should've been called ``The Raging Hormones'' _ without a
thought about the dangers of AIDS or any other sexual fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``She's All That,'' it features a heroine who's only
unattractive in the Hollywood sense _ that is, she doesn't doll
herself up like all those nasty, evil girls do. As with almost all
the recent teen movies, the young people here are almost impossibly
affluent _ wait'll you see the house where the party scene takes
place _ and the outcast heroine is the only person from the wrong
side of the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope the teens who bother to compare the original with
``Rage'' realize the difference between a movie with dazzling style
_ De Palma's master craftsmanship injected the original with
incredible flash and verve _ and a movie with little style at all.
Given that ``Rage,'' like the teen films it apes, reflects their
culture in the most cynical light, it may be time for the kids to
boycott.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Rage: Carrie 2''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Katt Shea
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Emily Bergl, Jason London
</P>
<P>
   Length: 104 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ sexual situations, strong language and graphic
violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
