<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS12-     03-11 2568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel, Steve Murray and Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affliction'' R (profanity and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nick Nolte and James Coburn.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar nominee Nick Nolte gives a searing, career-defining
performance in this soul-weary study of one of the walking dead.
Nolte plays a troubled New England cop whose ``afflictions''
include an angry ex-wife, a frightened young daughter, a boss who
belittles him and a roaringly abusive father (James Coburn, also
Oscar-nominated). 1 hour, 44 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This'' R (profanity, sexuality, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Robert De Niro, Billy Crystal and Lisa Kudrow.
</P>
<P>
   This farce about a mobster (Robert De Niro) who takes his issues
to a psychiatrist (Billy Crystal) never becomes the laugh-riot it
could be. It's an offer you could refuse, but the stars (plus Lisa
Kudrow as Crystal's fiancee) make it worthwhile.1 hour, 46 minutes.
B
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Geniuses'' PG
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kathleen Turner, Peter MacNicol, Christoper Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Turner and Peter MacNicol play rival researchers _ she
the breathy villainess, he the bland do-bee _ rushing to crack the
baby talk code emanating from five brilliant babes. Sly _ the
toddler leader _ has got a secret twin and you've got yourself 94
minutes chock full of stupid pint-sized tricks from the brain of
Bob Clark. At first, ``Geniuses'' is dumb, and then it just gets
dumber.94 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Beloved'' R (violent images, sexuality, nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Oprah Winfrey, Danny Glover, Thandie Newton and
Kimberly Elise.
</P>
<P>
   An A-list epic that inadvertently proves that Toni Morrison's
novels are unfilmable. Oprah Winfrey plays Sethe, a former slave
haunted by the ghost of her dead daughter, who takes in the
mysterious stranger Beloved (Thandie Newton). Too faithful to
Morrison's magic-realist prose, the movie substitutes mood for
emotional power and narrative clarity. 2 hours, 52 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Blast From the Past'' PG-13 (profanity, sex, drug references)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brendan Fraser, Christopher Walken and Sissy Spacek.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Fraser does another culture-clash, fish-out-of-water
flick, playing a guy who climbs into the '90s after spending all
his life in a bomb shelter. You wait for the high-concept comedy to
make some smart observations (or at least some decent jokes) about
the collision of the '60s and '90s. But the humor and the plot are
amateurish, leaving its cast flailing. 1 hour, 52 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Central Station'' R (profanity and mature themes)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Fernanda Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   In this tender and unexpectedly moving Brazilian film, a sour
old woman (Oscar nominee Fernanda Montenegro) takes a motherless
boy she barely knows into rural Brazil to find the father he's
never met. Montenegro's performance is a beautiful study in
bitterness dissuaded, of possibility and optimism stumbled on after
too long an absence from someone's life. Subtitles. 1 hour, 55
minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Corruptor'' R (violence, profanity, sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Chow Yun-Fat, Mark Wahlberg.
</P>
<P>
   Chow Yun-Fat and Mark Wahlberg play Chinatown cops forging an
uneasy truce in this violent, densely plotted action flick. Fueled
with betrayals and gunfire, it's the closest thing yet to Chow's
Hong King collaborations with John Woo. 1 hour, 51 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruel Intentions'' R (profanity, sexual situations, drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sarah Michelle Gellar, Ryan Phillippe and Selma Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Last decade's ``Dangerous Liaisons'' gets a makeover with Sarah
Michelle Gellar and Ryan Phillippe as a couple of desultorily rich
teens manipulating the romantic lives of everyone around them,
purely for their own amusement and without a whit of concern about
who may be hurt in the process. It's practically guaranteed to be a
runaway hit with the teen audience.1 hour, 37 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michelle Pfeiffer and Treat Williams.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when your son turns up living two blocks away with
a man who has no idea his then-unbalanced, now-deceased wife
kidnapped him years ago? Well, in this movie you become Michelle
Pfeiffer and self-absorb your way to family bliss. They should post
a warning: the deep end of this ocean is filled with melodrama. 1
hour and 45 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight Millimeter'' R (strong perverse sexuality, violence,
profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nicolas Cage and Joaquin Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   A new example of Morbidity Chic from the screenwriter of
``Seven.'' Nicolas Cage plays a private investigator pursuing the
possible death of a girl in a snuff flick. It's an unpleasant crawl
through the world of porn; you can tell the filmmakers think it's a
troubling exploration of moral ambiguity, but it's an exploitation
flick tricked out as art. At metro theaters. 2 hours, 3 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth'' R (violence and sex)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Cate Blanchett and Geoffrey Rush.
</P>
<P>
   This opulent period film puts a slight feminist gloss on the
early reign of 16th-century monarch Elizabeth I, showing her
transformation from a radiant, saucy innocent to a polished,
guarded ruler. Oscar nominee Cate Blanchett gives a luminous
portrayal, and Geoffrey Rush, also an Oscar nominee, gives her
sturdy support as court politics and intrigues swirl about. This is
a really good story. 2 hours, 4 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Everest'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by David Breashears.
</P>
<P>
   Breathtaking. Even filmgoers accustomed to the five-story IMAX
format may gasp at the unearthly scale of ``Everest.'' David
Breashears'
</P>
<P>
   documentary was filmed at the same time as the 1996 storm that
killed eight mountain climbers, memorialized by Jon Krakauer's
best-selling book ``Into Thin Air.'' 44 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``The General'' R (profanity and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brendan Gleeson.
</P>
<P>
   An entertaining character study of Martin Cahill, a real-life
Dublin criminal who was both lovable rogue and ugly thug. A cunning
thief who took everything from jewels to Vermeers, Cahill is shown
by writer/director John Boorman to be a natural contrarian, who
thumbed his nose at the IRA as well as the cops. Brendan Gleeson
gives a brilliant, blustery performance as Cahill. 3 hours, 3
minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters'' Not rated but sexual themes and brief
nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ian McKellen and Brendan Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   Three Oscar nominations. A brilliant reimagining of the final
days of gay British director James Whale. Whale, best known for his
classic horror movies (``Bride of Frankenstein''), died
mysteriously in 1957. Played here by the marvelous Ian McKellen
(best actor), he's an isolated, forgotten recluse who becomes
interested in the hunky new gardener (Brendan Fraser). 1 hour, 35
minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Is Beautiful'' PG-13 (Holocaust-related atrocities)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Roberto Benigni.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Oscar nominations including best picture, best actor and
best screenplay. An Italian Jew shields his son from the horrors of
a concentration camp by pretending their predicament is part of a
big, complicated game. Roberto Benigni's low-comedy slapstick
approach isn't entirely convincing and is often chillingly
wrongheaded. Subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 2 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' R (violence and
profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nick Moran and Jason Flemyng.
</P>
<P>
   Smokin'. This whip-smart lark is an English caper comedy
glistening with confidence and a wicked sense of humor. Four
likable, somewhat conniving East End lads have a week to settle the
debt they owe a hood named Hatchet Harry. Rookie writer/director
Guy Ritchie piles on the characters, the plot twists and the
violence, but one thing is clear: Everyone involved had a fine time
making this movie. You'll have fun watching it. 1 hour, 45 minutes.
A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Message in a Bottle'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Costner, RobinWright Penn and Paul Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Two messages here: Old-fashioned romances still work, and Kevin
Costner needs an ego check. Badly. For a good while, the movie lets
us luxuriate in the pleasures of sailboats, sunsets, candlelit
dinners, etc. Plus, there's comic relief courtesy of Paul Newman
and Robbie Contrane. But the last 15 minutes are a lunkheaded
embarrassment and Costner (he co-produced) is to blame. 2 hours, 12
minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``My Favorite Martian'' PG (violence, partial nudity and
profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jeff Daniels and Christopher Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   A big-screen remake of the '60s TV series, with the annoying and
unsubtle Christopher Lloyd as the Martian who camps in Jeff
Daniels' living room. The movie is cobbled together with cheesy
special effects and easy gags. But for kids, it's an OK
baby-sitter. 1 hour, 33 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``October Sky'' PG (profanity, sensuality, alcohol use, some
thematic elements)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jake Gyllenhaal, Chris Cooper and Laura Dern.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply satisfying tale of West Virginia teen Homer (Jake
Gyllenhaal) and three friends who, in the 1950s, began to build and
shoot off model rockets. Their goal: to win a science fair, which
could help them escape a future of working in the coal mine of
their small town. Based on Homer Hickam's autobiography ``Rocket
Boys,'' it makes the process of learning seem as exciting as a
special FX-driven action flick. 1 hour, 48 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Office Space'' R (profanity, partial nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ron Livingston, Jennifer Aniston, Stephen Root and Gary
Cole.
</P>
<P>
   An amusingly and eerily familiar comedy for anyone who's ever
struggled against the monotonous mind control of a large corporate
workplace. After wittily building audience resentment for nearly 90
minutes, writer-director Mike Judge (TV's ``Beavis &AMP; Butt-head,''
``King of the Hill'') seems to pull his punches with a
less-than-apocalyptic ending.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 30 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Other Sister'' PG-13 (thematic elements involving
sex-related material)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Juliette Lewis and Diane Keaton.
</P>
<P>
   Juliette Lewis' effective performance as a mentally challenged
woman is the best reason to see this comedy drama, an uneasy
mixture of sentimentality and yucks. Diane Keaton plays her
overprotective mother, and Giovanni Ribisi (also very strong) is
the man she falls for. 2 hours, 11 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback'' R (violence, profanity, drug and sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mel Gibson and Gregg Henry.
</P>
<P>
   A by-the-numbers vengeance thriller starring Mel Gibson. It's as
generic as its unnamed, dull gray city. 1 hour, 42 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rage: Carrie 2'' R (violence, gore, sexuality, profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Emily Bergl, Amy Irving.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Bergl plays a misunderstood, telekinetic teen in this
cheap, dull horror flick. The sort-of sequel is so bad, you might
mistake it for self-parody. Amy Irving also stars as the first
film's survivor, but skulks through her scenes looking like she's
ready to kill her agent. 1 hour, 45 minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``Rushmore'' R (profanity and brief nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jason Schwartzman, Bill Murray and Olivia Williams.
</P>
<P>
   This original prep school fable pits 15-year-old Max (Jason
Schwartzman) against a tycoon (Bill Murray) in a battle for the
love of a schoolteacher (Olivia Williams). The second film from
director Wes Anderson and co-writer Owen Wilson proves that they
haven't lost the off-kilter wit and viewpoint they first showed in
``Bottle Rocket.''
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 33 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love'' R (sexuality, nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth Paltrow and Geoffrey Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen Oscar nominations including best picture. Poor,
overworked Will Shakespeare (Joseph Fiennes) has to finish his play
``Romeo and Ethel, the Pirate's Daughter'' and try to win the hand
of noblewoman Viola (Gwyneth Paltrow) in this witty comedy that
uses some of the Bard's more outrageous plot devices. 2 hours, 2
minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``She's All That'' PG-13 (profanity, sexual innuendo)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Freddie Prinze Jr. and Rachael Leigh Cook.
</P>
<P>
   High school star Zack (Freddie Prinze Jr.) accepts a bet to turn
geeky Laney (Rachael Leigh Cook) into a prom queen, and falls in
love with her. An amusing, genial reworking of ``Pygmalion,'' the
comedy has one big problem: Its leads are beautiful, but distant. 1
hour, 37 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``A Simple Plan'' R (profanity, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton and Bridget Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   Anything but simple, this is a character-driven black comedy
with some powerful moral-qualm undercurrents. In the deep snows of
rural Minnesota, two brothers (Bill Paxton, Oscar nominee Billy Bob
Thornton) and a pal (Brent Briscoe) find a downed plane with $4
million in cash. Their ``simple plan'' to split the money leads to
a chain of increasingly disastrous events. 1 hour, 57 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thin Red Line'' R (profanity and war violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sean Penn, Jim Caviezel, Nick Nolte, Woody Harrelson
and Adrien Brody.
</P>
<P>
   Less a war movie than a meditation on life, death, love, hate,
man and nature. Terrence Malick puts his unmistakable stamp on the
drama of an Army division's struggle to capture Guadalcanal from
the Japanese during World War II. Fueled with voice-overs, gorgeous
images and sudden violence, it's superbly strange, an epic that
feels intimate but distant at the same time. 2 hours, 50 minutes.
B-
</P>
<P>
   ``T. rex: Back to the Cretaceous'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   Starring Liz Stauber and Peter Horton.
</P>
<P>
   The IMAX film has awesome special effects but, as a fictional
story, is too short. Ally Hayden (Liz Stauber) is a budding teenage
paleontologist who wants to go on a dig with her dino-hunting dad
(Peter Horton). When her dad brings what could be a dinosaur egg
into his lab, Ally, alone with it, accidentally cracks it and is
thrust back in time 65 million years, when the big beasts roamed
the Earth. 40 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``200 Cigarettes'' R (profanity, sexual situations, alcohol use)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Courtney Love, Ben Affleck and Christina Ricci.
</P>
<P>
   Like a New Year's Eve nightmare writ large, numerous New Yorkers
struggle to hook up with someone on the way to an end-of-1981
party. Most of the characters are obnoxious and sex-obsessed, but a
few performances, the only-in-the '80s outfits and most especially,
the music, shine through. 1 hour, 27 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Wing Commander'' PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Starring Freddie Prinze Jr., Mathew Lillard and Saffron Burrows.
</P>
<P>
   It's one loopy space lark, with pretty boy Freddie Prinze Jr.
and ``Scream's'' wonderfully woozy killer Matthew Lillard playing
fighter pilots in a galaxy at war. Earth is threatened by a
lumbering band of cat-like creatures wrapped in armadillo armor. It
takes eons for ``Wing,'' based on the popular computer game, to get
to the first big dogfight. 1 hour, 53 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolves'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Not as visually stunning as some IMAX films, this is a highly
instructive look at the once nearly vanquished gray wolf's gradual
reintroduction to Yellowstone National Park and other parts of the
American West. Covers a bit too much ground, historically and
geographically; the best parts show wolves ranging from adult pack
leaders to newborn cubs exploring and adjusting to the wild again.
41 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
