<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6662 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX     03-11 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seat-of-pants proposals take school funds into wild blue yonder
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If we take a hint from what happened last week
with charter schools, should Texas ever adopt a ``pilot'' voucher
program, in two years it wouldn't matter if 200 voucherized schools
have gone belly-up, if four dozen have been cited for fraud, and if
one had passed out poison Kool-Aid on a message from God.
</P>
<P>
   Texas would authorize a few hundred million more dollars for
school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in the face of many questions about charter schools,
and lacking evidence that they produce a solid yield on Texas'
investment, the state school board voted to lift the cap on the
number of charters the state could authorize. The 8-7 vote reversed
a hold-that-line vote which presumably was a message that Texas
should have a better handle on whether these open-enrollment,
state-funded schools performed as advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Charter proponents in the legislature had threatened to revoke
the board's power to authorize charters unless it supported more of
them.
</P>
<P>
   This rush to seed more charter schools comes in spite of
initially dismal test scores from 17 of the original 19 charters
(results on the other 130 in operation are unavailable), and horror
tales shared last week at a hearing by the board's planning
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The committee heard, for instance, of Waco's E.L. Harrison
Charter School, which has never made payments to the Teacher
Retirement System and is more than $275,000 in debt.
</P>
<P>
   One Houston charter school, Cypress Lodge Charter, took $240,000
of state money and never opened its doors. The Texas Education
Agency had to appoint a master to a third financially troubled
Houston charter.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it's too early to judge to what extent charter schools
in general are debacles or miracles, seemingly policy makers would
be circumspect about pumping more money into what in some cases may
turn out to be dubious Tinker Toys.
</P>
<P>
   Now for vouchers?
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Senate Bill 10 by State Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo,
to authorize vouchers that could be used by low-achieving students
in six major metropolitan districts. Private schools accepting
vouchers would have two years to gain accreditation, of what sort
we would have to rely on the state education commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins says he's neither pro-nor anti-voucher. He just wants to
see if the concept works. Students using vouchers would have to
take the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills. Results would be
compared with those of students ``of similar age and background.''
Sounds reasonable. But how within ``similar age and background''
does Texas quantify the participation of a parent in a child's
education? Many parents in public schools are fully engaged in
their children's education. Some aren't. Comparing children of
disengaged parents with those whose parents are involved is
apples-to-crab-apples analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Open-ended measure
</P>
<P>
   The bill appears to set the bar high for participating schools
with a ``partial termination'' clause. In year 2005 a school would
not be able to not accept vouchers ``unless that school's average
student performance level. . . is at least 10 percent higher than
the average performance level of comparable public school
students.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there's no clear provision in Bivins' bill for
scrapping vouchers in general, meaning schools that beat the 10
percent threshold could continue to accept vouchers forever.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened in the interim, Bivins' proposal would amount
to six years, three biennia, of funding private schools, including
church-run schools with no strings attached about how they use tax
dollars for religion.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins' professed clinical interests aside, this is
self-fulfilling legislation. Call it a pilot if you will. But it
portends to be a drain on public school funding from here to
eternity, with fly-by-night operations to cash in at take-off.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco, Texas
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
