<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6665 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-CORRUPTOR12-CO     03-11 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-CORRUPTOR12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bullets fly, tale twists in bloody `Corruptor'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The longer you watch ``The Corruptor,'' the more you realize
there ought to be an ``s'' at the end of that title. In the
blood-and-neon underworld of this Chow Yun-Fat vehicle, everyone is
out to bend someone else to his will _ through sex or drugs, money
or blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   Chow plays Nick Chen, star officer of the NYPD's Asian Gang
Unit, in charge of patrolling the streets of Chinatown. His latest
challenge: a bloody rivalry between the older Triad gang and a
bunch of upstarts led by a punk-haired kid named Bobby Vu (Byron
Mann). Into this tense setup strolls rookie Danny Wallace (Mark
Wahlberg). He's supposed to be Nick's new partner, but in the grand
tradition of a hundred cop flicks before, Nick complains to his
boss, ``He's green!''
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the script's many threadbare lines, along with
Nick's warning, ``You don't change Chinatown, boy, it changes
you.'' (That's not only a lame sentiment, it's dangerously close to
Joaquin Phoenix's howler about dancing with the devil in ``Eight
Millimeter.'')
</P>
<P>
   But you don't go to a movie like this to savor the dialogue.
``The Corruptor'' is a stylish genre exercise that's selling
hard-guy angst to bloodthirsty teen boys. (Even the name of the
young gang seems designed to make the Clearasil set break out in
giggles and nudges: the Fukienese Dragons.)
</P>
<P>
   Directed by James Foley, ``Corruptor'' tries to duplicate the
outrageous bouts of violence and the byzantine codes of honor found
in Chow's Hong Kong action films. In its opening minutes, it even
maneuvers the star into his trademark position: on the floor, a
pistol in both fists, firing endless rounds of bullets at the bad
guys.
</P>
<P>
   But exactly who the real bad guys are is a slippery question.
The plot can wear you out with its twists and counter-twists, as we
discover that neither Nick nor Danny is exactly who he seems to be.
The story takes us deep into a noirish Chinatown that's personified
by painstakingly polite but ruthless gangster Henry Lee (Ric
Young), who schemes to get both cops under his thumb.
</P>
<P>
   While you're trying to keep straight who's double-crossing whom,
the movie whips up some hyperviolence, including a couple of tense
car chases that fill the streets with twisted metal and bystanders'
corpses. There's also a subplot about Danny's uneasy relationship
with his father, a former cop who's now in debt to some goons. The
story feels overfamiliar, but actor Brian Cox gives the father
welcome shading.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's real star is cinematographer Juan Ruiz-Anchia.
Punctuating shadows with patches of gold, red and blue, he creates
a world that can simultaneously look cold and seductive.
</P>
<P>
   While Chow's Hollywood debut, ``The Replacement Killers,''
played more like an MTV riff on his movies with John Woo (``The
Killer,'' ``Hard-Boiled''), the new film comes closer to the real
thing. But it doesn't have the melancholy, romantic thread director
Woo tugged shamelessly but skillfully in other films (the blind
girl in ``The Killer,'' the imperiled babies in ``Hard-Boiled'').
``Corruptor's'' emotional core is the fragile loyalty between Nick
and Danny, but that never really seems enough.
</P>
<P>
   Chow comes off best here, working his volatile mix of charm and
mad-dog menace; unfortunately, his accent makes a few scenes even
harder to follow than they should be. Wahlberg is OK, but his
unmodulated, little-boy-lost whisper can get tiresome. He comes off
like a cop making his rounds on heavy medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Corruptor''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Chow Yun-Fat and Mark Wahlberg. Rated R for strong
violence, language and sexuality. 1 hour, 51 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A moody shoot-'em-up that captures the bloody
romanticism of Chow Yun-Fat's Hong Kong flicks.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
