<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6666 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-LOCK12-COX     03-11 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-LOCK12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `LOCK' glistens with confidence and a wicked sense of humor
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's how it works in the deliciously clever ``Lock, Stock and
Two Smoking Barrels,'' a new comedy-caper flick from Britain: There
are small-time bad guys, there are big-time bad guys, and there are
bad guys who are just kinda timeless.
</P>
<P>
   In the first category fall four likable young lads _ Eddie (Nick
Moran), Tom (Jason Flemyng), Soap (Dexter Fletcher) and Bacon
(Jason Statham) _ who aren't really so much bad as a bit too
conniving. They'd like to make a pile of money without working for
it. To that end they back Eddie, the cardsharp of the group, in a
high-stakes poker game.
</P>
<P>
   The game is, of course, rigged, and our boys end up owing
something like half a million pounds to a big-time bad guy known as
Hatchet Harry (P.H. Moriarty). While someone like Tom may have
``his dirty little fingers in a couple of dirty little pies,''
Hatchet Harry is someone with ``all his fingers into some very big
dirty pies.'' And, speaking of fingers, if they don't come up with
the cash in a week, Hatchet Harry's enforcer, Big Chris _ a
timeless bad guy played with deadpan aplomb by soccer star-thug
Vinnie Jones _ will cheerfully remove a digit each day the debt is
overdue.
</P>
<P>
   Things only get more complicated from there, with rookie
writer-director Guy Ritchie piling on the characters (including
Sting in a cameo as Eddie's bar-owner dad) and plot twists. But
don't be scared off by the intricate narrative (you followed ``The
Usual Suspects,'' didn't you?) or the thick East End accents.
``Lock, Stock'' is a whip-smart lark that glistens with confidence
and a wicked sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the niftiest aspect of the film is that it owes as much
to Damon Runyon as it does to Quentin Tarantino. There's the usual
post-Tarantino surplus of violence (one run-in is so over the top
that it could have been lifted straight out of a John Woo movie).
But Ritchie gives his characters the same shaggy-dog, colorful
appeal that Runyon lavished on his Times Square guys and dolls. One
of Hatchet Harry's minions is known as Barry the Baptist, because
he gets rid of people by drowning them. Or consider Tom's patter as
he sells some ill-gotten goods on the street: ``Hand-made in Italy.
Hand-stolen in Stepney.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture's exuberant visual style mixes ``Trainspotting''
point-of-view shots with mid-1960s freeze frames. Clearly, everyone
involved had a heck of a good time making this movie.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have a heck of a good time watching it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nick Moran and Jason Flemyng. Directed by Guy Ritchie.
Rated R for violence and language. 1 hour, 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Smokin'.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
