<HEADER>
A6671 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-BRAS14-COX     03-11 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BRAS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The abc's of bras
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bras are like shoes. Women need one for every outfit,
a style for every occasion, a color for every mood. They're hooked
on them, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   That's why brassieres were the top-selling garment in the
intimate apparel industry in 1998, with sales reaching $4.3
billion, according to NPD American Shoppers, a New York firm that
tracks consumer purchases.
</P>
<P>
   When the two-cup wonder made its debut in the early 1900s,
designed by Caresse Crosby, a New York socialite, its main function
was to stay tight and out of sight. Decades later, the
entertainment industry would help change all that. When performers
such as Madonna and Janet Jackson hit the stage in leather and
lace, a whole new era of bra-wearing was born. Companies such as
Victoria's Secret, Bali and Playtex have created a fleet of styles
to flatter every figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bras have come out of the dresser drawer,'' said Berna
Goldstein, vice president of merchandising at Bali. ``There's a lot
more focus on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of technological advances in fabric and construction,
bras are more comfortable than ever and can do wonders for
sculpting the body.
</P>
<P>
   Spring and summer are big seasons for bras. As women shed bulky
winter wear for the tighter, sheerer and slinkier fashions of the
warmer months, choosing the right bra becomes an important
decision, both for work and for leisure.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there are many more choices in bras than ever, many
women unknowingly wear the wrong size or the wrong style.
</P>
<P>
   You know the type. They're the ones constantly tugging at their
bra straps; or the ones who are bulging on both sides; or the ones
wearing a bra that's so old that elasticity is a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most women have no clue how a bra should fit,'' Goldstein
said. ``Probably the only thing worse is buying a bathing suit. The
choices are daunting, and a lot of women are shy and don't want
salesclerks to help them. But it's the best 15 minutes people could
invest.''
</P>
<P>
   A bra has three purposes, fit, function and fashion, said Karen
Bromley, a spokeswoman for the Intimate Apparel Council, a trade
organization in New York City. That's why women need to shop as
carefully for a bra as for the garment that covers it.
</P>
<P>
   Lace for business casual or romantic evenings. A sports model
for jogging and aerobics, and a lightly lined one for sheer tops. A
strapless convertible that can go around the neck for halters or be
worn strapless for bare shoulders. Smooth, seamless bras for knits,
sweaters and T-shirts. And figure-enhancing styles that lift, curve
and shape.
</P>
<P>
   That's just the bare minimum. Experts say the average woman buys
about three bras a year. But she needs a minimum of 12 to 14 to
complement her wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know a woman today who could survive with seven
bras,'' said Cleo Edwards, foundations buyer for Rich's. ``Bras
these days are really wardrobing. For every outfit you put on, you
need a different look.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure to get the correct size by having a certified fitter
take your bust measurements. Most major department stores have
fitters on staff, and the service is free. Call ahead for schedule
information.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When fitting yourself, measure around the rib cage directly
under the bust, then add 5 inches to get the band size. Then
measure around the fullest part of the bust. If the difference
between these two measurements is 1 inch or less, you are an A cup;
if the difference is 2 inches, you're a B; if it's 3 inches, you're
a C; 4 inches is a D; and 5 inches is a DD.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If your measurement is an odd number, you'll need to go up 1
inch in size, because bras are measured in even numbers. For
example, if you meaure 35, you'll need a size 36. &QR;  Fit can vary
according to style and maker, so it's always best to try on a bra
before purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For an opaque look, wear a bra the same color as the garment.
White bras should be worn with white tops, black bras with black
tops, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Weight loss or gain could change your bra size; it's a good
idea to get refitted.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A good bra should last about three years, with proper care.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Machine wash on the gentle cycle in a lingerie bag. The bra
should be hooked together before washing. Avoid placing bras in a
dryer, because it weakens the elastic.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Remember, if the straps are too tight or rub the skin, the bra
is too small.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If the straps fall down or a cup puckers, the bra is too big.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
