<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DATE-RAPE12-COX     03-11 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATE-RAPE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABUSE OF 'DATE RAPE' DRUGS IS SPREADING, PANEL TOLD
 &HT;    580&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Candace Pruett didn't know Rohypnol had been
slipped into her soft drink, and doesn't remember being raped three
years ago at the age of 15.
</P>
<P>
   The drug and assault were revealed by hospital tests after she
was found by police called by her distraught parents, the high
school senior from Northern Virginia told congressional
investigators Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drug I was given unfortunately had robbed me of my
memories of what happened that night,'' Pruett said. ``What my
attacker did to me also robbed me of my childhood. Going through a
trial took away my innocence and forced me to become a grown-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Such sexual assaults are only the most dramatic element of an
exploding problem with so-called ``date rape drugs,'' witnesses
told the House Commerce subcommittee on oversight and
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agents and public health officials said the
drugs are much more widely abused as a way to get high, despite the
considerable risks of users lapsing into a coma or dying.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency has documented 32 deaths and
more than 3,500 overdoses since 1990 from just one of the drugs,
gamma hydroxybutyrate (GHB or ``Georgia Home Boy''), said Rep. Fred
Upton, R-Mich., the subcommittee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said law enforcement agencies, while busy combating
the traditional drugs of abuse like cocaine, marijuana and heroin,
haven't kept up with ``party'' drugs such as GHB, flunitrazepam
(also known as Rohypnol or ``roofies''), and Ketamine (''Special
K'').
</P>
<P>
   The drugs have become favorites at ``raves,'' where teen-agers
dance all night, and at clubs catering to affluent young adults, as
well as with subcultures ranging from body-builders to strippers.
</P>
<P>
   Ketamine, which is chemically akin to PCP, produces effects
ranging from dream-like states to delirium and hallucinations. GHB
is an intoxicant and euphoriant so powerful that users say a bottle
cap full produces the ``high'' of 12 beers. Rohypnol is a
``downer'' belonging to the same chemical family as Valium and is
often taken in combination with alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   For computer-savvy kids, information on finding, using or making
these drugs is available with a couple of clicks of a mouse, the
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ``GHB is truly the child of the Internet,'' testified Trinka
Porata, a private pharmaceutical consultant and former narcotics
detective for the Los Angeles Police Department. An assortment of
Web sites claim that the drug is safe and non-addictive and provide
directions on how to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, GHB is dangerous, addictive and harder than
heroin to shake,'' Porata told the subcommittee. ``GHB is the
easiest drug on Earth to make and the hardest drug to recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   A Food and Drug Administration official told the subcommittee
that GHB is not an approved drug in the United States, but is being
studied as a treatment for narcolepsy, a rare sleep disorder.
Rohypnol, a prescription anesthetic in some foreign countries, is
also not approved for use in the United States. Ketamine is an
anesthetic and has been approved by the FDA for both human and
animal use. Its most common legal use is by veterinarians as an
animal tranquilizer.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bart Stupak, D-Mich., has introduced legislation to add GHB
and Ketamine to the Drug Enforcement Administration's Schedule III
list of controlled substances, making possession of either drug by
a first-time offender punishable by five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine. It is already illegal to possess Rohypnol.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill has been introduced by Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee,
D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Quick action is likely, Upton predicted. He told of a recent
tragedy involving two teen-aged girls in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``While they were at a party, their beverages were laced with
GHB, probably without their knowledge. Fifteen-year-old Samantha
Reid and her friend lapsed into comas, and Samantha died,'' he
said. ``I am the father of an 11-year-old daughter, and I can only
imagine what Samantha's family and friends have endured.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for a pharmaceutical firm cautioned that GHB could
have medical value in treating narcolepsy _ a rare sleep disorder
that affects about 180,000 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In an attack, ``the patient appears unconscious. In reality,
however, the person is quite alert and awake, but unable to talk,
move or even remove himself or herself from a potentially dangerous
situation,'' testified Patti Engel, a spokeswoman for Orphan
Medical, a Minnesota firm that specializes in developing medicines
to treat rare ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Tests have shown doses of GHB can reduce attacks in some
patients from 50 a day to two a month, Engel said. She was not
opposed to federal action to stop misuse of the drug, however.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not with medicinal GHB, she said in prepared
testimony. ``Anyone with a computer, credit card, and the
inclination to surf the Net can find the recipe, buy the
ingredients and make a batch of 'home-brewed' GHB,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
