</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Entering the GOP presidential
sweepstakes, Elizabeth Dole failed to mention her husband in order
to stress that she is in this alone, running on her own public
service credentials. Nor was he at her side, as a supportive spouse
usually is for such a momentous event. Yet she would not be a
front-runner if her name was Elizabeth Hanford. And it is going to
be a strain to ignore him. So what to do with Bob during her
campaign? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOX-HOLYFIELD (New York) _ In a recent poll by Ring Magazine,
Evander Holyfield was rated as third-best heavyweight champion of
all-time behind only Muhammad Ali and Joe Louis. This has many
boxing fans screaming foul and saying what about Jack Dempsey and
Rocky Marciano. By W.H. STICKNEY.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA-SOUTH (Indianapolis) _ Complete coverage of the four
first-round games at the NCAA South Regional, where No. 1 Auburn
opens its bid to reach the first Final Four in school history. By
JERRY WIZIG.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA-WEST (Denver) _ Coverage of the four first-round games
at the NCAA West Regional in Denver, where Arkansas, Iowa and
Connecticut will be playing. By BILL SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA-EAST (Boston) _ Advance on the Texas Longhorns as they
head into the NCAA Tournament to face a Purdue team that struggled
mightily down the stretch and limps into the postseason. By JEROME
SOLOMON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN and BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-VACCINES (Washington) _ While some drug makers have
cautiously begun work on AIDS vaccines, the pharmaceutical industry
has been reluctant to commit resources for such work. Yet there is
world-wide demand for a vaccine to halt the spread of the disease
that afflicts 35 million people and infects 16,000 additional
individuals every day. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ The battle for the soul of the
Republican Party may be just as intense in 2000 as it was in 1952
when Dwight Eisenhower, a moderate, snatched the GOP presidential
nomination from the conservative Sen. Robert A.Taft. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
