<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING UP, AND AWAY, FROM A PROTECTIVE MOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE OTHER SISTER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Juliette Lewis, Giovanni Ribisi, Diane Keaton, Tom Skerritt,
Poppy Montgomery, Sarah Paulson, Linda Thorson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Garry Marshall &QL;
</P>
<P>
   131 minutes PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Toting her goldfish in a water-filled plastic bag, Carla Lewis
(Ms. Lewis) returns to her well-to-do family in San Francisco.
Carla, who is 24 and mentally retarded, has been away at a special
school and now it's time to try life on the outside, which, as the
situation suggests, will be a carefully monitored, ripple-free
existence behind all the buffers money can provide.
</P>
<P>
   Carla, however, has other notions. She wants to enroll in trade
school and become a veterinarian's assistant. She also wants her
own apartment. Just these thoughts are enough to send her mother, a
controlling monarch of a woman named Elizabeth (Ms. Keaton), into
fits of fretful disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   But Carla, who is as headstrong as her mother, gets her way. At
trade school she meets a similarly retarded young man named Danny
(Ribisi). Danny also has his own apartment, where he and Carla go
to discuss their places in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Soon they decide that they want a romantic attachment along with
their independence. With the mental development of young children,
they have a tendency to blurt out whatever is on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you two do it yet?'' Carla asks her sister and her
boyfriend. Given that, she is plenty smart and common-sensical.
Reminded by her mother that Danny isn't worthy because he won't be
able to pay the rent, Carla notes that Elizabeth doesn't pay the
rent either.
</P>
<P>
   Danny and Carla want to marry. Elizabeth, who insists Carla pack
pepper spray for encounters with men, has had quite enough. ``Can't
you see me? You never look at me!'' Carla screams at her. Ready or
not, here comes the bride.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX In their ingenuous way, Carla and Danny decide they want to
make love. ``More Joy of Sex'' is consulted. ``We could try page
39,'' Danny suggests. Eventually they retire behind closed doors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY The language gets strong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 They'd survive, but why put them through a long,
complicated movie? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 They will be engaged by Ms. Lewis and Ribisi, who
give startling and engaging performances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Audiences are accustomed to Ms. Lewis in road
films so her role here is appealing. But a movie that could have
been grittier chooses to stay heavily sentimental. That may attract
others, but it doesn't draw teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   200 CIGARETTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Love, Paul Rudd, Martha Plimpton, Janeane Garofolo,
Christina Ricci, Gaby Hoffmann, Ben Affleck, Jay Mohr, Dave
Chappelle, Kate Hudson, Casey Affleck, Brian McCardie, Angela
Featherstone, Caleb Carr &QL; 
Directed by Risa Bramon Garcia &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 102 minutes
</P>
<P>
   It's New Year's Eve, 1981, in New York and around the East
Village everybody feels more or less obliged to go to a party at
Monica's. With love lives on hold or in disarray, no one is looking
forward to it and that includes Monica (Ms. Plimpton), who awaits
terrified that no one will show up and weighing which is worse:
going to New Year's Eve parties or giving them.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least going I'm not responsible for how horrible they
are,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody straggles around town, stopping in clubs and
restaurants to kill time before midnight. Lucy (Ms. Love) and Kevin
(Rudd) quarrelsomely review their longtime friendship and on two
occasions attempt to have sex in a diner bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   In from Long Island, two would-be hipsters (Ms. Ricci and Ms.
Hoffmann) brave Satan's Pit and wonder if they'll survive Avenue B.
</P>
<P>
   At the dawn of yuppiedom a good-looking bartender betrays his
true motivations to two potential conquests. He's in law school and
wants to get into real estate. ``Time to pump,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Cindy (Ms. Hudson), an innocent from uptown, gets
together with Jack (Mohr), who the night before was the first man
she ever went home with.
</P>
<P>
   It's Kevin's birthday and Lucy gives him a carton of cigarettes
(200 of them). People kvetch and smoke and smoke. Crowds pile in
and out of the Dog Dive, but no one seems to be getting much closer
to Monica's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help me out, I'm hanging by a thread here,'' she says to her
one guest at the moment. But get there they do, even Elvis
Costello.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Other than some brief pushing and shoving in a club,
none. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Sex is often under discussion, but none is performed. Lucy
and Kevin's fumblings don't amount to much. The next morning people
turn up in bed, but the party is over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Some but mild. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12-14 For the most part, of course, parents don't accompany
their children to movies of this nature. Children who go with their
friends won't be uplifted, but the film is fun and not that
harmful. Perhaps the most objectionable element is all the
smoking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP Parents might cringe, but teen-agers will go.
</P>
<P>
   CRUEL INTENTIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Phillippe, Sarah Michelle Gellar, Reese Witherspoon, Selma
Blair, Louise Fletcher, Joshua Jackson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Roger Kumble &QL;
</P>
<P>
   97 minutes R
</P>
<P>
   With the movies always dredging up things for teen-agers to do
on screen, Kumble's film sets up a ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses''
junior division, with characters and plot modeled after Choderlos
de Laclos' 18th-century novel.
</P>
<P>
   On summer vacation in Manhattan and the Hamptons, the seductive
Sebastian Valmont (Phillippe) and his vile step-sister, Kathryn
Merteuil (Ms. Gellar), have some sexual projects to carry out while
inflicting as much pain and humiliation on other parties as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The top priority is Annette Hargrove (Ms. Witherspoon). An
All-American preppie queen, Annette has announced her intention to
``save herself'' in a national teen magazine. Kathryn and Sebastian
make a little bet: if Sebastian can't bed her, Kathryn gets his
sports car; if he can, Sebastian gets Kathryn.
</P>
<P>
   Around and around it goes, with Sebastian softening up his
quarry but not quite to the extent necessary and both Kathryn and
Sebastian working their wiles to inflict damage on a variety of
other pliant young people. But there's comeuppance ahead, right in
front of everyone at school, too.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE A latent kind of violence is present throughout.
Otherwise there is a fist fight and a fatal incident late in the
film. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Sex being the one and only subject, it stands to reason that
there are numerous sexual situations and continual references. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY These characters talk dirty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12-14 This is another of those R-rated films about children
but not for children. It's a reach, and not a little silly, to make
juveniles the protagonists of such a story, but many young viewers
won't agree. Also the stars are very popular. Parents beware. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP Like it or not, the film is a natural for many
older teen-agers.
</P>
</TEXT>
