<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON HOME VIDEOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The D.J. Apostles Of Rock 'n' Roll &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Documentaries often make the better shows on video. On March 23,
for example, Winstar is to release ``Rock 'n' Roll Invaders,'' a
Canadian film that goes past the performers to get at the AM radio
disk jockeys who brought the music to the people in the 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Dramarama, a Toronto company, the documentary took
its director, Paul Eichgrun, around the United States on a
three-year search for material about a little band of visionaries
who sensed an impending revolution and spun every record they could
get their hands on.
</P>
<P>
   Postwar America was nervous about race and its increasingly
restless teen-agers. ``Kids were becoming an economic power, buying
their own cars and clothes and records,'' Eichgrun said. ``It was a
shock.''
</P>
<P>
   But race was the sore point. The documentary is especially good
at showing how disk jockeys helped move the music that became rock
'n' roll from black to white in the middle and latter part of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Several years earlier radio itself had been revitalized by black
rhythm-and-blues, spread far and wide by the likes of Rufus Thomas
and Martha Jean (The Queen) Steinberg, black disk jockeys on WDAI
in Memphis (later she went to Detroit). Soon rhythm-and-blues met
white rockabilly, introducing white disk jockeys like Dewey
Phillips, the man with Beale Street connections, John R. (John
Richbourg) and Bill (Hoss) Allen of WLAC in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   The music worked its way north, and in places like the Record
Rendezvous in Cleveland, white teen-agers combed ``sepia bins'' for
the hot, sweaty, boozy workingman's rhythm-and-blues. At Alan
Freed's Moondog Ball, the first rock concert, a crowd of 26,000
tried to occupy 6,000 seats and there was a riot.
</P>
<P>
   The rambunctious Freed ruled the scene, and the white mainstream
was getting anxious. Rhythm-and-blues was about to become a white
creation. ``They bleached it and changed the name,'' Eichgrun said.
Now it was rock 'n' roll and headed for the coasts.
</P>
<P>
   There was trouble. Freed was on WINS in New York and promoting
concerts around the East. ``Kids, it looks like the Boston police
don't want you to have fun,'' he told a packed crowd in Boston
Arena. That got him indicted for inciting a riot and cost him his
job at WINS.
</P>
<P>
   ABC television hired him, but he lost that job, too, when the
black singer Frankie Lyman danced with a white girl. The show was
instantly canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Middle America wasn't amused when Jerry Lee Lewis married his
13-year-old second cousin. The payola scandals, with many leading
disk jockeys caught taking money to play records, were no help
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Booze, Broads, Bribes,'' shouted a headline about a riotous
disk jockey convention in Miami. Station management introduced the
Top 40, which were played over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Disk jockeys responded by becoming performers in their own
right. At the Apollo Theater in New York, Jocko Henderson gave
songs rhymed introductions that were the forerunners of rap. In
Mexico, Wolfman Jack ruled border radio, the one-million-watt
stations heard all over the country and beyond. ``The Russians had
to spend time blocking out the Wolfman,'' Eichgrun said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bulworth &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jay Bulworth (Warren Beatty) is so tired of campaigning and
life in general that he hires a hit man to kill him for his life
insurance. Then it occurs to him that he is free to do the utterly
unthinkable for a politician up for re-election: tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he is regaling black audiences to beware of lying white
liberals like him. It's a different approach all right, but
Bulworth stays loose, attracts a young black woman (Halle Berry)
and turns himself into a white rapping homeboy. And that, Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times, suits a political satire with
``jubilant wit and energy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Fox. $104.16. 106 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: March 16. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One True Thing &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Kate Gulden (Meryl Streep) develops terminal cancer, her
daughter Ellen (Renee Zellweger) puts her career on hold and goes
home to care for her. As the illness progresses, the younger woman
struggles with caring for a parent who is reluctant to surrender
control.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for them, the ordeal takes place in a spacious dream
house of the kind invariably used in films that add plenty of
cushioning to their tough situations. All the right emotions get
used _ anger, grief, helplessness and frustration _ but as awful as
the situation is, one is always aware that the movie ``shrewdly
blurs the line between tear-drenched suds and serious drama''
(Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $107.37. 128 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: March 16. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Waterboy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Boucher (Adam Sandler) is an extremely simple Louisiana
bayou boy of 31 who talks as if he had an infected molar in need of
immediate extraction and lives to pass out water to the louts on
the local college football team. Ridiculed for his efforts, Bobby
is finally terminated from his post and sent home to mama (Kathy
Bates).
</P>
<P>
   But Bobby craves water (or serving it) and lands with another
team whose coach (Henry Winkler) unleashes his anger and turns him
into a star linebacker. That's probably dumb enough, but ``this
escapist comedy is so cheerfully outlandish that it's hard to
resist'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Touchstone. $108.67. 88 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: March 16. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Polish Wedding &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jam a stunning and lusty Polish-American cleaning woman named
Jadzia (Lena Olin), her husband (Gabriel Byrne), their four sons
and daughter, their daughter-in-law and a grandchild into a crowded
house on the outskirts of Detroit, and you have what might have
been one of those funny, earthy working-class films that Hollywood
has unsuccessfully been trying to make ever since ``Moonstruck.''
</P>
<P>
   But in this case an emphasis on heartwarming nostalgia drains
much of the humor from ``an aggressively sentimental, nearly
laugh-free comedy'' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Fox. $100.96. 107 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: March 16. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE WONDERFUL ICE CREAM SUIT. As a youth, the writer Ray
Bradbury spent time among Mexicans who often bought clothes
together and shared them. In this Bradbury tale, five friends from
the Boyle Heights district in East Los Angeles buy an enchanted
white suit that each of them will wear for an evening and use to
realize his dreams. The story first appeared in The Saturday
Evening Post in 1957. It became a play in 1973 and now is a
straight-to-video film that stars Edward James Olmos and Joe
Mantegna and is directed by Stuart Gordon. 1999. Touchstone.
$104.16. 77 minutes. Closed captioned. PG. Release date: March 16.
</P>
<P>
   KRZYSZTOF KIESLOWSKI: I'M SO-SO. In Krzysztof Wierzbicki's
documentary, Kieslowski, the Polish director, whose films include
``Blue,'' ``White,'' ``Red'' and ``The Double Life of Veronique,''
reflects on work and life. ``To me the future is a black hole,''
says Kieslowski, a brooding intellectual and pessimist who died in
1996. He did call the world's attention to Juliette Binoche and
Irene Jacob, however, certainly positive accomplishments. 1998.
First Run Features. $39.95. 56 minutes. Polish with English
subtitles. Release date: March 16.
</P>
<P>
   WHO THE HELL IS JULIETTE? In Carlos Marcovich's film, a
16-year-old Cuban girl named Yuliet Ortega joins with a Mexican
model to explore their pasts and map their futures. 1997. Kino.
$79.95. 91 minutes. Spanish with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1615EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
