<HEADER>
A6693 &Cx1f; tad-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMUGGLING-ADVISORY-CO     03-11 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLING-ADVISORY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   THREE-DAY SERIES ON THE BUSINESS OF SMUGGLING ALIENS
</P>
<P>
   Attention: National, International editors
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Post is producing a three-day series for
Saturday, March 13, Sunday, March 14, and Monday, March 15 on the
business of smuggling aliens. The series follows in the wake of
news stories this week about two boats carrying more than three
dozen people that sank Saturday 26 miles east of West Palm Beach in
what could be the worst smuggling catastrophe in Florida history.
The Post's series looks at why the U.S. Border Patrol, the
Immigration and Naturalization Service and the federal court system
cope poorly with alien smuggling in Florida and why Florida
employers are able to hire hundreds of thousands of illegal workers
each year. Stories, graphics and photos will be available Friday
evening. If you have questions or need more information, call the
Cox News Service in Atlanta at 404 526-5456. Here are budget lines
for each day in the series:
</P>
<P>
   FOR SATURDAY PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   PURSUIT _ WEST PALM, BEACH, Fla. _ Smuggling immigrants into
Florida is a money-making enterprise. It's becoming a booming
business as more and more immigrants find that paying smugglers
equipped with fast boats and high-tech gear improves their chances
of reaching the United States. Sometimes it goes wrong, as when 40
Haitians drowned between the Bahamas and Palm Beach County last
weekend. The Border Patrol is charged with the responsibility of
putting the alien smuggler out of business. But the Miami sector
has less than 60 agents to patrol its four-state region. The agency
hasn't seen an increase in its workforce in 10 years. During that
period, the U.S. Border Patrol has experienced dramatic growth,
doubling the number of agents to a force of nearly 8,000.
Unfortunately for the Miami sector, almost all of the thousands of
agents hired during the past few years have been assigned to Texas,
California, New Mexico and Arizona. For example: The Miami Sector
has 52 agents assigned; Laredo (Texas) has 638; El Paso has 9,752;
Tucson has 1,022; and San Diego has 2,257. Miami's budget is $6.2
million; San Diego is $178 million. (Kane, Palm Beach Post) 60
inches.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   Charts on budget and manpower numbers.
</P>
<P>
   DAY _ Border Patrol Agent Larry Belotti works the graveyard
shift. He says he's the often the only Border Patrol agent working
from Corpus Christi, Texas, to Vermont. One recent night, he
rounded up 26 Cubans who came ashore in Miami Beach. This
effectively shuts down the Border Patrol station because Belotti
will spend the rest of the night processing these refugees. (Kane,
Palm Beach Post). 30.
</P>
<P>
   FOR SUNDAY PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   PUNISH _ U.S. Attorney Tom Scott says his office is adopting an
aggressive stand against alien smugglers. These cases are tough to
prosecute, particularly when Cuban refugees are involved. Justice
Department data shows that federal prosecutors historically haven't
taken on many alien smuggling cases. A couple reasons. The
smugglees make lousy witnesses. There's also the built-in defense:
``I'm not a smuggler. I was fishing and rescued these Cubans from
their sinking raft.'' Prosecutors also have felt that juries of
Cuban exiles and other immigrants find it hard to convict someone
of helping their fellow countrymen escape oppression. Furthermore,
the courts haven't been very tough on convicted smugglers, even if
the case involves the deaths of refugees. For example: In South
Fla, the USAtty prosecuted 62 percent of cases referred by the
Border Patrol; in Arizona, 92 percent; in Southern California, 99
percent; in South Texas, 99 percent. In South Fla, 26 percent of
smu
</P>
<P>
   ggling cases referred to USAtty ended with prison sentences; in
Arizona, it's 40 percent; Southern California, 57 percent; South
Texas, 58 percent. 60 inches. (Kane, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   Charts on court data.
</P>
<P>
   Graphic on brief profiles of alien smuggling cases to be posted
in BORDER folder on Cox file server.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MONDAY PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   WORKSITE _ It's unlawful to hire non-citizens. But Florida is
still the land of opportunity. An estimated 350,000 illegal aliens
reside here. Most work in the vegetable and citrus farms. Many keep
the tourism industry booming as waiters, hotel maids, etc. Some
work on landscaping and construction crews. But the INS cannot go
into the agricultural fields and doesn't have the manpower to do
much other worksite enforcement because it has to focus attention
on alien smuggling. Farmers hire scores of illegal workers and
escape liability by paying licensed farm labor contractors provide
crews. They also argue that workers today carry counterfeit
documents. The INS says they don't expect growers to be document
experts. Migrant worker advocates argue that farmers use their
political clout to handcuff the INS. For example: in 1990, the INS
sanctioned 38 employers in Florida for hiring illegals. That
dropped to 16 in 1991, 6 in 1992 and 2 in 1993. In 1994, 1995 and
1996, it was a dozen or fewer. Only in 1997 did it get back up to
about 20-25 employers. (Kane/Holland, Palm Beach Post). 60.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   Graphics on employer sanctions..
</P>
<P>
   ONEWAY _ Most illegal aliens enter Florida not by sea, but by
land. In Operation Oneway, the U.S. Border Patrol discovered that a
network of smugglers were routinely renting trucks in Arizona from
Penske, Avis, etc. for one-way trip to Florida's farmland. (Kane,
Palm Beach Post). 20.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
