<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND DECOR ON THE BLOCK  
 INDUSTRIAL CHIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many people think it's news when a prominent interior designer
acts to redo his space. Alberto Pinto, the veteran Paris decorator,
is making news by deciding to un-do his space.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of the best five decorators in Paris,'' said Laure
de Gramont, a former editor of Paris Vogue who is now an
international book scout. ``He has to keep reinventing his decor,
just as Hubert de Givenchy and Karl Lagerfeld have done recently.
Creative people get bored with their old things.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinto, whose enviable client list includes and Mrs. Moise Safra,
and Mrs. Michel David-Weill, Count and Countess Hubert d'Ornano,
and President and Madame Chirac, said he'd been thinking about
``changing a few things'' in his apartment for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept asking myself, `What should I keep, and what should I
not keep?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pinto is internationally known for the splendid interiors he has
been confecting for 30 years. His current apartment in a 1920s
building has a grand decor like an intricate music box.
</P>
<P>
   On the Quai d'Orsay overlooking the Seine, the space resembles a
Roman palace, with a monumental staircase, a large, formal drawing
room, a grand dining room and a salon lined in 18th-century
boiseries.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms boast crystal chandeliers and fabulous carved giltwood
mirrors. The windows are swathed in yards of pale pink silk. Tables
and armchairs are festooned with ormolu. Walls have faux finishes,
fine paintings and assemblages of beautifully framed paintings and
gouaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such sumptuous taste is not for everyone, but it's glorious,''
said Mrs. Beatrice de Patino, the widow of a Bolivian tin tycoon.
``The apartment has the proportions of a palazzo and is filled with
beautiful things.''
</P>
<P>
   In the drawing room, overscale antique Russian armchairs rest on
an enormous Napoleon III Aubusson carpet. In the room next door,
the Salon Jaune, a Louis XIV-style Boulle cabinet with
tortoise-shell inlay is placed against a wall upholstered in a
bright yellow toile de Jouy print with red figures.
</P>
<P>
   Every flat surface has its own still life: sets of hard-stone
and semi-precious-stone boxes, busts of Roman emperors,
19th-century animal sculptures and groupings of carved rock
crystal. Even the flatware is over the top; the German silver-gilt
dessert silverware from Hertler of Dresden has porcelain handles.
</P>
<P>
   How could he possibly pull this decor apart and sell it
piecemeal?
</P>
<P>
   ``I closed my eyes and decided to sell everything,'' said Pinto
in a recent interview. ``I thought it would be more fun if I
started again from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would keep the apartment but redo it ``in a more
contemporary style with just a few over-scale pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinto is selling his possessions at Sotheby's in New York.
Scheduled for March 29 and 30, the 282-lot sale is already
generating a lot of buzz.
</P>
<P>
   The 304-page catalog looks like a shelter magazine. Sotheby's
had the apartment photographed so the curious can see exactly how
the maestro placed each treasure.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog also includes quotes from some of Pinto's friends
and clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only the second time we've done this,'' said Pete
Hathaway of Sotheby's European furniture department, referring to
the decision to use such quotes. ``But everyone loves him.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Sotheby's is worried that Americans don't know Pinto's
work well enough, even though his clients include Saudi princes,
French nobles and David and Julia Koch, the American couple who
bought the apartment on Fifth Avenue that was owned by Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis.
</P>
<P>
   Diane von Furstenburg, the New York dress designer, for example,
wrote: ``Alberto Pinto is one of the most generous men I know. It
reflects in his taste, elegance, opulence and warmth.'' Countess
Ruy Brandolini d'Adda wrote: ``He can mix things antique and modern
in a very elegant way. He can create different atmospheres in one
minute, all in a very refined style.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinto is not selling everything he owns; he's keeping, for
example, his family silver and paintings. But he is selling a lot.
``He's the Imelda Marcos of antiques collectors,'' Hathaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Memorable items include a Napoleon III ormolu 12-light
chandelier with small Imari porcelain cups hanging from it
(estimated to sell at $30,000 to $50,000); a pair of Danish
mahogany armchairs decorated with gilded rosettes and leopard-print
upholstery ($15,000 to $20,000 for the pair), and a grand
19th-century Italian mahogany neoclassical center table that rests
on four carved gilt-wood lion supports ($25,000 to $35,000).
</P>
<P>
   Some items from the 19th century are not too expensive,
including the many examples of Palissy-style majolica (each plate
estimated at $800 to $1,200), an Italian mosaic-and-etched-glass
dressing mirror ($2,000 to $3,000) and a few sets of Russian silver
trompe l'oeil wicker baskets, complete with cast-silver damask
napkins ($4,000 to $6,000 apiece).
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he regretted putting any item up for auction, Pinto
said: ``Yes, my favorite green bird. But all my friends want it so
I decided to let them have it.''
</P>
<P>
   The piece, a charming 19th-century Indian enameled silver
cockatoo, used to sit on its silver perch in Pinto's drawing room,
pretending to eat the real pistachio nuts he put out for it.
Estimate: $10,000 to $15,000. At 12 inches high, it's probably
about the smallest item in the sale. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Metal seems to be the password for this year's Triple Pier Expo,
which returns to Piers 88, 90 and 92 on the Hudson River this
weekend and next; several dealers are selling industrial-metal
furniture in stainless steel, chrome and aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   For example, David Teague, of America Antiques in Lambertville,
N.J., who will be at Booth 301 on Pier 90 this weekend, is selling
a circa 1950 stainless-steel corporate conference table for $4,800;
a metal Parsons-like table for $2,500, and a collection of
dome-topped medical cabinets in steel with brass feet from Buenos
Aires.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan dealer Michael Ward, who will be showing at Booth
441 on Pier 90 on March 20 and 21, said he had specialized in
examples of industrial design made ``between the Victorian and Art
Deco periods.'' This year he has several circa 1900 ``task'' lamps
that can pivot in many directions; prices range from $400 to $1,200
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   He also has sets of similar lamp shades that can be hung in a
row over a table on cords that drop six feet from the ceiling.
These lights have industrial-glass shades attached to the light
sockets and cost between $250 and $300 per light.
</P>
<P>
   Other dealers are showing metal recycled medical cabinets, and
aluminum storage lockers and factory tables. Who knows, maybe Pinto
will be filling up his apartment with industrial-aluminum
furniture?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
