<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 STANLEY KUBRICK: THE MAN WHO INVENTED THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
 bc-headgen (4,200 words OR 1,500 words) Includes a color slide of Stanley
Kubrick directing ``Full Metal Jacket'' (1987) and a
black-and-white photo of Stanley Kubrick in 1984. 
 By ERIC NORDEN  
 c.1968 Playboy  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When director Stanley Kubrick died on March 7, he left a
dazzling body of work _ and a legacy of almost total silence.
</P>
<P>
   In four decades as a filmmaker, Kubrick virtually never agreed
to be interviewed. In 1968, however, shortly after the release of
his seminal science-fiction film ``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' the
director was interviewed by Playboy magazine, and talked about
``2001'' and ``Dr. Strangelove'' (1964), his visions of the future
and his philosophy of filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from this interview are available in a long and a short
version, of 4,200 and 1,500 words respectively. For information,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-KUBRICK-INTERVIEW-NYTSF, priority code w, category
code e)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
