<HEADER>
A6713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      03-11 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VAN GOGH ON THE BLOCK  
 TELLING ALL  
 GRACES GO HOME  
 NEW MUSEUM DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Do you remember among the little drawings a wooden bridge with
a washing place, and a view of the town in the distance?'' Vincent
van Gogh wrote his brother, Theo, on June 16, 1888. ``I have just
painted that subject in a large size.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting, ``Canal With Washerwoman,'' was last seen publicly
in 1984 at the Metropolitan Museum of Art's blockbuster show ``Van
Gogh in Arles.'' Now Christie's is selling the painting in its May
12 auction of important Impressionist and 19th-century art in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape, 29[ by 23| inches, captures the spot where the
women of Arles did their laundry. Its vivid colors, wide brushwork
and Japanese-inspired perspective epitomize the work van Gogh did
while living in the south of France.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings from this period are the most sought-after by
collectors and are among the most difficult to find. Few ever come
on the market because most of those that are still in private hands
have already been promised to museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The painting belongs to a collector in the United States who
is very private,'' said Franck Giraud, Christie's worldwide
director of 19th- and 20th-century fine art. ``Van Gogh went to the
south of France because he was attracted to the very strong light.
But when he first arrived there it was winter and he was
disappointed by what he saw. This painting was done in June, and it
records the artist's first encounter with the strong light he had
dreamed about. In the top right-hand-corner he actually painted the
sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's expects the painting to sell for about $20 million.
But this could skyrocket if the market for important van Goghs is
still as strong as it was in November, when an 1889 self-portrait
sold for $71.5 million, nearly three times its high estimate. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Museum labels are generally an informative tool meant to gently
explain to museumgoers what they are looking at. But the labels
that appear in the ``Mirror of the Medieval World'' at the
Metropolitan Museum tell all: where an object came from; if it was
through a dealer, the name of the dealer; if it was bought at
auction, which auction house and even the lot number.
</P>
<P>
   The labels also record a work's source of financing, in some
cases gifts but in others what the museum defines as a curatorial
purchase. These were often less expensive but nonetheless
historically important objects that did not require approval by the
museum's acquisitions committee.
</P>
<P>
   Some required approval from the museum director, others were
even less costly and were acquired solely on the prerogative of the
head of a department.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time the Metropolitan has given the viewer so
much information. ``We decided to deal with the process,'' said
Philippe de Montebello, the Met's director. ``It's part of the
transparency of sharing with the public that the job of a curator
is not mysterious and objects pass through many hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason the museum decided to write such extensive
labels is that all the objects were acquired over the last 20 years
and are part of the Met's own collections. When an exhibition
includes loans from private collectors or other institutions, the
lender may not want to be so forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for reviewing the provenance of each of the
show's nearly 300 objects was to clarify any issues that could
arise concerning property that might have been stolen by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   De Montebello said that there had been such questions about a
few of the medieval objects in the museum's collection. In one or
two cases, he said, information concerning a work's provenance may
not have been as complete as they would have liked, raising
provenance questions.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances the curators were able to track down the
Jewish families who had owned a work and the dealer who had sold
the objects to them. They were also able to get copies of all the
correspondence regarding the history of the object, thereby
clearing up any doubts.
</P>
<P>
   It took museum officials about three years to review all the
medieval objects in the show. ``Since the show tells the story of
the most recent 20 years of collecting in the medieval department,
it was a good way of reviewing our records and trying to flesh out
our own knowledge,'' said Peter Barnet, the curator in charge of
the department of medieval art at the Metropolitan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After three and a half years at the National Galleries of
Scotland, where it drew record crowds, ``The Three Graces,''
Canova's much-loved sculpture, has returned to the Victoria and
Albert Museum in London.
</P>
<P>
   The two institutions bought the object together in 1994, after a
five-year effort by the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles to
acquire it. Because the sculpture was deemed a national treasure
and the two museums could match the Getty's $12 million offer, the
Getty was denied the right to take the sculpture out of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The two museums agreed to transfer the sculpture between them
approximately every seven years. It moved to the V, and A. early
this time so it could be included in the museum's centenary
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture is on display in the museum's newly reopened
sculpture galleries, near other works by the 19th-century master.
It will remain in London until the end of 2005, when it will return
to Scotland. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles has named its new
director: Jeremy Strick, curator of 20th-century painting and
sculpture at the Art Institute of Chicago. Strick will start his
new job on July 1, replacing Richard Koshalek, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Strick has little administrative experience, but his curatorial
accomplishments have been well received. A native of Los Angeles,
he was a curator of modern art at the St. Louis Art Museum and an
associate curator of 20th-century art at the National Gallery of
Art in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, he oversaw the installation and opening of a new set
of galleries and organized many exhibitions, including ``In the
Light of Italy: Corot and Early Open-Air Painting,'' ``Louise
Bourgeois: The Personages'' and ``The Sublime Is Now: The Early
Work of Barnett Newman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
