<HEADLINE>
ISLAND WHIRL: THERE'S MORE TO GALVESTON THAN BEACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARILYN BAILEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Galveston has changed identities many times, from Texas' main
business hub in the 19th century to a wide-open gambling and
bootlegging mecca in the middle of this century. Today, of course,
tourism's the thing, as the city has become increasingly
sophisticated about packaging its charms.
</P>
<P>
   The beaches everyone complains about will always attract hordes,
but, more than ever, it's possible to have other kinds of vacations
on the island as well _ one of shopping, strolls through historic
neighborhoods, and bed-and-breakfast luxury, or a family vacation
of kid-friendly museums and theme-park attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The Strand district, which was restored and developed for
tourism in the '70s and '80s, is growing up and getting more
texture. It has even acquired a bit of hipness in the past several
years. Tourist traps and Victorian-themed shops are still thriving,
but young locals hang out here, too, now that there are brewpubs,
coffeehouses, more restaurants than ever and a better variety of
shops.
</P>
<P>
   With the Strand's impressive stock of 19th-century office
buildings and warehouses, and with stately residential
neighborhoods of delicate gingerbreads and castlelike stone houses,
you can spend days touring Texas' best collection of Victorian
residential and commercial architecture.
</P>
<P>
   And away from the historic neighborhoods, the newer end of town
has its own blockbuster attraction: Moody Gardens, a
family-oriented entertainment/educational complex with an eccentric
menu of attractions.
</P>
<P>
   MOODY GARDENS: Its name tells you little about what's in store.
Part amusement park, part botanic garden, the complex is a little
Giza on the Gulf, dominated by three huge pyramids housing a rain
forest, an interactive space exhibit and, soon, an aquarium. But
there's also a white-sand beach with a blue lagoon, a working
replica of an 18th-century paddle-wheel tour boat, two IMAX
theaters and a Vietnam memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-story glass Rainforest Pyramid swarms with beautiful
tropical birds, butterflies, bats and insects under a dense canopy
of greenery. The Discovery Pyramid houses an interactive space
exploration exhibit. The new aquarium, opening this summer, will be
one of the biggest anywhere; there's much ado locally about a
colony of king penguins that arrived months early and is being
refrigerated in a downtown building.
</P>
<P>
   There's also America's first 3-D IMAX theater, where moviegoers
wearing Elton John-sized glasses can see the likes of ``T-REX: Back
to the Cretaceous,'' starring life-size dinosaurs. And in the
separate IMAX Ridefilm theater, you get strapped into a moving seat
and jerked around while viewing a huge wrap-around screen. You'll
feel like you're ``in'' the movie rather than just watching it.
Currently playing are ``Asteroid Adventure'' and ``Dolphins: The
Ride.''
</P>
<P>
   A project of the nonprofit Moody Foundation, Moody Gardens was
opened to provide horticultural therapy and animal-assisted therapy
for people with head injuries. Some patients work at the
greenhouses and Rainforest Pyramid. The whole place is luxuriantly
landscaped with subtropical trees and flowers; the parking lot has
more palm trees than you've ever seen in one place. It's a
therapeutic place for anybody _ a must-see for families.
</P>
<P>
   OLD GALVESTON: Galveston itself is a living museum, with 550
historical landmarks on the National Register of Historic Places.
For residential architecture, the Silk Stocking district and the
East End historical district are well worth driving through for a
sense of what whole neighborhoods were like; there are modern
houses and shabby old houses among the restored gems, but there are
still plenty of glimpses of brick streets, trolley tracks and a few
iron fences.
</P>
<P>
   The first English-speaking settlers came to the island in the
1830s, a few years after pirate Jean Lafitte _ with his village of
2,000 bootleggers, gamblers and carousers _ was run off the island
by the U.S. Navy. And in a few decades, Galveston became a
prosperous port city, with money pouring in from cotton, banking
and shipping. It grew quickly, especially after the Civil War, into
a wealthy city of stately avenues and homes outfitted with all the
fineries that could be imported.
</P>
<P>
   The richest Galvestonians built their showplace houses on
Broadway, today a six-lane avenue with a wide, heavily treed
esplanade. The grandest of the mansions was an imposing sandstone
and granite home built in 1888, now known as the Bishop's Palace,
1402 Broadway Blvd. The American Institute of Architects named it
one of the 100 most significant buildings in the United States, the
only Texas residence on the list. It really does look like a
castle, with turrets and lots of balconies. The interior is famous
for its multiple fireplaces imported from all over the world and
for extensive woodwork of rosewood, satinwood and white mahogany.
This and many other houses are open for tours; get information and
maps at the Strand Visitor's Center, 2016 Strand.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   The Strand, in its heyday, was known as the Wall Street of the
South. Today, it's the Strand National Historic Landmark District,
with 36 square blocks of shops, restaurants and galleries in an
amazingly intact collection of 19th-century office buildings and
warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   The street didn't need much dressing up to become a stand-in for
19th-century Fort Worth a couple of years back during the filming
of one of the wretched ``Gambler'' TV movies. A few modern signs
were removed, and a cattle drive was staged on one of the central
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   One block north of the Strand, on Ship's Mechanic's Row, is the
Tremont Hotel, the city's most elegant. Across the street is a tiny
but wonderful bookstore, Midsummer Books.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery district on Postoffice Street, two blocks farther
south, is a row of art galleries and antiques stores. Check out The
Firm, a funky one-of-a-kind clothing store for women and men. Look
in at the exquisite Grand 1894 Opera house, 2020 Postoffice, where
the likes of Sarah Bernhardt and Lillian Russell performed. Call
(800) 821-1894 for performance information; the theater gets a lot
of the same touring acts as Bass Performance Hall, and no seat is
more than 70 feet from the stage.
</P>
<P>
   For kids, not known for their interest in Victoriana, downtown
has three transportation-themed museums. At the Railroad Museum,
located in the Strand's restored train depot, you can poke through
46 locomotives, Pullman sleepers and cabooses. The Classic Car
Museum, 19th and Mechanic streets, houses 53 vintage automobiles,
including a 1940 Mercury given to Carole Lombard by her husband,
Clark Gable.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Seaport Museum, on the waterfront at Pier 21, one
block south of the Strand, has the 1877 tall ship Elissa, and
exhibits explaining the workings of a 19th-century port and
chronicling Galveston's role as a port of entry for immigrants. The
city claims to have been second only to Ellis Island in the number
of people who came through.
</P>
<P>
   Also at Pier 21, be sure to see the film ``The Great Storm,'' a
27-minute documentary on the hurricane that devastated Galveston in
September 1900. It's a mystery why this event doesn't loom larger
in the American memory. More than 6,000 people were killed, making
it by far the worst natural disaster in U.S. history. Bodies were
weighted and buried at sea but later washed ashore and had to be
burned. The storm flattened one-third of the city and ended forever
its status as a major port and economic center.
</P>
<P>
   After the storm, the city rebuilt and erected a 17-foot-tall
seawall, a protective concrete barrier along the coastline.
Designed to give some protection from storm tides, it also created
a great public space, much like the Atlantic Coast boardwalks. When
the weather's nice, the longest sidewalk in the world is always
busy with in-line skaters, bikers and people cruising. The
refurbished Hotel Galvez (built in 1911) is the street's most
gracious hotel. Another great seawall institution that's not to be
missed is Gaido's, a seafood palace announced by a bathtub-sized
crab on a pedestal out front. Texas Highways readers just voted it
the best restaurant in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the eroded in-town beaches have been replenished
with imported whitish sand from Florida, the best beaches are to
the east and west of the seawall. Galveston Island State Park, west
of the city off Farm Road 3005, is the place to go for camping.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FYI
</P>
<P>
   Now that spring break is about over, it's safe to ponder
vacationing in Galveston. Here are some more reasons to visit the
island this spring:
</P>
<P>
   Through April 4: IMAX Film Festival at Moody Gardens. Ten films
are showing, most screening at least once daily. For reservations,
call (800) 582-4673.
</P>
<P>
   May 1, 2, 8 and 9: Historic Homes Tour, Galveston Historical
Foundation. Guided tours of 10 restored houses, mostly private
homes not usually open to the public. Tickets: (409) 765-7834.
</P>
<P>
   June 5: The American Institute of Architects sand-castle
competition, at East Beach, attracts entrants from all over the
country; winning creations are always amazingly elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Also in June: Moody Gardens opens its aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston is about 300 miles southeast of Fort Worth on I-45.
Both Southwest and American Airlines offer $100 round-trip fares to
Houston's Hobby airport, a 50-minute drive from Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Inn on the Beach, 5002 Seawall Blvd., has spring rates
of $99-$199 for doubles. Summer weekend rates at the luxurious
Hotel Galvez, 2024 Seawall Blvd., are $175-$195 per night for
doubles, depending on ocean view.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites: Galveston Convention &AMP; Visitor's Bureau:
www.galvestontourism.com; Galveston Historical Foundation:
www.galvestonhistory.org; Moody Gardens: www.moodygardens.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Five best things to do (besides the beach):
</P>
<P>
   1. Ride on the Galveston Island Ferry, a commuter service
connecting the island with the Bolivar peninsula to the east.
You'll get close to supertankers and a shipwreck, and maybe a
dolphin or two. Since they've returned to Galveston Bay, you'll
often see a few dolphins merrily trailing the ferry as its makes
the 20-minute trip across the Houston shipping lanes. It's best to
walk onto the ferry instead of driving. There's an observation deck
above, but it's fun to stand right at the bow, get sea spray on
your face and throw snacks to the seagulls.
</P>
<P>
   2. Stroll the Strand and the wharves district.
</P>
<P>
   3. Eat at Gaido's, just named the best restaurant in the state
by readers of Texas Highways. 3800 Seawall Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   4. Get your glasses fogged up at Moody Gardens' rain-forest
exhibit, a 10-story enclosed re-creation of a tropical paradise.
</P>
<P>
   5. If you have time to tour only one historical building, make
it Bishop's Palace, 1402 Broadway Blvd., the most lavish of
Galveston's old residences.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
