<SLUG> BC-MISSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED MESSAGES IN CASE OF MISSING TRIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The investigation into the disappearance of a
woman and two teen-agers last seen at a lodge outside Yosemite
National Park has taken two new turns, with a devastating message
from the FBI and the arrest of a lodge employee on an unrelated
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Jens Sund, the missing woman's husband, said Wednesday that the
FBI had briefed him on what he considered a major development in
the 3-week-old case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm devastated,'' he said outside the FBI's command post in
Modesto. ``My worst possible fears have come true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look good for my family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman Nick Rossi, however, said there were no major new
developments in the case. ``Rumors that the FBI has discovered the
bodies of the victims or their vehicle are false,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Sund, 42, her 15-year-old daughter, Julie, and Silvina
Pelosso, a 16-year-old family friend from Cordoba, Argentina,
vanished Feb. 15 from the Cedar Lodge, a restaurant and motel in El
Portal on the western edge of Yosemite.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an employee of a restaurant next to the Cedar Lodge
was being held in the Mariposa County Jail at the request of the
FBI and his parole agent on an unrelated charge, the Associated
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Strange, the restaurant's night cleaner, was jailed Friday
night for a parole violation after agents found marijuana in his
cabin a few miles from the lodge, co-workers said. He has been
jailed for domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and the Mariposa County sheriff declined to comment on
Strange's arrest, though his colleagues at the lodge said they
doubted he had any role in the trio's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI returned Strange's van and a car belonging to his
girlfriend, after seizing and searching them.
</P>
<P>
   Strange's girlfriend, who works as a desk clerk at the lodge,
has denied any ties to the missing threesome.
</P>
<P>
   Sund declined to disclose details of his discussion with the
FBI, saying he did not want his remarks to taint potential jurors
in any future prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   A family friend who was with Sund during his meeting with the
FBI confirmed that agents had not reported finding the missing
sightseers or their missing rental car.
</P>
<P>
   Rossi said that agents would focus their search around El Portal
for the next few days, because investigators had found no credible
evidence that the threesome went elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The three left the Sunds' Eureka home Feb. 12, flying to San
Francisco where they rented a red 1999 Pontiac Grand Prix. Driving
east, they stopped in Stockton to see a college cheerleading
competition and arrived Feb. 14 at the Cedar Lodge. They were last
seen the evening of Feb. 15, leaving the lodge restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, the FBI recovered Carole Sund's black leather
credit-card holder, with credit cards, about two hours away on a
road leading to the Modesto airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
