<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEVIL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEVIL'S ISLAND': A LONELY CIRCLE OF HELL IS COLD, BUT NOT ALL
DESPAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Icelandic equivalents of trailer-park trash run rampant
through ``Devil's Island,'' which opens Friday at the Angelika Film
Center.
</P>
<P>
   This small, vividly realized, comic and pungent slice of life is
carved with directorial dexterity by Fridrik Thor Fridriksson out
of the bleak, junk-filled landscape of Quonset huts, mud puddles
and windblown garbage that was once Camp Thule, an American
military base on the edge of Reykjavik in Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the 1950s, ``Devil's Island,'' written by Einar Karason,
tells a tale of sociological dislocation and cultural invasion as
it focuses on four generations of one of the Icelandic families
living in these shabby huts as part of a community populated mostly
by drunken men, unhappy women and miserable or dysfunctional
children.
</P>
<P>
   Reviled or mocked by outsiders and a vexation to the police,
these people are nonetheless a colorful lot whose principal family
includes a witch who curses God; a mother of three who promptly
marries an American pilot and leaves, and her married daughter, two
adult sons and a grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   The sons, Baddi and Danni, played by Baltasar Kormakur and
Sveinn Geirsson, are in sharp contrast. Baddi is nothing but
trouble, a bad-tempered layabout who drinks heavily, brawls, pals
around with an ex-convict and cadges money from his grandfather,
Thomas (Gisli Halldorsson). Danni is a shy, quiet stay-at-home with
a suppressed decency and potential for heroism.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the film's consistently comic touches, Baddi goes off
for a visit to the United States and returns with an Elvis hairdo,
black leather biker's jacket, shades and a red Plymouth with fins,
which catapult him instantaneously into what passes for the local
avant-garde.
</P>
<P>
   It is he who christens the community Devil's Island, though its
anarchic, edge-of-the-world isolation appears to suit some of its
inhabitants just fine.
</P>
<P>
   The cast, which includes Sigurveig Jonsdottir as Thomas' wife,
the ghost-plagued witch Karolina; Halldora Geirhardsdottir as the
unhappily married sister of Baddi and Danni, and Pallna Jonsdottir
as the pretty young woman who has the misfortune to marry Baddi,
delivers performances so convincing and unself-conscious that
``Devil's Island'' at times seems to be a documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The picture it presents may not be attractive, but it is created
with admirable skill.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `DEVIL'S ISLAND'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Fridrik Thor Fridriksson; written (in Icelandic,
with English subtitles) by Einar Karason; director of photography,
Ari Kristinsson; edited by Steingrimur Karisson and Skule Eriksen;
music by Hilmar Orn Jilmarsson; production designer, Arni Pall
Jahannsaon; produced by Fridriksson, Peter Rommel, Egil Odegaard
and Peter Aalbaek Jensen; released by Artistic License Films.
Running time: 103 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Baltasar Kormakur (Baddi), Gisli Halldorsson (Thomas),
Sigurveig Jonsdottir (Karolina), Halldora Geirhardsdottir (Dolly),
Sveinn Geirsson (Danni), Guomudur Olafsson (Grettir), Pallna
Jonsdottir (Hveragerdur) and Ingvar E. Sigurdsson (Grjoni). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
