<HEADER>
A6744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-11 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WING COMMANDER': GEE, COMMANDER, YOU'RE CUTE WHEN YOU FIGHT GREEN
ALIENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Wing Commander'' is based on a video game and has roughly the
same degree of character development. That is all most moviegoers
will need to know.
</P>
<P>
   For others, here is the so-called plot: In the year 2564 Earth
is at war with the Kilrathi, who appear to be murky dark green
monsters. (Or is it the lighting on their spaceships?)
</P>
<P>
   Two scrappy young soldiers _ Christopher Blair (Freddie Prinze
Jr.) and Todd Marshall (Matthew Lillard), nicknamed Maniac _ have
to deliver an encoded disk with a message about an invasion.
Afterward they meet two fabulous women: Deveraux (Saffron Burrows),
nicknamed Angel, their stoic wing commander, and Rosie (Ginny
Holden), another fighter pilot. It's good to see that they've got
that women-in-combat thing worked out in the 26th century.
</P>
<P>
   Both men fall in love, as illustrated with dialogue that a
12-year-old might write or believe, but duty calls everyone into
action. Thus the characters spend most of their time risking their
lives jumping quasars and pulsars, trying to determine the
Charybdis jump coordinates and counting the number of enemy vessels
still on their tail.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Vulcan-copycat subplot about an almost extinct group
called the Pilgrims. (Blair's mother was one, so one bigoted
character periodically calls him a half-breed.) Some highly
respected actors, including David Suchet, appear in the film;
everybody's got to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Roberts, who created the video game the film is based on,
directed and wrote the original story for ``Wing Commander.'' The
film is painfully boring and funny in the wrong places. The best
exchange is between Chris and Deveraux, after she gives him a
direct order to leave her for dead. She: ``You disobey my order and
I'll have you court-martialed.'' He: ``Like I care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wing Commander'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned).
It contains profanity, metaphor-cloaked sexual situations,
hand-to-hand combat and outer-space explosions.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `WING COMMANDER'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Chris Roberts; written by Kevin Droney, based on a
story and characters created by Roberts; director of photography,
Thierry Arbogast; edited by Peter Davies; music score by Kevin
Kiner, with theme by David Arnold; production designer, Peter
Lamont; produced by Todd Moyer; released by 20th Century Fox.
Running time: 105 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Freddie Prinze, Jr. (Blair), Saffron Burrows (Deveraux),
Matthew Lillard (Maniac), Tcheky Karyo (Paladin), Jurgen Prochnow
(Gerald), David Suchet (Sansky), David Warner (Tolwyn) and Ginny
Holden (Rosie).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
