<HEADER>
A6751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTISTS-MUSEUMS-2TAKE     03-11 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTISTS-MUSEUMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MODERN LOOKS AT ARTISTS LOOKING AT MUSEUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Exhibition notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Of all the love-hate relationships that roil the art
world, none is more fraught or stimulating than that between
artists and museums. This makes perfect sense, since the two occupy
opposite ends of the art world food chain.
</P>
<P>
   Artists make art; museums select some of that art for their
collections, where it is preserved, elevated and, most of all,
displayed. Once on view, it offers other artists inspiration,
helping them unlock their own talents, which brings the food chain
full circle.
</P>
<P>
   The artist-museum relationship could be called capitalist, a
case of supply and demand, with the consumer (the museum) causing
pain and competition among the producers (the artists). It could be
called Oedipal, with the museum as a parental authority whose
ordering, judgmental nature is anathema to the rebellious
sensibilities of artists, even though they crave its approval. Or
it could be seen as micro versus macro: Artists are individuals and
museums are institutions, but they are driven by a similar passion
for the accumulation, enjoyment and perpetuation of art. The
similarities and differences create a perfectly balanced mutual
fascination.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever it's called, this connection powers ``Museum as
Muse: Artists Reflect,'' a remarkable exhibition that opens Sunday
at the Museum of Modern Art. Organized by Kynaston McShine, the
longtime senior curator in the department of painting and
sculpture, it examines the many ways that artists, mostly in the
20th century, have seen the museum as the subject, rather than
simply the destination, of their art.
</P>
<P>
   This tendency has been on the rise since the advent of
Conceptual Art, when artists became more aware and critical of the
complex context _ esthetic, social, economic _ surrounding art. But
the show also includes a handful of works from previous centuries,
suggesting that this fascination predates modernism. Its 62 artists
range from Roger Fenton (a 19th-century photographer) to Marcel
Duchamp and Joseph Cornell, to Hans Haacke, Daniel Buren, Ed
Ruscha, Sherrie Levine and Fred Wilson. Janet Cardiff, a young
Canadian artist, has provided an amusingly disorienting audioguide,
which takes the viewer into the Modern's permanent collection and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is stronger in big ideas than in profound visual
experiences, ``Museum as Muse'' is an unusually coherent,
well-orchestrated theme show that transcends typical theme-show
fare (as in the cow, nude or machine in art). Part of its power
lies in the simple fact that, to paraphrase Frank Stella, what you
see is where you see it. Its contents and its context are one.
</P>
<P>
   Including painting, video, printed brochure and installation
art, the show's 182 works mix media with a freedom that's unusual
for the Modern, while veering pleasantly between the arcane and the
accessible, the beautiful and the thought provoking, the
celebratory and the critical. The totality examines the museum from
every angle, as a public place, as an accumulator and classifier of
knowledge (natural-history museums are also touched on), as a
colonizer of cultures (so are ethnographic ones), as an exclusive
social club and as a big business with products of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Almost in passing, interrelated smaller themes are encompassed.
The show offers an unusually comprehensible outline of the
development of Conceptual Art, with its emphasis on language and
photography and its influences on subsequent generations. It shows
how photography especially has metastasized throughout the art of
the last 30 years. And, of course, by definition the show also
considers one of 20th-century art's biggest ideas: site
specificity. This is, after all, an exhibition of art about art
museums in the world's pre-eminent museum of modern art. For
contemporary artists, a site can't be much richer with possibility.
</P>
<P>
   This is nowhere clearer than in the works, like Ms. Cardiff's
audioguide, that McShine commissioned specially for the show. The
results are impressive, not least because they show the Modern
being very flexible, uncharacteristically so, some would say. The
museum clearly bent the furthest for a piece by the California
Conceptualist Michael Asher: a brochure listing, as accurately as
records permit, every work of painting and sculpture that the
Modern has ever deaccessioned. Attached to one of the benches
toward the end of the exhibition, it makes fascinating reading and
is also available without charge (but with a museum ticket stub) in
the Modern's bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   The French artist Daniel Buren, famous for reducing art to
bright stripes that he applies to all kinds of surfaces, has been
allowed to put his stripes not in the show proper but upstairs in
the permanent collection galleries. To be precise, they appear on
two walls that usually hold four paintings by Giorgio de Chirico.
Meanwhile, the de Chirico paintings are on view in McShine's
exhibition, where they provide an encounter as pleasantly
surprising as Buren's walls of stripes upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   And Wilson was given free rein in the Modern's photo archive,
emerging with ``Art in Our Time,'' a wall of images that evoke the
museum as a bastion of the rich and the white. The central image
shows the museum ``opened up,'' after a fire in 1958, with the
windows of its famous stairwell knocked out by firefighters. It is
typical of the exhibition that Wilson's work faces more traditional
museum pictures of openings by Garry Winogrand and Larry Fink,
which also don't always flatter the powers that be.
</P>
<P>
   McShine rather slyly includes an instance of earlier flexibility
at the Modern, in a work that was created for ``Information,'' his
1970 survey of Conceptual Art. Titled ``Service Piece,'' it is by
Vito Acconci and documents the artist using his allotted space in
the earlier show as a mail pickup. (Other ``Information'' alumni
include Buren, Jan Dibbets, Hans Haacke, Robert Smithson, Dennis
Oppenheim and, surprisingly, Jeff Wall.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Installed with the density of an 18th-century kunstkammer _ the
collections of art, artifacts and natural wonders assembled by
monarchs and aristocrats that is the point of origin of museums _
the show nonetheless moves easily from one idea to the next, while
individual works play off each other well. Organizationally, it
lures viewers in, saves its more difficult works for the middle and
then sets them down gently.
</P>
<P>
   The show's long narrow antechamber, as the first gallery might
be called, concentrates on the museum as a public space that
foments private experience, a stage whose social and visual
dynamics have always attracted artists. Most of the works are
photographs, and most of them show people looking at art. Thomas
Struth's enormous images _ almost big enough to walk into _ show
people gazing at the Modern's big Pollock, ``One: Number 31,
1950,'' or at Gericault's looming ``Raft of the Medusa'' at the
Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, Cartier-Bresson's ``Musee du Louvre,'' with its
clutch of people studying David's ``Napoleon Crowning Josephine,''
is surely an ancestor to the Struths. David Seymour shows Bernard
Berenson contemplating a marble odalisque with self-satisfied calm,
while Cartier-Bresson photographs two small boys homing in on a
sculpture in a museum in Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Erwitt and Eve Arnold capture the sexual puns in chance
juxtapositions of viewers and objects, and Candida Hofer's
photographs of modern museum lobbies reveal antiseptic spaces
devoid of either art or people. A short wall of 19th-century
photographs by Fenton, Gustave LeGray and Charles Thurston Thompson
underscore the point that photographers sought out museums and
their contents as soon as the camera was invented.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Charles Willson Peale, the 18th-century portrait painter
who was also an inventor, zoologist and engraver, literally raises
the curtain on the show. In a large 1822 self-portrait he unveils
America's first museum, which he founded, a place where stuffed
birds and painted portraits are overwhelmingly abundant. Gathering,
selecting and classifying _ the museum's chief functions _ are the
themes here, adapted by artists to their own purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the result is highly personal, a museum of the self,
the soul or the artist's work. Examples include Cornell's
``Untitled (Bebe Marie),'' a suitcase full of cards, photographs
and illustrations forming a tender, obsessive dossier, and the
various boxes that Duchamp filled with miniature replicas of his
art, creating portable retrospectives. Herbert Distel's ``Museum of
Drawers,'' created in the 1970s, contains miniatures of, and by,
other artists, 500 of them. Barbara Bloom's ``Reign of Narcissism''
is a portrait of the artist as demure museum display, while
Christian Boltanski's ``Vitrine of Reference (II),'' from 1970,
recalls his childhood in a series of pathetic little artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   And not only art is gathered. Mark Dion amasses animal,
vegetable and mineral specimens in ``Chain of Being,'' a
bookshelf-as-cornucopia and one of the show's commissions. Hiroshi
Sugimoto's eerie photographs of natural history dioramas show how
this material is put to use. And Susan Hiller's ``From the Freud
Museum'' preserves valueless, meaningless little found objects and
texts, assembled into 50 separate boxes in juxtapositions that set
off all sorts of bells, concerning history, myth and memory.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing here is Claes Oldenburg's fabulous
``Mouse Museum,'' a walk-in room in the shape of Mickey's head that
is in fact a portrait of the Pop artist's fertile imagination and
his omnivorous interest in popular culture. Too big for the
exhibition, it is in the museum's lobby, along with works by Allan
McCollum and the Canadian artist-team General Idea.
</P>
<P>
   In the show's middle section, the museum is not so much imitated
as scrutinized, with particular attention to the artwork as
commodity and stolen property. Duchamp is back, with his defaced
reproduction of the Mona Lisa. Haacke traces the provenance of the
small version of Seurat's ``Les Poseuses'' from the artist's studio
in 1888 to the vaults of an investment group nearly 90 years later.
Sophie Calle's ``Last Seen ...'' series dwells upon another sort of
transaction, the theft of three paintings from Boston's Isabella
Stewart Gardner Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Lothar Baumgarten's slide-projection piece '`Unsettled Objects''
considers a more extensive form of theft, in images of the plethora
of non-Western art and artifacts warehoused in the Pitt Rivers
Museum, an ethnographic museum in Oxford, England. These
dense-packed displays, untouched for most of this century, are as
disturbing as they are riveting.
</P>
<P>
   Such cultural presumption echoes in Andrea Fraser's ``Welcome to
the Wadsworth Atheneum: A Museum Tour,'' a 1991 videotape that
never gets to the art, and instead reviews the historical matrix of
prominent individuals and families who created the city and
provided the museum with art, patrons, wings, architects and even
the occasional director or curator.
</P>
<P>
   In the exhibition's final gallery, the end of the museum is
broached with a lightness that suggests that reports of its death
are greatly exaggerated. A 1966 painting by Ruscha shows the Los
Angeles County Museum of Art, built over the La Brea Tar Pits, on
fire. A maquette by Christo shows the Modern under wraps, and the
artist team Komar and Melamid's paintings depict it and the
Guggenheim in ruins. Quietly optimistic, Wall's illuminated
cibachrome image ``Restoration'' shows a panoramic history
painting, vaguely Napoleonic, being tended to by a team of
conservators.
</P>
<P>
   The last work in this rewarding exhibition is also the oldest,
Hubert Robert's late 18th-century oil study for an imaginary scene
of the Louvre's Grand Galerie in ruins. Like the large version,
this work is in the Louvre's collection, making it an early
instance of site-specific art. As such, it marks the beginning of a
very fruitful relationship.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `MUSEUM AS MUSE: ARTISTS REFLECT'
</P>
<P>
   At the Museum of Modern Art, 11 W. 53rd St., New York, from
Sunday, March 14, through June 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
