<SLUG> BC-CALIF-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR'S EDUCATION PLANS FACE CRITICISM FROM FELLOW DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ California Gov. Gray Davis is quickly
learning that family fights, among Democrats at least, often can be
the most contentious.
</P>
<P>
   In a capital dominated by Democrats, the most pointed criticisms
of the governor's education proposals are coming from Sens. John
Vasconcellos of San Jose and Tom Hayden of Los Angeles, both
old-guard liberals who sit on the Senate Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   They have repeatedly asked Davis _ elected in November as the
state's first Democratic governor in 16 years _ and other lawmakers
to look at why California's schools are so mediocre, rather than
rushing through bills they say could ignore children in low-income
families and minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   The problem reached a boiling point Wednesday for Hayden, who
finds himself part of a very small, very vocal minority of
lawmakers savaging Davis' education bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the blank looks when Mr. Vasconcellos tells you what
the deeper problem is,'' Hayden barked at Davis' education
secretary, Gary K. Hart, during a contentious hearing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you, nothing is going to happen. It's like:
`Comment noted. On we go.'''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his inauguration, Davis called a special session of
the Legislature to urgently approve four education bills. The bills
would require a test in order to graduate from high school, boost
reading improvement programs, install a ``peer review'' system to
root out failing teachers, and require performance standards for
the state's worst schools.
</P>
<P>
   At a state Senate Education Committee hearing Wednesday, during
consideration of two of Davis' measures, Vasconcellos continued to
criticize the administration. But it was Hayden who appeared on the
warpath, even though he voted for the measures by the end of the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Kerry Mazzoni, D-Novato, who is sponsoring Davis'
reading reform measure, shot back at Hayden during the hearing
Wednesday when he repeatedly questioned a $4 million outreach
program to promote reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it comes down to whether you are willing to at least
try something or if you are going to resist constantly,'' Mazzoni
said. ``Yes, we have many, many problems in this state. But we have
to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The $4 million reading promotion program would include a
television advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden ridiculed a provision that would provide $2 million to
reward schools with $5,000 grants if they get students to read more
books. Hayden said the money should be used for tutoring and
training teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish people would listen because there is going to be a
disaster when you find out there has been no significant
improvement as a result of these programs in four years,'' Hayden
said. ``We are at the bottom. Something is wrong that will not be
fixed by taking to the television to tell kids to read. It only
re-enforces their television fixation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart, defending the reading campaign, said: ``The purpose of
this provision is to advocate that the teaching of reading is more
than just a teacher and a student's responsibility. That parents,
grandparents, that all in the community have a responsibility to
attempt to encourage and nurture reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante described the criticism from
Vasconcellos and Hayden as ``Democracy at its finest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having a dissenting point of view is important to
developing legislation that will have an impact,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
