<SLUG> BC-FILM-DEEP-END-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURE DIRECTION LETS `DEEP END' RISE ABOVE LIMITATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The modern ``family-healing drama'' has become such a staple of
feature and television movies since it was more or less invented by
1980's ``Ordinary People'' that it's hard for one to seem very
fresh and original, or to move us in any new way.
</P>
<P>
   And, as a literary property, Jacquelyn Mitchard's novel, ``The
Deep End of the Ocean,'' has its share of familiar elements and
glaring improbabilities, as well as one huge coincidence as a plot
point that makes it particularly hard to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, under the sure hand of director Ulu Grosbard
(``Straight Time,'' ``Georgia'') and with near-flawless
performances from Michelle Pfeiffer and Treat Williams, the film
rises well above these built-in limitations to emerge as something
special.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchard's story is about a seemingly perfect (maybe too
perfect) Madison, Wis., family that experiences an almost
unimaginable tragedy when the middle of the three children is
snatched one afternoon from a crowded Chicago lobby where the
mother (Pfeiffer) is having her high school reunion.
</P>
<P>
   When the police, lead by a sympathetic woman detective (Whoopi
Goldberg), can find no trace of the three-year-old boy, the agony
of the days and weeks and months of waiting to hear something
exacts a punishing toll on mother, father (Williams) and the
family's older son (Cory Buck).
</P>
<P>
   Cut to nine years later. Somehow the family has survived, and
one day the abducted son comes back into their lives. The rest of
the movie deals with the impact of this miraculous reappearance,
and the way the family finds to heal the many wounds the experience
has created.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 novel was, of course, a monster best-seller, given a
huge boost by the advocacy of Oprah Winfrey. Thus, the filmmakers
have had to stay very close to its proven success formula,
maintaining its shakier elements, as well as an ending that seems
almost too tidy to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Stephen Schiff's script does an admirable job of reducing
a long novel into a tight, dramatic line that communicates every
beat of the gut-wrenching experience, while keeping us oriented
with the individual emotional devastation of each one of the
characters.
</P>
<P>
   The movie makes a terrific star vehicle for Pfeiffer. She's
excruciatingly perfect in the role, forcing us to experience all
the guilt, pain and anxiety her character is feeling in every
agonizing scene. If this film had been released in November or
December, she'd be a guaranteed Oscar nominee.
</P>
<P>
   As her husband, Treat Williams is almost as effective. Always an
underrated actor and star, he's never seemed quite so sympathetic a
presence, such an appealing mixture of strength and vulnerability.
If the film is a hit, it should revitalize his somewhat stagnant
career.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, ``Deep End'' works off the sharp eye and
intuitive skill of Ulu Grosbard _ its 70-year-old, New York-based
director who made his first film, ``The Subject Was Roses,''
exactly 30 years ago, but has never come close to the A-list in
Hollywood, and has worked mostly in theater.
</P>
<P>
   By giving a startling verisimilitude to every scene, every
gesture, every nuance, his direction creates an inexorable
precision and honesty that makes us forget all about its creakier
plot elements. The film may not be an instant classic, but it's as
expertly and poignantly directed a family-in-crisis drama as
Hollywood has produced in a while.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
