u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALLARME-EXHIBIT-NYT &LR;      03-11 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALLARME-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POET WHO MADE AN IMPRESSION ON THE IMPRESSIONISTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)   By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although his writing was more than occasionally
readerproof, Stephane Mallarme (1842-98) was one of the most
influential cultural figures of 19th-century France. An
avant-gardist, a wit, a salon keeper, a fashion commentator, a
translator of Poe's poems, a critic who supported the
Impressionists and a forerunner of the Symbolist poets whose
innovative ways with language had a significant impact on
Modernism, he himself was nothing less than a work of art.
</P>
<P>
   His closest friends were painters: Edouard Manet, Berthe
Morisot, Pierre-Auguste Renoir, Edgar Degas and James Whistler. He
defended their work in his critical writings, and they did
portraits of him and illustrations for his books. Paul Gauguin,
Henri Matisse, Edvard Munch, Odilon Redon, Auguste Rodin and Felix
Vallotton, among others, also produced Mallarmean images and
tributes.
</P>
<P>
   More or less pegged to the centenary of Mallarme's death, an
intense but unfortunately short-lived little show, ``A Painter's
Poet: Stephane Mallarme and His Impressionist Circle,'' can be seen
at the Bertha and Karl Leubsdorf Art Gallery of Hunter College
through March 20. The show was organized by Jane Mayo Roos,
associate professor of art history at Hunter, and a team of
graduate students in conjunction with the Bibliotheque Litteraire
Jacques Doucet in Paris. Its informative catalog, with many
scholarly contributions, is an essential part of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Though literary in tone, displaying a slew of books, autograph
manuscripts and letters, this display is also a visual treat,
beguilingly laced with portraits, prints, photographs,
illustrations and rare items like Mallarme's charts for the
teaching of English. There are works relating to Mallarme by Manet,
Morisot, Renoir, Redon, Gustave Dore, Maurice Denis, Whistler,
Raoul Dufy and Matisse. There are a number of Mallarme portraits,
among them a wonderful 1889 oil by the Swiss-born artist Charles
Giron; an 1895 photograph by Degas of Mallarme and Renoir; another
(undated) by Nadar of the aging Mallarme with a little shawl around
his shoulders, and small etchings by Whistler and Gauguin. The
portraits alone are worth a visit to the show.
</P>
<P>
   Mallarme was born in Paris to parents who came from a long line
of civil servants. He wrote poetry early on and studied English so
he could read the work of Edgar Allan Poe, a strong influence on
Mallarme's idol, Charles Baudelaire. His language study paid off in
another way: for all of his adult life Mallarme earned his bread
teaching English in French schools. In his early 20s he began two
of his major poems, ``Herodiade'' (1869) and ``The Afternoon of a
Faun'' (1876). The sensual ``Faun'' inspired the 1894 tone poem by
Debussy and the 1912 ballet by Nijinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mallarme believed that writing should be close to the
abstraction of music, that it should create its effects by enigma
and veiled suggestion rather than description or exposition, and
that conventional syntax could be dispensed with, much of his work
is far from an easy read. In 1866, when 10 of his poems were
published, the school board of the Lycee Imperial in Tournon, where
he was teaching, was scandalized by a teacher's venturing to write
poetry and dismissed him. He had to transfer to another post.
</P>
<P>
   But his writing was hailed by his peers, and in 1873, at the age
of 31, he met Manet, 10 years his senior. A close friendship
developed that lasted until Manet's death a decade later. Manet
agreed to illustrate Mallarme's translation of ``The Raven,'' Poe's
most popular poem. Their collaboration was published in 1875, a
folio containing six black-and-white lithographs by the artist _ on
display here _ sketchy, dark but very legible vignettes much in the
spirit of Poe's haunted rumination.
</P>
<P>
   Manet also did illustrations for ``Afternoon of a Faun,'' and
other Mallarme poems, and in 1876 painted Mallarme's portrait, a
warm, informal view of the poet holding forth in the artist's
studio, cigar in hand. The painting itself _ said to be more of a
likeness than any other image of Mallarme _ is not here, but an
etching of it appears as an illustration in the book ``Les Poetes
Maudits'' (1884) by Paul Verlaine.
</P>
<P>
   Mallarme wrote in praise of Manet's work and in 1874 produced a
clever defense of the artist when the government-chosen jury for
that year's Salon turned down two of four paintings _ three oils
and a watercolor _ he had submitted. After subtly mocking the
jury's conservatism, Mallarme predicted that public taste for
Manet's work would prevail eventually. Two years later he published
a more important discourse, ``The Impressionists and Edouard
Manet,'' an eloquent paean to the new painting and the man he saw
as its master.
</P>
<P>
   Through Manet, Mallarme met such luminaries as Emile Zola,
Morisot (Manet's sister-in-law), Claude Monet, Renoir, Degas and
Mery Laurent, a cultivated muse to many, who would become the
extramarital love of Mallarme's life. A rather jolly undated
photograph of her at the piano in her art-crammed apartment
includes Mallarme and another male friend.
</P>
<P>
   Always intrigued _ like Manet _ by modish matters, Mallarme
tried his hand as a fashion columnist in the mid-1870s, writing
under the nom de plume ``Miss Satin.'' In 1881 he began his
celebrated weekly ``mardis,'' Tuesday evening salons in his tiny
apartment, where his artist and writer friends pontificated in
clouds of smoke while his wife and daughter did needlework at the
dining room table.
</P>
<P>
   In 1897, the year before his death, Mallarme published his last
major poem, ``A Throw of the Dice Will Never Abolish Chance.'' It
was his most convoluted creation, unpunctuated and unrhymed, whose
typographical idiosyncrasies (as seen here in printer's proofs and
finished book) are part and parcel of the work.
</P>
<P>
   According to an essay by Robin Kaye Goodman in the catalog, the
poem was perceived by the painter Redon, who illustrated it, as an
attack on bourgeois notions of reading, meaning and sense _ if so,
a fitting forecast of the century to come.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it, Mallarme is a formidable subject. But this
well-conceived show is a lively introduction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
