<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOCK-STOCK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLISH FIRST FILM IS LOCK, STOCK AND BARRELS OF FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's always daunting to jump on board a bandwagon of raves for a
new, small film. It's important not to oversell the movie's merits
because it can cause over-inflated expectations for the audience.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels,'' which has already
taken Britain by storm, has become the biggest thing since
``Trainspotting.'' First-time director Guy Ritchie brings such a
seamless collision of working-class humor, unpredictable folly and
adreneline-rush fury to the film that it's impossible to resist.
</P>
<P>
   This comedic caper might easily be likened to some of the
obscure, gritty '60s English films such as ``The Lavender Hill
Mob'' or anything that starred crime-story regular, actor Stanley
Baker. But Ritchie, who swears he knows very little about proper
cinema history, has a wholly original visual eye. His lack of
pretension enhances the film's charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' is tinged with tobacco
stains, a yellowing, dingy and faded hue, and a wild, careening
camera and it fits perfectly with its East End London locale.
</P>
<P>
   The area is a seedy, slummy part of town and it's here four best
mates _ Eddie (Nick Moran), Tom (Jason Flemyng), Bacon (Jason
Statham) and Soap (Dexter Fletcher) _ rule with a not very assured
iron fist.
</P>
<P>
   They're cocky young lads and they stake Eddie, who is a gifted
card shark, in a big poker game against evil porno and underworld
mob boss, Hatchet Harry (P.H. Moriarty). Everything is going fine
until Eddie is set up and gets taken for everything he owns,
including his friends' money _ and maybe even his dear old dad's
pub, which Harry wants as collateral.
</P>
<P>
   The boys embark on a plan to steal a bundle from the drug thugs
next door to pay off the debt. But every den of thieves has its own
code of honor and soon the East End is blown apart by the rowdiest,
nastiest, craziest bunch of hoodlums, who descend en masse upon the
already roughshod sector.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie manages to infuse a routine scam and counter-scam
scenario with a fresh twist upon the gangster persona.
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' ends, we're
exhausted from the wild ride. But it's been fun _ although violent.
</P>
<P>
   The film should make stars (finally) of Jason Flemyng, who was
quite memorable as the gay dancer in ``Alive and Kicking'' and as
an abusive boyfriend in ``Hollow Reed,'' and of Ritchie, who will
have his work cut out in trying to match the crisp, energetic
frenzy of this stylish first film.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1714EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
