<SLUG> BC-BABY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABY GENIUSES':   NOT THE WORST MOVIE EVER, BUT CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One way to get through ``Baby Geniuses'' is to think about
whether it really is the worst movie you've ever seen. Probably
not, but pretty darn close.
</P>
<P>
   Deceptive trailers and television shots may make this
talking-toddler film look competently made, but that proves not to
be the case. Its technical caliber is what you'd expect from ``Look
Who's Talking 12.'' The plotting is dopey and barely
comprehensible. The sound looping is off-kilter. The look is sad
and cheesy, often bordering on the grotesque, so that the badly
lighted faces of the film's adult actors take on a grayish pallor.
</P>
<P>
   And the babies don't fare any better. Ably executed computer
tricks enable these tots to talk like obnoxious adults (they
admiringly discuss ``The Jerry Springer Show''), but this trick is
better suited to piglets than people. The morphed children look
gnomish and strange.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Bob Clark, whose most notable film credits over a
long career remain ``Porky's'' and ``A Christmas Story,'' and
written by him with Greg Michael, this flawlessly unfunny comedy
concerns an evil child psychologist and CEO, Dr. Elena Kinder. She
is played by Kathleen Turner in a performance that says, ``Hey,
it's a living,'' and is abetted by an overlooked sidekick played by
Christopher Lloyd.
 &UR;  &LR;  These two study the language of babies who can secretly say
things like ``jerk!'' and plan to exploit their little laboratory
specimens for evil gain. Meanwhile, nicer baby researchers (Peter
MacNichol and Kim Cattrall) are unselfishly studying the same kind
of data. The film's single weirdest stroke is to cast, as their
assistants, Dom DeLuise and Ruby Dee (the only performer who
escapes unscathed). According to production notes, these two are
meant to be ``an older hippie couple''
</P>
<P>
   The story also involves twin babies (played by triplets named
Fitzgerald) who switch places in ways meant to heighten the fun.
Filmed as awkwardly as they are, they prompt thoughts about how
children in glossier films and commercials are made to look so
right. The babies' clumsy antics in this Tri-Star film often
involve conspicuous use of Sony products. If Sony made diapers they
would be plugged here too.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BABY GENIUSES'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bob Clark; written by Clark and Greg Michael, based
on a story by Steven Paul, Francisca Matos and Robert Grasmere;
director of photography, Stephen Katz; edited by Stan Cole; music
by Paul Zaza; production designer, Francis Pezza; produced by Paul;
released by Tri-Star Pictures. Running time: 94 minutes. This film
is rated PG (parental guidance suggested). It includes mild
profanity and smart-aleck baby talk.
</P>
<P>
   With: Kathleen Turner (Elena), Christopher Lloyd (Heep), Kim
Cattrall (Robin), Peter MacNicol (Dan), Dom DeLuise (Lenny) and
Ruby Dee (Margo).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1720EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
