<HEADER>
A6821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      03-11 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not be the worst decision of the season. (Remember ``More
to Love''?) But the booking of ``Band in Berlin'' in the Helen
Hayes Theater on Broadway over the acclaimed drama ``Wit'' is
looking more and more suspect.
</P>
<P>
   For those just tuning in, last fall the owner of the Helen
Hayes, Martin Markinson, opted to book ``Band in Berlin,'' a
musical based on a Nazi-era singing group, over ``Wit,'' which was
earning stellar reviews in a small theater Off Off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   His reasoning, he said, was that the subject matter of ``Wit,''
a literature professor's battle with ovarian cancer, was not
appetizing to audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Spurned, ``Wit'' subsequently reopened on Jan. 7 in the Union
Square Theater, an Off Broadway house that, with 499 seats, is the
same size as the Helen Hayes but is not Tony eligible. The move has
been a rousing success.
</P>
<P>
   This week producers of ``Wit'' announced that they had earned
back the $500,000 it cost to mount the show and were making
approximately $60,000 a week in profit. Weekly grosses have been
running about $145,000, out of a potential $148,000, said Roy
Gabay, the show's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile at the Helen Hayes the producers of ``Band in
Berlin,'' which opened on Sunday to dismissive reviews, reported
sales of a meager $66,283 last week. But Robert V. Straus, the lead
producer, said the figure was low in part because on opening night
most seats are given free to the press, investors, friends and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Straus said he was giving the show two to five weeks to build an
audience. ``If we're at $60,000 in three weeks,'' he said, ``you
know what we're going to have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Markinson said: ``I'm very happy for `Wit,' but I come from a
place where I never look back. To me that's negative energy. Would
I have made the same choice? Probably. But I simply don't allow
myself to take a whip out and beat myself.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Mackintosh was in New York this week laying the
groundwork for what promises to be a coming onslaught on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh, the producer of commercial behemoths like ``Les
Miserables'' and ``Miss Saigon,'' spent most days casting for
``Martin Guerre,'' his oft-reworked musical, which will open in
Minneapolis in September and then tour. It is aiming for Broadway
in spring 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But in his spare time _ and there wasn't much _ he turned his
attention to several other shows. The first is ``Putting It
Together,'' a Stephen Sondheim revue, which now looks likely for
the Barrymore Theater in September or October. Mackintosh dined
with Sondheim on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh also was discussing his forthcoming revival of
``Oliver,'' which will probably try out in Toronto, Chicago and
possibly Boston before landing in New York in early spring. Audra
McDonald and Geoffrey Rush have been mentioned for roles; a
spokesman for Mackintosh, Marc Thibodeau, said he could not confirm
any negotiations. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If any more proof were needed of this season's strange economic
logic, consider this: The only real moneymakers have been straight
plays.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the pack last fall was ``The Blue Room,'' which sold out
a three-month run and returned a tidy $2 million profit, and
``Electra,'' which will conclude a four-month run on March 21 about
$400,000 in the black.
</P>
<P>
   The spring's first major opening, ``Death of a Salesman,'' has
also put up good numbers, regularly selling out and building a $3.5
million advance.
</P>
<P>
   And more winners may be on the way. Emmanuel Azenberg, the
producer of ``The Iceman Cometh,'' opening in April, said this week
that advance sales of his show would likely top $4.4 million this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Producers of ``Amy's View,'' another April entry, declined to
say what their advance was, but a member of the production who had
seen sales figures said they were ``Blue Room-like.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, of the season's musical offerings, only ``Annie Get
Your Gun'' and ``Fosse'' are showing any real box office vigor.
``Footloose,'' which has had good weeks and bad, has slipped of
late. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cast of the Encores concert series' next show, ``The
Ziegfeld Follies of 1936,'' opening on March 25, will include two
alumni of the musical ``Chicago'': Karen Ziemba, who was in the
current New York production, and Ruthie Henshall, who was nominated
for an Olivier Award for ``Chicago'' in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ziegfeld''s cast also includes Peter Scolari and Mary Testa.
Ms. Henshall also looks likely to join the New York ``Chicago'' in
May, playing the role of Velma opposite Sandy Duncan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Deidre Murray, composer of the music for ``Running Man,''
first proposed a performance piece about her brother's heroin
addiction to her collaborator, Cornelius Eady, he thought the
concept was slightly unwieldy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have had to be an opera,'' said Eady, recalling Ms.
Murray's original 20-page outline. ``With a cast of thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Murray said, ``I wanted to do a homage to people who never
make it.'' Her brother, Wellington, died in 1991. ``He fell and
kept falling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But over the course of two years the piece was whittled down
into a 75-minute, jazz-infused piece, playing now through Sunday at
the Here performance space in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running Man,'' which has received some critical praise and
subsequent attention from commercial producers, was commissioned by
the Music-Theater Group. Lyn Austin, the producing director of the
group, said negotiations were under way to reopen in a larger
theater this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Eady nor Ms. Murray are accustomed to working in the
theater. Ms. Murray is a accomplished jazz cellist; Eady is a poet.
</P>
<P>
   But both seem to be enjoying their excursion. ``Theater is kind
of like dreaming out loud,'' Eady said. ``I think I'm hooked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
