<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6831 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-CHILDREN-SPI &LR;      03-11 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHILDREN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIR OF MISSING SHOES SPEAKS VOLUMES ABOUT LIFE OF IRANIAN CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's best foreign-language film Oscar nomination for
Majid Majidi's ``Children of Heaven'' puts the official seal of
approval on one of the true phenomenon of international cinema in
the '90s: the renaissance in Iranian filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   The film is virtually a compendium of the style, themes and
sensibility of the New Iranian Cinema. Like so many of them (``The
White Balloon,'' ``And Life Goes On,'' etc.), it's an Islamically
correct, neo-realist parable about a vulnerable child struggling
with a big problem.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the child is a schoolboy from a poor family named Ali,
whose ordeal begins in the midst of a shopping trip for his
bedridden mother when he loses his younger sister's shoes, which he
had just taken to a cobbler for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing his family cannot afford a new pair of shoes and already
in the doghouse with his father, Ali devises a scheme with his
little sister, Zahra, to ``share'' his well-worn sneakers: she
wears them in the morning, he wears them in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   From this premise, the film moves along in an episodic manner as
various problems arise both in their family and in each of their
schools as they struggle to live with the one pair of shoes, and it
builds to a grand climax in which Ali's anxiety over the situation
drives him to desperate measures.
</P>
<P>
   The film, reportedly a huge hit in Tehran, operates on several
levels that can't be translated into subtitles. For instance,
though it goes unmentioned, the children are Iranian Turks, a
minority whose accent immediately establishes them as outsiders to
Iranian society.
</P>
<P>
   But what does translate is another lean, uncluttered, totally
engaging look at a brave Iranian child trying to cope with a
seemingly insurmountable problem in a horror-filled world he
doesn't understand, run by adults who are as remote to him as
Martians.
</P>
<P>
   As in other Iranian childhood films, director Majidi has given
much attention to the casting of the children. They're both
adorable, and, as Ali, little Mir Farrokh Hashemian is an
astonishingly good actor, with eyes that seem to carry the sorrow
of the whole world in them.
</P>
<P>
   Also, like so many of the New Iranian Cinema's international
hits, ``Children of Heaven'' is, despite its grimness, ultimately
quite optimistic. Life is hard, it tells us, but people are
intrinsically good, and everything tends to work out in the end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1729EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
