<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRENCH-FILMS-830(3TAK     03-11 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-FILMS-830(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE'S CINEMATIC PASSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 3rd take is an optional sidebar with the schedule of film
showings.) 
(js) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Having to consume the $40 million buckets of toxic
popcorn Hollywood churns out month after month can throw a film
critic into a state of hand-wringing despair. Why, why, why? Why
has an industry with the potential to enrich our lives sunk into a
soul-deadening wasteland of cartoonish violence and adolescent
pranks? The answer, of course, has something to do with commercial
calculation and least-common-denominator marketing.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the questions: Where can you go to find a cinematic
semblance of flesh-and-blood people with complicated emotions and
bodies that perspire, instead of pose, when they make love? Where
can you find movies with characters who think as well as act,
movies that capture a recognizable sense of life's texture, the
feeling of here and now? Heaven knows America's independent films
are trying to fill the gap, and some are succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a better answer, and it can be summed up in one
word: France. The French cinema, like no other, has a solid
tradition of films that celebrate the realm of the senses: food,
love, air, light, trees and architecture. Those visual delights can
be savored for the next 10 days at the Walter Reade Theater where
the Film Society of Lincoln Center is presenting its annual series
Rendez-Vous With French Cinema Today. But unless they find American
distributors, many of these films _ shown in cooperation with
Unifrance, France's film-export agency; the French Film Office, and
the French Cultural Services _ may never be seen in the United
States again. That would be a shame, since most, if not all, merit
engagements here.
</P>
<P>
   After an immersion in 11 of those 13 films, I came away feeling
the elation of having returned from an unusually stimulating
vacation. None of the films shown at the press screenings may be
outright masterpieces, but most of the 11 delineate complex
characters, finely nuanced naturalistic performances and a
matter-of-fact erotic realism that every Hollywood director could
learn from.
</P>
<P>
   The most quintessentially Gallic of the movies is deliriously
romantic: Claude Lelouch's irresistibly sensuous ``Hasards ou
Coincidences'' (``Luck or Coincidences''), one of many in the
series to have a female protagonist. If Lelouch, who made his name
33 years ago with the ultimate mid-'60s date movie, ``A Man and a
Woman,'' is still trafficking in the same giddy live-for-life
romanticism that infused that breakthrough movie, his vision has
deepened appreciably.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hasards'' offers frothier variations on a theme explored in
much darker and more anguished ways by the great Polish director
Krzysztof Kieslowski, who died three years ago. Alessandra Martines
is Myriam, a beautiful and successful dancer, adrift after a failed
marriage and a career that has peaked, who finds a fairy tale happy
ending with a wealthy older man. But when he takes her and her
young son on a euphoric global jaunt, he and the boy die in a
drowning accident, leaving Myriam grief-stricken and suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   The son's video camera, which recorded the trip and the fatal
accident, passes to thieves and ends up in the hands of a
philosophy professor who deduces what happened and becomes obsessed
with finding Myriam. Meanwhile, she is determinedly retracing her
steps and refilming the scenes as an anguished personal memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hasards,'' which moves from France to Canada to Turkey to
Acapulco, is, among other things, a gorgeous travelogue. An
unabashed sentimentalist, Lelouch has a gift for portraying the
beauty of the world and the joy of happy people with an intensity
that almost hurts. And in this film, the philosophical questions
about chance and coincidence that he toys with give his film an
intellectual underpinning that keeps it from spinning off into the
romance-novel ozone.
</P>
<P>
   Tonie Marshall's ``Venus Institute,'' a huge hit in France, has
a similar aura of fairy tale enchantment enriched by wit as well as
a fiercely intelligent portrayal by Nathalie Baye of a 40-year-old
beautician who is so burned by love that she limits her sexual life
to flings with men she picks up. One day a handsome younger
sculptor, observing her breakup with a lover in a restaurant,
becomes smitten with her and embarks on an ardent pursuit that she
furiously resists. The movie may be little more than a modern
Cinderella fantasy for middle-aged women, but it is beautifully
acted and lightheartedly sexy.
</P>
<P>
   Sex, in fact, is so pervasive in this year's Rendez-Vous that
the series might as well have been subtitled Sex and the Single
Woman. Six films _ Catherine Breillat's ``Romance,'' Cedric Kahn's
``L'Ennui,'' Catherine Corsini's ``Nouvelle Eve,'' Laetitia
Masson's ``A Vendre'' (``For Sale''), Philippe Grandrieux's
brilliant, experimental ``Sombre'' and Nicole Garcia's ``Place
Vendome'' _ explore female sexuality with a depth and complexity
that is light-years beyond the sexist caricatures and Puritanical
moralizing that typify Hollywood's view of women.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a witty role reversal, Bruno Poldalydes' ``Dieu Seul Me
Voit'' (``Only God Sees Me'') tells a kind of male Cinderella
story, in which a shy, indecisive sound engineer can't make up his
mind which of three beautiful, strong-willed women he wants. This
light, engaging comedy just won the Cesar, the French Academy
Award, for best first feature.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Breillat's ``Romance,'' one of two films not screened in
advance _ the other is Jean-Philippe Toussaint's ``Patinoire''
(``The Ice Rink'') _ explores in graphic detail the erotic life of
a young woman (Caroline Ducey) who lives out her sexual fantasies
with three lovers, one of whom is frightened by the devouring
intensity of her desire for him. Ms. Breillat has pushed the
boundaries of sexual explicitness in earlier films like ``Sale
Comme un Ange'' and ``Parfait Amour,'' and here she is said to have
gone even further.
</P>
<P>
   In ``L'Ennui,'' adapted from a novel by Alberto Moravia, Martin
(Charles Berling), a philosophy professor separated from his wife
and suffering from an agitated depression, begins an affair with
Cecilia (Sophie Guillemin), a Rubenesque 17-year-old whose previous
lover, a much older painter, suffered a heart attack while making
love to her. Cecilia is as inexpressive as she is sexually
inexhaustible. And as the affair develops, Martin becomes
obsessively jealous of the young woman, who eventually concedes
that she is also involved with someone else.
</P>
<P>
   This brilliant, emotionally harrowing film, which has several
graphic (but simulated) scenes of intercourse, explores not just
the physical and psychological but the philosophical ramifications
of sexual possession, and follows Martin's quest for an elusive and
ultimately unattainable control to the brink of madness. Ms.
Guillemin gives a luminously mysterious performance of the
wide-eyed, milky-skinned love object, who is at once infinitely
available and ultimately unattainable.
</P>
<P>
   Variations of the boredom and aimlessness that motivate Cecilia
also drive the protagonist of ``La Nouvelle Eve,'' an incisive
dissection of a selfish, angry young Parisian. Camille (Karin
Viard) is an attractive, single 30-year-old who becomes fixated on
Alexis (Pierre Loup Rajot), a happily married man at whom she hurls
herself relentlessly until his resistance cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Viard's Camille chillingly embodies a certain kind of sexual
ruthlessness. She wants everything, and she wants it her way or not
at all. Whenever she feels rebuffed or rejected by Alexis, she
carelessly throws herself at the nearest man for comfort and
revenge. When Alexis jokingly calls her a terrorist, he is not far
from wrong. The power of Ms. Viard's performance is that she makes
us understand Camille and even care for her a little.
</P>
<P>
   In the somewhat weaker ``A Vendre,'' a detective (Sergio
Casetllitto), hired by a businessman whose young fiancee
disappeared the day they were to be wed, digs into the past of the
woman (Sandrine Kiberlain) and slowly discovers a restless creature
driven by an inexplicable rebelliousness into prostitution. Like
``La Nouvelle Eve,'' ``A Vendre'' avoids trotting out condescending
pop-psychological truisms to explain her angst, suggesting only
that it stems from some perverse deep-seated longing for an
unattainable independence. What holds this quasi-Hitchcockian yarn
together is Ms. Kiberlain's sullen, spellbinding performance. The
movie really only stumbles in its final scenes set in New York
where the American characters have strong French accents.
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist of ``Sombre'' is a virginal young woman (Elina
Lowenstein) who falls in love with a serial killer (Marc Barbe) who
in the film's early scenes is shown methodically murdering
prostitutes. Filmed in semi-darkness with a hand-held camera and
sometimes veering into pure visual abstraction, the movie, the most
experimental in the series, is a deeply unsettling, stylistically
audacious mood piece that attempts to enter a psychotic state of
mind.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Sombre'' is the most daring in the series, Nicole Garcia's
``Place Vendome'' is the most conventional. Catherine Deneuve gives
an elegant and subtle performance as the alcoholic widow of an
unscrupulous diamond merchant. After her husband's death, her
effort to sell some valuable stolen gems leads her into a reunion
with another dealer and former lover who betrayed her many years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The sexuality of many of the characters in these films is much
more fluid than it used to be in French movies. Camille's best
friends in ``Nouvelle Eve'' are a lesbian couple, and she enjoys a
casual lesbian fling. One of her boyfriends describes a homosexual
encounter he had. A party she attends is a kinky, drug-infested
bisexual orgy.
</P>
<P>
   And in ``La Poulpe'' (``The Octopus''), an entertaining film
noir set in a grim seaside French town riddled with corruption
stemming from the clandestine smuggling of slave labor, the Nora in
a modern-day Nick-and-Nora couple of amateur sleuths casually
sleeps with women as well as men. Clothilde Courau brings an
irresistible vitality to this tomboyish urchin who in one memorable
scene emerges nude from a bathtub, pointing a gun to fend off a
gang of sadistic thugs.
</P>
<P>
   The erotic shenanigans in ``Ceux Qui M'Aiment Prendront le
Train'' (``Those Who Love Me Can Take the Train'') are
programatically pansexual. The film, by Patrice Chereau, who
directed ``Queen Margot,'' follows a group of relatives, friends,
former lovers and students of a famous painter as they travel from
Paris to Limoges for his funeral. The artist being remembered is
compared to Francis Bacon in both the ferocity of his work and the
tumult of a personal life that crossed all conventional boundaries.
And those who remember him (including Vincent Perez as a
transsexual) reflect the chaotic sexuality in which he reveled.
</P>
<P>
   This extravagantly romantic film, whose rich musical score
ranges from Jeff Buckley to Mahler's 10th Symphony, begins with a
dazzling sequence at the train station in which the camera
crosscuts among the various mourners and their complicated
relationships. Eventually the film loses steam. But before it does,
it offers a provocatively sexy vision of Paris' vie boheme,
late-'90s style.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there is Claude Miller's ``Classe de Neige'' (``Class
Trip''), an eerie tour de force of escalating horror that at
moments suggests a Gallic equivalent of ``The Shining.'' The movie
tells the story of a shy young boy plagued by horrifying
nightmares, many of which originate from the gruesome stories his
overprotective and slightly sinister father has told him.
</P>
<P>
   When he goes on a class ski trip to a lodge in the French Alps,
he experiences familiar childhood terrors, and at first the film
appears to be a conventional rite-of-passage story about a boy
growing up and facing down his fears. As the film proceeds, those
terrors both escalate and seem less fantastic all the time.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``La Classe de Neige'' has the same attractively
high-gloss visual imagination as Lelouch's ``Hasards,'' it uses
scenic beauty to an opposite and diabolical effect by pulling the
rug out from under your sentimental expectations. What if your
worst nightmare _ one that is so horrible that you can't even
describe it _ turns out to be true?
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   RENDEZ-VOUS WITH FRENCH CINEMA TODAY
</P>
<P>
   Rendez-Vous With French Cinema Today, a 13-film series sponsored
by the Film Society of Lincoln Center, runs through March 21 at the
Walter Reade Theater at Lincoln Center. The films, all made in
1998, are in French with English subtitles, and most of the
directors will be present to introduce and discuss their work.
Tickets are $8.50; $5 for film society members; $4.50 for the
elderly at weekday matinees. Information: (212) 875-5600. Here is a
schedule:
