<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEEP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-11 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEEP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DEEP END OF THE OCEAN': A CHILD IS GONE, AND THEN HE IS NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to see why ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' became Oprah
Winfrey's first book club selection, the first book she thought
America might read en masse. Jacqueline Mitchard's novel about a
family thrown into turmoil tells a page-turner of a story that hits
a universal nerve.
</P>
<P>
   All Beth Cappadora need do is get caught up in the hubbub of a
high school reunion and take her eyes off her 3-year-old for a
couple of minutes. That's all it takes to explode Beth's
picture-perfect Middle American family life. The boy is gone,
perhaps forever, and all bets are off.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mitchard sent Beth into a somewhat wilder, angrier downhill
spiral than the glossy film adaptation of ``The Deep End of the
Ocean'' chooses to. But like Ulu Grosbard's previous film,
``Georgia,'' this one summons the kind of family friction that
creates sparks.
</P>
<P>
   With a fine, impassioned performance from Michelle Pfeiffer as
the story's raw-nerved heroine, the film moves beyond the
detective-story aspects of its material to concentrate on what kind
of shock waves batter a family after an event like this. The
aftereffects are keenly observed, and you needn't read further if
you'd like to be surprised by the plot twist behind 3-year-old
Ben's disappearance. It's startling, and I'm glad I didn't know
about it going in.
</P>
<P>
   However: the revelation comes midway through the story, and the
film doesn't reveal the full range of its family conundrum until
its second half. The first part of the film, straightforwardly
adapted and adroitly pared down by the former film critic Stephen
Schiff (whose ``Lolita'' screenplay likewise preserved the essence
of its material), concentrates on fault lines created by Ben's
vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   Relations grow strained between Beth and her Italian-American
husband, Pat, who is played by Treat Williams. (Ethnicity is one of
the rough edges that have generally been smoothed here.) Beth
drifts into a despairing haze and neglects her other children,
baleful 7-year-old Vincent and baby Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she forms an alliance with the female police
detective assigned to the case. Ms. Mitchard may have described
Det. Candy Bliss as looking just like Gloria Steinem, but she's
played sturdily by Whoopi Goldberg here.
</P>
<P>
   Beth eventually leaves Chicago, where she lost Ben, and returns
to her Madison, Wis., home. Then time passes, Pat moves the whole
family to a stereotypically pleasant Chicago suburb and one day a
nice neighborhood schoolboy asks if he can mow the Cappadoras'
lawn. He calls himself Sam (Ryan Merriman), but Beth knows him
instantly. Sure enough, the fingerprints match.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Now what?'' stage of the story may be the one that most
defies credulity, but it's also the one that Grosbard makes most
intriguing. The long-missing child is reunited with his proud
father, still-grieving mother and sullen older brother (played
especially convincingly as a teen-ager by Emmy-winning Jonathan
Jackson).
</P>
<P>
   But he now has another family (John Kapelos touchingly plays his
adoptive father), and he is no longer the same golden-haired child
who rules Beth's imagination. Much of the film's emotional impact
comes from its awareness of how wrenchingly, in any family, real
and idealized relationships can diverge.
</P>
<P>
   Grosbard mercifully avoids melodrama. And he paces the film so
simply and determinedly that its early scenes are like a string of
picture postcards, each one depicting a new phase of the family's
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the film seeks tidy resolution for a tangled set of
problems does this restraint seem overwhelmed by the complexity of
the situation. But the only real false notes are musical ones, from
a score by Elmer Bernstein that turns familiar and trite when the
film does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned.) It includes profanity and sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE DEEP END OF THE OCEAN'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ulu Grosbard; written by Stephen Schiff, based on
the book by Jacquelyn Mitchard; director of photography, Stephen
Goldblatt; edited by John Bloom; music by Elmer Bernstein;
production designer, Dan Davis; produced by Kate Guinzberg and
Steve Nicolaides; released by Columbia Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Michelle Pfeiffer (Beth), Treat Williams (Pat), Whoopi
Goldberg (Candy), Michael McElroy (Ben), Ryan Merriman (Sam), Cory
Buck (Vincent at 7), Jonathan Jackson (Vincent at 16), Alexa Vega
(Kerry at 9), Michael McGrady (Jimmy Daugherty), John Kapelos
(George), Tony Musante (Angelo), Rose Gregorio (Rosie), Lucinda
Jenney (Laurie), John Roselius (Bastokovich), Brenda Strong (Ellen)
and K.K. Dodds (Theresa).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
