<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARMONISTS-FILM-REVIE     03-11 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARMONISTS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGERS SILENCED BY A SINISTER BACKBEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wreathed in melody and suffused with the nostalgic glow of
remembered romance and youthful hope, the fathomless mystery of the
Holocaust and Germany's long struggle with its Nazi past weight
``The Harmonists'' with a compelling gravity.
</P>
<P>
   This handsome and thought-provoking film does more than relate
the story of the Comedian Harmonists, the musical sextet that
achieved enormous popularity in Germany as the enfeebled Weimar
Republic gave way to Hitler and anti-Semitism in the 1930s. It also
grapples with questions of love of country and how the same people
could cherish culture and embrace barbarity. ``The Harmonists,'' in
German with English subtitles, was written by Klaus Richter and
directed by Joseph Vilsmaier.
</P>
<P>
   Vilsmaier's film, opening Friday at the Lincoln Plaza and
Angelika Film Center, tells essentially the same story as is
recounted in the new Broadway musical ``Band in Berlin.''
Skillfully acted and sung and filled with period details, from
pornographic photos hung inside a seller's shabby overcoat to the
Parmelee taxis that roamed New York, it traces the Comedian
Harmonists from their founding through their success, then on to
the Nazi edicts that forced the group's three Jewish members into
exile after a final concert in Munich in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, as a welcome epilogue notes, the original members
reconstituted as two ensembles, one performing in Germany and one
elsewhere. But their heyday was over. By 1941, the Comedian
Harmonists had disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the dark history that colors and shapes its
narrative, ``The Harmonists'' could be a European version of one of
the countless Hollywood musicals that track the rise of some poor
musician who struggles against the odds to realize his vision. The
film is filled with stylish renditions of lively, funny and
sentimental songs like ``Beautiful Isabella From Castile,''
``Creole Love Call,'' ``Auf Wiederseh'n, My Dear'' and ``When Yuba
Plays the Rumba on the Tuba.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, in 1927, the dreamer is Harry Frommermann (Ulrich
Noethen), a comical-looking failure as an actor but a talented
musical arranger who conceives of forming a German equivalent of
the popular American a capella group the Revellers.
</P>
<P>
   Frommermann, a Jew, is conducting auditions in his garret for a
long line of talentless hopefuls when the room is invaded by a
beefy blond bass, Robert Biberti (Ben Becker), who leads him to a
trove of singers, including the lady-killing Bulgarian Ari
Leschnikoff (Max Tidof), as well as a pianist, Erwin Bootz (Kai
Wiesinger).
</P>
<P>
   After months of rehearsals that tax the group's patience,
followed by rejection at an audition, the musicians finally get an
engagement and, with Biberti assuming the role of business manager,
achieve overnight success.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of Champagne, song and women follow, including Erna
(Meret Becker), the gentile student and clerk in a Jewish-owned
Berlin music shop who has won the shy heart of Frommermann as well
as the less-inhibited attention of Biberti.
</P>
<P>
   But before long, Nazi brownshirts are on the rampage, daubing
storefronts with anti-Semitic insults, smashing windows and
visiting violence on those who rouse their rage. ``It's just some
kids,'' says Mrs. Grunbaum (Susi Nicoletti), the white-haired wife
of the music-shop owner. ``When you're out of work, you get into
mischief.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon Frommermann and Biberti are put on official notice that
despite friends in high places, the Jewish component of the
ensemble renders them collectively unacceptable to Nazism.
</P>
<P>
   On a tour that brings them to New York, the Harmonists confront
the question of leaving Germany forever. Biberti, speaking of his
old mother and of love of country, cannot. The Harmonists return,
and just before the concert in Munich are told it is to be their
last.
</P>
<P>
   At its end, the elegant audience members in black tie and gowns,
aware of the circumstances, render a standing ovation and surge to
the stage. In this moment in ``The Harmonists,'' at the end of a
performance in a city deeply resonant with Nazi history, the tide
of yearning for absolution in the generations of post-World War II
Germany sweeps against the rock of historical fact.
</P>
<P>
   In the glamour and entertainment of ``The Harmonists'' lie
questions that will not go away.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE HARMONISTS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Joseph Vilsmaier; written (in German, with English
subtitles) by Klaus Richter, based on an idea by Juergen Buescher;
director of photography, Vilsmaier; edited by Peter R. Adam; music
by Harald Kloser; production designer, Rolf Zehetbauer; produced by
Hanno Huth, Reinhard Kloos and Danny Krausz; released by Mirama
Disney Films. At Lincoln Plaza, Broadway at 63rd Street, and the
Angelika, 18 W. Houston St. Running time: 114 minutes. This film is
rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian).
It includes some violence, sex and ethnic slurs.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ben Becker (Robert Biberti), Heino Ferch (Roman Cycowski),
Ulrich Noethen (Harry Frommermann), Heinrich Schafmeister (Erich A.
Collin), Max Tidof (Ari Leschnikoff), Kai Wiesinger (Erwin Bootz),
Meret Becker (Erna Eggstein), Katja Riemann (Mary Cycowski), Dana
Vavrova (Ursula Bootz), Susi Nicoletti (Mrs. Grunbaum) and Noemi
Fischer (Chantal). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
