<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN COALITION STARTS MASSIVE CAMPAIGN FOR 2000 VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Christian Coalition on Thursday unveiled a $21
million effort to bring religious conservatives to the polls in the
2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are launching, effective today, the most massive effort to
mobilize the (coalition's) grass-roots in our history,''
tele-evangelist and Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson told
a news conference here. ``There's nothing radical about it. We're
just talking about voter participation where there is apathy at
present.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition, which claims 2.1 million members, will attempt to
raise $21 million to increase its paid field organizing staff,
according to Robertson. The coalition will recruit and train 1.5
million conservative activists who will then be tasked with getting
out the religious conservative vote.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said the coalition also aims to distribute 75 million
of its voter guides in conservative Christian churches nationwide _
19 million more than in 1996. The guides pinpoint the stands of
candidates on such issues as abortion, school prayer and vouchers
for private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition has been buffeted by a series of high-level
departures in recent years, including former executive director
Ralph Reed and former president Donald Hodel, raising the question
of whether the 10-year-old coalition still packs a potent political
punch.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, coalition executive director Randy Tate told
reporters that the coalition ``will continue to be a permanent
fixture on the American political scene.'' The effort in 2000
``will ensure that pro-family voters and pro-family issues will be
front and center in election 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Tate and others blamed Republicans for not putting
forward a clear message on such issues as tax cuts and abortion
that might have yielded more votes. Democrats gained five House
seats in the 1998 election.
</P>
<P>
   Although technically non-partisan, Robertson and Tate on
Thursday made little secret of their support for Republicans vying
for the presidential nomination, as well as their abhorrence of the
Democratic frontrunner, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any (of the Republicans) are going to be a lot more acceptable
than Al Gore,'' Robertson said. ``I'm quite enthusiastic about the
way (the Republican race) is shaping up.''
</P>
<P>
   The leading GOP prospect, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, angered
some social conservatives by saying in an interview Monday that
while he opposes abortion, ``I'm a realistic enough person to know
that America is not ready to ban abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, however, said he was not troubled by Bush's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush (is) profoundly on the pro-life side,'' he said.
``I'm not going to take issue with a few words.'' Robertson added
he is ``under the impression'' that another GOP possibility,
Elizabeth Dole, also opposes abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's upbeat talk contrasted with the view of some other
social conservatives who have recently proclaimed President
Clinton's impeachment survival as a virtual death knell for their
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent conservative Paul Weyrich raised eyebrows last month
by equating Clinton's Senate acquittal to ``a cultural collapse of
historic proportions, a collapse so great that it simply overwhelms
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Urging a virtual withdrawal from mainstream culture, Weyrich
said conservatives ``need some sort of quarantine'' to protect
their families from a society in which Clinton's poll numbers
climbed despite the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Weyrich's chagrin, Robertson responded: ``I'm an
optimist. Come the next election cycle, the mood of the American
people is going to be vastly different than what the polls showed
during the impeachment proceedings. I'm not discouraged one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the voting strength of religious conservatives
vary.
</P>
<P>
   In exit polls during last November's elections, 13 percent
identified themselves as religious conservatives. But Everett Carll
Ladd, director of the Roper Center for Public Opinion Research at
the University of Connecticut, said the pool of religiously
oriented voters who could be influenced by the coalition's appeal
may be as large as one-third of the electorate _ 55 million out of
165 million eligible voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 election, however, the coalition's grass roots
stayed home in larger numbers than expected. A coalition survey
found that 28.6 percent of religious conservatives voted, down from
33 percent in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
