<HEADER>
A6850 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-WING-COMMANDER-S     03-11 0314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WING-COMMANDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WING COMMANDER' HAS SEEN IT ALL BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's said there are few original ideas in movies anymore. If
``Wing Commander'' is an indicator, it's true.
</P>
<P>
   Take one part ``Top Gun,'' mix with a couple of scenes from
``Aliens,'' stir in the tried-and-true formula from ``Star Trek,''
and the result is an uninspired if well-cast cocktail of a film
from first-time director Chris Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Even on paper this project must have looked contrived. And it
doesn't have the humor or over-the-top campiness to make it a cult
classic. So how did it acquire a cast that includes up-and-comers
Freddie Prinze Jr., Matthew Lillard and Saffron Burrows as well as
established actors like Tcheky Karyo, Jurgen Prochnow, David Warner
and David Suchet?
</P>
<P>
   A paycheck has got to be the answer.
</P>
<P>
   It's 2564 and the Confederation is battling the alien Kilrathis
who have managed to steal a navigation device that could allow them
to capture Earth. Then two brash young fighter pilots, Chris Blair
(Prinze) and Todd ``Manic'' Marshall (Lillard), board the
Confederation carrier that's home to an elite group of ace flyers.
They're led by Wing Commander Devereaux (Burrows), a beautiful
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, who is shunned by the other pilots because he is half
``pilgrim,'' a race of people who spent too much time ``alone in
space'' and began to lose their humanity, falls for Devereaux.
Ultimately it's up to Blair's half-human, half-pilgrim sixth sense
to lead the final fight against the Kilrathi.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who designed computer games before becoming a director,
erases any sense of character and emotion from his cartoon cast as
well as his film. ``Wing Commander'' is as one-dimensional as a
game of ``Doom'' and the outcome is as predictable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1741EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     03-11 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DELIVER THE GOODS'  
 WHERE CREDIT IS DUE  
 IN THE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Perhaps the last person to see Stanley Kubrick's
film ``Eyes Wide Shut'' before his death was an unlikely figure.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Kingsley, a top public relations executive who represents
some high-profile movie stars, saw the movie last Friday afternoon
at Kubrick's home in Hertfordshire, outside London. Kubrick was not
at the screening but upstairs in his bedroom because he said he was
coming down with the flu. But after Ms. Kingsley saw the film, she
spent about 45 minutes talking to Kubrick by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday morning the 70-year-old director of ``2001: A Space
Odyssey'' and ``Dr. Strangelove'' had died in his sleep. Among
those scheduled to attend his funeral in England on Friday are the
film's two stars, Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman , as well as Steven
Spielberg and other filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday a 90-second clip from the film was shown to
thousands of theater exhibitors at the Showest convention in Las
Vegas, Nev. The eye-opening excerpts included an explicit nude
scene of Ms. Kidman (who also shed her clothes in ``The Blue Room''
on Broadway) and a passionate interlude between her and Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kingsley, who is based in Los Angeles and is a partner in
the PMK public relations agency with Leslee Dart and Lois Smith,
represents Cruise and Ms. Kidman. She said she had met Kubrick
three times while he was shooting ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' now one of
the most widely anticipated films.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick was characteristically secretive about every aspect of
the movie. By several accounts ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' which is being
released by Warner Brothers on July 16, is a drama about a pair of
married psychiatrists (played by the married Cruise and Ms. Kidman)
and their sexual lives.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kingsley, who has been hired by Warner Brothers to promote
the movie, said she watched the 2 hour 17 minute film in a small
screening room at the Kubrick home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect,'' she said. ``But I was stunned.
I was really at the edge of my seat. I was spellbound. It was very
suspenseful.
</P>
<P>
   After the screening Ms. Kingsley was about to walk out of the
house when an associate of Kubrick said the director wanted to
speak to her. Ms. Kingsley recalled: ``He said, `Let me put you on
with Stanley.' I said, `I'll call him when I get to L.A.,' and he
said, `No, no, he wants to talk to you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick got on the phone and told Ms. Kingsley how delighted he
was with the film, which he showed earlier in the week to Cruise
and Ms. Kidman as well as to Bob Daly and Terry Semel, the Warner
Brothers co-chairmen. The film had been hand carried from London to
New York by Kubrick's editor, who returned home on the next flight.
( Kubrick had stopped flying years ago after eavesdropping on
conversations between pilots and controllers at La Guardia
Airport.)
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick's conversation ``was all about the work; he was consumed
with the movie and the work and how happy he was that everybody was
reacting the way they did to the film,'' Ms. Kingsley said. ``He
said he made the movie he wanted to make.'' She added: ``He was
very joyous. He sounded great.''
</P>
<P>
   During the conversation the reclusive director told Ms. Kingsley
that he would be happy to talk about the film and his work with a
few interviewers. But he said he would not come to Los Angeles or
New York; he wanted to conduct the interviews near his home.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kingsley returned to Los Angeles the next day and began to
make plans for the promotion of the film. On Sunday morning she was
awoken and told that Kubrick was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to deliver the goods for this man,'' she said. ``This
will be a major part of his legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Credit Is Due
</P>
<P>
   Warren Beatty, like numerous others in Hollywood, has ambiguous
but positive feelings about the decision by the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences to present Elia Kazan with an honorary
Oscar on March 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the guy,'' said Beatty , whose first film, ``Splendor
in the Grass'' (1961), was directed by Kazan, now 89, and made the
actor a star.
</P>
<P>
   Kazan's award for lifetime achievement has touched off
controversy because of his decision in 1952 to inform on eight
friends from the Communist Party before the House Un-American
Activities Committee. Martin Scorsese and Robert De Niro are set to
present the award, Daily Variety reported.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty appeared on Wednesday at a ceremony at the Los Angeles
headquarters of the Writers Guild of America to read the names of
uncredited blacklisted writers who used pseudonyms and fronts to
write films between 1948 and 1961.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony was part of the guild's effort to determine and
recognize the writers who were blacklisted because of accusations
that they had been Communists, sympathetic to Communists or even
strong-minded liberals who signed a petition or two in the '30s or
'40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that American history makes these credit
corrections necessary,'' said Daniel Petrie Jr., president of the
guild's West Coast branch. ``But the guild is proud to ensure the
public recognition these writers and their work deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best known film affected by the guild's research is
the 1961 Anthony Mann spectacle, ``El Cid,'' which starred Charlton
Heston and Sophia Loren; one of the writers, the blacklisted Ben
Barzman, was omitted from the credits.
</P>
<P>
   After extensive research, including interviews with the crew and
the two stars, Barzman's name was restored. The guild also had the
name of Donald Ogden Stewart, who wrote ``The Prisoner of Zenda''
(1952), restored to the credits of that movie.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty, who has involved himself in mostly Democratic and
liberal politics for years, said he had received numerous calls
about the Kazan award but had shied away from talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel it's my place to address myself to his politics
of 50 years ago,'' he said. ``I can only say he is a person for
whom I have tremendous respect and affection and whose work in
movies speaks for itself. He was my first teacher. I learned more
about movies from Kazan than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   But Beatty went on: ``I don't want to be reductive about his
politics. Although you and I might feel he made a mistake, neither
you nor I were around in that period. And although you and I may
think we would not have made that mistake, we didn't have to make
that choice. We all make mistakes. Some of them are mistakes that
everyone knows about. Some of them aren't.'' And then he said, ``I
love the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In the Race
</P>
<P>
   Ian McKellen, nominated for the Academy Award as best actor for
his role in Bill Condon's ``Gods and Monsters,'' has come to Los
Angeles from his London home until the Oscar presentation. Although
obviously buoyed by the nomination, McKellen also seems puzzled and
a bit irritated at the swirl of political-style campaigning for the
award. He is, after all, a serious British stage actor who is
unaccustomed to Oscar fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, I never want to do it again,'' he said. ``It takes up
an enormous amount of time as you throw yourself into it. And the
situation I find myself in is I would very much like to win the
Oscar. But I seem to be in a race, a race I didn't enter. It's got
a course I'm unfamiliar with. And I'm running along, but I don't
know where to run. I'm not complaining about it. It's all a bit
complicated for me.''
</P>
<P>
   McKellen's role in ``Gods and Monsters'' is loosely based on the
final days of the director James Whale, creator of the Frankenstein
movies of the '30s, who lived in Pacific Palisades after suffering
a stroke and committed suicide in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   McKellen is considered a front-runner for the best acting award
with Roberto Benigni, who won the Screen Actors Guild prize last
weekend, for ``Life is Beautiful.'' Also up for the prize are Tom
Hanks for ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Nick Nolte for ``Affliction''
and Edward Norton for ``American History X.''
</P>
<P>
   McKellen arrived here the other day from England after
completing appearances in three plays _ ``The Tempest,'' ``Present
Laughter,'' and ``The Sea Gull'' _ at the West Yorkshire Playhouse
in Leeds.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not especially aware that his nomination had made
him a hot property in Hollywood. Far from it, the 57-year-old actor
said with a laugh. ``Most of the scripts I get are not financed and
come straight from the screenplay writers or putative directors,''
he said. ``I read a lot of them. I have a suitcase full of them.''
He said he was unsure of his next project.
</P>
<P>
   McKellen said that he had certain similarities with his
character in ``Gods and Monsters,'' but only up to a point: ``Like
me, he was an actor most of his life. He was openly gay. And he
was, of course, an Englishman who made the journey to Los Angeles,
and that's one I've made myself.''
</P>
<P>
   McKellen grew up in northern England, the son of a civil
engineer, and acted at Cambridge University after spending his
teen-age years working backstage at local theaters.
</P>
<P>
   And what appealed to him about acting? McKellen paused. ``I
think probably the sense of family backstage,'' he said, ``and
belonging to a world one could control more readily than life
outside the theater.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
