<HEADLINE>
NOTHING SMART ABOUT `BABY GENIUSES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TriStar's cute-toddler epic, ``Baby Geniuses,'' might more
properly be called ``Look Who's Talking IV.'' It takes roughly the
same premise of that series and moves it up a technological
generation, so we don't just hear the babies deliver one-liners in
voice-over, we actually see their lips move.
</P>
<P>
   It's an impressive effect _ the morphing of baby lips, teeth,
and faces into adult postures _ and the movie does it so
relentlessly, and to such low-humor effect, that it could be a huge
hit. After all, as much as critics hated the earlier films, they
made a ton of money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the novelty of the adult-like babies wears off so fast,
and the movie is so incorrigibly stupid, distasteful, and maudlin,
that it's hard to see how anyone over the age of 10 could possibly
sit through its 94 grueling minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The story is about an evil corporation led by a Cruella De Vil
of a child psychiatrist (Kathleen Turner) who's been illegally
holding and studying gifted babies in its underground laboratories
_ in hopes of deciphering, and profiting by, the ``secret
pre-literate language.''
</P>
<P>
   Havoc breaks out when Sly, the most gifted of all the rugrats,
escapes the institution and somehow gets mixed up with his twin
brother, Whit, who is being raised by the evil psychiatrist's
all-American niece (Kim Cattrall) as part of a comparative
upbringing experiment.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the movie has Sly fighting and outsmarting the team
of baby-exploiters trying to get him back, and Wit leading a revolt
of the slave babies inside the institution. (Yes, this is a bizarre
combination of ``Baby's Day Out'' and ``The Corsican Brothers.'')
</P>
<P>
   The chief attraction here is the spectacle of seeing barely
ambulatory children not just talking and making the facial
expressions of adults, but also smoking cigars, dancing like John
Travolta, karate-chopping like Bruce Lee and kicking bad-guys in
the testicles.
</P>
<P>
   The level of the humor is so low it makes the Three Stooges look
like Noel Coward. The movie's running gag is the pungent odor of
diarrhea _ or, as the film keeps calling it, ``diaper gravy.'' You
haven't lived until you've seen a big glaring close-up of Dom
DeLuise picking his nose.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Canada's Bob Clark, who previously directed the
near-classic holiday movie, ``A Christmas Story,'' but is working
here more in the spirit of his 1981 trash-a-thon, ``Porky's.''
Except for the always reliable Kim Cattrall (the movie's one
winning presence), his players are so maliciously wasted they might
be able to recover damages in court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
