<HEADER>
A6857 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRATION-WORKERS-H     03-11 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-WORKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRATION POLICY HURTS POOR AMERICANS, PROFESSORS CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 300,000 immigrants with less than a high school
education who come to the United States each year are driving wages
down and pushing unemployment up for unskilled American workers,
particularly blacks and Hispanics, two professors said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The slight gain in wealth that immigration provides the
country as a whole is being paid for by unskilled, native-born
workers,'' George J. Borjas, a professor at Harvard University's
Kennedy School of Government, told the House Subcommittee on
Immigration and Claims.
</P>
<P>
   Borjas estimated that while immigration benefits the country by
$10 billion annually, American workers without a high school
education lose an average of $1,915 a year because of competition
from low-skill immigrant laborers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, immigration, as it stands today, is great for
educated, middle-class consumers and terrible for poor, working
families,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, Borjas said, about 900,000 legal immigrants enter the
United States. Of these, 300,000 have less than a high school
education. Nine percent of American workers have less than a high
school education.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee's chairman, Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, who
favors tighter restrictions on immigration, called the nation's
current policy on the issue a ``recipe for disaster'' for American
blue-collar workers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said U.S. policy should be changed to protect the jobs and
wages of unskilled American workers.
</P>
<P>
   He said African-American and Hispanic workers, who are more
likely to be unskilled, have been hurt the most, adding, ``We can't
pretend that the adverse impact of mass immigration on minorities
doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Vernon M. Briggs Jr., a business professor at Cornell University
in Ithaca, N.Y., suggested that U.S. immigration policy should stop
giving preference to foreign relatives of citizens and start
favoring more applicants with higher job skills and educational
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``With perhaps the most high-skill, high-tech economy in the
world, it seems odd that the United States gears its immigration
policy toward attracting the most low-skill, uneducated
immigrants,'' Briggs said.
</P>
<P>
   But others testifying at Thursday's hearing disagreed with the
charge that low-skill immigrant workers are hurting American
laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Moore, director of fiscal policy studies at the CATO
Institute here, a libertarian think-tank, said the large wave of
immigration to the United State over the past 30 years has helped
fuel one of the country's greatest economic booms.
</P>
<P>
   Citing U.S. Census Bureau figures, he said the immigrant
population in the United States has grown from 9.6 million in 1970,
or 4.8 percent of the total population, to 26.3 million, or 9.8
percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Moore also argued that the influx has not hurt job opportunities
or wages of minority workers. Citing other Census statistics, he
said the income gap between blacks and whites has narrowed to its
lowest level in history, with blacks now earning 69 percent of what
whites make.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, from 1981 to 1998, unemployment rates for
blacks and women have fallen dramatically, from 15.6 percent to 8.9
percent for African Americans and from 7.9 percent to 4.6 percent
for females.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the talk of doom and gloom, the evidence shows we
have had record immigration since 1981 and that in that same period
we have had record economic improvements for blacks,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Najar, a spokesman for the National Council of La Raza, the
nation's largest Hispanic rights organization, said immigrants
should not be made the ``scapegoats'' for wage gaps between skilled
and unskilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rep. Smith ignores the great benefits that today's immigrants
have brought to the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, the ranking Democrat on the
committee, said lawmakers should stop ``attacking'' immigrants and
focus on why black and Hispanic workers tend to have lower skills
and less education than white workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure that job opportunities and educational
opportunities are open to African Americans and Hispanics in a
country where racism still exists,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
