<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-POPE-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S PRESIDENT MEETS WITH POPE IN THE VATICAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Seeking to improve relations between Christianity and
Islam, Pope John Paul II gave a private audience to Iranian
President Mohammad Khatami on Thursday. It was the first papal
encounter with an Iranian head of state since the shah's regime.
</P>
<P>
   As the pope escorted Khatami, a Muslim Shiite cleric, out of his
study in St. Peter's after a 25-minute talk, he called their
meeting ``very important and promising.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit was particularly important to Khatami, a moderate who
is the first Iranian leader to visit Western Europe since the
Islamic revolution in 1979. He came seeking to improve Iran's
economic and political ties with the West.
</P>
<P>
   As he was leaving, Khatami asked the pope to pray for him and
for the pope's own health and success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is for the final victory of monotheism, ethics and
morality, together with peace and reconciliation,'' he told the
pope through a translator. ``May God protect you.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit was described as cordial and friendly. One member of
the Iranian delegation, also a cleric, was apparently so moved that
as he passed the pope on his way out, he stopped and asked John
Paul if he could do something. He then leaned down and kissed the
pope on the cheek.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has long stressed the common bonds and beliefs between
Christianity, Islam and other faiths. Since he arrived in Italy on
Tuesday, so has Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the divine faiths are not quintessentially different,''
Khatami said in a speech Wednesday to the European University
Institute at Fiesole, near Florence.
</P>
<P>
   The last meeting between a pope and a top Iranian leader was in
1970, when Pope Paul VI was greeted during an airport stopover in
Tehran by Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlevi. The Vatican did not break
diplomatic relations with Iran after the revolution, and John Paul
has talked with other Iranian officials in the Vatican, but
Thursday was his highest-level meeting. Iran currently holds the
chairmanship of the 54-nation Islamic Conference, and that gave the
audience additional weight.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The meeting with the pope, therefore, assumes capital
importance,'' the papal nuncio in Iran, Archbishop Romeo Panciroli,
said on Vatican radio.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami also met with Vatican City's secretary of state,
Cardinal Angelo Sodano. According to a Vatican spokesman, they
discussed the Middle East, Christian-Islamic dialogue and human
rights in Iran, including the rights of Catholics there.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican is interested in improving conditions for Christians
in Iran, a small community of about 120,000 in a total population
of nearly 70 million. There are only 13,000 Catholics, and they are
allowed to worship in their churches, but according to Fides, the
missionary news agency of the Holy See, Catholics are strictly
watched and denied some civil rights, like serving in the army or
the government.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian government is less tolerant of larger minorities
like the Bahais, followers of a faith that originated in
19th-century Persia and that Iranian clerics consider apostasy.
Rights organizations and Iranian dissident groups say the Bahais
are fiercely persecuted by the more conservative wings of the
Iranian judiciary and by security forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, where security for Khatami was tighter than for any
official visitor since Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev in 1989,
about 50 Iranian demonstrators managed to squeeze into a far corner
of St. Peter's Square, but were cordoned off by barriers and a wall
of police officers, who outnumbered the demonstrators almost two to
one.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters waved banners and shouted slogans against
Khatami. ``He is a fascist and a terrorist!'' one protester
screamed. Despite the security, protesters managed to throw
paint-filled eggs at Khatami's motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, Salman Rushdie was in Italy at the same time as
Khatami, receiving an honorary degree Wednesday at the University
of Turin. Rushdie was sentenced to death in 1989 by Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's revolutionary leader at the time, who
accused the writer of blasphemy against Islam in his novel ``The
Satanic Verses.''
</P>
<P>
   Last September Khatami's government lifted the sentence, known
as a fatwa. But conservative clerics reaffirmed the sentence on the
10th anniversary of Khomeini's decree.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami did not publicly mention Rushdie during his visit, but
Iranian newspapers sharply criticized Italy for acting as host to
Rushdie during the president's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Before visiting the pope, Khatami had a breakfast meeting at the
Italian Foreign Ministry with two dozen top business executives,
including Guglielmo Moscato, chairman of Ente Nazionale
Idrocarburi, the Italian energy conglomerate. ENI and the French
energy group Elf-Aquitaine recently signed a $1 billion contract to
develop an offshore oilfield in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   A Foreign Ministry official said Khatami sought to reassure the
executives that Iranian society is opening up and that foreign
investors could have confidence in the new climate.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who flew back to Tehran on Thursday, told the
pope that he left with ``beautiful memories'' of his visit in the
Vatican.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
