<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TAX-FILING-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNATURE NOT REQUIRED (BUT TAX IS STILL DUE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 14)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The signing of income tax returns, an American ritual in its
86th year, is being swept into the dustbin of history.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing those traditional John Hancocks with digital
signatures will ease the electronic filing of returns, but the
method chosen by the IRS will also mean continuing costs for
taxpayers. That is because they must still go through software
vendors and electronic filing agents to send their returns to the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, anyone who filed a return electronically also had to
mail in a signed paper form, or jurat, the statement that makes an
individual who files a false return liable for prosecution for
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has directed the IRS to move 80 percent of taxpayers to
electronic filing by 2007, up from 20 percent now, because it will
be cheaper, faster and far less prone to errors. The IRS estimated
that its cost to process an electronic Form 1040 was $5 last year,
compared with $3.85 for a paper return. But once most people move
to electronic filing, the IRS figures, costs should fall to less
than $2 a return, in 1996 dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The cumbersome system for obtaining signatures, however, is seen
as a big obstacle toward meeting the government's 80 percent goal.
Though the number of electronic returns grew by more than 5 million
last year, to 24.8 million, the growth rate must nearly double to
meet the objective.
</P>
<P>
   Because of concerns about computer security, individuals cannot
file electronic returns directly with the IRS. Instead, the IRS has
licensed about 93,000 accounting firms, enrolled agents and other
preparers as their intermediaries. If a taxpayer files a return
over the Internet through vendors like Turbotax, Securetax,
Taxlogic or Taxact, the return first goes to the software company,
which is licensed as an ``electronic return originator.'' The
originators, which have access to IRS computers, make sure the
return meets IRS protocols and, typically, charge fees for the
services.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in a shift in strategy, the IRS has offered to drop
the signature-form requirement for a big group of taxpayers _ 8
million people whose returns indicated that they prepared their own
1997 tax returns by using computer software. A year ago, most of
those taxpayers printed out and mailed in their returns, but nearly
1 million chose electronic filing.
</P>
<P>
   Attracting those filers is a key to rapid growth in electronic
filing, said Robert Barr, the IRS's assistant commissioner for
electronic tax administration, who previously was an executive at
Intuit, maker of Turbotax.
</P>
<P>
   The 8 million taxpayers were sent postcards containing
electronic customer numbers, much like the personal identification
numbers on bank cards. Those numbers can be used to file a return
electronically without having to submit the separate signature form
or mail-in W-2s (but keep them in case of an audit).
</P>
<P>
   Barr said that if taxpayers did not receive or keep their
postcards, they could not get new customer numbers for this year.
But there are two other options.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS is allowing 8,100 tax preparers to let their customers
select their own four-digit codes, which can be used instead of a
traditional signatures, Barr said. The IRS does not publish a list
of those preparers, so taxpayers choosing that option will have to
shop around.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, since 1996, taxpayers have been able to use
Telefile, which uses touch-tone phone technology for filing Form
1040EZ, a simplified form for people who make less than $50,000. In
lieu of the signature form, EZ filers can use a code found on tax
materials the IRS mailed to them at the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, the IRS focused its electronic-filing strategy
on lower-income taxpayers, who commonly have more money withheld
from their paychecks than is required and then collect big refund
checks. That strategy created a perception problem for electronic
filing, especially among accountants who work with wealthier
clients; many perceived the electronic system as not designed for
them.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Krokus, an accountant in Norwalk, Conn., saw the problem
at a recent tax seminar for fellow accountants whose clientele are
middle- to upper-income taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked how many people in the room filed their clients'
returns electronically, and not one hand out of more than a hundred
went up,'' Krokus said. ``I explained that I have used electronic
filing exclusively since it was first available in Connecticut in
1989, and that it is good for clients because it reduces the chance
that a government clerk will make a keypunch mistake transferring
numbers from a paper return.''
</P>
<P>
   Solving the image problem could mean hundreds of millions of
dollars in annual savings for the IRS in processing and follow-up
work. ``You are far less likely to hear back from us if you use
electronic filing,'' Barr said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
