<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PHOTOGRAPHY-2TA     03-11 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PHOTOGRAPHY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF INDIA: HISTORY AND BEAUTY IN A COLONIAL CONTEXT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By VICTORIA GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before Indian independence, some Britons seemed to
think that Queen Victoria had acquired the subcontinent almost by
default. After all, the East India Company had taken direct control
of 60 percent of India and indirect control of most of the rest by
the mid-19th century. In 1857, the Indians finally rebelled. The
Great Rebellion, also known as the Indian Mutiny, ensued; British
firepower won; the company failed, and what was the Crown to do but
step in?
</P>
<P>
   Victoria was fascinated by the jewel in her crown, and so were
her subjects. Photographs show the Queen at table with Indian
manservants standing by, looking suitably foreign and imposing;
pictures of the Queen being served by representatives of her
largest colony must have been a matter of some pride to the
populace. She also sent British artists abroad to paint the newest
members of her realm.
</P>
<P>
   But photography was the great recorder of the age and the medium
of choice in a land that not only entranced and enriched the
British but also bewildered them by never being quite what it
seemed.
</P>
<P>
   You can see more than 100 photographs, mostly from India,
ranging from daguerreotypes to silver prints to hand-painted
portraits, in ``Re-Orientations: Photography from South Asia,
1845-1920'' at Sepia International and the Alkazi Collection in
Manhattan's Chelsea area. Both shows run through April 24.
</P>
<P>
   This space, which opened last month, is a highly unusual
combination of museum and commercial gallery. The Alkazi
Collection, more than 40,000 photographs of South Asia, belongs to
Ebrahim Alkazi, an Indian who was director of the National School
of Drama and of the Asian Theater Institute in New Delhi for 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 he founded the Center for International Contemporary
Arts in New York, which closed in 1992. His photographs and a
research library are available to scholars at this space, and
lectures, films and publications are planned. The exhibition space,
with close to 2,000 square feet, will have one or two not-for-sale
historical exhibitions drawn from the collection each year, plus
several commercial shows of established and emerging artists.
</P>
<P>
   Photography reached India less than a year after its invention
in 1839. By 1865, an exhibition there attracted thousands of
photographs, both amateur and professional, from all parts of the
country. ``Re-Orientations'' includes superb works by foreigners
and Indians alike, from Samuel Bourne's 1869 photograph of
exuberantly rearing horses on a temple facade to Johnson and
Hoffmann's debonair portrait of the boy Maharajah of Jodhpur to
anonymous hand-painted portraits of men with rambunctious beards.
</P>
<P>
   Not every image reaches this level, and there's a fair amount of
material of more historical than esthetic interest. But the show
has a broader target than mere beauty; the catalog and wall texts
excerpted from it try to place the imagery within the context of
British dominion and domination. This is illuminating, especially
for those not thoroughly versed in Indian history. The ideas are
provocative; the photographs do not always bear them out as
thoroughly as they might.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a wall text reads: ``The rebellion was the first
instance when the camera was used as a political instrument to
assert the authority of the ruling power and to proclaim its
triumph to the world at large. Coming as it did soon after
Britain's loss of its American colonies, the propagation of
imperial success in India was important as a booster of morale.''
</P>
<P>
   If this claim is correct, it makes the British the originators
of one of the more insidious uses of photography. Looking at
photographs of destruction _ Felice Beato's pictures of the dead in
the rebellion, not shown in ``Re-Orientations,'' were the most
grisly images of war victims to date _ as part of a political
program reflects up-to-date thinking about photography. It is
especially intriguing here, for just two years earlier British
pictures of the Crimean War were at least partially designed as
government propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of destruction during the rebellion and of British
retribution for it may have done exactly what this text suggests,
but it is hard to know how two lovely pictures of an Indian fort,
apparently intact, contributed to the effort. Then, too, pictures
of wartime damage tend to get tangled in double messages of victory
and viciousness. George Barnard's photographs of the South in ruins
after the American Civil War bear, at least in our time, a mixed
message about the Northern conquest.
</P>
<P>
   But today, as images are re-evaluated and the question of who
controls them rethought, it is possible to read many of the travel
photographs of the 19th century as exercises in colonial power. The
attitude is: We own that rich or beautiful or exotic land (or else
we ought to), and we are clearly superior to those people, charming
as they may be, and are providing them the beneficent guidance of
our highly developed civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the photographs of the celebrations of 1877, when
Victoria was proclaimed Empress of India; of 1903, when Edward VII
was proclaimed Emperor, and of 1911, when King George V and Queen
Mary were the first British monarchs to visit the country, were
intended to underline the majesty, pomp and authority of the
sovereigns. That's what coronations and entries into cities always
have been about, and the camera merely has provided an economical
way to record them and distribute the news.
</P>
<P>
   As the wall texts and catalog in ``Re-Orientations'' point out,
ethnography and anthropology were comparatively new sciences in the
late 19th century, and photographers fanned out across the fringe
lands in and around India to photograph the diversity of tribes and
races. The government moved in on this undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Canning, the first Viceroy of India, set in motion the
documentation of all the peoples of the subcontinent, apparently as
a souvenir for officials returning home, but by 1858 the Political
and Secret Department of the government of India had a vivid
interest in this undertaking and would eventually buy half the
published sets. Ethnographers, anthropologists, criminologists and
phrenologists had theories about facial and other physical features
that supported the notion of a superior white race; these kinds of
photographs bolstered such ideas and were sometimes taken with them
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pictures are important historically and sometimes
visually striking. When it came to photographing the local rulers,
some local photographers or at least some local artists may have
had the best of it.
</P>
<P>
   The painted portraits in this show, which can resemble Indian
miniatures much as American painted tintypes can mimic folk
paintings, are delicious, with faces and hands in black and white
and costumes in brilliant colors, or pearl necklaces painted atop
the gentlemen's very Western jackets and ties.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   India's monuments are dizzyingly varied and disconcertingly
breath-taking, and only the flinty-hearted or blind could fail to
admire an anonymous photographer's picture of marble inlays,
delicate as painted porcelain, in the Red Fort in Delhi or Colin
Murray's 1873 image of the Lake Palace in Udaipur, with its lilting
reflections and gentle mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Such photographs, generally made for military families, tourists
and stay-at-home British citizens, also constituted a large,
architectural and archeological survey of the country and
conceivably helped preserve the glories of India's history.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers also trekked into uncharted territories and made
the earliest pictures of the Tibetan Himalayas, including Everest.
</P>
<P>
   If you cannot get to India soon, you could do worse than take a
peek at its history in photographs.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1801EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
