<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6877 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-WATCHING-$ADV     03-11 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-WATCHING-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEARTH OF SNOW BRINGS A FLURRY OF EXPLANATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 14)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Tom Stoner checks his rain gauges and wind
instruments regularly. Regularly, that is, 50 or maybe 100 times a
day.
</P>
<P>
   What would you do, he wonders, if you were handicapped,
semiretired and an avid amateur weather-watcher? Wouldn't you take
lots of looks at your state-of-the-art digital system? After all,
it automatically records wind speeds and temperatures every 30
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The one phenomenon he needs assistance measuring is snowfall.
Stoner, who lives in Columbia County in upstate New York, uses a
motorized scooter to compensate for what multiple sclerosis has
done to his right leg and hand. Getting outside after a snow storm
is often problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My primary gauge for determining snow totals is known as a
wife, and a ruler,'' he muses, referring to the assistance his
wife, Mary, provides for measuring snowfall. ``Sometimes we have to
wait a couple of days for the snow to melt to read the actual water
content in our rain gauge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stoners were able to determine that a March 7 storm, the
most intense of this decidedly unsnowy winter, left a mere 5.9
inches of snow at his house. ``I pay attention to the weather
reports,'' he says. ``I know other places got a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   That's for sure. Al Tedeschi, who lives outside the village of
Westerlo in Albany County, measured 12.1 inches of snowfall that
same day.
</P>
<P>
   And Joe Driscoll, near Lake Desolation in northwestern Saratoga
County, recorded 12.9 inches of snow. That increased his winter
total to 73.2 inches of snow, more than twice the 31.1 inches that
Stoner has measured some 75 miles to the southeast in Columbia
County.
</P>
<P>
   Between those two extremes are some undeniable truths:
</P>
<P>
   _ There are numerous microclimates within regions, and
snowstorms wallop some places while they gently massage others.
</P>
<P>
   A microclimate is a localized variation within a region. It is a
term that first came into use in the 1960s and has since been
regularly employed by meteorologists and forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Topography more than any other factor determines and
influences specific microclimates, according to Michael Landin, a
meteorologist who teaches a course in weather forecasting at the
State University of New York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   _ There's no sure-fire way to predict where snow falls will be
heaviest, of course, but there are general rules that apply to the
Albany area, according to Richard ``Doc'' Taylor at the state
Department of Environmental Conservation. Taylor officially is an
air pollution meteorologist, but his pet project is keeping track
of regional snowfall accumulations, a task he has monitored like a
mad scientist for the past 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   Stoner, Tedeschi and Driscoll are three of 80 volunteers in an
eight-county area who submit detailed daily reports every month to
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snowfall is pretty elevation-dependent throughout the
region,'' he explains. ``The Hudson Valley area almost always
receives the minimum totals for the season, and the Hilltowns and
farther north and west, like in Saratoga County, are where you're
going to get the most snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor loves snow, it should be noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a bum winter, a real bum winter,'' he mutters. ``I
get so sick of hearing people say they hate the snow. If you don't
like the snow, move to Florida or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor attributes this winter's low snow totals to the absence
of nor'easters, the pounding storms that develop off the Atlantic
Coast and move inland with a fury. He points to the storm in late
February that came up the coast and crippled Cape Cod, dumping a
foot of snow or more throughout much of New England, as a good
example of the typical weather pattern for this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been no East Coast storms coming our way, plain and
simple,'' Taylor explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can throw out all kinds of climatological claims, La
Nina, what have you, but weather patterns develop and tend to lock
in for a period.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the major storms this winter have been coming out of the
Rockies and going out over the Great Lakes. The storm tracks have
been too far to the west for this area to receive much, if any,
snow, according to Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Eggleston, a regional climatologist at Cornell University
in Ithaca, is in charge of the New York State Snow Survey. Every
winter is unique, according to Eggleston, who believes the Albany
area can't be defined in terms of snow belts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Albany area gets storms from the west and the south, and
usually a combination of storms coming from those different
directions,'' he explains. ``Buffalo, on the other hand, doesn't
need a large storm to get significant snowfall because of the lake
effect. However, when Albany gets snow, it's usually from a
large-scale storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Eggleston knows firsthand how upstate New York's numerous
microclimates can produce dramatically different results. He was
unable to take calls on March 4 to discuss snow patterns because he
was snowed in at home in Ithaca, coping with a 10-inch dumping the
same day the Rochester area received two feet of snow. That same
day the Albany area received not even a dusting, as the storm moved
north toward Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s have been the warmest decade in recorded history, he
noted, and during the past nine years the Albany area has
experienced what meteorologists call ``a lot of weather.'' Two
winters have been among the Top 10 snowiest, and three have been
among the Top 10 least snowy.
</P>
<P>
   Stoner pauses during a conversation to observe his gauges.
``Wow, we just had a 25-mile-an-hour wind gust out of the south,''
he notes.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that the folks at nearby Catamount Ski Center rue the
wimpy snow totals in their section of Columbia County, but he is
not a bit unhappy with how the winter of 1998-99 has unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody that bought a plow or a snowblower is upset because
they're not getting any work, but I don't miss it,'' Stoner says.
``I'm glad there's no frost on the ground; there's robins out here
flying all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it snows I have a hard time getting out. When the ground
is slippery, I don't get too far with MS. You end up on the
ground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
