<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERKIN-PIANIST-PROFIL     03-11 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERKIN-PIANIST-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWESOME VISTAS, BIRDCALLS AND RUSTY COLORS, WITH SERKIN AS GUIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Peter Serkin was told during a recent interview
that in a publicity brochure for the Chamber Music Society of
Lincoln Center's performance on Sunday afternoon of ``Des Canyons
aux Etoiles'' (``From the Canyons to the Stars'') by Messiaen, he
is described as the project's ``soloist'' and ``guiding spirit,''
the self-effacing pianist gulped, blushed and said, ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   Soloist, yes.
</P>
<P>
   Though this ecstatic work, inspired by Messiaen's trip to Bryce
Canyon and Cedar Breaks in Utah, is scored for 44 instruments,
including solo trombone and all manner of percussion, the daunting
solo piano part dominates and drives the music. At nearly 100
minutes, ``Des Canyons aux Etoiles'' (``From the Canyons to the
Stars'') is, in effect, the largest work for piano and orchestra
ever written.
</P>
<P>
   But guiding spirit? ``I thought that was the composer,'' Serkin
said, adding, ``All that means is that I approached the society
members and asked them if they would be interested in this very
great work that has such a deep connection to their home, Alice
Tully Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it does. It was commissioned by Alice Tully herself for a
performance at the hall to celebrate the American Bicentennial.
Messiaen wrote it with the hall in mind, right down to the number
of instruments he felt could be accommodated on its stage. The
premiere was given in late 1974 by Musica Aeterna, with Yvonne
Loriod, the composer's wife, playing the piano part. Serkin was
there and decided on the spot that he would play it some day.
</P>
<P>
   Serkin's slightly embarrassed reaction at being called a guiding
spirit is in keeping with his character. The 51-year-old pianist
has always had a keen interest in new music. This is especially
notable given the degree to which he was steeped in the European
classical tradition as a child. His father was the eminent pianist
Rudolf Serkin, and his mother, Irene, who died in December, a
trained string player, was the daughter of the renowned German
violinist Adolf Busch. Both parents expected young Peter to
maintain the family reverence for the great masters.
</P>
<P>
   But for Serkin, his interest in new music is a natural extension
of his interest in all music, and he resists any suggestion that he
is engaged in a mission, or is a champion of anything. The story of
his involvement with Messiaen's music is a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   The desire to perform Messiaen's ``Quatour pour la Fin du
Temps'' (``Quartet for the End of Time'') brought Serkin together
in 1973 with three friends _ the clarinetist Richard Stoltzman, the
violinist Ida Kavafian and the cellist Fred Sherry _ to form the
contemporary music ensemble group Tashi, which for many years
commissioned new music, toured and made records, often appearing in
T-shirts, dashikis and other emblems of the counter culture. But
the Messiaen quartet, which they performed over 150 times, Serkin
estimates, was Tashi's signature work.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Tashi's founding, Serkin was immersed in
Messiaen's ``Vingt Regards sur l'Enfant Jesus'' (``20
Contemplations on the Infant Jesus''), a set of 20 pieces for solo
piano of astounding difficulty that oscillate between states of
meditative timelessness and wildly exuberant spirituality. The
pieces were not necessarily intended to be performed complete. But
after working on them individually for four years, Serkin played
the entire two-and-one-half-hour work from memory on a tour in 25
cities during the 1974-75 season.
</P>
<P>
   Most pianists, having mastered such a colossal work, would
continue to play it prominently, milking it for critical kudos and
presenting themselves as advocates of Messiaen. But, having
explored the music extensively, Serkin simply moved on. For over 15
years, he played no Messiaen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't discarding the music,'' he said. ``I still loved it
and respected it immensely. I just wasn't into playing Messiaen's
music as I had been in earlier years. My interest shifted
elsewhere. I can't help that. I'd just as soon be that way, and not
doggedly champion this or that composer.''
</P>
<P>
   Serkin's shift from Messiaen was no different, he said, from
what goes on for him with the standard repertory all the time. For
example, Beethoven was a staple of his musical diet when he was
young. But when he got involved with Tashi, he didn't look at the
Beethoven sonatas for 10 years, he said. Now he is completely
enthralled by them again.
</P>
<P>
   And now Serkin is again engrossed with Messiaen. What brought
him back? ``I must say, his death was part of it,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Messiaen's death in 1992 had initially escaped him.
Serkin was at home in his apartment in Manhattan when Messiaen's
``Transfiguration,'' an enormous work for vocalists and orchestra,
came on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't heard it in years and was very moved,'' he said.
``When it was over, the announcer said that Messiaen had died the
day before. It got me thinking about him again.''
</P>
<P>
   What also rekindled his interest was ``Des Canyons aux
Etoiles.'' In 1994, when Reinbert de Leeuw, the Dutch composer and
conductor who was then the director of contemporary music
activities at the Tanglewood Music Center in Massachusetts, asked
Serkin, who is on the Tanglewood faculty, to perform the work with
the student orchestra under his direction, Serkin readily accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The work is structured in 12 parts, grouped into three large
sections. And it takes the listeners on an ascent from the canyons
to the stars to a vision of heaven beyond. Songs of birds with
leaping, jagged melodic lines are interspersed with sustained
harmonic passages, like celestial chorales, and wildly inventive
instrumental writing.
</P>
<P>
   The piece is scored for 44 individual instruments. To assemble
an ensemble to perform the work is a musical and logistic
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the kind of piece you ask your manager to offer to a
few orchestras,'' Serkin said. ``We actually tried, but, as I could
have predicted, we had no success.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he approached the Chamber Music Society, which is
celebrating its 25th anniversary season and was looking for special
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing to perform this work for 44 players meant expanding the
notion of what chamber music is, said David Shifrin, the
clarinetist who is the society's artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he explained, ``when I'm asked to define chamber music,
I usually say the bottom line is a work with one player per part.
So this one fits.''
</P>
<P>
   Serkin is excited to be playing Messiaen again, and recording it
as well. RCA Victor has just released a splendid disk of two
Messiaen works featuring Serkin: ``Visions de l'Amen'' for two
pianos (with Yuji Takahashi) and a nearly 30-minute solo work, ``La
Rousserolle Effarvatte,'' from Messiaen's catalog of birds, which
evokes and transforms birdcalls into bracingly contemporary piano
music.
</P>
<P>
   Serkin notes some irony in the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of decades ago, when I was so interested in new
music, I couldn't interest anybody in the recording business in
it,'' he said. ``Now that I am coming around and want to record
Beethoven and Mozart sonatas, it's hard to find anyone interested
in that. It's weird.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
