<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6882 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-LAFAYETTE-2N     03-11 1546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-LAFAYETTE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 EASTON, Pa.: ... status quo.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Leopards never wavered from their objective. They
came out of the gate 6-1, their best start in 13 years. They scared
nationally ranked Purdue until succumbing in the final minute _ at
Purdue. They cleaned up in the Patriot League to the tune of a 10-2
record. And last Friday they scaled the summit, joining George
Davidson's '57 Leopard crew that lost by 4 points to Syracuse in
the NCAA East semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call from George Davidson Thursday,'' O'Hanlon told
the press after Friday's game. ``He told me it had been too long,
that it was about time the team goes to the NCAAs. I thought it was
a good omen when he told me his team couldn't use the gym the day
before their big game, just like us, because of a sock hop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, Coach,'' asked Cole, ``what's a sock hop?''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind, kid. All that matters now is getting ready for the
Big Dance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Leopards are in the big time, but they are not of the big
time. The morning after learning of their first-round assignment _
or sentence _ they begin assembling intelligence on Miami. It's
sort of like preparing in a closet with the lights out. No
Hurricane game tape will be available until tomorrow; for the time
being, the coaches have to rely on telephoned reports from their
network of contacts who have seen Miami and on what they remember
from the many TV appearances by the nation's 10th-ranked team.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Hanlon wastes no time lamenting the lack of information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be prepared,'' he promises. ``We've still got three days
to work on the nuances of our own offense. That's just as
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, any little edge is welcome. Scanning the Hurricane
roster, assistant coach Pat Brogan notes that one of the players,
guard Todd Manuel, was recruited by Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can get him to transfer here before Friday,'' says
O'Hanlon, ``and get some information on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Leopards have access to their own floor for their Monday
afternoon practice, their first work in uniform since Friday's
Patriot clincher. The court is ringed by a wagon train of red
canvas rollers so that the track team's practice on the adjacent
oval won't be an intrusion. But clearly, the Leopards are
distracted. Their minds seem to be on the spotlight, not the task
at hand.
</P>
<P>
   During the huddle at midcourt preceding the day's drills,
O'Hanlon announces that they'll be facing Miami at 7:40 Friday _
prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think they'll show much of our game on TV?'' asks one of
the players, mindful that CBS doesn't dwell on blowouts.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon turns that fear on its ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Miami is able to stick with us,'' he tells the Leopards,
``then CBS will probably keep showing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, the Leopards are accorded the closest thing
to a coronation Easton has to offer _ a media luncheon at Larry
Holmes' Ringside Restaurant. While the topic at the dais is
basketball, the proprietor of the establishment, still chasing
megafights though years removed from his heavyweight championship
heyday, dines quietly in a back corner with three friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I follow the team,'' says Holmes. ``I watch the games on TV.
And we have the media luncheon for them every Tuesday. I'm happy
for them. It seems like our area never gets much play. People never
think about this itty-bitty place.''
</P>
<P>
   Might he be on hand in Boston when Lafayette _ and Easton _ gets
a piece of the limelight?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm not out of town promoting a fight in Vegas or
someplace, I'll probably go up there,'' says Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   One of his dining companions chimes in, ``If somebody doesn't
offer him $4 million or $5 million to fight someplace that night,
he'll be in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Tuesday's practice, the Leopards again cram into
the assistants' office for their first look at Miami on film. This
time the accommodations are a bit roomier; Bieg has an English
test, Klaus a retro deisgn exam in engineering, so neither is here.
</P>
<P>
   Such concessions to academics are standard practice at a
nonscholarship school where the emphasis is on student more than
athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time,'' O'Hanlon says of missing players. ``At some
schools, guys can go to sumer school to lighten the load during the
season, but we're a financial aid school, so summer school tuition
isn't picked up. You've got to take care of your workload during
the school year. This weekend will be the first time we've missed a
full day of class all year.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon spends about 15 minutes reviewing the Hurricanes'
fast-break offense and pressure defense, focusing on deadly weapons
such as Hemsley and James. Then he dismisses the Leopards with this
advisory: ``Remember to bring your gear with you tomorrow. We'll be
leaving for Boston right after practice.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't tell them to pack their track shoes, but it might not
be a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon has decided that the team will travel to Boston by bus,
not to spare the expense but the logistical nuisances. He figures
when airport tie-ups are factored in, the scenic route will take
only about an hour longer, ``and this way, we can go door to
door.''
</P>
<P>
   The players' reaction is mixed. Bieg hates to fly, ``so I'm glad
the regional is close enough that we can drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Klaus wouldn't mind a little glamour.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see these big-time teams on TV arriving at the site and
getting off a plane,'' he says. ``That would be kind of neat.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not a red-carpet sendoff. The players have a half-hour
after Wednesday's practice to hustle into travel mode. Meanwhile,
the assistants handle the catering. Brogan provides the main
course, making an emergency call to Morici's Pizza for ``15 pies _
in 25 minutes.'' Mike Burden and Mike McKee feverishly transfer
12-packs of soda and ice tea from shopping bags into a cooler. They
they scurry off to the WaWa convenience mart for the appetizers,
chips and pretzels. When they return, the players are boarding the
bus, filing past the farewell party _ the bus driver's wife, who
gets autographs as the Leopards climb on. The big contingent of
some 350 supporters won't be with the team until game day.
</P>
<P>
   The local TV station from Allentown does a remote from the
sidewalk outside the bus. When his interview is finished, Bieg _
who at the start of the season caused a bulletin-board commotion
around the league when he was quoted as saying there was no reason
the Leopards shouldn't dominate the Patriot _ announces, ``I told
'em we're going all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the way to Boston,'' says O'Hanlon.
</P>
<P>
   But first comes a stop two blocks into the journey for the
pizzas, which are quickly devoured by the ravished troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ridin' in style,'' guard Mike Homer yells from the back.
</P>
<P>
   In tranquility, too. The 5 1/2-hour ride across New York and
Connecticut is relatively quiet, save for the excited chirping of
O'Hanlon's children, 6-year-old Timmy and 5-year-old Grace. The
players stretch across the aisle to grab some sleep, listen to
headphones, or partake of the evening's entertainment on the
overhead monitors: a ``Seinfeld'' medley, ``What About Bob?'' and
``Kingpin.'' Apparently, ``Hoosiers'' was rented out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we lost?'' Timmy saks as the bus turns on to Interstate 84
in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   No _ until the traveling party reaches Boston, where the bus
pulls onto Commonwealth Avenue instead of Beacon Street. ``He gets
lost in Boston all the time,'' says one passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Once the mistake has been corrected, the Leopards get a look at
the landmark they consider the most revered in this historic city _
Fenway Park, silhouetted against the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   But by now, they're too tired to savor the sighting, and when
they arrive at their hotel at midnight, most decline Brogan's offer
to drop by O'Hanlon's room for more pizza, the foodstuff of
champions.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon carries his sleeping daughter, wrapped in a blanket, up
to their room, and most of the players head directly to theirs. But
they can still muster some enthusiasm for the new surroundings. ``I
like Boston,'' says Klaus. ``It's a city town. That Beantown aura
and attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, after a team breakfast buffet at the hotel, the
Leopards are off for a two-hour workout at their designated
practice site, Boston College. They are immediately awed by an
exotic sight. ``Hey, look at this,'' Guy yells from the balcony.
``It's a hockey rink.''
</P>
<P>
   But their focus is on the main stage _ the FleetCenter, which
they won't see until later in the night, and then only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a 7:10 practice for 50 minutes,'' says McKee. ``Then a
20-minute shootaround Friday morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That' it?'' says Brogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very efficient,'' says O'Hanlon, the NCAA veteran.
``They don't waste time. After 20 minutes, it's `OK, time's up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the players are thrilled just to step onto the court,
especially when they find out it's the fabled parquet, sans rats,
transferred from the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something special just knowing all the great players
who've been out there,'' says Ehlers. ``It's the most famous floor
in basketball history. Maybe we can make a little history on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lafayette, you are here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
