<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6884 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-LAFAYETTE-2T     03-11 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-LAFAYETTE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEOPARDS CLAW THEIR WAY TO FIRST TOURNAMENT SINCE 1957 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTON, Pa. _ The three Chinese tattoos scrolled along Tyson
Whitfield's right arm proclaim that he fears no man. No such
announcement is necessary to reveal that shooting a basketball
doesn't bother him, either.
</P>
<P>
   His utter lack of inhibition _ or conscience _ is on implausible
display just before the halftime buzzer in the Patriot League final
last Friday at Kirby Field House. Bucknell's Jake Ramage has just
drilled a 3-pointer, and favored Lafayette, host Lafayette,
regular-season champion Lafayette, seems destined to carry a
deflating 5-point deficit into the locker room, the nadir of a half
littered with mistakes and jitters.
</P>
<P>
   But as the clock approaches zero, Whitfield pulls up with the
ball in front of press row, three-quarters of the court from the
Bucknell basket, and lets fly a jumper. His apparent afterthought
of a missile banks in smartly off the glass, and Whitfield turns to
the Zoo Crew, the Lafayette loons overflowing the stands behind the
press table. He stands there motionless, expressionless, as if to
say, ``Well, what else did you expect?''
</P>
<P>
   Then he casually joins the parade of his revivified teammates
exiting the court.
</P>
<P>
   When they return, the Leopards are a new breed of cat. They claw
their way to a 67-63 victory that triggers a stampede onto the
court by the Zoo Crew, which threatens to engulf the ESPN cameras
on hand for the occasion and officially trumpets Lafayette's first
trip to the NCAA tournament since 1957, back before Larry Holmes
bought up Easton.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield's 71-foot bomb is immortalized as one of ESPN's Shots
of the Week and CNN's Play of the Week. It also serves as the
launching point for one of the longest shots in the 64-team NCAA
field, Lafayette, and the greatest week in Leopard basketball
history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest men on campus are fighting a losing battle for elbow
space in one of the smaller rooms in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Contorting themselves into forms they perhaps didn't think the
human body was capable of assuming, the Leopards are shoehorned
onto every desktop, into every chair, along every centimeter of
carpet available. You couldn't fit another big toe in the room; the
three assistant coaches who have territorial rights to this office
are forced into the corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Hoops are big on campus; egalitarianism is bigger. This is a
tiny school of some 2,000 students who are here at the confluence
of the Lehigh and Delaware Rivers to partake of Lafayette's
reputation for academic excellence. There is no such thing as an
athletic scholarship; even if you can stick the J, you're entitled
to no more financial aid than a fellow freshman who can read a
blueprint. The philosophy was set forth by the school's namesake,
the Marquis de Lafayette, in his landmark 18th-century treatise,
``Declaration of the Rights of Man.''
</P>
<P>
   The marquis probably was thinking of the Lafayette gym when he
wrote it, because it seems everyone has equal rights to this place.
</P>
<P>
   So while the Leopards may be the toast of College Hill _ and are
less than two hours from bringing the school another sliver of
national attention when the NCAA brackets are announced _ they
don't have dibs on the facilities. When a Rusted Root concert was
booked onto the Kirby floor the previous Thursday, it meant there
was no room for the basketball team to practice on its court on the
eve of its biggest game to date.
</P>
<P>
   And since a volleyball tournament has commandeered Kirby for the
weekend, that means Mack Lounge _ with spacious seating that could
accommodate even a basketball player's physique _ is off-limits to
the team this Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   So the Leopards crane their necks to see the small television
perched in a corner and listen intently as head coach Fran O'Hanlon
gently brings them back to earth from Friday's magic carpet ride.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking barely above a whisper, O'Hanlon dissects the errors
that marred the early going against Bucknell.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon, 50, is a teacher, not a tyrant. This film review,
while emphasizing the negative, is a dialogue, not a harangue.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the profile of the team we're going to face Thursday or
Friday?'' O'Hanlon asks. ``Ross?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Up-tempo,'' says senior forward Ross Harms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right,'' says O'Hanlon. ``So how do we control the game? On
offense or defense?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both,'' ventures guard Brian Ehlers, the Patriot Player of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, obviously,'' says O'Hanlon. ``But especially offense. We
set the tempo of the game by controlling the ball. Our shots, our
decision-making, have to be better than they were at the start
against Bucknell.''
</P>
<P>
   That's enough of this tutorial. The Leopards are about to learn
their NCAA fate, and O'Hanlon believes they've absorbed as much as
they're going to, given the distractions at hand. So he dismisses
the class, sending them off to the student union for the pizza
party that will serve as the appetizer for the tournament selection
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll practice at 4 tomorrow,'' he says as the players depart.
``If we can get the court.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Leopards are justifiably proud about ending the
second-longest NCAA Tournament drought in history, leaving
Harvard's 53-year record of futility unchallenged. They take great
satisfaction in knowing that they have resurrected the program from
the 2-25 shambles that preceded O'Hanlon's arrival four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But they are also realists. They know that despite a 22-7 record
and league championship, they are bottom-feeders in the NCAA pool.
CBS's ``Selection Show'' Sunday evening reveals as much. The
Leopards are Boston-bound, seeded 15th and last in their East
subregional, would-be first-round fodder for No. 2 seed Miami
Friday night at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon betrays no emotion when the seedings and pairings are
announced; he doesn't want this to be the zenith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some teams are just happy to get there,'' he says. ``I
don't want to stop playing after one more game.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. O'Hanlon won't be overwhelmed by the NCAA
trappings, and he'll make darn sure his team isn't, either.
</P>
<P>
   He is the quintessential gym rat, a Philadelphia kid from Wilt
Chamberlain's neighborhood who was a flamboyant guard on
Villanova's 1970 NCAA quarterfinalist, played a year with the ABA
Miami Floridians, then followed the bouncing ball around the world.
By his rough count, he has played or coached in more than 55
countries.
</P>
<P>
   He has coached a high school champion in Philadelphia. He has
coached women at Temple. He has coached NCAA tournament teams at
Penn, where he spent six years as an assistant to boyhood buddy
Fran Dunphy.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, he has been sustained by a puckish sense of
humor and a decided lack of pretension or panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``His coaching style is not to rant and rave,'' says Lafayette
athletic director Eve Atkinson, who four years ago entrusted
O'Hanlon with a program that ranked 305th among 306 Division 1
schools, a sad demise since the days when Pete Carril played here
and Butch van Breda Kolff, Tom Davis, and Gary Williams coached
here. ``His style is thought-provoking. There is not a better
professor of X's and O's.''
</P>
<P>
   Even during the dark days, the 7-20 debut season stigmatized by
a loss to Division 3 Swarthmore, the Leopards began to come
together under O'Hanlon. The lunch-bucket frontcourt _ Ted Cole,
Harms, and Dave Klaus, who refused to be dissuaded even when the
coaches discouraged him from trying out _ arrived and set a
gut-busting tone that has become the Leopards' trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers, the big gun, came aboard a year later. And last year
O'Hanlon found the missing link, Tim Bieg, the point guard he
needed to distribute the ball and hit the open shot.
</P>
<P>
   There were supplementary ingredients, too. Whitfield, last
season's Patriot League Rookie of the Year, brought his bravado and
microwave scoring bursts from Yakima, Wash. Reggie Guy supplied
relentless defense in the backcourt. Frank Barr, a 6-foot-11-inch
stringbean, transferred from Hofstra and gradually took over in the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   It became a 12-man ensemble, and O'Hanlon utilized every piece.
The Leopards went 11-17 in his second year, shared the Patriot
League regular-season title in 1998 before losing to Navy in the
tournament final, and this year ignored what could have been a
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   It began with the loss of 6-11 Romanian import Stefan Ciosici,
the 1998 Patriot Player of the Year, who wrecked his knee during
the summer. Rather than concede disaster, O'Hanlon chose to
downplay Ciosici's absence. ``We've got a system,'' he preached to
his team. ``And the system works.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were impediments. While two of the Leopards' Patriot
brethren, Holy Cross and Lehigh, chose to exercise the new league
option allowing athletic scholarships, Lafayette steadfastly
resisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to dwell on what we don't have,'' shrugs O'Hanlon.
``That's a built-in excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he admitted to ``a lot of sleepless nights'' caused by
the administrative guillotine that threatened to come down on the
season: the possibility that Lafayette would downgrade to Division
3 in all sports. Not until halftime of the Jan. 16 game against
Army was it announced that an infusion of alumni dollars would
maintain the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
