<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-MASON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANS BRINGS MATURITY TO GEORGE MASON ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Don't expect George Evans to be intimidated by anything
Cincinnati tries to throw his way today. Somehow the spector of a
full-court press or a double-team isn't quite as threatening as
facing the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been shot at,'' he shrugged. ``It's going to be kinda
hard to be intimidated (today).''
</P>
<P>
   The Colonial Athletic Association's Player of the Year and
postseason tournament MVP just completed his second season at
George Mason. He's also 27 years old and, among his basketball
credentials, is a listing on the All-Army team from 1996-97. He
averaged 40 points and 18 rebounds a game playing for a club team
in Aberdeen, Md., while finishing up what proved to be a seven-year
hitch for Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just took a different route than everyone else,'' shrugged
teammate Jason Miskiri. ``He jokes and plays around, probably more
than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has been around more than they have. This is a guy who
drove generals around in Belgium and who served in Somalia, Haiti,
and in Operation Desert Storm. He's got more than a few war
stories.
</P>
<P>
   There was the time at the end of Desert Storm when he was on
patrol with four others. Eight Iraqi soldiers, guns loaded, came up
from behind. The Iraqis didn't shoot. They surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hungry,'' Evans said. ``They wanted food. But to
have been that close to death. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   He also talked about serving in Haiti, where he saw people jump
into fires for food and living in cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had it bad,'' he said. ``It just goes to show you,
it's not as bad (here) as it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   He has perspective that no one else has. He has responsibilities
few have; his wife and 7-year-old daughter live in Florida, where
the mother has a job. They saw each other during vacations breaks.
It's not the way he'd like to live, but he understands the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about goals, and she's been supportive of me,'' Evans
said. ``It's kinda hard to ask her if I can get a couple (more)
weeks to play basketball in the tournament. She don't understand
that. But it's a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity and I thank God for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans is a native Virginian, having attended high school in
Portsmouth, where he once went navel-to-eyeball with a hot shot
named Alonzo Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was '88 or '89,'' Evans said. ``He was 6-10. I was 6-1 1/2
and played center. I still had to guard him. He dunked it every
time. So our strategy was to hold the ball. I think the final score
was 15-14. We lost.''
</P>
<P>
   He went into the service after high school and, playing at
Aberdeen, where the competition is mostly other Army bases, prep
schools, and junior varsity teams, he caught the eye of Paul
Westhead, then the coach at George Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Evans had never even heard of George Mason, founded 42 years ago
and located in Fairfax, Va. But Westhead, using persuasive powers
he was later unable to transfer to on-the-court success, convinced
Evans to come. Evans had never set foot on the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Westhead was relieved of his position _ he's now an
assistant to P.J. Carlesimo with the Golden State Warriors _ and
Jim Larranaga arrived from Bowling Green. One of the first phone
calls Larranaga made was to the 26-year-old Evans, who had signed a
national letter of intent with George Mason the previous fall.
</P>
<P>
   The question: Was Evans going to honor the letter of intent?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: No.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt there was a sign from God not to attend George Mason
because of the change,'' Larranaga said. ``We simply asked him if
he would give us some time to talk with him, get to know him, and
see if it was still a workable situation. So my staff and I
basically went about the task of re-recruiting him.''
</P>
<P>
   Larranaga saw Evans play while at Aberdeen and was impressed
with his ability and size. (Evans no longer was the 6-1 runt from
high school. He was now 6-7, 225.) He got Evans to visit the
campus, talk to the players, mingle with the students. Evans
decided he'd stay after all, with one provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me, `will I be treated the same as everybody else?'
He wanted to be an equal member of the team,'' Larranaga said. ``We
said, `yes, you'll live in the dormitory as a freshman and hang out
with the guys and other college students.''
</P>
<P>
   That was all Evans needed to hear. He was the conference rookie
of the year as a freshman, averaging 13.1 points and 8.1 rebounds.
George Mason won only nine games, but that was still more than
predicted. This year, they were picked to finish fourth in the CAA
by the Blue Ribbon Yearbook, but instead won the CAA title and
postseason tournament. The Patriots, 19-10 overall, bring a 10-game
winning streak into Friday's game with Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Evans averaged 17.8 points and 8.6 rebounds during the regular
season and then was a force in the tournament, averaging 15.3
points, 11.7 rebounds, and 2.6 blocks as the Patriots beat
American, UNC-Wilmington, and Old Dominion to continue their
magical run.
</P>
<P>
   They're big underdogs against Cincinnati, but they're used to
such status by now. After what Evans has been through, mere numbers
hardly faze him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
