<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, March 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moderate to heavy rains will douse parts of the southern Plains
and lower Mississippi Valley Friday as a potent jet stream
disturbance, which Thursday spawned moderate rains over Southern
California, lifts increasingly moist air streaming rapidly
northward from the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms will erupt near the Gulf Coast, where the warmest,
most humid air gathers during the day. Thunder will also occur in
the cooler air mass across northern Texas and the lower Mississippi
Valley, with a few of these storms producing hail.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate to heavy snows will fall along the Front Range of the
central Rockies as the developing low pressure system over the
southern Plains draws moist, cold winds up the sloping terrain.
Moderate to heavy snows will spread eastward across the central
Plains, with the heaviest accumulations likely falling on the high
plains across western Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   A batch of steady rain will fall in Oklahoma south of this area
of steady snow, with a narrow corridor of ice separating the snow
and rain areas. Precipitation will gradually spread eastward during
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, clouds circulating around a stalled low-pressure
system off the coast of Maine will spread across much of the
Northeast Friday, with patchy light snows and narrow bands of
accumulating snows in the mountains of Vermont, New Hampshire and
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Some snow will spread southward toward the Catskills of New York
and the Berkshires of western Massachusetts. Patchy, light snow
will also occur over parts of the New England seaboard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Wrong-way Warm Front
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday morning, the National Weather Service at Gray,
Maine, canceled a winter weather advisory for snow and ice across
the state's northern tier as temperatures climbed above 32 degrees
in the wake of a wrong-way warm front. Unlike traditional warm
fronts which move from south to north, Thursday's warm front moved
southwest from the Canadian Maritimes as mild ocean air circulated
counterclockwise around a stalled low pressure system over the
Atlantic Ocean. The low had been stalled since the weekend after
its path was blocked by a high pressure system east of
Newfoundland. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
