<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6889 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-MIAMI-BOS &LR;      03-11 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-MIAMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERDOG MIAMI RELISHES THE ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORAL GABLES, Fla. _ His office is half the size of his
counterpart in football, Butch Davis. If he looks out the window,
he has a nice view of . . . the football practice field.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life at a school that has four national championships in
football and is re-tooling for another run.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not bother Leonard Hamilton. No, his vision goes
beyond the lush grass of the practice field. It goes beyond the
fence to a quadrant of two-story buildings that have housed
University of Miami students for the last couple of generations,
but will be torn down this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Hamilton sees what most people cannot. At least not
without some prompting.
</P>
<P>
   What the University of Miami baketball coach sees is the future.
He sees a state-of-the art $35 million arena called the Ryder
Center. He sees a building that will have 81 skyboxes, which he can
point to with pride when he brings recruits to a campus that keeps
adding first-class facilities.
</P>
<P>
   He also sees a challenge that would seem to be mind-boggling to
anyone who has paid even the slightest attention to Miami
basketball over the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Hamilton, sitting in his office earlier this week,
can only laugh when someone talks about ``Cinderella Lafayette vs.
Miami'', which is the prime-time game in Friday tonight's first
round of the NCAA East Regional at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinderella?'' said Hamilton, shaking his head. ``That's still
us. We have a long way to go yet. A long way.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the No. 2 seed in a region that contains top-ranked Duke,
the Hurricanes, who bring a 22-6 record into the game, can only
play that underdog card so long.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hamilton doesn't have the right to feel that way. When
he came to South Florida nine years ago, Miami was only five years
removed from a return to basketball after a 14-year absence.
University officials had dropped the program in 1971 for a variety
of reasons, the primary one being lack of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone noticed. Fewer people seemed to care.
</P>
<P>
   One person who did was former athletic director Sam Jankovich,
who knew that if Miami was to be regarded seriously by its peers,
it needed not only a basketball program, but a league to play in as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Using the power of the football team, which was just starting a
dynastic run that would include four national titles in 10 years,
Jankovich played power politics. Miami would be the foundation of a
newly formed Big East football league, if the Big East would take
the basketball team as a new member.
</P>
<P>
   When the Big East blinked, Miami was in and Jankovich was on his
next mission, getting an on-campus arena.
</P>
<P>
   Even in its best days, Miami basketball was an orphan. ``Some
games were played at Coral Gables High School,'' said AD Paul
Dee.``Others were at the Miami Beach Convention center. Some were
at Miami-Dade (Community College).'' Dee was able to push through
the last bit of funding, which should allow the ground to be broken
on the Ryder Center next fall.
</P>
<P>
   When Hamilton arrived in April 1990, the 'Canes were slowly
reestablishing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich, who had gone to Oklahoma State to find a football
coach in Jimmy Johnson, went back to Stillwater to hire Hamilton,
whose pedigree included 12 years as an assistant at Kentucky, as
well as a revival of the Oklahoma State program in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always dreamed about being a head coach,'' said Hamilton.
``But not at a well-heeled school like Kentucky or Duke. I needed
to be at a place that hadn't had a whole lot of success.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State had not had that in recent years, and Miami
certainly was hardly more than a blip on the radar screen in the
world of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton had all the ingredients Miami needed. He was young and
hungry. He was also comfortable at Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked it there,'' he said. ``I was starting to get
the kids I wanted and I was building something.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hamilton liked challenges. Always had. He was the first
black player at Gatson (N.C.) Community College. He was the first
black player at Tennessee-Martin. He was the first black coach in
the Ohio Valley Conference. He was the first black assistant coach
at Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   When Jankovich called, Hamilton and his wife, Claudette, took a
trip to Miami. ``My wife said that it was nice, but she knew I
wouldn't take the job,'' said Hamilton with a laugh. ``She took an
earlier flight back to Oklahoma. When she got home, she turned on
the television set, and I was accepting the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton says the building process, which has come from the
depths of an 0-18 season in the Big East in 1993-94, continues.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his protests that Miami is still the underdog, the
achievements of the past few years, including this year's
remarkable 15-3 run in the Big East (which included a pair of wins
over St. John's and a victory against the University of Connecticut
in Storrs) indicate an upward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw anyone able to clear as many hurdles as Leonard
and do it without getting discouraged,'' said Big East commissioner
Mike Tranghese. ``He's always focused on what he has, rather than
what he doesn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Dee, who rewarded Hamilton with a five-year extension after the
0-18 season, says he sees the progress not only in the basketball,
but in the quality of people Hamilton has brought in. ``No Prop
48's (Miami does not take them),'' said Dee. ``And Leonard is on
top of them on everything, from going to school to staying out of
trouble. We've got the right guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton feels he is in the right job. ``We've got a belief in
what we are doing,'' said Hamilton, who has recruited overacheivers
who came to Miami not as McDonald's All-Americans, but as
All-America wannabes. ``We feel we're doing things right, so why
change? The kids we get are working harder and doing good things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton knows the next few weeks will be crucial in the
perception of Miami basketball. Win a few games and suddenly the
Hurricanes move to a higher level. Lose early and the 'Canes
quickly fade from view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he says with a smile and shrug, ``we haven't
accomplished a thing yet.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hamilton came back from practice the other day, a note was
pinned on his office door. ``ESPN satelite feed, 7:30, John
Saunders, Dick Vitale. Don't forget.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was this after Davis was asked about the 'Canes'
success in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we want,'' said Davis with a straight face, ``is a
football team our basketball team can be proud of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
