<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, March 12. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Over the fierce objections of the
Clinton administration, the House moved ahead on Thursday with
debate over whether U.S. troops should be sent to Kosovo as part of
a NATO peacekeeping force should a settlement be reached in the
Balkan conflict. By Alison Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   NATO (Warsaw, Poland) _ When Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic formally join NATO on Friday, it will be the return of
three nations, and not merely their militaries, to the center of
European civilization. At the start, these three countries will not
add much to NATO's military capacities. In fact, they have just
managed to meet the alliance's minimum military requirements for
integrated air defense, security procedures and language-training.
By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-MINISTER-RESIGN (Bonn, Germany) _ Germany's left-wing
finance minister, Oskar Lafontaine, resigned Thursday after
apparently losing a power struggle with Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder. Lafontaine, who had become the bete noire of the
financial markets in less than six months in office, also stepped
down as chairman of the governing Social Democrat party, clearing
the way for the pragmatic Schroeder to assert control. (Early
summary by wires.) By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-EDUC (Washington) _ The House and Senate handily
approved legislation Thursday to give states and schools more
flexibility in how they spend $11 billion in federal money, and to
give each party a claim on being in tune with the public's interest
in education. But after a week of partisan squabbling in the Senate
over amendments, a Democratic measure pushed by President Clinton
to authorize the hiring of 100,000 teachers failed to muster a
majority. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   TRADES-SHORTAGE (Chicago) _ Faced with a shortage of
tradesworkers to meet the voracious demand for new construction in
the United States, desperate builders and eager unions have kicked
off aggressive campaigns to court new workers, attracting women and
members of racial minorities to the traditional bastion of white
men, a world where a coveted union card was handed from father to
son. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-SECURITY (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ As modern science
becomes an overwhelmingly international enterprise, a clash has
intensified between the scientific value of sharing information and
the national security need to keep secrets _ including advanced
designs of nuclear weapons. Scientists and engineers who have
watched their world evolve from a small club of male elites into a
yeasty mix of men and women from every continent say that the
balancing act has grown extraordinarily difficult. By Sandra
Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NETS-MARBURY (Undated) _ On the day of the NBA trading
deadline, the New Jersey Nets appear poised to make a big trade,
acquiring Stephon Marbury, one of the league's premier point
guards, from Minnesota. By Chris Broussard.
</P>
</TEXT>
