<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6906 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-11 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOLE'S TURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As she took the first official step toward a
presidential bid, Elizabeth Dole had yet to figure out how to solve
her unique problem: what to do about Bob?
</P>
<P>
   She clearly understands that to be taken seriously she must run
in her own right, stressing her public service credentials and
management experience rather than her famous married name. That is
what she did Wednesday in an expert performance in Iowa in which
she outlined her aspirations and her job achievements, which are
considerable.
</P>
<P>
   As a female pioneer at the highest level of national politics,
she cannot escape the cultural double standard that treats men as
instinctive leaders and women as natural followers. That barrier
has been increasingly overcome by talented, determined women in
statewide campaigns. But Elizabeth Dole is also burdened by the
fact that most people know her merely as Bob's capable wife and
that she has had a habit of ducking issues by saying she agrees
with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Her initial solution to handling their partnership was silly.
She didn't even mention her husband or just why it was that ``I
know a lot about running in a presidential campaign.'' The former
senator was conspicuously not at her side staring raptly at the
candidate in the customary fashion of other spouses at such
momentous events. For these purposes, he was a nonperson.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole was testifying before Congress halfway across the
continent, reinforcing the image of two independent political
leaders who live together but follow separate careers. Sitting next
to Elizabeth, he would have been a distraction, a center of
interest competing with her own appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But better a distraction than a transparent political pretense
that he doesn't exist, which will be exposed as fiction the first
time he makes a fund-raising call for her.
</P>
<P>
   This hands-off act is an unrealistic position to maintain for
nearly two years in a high-visibility presidential campaign. How
often are they to be seen together? Is he to be so absent that
rumors start about the state of their marriage? The level of his
support?
</P>
<P>
   Or is he to be so often at her side that they become
indistinguishable, in a pale rerun of the losing 1996 campaign? Is
he to be the new Hillary Clinton, about whom the president once
said if voters bought one, they would get two?
</P>
<P>
   It is not possible for the female Dole to ignore forever the
most recent Republican presidential nominee, the titular head of
her party. They have had independent careers, but they have not
been equal.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he lost the White House to the incumbent Democrat,
Bob Dole remains a formidable, well-liked GOP stalwart whose name
has repeatedly been on the ballot, as senator in Kansas, the 1976
GOP vice presidential nominee and presidential candidate. The
shadow of his presence looms over her candidacy, no matter how she
may pretend otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of her other qualifications, Elizabeth Dole has never
before stood for elective office and would not be a hot prospect
for the GOP nomination if her name was still Elizabeth Hanford.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at how much attention Lamar Alexander, also a former
Cabinet officer as well as a duly elected governor and presidential
candidate, is getting. Hardly anybody knows him despite his
campaigning in Iowa, which holds the first caucuses, for more than
two years. A new CNN poll there says he's favored only by a measly
7.7 percent of likely GOP caucus participants.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity through surrogate name identification also helps
President Bush's son, Texas Gov. George W Bush, just as it has
helped Sen. Edward Kennedy and other candidates who inherited
famous names through history. There is nothing wrong with this. It
indicates, if nothing else, a sense of continuity in politics,
which is not to be lightly dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole has long been rightfully admired for her
leadership, her professional ability and her charming Southern
manner. Frequent remarks that the ``wrong Dole'' ran in 1996 were
made only half in jest. And it is not fair that she be judged on a
different standard of political qualification than her male GOP
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fact remains that no male candidate has the problem of
what to do with a more prominent spouse. Bush, Pat Buchanan and the
others can look good displaying their ``family values'' by
campaigning beside mostly muted wives who are at best sidekicks and
at worst irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   When Bob ran for president, the Doles solved the problem of
Elizabeth's independent stature by having her campaign separately,
visiting smaller groups and less crucial states than those he
personally wooed. But can this work in reverse? Would Bob Dole
really play second fiddle on the road to his wife, even to have a
shot at becoming First Husband and a permanent secondary role?
</P>
<P>
   The female Dole described herself in her Iowa appearance as a
public servant who was ``not a politician.'' This is meant to
explain away the fact that as a political wife she does not enjoy
the hard-core insider status flaunted by Bush, as evidenced in his
impressive array of endorsements from prominent GOP establishment
figures.
</P>
<P>
   But she cannot distance herself from Washington, where she and
her husband have spent their careers. Nor is she trying. She is
neither insider nor outsider, a strange but potentially promising
position in which many ambitious women in other fields also find
themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
