<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-PURDUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEADY HOPES HE HAS PURDUE UP TO CELTICS STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gene Keady does not want you to know this, but . . . ``I grew up
a Yankees fan,'' the Purdue basketball coach says, laughing. ``I
don't want people in Boston to know that, because then they might
start booing me.'' But he quickly points out that, as a lad growing
up in Larned, Kan., he also passionately rooted for the Celtics.
``Everyone during my time rooted for the Celtics, Packers, and
Yankees, because they all won championships,'' he says. ``They were
winners.''
</P>
<P>
   And everyone loves a winner, be it in Boston, New York, Green
Bay, Wis., or even Larned, Kan. That's why Keady should have no
such worries about an inhospitable response from the FleetCenter
crowd _ unless, of course, he plans to be ushered onto the court by
Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette _ when he arrives with his No.
10 seed Boilermakers for their first-round matchup Friday night
against No. 7 seed Texas in the NCAA East Regional.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Purdue's season will start anew. At the FleetCenter.
Beneath the championship banners and upon the famed parquet floor
of Keady's beloved Celtics. And Gene Keady cannot wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity for us to get on the right track again,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   How often does a basketball team, coaching staff, and program
get the opportunity to erase a season of lowlights _ of which there
were many for the Boilermakers _ and start again in the NCAA
Tournament with a fresh, white canvas?
</P>
<P>
   When Purdue got off to a 12-2 start in November and December,
the season took on the look of a carefully crafted work. With a
dash of color here. A bold sense of style there. And very broad
brushstrokes throughout. It was a work in progress, no doubt, but
one that Keady nonetheless hoped to put on display in March along
with the rest of the gallery of teams in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But it was all very nearly ruined by a 7-10 finish in which the
Boilers lost five of their last six games. Add to that the
lingering specter of an ongoing NCAA investigation into allegations
of improprieties involving arranged loans for Luther Clay _ then a
freshman recruit looking to enroll from Maine Central Institute _ a
chemistry problem on the team, and an unforgiving Big Ten schedule,
and the season began to look less like a masterpiece and more like
a jumbled mess.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the 62-year-old Keady, considered one of the most
successful coaches never to reach the Final Four, was questioning
himself: (itals)Did I do a good job motivating the kids? Did I do a
good job getting the right players? Did I handle that right? Am I
handling this right?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   ``I blamed myself when things didn't go right,'' Keady says.
``The buck stops here. You go back and reevaluate and see what
happened. All of our players are very proud of what they did here,
and the thing that hurt me the most was ex-players calling up and
asking me, `Why aren't you guys playing better? What the heck's
going on?' I'm glad they're calling, because they built it up and
we don't want to let everybody down.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a problem on the team. And it didn't become
apparent to Keady until after the Christmas break when the Boilers
lost four of their first seven conference games.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we got into the season I don't know exactly what happened,
but I think there was some selfishness and maybe some
self-centeredness that kept us from being totally focused like the
previous Purdue teams,'' says Keady, who after 20 seasons ranks as
the school's all-time winningest coach with a 413-179 record
(.698), six conference titles, and 16 NCAA Tournament berths. ``We
didn't build and get better like we had in previous years, and I
think it caught the coaches off guard a little bit, because we'd
always gotten better and when it started caving in on us, I don't
think that we probably handled it in a proper manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Keady has endured tougher years, to be sure. He ranked the
1989-90 season, one in which he had two starters go down with
injuries and an insurrection of ``very immature children''
undermine the team, among his most difficult. Still he wound up
going 22-8 and advanced to the second round of the tournament
before losing to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But this season? ``It's probably one of the toughest,'' he
acknowledges. ``I don't think people realized how good the Big Ten
was going to be. It was probably one of those situations where the
players probably didn't work at their game like they should have
last summer to maintain the tradition we have here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little slippage there, and when we started slipping
our attitude started slipping and we started losing, and it was not
much fun here for a while,'' he adds. ``But this is new life for
us, and I hope we can get it on the right course again. If you
coach long enough, you're going to have those years where it
doesn't go smooth. We've been pretty spoiled here at Purdue for
five years. We've had a lot of great kids that won pretty big
games. So, not to do that, our fans were not very happy about that
this year and the coaching staff was really unhappy about it, so we
didn't handle it too well.''
</P>
<P>
   But Selection Sunday had a redemptive effect on Keady, his
staff, and his team. When Keady huddled in front of a TV set with
his staff to watch the ``NCAA Selection Show,'' they were stunned
to see ``Purdue'' in the East Region bracket as a 10th seed, the
lowest in school history. ``To tell you the truth, I didn't even
notice who we were playing, I was so happy,'' Keady says. ``It was
one of the best moments of the season. We gave more high-fives
around the office than we did in those years when we got the No. 1
seed.''
</P>
<P>
   There was favorable change in attitude three weeks before a
gut-wrenching overtime loss to Michigan in the Big Ten tournament,
but Keady was bouyed when he noticed a definite snap, crackle, and
pop in practice that evening after Purdue earned its NCAA berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the stretch, we were as not good, didn't play with as
much fire in our belly; we really weren't having a lot of fun,''
Keady says. ``But I can tell you that the last couple of days of
practice the kids have practiced hard and seem to be having a lot
more fun, like they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, too, is their coach _ deservedly so. After the
tumultuous season he's had to endure, no one in Boston can begrudge
Gene Keady that inalienable right.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he is a Yankees fan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
