<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6913 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-RYAN-COLUMN-     03-11 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY FROM THE MID-AMERICAN CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following does not constitute a major news bulletin: Kent
University will not be winning the national championship this year.
</P>
<P>
   Or any other year.
</P>
<P>
   There are schools with the resources to get the ultimate job
done, but Kent is not one of them, nor is anyone else in the
Mid-American Conference. This is the reality of life in what is
referred to in the trade as a ``mid-major'' conference (not that
anyone ever 'fesses up to residing in a ``low'' major conference).
</P>
<P>
   So let's be honest about it. Kent has not come to the Fleet
thinking it is the first step toward cutting down the nets March 29
in St. Petersburg, Fla. Kent has come here trying to win one game
and maybe, if the sun, moon, stars, and all needed planets are
properly aligned, another. Get to an East Regional semifinal, and
Kent will have achieved all that any mid-major could hope ever hope
for. Get to the regional semifinal, and the players will be Kent
heroes forever. Get to the regional semis, and they will have
something to be proud of for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The Kent coach is Gary Waters, and he understands. He knows the
MAC turf. He knows what is and isn't possible. He has actually seen
the sun, moon, stars, and planets cooperate. He has also seen Brian
Tolbert and Earl Boykins rain threes on someone's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I can compare us with Eastern Michigan,'' he
says, ``but when I was an assistant at Eastern Michigan one year we
got to a Sweet 16 and another year we beat Duke. But I can tell you
how hard it is for a mid-major to get to a regional (semifinal),
especially if you are seeded higher than 10th.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mid-American Conference-champion Golden Flashes _ and don't
you just love that nickname? _ are seeded 11th in the East. They
will be playing sixth-seeded Temple in the second game of Friday
afternoon's doubleheader. If they should figure out a way to combat
both Temple's legendary zone defense and its major height
advantage, the likely reward will be a matchup on Sunday with
third-seeded Cincinnati, a scary team that was good enough to
defeat supposedly omnipotent Duke.
</P>
<P>
   We world-weary observers give Kent a slight chance against
Temple (which did, after all, lose by 30 to West Virginia in a
first-round game last year), but we give the Flashes no, as in
z-e-r-o, chance against Cincinnati, which is a lot closer to being
a No. 1 seed than it is to being a No. 4. Fortunately for Kent, the
kids who will actually be playing the game pay no, as in z-e-r-o,
attention to things we world-weary commentators have to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play as good ball in the MAC as anywhere in the country,''
maintains Kent center John Whorton. ``It doesn't really matter to
us what people say or how they rate things. You still have to play
the game on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just look at it as another challenge,'' shrugs senior guard
Ed Norvell. ``We're just going to play basketball, and we're going
to play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Whorton is 6 feet 8 inches and 250 pounds. He will be going up
against a 6-10, 6-9, 6-5 front line, the likes of which is simply
not seen in the MAC, which, by nature, features somewhat undersized
and underrecruited players.
</P>
<P>
   What Temple will find is that Whorton will be presenting himself
for the Owls' perusal with great authority. ``I like contact,'' he
explains. ``I like for the game to bump and grind a little. There
aren't too many players who enjoy playing in the low post nowadays,
but I think it's something we need to get back to. You shoot a
better percentage down there. If more players got down there, the
scores would go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Whorton leads the wonderfully balanced (five guys between 8 and
12 points per) Golden Flashes with 12.8 points a game. He practices
what he preaches by shooting 57 percent from the floor. He's been
in double figures 20 times, with a high of 23 against Eastern
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   You often hear about mid-major players swearing vengeance on the
snobby power conference teams that would not recruit them. Such
thinking is irrelevant in the Whorton scheme of things. ``I don't
hold grudges,'' says the Columbus, Ohio, native. ``If teams didn't
want me, they didn't want me. Someone did, and that someone was
Kent State.''
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, life will go on for Temple, which will operate as a
major-major, the way it always has. Temple's legacy includes
winning the first National Invitation Tournament back in 1938.
Temple has been to the Final Four. Temple has seen itself ranked
No. 1 in the country. Coach John Chaney has a major national
profile.
</P>
<P>
   But one win in this tournament can have enormous repercussions
for both Kent and the Mid-American Conference. It would mean, for
example, another day of television exposure, and Waters is very
passionate on that topic. ``More than anything else,'' he says,
``that is what our conference needs. We have got to get on TV more.
That is something our new commissioner has got to address. I look
at certain conferences on TV, and I am concerned that we don't have
as good a TV package. We play some good ball in this conference,
and we've beaten some good teams. We didn't do it by holding the
ball, either. We went head to head with people and won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   There it is: no trickeration, no deception. Kent comes at you
with aggressive, honest basketball. Win it all? Not reasonable. Win
a game? Why not?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
