<HEADLINE>
BEARCATS BRING WIN OVER DUKE TO EAST REGIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, it was months ago and things have changed a lot since then.
One team, Duke, hasn't lost since and is the people's choice to win
the NCAA Tournament. The other team, Cincinnati, has lost five,
including the last one it played. It is the people's choice in,
perhaps, Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bearcats remain living proof that, yes, Duke can be
beaten, which of course will mean little or nothing when they play
George Mason Friday afternoon in the first round of the East
Regional at the FleetCenter. If the Bearcats do see Duke again, it
will mean they will have made it to the regional final, but that's,
well, down the road.
</P>
<P>
   But beating the Dukies does have its advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get that same attitude back,'' says Melvin Levett, ``no
one will stop us.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Pete Mickeal, a highly recruited junior college transfer
from Indian Hills (Iowa) who led the team in scoring, ``If we can
get back to the point where we practiced that hard and were focused
that hard, we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   You almost feel compelled to talk in the past tense about
Cincinnati. The Bearcats did, indeed, beat Duke in the Great Alaska
Shootout with a terrific end-of-game play (a dunk by Levett). At
the time, no one thought it would be as significant as it was. But
they've also lost twice to North Carolina-Charlotte and thrice to
teams not even deemed worthy of the tournament: DePaul (a referee
robbery), St. Louis, and Marquette. The latter two had losing
records.
</P>
<P>
   So which Cincinnati team will we see, the one that started the
season 15-0, was ranked as high as third in the country, and beat
Duke, or the one that finished 11-5 and didn't win its conference
tournament? Either might be good enough to beat George Mason, but
while the Bearcats have higher goals, they aren't taking the
Patriots lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled in the first round last year against Northern
Arizona,'' said coach Bobby Huggins, referring to a 65-62 victory.
Cincinnati, the No. 2 seed in the West last year, then lost to West
Virginia in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our practices have been pretty good,'' Huggins said. ``If we
don't fare well, it will be because they played better. We've never
had a problem taking it seriously. I understand those teams (low
seeds) are good enough to win, and our guys understand that. We've
lost games to teams we probably shouldn't have lost to.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Levett, who averaged 14.3 points a game, ``I think we just
hit a wall in the second half of the season. Every team experiences
them. We tried to work as hard as we could to get over it. I think
the loss to UNC-Charlotte opened up a lot of eyes. It's one and
out. We're ready to play ball now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati has drawn the No. 3 seed in the East, the fourth
straight year it has been either a No. 2 or a No. 3. In only one of
those years, 1996, did the Bearcats get past the second round. They
like to play fast and furious, also the preferred pace of George
Mason, but they also take pride in their defense. Cincinnati's
opponents this season shot 38.4 percent from the field and averaged
an NBA-ish 61.5 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Bearcats also are tournament-tough, having been here every
season since their surprise Final Four run in 1992. They are 8-2
this season against tournament teams, the only losses coming to
UNC-Charlotte. They did win their fourth straight regular-season
Conference USA title, their sixth in the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   What concerns Huggins entering the tournament is his club's
shooting. Cincinnati is coming off a 16-of-45 performance against
UNC-Charlotte, including a jaw-dropping 1 of 17 on 3-pointers. In
their last five games, the Bearcats are 16 of 82 from international
waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make shots,'' the coach said, matter-of-factly.
``We have to shoot it better than we did the last month. I know
we're going to guard people and rebound. We'll be consistent there.
But we've got to make the shots. When we've been successful, we've
shot the ball well.''
</P>
<P>
   Huggins also said he'd like to get the ball inside more, and
that makes sense given the team's physical front line of Mickeal,
Kenyon Martin, and Jermaine Tate. Levett, too, is chiseled. A
freshman, Steve Logan, is the starting point guard. He moved into
the position in the second game of the season and, Huggins said,
``has come a long way, especially defensively.'' He's also the
team's best perimeter shooter.
</P>
<P>
   When they have their game faces on, the Bearcats are terrific.
They are athletic, strong, and active. They create havoc and feast
on mistakes. They may not be the nation's favorite _ they've had
their share of thugs and ``incidents'' over the years; Nick Van
Exel, after all, went there _ but they remain a potent force in the
regional.
</P>
<P>
   They have George Mason Friday, and that's the team on their
minds. But they also have expectations to play a few more before
it's all over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
