<SLUG> BC-APPLE-STARWARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' PREVIEW TO APPEAR ON APPLE COMPUTER'S WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `e' code) 
(bl) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a promotional coup, Apple Computer Inc. said
Thursday that it had joined with Lucasfilm Ltd. to present a
preview of the new ``Star Wars'' movie on its Web site. The preview
began appearing on the web site Thursday, the day before its first
appearance in theaters Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jobs, Apple's co-founder and interim chief executive, said
in a telephone interview that the company had added network
capacity to accommodate an anticipated 10 million downloads of the
two-and-a-half-minute film clip. It is accessible at www.apple.com
or www.starwars.com and is offered in several different resolutions
so that viewers can pick a download suitable to the speed of their
connection to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're incredibly thrilled and honored to be selected by
Lucasfilm,'' said Jobs, pointing out that the film company had
chosen Apple's Quicktime video technology over Real Player from
Real Networks Inc. or Media Player from Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be the biggest download in history,'' Jobs said.
Apple is expecting ``an order of magnitude'' more downloads of this
trailer than the one presented by Walt Disney Co. for ``A Bug's
Life,'' the animated film co-produced by Disney and Jobs' other
company, Pixar Inc., he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Ward, Lucasfilm's director of marketing, said the trailer
was longer than the so-called teaser clip that began appearing in
theaters last November. While the teaser focused on the story of
Anakin Skywalker, a major character in ``Star Wars, Episode I: The
Phantom Menace,'' directed by George Lucas, the new trailer tells
more of the full story, offering a glimpse at the movie's scope.
Many fans bought tickets to theaters just to see the first
two-minute trailer and then left without watching the feature film
that followed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the home stretch, this is the last trailer for the
film,'' Ward said. The film will open in theaters May 21. ``We
wanted something that would both blow the fans away and sustain
them during the last stretch before the movie opens,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is difficult to draw a direct line between such a
promotion and increased Macintosh sales or Quicktime use, it is
still a victory for both Apple and Lucasfilm, said Tim Bajarin,
president of Creative Strategies in Cupertino, Calif. ``Apple gets
great cross-promotion and Lucas gets great promotion,'' he said.
``This is Steve calling in the chits from his Hollywood pals. It's
Steve Jobs at his promotional best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
