<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-TEMPLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVER-FOCUSED CHANEY BRINGS HIS OPINIONS TO THE FLOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An entertaining and always opinionated John Chaney spent most of
his alloted press conference time speaking about his 16-year pet
peeve, the Proposition 16 and 48 rules that were overturned this
week in a federal court, but Chaney is also quite focused on his
Temple team, concerned about the sore hand of guard Quincy Wadley
as well as how to go about beating what he considers a
``well-coached ballclub'' in underdog Kent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor has taken a look at him,'' said Chaney. ``I'm
concerned. I don't know if I want to risk playing him. He said he's
all right, but this morning that hand was a little bit stiff. I'll
play it according to how he feels. We'll see if that hand loosens
up. He means a lot to our offense. He's perhaps one of the two guys
in terms of outside shooting that we would miss a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadley, who injured the bone in the back of his hand in the
Atlantic 10 Tournament, had the hand heavily wrapped as he shot
during the team's walk-through at the FleetCenter Thursday
afternoon. Chaney has already lost sophomore guard Lynn Greer for
the season, and has had to play without freshman Alex Wesby, a
victim of the Prop 16 ruling, but is expected to return next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prop 48 never should have taken place; never,'' said Chaney,
wearing a green overcoat over a nylon sweatsuit and sporting a
black Nike hat. ``First of all it destroys the mission of every
college in this country. Every university has a different mission.
The guy who headed up that (NCAA) commission _ Derrick C. Park _
who was right here at Harvard at the time, headed a committee with
43 white presidents from all the big football schools over the
country back in 1983. It's 16 years old now. It should never have
happened. He said no one should tell him who enters his school
because he has blacks, he has kids from disadvantaged backgrounds,
entering Harvard right here in this city. So this should never have
come about.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney emphasized that in no way should SAT scores be the sole
instrument for deciding whether a kid gets into school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish you guys would get it right,'' he said. ``This judge
only made this judgment based on the fact that the NCAA was asked
to present them data _ to present to him information _ `show me
some evidence as to why you came up with this ruling.' They
couldn't do it. They showed no evidence at all. None.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can use writing essays, you can have resumes presented
with all kinds of recommendations, and you can have other types of
testing in addition to SATs. But it should not be the sole
instrument of not allowing kids to get into school. That was
unfair. Since when does an athletic entity tell the university and
academic environment how it should admit students?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need everybody educated. That's why my gradation rate is
low. It's low because I will try my best to get every Tom, Dick,
and Harry in school that I can. If you're driving down the street
with your family, don't you want the guy coming across that stop
sign to be able to read `Stop'? I want him to be educated because
it might save my life and my families' life. But people are so
pompous to suggest we shouldn't let these kids in school. So what,
they come back home after two years? Let them shoot themselves in
the foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney doesn't envision the NCAA changing its mind and expects
there will be appeal after appeal on the ruling. While
acknowledging he was pleased with decision, ``The damage has been
done,'' he said. ``You've destroyed the aspirations of so many
youngsters.''
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite Chaney topic is his matchup zone defense, which
he says has been much maligned in the Philadelphia area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very fortunate in that I really don't care what people
think,'' Chaney said. ``But the people in our city talk about the
way we play basketball as the worst basketball in the country. I
only get applause when we win championships. Our city hates the way
we play basketball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
