<HEADLINE>
CHINESE WOMEN HOLD US TO SINGLE GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANTAA, Finland _ That the Chinese women's hockey team has a
strong defense is hardly news: at the Olympics, it held the
gold-medal United States team to five goals and silver medalist
Canada to two. If its offense ever catches up, the No. 4 finisher
in Nagano is going to be a dangerous team.
</P>
<P>
   Led by goaltender Lina Huo, the patient Chinese held the US to a
single goal on 12 shots in the first period Thursday before Karyn
Bye (hat trick) and Jenny Schmidgall (a goal and four assists)
sparked the Americans to a 6-0 victory. Laurie Belliveau, of
Manchester-by-the-Sea, Mass., via Yale, got the shutout with eight
saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rely on their defensive game and they were right in it
for the first half,'' said US coach Ben Smith. ``They were a very
difficult match for us and I didn't expect anything less. The
Chinese goalie is very hard to score on.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Canada barely survived a scare by Finland to win,
1-0, thus keeping hopes alive for an Olympic rematch with the US in
Sunday's final. Canada hung on to win even after Caroline Ouellette
was called for hooking with 1:01 remaining, giving Finland a 6-on-4
power play when it pulled its goalie.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, the US clinched first place in Group A, advancing
to the medal round in which it will meet Finland, the runner-up in
Group B, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way (Finland) played . . . , we will probably be ready for
them in the final,'' said Canadian coach Daniele Sauvageau.
</P>
<P>
   In its semifinal game, Canada, winner of Group B, will face
Sweden, the runner-up in Group A.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, China kept the US quiet until 12:15 in the first
period, when Katie King of Salem, N.H., penetrated a scrum in front
of the net to put the US on the board, 1-0. The Americans weren't
heard from again until 5:59 had passed in the second, when Huo made
a nice save on a shot by Cammi Granato only to have Schmidgall poke
in the rebound. Bye got the first of her three goals with a
bull's-eye shot up the middle from six feet out 16:52 into the
second, which ended 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Dorchester's Stephanie O'Sullivan came alive in the third,
assisting on all three goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
