<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGSTORE-RETAILERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRY DISPENSING PROFITS, WITH BIG CHAINS LEADING THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CONSTANCE SOMMER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ That Bartell Drugs down the street may look like a big
box of a store. But don't be fooled _ it's really one of the little
guys.
</P>
<P>
   From Syracuse to Seattle, the nation's drugstore retailers are
waging campaigns of individual expansion and industry
consolidation. Nearly every day brings a new report of a drugstore
giant gobbling up another regional chain such as Seattle-based
Bartell. Meanwhile, the nation's top four chains continue to pump
out sales increases so strong that last year Wall Street giddily
bid up the stock of No. 1 Walgreen by 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As staid as the drugstore business may seem, with its cluttered
aisles, awash-in-white pharmacies and garish cosmetics displays,
this is a hot retail sector where ever-bigger players are learning
how to squeeze nice profits from the low-profit-margin operation of
prescription drug dispensing. The increased competition _ though it
drives out the smaller operators _ can also mean good news for
customers, as stores woo time-pressed shoppers with amenities such
as ample parking at corner locations, drive-through pharmacies,
film-processing services and even the sale of grocery staples such
as milk and eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drugstore industry is on a roll,'' wrote analyst Sandra
Skrovan in a 1998 report for PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``And the big
are poised to get bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1990, the top 10 drugstore chains generated 42.6
percent of industry sales, according to the PricewaterhouseCoopers'
report. Seven years later, the top four companies alone _
Illinois-based Walgreen Co., CVS Corp. of Rhode Island,
Pennsylvania-based Rite-Aid, and Eckerd Corp., the Florida-based
subsidiary of J.C. Penney _ accounted for nearly half of all
industry sales, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   Two distinct trends are pushing these changes: the aging of the
baby boomers and the continued rise of managed care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby boomers are starting to get on medications,'' said
Don Downing, pharmacy care coordinator for the Washington State
Pharmacists Association. ``Retailers are filling far more
prescriptions per store than they ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is only the beginning of the wave. The baby boom
generation is just barely edging into its 50s. Retail experts say
drug store companies are racing to position themselves for an
explosion in prescription business over the coming decades.
</P>
<P>
   In any other industry, this population shift would be good news
for all comers, large and small. But thanks largely to managed
care, the drugstore business has morphed into a unique creature
seemingly only capable of survival on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care companies encourage doctors to treat patients with
drug therapy rather than more costly surgical procedures, and in
that way they're a boon for drug sales. They also, though, drive
hard bargains on pharmaceutical reimbursement, pushing down what
was formerly a high-profit-margin business into one that now can
only eke out, in many cases, 1 percent to 2 percent profits on
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Bartell Drugs decided to fight back _ and in a
telling incident, lost. The company had to backpedal. The then
41-store chain (it has since added three stores) refused to fill
prescriptions for Blue Cross of Washington and Alaska members,
citing the health plan's new low reimbursement rates.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the Washington State Pharmacists Association estimated
that an independent pharmacist had to earn an average gross profit
of $6.79 per prescription to break even with expenses. The gross
profit under the Blue Cross rates came to $3.80.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no way we can justify doing business with the
plan under their most recent proposal,'' Bartell's director of
pharmacy, Dan Connolly, told the Post-Intelligencer in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bartell stopped filling the prescriptions Oct. 1 of that year.
But no other chain store followed its lead, and six weeks later the
company reversed course after shoppers complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that drove us hardest to go back (to Blue Cross) was
our customers,'' said Mike McMurry, Bartell's director of
marketing. ``It's the kind of commitment we have to our
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   With barely more than three dozen stores, Bartell wielded no
clout with Blue Cross in its efforts to punch up reimbursement
rates. A company such as Walgreen, boasting nearly $16 billion in
annual sales and more than 2,500 stores nationwide, is a different
story.
</P>
<P>
   The company dropped a half-dozen insurance plans last year
because of low reimbursement rates and is getting tough with the
many more managed care plans it continues to serve, Walgreen
spokesman Michael Pulvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing (profit) margins leveling off now'' after a few
years of decline, he said. ``We're using our leverage as the
nation's largest pharmacy chain to say, `Look, we can't continue to
provide the services your patients need at these rates.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chains also respond to the price pressures by trying to become
more efficient in their pharmacies, investing in technologies that,
for instance, can let machines fill common prescriptions or at
least take automated refill orders over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Some have begun pushing the pharmacists themselves to do more,
faster, said Jann Hinkle, a spokeswoman for the American
Pharmaceutical Association, which represents the nation's
pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're working at such a high volume that not only is it
potentially dangerous for patients, but these pharmacists are
working 12, 14 hours at a stretch without being able to take a
lunch break,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the State Board of Pharmacy recently fined Rite-Aid
$50,000 for what the board termed an unacceptable amount of
mistakes in filling prescriptions. Understaffing may have
contributed to the problem, the board's executive director said.
</P>
<P>
   So with all the pressure to contain costs, why are big companies
such as Walgreens opening so many new stores? It's not just drugs.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Association of Chain Drug Stores, a
bit less than half of the industry's sales are prescription drugs.
Obviously, drugs didn't account for an 18 percent rise in
fourth-quarter earnings recently at CVS, the nation's No. 2 drug
store chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to do it (make their money) in the front end,'' said
analyst Philip Muldoon III of McDonald Investments Inc. in
Cleveland, using the industry jargon referring to everything in a
drugstore that's not the pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it _ who looks for bargains at a drugstore? They're
the places that serendipitously offer motor oil, mascara, diapers,
board games and scented candles in the narrow aisles between the
pharmacy counter in the back and the cash registers in the front. A
thriving drugstore gets shoppers buying things they only dimly knew
they needed, at full retail price to boot, during an errand they
ran to pick up something else.
</P>
<P>
   This is what allows Bartell Drugs to stay alive and even,
slowly, expand despite its inability to twist tough deals out of
the managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had terrific sales gains last year,'' said President and
Chief Executive George Bartell. ``We get offers to buy us from time
to time, but basically, we're not interested.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's also what's killing the nation's remaining small,
independent pharmacies who traditionally have relied on the
prescription drug business to pay the bills each month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would make me feel better if I could make money at the end
of the year,'' said Doug Hendrecks, owner of the Greenwood Medicine
Man pharmacy, who says he's hanging on waiting for the financial
tides to turn in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrecks points out that he can't stock one of every item under
the sun. He simply doesn't have the room. And because he doesn't
have the room to stock every random good on the market, he can't
make enough money to pay for a 24-hour staff or even one that stays
on into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he tries to keep his prescription drug prices
competitive for the customers who pay for their medications
themselves _ about 20 percent of the national market. He also
stocks a wide variety of herbal and other natural remedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any independents who are still around, my hat's off to them,''
he said. ``They are doing something right.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there are about 20,000 independent drugstores left in
the country, according to United Drugs Cooperative. But the trend
is definitely toward the chains.
</P>
<P>
   In such a skewed marketplace, everything ultimately turns on
convenience, and that's what today's chain drugstores are after in
their push to increase market share.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstores not so long ago sought locations in strip malls,
separated maybe by a dry cleaner and a little photo shop from a
major supermarket. But today, with the supermarkets opening their
own pharmacies and the drugstores doing film processing, that's not
the kind of competition anybody wants. Plus, customers couldn't
always find convenient parking spots in the strip malls.
</P>
<P>
   So the chains are striking out on their own. Generally, they
want to replace their old stores with new ones at high-traffic,
corner locations with ample parking and room for that ultimate in
convenience items, a drive-through pharmacy, said Rolland Jones, a
local commercial real estate broker who has looked for sites for
major chains.
</P>
<P>
   In the financial short run, drive-through pharmacies make no
sense. They allow a customer to use only the most expensive part of
the drugstore business while avoiding the higher-margin temptations
inside.
</P>
<P>
   But in the long run, drugstores see the drive-throughs as just
one more ploy to make loyal customers out of fickle shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're willing to believe that people aren't going to do that
(the drive-through) every time,'' said Bert Hambleton Jr., an
Issaquah-based retail consultant. ``The idea is get you locked into
coming to that location. When you have time, you'll come into the
store.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
