</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE PEDRO AND RAMON SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Allman Brothers. Brothers Karamazov. Sutter
Brothers. Wright Brothers. Smothers Brothers. Hendricks Brothers.
Righteous Brothers. Flying Burrito Brothers. Doobie Brothers. Smith
Brothers. Everly Brothers. Baldwin Brothers. Brothers Gibb.
Menendez Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Martinez Brothers _ Pedro and Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez officially joined the Boston baseball family
Thursday, signing a contract that will reunite him with his younger
brother, Pedro. The Martinez Brothers pitched together with the
Dodgers for the entire 1993 season and should comprise 40 percent
of Jimy Williams's starting rotation when Ramon returns from
shoulder surgery sometime this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers on the Red Sox. Sweet.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a first for the Sox. Baby Boomer fans remember 1969
and 1970 when Tony and Billy Conigliaro patrolled the outfield for
the Red Sox. It was an interesting time. Reggie Smith and Carl
Yastrzemski were the other two Boston outfielders and they hated
the Conigliaros. It was a daily soap opera with Yaz and Reggie
ripping Tony and Billy.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years earlier, Rick and Wes Ferrell played three seasons
together with the Sox. They were battery brothers. Rick was a Hall
of Fame catcher and Wes won 25 games in 1935 and 20 more in '36.
The Ferrells would be the Sox' best brother tandem.
</P>
<P>
   And now we have Pedro and Ramon, a former Cy Young winner
(Pedro) and his big brother who won 20 games for the Dodgers in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have made a considerable investment in Ramon. It is
believed they'll pay him $2 million this year and $5 million next
year even though there's no guarantee he'll come back from last
June's shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   This may not be money well spent. Maybe the Ramon dough will go
into that giant shredder that swallowed the contracts of Robinson
Checo and Butch Henry. But the Sox are to be applauded for trying.
It's not our money and if Ramon returns to form, this brother combo
is going to be fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it Red Sox fans: Pedro and Ramon could be the
Dominican Deans. When the St. Louis Cardinals beat the Detroit
Tigers in the 1934 World Series, all four games were won by the
Brothers Dean. Old Diz won Game 1 and Game 7, and brother Paul won
Game 3 and Game 6. Now close your eyes and try to imagine Pedro and
Ramon winning all four games of the 2000 World Series for the
Boston Red Sox. Heady stuff, no?
</P>
<P>
   Ramon is four years older than Pedro. Ramon says when they were
kids, he and youngest brother, Jesus, would take on middle brothers
Pedro and Nelson. The competition extended to the major league
level when Pedro pitched for the Expos while Ramon hurled for the
Dodgers. They faced one another once in a big league game with
Ramon winning, 2-1, even though Pedro went the route and struck out
13. They also sqared off once in a spring training game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struck him out the first time I faced him,'' said Ramon. ``I
hit a ground ball to short off him. After that, I didn't hit him.
He struck me out three times. In spring training once I got up and
pointed to the fence. I called a home run. He didn't know what to
think. Then I put down a perfect bunt. In my second at-bat, I got a
base hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers are excited about being teammates. Wearing Dennis
Eckersley's old No. 43 (Ramon wore 48 with the Dodgers, but that
belongs to Sox coach Dave Jauss), Ramon threw 40 pitches Thursday
morning. He will work out with the Sox Friday, return to the
Dominican Republic until March 22, then come back to Fort Myers and
work there until he's ready to join the Red Sox. Boston general
manager Dan Duquette said he expects Ramon to help the Sox this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro's only making $12.5 million per year. Living together
would allow them to split the utility bills. Will Ramon crash at
Pedro's pad when he reports to Boston?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I have a wife and two children,'' said Ramon, a handsome
man with an easy smile. ``It's different when you have a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro and I talked about a lot of things,'' he said. ``He
pitched in the American League last year and he's got to help me
with scouting reports. I can learn a lot from him. We're going to
help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro and Ramon. The Brothers Martinez. The Dominican Deans.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good story. It makes the Red Sox less boring. And maybe
more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
