<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-BUSINESS-840&AMP;ADD     03-11 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-BUSINESS-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT BANKS WALK A TIGHTROPE IN ASIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Investment banks have always struggled to reconcile
their roles as tough-minded analysts and smooth-talking
salespeople. Nowhere is this truer than in Asia, where the lines
between government and business can be blurry and the opportunities
to offend both are legion.
</P>
<P>
   The regional division of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. has become the
latest to stumble in this minefield. The investment firm recently
felt obliged to apologize to Thailand after one of its reports
drove down the shares of the nation's largest bank and angered the
finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us at Goldman Sachs deeply regret the controversial
media attention that our `Market Flash' dated February 8th
subsequently generated in the Thai press,'' said the president of
Goldman Sachs Asia, Philip Murphy, in a letter last month to
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda.
</P>
<P>
   In that report to clients, Goldman's chief Asian banking
analyst, Roy Ramos, said that Tarrin viewed Bangkok Bank as the
``biggest risk factor in Thailand's banking system.'' After Tarrin
denied saying that, Ramos conceded that the characterization was
his own.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of its competitors, Goldman has hastened to make
amends, rather than risk losing business from either the government
or private companies, which are loath to use a bank that is in
disfavor.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene K. Galbraith, former head of research at ABN Amro in Hong
Kong, remarked, ``Since the nexus of government and business is so
much closer in Asia than in Europe or the U.S., the consequences of
offending the government are much greater.''
</P>
<P>
   While officials can be thin-skinned in any Asian country,
bankers feel this most acutely in dealings with China. Almost every
major firm here can tell of a chill wind from Beijing after they
published reports critical of the economy or of politically
connected companies.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most prominent examples, Morgan Stanley ran afoul
of Beijing when the firm's chief strategist, Barton M. Biggs,
advised clients in October 1997 to steer clear of the Hong Kong
stock market. (He had unkind words for some other Asian markets,
too.)
</P>
<P>
   The report outraged Wang Qishan, who was then chairman of the
China Construction Bank, which was co-managing the sale of shares
in China Telecom. Wang is now the executive vice governor of
Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Shandong International Power Development, a
government-controlled company, dismissed Morgan Stanley as its
investment banker. A spokesman for the investment bank said he
doubted that there was a direct link between the Biggs report and
the bank's action, though he confirmed China's hard feelings.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the head of China research at HSBC Holdings
resigned after clashing with his superiors over his forecast for
economic growth in China in 1999. The researcher, Joe Zhang, had
projected that China's gross domestic product would grow only 3
percent this year. Recent Chinese growth has approached 10 percent
in some years, and this year's official projection is for 7 percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The subdued forecast angered officials in Beijing, who expressed
their objections to HSBC's group chairman, John Bond, according to
two executives at the banking group. When Zhang refused to endorse
a more optimistic outlook, these people said, he was forced out. At
the time, HSBC's investment banking unit was helping to underwrite
a $1 billion bond issue by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   HSBC has declined to discuss Zhang's departure. But in an
interview late last month, the group chief executive, Keith R.
Whitson, said: ``We are in 79 countries around the world. By
definition, that means we are a guest in 78. And we believe in
behaving as guests should behave.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a gentlemanly approach comes more easily to commercial
banks like HSBC than to investment banking firms like Goldman. As
lenders of capital rather than wooers and deal financiers, they
rely less on their research to market themselves. Goldman, by
contrast, uses star analysts like Ramos to lure clients.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, who joined Goldman in 1984, was ranked as the No. 1
banking analyst in Asia by Asia Money magazine in 1998. A
soft-spoken former executive at Mellon Bank, he enjoys easy access
to finance ministers.
</P>
<P>
   That access may have landed him in trouble. It was after a
meeting with Tarrin on Feb. 5 that Ramos issued a downbeat report
on Bangkok Bank. The remarks attributed to Tarrin scared investors,
and the bank's shares plunged 8.1 percent after the report became
public.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Goldman said Ramos' report had been scrutinized by
lawyers, compliance officers and the head of research before it was
released. But they said the reviewers would not generally question
a senior analyst on the substance of talks with a government
official.
</P>
<P>
   In Goldman's letter of apology, Murphy said Ramos admitted that
he had, in effect, put his words in Tarrin's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos was traveling in the United States and did not return a
telephone call. Murphy also did not respond to requests for
comment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Peter Rose, a Goldman spokesman in Hong Kong, said, ``We deeply
regret the mischaracterization.'' But he added, ``We were never
asked to, nor did we, alter our conclusions on the Thai banking
sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason Goldman is so eager to resolve this dispute is
that it may have inadvertently fed ammunition to Tarrin's critics.
Opposition leaders have seized on the report as grist for their
accusations that the government wants to sell Thailand's troubled
banks to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Parliament members are now considering whether to ask the
government to sever its relationship with Goldman. E. Gerald
Corrigan, a Goldman partner and former president of the Federal
Reserve Bank of New York, advises Tarrin. The firm also handled an
$850 million stock offering for the Thai Farmers Bank.
</P>
<P>
   If Goldman hopes to win more such assignments, it needs to
convince Thailand's business elite that it has not lost its friends
in high places.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
