<HEADER>
A6929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-FARMS-NYT &LR;      03-11 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-FARMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN FARM MINISTERS REACH AGREEMENT TO REDUCE SUBSIDES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ European farm ministers reached a broad
agreement Thursday to reduce the European Union's $45 billion
program for agricultural subsidies, a potentially important
breakthrough on one of Europe's most divisive political problems.
</P>
<P>
   If the agreement holds up, it could pave the way for European
heads of state to rebalance what is now a lop-sided budget that
channels billions of euros to countries like France and Spain.
European leaders are scheduled to hammer out that budget at a
meeting in Berlin on March 24 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also would allow the European Union to open its
membership to Central European nations like Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic. Those countries sell meat, grains and dairy
products at much lower prices than allowed in Western Europe, and
their admission to the European Union's free-trade zone would
either bankrupt the subsidy system or cause havoc with farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But it remained unclear Thursday whether the agreement would
hold together. For one thing, the proposed farm budget is about 7
billion euros, or $7.7 billion, higher than the overall limit that
European leaders had originally established. Beyond that, the deal
infuriated farmers in several countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the work remains unfinished,'' Jean Glavany, France's
agricultural minister, told reporters in Brussels Thursday. ``There
is a risk that the accord will founder on the financial aspects.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the deal marks a major breakthrough in what had
been a bitter deadlock. Germany, which is by far the biggest net
loser under the so-called Common Agricultural Program, has been
pushing for big cuts across the board. France, the biggest net
winner, had been fighting to retain as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations stalled two weeks ago, but German leaders revived
efforts by offering an unexpectedly tame compromise. Thursday's
deal, which came after an 18-hour bargaining session in Brussels
among Europe's 15 farm ministers, is in some ways tougher than the
German compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the support prices for cereal grains would be
cut by 20 percent between the year 2000 and 2003. Beef prices would
be cut by 20 percent, while milk prices would be cut by 15 percent.
But in a concession to dairy farmers, milk prices and milk
production quotas would only start to be rolled back in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, the agreement remains a modest one that
would essentially freeze farm spending at current levels. Advocates
of more radical reform, like Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain,
said they were still not satisfied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1851EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
