<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6930 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV- &LR;      03-11 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICK FLEETWOOD SEEKS TEEN HELP IN `MR. MUSIC' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mr. Music'' isn't much of a movie, but it does point to a
pressing problem.
</P>
<P>
   Which is that a whole generation's rock music icons are a few
years older than their fans. And led, shall we say, accelerated
lives.
</P>
<P>
   So now they're creaky and a wee bit embarrassing, the more so
because they still insist on wearing T-shirts, leather pants and
ponytails.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these ancient rockers might want to consider an
overcoat, a wool cap, a thermos and a nice spot on a park bench.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Showtime's ``Mr. Music,'' premiering Sunday, Mick
Fleetwood of Fleetwood Mac has that weathered look. But at least he
seems capable of chuckling at his own state of affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, the cable movie is for teenagers. Fleetwood,
who is more of a presence than an actor, plays Simon Eckstal, head
of Tone Records.
</P>
<P>
   Tone Records is a label that supposedly peaked in the early
1970s and is now withering. Simon figures that a jolt of publicity
might attract a big-name band or two, and he has an idea. He picks
15-year-old Rob Tennant (Jonathan Tucker), practically at random,
and appoints him vice president for talent at Tone Records.
</P>
<P>
   Teen gets big job at record company. If most successful TV
really amounts to fantasy fulfillment, this movie ought to be a
magnet for the intended audience.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Mr. Music'' is promptly mired in a by-the-numbers formula.
Rob's enthusiasm wanes when he learns that he was hired solely to
generate publicity, but he finally eclipses the corruptive schemes
of grown-ups and saves the company. Hurrah.
</P>
<P>
   It's absolutely, totally predictable. But when you get to be
Fleetwood's age, surprises can be a strain.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Darklings,'' on the Fox Family Channel (also showing
Sunday), is targeted for nearly the same audience and itself is
hardly original. It makes better use of its formula, though. In
this instance, it's an adolescent variation of Alfred Hitchcock's
``Rear Window.''
</P>
<P>
   Infected with mononucleosis and confined to a bedroom at his
grandmother's small townhouse, 14-year-old C.J. Jackson (Ryan De
Boer) thinks he witnesses a murder through his window one night.
</P>
<P>
   The supposed killer is a former baseball star (Timothy Busfield)
who has just moved in across the street, and the apparent victim is
a town resident (Suzanne Somers).
</P>
<P>
   The ``supposed'' and ``apparent'' are because the investigating
cop (Martin Sheen) finds no evidence of a crime. In fact, the
victim materializes in fine fettle as C.J. and two young chums (Ben
Johnson and Meghan Ory) begin to pry into the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Darklings'' strains on the creepy front _ spiders, a rat,
a closeted corpse, an over-the-top performance and maniacal laugh
from Busfield _ and its efforts aren't wasted.
</P>
<P>
   The movie requires modest expectations. But it skips along
agreeably as a kind of nonthreatening thriller. Think ``Hardy
Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1854EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6931 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRYOZOAN-0312-COX     03-11 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRYOZOAN-0312-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE URGES SETTLEMENT IN FLORIDA DREDGING SUIT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The federal judge who has temporarily halted a U.S.
Corps of Engineers project to ``renourish'' an eroded south Florida
beach agreed Thursday to hear lawyers' arguments in the case next
week -- but appealed to them to save him the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Henry H. Kennedy set a hearing for Wednesday
on complaints that the South Beach project in Fort Pierce has
illegally endangered a group of obscure single-celled ocean
creatures known as bryozoans.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with an appeal that lawyers in the case settle the dispute
among themselves, he walked out of the courtroom, leaving them to
talk about the dispute and the marine bryozoans whose welfare has
blocked work on pumping sand onto the beach from offshore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're evaluating things. I really don't want to talk about
it,'' said Lawrence R. Liebesman, a Silver Springs, Md., lawyer
hired by St. Lucie County to represent its interests in what
initially was a dispute between the Corps of Engineers and marine
scientists and environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   The groups' lawsuit last week resulted in a temporary
restraining order by Kennedy, bringing the dredging to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs in the case are Judith Winston, a Martinsville, Va.,
biologist; North Beach resident Brian Killday, who works at Harbor
Branch Oceanographic Institution; the St. Lucie Audubon Society;
the Conservation Alliance of St. Lucie County; and the St. Lucie
Waterfront Council.
</P>
<P>
   They complained in the suit that the Corps of Engineers had
ignored concerns it was required to address the impact the $5.3
million project would have on several new bryozoan species
identified by Winston in sand near the spoil used to renourish a
section of South Beach. They say the creatures have never been
found anywhere else, although they appear to be related to other
bryozoans that have made important contributions to cancer
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether there's a way we can come up with a compromise that
would allow the project to go forward without endangering these
species remains to be seen,'' Eric R. Glitzenstein, the attorney
for Winston and the other plaintiffs, said following a brief
meeting with Liebesman and Justice Department lawyers representing
the corps.
</P>
<P>
   Before work was suspended, the project was being financed
jointly by St. Lucie County, the Corps of Engineers and the State
of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1854EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
