<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PASTA ANTI-DEFAMATION LEAGUE SPEAKS UP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Wednesday's Personals mention of a 1939 Life
magazine article asserting _ in a positive tone _ that  &UR; Joe &LR; 
 &UR; DiMaggio &LR;  preferred chow mein to spaghetti, pasta-defending
baseball fan  &UR; Jack Breibart &LR; , owner of the authoritative two-volume
``DiMaggio Albums,'' submits a number of citations:
</P>
<P>
   - A 1936 clipping from the New York World Telegram said, ``Joe
likes movies, but hasn't much use for books. He also likes
spaghetti.''
</P>
<P>
   - A 1938 clip from an unknown newspaper said DiMaggio ``goes
strong for spaghetti. Says his favorite dish is chippino (check)
which is an Italian concerto composed of cracked crab and spaghetti
sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   - According to the United Press in 1939, ``Joe likes movies and
spaghetti and hasn't much use for books.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no mention of whether he liked books &LR;  about &LR; 
spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY MATT GROENING HATES HOLLYWOOD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Matt Groening, &LR;  creator of ``The Simpsons'' and now
``Futurama,'' told Mother Jones magazine that working on the new
series ``has been by far the worst experience of my grown-up
life.'' He said it seemed to him typical of how people are treated
in Hollywood, ``but I thought I would have a bit more leeway since
I made Fox so much money with `The Simpsons.'''
</P>
<P>
   Groening said that ``any time I've been gracious, it's been seen
as a sign of weakness. And every time I've yelled back, I've been
treated with respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother Jones asked Groening what it was like working for
 &UR; Rupert Murdoch &LR; , and Groening said his boss had treated him
cordially. ``I think his politics are a little more complicated,''
said Groening of Murdoch. ``I think he likes power. If lefties were
in power, he'd be schmoozing with them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSUMING INTERESTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Dan Mankin &LR; , head clown of Make-A-Circus, self-proclaimed
``commander in chief of a vast arsenal of clowns ready to be
unleashed'' and planner of a 25 pie-throw salute for the circus'
25th anniversary, is upset by the notion of pie-throwers going to
jail. ``When pies are outlawed,'' he says, ``only outlaws will have
pies.''
</P>
<P>
   - The lipstick &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  wore for her  &UR; Barbara Walters &LR; 
interview was Glaze by Club Monaco, reports USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   - Shopping at a discount dented-can outlet, one delighted
customer came upon rock Cornish hens, wrapped up neat and tidy,
with the outside labeled ``Parts Missing.''
</P>
<P>
   - A sign in the window of Leather, Etc. on Folsom Street in San
Francisco advises: ``You will not find a friendlier adult
emporium.''  &UR; John Ferguson  &LR; noticed this while pressing the button
that allowed him to be admitted through the iron gate in front of
the front door.
</P>
<P>
   - All About You, a magazine for teenagers, reports that even
celebrities sometimes over-accessorize.
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut Butter &AMP; Company, a new restaurant in Manhattan, sells
13 kinds of peanut butter sandwiches _ about $5 each _ that use six
varieties of peanut butter, all fresh ground.
</P>
<P>
   - Tinky Winkyism is spreading: A concerned reader _ ``Have they
no shame?'' she writes _ forwards a page from L'Art de Vivre
catalog, picturing a $300 Steiff teddy bear in lavender.
</P>
<P>
   - Starbucks is thinking of adding breakfast to its pastry
offerings, reports Advertising Age, in order to compete with
McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   - Oberhofer Hand-Crafted Computers _ of Beverly Hills, not
surprisingly _ makes computer peripherals in hardwoods, ``to fill
the void of luxury products in the computer business.'' The
company's keyboards, flat panel monitors and mice, available
through Neiman Marcus, are intended as an alternative to ``gray,
beige, charcoal gray and putty,'' says  &UR; Dennis Oberhofer &LR; . ``There
are five colors of iMac. We scoff at that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Princess Beatrice &LR; , 10-year-old daughter of the  &UR; Duke  &LR; and
 &UR; Duchess of York &LR; , had her pocket picked on an outing with
schoolmates, and the British press reported _ to outraged response
_ that she was carrying the equivalent of $150 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a president who is accused of being a rapist, and yet
people go about their business. ... Forget Teflon. He's the iridium
president. He's like someone from another planet.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Katrina vanden Heuvel &LR; , editor of the Nation, in the New York
Observer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
