<HEADER>
A6942 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MAJOR-ZEMAN-2TAKES     03-11 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MAJOR-ZEMAN-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANGEROUS OR CAMP, PROPAGANDA GOES INTO RERUNS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
Peter S. Green is the East Europe correspondent of The
International Herald Tribune. 
 By PETER S. GREEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ Major Jan Zeman was a Czech Communist
Columbo, Peter Falk in immaculately pressed fatigues, a savvy
television cop whose tough questions and dogged detective work
unraveled the greatest mysteries of the Czechoslovak Socialist
Republic and always got the party's man.
</P>
<P>
   From 1970 to the mid-1980s, ``The 30 Cases of Major Zeman'' was
one of Czechoslovakia's greatest television hits, avidly followed
by party members and counter-revolutionaries alike.
</P>
<P>
   The premise was simple. Introduced in honor of the 30th
anniversary of Czechoslovakia's Communist police force, the show
took its plots from celebrated crimes, each reworked to turn party
members into heroes and the capitalists, kulaks (well-to-do farmers
who profited from the work of poorer peasants) and hippies into
enemies of socialism.
</P>
<P>
   When Vaclav Havel and the Velvet Revolution swept
Czechoslovakia's ossified Communist regime from power in 1989,
Major Zeman turned in his badge, and reruns of old American police
shows like ``Miami Vice'' and ``Hill Street Blues'' patrolled Czech
airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   But now Major Zeman has been recalled to active duty. The public
service broadcaster Czech Television has decided to rebroadcast the
series sometime later this year, outraging some of the Communists'
real victims.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Czech Television's plans to show each episode alongside
a documentary telling the real story behind it, the victims fear
that reinstating ``Major Zeman'' will whitewash the crimes of
communism.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Confederation of Political Prisoners say they and
others like them were described as criminals in the show, and
events were distorted. Their fear is that if people are misinformed
about the events _ again _ they will never understand what really
happened.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the organization, who spent 10 years in Communist
prisons and the uranium mines as an enemy of the working class,
said he did not set much store by the idea that the documentaries
would rob ``Major Zeman'' of its power. For one thing, after the
episodes are over, many viewers may turn off their television sets,
never watching the documentaries that set the record straight.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is acute because a decade after throwing out the
Communists, the Czechs remain deeply troubled by their past, yet
virtually silent. Efforts to try former Communist officials and
secret police officers have repeatedly been stymied by courts,
prosecutors and ambivalent government ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Three top Communists served short jail terms for oppressing
dissidents, but no senior officials were ever tried for inviting
the Soviet Army to lead the 1968 invasion that crushed the Prague
Spring Communist reform movement, and only late last year was the
first officer of the STB, the Communist secret police, convicted
for torturing a prisoner in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Last December the new interior minister, a longtime Communist
Party member, threatened to dismantle a special police unit that
had been slowly investigating Communist crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Many Czechs think, with some justification, that much of the
post-Communist elite owes its success to Communist-era old boy
networks. And a sense of national shame, because few Czechs dared
to resist the Communist regime while millions of Poles openly
backed Solidarity against Poland's Communist rulers, has left the
country uneasy about pursuing collaborators, but quick to denounce
anyone already publicly linked to the Communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   Banning the rebroadcast of ``Major Zeman,'' says Vladimir
Brabec, the actor who played the title role, would hardly help the
country come to terms with its past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like closing the door on something that the entire
Czechoslovak society went through,'' he said. ``We tend to want to
improve the past, but we were that way. We collaborated. We
couldn't all emigrate abroad; some of us had to live here and raise
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   At Czech Television, Martin Bezouska, director of programming,
agrees and dismisses the arguments over ``Major Zeman'' as ``a
media storm in a glass of water.'' (Czechs don't drink much tea.)
</P>
<P>
   `The Communists had this idea that when they wanted to hush
things up, they erased them from textbooks, locked them in safes
and thought they could be made to be forgotten,'' said Bezouska.
``But if things are left locked up, ultimately they are glorified
and acquire a mystique.''
</P>
<P>
   He argues that the show's dramatic appeal _ and its propaganda
power _ will wither when it is broadcast and viewers compare it
with the sophisticated American and British police series of the
late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political prisoners should be glad we are demythologizing
the whole business,'' said Bezouska.
</P>
<P>
   But the show does attract a following. When ``Major Zeman'' was
shown last year on a station in neighboring Slovakia, Czechs near
the border taped episodes and the show became a minor cult hit,
fueled by a mixture of nostalgia and pure camp.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasting the documentaries alongside the show also gives
Czech Television an opportunity that its new 30-something
management team believes it needs to atone for the station's past
as a Communist mouthpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to say that television worked as a part of the
Communist regime and that many things created here were merely lies
to support the regime,'' said Bezouska, ``There's no denying that,
and we have to face this fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Communist-era series have been shown without much fuss.
``The Hospital at the Edge of Town,'' for instance, showed an
idyllic Czech hospital and a country doctor, filmed at a time when
Czechs were dying because the government refused to spend hard
currency on imported drugs and when heavy pollution had given the
country's industrial heartland one of the highest infant mortality
rates in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Lacina, 28, a producer working on the documentaries, says he
understands the political prisoners' concerns but he, too, believes
they are misjudging the show's appeal. ```Major Zeman' is more
comic than dangerous for me,'' he said, ``and I think that it will
make that same impression on everyone from 0 to 40.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not shooting counterpropaganda, but in a very British
way we are simply saying this is how it was,'' said Lacina.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the show 20 years later, it's clear that Zeman fever is
not about to sweep the country. The films are well shot, but much
of the acting is wooden, the dialogue forgettable and the plotting
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come to preach; I came to investigate,'' Zeman tells
a group of peasants who fear a reactionary is plotting to destroy
their new Communist cooperative in an episode about recalcitrant
kulaks in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In Zeman's world, priests betray beautiful women, rock musicians
are all drug addicts and part-time garbage collectors, and Zeman's
own teen-age daughter is successfully recruited to fight the
omnipresent class enemy.
</P>
<P>
   A teen-ager when the show was first broadcast, Anastazie
Kudrnova, now 34 and editor of the Czech edition of Cosmopolitan
magazine, said the political prisoners had little to fear from the
return of the show. ``Major Zeman'' probably did more to undermine
communism than to glorify it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a source revealing things about things you never heard
of on socialistic television,'' she explained. ``Drugs _ God, we
had no clue about them. When we watched this show, it made us more
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Czechs lead a much less sheltered life than under
communism and are unlikely to be taken in by the show's simplistic
propaganda. And even if the show does become a national cult
classic (the polyester lapels and bell-bottoms of the 70s are the
latest retro craze among Prague's teen-agers and 20-somethings),
says Ms. Kudrnova, it won't bring back communism.
</P>
<P>
   But others say that especially for young people who barely
remember the old days and who are unlikely to hang around watching
the documentaries, rebroadcasting ``Major Zeman'' will doubtless
create a too-pretty picture of communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``History taught at school is simply not absorbed as easily as
pictures,'' said Adela Gjuricova, a political scientist at Charles
University in Prague.
</P>
<P>
   Mejla Hlavsa, a rock guitarist whose band, Plastic People of the
Universe, is the villain in one of Zeman's last cases (and is
himself a one-time political prisoner), says he doesn't see any
real danger in broadcasting the show.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic People were portrayed in one episode as a
heroin-addicted, child-abusing gang of dissolute murderers who
hijacked a plane to West Germany, when in fact, all they wanted was
to be free to play their music and smoke a little marijuana. ``If
it contributed to the overthrow of communism, then that's good,''
Hlavsa says of the episode. ``But we had no ambition to overthrow
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hlavsa spent six months in jail for anti-Socialist agitation but
was released because unlike the rest of the band he hadn't gone to
college and was therefore a member of the working class.
</P>
<P>
   While the show may give viewers a distorted image of his band,
he says, he doesn't fear they will be duped into thinking communism
was all that great.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't really bother me,'' he said, ``because I think
there's a fair amount of intelligence out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
