<HEADER>
A6944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HASTERT-REPUBS-ART-72     03-11 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HASTERT-REPUBS-ART-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIVIDED PARTY GIVES NEW SPEAKER LITTLE ROOM TO MANEUVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(wg) 
 KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dennis Hastert of Illinois, the new speaker of the
House, may be trying to shed all comparisons with his mercurial
predecessor, Newt Gingrich. But he cannot avoid one of the central
problems that Gingrich faced in trying to run the House _ his party
appears hopelessly split, and with just a 10-vote majority, Hastert
has even less room to maneuver than Gingrich had.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert was overruled by party conservatives last week on aid to
help Central America rebuild from Hurricane Mitch. The party
conservatives held that foreign aid should be offset by cuts in
domestic programs, like food stamps. The week before, the speaker
signaled a compromise with moderates after they complained about
the proposed tax cut of 10-percent across the board, which had
become the party line, saying they wanted narrower tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert even seemed to be compromising with Democrats, who have
been pushing for an increase in the minimum wage. He suggested that
he did not have the power to stop it, only to shape the final
package.
</P>
<P>
   Two months into his accidental speakership _ he was chosen after
Robert Livingston of Louisiana renounced the post, admitting to
having had extramarital affairs _ Hastert has shown himself to be a
pragmatic and cautious politician, mindful that he needs to cement
the political center if he hopes to pass any legislation and keep
control with his whisker-thin majority.
</P>
<P>
   He is also more comfortable behind the scenes than on stage.
This has made it difficult for many outside of House Republicans to
get to know him and has raised the inevitable question: Are his
initial steps toward compromise the unintended result of an
inexperienced and tentative leader? Or are they the deliberate
strategy of a shrewd negotiator who knows how to piece together
legislation and will ultimately undercut Democratic accusations
that this is a do-nothing Congress?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too soon to say,'' said a Republican House member who
supports Hastert. The congressman said the new speaker was slowly
consolidating his power, vote by vote. ``Unlike Newt, who got up
every day and told us how to save the world, Denny is calmly trying
to stake out a position where 218 will agree on taxes, 218 will
agree on health care, 218 will agree on education. It's not
glamorous, but he is dealing with congressmen one on one.''
</P>
<P>
   Every day, Hastert must confront the cold reality that five of
his 222 Republicans could abandon him on a vote and, assuming
Democrats hold together, his party's legislative agenda could
collapse. Then the Republicans could lose control of the House.
They could lose the House anyway, of course, but some legislative
achievements would help gird against becoming forever known as the
party of impeachment, the party that could not govern.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes could not be higher. And the calculus _ to balance so
many competing interests and hold the majority _ must be precise.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this is bean counting, not vision,'' said Marshall
Wittmann, an analyst at the Heritage Foundation, a conservative
research group. ``Denny Hastert is meeting with everyone and going
over the schedule and counting heads. `How many do we have for this
rule? How do we calibrate this?' It's a green-eyeshade form of
legislating. You can't spare a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   This plays to Hastert's strength. His previous role in the
House, as deputy whip, was to take the temperature of his
colleagues on bills coming to the floor and round up votes by
applying pressure points to his colleagues and tinkering with the
bills to bring them into alignment. He used these skills most
notably on health care legislation in 1996, when Republicans got an
experiment in Medical Savings Accounts added to the
Kassebaum-Kennedy legislation allowing workers to keep their
health-care coverage if they change jobs. This took endless
meetings and a careful, member-by-member attention, a modus
operandi that Hastert has brought with him to the speaker's office.
</P>
<P>
   He has also brought with him the instincts of the coach he once
was. By design and temperament, he shuns the limelight, preferring
to promote his team, not himself. Toward this end, he has
reinvested authority in his committee chairmen, defusing and
decentralizing the power that Gingrich had amassed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He will restore the speakership to the traditional mold,''
said Rep. J.D. Hayworth, a conservative Republican from Arizona.
``That means using the tools of the institution which over time
have worked rather than try to reinvent the process. Using
committees. Spending time on the floor. Reaching out on the
telephone. Being accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has been accessible not only to members but to
fund-raisers. He has been hobnobbing with Republican donors across
the country and lobbyists in Washington in a coordinated attempt to
keep dollars flowing into the party's congressional campaign
committee, which plunged into debt in last year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   All of this private activity leaves little time for developing a
public persona, and Hastert remains relatively anonymous. This,
combined with his conciliatory style and his continued role as a
vote counter, has contributed to a perception that he has no
specific agenda of his own, beyond his oft-stated desire to make
the trains run on time. That, in turn, has raised some concerns
within the House that he has ceded big-picture decision-making and
pre-eminence on Capitol Hill to the Senate, particularly on tax and
budget matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is getting up to speed every day,'' said Rep. Thomas Ewing,
a fellow Illinois Republican and long-time friend of Hastert's from
their roommate days in the state Legislature. ``When you're working
with such a slim majority, you really have to keep some
flexibility. If he had a 20- or 30-vote majority and a little more
experience, he would probably have more definite ideas, but his
strength right now is not being hamstrung by feeling `it has to be
my way.'''
</P>
<P>
   He is operating with virtually no margin for error, a task
complicated by the rift in his party. The moderate Republicans in
the House _ 30 to 40 members, most of them from the Northeast _ are
flexing a new-felt power. It stems from their near-party-line vote
on Dec. 19 to impeach President Clinton, even though a majority of
constituents in their districts supported the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's next to impossible for leaders to go to the moderates and
say `You've got to cast a hard vote for me,''' said Wittmann of the
Heritage Foundation. ``They've already cast it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they need to assert their independence, and Hastert appears
sensitive to their needs. After they protested the 10-percent tax
cut as too steep and proposed alternatives, Hastert all but
conceded it would not fly.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson, the moderate Connecticut Republican who led
a dozen of her colleagues against the 10-percent tax cut, praised
him later. ``He's a good strategist,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hastert must satisfy the moderates while not antagonizing
the Southern-dominated conservative wing of his party. There is a
large reservoir of goodwill toward Hastert on both sides. But
privately, some conservatives say they are worried that he is
making tactical blunders by ceding conservative goals too quickly
and that his conciliatory instincts will give them little with
which to distinguish themselves from Democrats in next year's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need definitional bills that pass but that Clinton vetos so
we can say, `Here are the differences between us and Gore,''' said
one conservative, anticipating the presidential candidacy of Vice
President Al Gore. ``That was the beauty of the 10-percent cut. Now
Hastert has undermined it without even making an effort to sell
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing his own majority is fragile, Hastert has been diligently
seeking Democratic support for various bills on taxes, education
and missile defense, hoping that for every Republican vote he might
lose, he can gain a Democrat vote. ``Quite frankly,'' he has said,
``with the margin of votes that we have, we need to do as much
stuff as we can on a bipartisan basis.''
</P>
<P>
   But he cannot for a moment forget that the Democrats are
determined to retake the House and replace him with Democratic
leader Dick Gephardt. Despite Hastert's friendly public overtures _
he has met not just with Democratic leaders but with the various
Democratic factions _ the Democrats smell blood.
</P>
<P>
   And many in the House expect that as election-year politics come
into focus, the Democrats will decide that they have little to gain
by helping Hastert and the Republicans look good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
