<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTICE-STARR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE OFFICIAL SAYS DEPARTMENT NOT TRYING TO HAMPER STARR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder Jr. on Thursday
bluntly dismissed allegations that the Justice Department has begun
to examine Kenneth Starr's tactics solely to hamper the independent
counsel's investigation of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He was reacting to claims leveled by Robert J. Bittman, a former
top deputy to Starr who helped lead the investigation of Clinton's
unsuccessful efforts to conceal his extramarital affair with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Bittman, in a televised interview earlier this week, said he
believes the department's examination of Starr is intended to
distract the investigator as he continues to weigh whether Clinton
broke the law during the Lewinsky scandal and in a failed Arkansas
land deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as the closer we get to the president, and that the
investigation gets to the president, that they have all of a sudden
insisted on conducting a very intrusive investigation into the
heart of what we have been doing since the Lewinsky scandal broke
in January of 1998,'' Bittman said Wednesday on ABC's ``Good
Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Feb. 12 acquitted Clinton of House impeachment
charges following Starr's report that the president lied to a
federal grand jury and obstructed justice in his failed attempt to
keep his White House trysts with Lewinsky secret. Bittman left
Starr's office the week before the Senate vote to take a job with a
Richmond, Va., law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Holder disputed Bittman's allegations against the Justice
Department, saying Attorney General Janet Reno's motives for
examining Starr's conduct are not political. Rather, the attorney
general's inquiry is part of her legal obligation to examine
credible allegations of wrongdoing by an independent counsel, said
Holder, Reno's second in command.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me ... that we have a duty that's laid out pretty
clearly in the independent counsel statute to investigate matters,
or at least to consider whether or not to investigate matters that
have been raised with regard to the conduct of independent
counsels,'' Holder said. ``And I'll stand on the record of this
department as to whether or not we have the ability to do those
kinds of things. That should not be read as meaning that we are
conducting an investigation, but we certainly take the allegations
that we have received seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department disclosed last month that it was
examining whether Starr violated the agency's ethics rules in
several matters.
</P>
<P>
   Among the allegations brought against Starr is the claim that
the independent counsel's office in January 1998 offered Lewinsky
immunity from prosecution in return for her testimony without her
lawyer present. Department rules require that lawyers be on hand
when immunity deals are discussed.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department also is examining whether Starr himself
had improper contact with lawyers for Paula Jones, whose sexual
harassment lawsuit against Clinton led investigators to Lewinsky.
Starr, a veteran Supreme Court advocate, consulted with Jones'
lawyers before they successfully argued before the justices in 1997
that presidents may be sued while in office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who has denied any wrongdoing in his continuing
five-year-old investigation of the president, has met with Reno and
Holder to discuss how an examination of his office would be handled
and whether an outside attorney should be brought in to conduct the
inquiry. The attorney general has not reached a decision on these
matters, Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, an attorney general can dismiss an
independent counsel for ``good cause.'' That statutory provision
gives the attorney general the authority to examine an independent
counsel's conduct to determine if there is sufficient cause to fire
him, Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Senate's acquittal of the president, Starr could
still bring criminal charges against Clinton in the Lewinsky
matter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Starr is continuing to investigate whether the
president committed perjury when he told a jury he knew nothing
about a fraudulent loan that helped fund Whitewater, an Ozarks land
deal in which Clinton and his wife, Hillary, were partners. Starr's
investigation of that $300,000 federally backed Small Business
Administration loan has resulted in the 1996 fraud conviction of
Clinton's partners, Susan McDougal and her ex-husband James
McDougal, and former Arkansas Gov. Jim Guy Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
