<HEADER>
A6957 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-ONLINE-BOS &LR;      03-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-ONLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET WEIGHING IPO FOR ITS INTERNET BROKERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Seeking to capitalize on the explosive growth in
on-line investing, Fleet Financial Group Inc. said Thursday that it
was considering a public offering for its Internet brokerage,
Suretrade.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, which also said it was pondering joint venture
opportunities for Suretrade, could earn upwards of $600 million
from a sale, according to Bill Burnham, an on-line analyst at CS
First Boston in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, which acquired Suretrade last year when it paid $1.6
billion for its owner, discount stock brokerage Quick &AMP; Reilly
Group Inc., joins others looking to tap into investor enthusiasm
for on-line investment shops. Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc., a
New York investment bank and brokerage, and Toronto Dominion, a
Canadian bank, have been exploring ways to take their Web-based
brokerages public.
</P>
<P>
   Suretrade, launched in October 1997, is a no-frills,
fast-growing shop that caters to traders who buy and sell
securities on line frequently. The company offers top-notch
investment research, interactive charts, and, with a rock-bottom
charge of $7.95 per transaction of 5,000 shares, some of the lowest
prices around. Suretrade customers can also trade Treasury bills,
corporate bonds, and options.
</P>
<P>
   The price for such cheap trading is bare-bones service.
Suretrade has little customer service or technical support for
investors who need handholding and advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are unusual in that they have focused on the pure
Internet user and very active traders,'' Burnham said. ``It's a
very lean, no-frills service at a very low price.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic retail trading, in which ordinary investors buy and
sell securities via the Web, is one of the investment world's
fastest growing areas. By various estimates, Internet brokerages
now account for one quarter to one third of all stock trades made
by individual investors. Fleet said Suretrade, whose technical
offices are in Lincoln, R.I., would turn its first profit this
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 12 months, Suretrade's accounts and trading volume
have tripled. Now with 250,000 accounts, including 45,000 opened in
the last quarter, the company does 11,500 trades a day, and
accounts for 2.9 percent of the on-line brokerage market. The
company, with customer assets of $1.1 billion, will record revenue
of around $60 million this year, Burnham said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts speculate that Fleet, New England's largest
bank, wants to spin off Suretrade to focus more on Quick &AMP; Reilly,
the nation's third largest discount brokerage. While a Fleet
spokesman declined to say when Suretrade might be spun off,
analysts predicted a sale sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the way the market is, you'd want to take it public as
soon as possible,'' Burnham said, adding that he saw an offering in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Web-only brokerage stocks are hot. The biggest online-only
brokerage, E(asterisk)Trade, has seen its stock soar since going
public in 1996, and now has a market capitalization of around $6
billion. Next in line is Ameritrade, which issued shares in early
1997 and is now worth around $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   How much Fleet might earn from selling Suretrade will depend
upon how those two top brokerage stocks perform in coming months,
according to Burnham. On a day in which Wall Street hit new highs,
Fleet shares were lukewarm to the prospect of a sale, edging up
only 11/16 to close at 44 5/8 Thursday on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Suretrade has drawn most of its customers from outside Quick &AMP;
Reilly, which has its own Internet investing service, called Quick
&AMP; Reilly Internet. The average Suretrade customer is 34 years old,
has investable assets of $48,000, and trades 26 times a year,
compared to the average Quick &AMP; Reilly Internet customer, who is 43
years old, has investable assets of $168,000, and trades 21 times a
year, according to company data.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez Advisors Inc., an online brokerage consulting firm in
Concord, Mass., noted that Suretrade had customer margin debits _
interest-bearing loans that clients take out from Suretrade to
finance their stocktrading _ of $225 million. That hefty figure,
Gomez said, is a big income-earner for Suretrade, and could make
the firm ``an attractively priced play for any firm interested in
entering the online brokerage business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
