<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARRIE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE RAGE: CARRIE II': UNINSPIRED UPDATE, UNINTENTIONAL LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review) 
(bl) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody is expecting much from the sequel to ``Carrie.'' The only
star from the original 1976 film who's back for ``The Rage: Carrie
2'' is Amy Irving _ but, of course, the other major characters died
in that unfortunate conflagration at the prom. The director is new;
the screenwriter is new, and Stephen King, whose early novel was
the basis of the first film, is nowhere to be found. The film
itself is an uninspired update with video cameras, sexual
frankness, margaritas and tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel, the teen-age outcast who doesn't know she has
telekinetic powers, although things are always rattling and shaking
whenever she's upset, is played by Emily Bergl, who looks like a
cross between the young Ms. Irving and Christina Ricci. This is a
pretty interesting cross. Ms. Bergl is also appearing in New York
in the Roundabout Theater's new production of ``The Lion in
Winter,'' with Stockard Channing and Laurence Fishburne, so she
probably won't end up typecast.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Irving plays Sue Snell, her original character two decades
later, now a guidance counselor at Bates High School. Sue comes to
Rachel's emotional aid right after Rachel's best friend, Lisa,
jumps to her death from the school roof. Sue soon notices Rachel's
ability to make objects explode and fly _ just like Carrie! _ and
tries to help before the power gets out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Rachel is falling for the good-looking Jesse (Jason
London), who is a football player and part of the popular crowd,
but nice. And the other football players, the kind of guys who keep
a log of how many girls each of them has seduced, assigning points
according to difficulty and desirability, are planning a nasty
surprise for Rachel. Most of the entire student body of the high
school end up in one place, a party at a rich boy's house,
completely oblivious to what lies in store if Rachel gets really
upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rage'' is the kind of film that gets unintentional laughs.
They happen when Sue takes Rachel to the site of the burned-out old
high school, where nobody has even cleaned up the rubble after 20
years, and every time there's a flashback to the original movie,
mostly showing Sissy Spacek covered in blood.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, this is typical B-movie making. The actors are
attractive and do credible jobs, and in the tradition of the
original film, there's one really good scare at the end.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE RAGE: CARRIE 2'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Katt Shea; written by Rafael Moreu, based on the
characters created by Stephen King; director of photography, Donald
M. Morgan; edited by Richard Nord; music by Danny B. Harvey;
production designer, Peter Jamison; produced by Paul Monash;
released by United Artists. Running time: 97 minutes. ``The Rage:
Carrie 2'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It contains profanity, sexual situations, partial
nudity, decapitations, immolations, impalements and a lot of flying
glass.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Emily Bergl (Rachel Lang), Jason London (Jesse Ryan) and
Amy Irving (Sue Snell).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
