<SLUG> BC-AFL-SWEENEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR TO WAGE POLITICAL INFORMATION CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The AFL-CIO will spend $40 million over the next two
years on political campaigns aimed at raising public awareness of
such issues as Social Security funding, Medicare, and the minimum
wage, AFL-CIO president John Sweeney said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who spoke to reporters after a private meeting at the
Federal Reserve Board in Boston, said the union federation would
endorse any Democrat or moderate Republican who supports policies
that help working families.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the AFL-CIO money goes to political candidates or
parties,'' Sweeney said. ``It goes to educate and teach working
people how to be good consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials are hoping to register 2.8 million new voters by
the year 2000, and put some 2,000 union members on election ballots
in political races across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said the AFL-CIO, a federation of 79 unions, is
considering a proposal by moderate Republicans that would increase
the minimum wage by $1 over three years and adjust wages
automatically to changes in the cost of living. Democrats have
proposed increasing the minimum hourly wage by $1 over a two-year
period only.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment on his speech before the Federal Reserve,
Sweeney said it was prompted by ``a strong interest in monetary
policy and how it affects working families . . . Productivity is
up, chief executives' pay is up, but workers' wages are only
moderately improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, in a statement made earlier Thursday, also criticized
General Dynamics' proposed $1.4 billion acquisition of Newport News
Shipbuilding as a ``bad deal for the American shipbuilding industry
and for tens of thousands of high-skilled workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Newport News, Va., disclosed last month it had received an
unsolicited $38.50-a-share bid from Virginia-based General
Dynamics. A merger of the two firms would bring together the
industry's only two makers of nuclear-powered submarines. The new
company would control more than 70 percent of all US Naval spending
on ships and submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said the AFL-CIO had commissioned an economic study that
shows there would be a dramatic decline in competitiveness within
the markets for military and commercial ships if General Dynamics
acquires Newport News.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1920EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
