<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEMOCRATS SEEK TO ALTER BUSH TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CASTILLO  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Democratic leaders in the Texas Senate vowed
Thursday to fight any effort to reduce property taxes until the
Legislature addresses the needs of public schools, health care and
other areas affecting children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some to whom a tax cut is the number one priority,''
said Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, D-Austin, chairman of the Senate
Democratic Caucus. ``We say that's approaching things backwards.
Let's take care of the needs of our kids first and then talk about
a fair tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, attended by about a dozen Democrats, takes
dead aim at one of Republican Gov. George W. Bush's initiatives: a
$2 billion property tax cut to be funded from the state's $5.6
billion budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also supports sending an additional $1 billion to
local school districts to be used at their discretion, possibly for
teacher pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Democrats, who up to now have provided little
resistance to other items on the governor's agenda, said they are
ready to make a stand.
</P>
<P>
   They fear a $2 billion tax cut would eat up most of what is
going to be left from the surplus once lawmakers account for issues
such as increased enrollment in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Budget specialists have said about $3.3 billion will be needed
to keep up with the growth in schools and other items in the
budget, leaving $2.3 billion for discretionary spending.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats want to see a greater commitment to pay raises for
teachers, college scholarships and day-care programs before they
will support tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're becoming frustrated,'' Sen. John Whitmire, D-Houston,
said. ``We've been very cooperative with the leadership in the
Senate and the governor's office. But we cannot continue to allow
the leadership to not make children our highest priority.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bush spokesman said education was the governor's priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor believes we must first meet basic needs, dedicate
the lion's share of new money to public education and then send
money back to the taxpayers,'' said Scott McClellan, a Bush
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's events came just days before Sen. Teel Bivins,
R-Amarillo, is expected to introduce a school finance bill that is
reported to include pay raises for teachers and a property tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Greg Luna, D-San Antonio, said he understood the package
earmarks $1.5 billion for property tax relief and $1 billion for
teacher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, I don't find it acceptable,'' said Luna, the
vice chairman of the Senate Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said he was taken off guard by the criticism,
particularly after he shared aspects of the plan with his
Democratic colleagues to get their input.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply regret the organized, partisan response,'' he said.
``This is a work in progress that I still hope will receive
bipartisan support in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said he had no intention of filing the school-finance
plan until it had widespread support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
