<HEADER>
A6969 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-GEESE-BOS &LR;      03-11 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-GEESE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOW GOOSE OVERPOPULATION PITS PROTECTIONISTS, GOVERNMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Canada and the United States are priming to wage
all-out war on the migratory snow goose, arguing that an Arctic
ecological disaster may be in the offing unless hunters can shoot
half the species, or millions of birds, from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   But a coalition of anti-hunting groups in both countries, led by
the Humane Society of the US, is seeking to stop a controversial
spring hunt already under &UR;  &LR; way in the American South, one expected
to be extended to Canada next month as millions of the graceful
white waterfowl with black-tipped wings beat their way north. As
they return to their nesting grounds, the birds eat a swath through
the grain farmlands of the Midwest and Canadian prairies.
</P>
<P>
   The animal rights groups go to US District Court in Washington
Freiday for an injunction to block what they describe as
indiscriminate slaughter. A similar suit is being readied in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a disturbing effort on the part of the US and Canada
to destroy millions of birds,'' said Lesli Bisgould, a Toronto
lawyer representing Canadian animal rights activists and Dene
Indians angered by the hunt. ``We are talking about wildlife
destruction on a scale not seen in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   But many wildlife experts and environmental organizations
support the expanded hunt, arguing that an abundance of food and
reduced pressure from hunters has caused populations of snow geese
to explode to dangerous levels, with disastrous results for the
fragile Arctic coastal marshes where the birds hatch their goslings
in late spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers of snow geese have gone out of control,'' said
Bruce Batt, chief biologist with Ducks Unlimited, the world's
largest waterfowl conservation group. ``The birds, when they reach
the breeding grounds, are feeding voraciously, stripping vegetation
and destroying a fragile ecosystem at an alarming rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Batt is chairman of the Arctic Goose Habitat Working Group. That
international team of biologists and other scientists has been
studying the problem for years, and has concluded that only a
massive hunt over several years _ one meant to reduce the numbers
of snow geese in North America by half, or about 2.5 million birds
_ represents the best way to save a narrow strip of marshland that
runs for 1,200 miles along the westen edge of Hudson Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a serious and potentially catastrophic ongoing loss of
habitat in the Arctic, one that could affect a large variety of
species, not just snow geese,'' said Steve Wendt, chief for
migratory birds for the Canadian Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Audubon Society, hardly a pro-hunting organization, has
come to agree with that assessment. ``Audubon's concern goes beyond
that of the snow geese themselves to the other species that are
tied to this ecosystem,'' said Genevieve Thompson in a statement
from the Society endorsing the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Snow geese were nearly wiped out by over-hunting and habitat
destruction earlier in this century. But populations of the three
snow goose species _ the greater snow goose, the lesser snow goose,
and the Ross's goose _ have tripled since the 1960s, to more than 5
million birds.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason, according to wildlife specialists, is that a
dramatic post-World War II expansion of cropland in Louisiana,
Texas and northern Mexico _ winter home of the snow geese _ has in
effect created huge new feeding grounds on which the birds can
gorge on leftover rice, sorghum, corn and soybeans. So much
easily-obtained food is available that the geese are waxing fat,
sassy and physically far more capable of surviving the long
migration back north to Canadian nesting grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Millions more snow geese arriving back in the Arctic marshes
means millions more serrated beaks grubbing away at the
nutrient-loaded roots of grass and sedge, upon which the waterfowl
survive upon reaching the nesting grounds. But as the grasses are
gobbled away, the narrow strips of marsh along the northern shore
are eroding away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humans caused the problem by altering the birds' habitat, and
now it's up to humans to fix the problem,'' Batt said. ``Increased
hunting is the most efficent, most humane way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The spring migration of snow geese is just getting underway down
south.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Migratory Birds Convention between the US and Canada,
goose hunting is forbidden in both countries beginning March 10
until early fall to permit waterbirds safe passage back to breeding
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   But the US Interior Department last month gave approval to the
first spring hunt for snow geese across 28 states in the South and
Midwest in the hopes that hundreds of thousands more birds will be
bagged before making it back to the threatened shorelands. Canada
is readying to legalize a spring hunt beginning April 15, about the
time the snow geese start flocking north across the prairie
provinces and on to the Arctic.
</P>
<P>
   Even more controversial are new rules allowing snow goose
hunters to spread bait, use taped goose calls to trick unwary
birds, and to allow hunters to pack their shotguns with more
cartridges.
</P>
<P>
   Animal rights groups are aghast at the prospect, comparing the
hunt to wholesale slaughters of bird and mammal species undertaken
by commercial hunters in the 19th century. Aside from their
opposition to hunting, they claim that the massive cull represents
bad ecological practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy to think that taking a huge whack out of the
population of just one species will somehow correct an imbalance,''
said Liz White, director of the Toronto-based Animal Alliance of
Canada, one of the groups going to court to fight the hunt. ``All
it is going to do is carve out another hole in the ecosystem. Snow
geese have been doing just fine for millenia. It's arrogant for
humans to suggest we can save geese only by slaughtering geese.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
