<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6971 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNTIES-GROWTH     03-11 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTIES-GROWTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forsyth County to list of fast growing counties
 &HT;    By Lucy Soto
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Forsyth County, making perhaps the final step from
metro Atlanta's Northside outpost to booming suburb, was named the
nation's fastest-growing county in a report issued today by the
U.S. Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 2,426 U.S. counties, four of the top 10 fastest-growing
were in Georgia, two each were in Colorado and Texas, and one each
was in Nevada and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Forsyth has hit the top spot, although
it's made the fastest-growing list before. The county's population
soared 13 percent over the year, from 76,213 to 86,130. The ranking
comes as the county struggles to cope with the phenomenal growth.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, Paulding and Dawson counties ranked fourth, sixth and
seventh, respectively, in population growth from 1997 to 1998. And
while Henry and Paulding have made the Census' annual list of top
growers, this was Dawson's first time.
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth grew a staggering 95.4 percent from 1990 to 1998,
followed by Henry at 78.2 percent and Paulding at 76.7 percent,
according to the Census.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Forsyth's new residents have come from Fulton and other
metro counties. Mark Vitner, a vice president and economist with
First Union National Bank, says Forsyth's growth is an extension of
the tremendous development boom in north Fulton.
</P>
<P>
   People rushed to neighboring Forsyth County when land became
scarce and expensive in north Fulton. Highway access on Ga. 400 and
the opening of North Point Mall made the area attractive to
homebuyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had to travel all the way to Perimeter Mall or Lenox
to go shopping or work, then Forsyth would not be so attractive,''
Vitner said. ``Now there's North Point Mall and all sorts of office
parks, so that people can work and shop in the North Point area and
easily commute to and from Forsyth County.''
</P>
<P>
   Steady growth has been a fixture in the metro area for several
years and some of the larger counties continued to make big gains
over the year. Gwinnett, for example, added 21,677 people from 1997
to 1998. Cobb added 14,889 and Fulton 13,516.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that the Atlanta metropolitan area is the
second-fastest growing in the country after L.A.,'' said University
of Georgia demographer Doug Bachtel. ``So, it's really no
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was a bit of one for Larry Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmm, we knew we were growing fast, but I guess we didn't know
what the comparison would be,'' said Robertson, the soft-spoken
county manager in Dawson, the county just north of Forsyth
straddling the end of Ga. 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's people wanting to get up here to get larger
tracts of land, to get one to five acres. People that don't want to
be in the cramped subdivisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Quality of life is the name of the game. And while that might
mean different things to different people, Bachtel says most
newcomers talk about it in terms of schools, taxes and open space.
Ironically, those are the first things to change when growth comes
to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge part of this growth is new people moving in,'' Bachtel
said. ``Those people have kids in school, and they have dogs and
cars. They make this huge immediate impact on a community, and they
sort of begin to suck up services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local officials are always playing catch up because they
can't make ends meet on just residential property taxes,'' he said.
``Then, all these new people move in and say they don't want any
industrial development because they want to keep the county as they
found it.''
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy of development in Forsyth is pretty clear outside
Pappy Red's BBQ on Ga. 20 near Ga. 400. Cars slow to a crawl every
morning and evening. And just try making a ``quick'' run to the
nearby Wal-Mart or the Home Depot on a Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing pretty good, but nothing like we used to,'' said
Chip Garner, who opened up his restaurant six years ago. ``Five
restaurants opened up near us. We were the only one there for a
while. ... What's happening is a good thing I guess. I'm not sure
if the county has planned for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth County commissioners hope not to make the top 10 list
again next year. They imposed a 16-month rezoning moratorium in
November because the county was overwhelmed with traffic and was
hitting its sewer capacity limit. Still, they already have enough
property being developed to keep workers busy well past that
deadline. County officials also are exempting some projects from
the moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth hopes to complete a 10-million-gallon-a-day water
treatment plant next year, and is trying to persuade the state to
give it a permit to build a wastewater treatment plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that being at the top puts a lot of pressure on
our infrastructure,'' said County Manager Stevie Mills, who was
born and raised in Forsyth. ``We have virtually no sewer capacity
to offer for commercial and industrial growth, much less the
residential that's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Soto writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
