<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6976 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTAM-CLINTON-0312-C     03-11 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTAM-CLINTON-0312-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, CENTRAL AMERICAN LEADERS AGREE FOR MORE COOPERATION
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTIGUA, Guatemala _ Wrapping up the most extensive trip to
Central America by any U.S. president, Bill Clinton joined 13
leaders from seven countries here Thursday to adopt a regional
agreement for a future cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The nonbinding agreement sets out a series of principles related
to promoting free trade, restraining drug and human smuggling,
calling for equal treatment of all immigrants and promoting human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's four-day visit to Nicaragua, Honduras, El Salvador and
Guatemala -- viewing damage caused last October and dispensing tens
of millions of dollars in humanitarian aid -- highlighted the
transformation of the United States' role in the region.
</P>
<P>
   From the role of ``Big Brother'' and financier of militaristic
authoritarian regimes -- which resisted communist advances at the
expense of human rights -- Clinton said the United States was now
part of a ``new partnership'' with Central America based on shared
democratic values.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still face daunting challenges,'' Clinton said at the
beginning of the summit here in a converted 17th-Century monastery
in the old Guatemalan colonial capital in the Guatemalan highlands.
``But now we face them with a unique sense of solidarity and common
commitment to freedom, to democracy, to open markets and to meeting
the demands of our people for better schools, safer streets and
wider opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Clinton here were the presidents of Guatemala, El
Salvador, Nicaragua, Honduras, Costa Rica and the Dominican
Republic and the prime minister of Belize.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was committed to lowering trade barriers to
establish a free trade zone which eventually would encompass the
entire western hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has asked the U.S. Congress to reform the
Reagan-era Caribbean Basin Initiative, or CBI, to eliminate tariffs
on non-textile exports and textile exports using materials from the
United States assembled in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed by the administration as a critical tool for the
rebuilding of Central America, Caribbean countries already received
certain preferential trade privileges under the terms of the CBI.
Those countries have complained, however, that Mexico got an even
better deal under the provisions of the five-year-old North
American Free Trade Agreement, or NAFTA. The Caribbean countries
have been seeking new terms that would put them on parity with
Mexico. However, such a change was resisted by Congress during the
last congressional session.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the regional leaders he was committed to reforming
U.S. immigration policy to treat refugees from all countries
``equitably,'' while giving special attention to the needs of
countries that suffered most from Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is working on regulations to make it easier
for immigrants from Guatemala, El Salvador and Honduras to seek
permanent residency status. But Clinton said congressional action
probably will be needed to equalize the treatment of those refugees
with that of Nicaraguan refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the law provides more favorable treatment to
immigrants from Nicaragua and Honduras than from El Salvador and
Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States supports greater debt relief for
Central America. In their final communique, the leaders said debt
relief was critical _ particularly for Nicaragua and Honduras _ to
sustain development.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders muted their disappointment at Clinton's failure to
get swift congressional approval for $956 million in reconstruction
aid, freer access to U.S. markets and a suspension of the
deportation of illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   As he has in virtually every stop on this goodwill tour, Clinton
called for a ``common struggle against violence and drug
trafficking and drug abuse, to shared responsibility for the care
of our environment, with education of our children and for the
health of our people.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
