<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DROUGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DECLARES POTENTIAL FIRE EMERGENCY IN MUCH OF DRY TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As Gov. George W. Bush declared a potential
wildfire emergency in 167 of Texas' 254 counties Thursday,
Agriculture Commissioner Susan Combs said the persistent drought
may drive up to 15 percent of the state's agricultural producers
out of business this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agriculture, which is the second-largest industry in the
state, is truly in peril by drought,'' Combs said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference with Bush and Combs, state officials said
Texas' drought conditions currently are at the stage they were last
year in May and June. Bush said Texans need to conserve water,
reduce fire risks and prepare firefighting equipment for an
expected outbreak of wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drought has a head start on Texas this year,'' Bush said.
``All this adds up to a drought that could be as bad or worse than
the devastation we experienced last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Combs said the drought caused by the weather system known as La
Nina has combined with low commodity prices to deal a probably
fatal blow to even well-run agricultural businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Combs said Louisiana Agriculture &AMP; Forestry Commissioner Bob
Odom expects 15 percent of his state's producers to go out of
business this year, and she said she expects the Texas toll to be
between 10 percent and 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Combs said she is hearing anecdotal Texas stories about farmers
and ranchers who have been unable to renew bank loans to begin
their spring production. She said she also has heard that the
managers of Falcon and Amistad reservoirs likely will cut off
irrigation May 1 if a major rainfall does not occur.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton is in trouble, Combs said, as well as every crop in the
Lower Rio Grande Valley. Ranchers are in danger of losing what
little grass they have to wildfire, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he is asking President Clinton for an emergency
declaration for counties along and west of Interstate 35 and
Interstate 37 to help the state to position firefighting teams and
gear. A declaration would allow the state to apply for federal
matching funds that would pay for up to half of the costs of such
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that at present the state is spending $167,000 a week
on special wildfire teams.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hull, director of the Texas Forest Service, said last summer
the cost of fighting wildfires rose to $5 million a week.
</P>
<P>
   Hull said a big fear this year is that Texas may have difficulty
getting out-of-state help. He said drought was mostly localized
last year in Texas and along the Gulf Coast, with most of the
United States being wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the southwestern United States, where we received
90 percent of our out-of-state help, is in the same condition Texas
is,'' Hull said. ``This year, instead of having an abundance of
people we can bring in, we will be competing for resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull said that last year Texas brought in 5,000 firefighters
from other states, along with 193 air tankers and helicopters and
430 firetrucks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he also is writing all Texas mayors and water
suppliers, asking them to prepare water conservation plans and to
consider burning bans. He noted that the Legislature also is
considering a $25 million emergency appropriation bill that
includes $3.5 million to connect to community water supplies 20
small, at-risk water supply systems in the Lower Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Combs complained that drought disaster assistance for Texas
farmers that was approved last October is being held up by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture and probably will not reach producers
until June.
</P>
<P>
   Combs said she already is contacting neighboring states about
providing hay to Texas if a feeding emergency develops later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was asked whether he believes the state's drought
conditions have been caused by global warming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to pray for rain,'' Bush said. ``The science is still
out on issues like global warming. We need to gather enough data
that if there are any public policy decisions we base them on
science.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have criticized Bush, a likely contender for
the GOP presidential nomination, as not having done enough to stop
air pollution from grandfathered industrial plants. Pollution is
considered by many to be a cause of global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, a leading contender for the Democratic
presidential nomination, has said he believes ``global warming is a
real and serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
