<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKPLACE FUN IS THE NAME OF THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Steve Riley worked in strollers. Not exactly the spot
where Disney's famous ``magical moments'' are made.
</P>
<P>
   Wanna bet?
</P>
<P>
   Riley these days is a leadership and customer-service trainer.
He goes around the country giving seminars on the Disney way. In a
training session Wednesday, Riley told of post-visit correspondence
he received _ by name _ from visitors delighted with their
stroller-station moment.
</P>
<P>
   Disney World figures their typical theme park guest has 60
interactions a day with ``cast members,'' the only words the
organization uses for its employees. Any one of those encounters
can blow the magic built by the other 59.
</P>
<P>
   You might argue that a place selling fun and memories has an
easier customer-service challenge than a place peddling tires or
tomatoes. Riley urges you to think otherwise. The same customer
demands, the same customer emotions apply.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, brought to Kansas City by the Greater Kansas City Chamber
of Commerce, said an organization that earns customer-service stars
does so because its leaders and workers remember to see its
products or its services as the customers see them.
</P>
<P>
   He no longer shops at his most convenient grocery store, for
example, because the checkers never looked at him, never greeted
him, never did anything but scan his groceries and stick out their
hands for his money.
</P>
<P>
   One day, he simply decided his money wasn't going to pay their
salaries any more, and it certainly wasn't going to the manager or
organization who allowed their behavior to exist.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney strategy for delivering customer service starts with
hiring people who are either naturally people- and service-oriented
or trainable. It continues with classroom and on-the-job training
that sets clear guidelines, procedures and expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Then it cultivates an environment where rewards and recognition
flow to those who deserve it, and makes it clear that work is a
place where fun is expected _ not just for guests but for cast
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backstage'' in strollers, cast members had a non-stop party
going, Riley revealed. Their boom box was cranked. They celebrated
birthdays and milestones. They had fun. When they went through the
door to deal with guests, they found it easier to deal with even
the cranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to keep the cast members happy,'' Riley warned
attendees. ``If they're not happy, it spills out into their work,
and it affects your turnover.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney has strict rules about grooming, costuming and behavior
for cast members on the job. Yet, Riley said, there's an overlying
permission to be creative, to take individual ownership of their
jobs, to take certain risks in the name of good customer service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lead and get out of the way,'' Riley exhorted.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Disney folk, it didn't seem all that hokey to hear
Mary Poppins offering one secret to customer-service success:
</P>
<P>
   In every job that must be done, there is an element of fun.
</P>
<P>
   You find the fun and _ snap _ the job's a game.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, theme parks don't have sole claim to workplace fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
