</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEPHONE PROTOCOL REMAINS A PROBLEM AT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Once again I have failed to win the company's customer
satisfaction award, and I am doing my best to come to terms with
the possibility that it may never happen.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, prizes aren't the whole measure of a writing life.
Quickly, name if you can the Nobel laureate for literature in 1968.
You see what I mean?
</P>
<P>
   But it stings all the same. So I sought out a member of the
selection committee, hoping to learn the reason for this
career-long disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a purely stylistic issue,'' said the committee person.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean I've been splitting infinitives again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That, too. But the real problem is that you don't follow the
telephone protocol.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the phone rings, you just pick it up and say `Hello.' We
have it on tape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you telling me my phone is bugged?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but we do fairly regular spot-checks. A simple hello is
unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I supposed to say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd read your employee manual, it's all in there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me, though.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're supposed to greet the caller in an alert and cheerful
voice and give your name, the name of the company, then say
something ingratiating, like `Please be kind enough to tell me how
I may be of help.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never say such a thing _ not in a million years!''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, and that's why you come up short.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, one of the best newspaper men I ever knew, when his
phone rang he yanked the instrument off its hook and yelled `Go
ahead!' into the receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'll bet he didn't get very far either.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He did all right,'' I said. ``He was the publisher of that
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Missing out on the award was bad enough. But a few days after
that I couldn't even get in the building.
</P>
<P>
   To gain entrance at the paper's side door _ the one used by most
employees _ you hold a photo-ID badge up to a camera, and a guard
sitting at a desk somewhere else, watching a remote monitor,
presses a button to undo the lock.
</P>
<P>
   The ID badges were issued 15 years ago, maybe longer. I mislaid
mine the next week. What I have done since the new security system
was installed is to pause in the foyer, look up at the camera and
pray to be admitted on the strength of a good reputation and an
honest face.
</P>
<P>
   Probably because I am small, inoffensive and have been employed
here since before the age of powered flight, it has always worked.
Until this recent day, that is, when I stood peering up at the
camera, foolishly, for many long minutes, and nothing at all
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Finally I walked around to the main entrance, guarded by a live
person whom I happen to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get in,'' I told my uniformed friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you show your badge?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a badge. I showed my mug.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably didn't recognize you.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out the man operating the button was a new man. Or he
may even have been a temp.
</P>
<P>
   It goes to show you can work a lifetime at a place, but if you
can't produce your badge and haven't won any of the big prizes,
you're still just another face in the crowd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
