<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-FUNDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL BRADLEY OFFERS CONTRASTS WITH AL GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The latest national polls have Bill Bradley
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to have a nominee who can win,'' the former
Democratic senator from New Jersey said Wednesday in Kansas City.
``I think I can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid were Bradley's sentiments on whether Vice President
Al Gore, his rival for the Democratic presidential nomination,
could win. The latest polls suggest that Gore faces an uphill
struggle for the presidency, trailing potential GOP nominee George
W. Bush by about 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, considered a long shot for the nomination, much less
the presidency, contrasted himself to Gore in other ways during a
news conference at the Ritz-Carlton, Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   He described Gore as cautious and suggested that during
Bradley's own three terms as senator, he took on such issues as
race and international trade.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also described Gore as a Washington insider. The former
Rhodes Scholar said his resume was more varied because it included
stints as a professional basketball player, a writer, a speaker, a
politician and a businessman who had traveled the country the last
three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a life before I got into politics and a life after
I left the Senate'' in 1996, Bradley said. ``I'm like a lot of
Americans who go out every day and do their work and don't think of
the federal government. I think the vice president has spent most
of his life in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   He said other contrasts would emerge during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a native of Crystal City, Mo., was in Kansas City to
jump-start fund raising. By his own estimate, He must raise up to
$25 million to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   On other issues, Bradley said:
</P>
<P>
   - Social Security should be taken off-budget so that Americans
could get a truer accounting of federal spending. He said he was
``very skeptical'' about President Clinton's proposal to invest a
portion of Social Security funds in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   - He wanted more information before commenting on an apparent
security breach at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   - European nations should play a larger role in safeguarding
Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
