<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6991 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JONES-9WEST-MARKETPLA     03-11 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONES-9WEST-MARKETPLACE-1080(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER BORN OUT OF FRIENDSHIP, BUT NOT UNIVERSALLY APPRECIATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn., Pa., Fla.)  (rk) 
 By   MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jones Apparel Group Inc. and Nine West Group Inc., the two
fashion companies that plan to waltz down the aisle soon, have much
more in common than aiming to sell chic clothing and shoes to the
same high-spending career women.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Kimmel, the chairman of Jones Apparel, and Jerome Fisher,
the chairman of Nine West, are friends. And both have spent some of
the millions of dollars they have made from their companies on the
construction of large waterfront mansions in Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kimmel, 70, and Fisher, 67, built their giant companies
with the idea that if they could imitate the top fashion designers
but sell their apparel and footwear for less than designer prices,
they could woo business from middle- to upper-class women who have
money to spend but not enough for an Armani suit.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, though both men sold most of their companies to the
public in the early 1990s, in many respects they still run their
businesses as if they were privately held.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in similar insider deals that are not viewed
favorably by some investors, until recently both men owned a stake
in the buildings where each company had its corporate offices. In
that way, both chairmen were able to earn extra money in the form
of rental payments on top of their lucrative salaries and other
perquisites.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies say that the terms of the building leases were
fair and based on market rates. Jones Apparel has since bought the
building, in Bristol, Pa., and although Nine West moved to White
Plains, it continues to pay rent on the building in Stanford,
Conn., where Fisher has a stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any transaction between a company and its management will
raise scrutiny from some institutional shareholders,'' said Robert
Newbury, a deputy director for corporate governance services at the
Investor Responsibility Research Center in Washington. Even if the
terms are proved to be fair, he said, ``some shareholders will
still say this is an inappropriate relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the same investment banker at Merrill Lynch helped take
both companies public. The banker, Mark J. Schwartz, who left
Merrill Lynch a few years ago to start his own Wall Street firm,
Palladin Capital Group Inc., recently became a director on the
Jones Apparel board. And Schwartz's ties to Kimmel go deeper,
including a deal unrelated to Jones in which the two men created a
partnership that invested $10 million in an Illinois music company.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the planned merger, Schwartz stands to earn even more
money in two ways: Jones will pay his firm for advising the company
on the Nine West acquisition, and if the deal goes through,
Schwartz stands to get another job by becoming the chairman of Nine
West, which will be a subsidiary of Jones Apparel. Jones has
disclosed neither the fee it will pay his firm nor the salary it
plans to pay him.
</P>
<P>
   Securities law experts say that Schwartz's many roles create
possible conflicts of interest. John C. Coffee Jr., a securities
law professor at Columbia University, said the Jones Apparel board
would most likely want to get an opinion from its investment banker
_ in this case, Schwartz _ on whether the company was paying a fair
price for Nine West.
</P>
<P>
   But with Schwartz expected to become Nine West's chairman,
Coffee said, it is not clear that he could provide independent
advice. ``Becoming chairman is an offer that will affect his
judgment,'' Coffee said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Jones Apparel, Anita Britt, said she could not
immediately comment on whether the company planned to hire another
investment banker for an opinion on whether the price was fair.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies defend the proposed merger by saying that it
will make them stronger and allow them to dress women from top to
toe in Jones' popular clothing brands such as Jones New York and
Nine West's footwear lines like Easy Spirit. In short, the two
companies say, a merger will lift sales and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, however, have their doubts. Since the companies
announced their intentions on March 2, at least four lawsuits have
been filed on behalf of Nine West shareholders. The suits contend
that Nine West did not search widely for a buyer willing to make a
better offer and instead, simply settled cozily with Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, Jones offered to pay cash and stock that was then
worth about $900 million for Nine West and said it would assume the
shoe company's $500 million of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Nine West executives did not return calls asking for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The deal did not please Jones Apparel's shareholders either.
Shares of Jones fell 12.2 percent the day after the merger was
announced, to $22.75, causing the value of Jones' stock-and-cash
offer for Nine West to fall by about $50 million. The stock has
since recovered a bit, closing Thursday at $24 a share, down 50
cents. Nine West rose 18.75 cents, to $23.1875.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two businesses are entirely different,'' said Josephine
Esquivel, an apparel and footwear analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, who last week lowered her rating of Jones stock.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Esquivel says that unlike some companies, Jones Apparel and
Nine West do not have many duplicate expenses to cut for cost
savings when they merge. By Ms. Esquivel's estimates, the combined
earnings of the companies will decline by about 8 percent this year
and then begin rebounding the next year.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Jones Apparel nearly went bankrupt when it
misjudged another acquisition: The company bought the license for
the hot-selling Gloria Vanderbilt jeans just as they were losing
their mass appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But Kimmel is nothing but bullish about the purchase of Nine
West. ``Nine West meets all of our acquisition criteria,'' Kimmel
said in a statement last week. ``The addition of Nine West is an
excellent example of our stated strategy at Jones of identifying
new opportunities and building a dynamic market presence.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Jones Apparel said the company would make no
further comments on the Nine West acquisition until it files more
information with securities regulators in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For Nine West shareholders, one thing is clear. Any investor who
bought the shoe company's shares when it went public in 1993 and
held them until today has received almost no return. At $23.1875,
Nine West's stock is little changed from $22 a share that investors
paid when the shares began to trade. In those six years, the value
of Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index nearly tripled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though Nine West shares reached a high of $57 in October 1996,
that was before the company misjudged some fashion trends, ran into
trouble with federal regulators over its reporting and pricing
practices and began paying millions of dollars in interest on a
growing pile of debt.
</P>
<P>
   But as the stock price has fallen over the last two years, Nine
West's top two executives, Fisher and his longtime partner, Vincent
Camuto, the company's chief executive, each continued to be paid
more than $1 million a year in salary.
</P>
<P>
   Some Nine West shareholders may have noticed in the company's
public filings that its employment agreements with Fisher and
Camuto expired on Feb. 9, just a few weeks before Jones Apparel
made its bid. The company has not disclosed whether the agreements
were extended or whether the terms and salaries were changed.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the proposed merger, Kimmel has offered to let Fisher
stay on and work for the combined apparel-and-footwear company as a
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, and the two men become close associates at
Jones Apparel, they might continue to have things to talk over as
neighbors in Palm Beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
