<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6993 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KANSAS-MUSEUM-KAN &LR;      03-11 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSAS-MUSEUM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY PREPARES FOR OPENING OF NATURAL HISTORY MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAYS, Kan. _ Even if the roaring, 17-foot animatronic
tyrannosaur that lives under the four-story dome might not act like
it, the people at the new Sternberg Museum of Natural History are
glad to have you stop by.
</P>
<P>
   They hope you'll stay a couple of hours on your way to Colorado,
grab a bite to eat and maybe even spend the night in what could
become the prehistoric capital of the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the museum's grand opening this weekend are gone,
but regular public hours begin Monday. Officials at Fort Hays State
University, which operates the museum, think at least 250,000
people will visit in its first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be very, very pleased to see the faces of young
and older folks in the museum when they see what we have,''
university President Edward Hammond said. ``They don't have
foggiest idea what's there. It will be a wonderful surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   What's there, in addition to the lifelike dinosaurs, is one of
the finest fossil collections in the country. The most famous
fossil is the ``fish within a fish,'' a large predatory fish that
died soon after ingesting a smaller fish. It was discovered in 1952
by George F. Sternberg, for whose family the museum is named.
</P>
<P>
   Only 1 percent or 2 percent of the collection of 3.75 million
artifacts is on display in the 100,000-square-foot building. About
one-third of the building's space is used for displays.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble Bookstore will operate the museum's gift shop,
and a full-service restaurant is to open in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was housed in cramped space on the Fort Hays
State campus until 1995, when the museum was closed to prepare for
the move. The new building, along Interstate 70, formerly housed a
recreation complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the outside, it doesn't look all that spectacular,''
museum Director Jerry Choate said. ``The dome, for some reason,
creates an illusion that it's not that big.''
</P>
<P>
   The university acquired the building for $1 in 1992 after the
former owner went bankrupt. Most of the money for remodeling came
from private contributions, including $1 million from Ross and
Marianna Beach of Hays. Some money came from federal and state
grants and state and local taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond had a vision for what he wanted the Sternberg to be, and
he didn't want to do the project until enough money had been raised
to match his expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't the least bit worried that this is not a traditional
thing for a university to be doing,'' Choate said. ``He could see
the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   What visitors will see is an attraction like few in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A cast of a woolly mammoth skeleton greets visitors at the
entrance, but the greatest treasures lie under the dome within a
walk-through diorama. The tour begins on the top level, with
visitors stepping into a setting designed to resemble western
Colorado 80 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Under a tall palm tree, a baby plant-eating dinosaur called a
hadrosaur champs on plants as an adult towers overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Around the first corner is the T-rex, which turns its neck and
roars at visitors. Pteranodons hang in the air over a short-necked
plesiosaur, a creature with flippers that looks like a sea lion
with a long, toothy snout.
</P>
<P>
   In the undersea portion lies a 14-foot xiphactinus, which is the
big fish in the ``fish within a fish'' fossil. Emerging from the
sea area, visitors see a lifelike replica of Sternberg himself,
brushing off the famous fossil.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a video presentation made from film of Sternberg
and his crew excavating the fossil in the chalk beds of Gove County
in western Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Also on display are several detailed fossils of the sea
creatures that inhabited prehistoric Kansas. Visitors can ask
questions of professors and graduate students as they work in an
operating fossil preparation laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Sternberg is a terrific museum,'' said Leonard
Krishtalka, director of the University of Kansas Natural History
Museum. ``Its collections...are world-class in terms of
representing much of the animal life that lived in Kansas in the
Cretaceous Period'' from 60 million to 90 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that this collection is in Hays can be attributed to
the Sternberg family.
</P>
<P>
   George Sternberg's father came to the area in 1866 when he was
stationed at Fort Harker, near Ellsworth. A fossil collector, he
passed along his passion to his three sons, who became renowned
fossil hunters themselves. Sternberg family findings are on display
in museums throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   George Sternberg established his headquarters at what was then
Kansas State Teachers College of Hays in 1927. He retired in 1961
and died in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 free tickets for museum tours this weekend were
distributed at a Dillon's supermarket in Hays. Other than invited
guests and public officials, no other visitors will get inside the
museum before Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we not done what we did with the Dillon's tickets, we
could easily have had 20,000 people waiting outside,'' Choate said.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond compared the excitement around town to 1996, when Fort
Hays State finished an undefeated men's basketball season by
winning the NCAA Division II championship.
</P>
<P>
   Hays, with a population of nearly 19,000, has long been a stop
for travelers along I-70. More than 300,000 people a year spend the
night in the city's motel rooms, according to the Hays Convention
and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are hoping the Sternberg museum makes them want to
stay around a little longer. Already, tour groups have shown
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's given us a whole new niche,'' said Jana Jordan, director
of the Hays visitors bureau. ``You just don't run into dinosaur
museums in the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Consultants hired by Fort Hays State think the museum will have
a $39 million annual economic impact on Hays. That's based on
250,000 visitors a year, a figure Hammond thinks is conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Within three years, he thinks annual visitation will reach
350,000, which would make the Sternberg the second-largest tourist
attraction in the state, based on 1997 figures supplied by the
state Department of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will come here to spend a couple of days or all day,
not just an evening or afternoon as they're traveling down I-70,''
Hammond said. ``It will be a site of destination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
