<SLUG> BC-CROWN-CENTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY'S CROWN CENTER UPDATING ITS LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Thirty-five years ago, the overseers of
Hallmark Cards Inc. looked at what was outside their offices and
saw a bleak sight _ Signboard Hill, a scattering of billboards
jutting out of a limestone outcropping, and not much more.
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't do, so they planted the seeds that would become
Crown Center, which today has stores, restaurants, movies,
theaters, hotels, offices, condominiums and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hallmark's redevelopment arm is ready to take the center to
the next level by spending $8 million over the next nine months to
jazz up its look and add more shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The most unusual addition could be the Crayola Cafe and Store,
which will serve sandwiches on brightly colored bread and dispense
drinks from crayon-shaped dispensers. Crayola is a wholly owned
subsidiary of Hallmark Cards.
</P>
<P>
   And the most eye-catching could be two colorful 30-foot-tall
towers to be built just inside a redesigned entryway and atrium.
One tower will reflect the heritage of Hallmark, the other that of
Crayola.
</P>
<P>
   The completion of the renovations in mid-November will dovetail
nicely with the Christmas retailing season and, more importantly,
the opening of Science City at Union Station.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hallmark officials had questioned plans to redevelop
Union Station as a retail center, they've fully embraced its use as
a science museum.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hall, president of the Hall Family Foundation, is
co-chairman of Union Station's private fund-raising campaign, and
the foundation is one of the project's two largest donors, along
with the Kauffman Foundation. Also, Hallmark Cards has contributed
money and volunteers to ensure the success of Science City.
</P>
<P>
   To solidify Crown Center's link to the museum, which is expected
to draw a million visitors its first year, an elevated walkway is
being built to join the two.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lucas, president of Crown Center Redevelopment Corp., said
other elements that would make the area a destination for in- and
out-of-towners were the refurbishment of the Liberty Memorial and
Museum and the flowering of the nearby Freight House District.
</P>
<P>
   Add new development on the Country Club Plaza and the
slow-to-progress proposed Power &AMP; Light District downtown, and the
whole area between the River Market and the Plaza could become a
draw for tourists from cities such as Wichita, Omaha and Des
Moines, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Power &AMP; Light District hasn't progressed as quickly
as planned, a co-developer may be named on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these things give Kansas City more top-of-mind awareness
for the so-called feeder markets,'' Lucas said. ``This isn't
Chicago, but it becomes more and more attractive for visitors from
the smaller cities in our region.''
</P>
<P>
   Other changes taking place at Crown Center include the addition
of Morton's, a Chicago steakhouse; a doubling in size of the toy
store Zoom; the expansion of Naturally Salon and Day Spa; and an
enlarged Hallmark Live, a showcase for Hallmark products.
</P>
<P>
   To make way for the Crayola Cafe and Store, Crown Center will
take over the space housing Saguaro Grill, the Limited, Franklin
Covey and Function Junction.
</P>
<P>
   Saguaro Grill will be closed, the Limited is pulling out of
Crown Center, Franklin Covey will move to a larger space on the
third level, and Function Junction closed last month because of a
bankruptcy reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   To make way for Zoom, Crown Center has closed the Museum
Collection store.
</P>
<P>
   Halls, Crown Center's upscale anchor store owned by Hallmark,
had taken over that space while the bigger Zoom lease was
negotiated, Lucas said. ``We don't like empty storefronts,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Crown Center, using the tremendous resources of its
parent company and Halls, fills empty spaces with unusual retail
ideas. If the ideas don't work out, Crown Center can go shopping
for new tenants while keeping the space occupied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
