<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6999 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUDENT-SLAYING-KAN &LR;      03-11 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-SLAYING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN NEIGHBORS APPALLED BY VIOLENT END TO AMY WATKINS' LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When she saw a man beating a woman at the St.
Louis airport last Christmas, 26-year-old Amy Watkins acted quickly
and without any apparent thought for her own safety.
</P>
<P>
   As the man screamed threats at her, Watkins led the woman into a
restroom and comforted her.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how she was: She tried to make a difference in
everyone's lives whether or not she knew them,'' said her aunt,
Judy Gehm of Roeland Park, Kan., who on Wednesday recounted the
story of the airport incident.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, a 1996 University of Kansas graduate, was killed Monday
night in New York after leaving a community center where she worked
with battered women.
</P>
<P>
   Police found Watkins with a 10-inch kitchen knife stuck in her
back and sacks of groceries surrounding her in the freezing
weather, about two blocks from her Brooklyn apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe robbery was the motive. They have no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins' death devastated her family and friends, who said her
life was about helping other people. Her goal was to be a champion
for battered women, and she had been working with victims of
domestic violence for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted to promote ways where society could end the
situation, rather than bandage it,'' said her friend and her former
teacher, Leslie Reynard, director of communications at the KU
School of Business in Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins was born in Chicago and raised in Topeka, Kan., said her
mother, Margy Tafoya of St. Louis. Watkins enrolled initially as an
art and design major at KU in 1990, but after volunteering at a
shelter and Community Living Opportunities in Lawrence, she changed
her major to social work.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Larry Watkins, also attended KU as a graduate
student and taught medieval history there while she was in school.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall semester of 1995, Watkins worked as an intern for
the Hope House for Battered Women in Independence, Mo. Her duties
included helping women in court and answering hotline calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very passionate person, easy-going and very
comfortable with people _ she drew them to her,'' said Mary Anne
Metheny, vice president of operations at Hope House.
</P>
<P>
   After Watkins graduated, she moved to Boston, where she
counseled mentally ill people, Reynard said. She applied to several
graduate schools for social work, including Hunter College in New
York, near her father, who now teaches at the Dominican Academy.
She also applied to Washington University in St. Louis, near her
mother. Watkins' parents divorced while she was at KU.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother, David Watkins, lives in Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   Reynard wrote letters of recommendation for Watkins and helped
her with essays.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very clear about what she wanted to do, and was
already doing it in her work,'' Reynard said. ``Hunter College
offered the policy studies, which is what she wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins was scheduled to receive her master's degree from Hunter
in June. As part of her studies, she spent more than 20 hours a
week as an intern for a community center in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins also worked with children and battered women in her
Brooklyn neighborhood, a heavily blighted area that is being
renovated. Almost 900 families live there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to bring an infusion of new life, energy and
hopefulness into the area, and Amy was very taken with that,'' said
Jack Doyle, director of community services.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Watkins led a vigil of 200 women to protest domestic
violence. Before Valentine's Day, she set up workshops with
teen-agers to discuss relationships that didn't involve verbal or
physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In her spare time, Watkins drew and painted, but her causes were
her hobbies and her life, friends said. In the days before her
death, she was planning a 50-foot community mural to be painted
this spring in the apartments where she worked.
</P>
<P>
   Her death is ``a tragedy,'' Metheny said. ``We as a society will
suffer because she is gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
