   CONGRESS-EDUC (Washington) _ The House and Senate handily
approved legislation today to give states and schools more
flexibility in how they spend $11 billion in Federal money, a vote
that gave each party a claim on being in tune with the public's
interest in education. But, after a week of partisan squabbling in
the Senate over amendments, a Democratic measure pushed by
President Clinton to authorize the hiring of 100,000 teachers to
reduce class sizes failed along party lines. In fact, Senate
Republicans pushed through an amendment that could jeopardize the
$1.2 billion already allocated to the program, a move that angered
Democrats. By Lizette Alvarez.
