A7014 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-EDUCATION-HN     03-11 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE, SENATE OK SCHOOL FLEXIBILITY PLANS  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House and Senate gave overwhelming approval
Thursday to rival bills that would give local school districts more
control over how they spend federal money.
</P>
<P>
   The House version contains no new funding for programs, but
would cut the red tape attached to $15 billion in federal education
money doled out to the states. Republicans say it fulfills their
pledge to free up more money for special needs programs because it
allows local authorities to spend it as they choose.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Senate version of the bill, which also is aimed at
improving student achievement by providing states with greater
flexibility to use federal dollars in more innovative ways,
includes $3 billion in new money for after school programs.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats had hoped to attach another $11 billion to the
measure to help pay for 100,000 new teachers sought by President
Clinton, but their amendment failed because of solid Republican
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans dealt another blow to the Clinton hiring plan by
voting over Democratic opposition to allow states to shift $1.2
billion earmarked last year for new teachers into special needs
programs if they choose.
</P>
<P>
   The latter amendment offered by Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., drew fire from the National Education Association,
which had lobbied forcefully for more money for new teachers and
special needs programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate is asking America's schools to make a false choice
between smaller class sizes and additional funding for special
education. Both are important priorities and both need additional
funding in order to best serve our students,'' said NEA President
Bob Chase. ``Forcing school districts to choose between smaller
class sizes and special education will only dilute the effort to
strengthen programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The separate House and Senate bills will be merged into one
later this month and could be on the president's desk by the time
Congress adjourns on March 26 for a two-week Easter recess.
</P>
<P>
   Passage in the House by a vote of 330-90 and in the Senate by
98-1 ended two weeks of political squabbling by Republicans and
Democrats as both parties sought to stake out positions on
education that they believe voters will warm to in next year's
presidential and congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   The bills would expand a pilot program in Texas and 11 other
states to the entire country, allowing state governments to grant
waivers of federal guidelines attached to some funding to encourage
greater student performance in reading, math and other skills.
</P>
<P>
   The money would have to be spent on the neediest of students,
but it could be used for a wide range of purposes, including hiring
new teachers to reduce class size, modernizing facilities,
experimenting with new programs and shifting dollars from one
program to another to help boost student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans and Democrats clashed over various
amendments, especially the measure calling for teacher-hiring
money, the underlying ``ed-flex'' bill drew bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides hailed it as a step forward in the effort to achieve
better student performance nationwide in grades kindergarten
through twelve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's action clearly puts progress ahead of partisanship,''
boasted House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to guarantee results, the bills contain provisions
calling for tougher accountability standards. It essentially adopts
procedures set up in the Texas pilot waiver program that requires
local districts to lay out specific objectives for shifting funds
or financing other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Once the waivers are granted, the districts are monitored
closely to ensure that the achievement results promised are indeed
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
