<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE IN IRELAND RENEWED AFTER ANTI-ABORTION MILITANTS OCCUPY
CLINIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ A group of anti-abortion militants, including
about 40 Americans, have reignited the highly emotional issue of
abortion in this overwhelmingly Roman Catholic country by forcing
their way into a Dublin family-planning office and occupying it for
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The occupation happened Saturday, and Thursday a judge extended
indefinitely an order prohibiting the militants, including the
leader of the American group, from picketing or trespassing at the
Irish Family Planning Association office in the center of the city,
which does not perform abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The militant groups were not represented in court, and the
prohibition, first granted on Monday, was ordered for an indefinite
period.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of the planning association, Tony O'Brien,
welcomed the decision of Judge Imelda Macken. The order includes
leaders of the Irish group, Youth Defense, which also had about 40
people in the office, and the Christian Defense Coalition, a
Washington-based group headed by the Rev. Patrick Mahony.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said the occupation of the office raised fears that
violence and killing by abortion opponents would spread to Ireland
from the United States. ``The involvement of extreme American
militants is probably the most sinister development in Ireland's
long-running abortion controversy,'' O'Brien said, ``given the
unfortunate history of the issue in America.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1992 ruling by Ireland's Supreme Court, abortion
is constitutionally permissible in cases of danger to a mother's
life. But there are no legal centers for abortions in Ireland and
no legal exception in cases of rape or incest.
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 Irish women go to Britain each year for abortions.
In a 1992 referendum, voters rejected a proposed revision of the
abortion law, some feeling the proposal was too liberal, some
saying it was too restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   The family-planning association may legally distribute
information on the availability of abortions in foreign countries,
but it is not allowed to advise women to undergo one.
</P>
<P>
   The incident led to scores of phone calls to radio talk shows.
Many callers defended the right of the intruders to enter the
clinic as a valid tactic to thwart the staff, whom they called
murderers.
</P>
<P>
   Others said, in effect, that the Americans should go home. Pat
Kenny, the moderator of the main morning talk show on national
radio, upbraided the leader of the American group, Mahony, a
Protestant evangelist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what we want to happen in Ireland,'' Kenny said.
``That's not the way we do our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny said many people feared that violent attacks, including
killings, by anti-abortion militants could spread from the United
States to Ireland. He noted reports that staff members at the
association office said they had been frightened, and had to lock
themselves in a back room during the incident.
</P>
<P>
   And that the intruders told callers to the office that no
officials would be allowed come to the phone because they were
murderers. Several of the intruders made videotapes of staff
members, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony told Kenny that he deplored violence by the small number
of Americans who have used it to advance their campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 1949EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
