<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLT-GUNS-ART-2TAKES-     03-11 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLT-GUNS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BESIEGED BY FALLING HANDGUN SALES AND LIABILITY SUITS, COLT FIGHTS
BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Fla, Ill., Va., W.Va., Maine, Belgium)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HARTFORD, Conn. _ For more than 150 years, the story of
Colt guns has been entwined with the history of America. Colt
sidearms were the weapon of choice among frontiersmen and outlaws,
Texas Rangers and Army rangers. Colt's M-16 is known to every
Vietnam veteran. The company is best known for the Colt .45 _ the
``Peacemaker'' that won the West and was celebrated in John Wayne
movies.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no peace these days at Colt's Manufacturing Co.,
which has suffered from a boom-and-bust history and is just now
rebounding from a 1994 bankruptcy. Handgun sales are falling. A
wave of liability lawsuits and legislation, similar to those
against the tobacco industry, are hitting Colt's and other gun
makers, threatening to put a severe dent in their business.
</P>
<P>
   In this difficult environment, Colt's new owners and new
managers are bringing fresh capital and ideas they say will reverse
the company's fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question is, how do we make money and do well given
the current legal environment?'' Donald Zilkha, who heads a
family-run investment firm that owns a majority of Colt's, said in
an interview in his New York office. ``Colt's is trying to be a
different animal.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Colt's hopes to capitalize on a global brand name
and diversify away from consumer handguns and toward military
small-arms sales. To blunt criticism and find new customers, it is
pushing forward on new technologies it says will make handguns
safer.
</P>
<P>
   But Colt executives say they are prepared to abandon the handgun
business entirely if it becomes impossible to make them profitably.
Colt's is backing its business plan with a heavy dose of hard-line
Washington and statehouse lobbying, intended to thwart courtroom
attacks and gain new financial support for research into handgun
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Colt's has brought in a new chief executive, Steven M. Sliwa, a
44-year-old former Silicon Valley aeronautical engineer who has
helped develop and take one company public. More recently, he
brought Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in Daytona Beach,
Fla., once financially troubled, onto sound footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We operate with a great brand name; we've got a great
tradition,'' Sliwa said in an interview in his office here. ``We
want to operate this company into the 21st century. We're trying to
modify, thrive and survive in a new environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Colt's must confront some hard realities. Domestic production of
consumer handguns, rifles and shotguns has fallen to 3.5 million in
1997, according to the most recent government data, from a high of
around 5 million a year in the mid-1990s. In 1994, 85 percent of
the company was bought by the Zilkha family of New York, once one
of Iraq's richest banking dynasties, for $12 million. But since
then, the company barely has eked out a profit _ just $2 million on
sales of $96 million in 1997, the most recent numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the gun industry, Colt's has stepped up its
spending for lawyers and lobbying. In February, in a verdict hailed
by gun-control advocates as breaking new ground in defining gun
makers' responsibilities, a federal jury in Brooklyn found Colt's
and other gun makers liable and negligent in three shootings _ two
fatal _ that involved the use of stolen weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Five cities, including Miami and Chicago, have sued gun
manufacturers and more lawsuits are expected _ all aimed at holding
the manufacturers at least partly responsible for the violence
caused by those who use their products.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, legislation was introduced this month in Congress to
toughen federal safety regulations on handguns. Military purchases
of small firearms, which represents about half of Colt's business,
is shrinking, as the number of soldiers continues to decline.
</P>
<P>
   So both Sliwa and Zilkha have been spending lots of time in
Washington, and the company has been writing large checks to
support industrywide efforts to counterattack anti-gun measures.
</P>
<P>
   Colt's is also supporting efforts led by the National Rifle
Association, one of the nation's most powerful interest groups, to
get bills introduced in state legislatures across the country to
prohibit municipalities from suing gun makers. Already, one such
measure has been passed in Georgia; similar ones are now being
considered by eight other state legislatures. In Congress, Rep. Bob
Barr, R-Ga, who is a member of the NRA's board, introduced federal
legislation on Tuesday to bar anti-gun lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Colt's strategy, though, is more multifaceted than other gun
makers'. The company is working, for example, to have lawmakers
push for government financing to develop a ``smart gun'' _ one that
can be fired only by its owner. That effort puts Colt's executives
at odds with many others in the industry, who are skeptical that
reliable technology can be developed.
</P>
<P>
   Colt's is pressing the Pentagon and Congress to maintain a
small-arms industrial base through contracts to gun makers, even as
it pitches its firearms to foreign governments. Profit margins on
gun sales to the Pentagon, while small, are steady. Once a weapon
is selected by the Pentagon, it often becomes the weapon of choice
for other nations willing to pay more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're writing a lot of checks, and I predict that we will be
writing a lot more,'' Sliwa said of these efforts. ``We want to win
the lawsuits or use politics to make them irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Colt's does not disclose how much it is spending on lobbying.
But the NRA and gun makers _ including Colt's _ spent more than $3
million between January 1997 and June 1998 to lobby Congress and
contributed roughly $4.3 million to federal candidates in the
1997-98 midterm elections. That was a 22 percent rise from the
previous midterm races, and easily eclipsed the $220,000 spent by
handgun control groups on Congressional lobbying and the $155,000
those groups gave to federal candidates in the same periods,
according to the Center for Responsive Politics, a Washington
nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   Colt's political strategy is intertwined with its business
agenda. By making the development of a smart gun its No. 1
priority, the company is in part trying to make itself less
vulnerable to lawsuits should its legislative actions fall short.
</P>
<P>
   Colt's has made two acquisitions beyond handguns. Late last
year, it bought Saco Defense of Maine, a maker of grenade launchers
and light military weapons, for an undisclosed price. It also
acquired for an undisclosed price Ultra-Light Arms, a small West
Virginia maker of expensive hunting rifles. These purchases came
after Colt's stumbled last summer trying to buy F.N. Herstal of
Belgium, the maker of Browning and Winchester firearms, when the
Belgian government blocked the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Colt's also has built legal firewalls to try to separate
potential liability from Colt's handgun business from its military
operations. The company says, it will leave the handgun business if
the political environment becomes too hostile.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they banned handguns, we'd still have a way to
survive,'' said Sliwa, who showed off his own gun during the
interview. ``We have adopted corporate strategies to make us less
dependent on the outcome of lawsuits. We want to win the lawsuits
and the political debate and conduct our business to survive no
matter what the outcome is. And we are doing everything to get
there as fast as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   At a company where the factory walls are plastered with
paintings of John Wayne and the Old West, Colt's view is that new
technology will be the ticket out of its current squeeze. More than
any other gun maker, Colt's is betting that developing a ``smart
gun'' will not only protect it from lawsuits and silence critics,
but will also open new markets among those who now hesitate to buy
a handgun out of fear of accidental shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Colt's says that it could produce a version of a smart gun for
law enforcement officers within two years and a commercial model
two years after that, if not sooner. With corporate resources slim,
it is trying to get federal money to support its research beyond a
$500,000 grant it already has received. Colt's estimates that it
will take as much as $40 million to develop a commercial smart gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount we've invested in our legal bills is more than what
we've invested in our smart-gun research,'' Sliwa said.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Ezell, executive director of the Institute for Research
on Small Arms in Alexandria, Va., said that ``Colt's is pretty
independent in the way it operates.''
</P>
<P>
   As one sign of Colt's independence, Zilkha came under criticism
when he contributed $2,000 to the 1998 campaign of Sen. Charles E.
Schumer, the New York Democrat, and $10,000 to the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee _ two of the gun industry's
least-favorite causes. This led several gun owners to set up World
Wide Web sites and call for a boycott of Colt's products.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Walker, president of the Center to Prevent Handgun
Violence, a Washington nonprofit group, said: ``Colt's was one of
the first companies to take seriously the lawsuits and potential
regulations. They were the first manufacturer to begin developing a
type of high-tech product that some call smart guns. They've been a
leader and more forward-looking with respect to how to change the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, in spite of all the work they are doing, we are concerned
that they, and others, still have a long ways to go in meeting
their corporate responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Zilkha says that if his strategy works, he can produce
compounded rates of return of 60 to 100 percent for the investor
group through a merger or recapitalization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-UN-BOS &LR;      03-11 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-UN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US DEBT TO UN PORTENDS TROUBLE, GROUP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BEARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States may lose its vote in the UN General Assembly
at year's end because the world's only superpower has refused to
relinquish its status as the body's biggest deadbeat, the head of
the independent United Nations Foundation said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in an increasingly bad situation with the United
Nations in New York. US credibility is declining significantly,''
Tim Wirth, a former US undersecretary of state and Democratic
senator from Colorado, said at a meeting of Globe editors.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, created last year by media billionaire Ted
Turner, is seeking to build grass-roots support to erase
Washington's $1 billion-plus debt in unpaid dues and assessments to
the world body.
</P>
<P>
   Wirth says an aggressive effort is needed to counter opposition
among some Republican lawmakers and to emphasize to Democrats and
the Clinton administration the urgency of payment. A sticking point
for years for many Republican lawmakers has been the world body's
funding for female reproductive programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard work. It's really pushing uphill,'' said Wirth,
acknowledging the lack of a US ambassador to the United Nations for
nearly a year and the administration's focus on issues such as
Kosovo and Chinese espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the United States barely retained its seat on the UN
General Assembly by making a token payment of some back dues, but
it must make a significantly greater payment by the end of the year
to maintain its voting status in the assembly, Wirth said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of 1996, the United States has been without a spot
on the UN budget committee, which is akin to a congressional
appropriations committee. Washington still has a permanent seat on
the 15-member Security Council, which makes most of the world
body's important day-by-day decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Washington owes nearly two-thirds of the total amount of dues in
arrears to the United Nations. In turn, the body has been unable to
pay some countries who have sent peacekeepers to world hotspots,
most notably Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the Brits are carrying us,'' Wirth said. ``A lot of
the best friends of the United States are getting very angry with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation will administer Turner's 10-year, $1 billion gift
to help carry out UN programs and tackle world problems, and it is
joining with business leaders and the United Nations Association to
push for payment of the UN debt. The issue has the support of all
former US presidents and secretaries of state, Wirth said, and the
group has hired former US representatives Vic Fazio and Vin Weber
to lobby their former colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The group also has conducted polls that show broad American
support for UN funding, which has gone toward peacekeeping,
eradication of infectious diseases, and children's issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy at a focus group said, `I really like the UN. It keeps
things at a simmer instead of a boil,' '' Wirth said. ``That's a
nice way of saying it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
