<SLUG> BC-UN-TIMOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR TO GET CHANCE TO VOTE ON INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Indonesia has agreed in principle for the first
time to allow the people of the former Portugese Colony of East
Timor to vote whether to become independent, according to UN
Secretary General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   The UN-brokered accord with Portugal ended more than two decades
of Indonesian refusal to grant the Timorese a say in their own
future. Annan said the UN would arrange a ``direct ballot'' that
would let more than 800,000 Timorese at home and abroad decide
whether to remain an autonomous province of Indonesia or set off on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia invaded East Timor in 1975 following Portugal's
withdrawal from its former colony. The bloody annexation of the
island territory, which has never been recognized by the United
Nations, resulted in the death of nearly 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The pact leaves many questions unanswered, which could
complicate matters down the road. For instance, there is no
agreement on the voting rules, the date for an election, or even on
whether the voting would take place on a single day.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said further talks between Portgual and Indonesia will
begin in New York on April 13. The two countries' foreign ministers
would probably arrive on April 22, hopefully to close the deal. His
chief negotiator, Jamsheed Marker of Pakistan, said the agreement
was a ``very, very large step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want autonomy, fine; if they want independence,
fine,'' Indonesian foreign minister Ali Alatas said following talks
with his Portuguese counterpart, Jaimie da Gama. ``We are relaxed.
We have no more fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally then we will know if it is true that 90 percent are
for for independence and only 10 (percent) for integration.''
</P>
<P>
   After prodding from Annan, Alatas also pledged to release the
celebrated Timorese independence rebel leader Xanana Gusmao from
house arrest once a final deal has been struck.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncertainty, observers said the vote marked an
important turning point following a year of UN-brokered autonomy
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a real breakthrough,'' said Joao Viegas
Carrascala, a leading Timorese independence politician. ``Now, it
is only a question of details.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrascala said there was no doubt that a vote would lead to
independence. And he said he was satisfied that the United Nations
can pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defining moment,'' added David Phillips, a political
analyst with Columbia University's International Conflict
Resolution Program, ``because it is an agreement on the principal
of one-man, one-vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the United Nations is to devise an election
that is conducted democratically but allows the Indonesians to
maintain that it does not constitute a formal referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said that he would send a UN team to the region to begin
exploring how to conduct such a vote. He said there are also plans
to have balloting for exiled Timorese in Australia, Portugal, the
US, Canada and Macao.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia first offered East Timor's 800,000 people a degree of
autonomy more than a year ago. It began negotiations with Portugal,
internationally recognized as East Timor's administrative power, in
December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would provide the Timorese with broad control over
their lives in most areas but defense and monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement comes less than a week after Indonesian Prime
Minister B.J. Haibibie voiced anxiety over the UN autonomy plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian leader is alarmed that the agreement would
encourage other Indonesian separatist groups to demand similar
agreements. Only two weeks ago, representatives of the province of
Iryan Jaya, on the eastern reaches of Indonesia, appealed to
Haibibie to grant it the same status as East Timor. Aceh and the
Mollucan islands, two smaller independence-minded regions, may
follow suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
