<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FERRIS-HUMANITIES12-C     03-11 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERRIS-HUMANITIES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ferris lends Southern touch to humanities
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Unlike Teddy Roosevelt with his big stick, Bill
Ferris drawls softly and carries a steel-string guitar. Since his
appointment to the chairmanship of the National Endowment for the
Humanities in 1997, William R. Ferris is the only government
official ever to distinguish himself by incorporating a solo
rendition of ``Be Bop a Lula'' into a Washington speech on public
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of dancing across this enormous state is in many ways
an appropriate image for the humanities,'' said Ferris, the keynote
speaker at Saturday's daylong celebration of the 25th anniversary
of the Texas Council for the Humanities. Held at the LBJ School of
Public Affairs (a fitting site, for it was the administration of
President Lyndon Johnson that provided the initiative for national
support of the humanities in 1965), the event is free and open to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   Ferris additionally will pay a visit today to the magnet program
at Johnston High School, reinforcing the NEH's commitment to public
education. From its sponsorship of summer teacher seminars to the
seed money it has provided for the documentaries of Ken Burns to
the preservation of historical papers, photos and documents that it
helps subsidize, the NEH has extended its cultural province from
the grass roots to the university archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to serve the American people, and as a folklorist I
believe in that very deeply,'' continued Ferris, who was the
founding director of the Center for the Study of Southern Culture
at the University of Mississippi, where he spent 18 years before
his NEH appointment. ``It's a good Texas tradition, with J. Frank
Dobie and the Lomaxes (the family of musical folklorists) all part
of that legacy that we're calling `Rediscovering America.' Looking
at the roots of your culture in Texas, the ranching communities,
the Hispanic and ethnic worlds, the blues and country music, the
rich tradition of your writers, that's all part of what we're
trying to do around the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in 1973, the Texas Council for the
Humanities has issued more than 1,500 grants, primarily from funds
provided by the NEH. In addition to speeches by Ferris and former
TCH executive director James F. Veninga _ from 3:30 to 5:30 p.m. at
the Bass Lecture Hall of the LBJ School of Public Affairs _ the
celebration will feature screenings from 9 a.m. until 3 p.m. (also
at Bass) of three award-winning documentaries that received TCH
grants: ``The Orphan Trains,'' ``Divided Highways: The Interstates
and the Transformation of American Life'' and ``The Death of Davy
Crockett.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an occasion for us to look at our own history, to take
stock of what it is we've achieved,'' said Richard T. Hull, who
succeeded Veninga.
</P>
<P>
   Since the national appointment of Ferris, a Southern populist as
well as an esteemed academic, there has been less criticism of the
endowment from some conservative Southern sectors, where the NEH
had earlier been stigmatized as the liberal-minded province of
ivory-tower elitists. Among the terms of Newt Gingrich's ``Contract
with America'' was an end to federal funding for the NEH and the
even more controversial National Endowment for the Arts. Shortly
after naming Ferris to the chair of the NEH _ an appointment that
passed without even a confirmation hearing _ President Clinton
tapped the Country Music Foundation's William Ivey, another
Southern folklorist, to head the NEA.
</P>
<P>
   Though the appointments proved politically expedient in
garnering Southern support, they sparked suspicion in some media
circles that civilized culture was going to seed. The New York
Times wondered whether Clinton was ``installing a sort of Southern
folklore Mafia inside America's cultural institutions,'' while
columnist George Will decried the ``depressing embrace of cultural
democracy,'' claiming that Ferris considered William Faulkner,
Elvis Presley and Goo-Goo Clusters candy equally venerable as
cultural icons. Since assuming his office, Ferris has been careful
to shake the hay from his cuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep the horses here, but they're well-bred horses,'' he
said with a laugh. ``I think those concerns have been totally
dispelled. We're working carefully with all of our traditional
institutions _ the Folger Shakespeare Library, the Newberry Library
in Chicago, the National Trust for Historical Preservation all just
received $600,000 challenge grants (which must be matched by grants
from the private sector) for their work. But we're also connecting
the agency to worlds that traditionally have not been a significant
part of it. We're reaching out to the American people, seeking to
make the humanities a part of every American's life.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is particularly acute in such a varied and rapidly
changing state as Texas, which must decide how support for the
humanities might best serve so many cultural constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful challenge,'' said Hull, formerly a philosophy
professor at the State University of New York in Buffalo. ``I have
a number of friends back East who think of Texas as hats and spurs,
and who would be amazed at East Texas or South Texas, or at what
Dallas and Houston and Fort Worth and Austin and San Antonio have
become in terms of urban centers.''
</P>
<P>
   The current NEH budget is $110 million (from a peak of $172
million in 1995), or 42 cents from each American taxpayer. Where
this country's entire governmental subsidy of the arts and
humanities is $3 per capita, Germany spends $39 per capita, France
$35. Deriving 90 percent of its budget from the NEH, the TCH has
seen its granting drop from $900,000 in 1989 to $300,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this says that we're still a young nation that has yet
to learn the value of its own culture,'' said Ferris. ``The fact
that we spend so little on our own rich heritage is a sad
commentary that we're trying to correct here. We've won the Cold
War and the economic battles, but we are forgetting the stories of
who we are. We are fighting for the souls of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that fight gives Ferris a chance to eat a little barbecue
and hear some music, so much the better. He long has been a
frequent visitor here, through his Austin connection with his
sister, Hester Magnuson (her novelist husband, Jim, is the director
of UT's Michener Center for Writers) and his academic ties to the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin is like my second home, and any excuse I have to come
there I jump on it,'' he said. ``I just love the university and the
city, and that whole culture of music and food is something I
consider rare and special.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
