<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SXSW Interactive returns to Internet roots
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Examining the origin of a successful event is
always amazing. The study makes it possible to catch a rare glimpse
of something as it churns, as life is breathed into a concept and
the idea grows into reality. To see the birth of genius.
</P>
<P>
   Take SXSW's Interactive Festival 1999. What _ on the surface _
appears to be the best, most organized Interactive festival to date
began as a cacophonous meeting of the minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first meeting was crazy; it was this totally unfocused,
nonlinear thing,'' says co-founder Hugh Forrest as he throws back
an iced coffee and runs his hand through his hair in recalled
frustration. ``When I think back on it, it really was reflective of
the Internet at the time. No one knew what the Web was going to be
and we sure didn't know what this festival was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The way everyone in that meeting saw it _ the group included
multimedia gurus Chipp Walters, Human Code's Lloyd Walker and the
late Dewey Winburne _ Austin's film scene was growing, as was this
multimedia thing. If they could just find a way to make these
burgeoning elements of Austin into a festival, they could help
their city grow and become an all-encompassing entertainment
metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   What came out of that blustery brain trust was the first spark
for the inaugural SXSW Film and Multimedia Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting SXSW F/M was discombobulated at best. Organizers
of the multimedia section of the conference were arguing in the
halls, panelists were confused and seeking information along with
their audiences and the trade show was bereft of trade. The only
truly successful part was a room called ``The Internet Theater.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were actually teaching people how to use the Internet,''
says Forrest, director of this year's festival. ``It was like `and
then you click here to see the page.' The funny thing is the room
was packed, standing room only.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to 1999. The SXSW film and multimedia festivals are
now separate conferences and Forrest and his staff are far from
``unfocused.'' In fact, 1999's SXSW Interactive Festival looks
leaner and meaner than ever.
</P>
<P>
   With panels like ``The Austin Interactive Scene'' and ``Click My
Lit: The Literate Web,'' the festival has laser-focused itself on
the Internet. SXSW Interactive will also have keynotes by muy
importante Internet leaders like Mark Cuban of the record-setting
IPO, Broadcast.com. All this adds up to the festival finally being
the informative, trend-setting event it set out to be when Forrest
and the rest of his think tank sat down to plan themselves a
celebration of Austin's technological cutting-edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really remember the early years,'' says Bob LeVitus,
author of a number of Macintosh books and the victim of a
lambasting at last year's ``Mac vs. Windows'' panel (``It wasn't a
good year for Macs,'' says LeVitus defensively). ``SXSW Multimedia
or whatever it's called this year always had these rough edges that
never got smoothed out. This year it actually looks like a real
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Forrest winces at the mention of this year finally being a
``real conference.'' But the evidence clearly supports LeVitus'
contention that SXSW Interactive didn't quite know what it was in
the beginning. After a well-attended, if unorganized, first year,
the founders kept the second year's Multimedia Fest centered on
CD-ROMs. To Hugh's delight, registration grew 300 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring they were on to something, in 1996 they moved the
conference to Austin Convention Center and kept the multimedia
focus with panels such as ``So you want to make a CD-ROM?'' and
``The Web is dead?'' Registration grew by only 5 percent. Not
keeping pace with the sonic speed of technology _ which was clearly
moving toward the Internet _ provided a bit of a wake up call.
</P>
<P>
   This epiphany led to a name change _ SXSW Multimedia/Interactive
_ and to a menu of panels more on the perceived fringe, plus a
smattering of Internet technology panels. Panels like ``The Future
of Sex,'' with UT cybersex guru Sandy Stone taking the audience
through a ``cyberorgasm,'' dominated the conference. Again, the the
public buzzed with low ratings for the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a progression, like they've been drawing tighter,''
says Nikol Lohr, creator of Disgruntledhousewife.com and former
designer of the now re-formed Texas Monthly site.
</P>
<P>
   One of those tightening the festival is Axel Ronsin, an eager
SXSW music volunteer who defected and joined Forrest last year.
Ronsin made it a life's goal to help turn around the festival. On
his way there, he wanted to build the trade show up and focus the
panels. He came up with three words he wanted the festival to
center on: Internet, (new) technology and games. The result _ a
tremendously improved trade show, but miserably attended gaming
panels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to SXSW Interactive very motivated and felt I could
really make it successful in my first year,'' says Ronsin. ``This
year, I was a lot more savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to SXSW Interactive Festival 1999, a conference
totally devoted to the Internet _ which, in hindsight, is what it
should have been from the moment organizers saw crowds packing in
to ogle over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Forrest says they are well on their way to booking a record
2,000 registrants, and digerati from media oracle Michael Wolff to
music maverick Phillip Glass have signed on to speak and perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I want people to feel like they're getting a huge
amount of information and making a lot of contacts,'' says Forrest.
``At its most basic level, SXSW Interactive is one big party. I'm
hoping to bring all these people together and next year they come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   SXSW INTERACTIVE BEST BETS
</P>
<P>
   With a stellar lineup of speakers and panels, it's hard to pick
the ``must-sees'' of SXSW Interactive '99. So here's our best shot.
All speeches and panels are at the Austin Convention Center:
Sunday, 10 a.m. _ Marc Cuban's keynote speech. This should be an
absolute hoot. After his Broadcast.com audio site set an IPO
record, he's the hottest celebrity in the Internet universe.
Sunday, 3:30 p.m. _ Building Women's Community Online for Fun and
Profit panel. Aliza Sherman (Cybergrrl), Heather Irwin (Estronet)
and Heidi Swanson (ChickClick) are a few of the stars that make up
this panel. The group is sure to touch on the growth market of
women on the Web and fulfill SXSW Interactive's ``spirited female''
quota. Monday, 1:30 p.m. _ ''Amazing Successes, Amazing Failures''
panel. It's always more interesting to hear a panel that talks
equally about the successes and failures of the hi-tech business.
Sit in on this one before you plan that Internet startup. Tuesday,
3:30 p.m. _ ''I Want My MP3'' panel. The new music technology for
the Web that has music industry execs quaking will be the topic of
discussion. It was moved to Tuesday to accommodate SXSW platinum
badge holders who also are here for the music festival. The music
guys will be the ones with looks of horror on their faces as
Michael Robertson (www.MP3.com) explains why they will soon be
obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
