<HEADLINE>
FROM A COFFIN MAKER, THE FINAL ACCESSORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Ark.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14)  
 (af)  
 By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Patrick J. Fant acknowledges that the designs on his
coffins may not be for everyone. But for some people, they are the
only way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Standing recently in a Houston mortuary, Fant gazed at one of
his favorites, which depicts a golf course with mountains in the
background. ``For a golfer, that's pretty much heaven right
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That design, ``Fairway to Heaven'' is one of 16 that Fant's
company, White Light of Dallas, sells to families that want to add
some originality to the business of sending loved ones to their
eternal rest.
</P>
<P>
   One model glimmers with faux stained glass; another portrays Our
Lady of Guadalupe with her hands folded in prayer. A third coffin
bears the design of an AIDS ribbon, and a fourth resembles a
package wrapped in brown paper, complete with a stamped message,
``Return to Sender.''
</P>
<P>
   Fant, who worked in the radio industry for 30 years, first as a
broadcaster and then as a general manager, said he came up with the
idea after noticing an advertisement for a coffin distributor. ``I
thought, `How odd, they're all so impersonal,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he was contemplating switching careers, and the
idea of personalizing funeral farewells appealed to him. So he
teamed up with a graphic designer in Houston to figure out the best
way to decorate the coffins. They developed a method for applying a
high-resolution photo-laminate mural to steel; a patent is pending.
</P>
<P>
   To keep his prices competitive, he starts with a white coffin
made of lower-end, 20-gauge steel. Then comes the laminating work.
Basically, he says, ``we're a van conversion company.''
</P>
<P>
   Fant has sold 30 caskets so far, about two-thirds of them to
funeral homes. He sells a casket that costs him about $1,000 at a
30 percent markup, he said. The caskets retail for under $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great concept,'' said Cynthia A. Jones, a vice
president at Mabrie Memorial Mortuary in Houston, which plans to
offer the caskets for sale. ``What better way of expressing a
person's life than through their going-home vehicle?''
</P>
<P>
   Fant believes that his coffins will appeal to the ``maturing Me
Generation and the free-thinking Gen X crowd'' looking for ways to
create an unforgettable final statement.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some potential customers might cringe at the
concept, fearing that it could trivialize a solemn occasion. But
Fant is betting that enough people will overcome such inhibitions
to make his business thrive _ people like June O'Donnell of Hot
Springs, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. O'Donnell and her husband, James, an Irish-American who was
dying of cancer, were shopping for a casket earlier this year when
Ginger, their 30-year-old daughter, spotted a Fant creation that
bore the green, white and orange bands of the Irish flag. She asked
her parents to take a look.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I had a difficult time with it,'' Mrs. O'Donnell
said. But O'Donnell, who had always wanted to retire to Ireland,
saw it as ``the only way to go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After his death in early February, his service was marked by
orange and green floral arrangements and the sounds of Irish music.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after her husband's death, she heard from friends about
the funeral of a car-wash owner who had been an avid fan of the
University of Arkansas Razorbacks: The 500 mourners demonstrated
their flair for the grand gesture by breaking into the school's
famous hog call. One thing led to another and Mrs. O'Donnell passed
along the concept of a Razorback coffin to Fant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had so much fun,'' Fant said. ``Either this is
totally crazy or we've come across a product whose time has come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
