<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, March 12 and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA-WEST (Seattle) _ Gonzaga shoots past a short-handed
Minnesota team in the first round of the NCAA West subregional at
KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Column from NCAA subregional at
KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-UW-CAREY (New Orleans) _ Washington's first-round NCAA
tournament hopes are in the hands of a freshman, point guard Senque
Carey.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Moore. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-THIEL-COLUMN (New Orleans) _ Column on Miami of Ohio,
generally a mystery to Westerners.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SONICS-BULLS _ The slumping Seattle SuperSonics play the
Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS-ROCKIES (Tucson, Ariz.) _ The Seattle Mariners at
spring training, playing the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NFL-HUSKIES (Seattle) _ Washington Husky hopefuls, led by
Brock Huard, work out for NFL scouts at Husky Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   By Clare Farnsworth. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGSTORE-RETAILERS (Seattle) _ From Syracuse to Seattle, the
nation's drugstore retailers are waging campaigns of individual
expansion and industry consolidation. Nearly every day brings a new
report of a drugstore giant gobbling up another regional chain.
Meanwhile, the nation's top four chains continue to pump out sales
increases so strong that last year Wall Street giddily bid up the
stock of No. 1 Walgreen by 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By Constance Sommer. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DEEP-END (Undated) _ The modern ``family-healing drama''
has become such a staple of feature and television movies that it's
hard for one to seem very fresh and original, or to move us in any
new way. And, as a literary property, Jacquelyn Mitchard's novel,
``The Deep End of the Ocean,'' has its share of familiar elements
and glaring improbabilities, as well as one huge coincidence as a
plot point that makes it particularly hard to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BABY-GENIUSES (Undated) _ TriStar's cute-toddler epic,
``Baby Geniuses,'' is so incorrigibly stupid, distasteful, and
maudlin, that it's hard to see how anyone over the age of 10 could
possibly sit through its 94 grueling minutes.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-20-DATES (Undated) _ It's hard to gauge if fledgling
filmmaker Myles Berkowitz desires a movie deal more than true love.
It's the basis of his quasi-documentary, ``20 Dates,'' which he
wrote, directed and stars in. It's darned incredible he found
either.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LOCK-STOCK (Undated) _ The new, small film, ``Lock, Stock
and Two Smoking Barrels,'' has taken Britain by storm and become
the biggest thing since ``Trainspotting.'' First-time director Guy
Ritchie brings such a seamless collision of working-class humor,
unpredictable folly and adreneline-rush fury to the film that it's
impossible to resist.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CORRUPTOR (Undated) _ Hong Kong superstar Chow Yun-Fat is
so charismatic in his second Hollywood outing, ``The Corruptor,''
that he almost makes us forget that the movie itself is one of the
more pretentious, muddled and incompetent action films to come
along in some time.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CHILDREN (Undated) _ This year's best foreign-language film
Oscar nomination for Majid Majidi's ``Children of Heaven'' puts the
official seal of approval on one of the true phenomenon of
international cinema in the '90s: the renaissance in Iranian
filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WING-COMMANDER (Undated) _ It's said there are few original
ideas in movies anymore. If ``Wing Commander'' is an indicator,
it's true.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
