<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LOYALTY, SHMOYALTY! 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My colleague William Safire recently wrote a much-noted column
that began by asking: ``What inspires the phenomenal loyalty to
Bill Clinton?'' Safire wondered aloud how everyone from the public
to the Democratic Party to presidential aides could remain so
``loyal'' to Clinton, despite all his perfidies. Safire's column
got me thinking. But the more I thought about it _ particularly in
the wake of George Stephanopoulos' insightful memoirs _ the more it
struck me as exactly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   For my sins, I actually covered the first year of the Clinton
White House. And looking back, what impresses me now is the
profound lack of loyalty at the core of that White House, compared
with President George Bush's. There was an unspoken sense conveyed
by Clinton officials that, if they ever got in trouble, this White
House could not be counted upon to come to their defense. And vice
versa. Before the Clintonites had even figured out where the
bathrooms were, both Bob Woodward and Elizabeth Drew were out with
excellent inside-the-White-House books, with administration
officials freely criticizing the president, and some even doing it
on the record!
</P>
<P>
   All I could think was that while Woodward needed ``Deep Throat''
to break the code of loyalty in the Nixon administration, when it
came to the Clinton administration he had ``Deep Chorus'' or ``Deep
Choir'' _ half the White House wanted to talk about their boss. It
has been downhill ever since. The number of not only kiss-and-tell
books but kiss-and-kill books about Clinton by former aides _ from
Robert Reich to Dick Morris _ is astounding to me. And those who
have not written books have provided the audio version on ``Larry
King.''
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty? Say what?
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Why the absence of loyalty? I posed that to a
Harvard University political philosopher, Michael Sandel. To begin
with, answered Sandel: ``Loyalty breeds loyalty and disloyalty
breeds disloyalty. It was clear early on in this administration,
particularly with the dumping of Lani Guinier, that loyalty was not
in season.'' Clinton reaped what he sowed.
</P>
<P>
   A second factor, argued Sandel, is a decline in the dignity and
sobriety that surrounds the presidency. ``During the Cold War,'' he
argued, ``with the president's finger always on the nuclear
trigger, leaks from the inner circle could imperil national
security. These days, the Oval Office is not the place of sobriety
and dignity it once was. Revelations about the president are now
the stuff of entertainment and titillation, not a threat to
national security. The national security presidency has given way
to the celebrity presidency. And in such a world, the rewards for
disloyalty include TV shows and book contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. Monica treated the Oval Office like a singles bar,
and the hot line as something you use for phone sex. And so did her
boss. That is not exactly an approach that breeds loyalty and
discretion. National security is out, National Enquirer is in.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, said Sandel, ``the revolving door between government
and media is spinning faster than ever, and the faster that door
spins, the more powerful the incentives to quickly tell all, and
the more people out there telling all.'' So commentators are out,
and what White House calls ``commentraitors'' are now in.
</P>
<P>
   That no Clinton official resigned in protest _ over the fact
that the president had spun them all by denying any liaison with
Monica _ was not a sign of intense loyalty to Clinton. It was a
sign of people either sticking it out because they were loyal to
his agenda, or people simply being loyal to themselves. What
cabinet official would be so foolish as to resign over being spun
by the president, in an administration built around spin? That
would be a one-day story.
</P>
<P>
   In this age, when the line between entertainment and news has
disappeared, it is not what you do on principle that matters. It is
simply how famous _ or even better, how infamous _ you are. That's
why so many ``news'' shows are now hosted by the likes of Johnnie
Cochran, Oliver North, G. Gordon Liddy, Dick Morris, etc. Infamy,
not fame, disloyalty, not integrity, is how you get ahead in an era
that will surely one day bring us ``The Charles Manson News Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't want to resign from this administration, you want to
get convicted. You don't want to fall on your sword, you want to
put it in your boss' back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
