<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: East Timor Ballot
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia and Portugal agreed to let East Timor decide through a
direct ballot whether to accept Indonesia's offer of greater
autonomy or seek full independence. Details of the vote remain to
be worked out. The accord came after two days of talks at the U.N.
among the Indonesian foreign minister, Ali Alatas, the Portuguese
foreign minister, Jaime Gama, and Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
Indonesia still has not decided how much additional autonomy to
allow the former Portuguese colony. Further talks will be held next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong: Legal Official Survives
</P>
<P>
   The top legal official survived a motion of no confidence in the
former British colony's legislature. Secretary of Justice Elsie
Leung faced the highly unusual vote after mounting public
dissatisfaction with her handling of legal cases involving
politically connected business people and Hong Kong's judicial
independence as a special region of China.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Citizenship for an al-Fayed
</P>
<P>
   Britain granted citizenship to Ali al-Fayed, saying it had
decided to disregard a damning 1990 government report of his
business practices that formed the basis of past denials of
citizenship for him and his brother, Mohamed al-Fayed, the owner of
Harrods. The Home Office said it had not reached a final decision
on the brother, father of Emad (Dodi) al-Fayed, who died in the car
crash that killed Diana, the Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Russia: U.S. Aid Package on Way
</P>
<P>
   The vanguard of the 3.1-million-ton package of food and
agricultural aid from the U.S. _ a boatload of seed grain for
farmers _ will arrive in St. Petersburg Friday, the U.S. ambassador
to Russia, James F. Collins, said.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey: Ocalan Lawyer Back on Job
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the imprisoned Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah
Ocalan who quit his post last week has reconsidered. Ahmet Zeki
Okcuoglu, who resigned after saying he feared for his life, said he
still does not feel secure, but that he and his brother, Selim
Okcuoglu, have been appointed by Ocalan and will undertake his
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Mafia Boss Seized
</P>
<P>
   A Mafia boss who was one of Italy's most wanted and most
dangerous fugitives, Giuseppe Piromalli, was arrested in his
southern hideout, a seemingly abandoned hut that the police said
was filled with documents, Champagne and James Bond-style
electronic equipment. Piromalli was sentenced to life for murder
and had been on the run since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Menem Ban Upheld
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Deputies voted to uphold a constitutional
provision that bars President Carlos Saul Menem from running for a
third straight term. The resolution was approved overwhelmingly,
but supporters of Menem boycotted the vote. While Menem has sent
mixed signals on his intentions, his supporters continue to press
the courts to allow him to run again.
</P>
<P>
   Canada: Toughening Juvenile Law
</P>
<P>
   Under a law introduced in the House of Commons, the names of
youths as young as 14 who are charged with violent crimes can be
made public. The legislation also lowers to 14 the age at which
youths can be tried as adults for murder and other violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Salt Company Sued
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups have filed suit against a salt company
jointly owned by the government and Mitsubishi of Japan, alleging
it damaged a lagoon on the Baja California peninsula that harbors
gray whales, sea turtles and other rare wildlife. The company said
there is no evidence of brine spills from its plant that might have
caused wildlife deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Tuition Increase Protest
</P>
<P>
   Protesters opposed to a tuition increase at the National
Autonomous University of Mexico blocked nearly 100,000 students, a
third of the school's enrollment, from classrooms. University
officials are proposing to increase annual tuition, now virtually
free, to about $210.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
