<HEADER>
A7066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERPLANTS12-COX     03-11 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERPLANTS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two more plants join power rush in Georgia
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two more companies have announced plans to build
electric power plants in Georgia, and more are expected in a rush
to meet the state's growing energy demands for the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Sonat Inc., a Birmingham, Ala.-based natural gas pipeline
company, said it would build a $230 million plant in Thomaston, 60
miles south of Atlanta, in Upson County.
</P>
<P>
   Dynegy Inc., a Houston-based energy marketing company, plans to
build a $100 million plant in Heard County, 60 miles west of
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Both facilities would be fueled by natural gas and designed as
``peaking plants'' to provide electricity when demand is the
highest, during the hot summer months. Gas plants are much cheaper
to build than the state's current inventory of coal and nuclear
facilities, and burn a relatively clean fuel.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of the capacity from the 680-megawatt Sonat plant is
under contract to Georgia Power Co., the state's No. 1 utility.
Dynegy said it would sell electricity from its 500-megawatt
facility in wholesale markets to Southeastern utilities.
</P>
<P>
   This week's announcements are the latest in a series of natural
gas-fueled power plants being built in Georgia and across the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for electricity in Georgia has been growing at an annual
rate of 3.5 percent. That is expected to taper off to 2.5 percent
as economic growth slows.
</P>
<P>
   But the generating capacity of Georgia Power and other utilities
will be strained, particularly during the summer, without
additions.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power is now soliciting bids to purchase between 800 and
1,200 megawatts of electricity to meet new demand in 2002 and 2003
beyond its current capacity of 16,000 megawatts, said Fred
Williams, senior vice president for resource policy and planning.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that process, the company is also preparing a
proposal to build its own 800-megawatt, natural gas-fired plant at
an undisclosed site.
</P>
<P>
   Under state Public Service Commission rules, the utility must
accept the lowest cost and most reliable proposal, either its own
or from an outside company. Capital requirements for such a plant
would likely figure in the utility's next rate hearings, which are
scheduled for 2001 and could affect consumer rates.
</P>
<P>
   A July bid selection will intensify the scramble to add power
plants, which is already under way:
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia Power is building a $100 million peaking plant in
Jefferson, in Jackson County, that will provide power for wholesale
customers. LG&AMP;E Energy Corp. has agreed to purchase electricity
from the plant. LG&AMP;E supplies electricity to Tucker-based
Oglethorpe Power Corp., which in turn serves 39 Georgia electric
membership corporations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oglethorpe is building a $70 million plant in Forsyth, in
Monroe County, that will produce 217 megawatts of electricity for
peak demand.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonat's plans to build a $235 million plant in Cataula ran
into a roadblock late last year when the Harris County Board of
Commissioners revoked its construction permit following local
opposition. Georgia Power had contracted to buy power from the
plant. Sonat is contesting the action in court.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Young, a Sonat spokesman, said the company's project
announced Thursday for Thomaston would meet the company's contract
obligations to Georgia Power, but Sonat intends to build both
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Sonat already operates a co-generation plant in Kathleen, near
Macon, that supplies a Frito-Lay food processing plant and Georgia
Power.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dynegy, which is a partner in Georgia Natural Gas Services,
the marketing affiliate of Atlanta Gas Light Co., has no contracts
for power from its planned ``merchant plant'' in Heard County, but
is confident of demand in wholesale markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Southeast is one of the fastest-growing markets in the
country for power sales,'' said Chuck Watson, chairman and chief
executive of the Houston-based company.
</P>
<P>
   _ Omaha, Neb.-based Tenaska Inc. has also announced plans for a
plant of comparable size near Franklin, in Heard County.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Adams, chairman of the Heard County Board of
Commissioners, said his West Georgia county welcomes both projects.
``They won't overload our infrastructure or schools, and it's clean
energy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each project will employ 150 construction workers and eight
permanent workers, and generate $13.5 million in tax revenue during
the next 20 years, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Heard County is desirable for the projects because it is
crossed by both the Trancontinental interstate natural gas
pipeline, which brings in fuel for the plants, and high-voltage
electric wires, which transmit electricity to power grids.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, of Georgia Power, said 10 or 15 sites across Georgia
have the same advantage and guessed that options are being taken by
investors hoping to cash in on the building boom.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of the announced projects will be able to attract
customers and financing, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will not all be built,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
