A7070 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-ARENA12-COX     03-11 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-ARENA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Work's on track for Atlanta arena
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The new downtown Philips Arena is already
three-quarters complete and on track to be finished Sept. 3 for the
next pro basketball and hockey seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The first ticketed event is scheduled to be an exhibition hockey
game about two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take two weeks to put the hot dogs in,'' quipped
Janet Marie Smith, president of Turner Sports and Entertainment
Development.
</P>
<P>
   From the 90 luxury suites that are all stacked on one side of
the arena so the nonsuiteholders on the other side are closer to
the action, to the 8-foot-tall shower heads in the Hawks locker
room, few details appear to have been forgotten in this $213
million project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about some big people,'' said Hawks coach Lenny
Wilkens, who toured the facility Thursday with reporters. The door
frames in the locker room are about a foot taller than normal and
the shower heads are nearly 2 feet taller.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's new nest for the Hawks and its hockey team, the
Thrashers, already has sold out the luxury suites for an average
annual price of $180,000 each. That's a total of $16.2 million _
about $3.5 million more than the annual debt service on the
building.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the beginning of the revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there's Turner Broadcasting System's $180
million-plus deal with Philips Electronics for the arena's naming
and sponsorship rights over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Also, about half of the 1,800 premium club seats, where waiters
will serve food, have been sold for either $8,000 or $9,500 apiece.
The tickets are good for both basketball and hockey games.
</P>
<P>
   Individual tickets for next season's Hawks and Thrashers games
aren't on sale yet. The Thrashers will be charging from $10 to $70
for individual seats, with an average price of $45. The Hawks have
not set next season's prices.
</P>
<P>
   The arena will house both a Hawk Walk and a Thrashers Nest. The
Hawk Walk is an indoor street of retail shops and interactive games
that will connect the arena to the Georgia World Congress Center.
Overlooking the walk is Thrashers Nest, a showcase of products and
technology that Philips is developing.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens said a state-of-the-art facility, such as the new 20,000
seat arena, is key to recruiting top basketball talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players want to play in a new, nice building,'' Wilkens said.
``It's part of the recruiting package.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the Hawks will have their own practice
facility inside their home arena. They have been practicing at Life
University in Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Thrashers are expected to announce a multi-year
lease agreement to practice at the IceForum in Duluth. The deal
also will provide offices for the Thrashers' coaching and training
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
