<HEADER>
A7073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-REMODELING12-COX     03-11 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-REMODELING12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Births, income increases stimulate remodeling craze
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bringing a new baby home is cause for a family to
celebrate. It's also good news for home remodeling companies. A new
addition to the family can mean an addition to the house, too.
</P>
<P>
   According to a three-year study released by the Joint Center for
Housing Studies at Harvard University, home remodeling now accounts
for about $150 billion a year, an amount that rivals new-home
construction and represents 2 percent of the nation's gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta probably does as well as any market in the nation, said
Bob Sokol, sales manager for Architectural Construction Renovations
by Paul Reardon. ``The (authors) expect activity to rise 2.4
percent in 1999, and I think we will see that here.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the study found more affluent people remodel their
older houses when family size changes or when household income
rises. Related spending trickles through the economy in the form of
furniture, floorings, appliances and technology that consumers buy
to jazz up the remodeled homes.
</P>
<P>
   There were 34 million such people in 1994-1995, the last year
for which data were available. They updated kitchens and bathrooms,
built additions and alterations, and made general improvements _
including disaster repairs _ to their property.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that money goes just to maintain and update aging
houses. The rest, though, goes to projects designed to suit the
house to the personality of its owners.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is expected to grow in the coming years because of
the rising level of homeownership, growing incomes and an aging
housing stock.
</P>
<P>
   An offsetting trend, however, is a projected decline in spending
as baby boomers start moving out of their peak remodeling years.
Even that trend has a silver lining for remodelers, though. Those
same boomers are increasingly likely to hire professional
contractors for their projects instead of doing it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The housing center's study is based on data from the U.S.
Department of Housing and Urban Development, from Commerce
Department research and from its own activity indicators. The
report does not include money spent by landlords on rental units or
have data broken down by region.
</P>
<P>
   The report foresees consolidation in the remodeling business as
retailers such as Home Depot expand their installation programs.
</P>
<P>
   Larger established companies are more likely to survive in an
industry dominated by one-person operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a high fallout rate,'' said Sokol, so much so that
customers are now as interested in warranty as in price because
they want to be sure the contractor will be around to fix problems
that might crop up later.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
