<SLUG> BC-BELL-ATLANTIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC REGIONAL PLAN BEHIND SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bell Atlantic Corp. chairman Ivan Seidenberg conceded
Thursday that his company's plans to become the first regional Bell
company to offer long-distance telephone service have continued to
slip behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based company is seeking federal and state
regulatory permission to offer long-distance service in New York
state. While the company had earlier predicted it would complete
its applications by late 1998, Bell Atlantic now expects to file
the paperwork within the next six weeks, said Seidenberg before
speaking at the Boston College Chief Executives Club.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic has said it plans to enter the long-distance
market in Massachusetts, Pennsylvania and New Jersey after New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when Bell Atlantic would start offering long distance in
the Bay State, Seidenberg, whose company has predicted a variety of
dates ranging from this past January to next December, now has
stopped forecasting a specific time. ``Frankly it is out of our
control,'' said Seidenberg, referring to the experience in New York
that has taken longer than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, the regional Bell companies are required to
first prove their local markets are open to competition before they
are allowed to sell long-distance services.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, as part of demonstrating it has opened local
markets, Bell Atlantic is reportedly struggling to meet the
technical requirements of an independent testing group which wants
to make sure that the company can quickly switch business and
residential customers to alternative local providers.
</P>
<P>
   While focusing on New York, Bell Atlantic has done comparatively
little of the technical work needed in the Bay State to make it
easy for customers to switch to alternative local providers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Seidenberg also responded to charges leveled by AT&AMP;T
on Monday that Bell Atlantic was signficantly behind schedule in
the required testing for quickly switching telephone customers in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Seidenberg dismissed AT&AMP;T's latest comments as ``self serving.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``MCI and AT&AMP;T have tried to put roadblocks in our
way. That's OK. They'll lose.''
</P>
<P>
   In his comments to the business community, he said that Bell
Atlantic's announced merger with GTE Corp., expected to close later
this year, will give Bell Atlantic the capabilities to expand
globally while serving the rapidly-growing long-distance and data
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our merger will give us the resources we need to invest in the
technology infrastructure that's so vital to the
information-intensive technology, financial and academic
institutions of Boston and the Bay State,'' Seidenberg said. He
said that Bell Atlantic has invested more than $8.8 billion in its
Massachusetts phone network in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
