A7080 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HOPE-HNS &LR;      03-11 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO DEDICATE FIRST BOYHOOD HOME IN HOPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton returns only selectively to his
southwestern Arkansas roots _ as in the 1992 campaign when he
wanted to be ``the man from Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   He makes one of those infrequent pilgrimages Friday to dedicate
the modest white clapboard home where he lived until he was 4.
</P>
<P>
   The day after returning from a Latin American trip, Clinton will
fly to Hope, Ark., where he was born, for a three-hour nostalgic
dip into his earliest years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will get his first look inside the house at 117 S.
Hervey, near the Union Pacific tracks, in more than 40 years, said
Clinton Birthplace Foundation project manager Beckie Moore.
</P>
<P>
   The restored 1917 three-bedroom house has been outfitted with
period furniture and knickknacks, including a blue-tasseled Evening
in Paris perfume like the ones used by Clinton's mother, Virginia
Clinton Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly advised decorators on details such as color and furniture
placement shortly before her death in 1994. None of the furnishings
are original, Moore said, but some Clinton kin recently supplied
family pictures that have been added to the display.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to greet a large group of Hope residents when he
arrives at the airport, before going on to the house for an
invitation-only ceremony and tour, where the president will make
formal remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was preoccupied with national affairs _ and the Monica
Lewinsky scandal _ when the restored house was unveiled last
summer. His stop Friday also will mark the opening of a garden on
the site in memory of his mother.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is Clinton's first to his home state since the House
impeached him as a result of his affair with Lewinsky and the
Senate acquitted him.
</P>
<P>
   Even political opponents of the president concede the yearlong
scandal inquiry did little to dim Clinton's aura back home.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepared to vote for two of the articles of impeachment
last December, the U.S. House member from the area, Republican Rep.
Jay Dickey said: ``So many people in my district have their own
self-esteem intertwined with the well-being of their friend, Bill
Clinton. So while they have reason to be embarrassed, disappointed
and even disgusted, they are in large part in denial of the
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many enterprises involving the nation's 42nd chief
executive, the $1.5 million restoration of his boyhood home has
been touched by multiple controversies. The latest is the refusal
of the Arkansas Legislature to appropriate $500,000 to help fund
the final development of the site.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Sandra Rodgers, D-Hope, was reduced to tears as
fellow House members refused this week to have the president's home
state chip in.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, congressional committees subpoenaed foundation records
to determine whether wealthy foreigners _ such as Hong Kong real
estate tycoon Nina Wang, who gave $50,000 to the project _ were
seeking to curry favor with the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy, at least initially, dampened contributions,
sources familiar with the foundation said.
</P>
<P>
   The home is where Clinton's mother was living with her parents,
Edith and Eldridge Cassidy, when she got the call in late spring
1946 _ three months before the future president's birth _ that her
husband, William Jefferson Blythe, had been killed in an auto
accident in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was born Aug. 19, 1946, in Julia Chester Hospital, which
was torn down years ago, but the site got a historical marker in
1992 as the most famous native son was headed to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The young Clinton made many friends in Hope who have played a
role in his political life, including Mack McLarty III, the former
energy company official who became Clinton's first White House
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton lived in the house on Hervey, his mother was
mostly in New Orleans studying to be a nurse. When she returned to
Hope, she married Roger Clinton, the local Buick dealer, and they
moved to another house in Hope. In 1953, the family moved about 70
miles away to Hot Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Her burial was one of the four times Clinton has returned to
Hope since the 1992 election.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Clinton was in Hope for the burial of Vincent W. Foster
Jr., a White House counsel who committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stopped in Hope again to visit a sick relative, Henry
Oren ``Uncle Buddy'' Grisham, and then to attend the man's funeral
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton-sparked tourism and trade has been a modest boon for the
Hempstead County seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's given our town a chance to rebound,'' said Hope native
Gary Johnson, manager of a visitors' center set up in the
refurbished train station.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 tourists a day stop at the center during the
summer, Johnson said, with visits dropping off in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's impeachment had little effect on the tourist traffic,
Johnson said, although he noted ``a good crowd'' on the day the
president was acquitted by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
