<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Column: Forget the Dow, Traders Were Watching S&AMP;P 500 Flirt
With  1,300   By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
With the Dow Jones industrial average toying with 10,000 and the
first round of the national collegiate hoops tourney tipping off,
how much work do you suppose got done yesterday?
</P>
<P>
   Between water-cooler wagers on the Dow and office pools on the
Big Dance, my bet is that gross domestic product declined
profoundly.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what might have been lost amid all of these worthy
distractions was the fact that the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 busted the
1,300 barrier, which is its own short-term psychological barrier.
The S&AMP;P 500 index hit a high during yesterday's trading session of
1,306 before running out of gas and closing at 1,297.
</P>
<P>
   For most Wall Street investors, the rise and fall of the broader
S&AMP;P 500 is far more meaningful than the trials and tribulations of
the Dow. (Of course, that's no revelation to the many mutual fund
investors who have been winning and grinning with index funds that
mirror the S&AMP;P.)
</P>
<P>
   But the Dow, with its 30 stocks, simply doesn't reflect what's
going on with the 500 listed in the S&AMP;P and the thousands traded on
the broader market. The S&AMP;P showcases such sexy, high-octane names
as Cisco, Microsoft, Dell, Gap and Pfizer, which are not to be
found on the dowdy Dow.
</P>
<P>
   So, when it came to what was grabbing the attention of traders
and money managers on Montgomery Street yesterday, it was the S&AMP;P's
flirtation with 1,300 ... not the Dow's dalliance with 10,000.
That, and Stanford's nailbiter with Alcorn State.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DELAYED GRATIFICATION: &LR;  With the stock market testing new
milestones and the Russian ruble crisis a mere memory, it would
come as little surprise that Goldman Sachs is antsy to float its
shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   While earlier news and wire services speculated that the
long-awaited initial offering was slated for this summer, people
familiar with the situation say the IPO is likely to happen much
sooner: the second week of May.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these things are subject to change as we learned from
Goldman's first postponement in the wake of last summer's market
meltdown. But after having the issue hanging over the partners'
heads for the better part of a year, the investment bank is anxious
to get on with its new life as a publicly held concern, says former
Goldman Sachs trader Lisa Endlich, who is author of a new book on
the bank: ``The Culture of Success.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET12 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``They've been living in limbo,'' Endlich says.
</P>
<P>
   Endlich, who insists that the timing of her book and the IPO are
a pure coincidence, says there was no turning back once Goldman
decided last year to go public. Once the emotional decision was
made, it was an institutional admission that private partnership
was not the best business model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've said that you are not operating in the most
optimal way, then you have to go forward with those changes'' that
have already been approved, says Endlich, who lives in London and
started writing her book about three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And while Goldman ``will change into a completely different
organization'' after the IPO, the firm isn't likely to buy a retail
brokerage business such as Morgan Stanley did with Dean Witter,
Endlich notes.
</P>
<P>
   However, the former trader says that Goldman soon will open its
exclusive doors to Main Street via the Internet. Goldman, which
requires its clients to invest a $5 million minimum with the firm,
plans to develop an online brokerage strategy that caters to ``mom
and pop'' investors.
</P>
<P>
   You don't suppose that Goldman will charge under 10 bucks a
trade do you?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
