<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Getting Your Ergonomic Needs Met  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  My friend is a programmer with 15 years of experience in
several computer languages. She had a car accident in 1996,
followed by surgery and extensive physical therapy. Now she's
trying to return to work but running into problems. She needs a
completely ergonomically sound workstation, including a computer
table that can adjust to either sitting or standing height. So far,
she's found that employers stop returning her calls when they learn
about her ergonomic needs. What can she do?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  The Americans with Disabilities Act and similar state
laws prohibit companies from discriminating against disabled
jobseekers like your friend.
</P>
<P>
   But face it, hiring someone who may need thousands of dollars
worth of special equipment can be a scary proposition. Potential
employers don't know the quality of her work; they don't know the
scope or cost of the equipment she'll need; they don't even know if
she'll stick around more than a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   Your friend needs to do as much as she can to defuse such fears.
That means presenting potential employers with a solution rather
than a problem. It means presenting herself as an active partner in
making that solution happen _ not as an adversary or a passive
complainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than just saying, `You need to spend all this money to
accommodate me,' she should say, `I know what I need, here are the
sources for the best price and equipment, and I'm going to do my
share to stay healthy and productive,''' said Gary Karp of Onsight,
an ergonomic consulting firm in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Your friend can start by researching precisely what equipment
she needs and how much it costs: One place to check is the
Ergonomic Sciences Corp., a Mountain View ergonomic equipment firm
with a Web site at  &LR; www.ergosci.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   She should also find out what outside financial help is
available. Most states, including California, have a Department of
Rehabilitation that will help pay for equipment or training to help
disabled people re-enter the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Your friend might also consider buying a small part of the
equipment herself _ especially if there are pieces that she'd want
to keep permanently. That would show employers she's willing to
meet them halfway.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco vocational counselor Betty Kohlenberg suggests
that your friend consider temporary or volunteer work that uses her
skills while she searches for a permanent position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking volunteer positions or temporary positions will help
update her skills and give her some recent work experience to talk
about with potential employers,'' Kohlenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the question of precisely when your friend
should reveal her ergonomic needs to a potential employer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WORKWAYS (89155 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Let's assume her disability isn't outwardly visible. Legally, she
doesn't have to disclose her need for an accommodation until she
starts work. So some disability experts suggest waiting to raise
the issue until she has a job offer in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should say, `I'm thrilled with your offer. Can we set up
an appointment to discuss a few things in person?''' said Judy
Doane, a San Francisco specialist in repetitive strain injuries.
``At that meeting, she should tell them how excited she is to have
the job, how she's looking forward to working really hard, and how
she will need (some ergonomic help) to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Paying Commissions
</P>
<P>
   Q: I work for a financial services company that is about to be
bought by another firm. I'm not a salesperson, but I receive
commissions for business that I help bring in. I recently helped
land a very big account that should generate quite a bit of money.
Here's the problem: Commissions for the deal are to be paid
quarterly over the next two years, based on how much revenue it
generates. But the company that's acquiring us doesn't have a
commission program at all. Is it required to keep paying my
commissions?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Companies can't refuse to pay wages for work that has
already been done. Similarly, they can't refuse to pay commissions
that have already been earned.
</P>
<P>
   When is a commission considered `'earned?'' When an employee has
done everything that is required from him or her as part of the
deal, according to Thomas Makris, an employment lawyer with
Rosenblum Parish &AMP; Isaacs in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say your company requires you to continue servicing this
client over the next two years in order to receive a commission.
Your work is not complete. That means the commission isn't legally
``earned'' yet. And the company could refuse to pay you if it
switches to a new no-commission policy.
</P>
<P>
   But let's say you've completed all your duties on this account.
You've earned your commission _ and you must be paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this person has done everything he was expected to do to
make the sale happen and now just has to sit back and wait for the
money to roll in, there's a very good argument that he should be
paid,'' Makris said.
</P>
<P>
   Does the fact that the company is changing owners affect its
obligation to pay commissions? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   When this new company buys your old one, it's most likely
assuming the old company's legal obligations _ including the
obligation to pay commissions that employees like you have already
earned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
