<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL reaches deal with SBC on high-speed Net access
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ America Online, the nation's largest online service,
and SBC Communications, the country's second-largest local phone
company, will offer high-speed Internet access to AOL members in
the West and South.
</P>
<P>
   SBC now offers high-speed digital subscriber line service in
California, Texas, Missouri, Oklahoma, Arkansas and Kansas. The
agreement also includes Nevada Bell, which plans to deploy DSL
service this year.
</P>
<P>
   AOL said it will now be able to offer high-speed access in 21
states. The service needs to team with phone or cable companies
because it doesn't own any networks. Instead, it buys access and
resells it with AOL's content for a monthly rate of $21.95. AOL
said SBC service will cost an extra $20 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Phone companies such as San Antonio, Texas-based SBC want to
increase their sales of Internet services, yet they haven't been as
successful as America Online in attracting consumers. DSL is more
than 50 times faster than most standard modems, and will allow
customers to use a computer and phone or fax simultaneously on one
line.
</P>
<P>
   In January, AOL formed an alliance with Bell Atlantic to offer
high-speed access to AOL subscribers in the Bell Atlantic region.
BellSouth, which serves all of Georgia and eight other states, has
been conspicuously absent from the recent flurry of DSL and
high-speed content announcements and partnerships. BellSouth
spokesman Ted Creech says the company has been talking to AOL about
a DSL deal.
</P>
<P>
   He says there are 2 million DSL-ready homes in BellSouth's
service area. BellSouth estimates 5 million households will be
ready for DSL before the end of the year. BellSouth offers DSL
service in parts of Atlanta, Jacksonville and Fort Lauderdale,
Fla., Birmingham, Ala., Charlotte, Raleigh and Durham, N.C., and
New Orleans. DSL will be available in 23 more markets before the
end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in discussions with AOL,'' Creech said. ``And we
still are. We have been in conversations with lots of Internet and
network service providers. We currently have contracts with 14
providers right now for ADSL. It's actually a very active area of
our business.''
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth has not been able to come to terms with key
players such as AOL and major Internet service providers such as
Atlanta-based MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
