<SLUG> BC-NH-EDUCATION-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES OUT REFERENDUM ON NEW TAX PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ The New Hampshire Supreme Court ruled Thursday
that Gov. Jeanne Shaheen cannot look to the voters to solve the
state's looming school funding crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous opinion, the court turned down Shaheen's request
that voters be allowed to approve by popular referendum any new tax
system created to meet the court's April 1 deadline for enactment
of a new education finance scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Referenda on legislation are unconstitutional in this state,''
the justices declared in an advisory opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen, who said that she welcomed the opportunity to pit a
funding plan she outlined this week against a plan that includes
the state's first tax on personal income, was clearly disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been my view that on an issue as important as school
funding, the people of New Hampshire ought to be able to choose,
and that our state constitution permitted such a vote,'' Shaheen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ruling leaves the state's political leaders _ and
especially Shaheen _ in a difficult position, forced to choose
between increasing business taxes and drastically expanding the
state's reliance on gambling; ending the state's famous refusal to
impose an income tax; or allowing the New Hampshire education
system to fall into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen insisted that one of those options, enacting an income
tax such as the one that narrowly passed the House last week, is
now out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a referendum, an income tax is off the table and we
must continue to working together to resolve this crisis in the
very short period of time that lies ahead,'' Shaheen said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But many observers believe the court's decision decreases the
chances that the badly fractured political system will be able to
reach a consensus. The binding referendum would have left the issue
of how best to raise the estimated $900 million needed every year
to fund schools up to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after 15 months of haggling, the state's political leaders
must decide. If they cannot agree over the next three weeks, the
school portion of property taxes will become legally uncollectable,
teachers will begin receiving pink slips, and New Hampshire, whose
loathing for taxes is legendary, could find itself in a grim
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes the worst of the scenarios more likely than they
were two hours ago'' said Tom Rath, a former attorney general and
Republican political activist.
</P>
<P>
   The court has been pushing this debate from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, the court ruled that the current system of
raising money for schools with local property taxes created
unconstitutionally high disparities between rich towns and poor
ones. Lawmakers, the court ruled, would have to find a better way.
With that began the long struggle to find a politically palatable
remedy.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the plans that have emerged since yet appears to
have the political support to pass.
</P>
<P>
   On March 4 the 400-member House narrowly passed a bill calling
for a combination statewide income and property tax and sent it to
the state senate which Democrats control for the first time in 86
years. This plan could pass in the Senate, observers agree, but
Shaheen has promissed to veto it. There are not thought to be the
votes to override a veto, especially in the House, where the
measure passed 194-190, far short of the needed two thirds.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen countered with a proposal that would raise the money
with a $6 statewide property tax, increased taxes on business, a
new 5 percent tax on capital gains, and an additional $145 million
by allowing video slot machines for the first time at the state's
four racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitality industry has already come out against Shaheen's
plan and business opposition is building. Nor are the odds for
legislative approval of video slot machines good. In the past, a
majority politians of both parties have consistently refused to
expand gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that the governor's plan would not raise enough
money to pass constitutional muster. The Shaheen plan would provide
an average of $4,554 per pupil, $500 less than called for in the
rival income tax plan and nearly $1,000 less than the state's
average per pupil spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some reservations now about her plan,'' said Scott
Johnson, a lawyer for the coalition of five property-poor school
districts that first sued the state in 1991. ``There are some
constitutional problems with the adequacy amounts.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Shaheen plan, other argued, is bound to experience more
opposition as it is given more scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the more you look at it the more warts you
find,'' said Republican House Speaker Donna Sytek, whose own plan
has failed to come up for a vote in the full House.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the deadlock has brought ever louder complaints that
the court has gone too far. Some have suggested rewriting the
constitution so that justices would no longer enjoy life tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is about a hair's breadth away from getting
themselves term-limited,'' said Stephen Duprey, the State
Republican party chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor, too, is feeling intense pressure. With
presidential aspirants in every coffee shop and the nation's eyes
on New Hampshire, Shaheen may have been looking forward to the
chance to veto an income tax. Now, she may find herself written
into history books as the governor who raised taxes on business and
brought casino-style video gambling to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure she wants to make some of these choices,'' Rath
said. ``This has thrown everything back to square one which will
certainly make for an interesting month.''
</P>
</TEXT>
