<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-LAWYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODWARD LAWYERS SAY THEY WANT TO STUDY NEW EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The lawyers who defended former au pair Louise Woodward
in the murder of eight-month-old Matthew Eappen want to put an end
to the controversy over Sunday night's ``60 Minutes'' program so
they can investigate its claims and ultimately demonstrate
Woodward's innocence, they said at a press conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But a former colleague fired off a written statement of her own
which promised to keep the controversy alive.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers Harvey Silverglate, Andrew Good, and Barry
Scheck dismissed as ``red herrings'' the debate over the
independence of experts who appeared on the televised report, and
criticism of the lawyers for releasing samples of the infant's
brain tissue to the freelance reporter who originated the segment.
</P>
<P>
   They said the debates distracted from what the experts, Dr.
Floyd Gilles and Dr. Marvin Nelson, had said on the television
program: that Eappen had died from the delayed effects of a
strangulation up to two days before his collapse, rather than from
being shaken and having his head slammed against a hard object, as
prosecutors had argued.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also tried to distance themselves from former
colleague Elaine Whitfield Sharp, who first told the press of the
firm's pre-trial relationship with Nelson, and has criticized the
strangulation theory posed by Gilles and Nelson. Sharp also said
this week that she had met with Gilles, of whom the defense denied
any knowledge before the ``60 Minutes'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp was dismissed from the defense team after her arrest for
drunk driving in June 1998. At the time, her former colleagues
released a statement saying she had exhibited ``an aberrant pattern
of behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   By day's end Thursday, Sharp had fired off a rejoinder to the
lawyers' statements about her, calling the strangulation theory
``grasping at straws,'' and asserting once more that her colleagues
had full knowledge of her meetings with both Nelson and Gilles.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, Woodward was found guilty of second-degree
murder by a jury that agreed with the prosecution's claims that she
had shaken Matthew Eappen and slammed his head into a hard object
just before he became unconscious on Feb. 4. But the conviction was
reduced to manslaughter days later, and she was set free.
</P>
<P>
   By attributing the infant's death to a strangulation up to 48
hours before his collapse, the doctors raised the possibility that
someone other than Woodward could have caused his death.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers said they would begin a weeks-long
investigation of the strangulation claims immediately, for which
they would not be paid, by either Woodward or E. F. Au Pair, the
company which placed her in the Eappens' home.
</P>
<P>
   If that investigation gives credence to the strangulation
theory, they said, they will approach Middlesex District Attorney
Martha Coakley to pursue a further, independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley was ambivalent about that plan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they feel there was an injustice, and Woodward was wrongly
convicted, as in every case we keep an open mind,'' said Coakley.
``But it's disingenuous of them to say now that having thoroughly
examined this case, that they want a second bite at the apple. But
having said that we'll keep an open mind. The ball is in their
court.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers avoided the question of whether they would
ultimately seek a new trial for Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're jumping about 95 steps ahead,'' said Good.
</P>
<P>
   They said they would see where the investigation takes them,
then consult with Woodward on whether to go back to court. But
Scheck said that Woodward has been prepared to take the riskier
routes throughout in the interests of demonstrating her innocence.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers lambasted the 77 doctors who signed a letter on
Wednesday criticizing the strangulation theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain totally confused (as to) why people rush to judgment
without looking at the data,'' Scheck said. ``It's not a letter
writing campaign where you vote on what your favorite thesis is
without looking at the underlying data.''
</P>
<P>
   And they dismissed criticisms of them for having turned over
microscopic samples of Matthew Eappen's brain tissue to the
journalist, Katie Leishman, for examination by Gilles. They called
the criticism ``an apparent effort to turn attention away from the
all-important questions of what the tissue slides and other
scientific exhibits prove.''
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the slides were not turned over to ``any Joe
Blow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Leishman) was more conversant with the evidence than any
other news media person we've talked to,'' said Silverglate.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of Sharp's contention she had met earlier with
both experts, a spokesperson for the hospital in Los Angeles where
both practised confirmed Thursday that Sharp had met with them
after calling them with repeated requests. But the spokesman said
the doctors had terminated the meeting when it became clear Sharp
``had little to say.''
</P>
<P>
   In their written statement, the lawyers said they had paid
Nelson for reviewing some materials about a month before the trial,
but did not call him as a witness in the trial. And they had no
knowledge of Gilles whatsoever, Good said.
</P>
<P>
   If Sharp met with the doctor, Silverglate, Good and Scheck had
no knowledge of it, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what she was doing most of the time,'' Good said
of Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp fired back an angry reply to that statement late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense team was made aware of my meetings with Drs.
Gilles and Nelson,'' she wrote. ``I kept the defense team informed
of every meeting I had with every expert and potential expert in
the case, and I have documentation which proves this fact.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Silverglate, Good and Scheck bristled at claims
that their investigation of the strangulation claims was an attempt
to rehabilitate their reputations after failing to win a not-guilty
verdict for Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   ``History and our mothers will take care of our reputations,''
said Silverglate. ``That's not what we're here for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
