<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Education bill gives states wider options
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress on Thursday passed an education bill that
would give states greater flexibility over how they spend more than
one-third of the federal education money flowing to local school
districts.
</P>
<P>
   But the lopsided votes in the House and Senate masked partisan
divisions over the bill. Senate Democrats threatened to urge
President Clinton to veto the bill because of an amendment they
said would gut his plan to lower class sizes by funding 100,000 new
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans have pulled an anti-education hat trick,''
said Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.) moments before the Senate voted
98-1 (Democrat Paul Wellstone of Minnesota voted no) to approve the
Education Flexibility Partnership Act.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans defeated an amendment that would have fully
funded Clinton's class-size initiative and adopted their own
amendment that would allow states the option of spending the $1.2
billion appropriated last year for lowering class sizes on either
new teachers or special education programs.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, school districts would be given more freedom in
spending $264.7 million of the $763.9 million the state receives
from the federal government for primary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
   The House version passed 330-90. Democratic Reps. Cynthia
McKinney and John Lewis were the only Georgians to vote no.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling in Antigua, Clinton issued a statement saying that he
will campaign to remove the Republican amendment allowing states
the option of funding special education instead of hiring new
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be working together to make continued progress on
obvious national needs such as reducing class size _ not attempting
to tear down the bipartisan work we did last year to address this
problem,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.), a Senate leader on education, said
the votes signaled the beginning of a trend away from federal
control over education and toward greater flexibility at the local
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole mission here is an acknowledgement that all of these
federal strings have not produced a very favorable result,''
Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   Newly elected Rep. Johnny Isakson (R-Ga.), a former state school
board chairman, said school districts might, for example, elect to
use money to lower teacher-pupil ratios in poorer school districts,
or purchase computer software especially designed for
non-English-speaking students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to bring about a lot of creative thinking on how to
use the money,'' Isakson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
