<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERMITES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiny pests devouring New Orleans history
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ In this tourist town, there are haunted tours,
voodoo tours, home tours and cemetery tours.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was that termite tour.
</P>
<P>
   A group of entomologists and pest control experts set out
Thursday from behind Jackson Square in the French Quarter to
inspect the damage Formosan termites do to homes, businesses, even
trees.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't have to go far. New Orleans is second only to
Honolulu for infestation by Formosan termites, which are much more
plentiful and destructive than the usual termites, called ``native
subterraneans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A colony of 1 million Formosan termites would consume a
two-by-four in 30 days,'' said Ed Martin, tour guide and termite
hunter. ``And most colonies number in the millions.'' He's been an
entomologist working in New Orleans pest control since 1948, around
the time the Formosans arrived in the United States hidden in
military equipment brought back from World War II campaigns in the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   At least 90 percent of the buildings in the French Quarter have
termites. A federal program called Operation Full Stop is under way
in a 15-block section of the historic neighborhood. By setting
traps and actually killing the termites instead of repelling them _
as was done in the past _ experts hope to rid the area of termites
in five years. If it works, the method will be used more widely.
</P>
<P>
   Once termites move into a region, it takes about 25 years for
them to cause noticeable damage. The French Quarter is so infested
because the buildings are attached to one another, Martin said. The
facade of one house on the tour was completely ripped off. Termites
had eaten through the brick and stucco to get to the wood beams
supporting the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll eat through anything _ your computer wires, your
telephone wires,'' said homeowner Pam Fortner, whose home is in the
15-block area being treated and studied. ``It's devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   In Armstrong Park, on the edge of the French Quarter,
entomologists are studying termites before they kill them. They
believe there are about 11 million termites lurking underground at
the park.
</P>
<P>
   The tour, arranged by a pest control industry group called
Responsible Industry for a Sound Environment, continued at City
Park, where about 20 percent of the trees are infested. The
largest, a 600-year-old live oak called ``Madonna,'' has branches
so rangy and long that they must be supported by wires and
telephone polls. Inside the trunk is a colony of at least 1 million
tiny wood-eaters. The city's Termite Control Board is working to
save the tree by trying to lure the termites away with underground
bait.
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of the trees in New Orleans are infested with
termites, said Mike Carroll with the Termite Control Board. Most of
the older houses in the city have been infested at one time, but
humans have been gaining ground over the pests in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the technology has now caught up with the problem,''
Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Termites cause $300 million in damage annually in New Orleans,
and more than $1 billion nationwide. They are most prevalent in
warm, wet climates. Treating and repairing damage to an infested
home can cost as much $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
