<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Seasons of growth by a sandy stream
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Helen C. Hynes
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   When my two cousins from Chicago, Fred and Bill, started
spending their summer vacations at our house in the little town of
Tiskilwa, Ill., life became an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the early 1920s, and as an only child, I usually spent
my days playing with my dolls and dog, reading books and helping
Mama.
</P>
<P>
   When ``the boys'' came, suddenly I was allowed to do things that
I couldn't before, and my embroidered dresses were quickly replaced
by an old pair of tan overalls.
</P>
<P>
   I tagged along with delight as we roamed the nearby woods,
climbed trees, gathered buckeyes, skipped stones in the big
``crick,'' picked berries, raked leaves for bonfires, played
hide-and-seek and pom-pom-pullaway and even snitched a few apples
from the orchard of the crabby old man at the edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   When it rained we sat on the porch strumming our ukeleles made
of cigar boxes and rubber bands, or played cards.
</P>
<P>
   Picnics were the most fun, and our favorite spot was over the
hill in a wooded valley back of Gus Magnuson's farm.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a small, rocky stream with a sandy spot on one bank
where we could have a fire and even an old log to sit on.
</P>
<P>
   Kids from the neighborhood went with us: Les, Baba, Avalon,
Wilma and little Doodie, who always straggled along at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Cousin Fred, at 13, was the only one allowed to carry a knife
and matches, so he built the fire and cut willow sticks to spear
the weenies and marshmallows.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the weenies were scorched or the marshmallows caught
fire, yet it all tasted wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   We would lie on our backs on the grass, vying to find the most
exciting pictures in the clouds, and wade in the stream.
</P>
<P>
   I so well remember the throat-bursting joy I felt at being
included in those picnics, of knowing I belonged with Fred and
Bill, of feeling so free, instead of being a little girl alone.
</P>
<P>
   As with every summer, our last picnic that year was a sad one
because my cousins were leaving the next day.
</P>
<P>
   While the others picked up the sacks and apple cores to burn, I
gathered willow sticks and playfully stuck them in the ground
behind the log, pleased with the little fence I made.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Fred kicked sand over the ashes of the fire and we
trailed back over the hill.
</P>
<P>
   So for me it was back to embroidered dresses, dolls and
schoolbooks; back to autumn leaves, winter snow, spring rain and,
inevitably, another glorious summer.
</P>
<P>
   As we trooped over the hill for our first picnic of that new
summer, the same little gang with Doodie trailing behind, we found
the rocky stream, the sandy spot for our fire and the log still
there.
</P>
<P>
   And behind the log, a straight line of tall and graceful
willows, bending slightly forward and making a lovely green bower
above our sitting place.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped and held my breath. The wonder of that miracle has
never left me.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Helen C. Hynes lives in Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
