<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7096 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-FINANCING-B     03-11 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-FINANCING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP-BACKED EDUCATION BILL APPROVED BY BOTH HOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Crying victory as both the House and Senate
approved education legislation ``essential to the country,''
Republicans Thursday took what they hoped was a giant leap away
from impeachment with passage of a popular bill that would give
schools greater freedom in the way they spend federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, known as ``Ed Flex,'' had been questioned by several
Democrats who believed it might let poor students slip through the
cracks. Patterned after a program already in place in 12 states,
including Massachusetts, the bill would give all 50 states the
possibility of waiving requirements that normally accompany
government grants.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of bitter wrangling in the Senate, and a far easier
day of discussion in the House, the bill was overwhelmingly
approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be the news _ not how we got there, or what
amendments were offered,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
``For the second time this year, in a bipartisan way, the Senate
passed a bill that's important to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in both the House and Senate had hoped to attach a
provision to authorize payment for 100,000 new teachers, a measure
that received a congressional nod of approval in last year's
spending bill. Senator Edward M. Kennedy fought for an amendment to
push the plan ahead, tying up Senate debate for more than a week.
Republicans blocked it, and the amendment failed 55-45 in a
party-line vote.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in a move that infuriated Senate Democrats, Republicans
designed a program that would not require schools to hire new
teachers at all. Through an amendment, Republicans said that the
money set aside last year _ $1.2 billion for 30,000 new teachers in
1999 _ could instead be used in special education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy called the move an ``anti-education hat trick.''
Accusing Republicans of pitting special-ed students against poor
ones, he said the amendment would ``effectively kill the commitment
Congress made last year for smaller class size.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think the Congress missed a very important
opportunity,'' Kennedy said on the Senate floor. Other Democrats
said the Republican plan would have a severe impact on President
Clinton's plan to hire 100,000 new teachers, at a cost of $11
billion, over the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accused the Republicans of using the bill ``to undermine
one of our most important educational achievements -- an initiative
to hire 100,000 well-prepared teachers to reduce class size in the
early grades to a national average of 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be working together to make continued progress on
obvious national needs such as reducing class size -- not
attempting to tear down the bipartisan work we did last year to
address this problem,'' Clinton said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, all but one Senate Democrat _ Paul Wellstone of
Minnesota _ voted for the bill despite the Republican amendment,
and despite underlying fears the program might let schools spend
federal funds recklessly instead of on the neediest. The final vote
was 98-1.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Republicans were not without their own moments of
frustration. Thanks to an agreement hammered out the day before,
Republicans were forced to vote ``no'' on five Democratic
amendments, leaving them open to accusations their education
rallying cry lacks legislative substance.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry, who plans to introduce his own education
bill next week, said the vote meant Congress had ``passed one step
of overall reform and missed the opportunity to do a comprehensive
approach because it remains too mired in partisan politics.''
</P>
<P>
   In the House, where the bill passed 330-90, Democrats offered
more resistance in their final votes than in the Senate. But during
the debate, they failed to stymie Republicans at all and even
missed a chance to offer their own amendment on the new-teacher
hiring plan.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois cited the victory as
a ``great first step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the bipartisan work we said we were going to do in
this Congress,'' said Hastert, who has worked furiously in recent
weeks to focus public attention on something other than Clinton's
impeachment, which bitterly divided the House last fall and caused
GOP approval ratings to plummet.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Ed-Flex (Education Flexibility Partnership Act) plan,
schools are able to apply for waivers from federal rules that
normally accompany some $15 billion in federal funds, including the
largest program, Title I, which sends money to the poorest schools.
Ed Flex enjoys wide bipartisan support, as well as the backing of
all 50 governors, and, according to Republicans, has not failed to
reach poorer students in the states where it has been tested.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, one of the first states where Ed Flex was
tried, educators say the program has allowed money allocated for
poor students to be used far more effectively _ for example,
freeing school officials from filling out endless paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   And yet in the short term, Ed Flex may have more of an impact on
politics than policy. After Thursday's vote, several senators in
both parties said the partisan divide had been widened by the
debate, which lasted more than a week and was led largely by
Kennedy. They also acknowleged that both parties remained locked in
a tug-of-war over the overall issue of education, and Ed Flex was
just the beginning the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Jack Reed, Democrat of Rhode Island, said: ``The
question of if people see this as the Democrats finally breaking
through and getting education on the agenda, or as Republicans
responding to education ... It's too early to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lott, saying Kennedy had ``not been constructive'' in
holding up the vote for so long, claimed victory right away,
pointing to the popularity of Ed Flex and its ultimate passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats, I don't think this has helped them,'' Lott
said. ``We were on the high ground. They were on the low ground.
They were trying to ball this thing up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
