u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-DREAMLAND-COX     03-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-DREAMLAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vivid portrait of old New York is best that `Dreamland' offers
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL MARCH 14: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Eileen M. Drennen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You read a novel like ``Dreamland'' because you want to get lost
in the past. And where better to get lost than New York City in
1910, with its millionaires and immigrants, factory girls and
gamblers, politicos and cops, outcasts and reformers. Their
collisions and alliances on the city's ragged streets forged much
that we recognize as America.
</P>
<P>
   By choosing such a sprawling canvas, and using an alternating
cast of narrators to carry the action forward, it's clear that
Kevin Baker has in mind nothing less than an epic.
</P>
<P>
   His command of the time and place are masterful. You can see the
Bowery by street lamp, with its pushcarts of oysters and potatoes.
You can hear the unholy din of the factory looms, relentless as an
army of trains. You can smell the crowded tenement hallways, where
the smells of dinner merge into a gumbo of Irish and Jewish and
Italian smoke. Where people are so poor, they rent out their beds
by day to roomerkehs (Yiddish for boarders) who work by night.
</P>
<P>
   As chief researcher for Harold Evans' ``The American Century,''
Baker stockpiled enough details of turn-of-the-century life
(including a heady mix of Yiddish, Irish and Chinese words, and a
handy glossary) to transport you to that place and time. Extended
scene pieces of boardwalk, factory and underworld life darken the
picture enough that we understand the allure of the bright and
blinking oceanside wonderland of the title.
</P>
<P>
   For it's not just the real Dreamland he's concerned with, that
famed Coney Island theme park to top all others, with its minarets
and moonscapes, its million lights, beer gardens, canals and roller
coaster. It's the darker land of dreams, the city itself, which
offers as much betrayal as promise.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Baker's scope _ and flabby way with words _ is his
undoing. No matter how fresh and real he makes this lost world, the
characters he unlooses upon it remain maddening shadows.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of alternating voices propel the narrative strands
forward. Trick the Dwarf, a sideshow regular who lives in the
tattered beachfront Tin Elephant hotel and whose idea of escape is
blacking his face with charcoal so he can ``pass'' for a newsboy,
is something of a guiding presence. His observations open and close
the book and supply some of its wilder moments (notably, the foul
pleasures of the rat pit, where one dog vs. many rats fight to the
death, and the true story of the mad circus elephant's execution,
which took more gruesome tries than you can imagine).
</P>
<P>
   Other voices include Lower East Side sewing machine operator
Esther ``Esse'' Abramowitz, who sneaks out to Dreamland with her
gangster sweetheart Kid Twist and strikes for better working
conditions; her brother Lazar, a.k.a. Gyp the Blood; and a fading
Irish pol called Big Tim Sullivan. Interspersed are ensemble
chapters called ``On the Boardwalk,'' which unfold on the salty
pleasure domes of Coney Island, and ``The Great Head Doctors From
Vienna,'' wherein psychiatrists Freud and Jung undertake their
grand visit to America.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, all of them meet, in the end, at Dreamland. But their
intersection feels more contrived than inevitable. All that happens
in the course of this saga doesn't seem to change anyone. Or if it
does, you never know: In one of the oddest wrap-up chapters ever,
Trick the Dwarf follows his account of the burning of Dreamland
with a long list of maybes:
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the rest of it, who knows? You want an epilogue, but
who knows where people go? They get swallowed up in the crowds, and
all that is left is speculation. Maybe Esther did get married, and
settled down to churning out children in spite of herself. While he
got a good position with the City or made his fortune bottling
celery tonic. ... Or maybe they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker can't have it both ways. If he wants readers to buy into
his lengthy sleight of hand, he owes them an actual payoff.
</P>
<P>
   -- FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Dreamland. By Kevin Baker. HarperCollins. $26. 519 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A fabulous ride that ultimately doesn't go
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen M. Drennen, a native New Yorker, edits the Dixie Living
section of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
