<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-VISIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Visions' of 20th century via man and machinery
 &HT;    (EDS: EMBARGOED UNTIL MARCH 14: DFO NOT MOVE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other night I was hunched over the dining room table, trying
to decipher a diagram I had pulled off the Internet. Around me were
scattered the guts of the family computer, including a faulty
internal modem I was trying to replace. Under my breath I was
cussing out the (at)! computer industry, wondering why they
couldn't make their products more reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly an image popped into my mind of my father back in the
'60s, hunched over the 17-inch family Zenith with a diagram in his
hand, trying to locate a faulty vacuum tube.
</P>
<P>
   Different times, different technologies. But the same problems.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Visions of Technology,'' Richard Rhodes has compiled an
anthology of more than 200 selections tracing the development of
technology through the 20th century. Some of the selections are a
sentence or two; others stretch for pages. Overall, the focus of
the book is not truly technology, but rather the human reaction to
it. Time and again, technology inspires both great hope and great
fear: Sometimes the hopes and fears prove justified; sometimes they
prove to be silly.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lewis Mumford and Benton Mackaye in 1931
anticipated the building of the interstate highway system _ they
called it the Townless Highway _ with controlled vehicle access to
allow high-speed travel. ``With no danger of anyone suddenly
cutting across, with no officious advertiser begging him to halt
and change his tires or his underwear ... the motorist has less
anxiety and more safety at 60 miles an hour than he used to have in
the old roadtime confusion at 25,'' they predicted.
</P>
<P>
   In that same year, another writer was a little more savvy as to
the human price to be paid. ``On the highway we used to meet men
and women. Whether on foot, on horseback, in buggies or even on
bicycles, it was always persons whom we encountered. Now we do not
meet individuals but automobiles ... grim, impersonal machines
which we try to crowd past, unmindful of our fellow-being behind
the glass and metal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dial telephones now seem impossibly old-fashioned, but when they
were introduced in the late 1920s, replacing whole banks of
telephone operators, they confounded many users. In 1930, the U.S.
Senate even adopted a resolution banning dial telephones from the
Capitol because they were too complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we chuckle, that same body today bars its members from
bringing laptop computers onto the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The power of the media is also anticipated in several selections
collected by Rhodes. After witnessing the first television
broadcast of a major political event, the 1940 Republican National
Convention, a New York Times reporter noted that the world had just
changed, that ``sincerity of the tongue and facial expression gain
in importance. ... How they comb their hair, how they smile and how
they loop their necktie become new factors in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Vannevar Bush, a remarkable visionary who headed the U.S.
government's science effort during World War II and later, mused in
1945 about something he called a ``memex,'' an information storage
device accessed by keyboard that would allow the user to travel to
sites offering information related to his topic of research, a
system that sounds remarkably like the Internet with its hypertext
links.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, however, Bush told Congress that the concept of
intercontinental ballistic missiles was some sci-fi writer's bad
dream. ``I think we can leave that out of our thinking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Any anthology is defined as much by what it excludes as by what
it contains. It also inevitably reflects the tastes and interests
of its editor. Rhodes, who won a Pulitzer Prize and National Book
Award for his 1988 book ``Making of the Atom Bomb,'' ranges widely
in his sources, drawing from the lyrics of a Loretta Lynn song as
well as the writings of biologist E.O. Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction, Rhodes makes clear his intention to limit
selections to the 20th century and to draw mainly from American
sources. But some of his other choices are odd. For example, the
most contentious and perhaps most important technology-related
debate at the end of the 20th century involves the use of
biotechnology: genetics, genetic testing, cloning and the
transplanting of genes among plants and animals, among other
issues. There's not a word about it in ``Visions of Technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Because most of its selections are so short and often charming,
the book lends itself well to night-stand reading. Unfortunately,
the lack of length precludes any in-depth discussion of
technology's impact and our reaction to it. Its best pleasures are
moments of startling clarity that put our own modern anxiety about
technology into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   It's somehow reassuring to read of a woman reminiscing in the
1920s about how simple things had been back when she was growing up
in the 1890s. Until the automobile came along, she says wistfully,
families and neighbors used to spend a lot of quality time
together.
</P>
<P>
   Her anxiety is familiar; we still feel it 75 years later,
although today we tend to blame TV and the home computer, not the
automobile. As another writer puts the lesson, ``We do not hate
machines. We hate new machines.''
</P>
<P>
   -- NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   Visions of Technology: A Century of Vital Debate About Machines,
Systems and the Human World. Edited by Richard Rhodes. Simon &AMP;
Schuster. $30. 380 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Moments of startling clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bookman is associate editor of The Atlanta Constitution's
editorial pages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
