<HEADLINE>
HOUSE, ADMINISTRATION WRANGLE OVER KOSOVO TROOP ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House unleashed a bruising rebuke of the
Clinton administration Thursday, rejecting White House pleas to
forgo a bitter debate over whether to send US troops to Kosovo,
amid a critical stage in the quest for peace in the embattled
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank of Massachusetts joined only four
other Democrats in endorsing the Republican-led initiative, which
Democratic leaders assailed as an ``irresponsible'' threat to the
Kosovo peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   After siding with all but one Republican in approving the
contentious debate, Frank criticized the White House for failing to
adequately consult Congress about plans to dispatch as many as
4,000 American soldiers as part of a 28,000-member NATO to
implement a peace deal in Kosovo, if it is reached.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement has been held up largely by the refusal of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept the presence of the
foreign troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how much I like this president, I can't acquiesce
when the administration unilaterally engages in military action
whenever it wants,'' Frank said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a news conference in Guatemala, criticized the
timing of the debate and suggested the showdown could harm the
peace negotiations. ``I do not believe Congress should take any
action that would in effect pre-empt the peace process or encourage
either side to say `no' to it,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, the only liberal among the Democrats who voted with the
Republican majority, also raised concerns about the high cost of
peacekeeping efforts, which generally require additional funding to
supplement the annual Pentagon budget. ``We end up in the situation
where the military budget eats up everything else,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans called for the showdown to protest what they
described as Clinton's penchant for committing the United States to
expensive peacekeeping missions and failing to meet his deadlines
for withdrawing the troops.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert said the administration has
exceeded the Pentagon budget by $21 billion on peacekeeping
missions, including an ongoing commitment in Bosnia that Clinton
had said would end in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the ability and limits of our armed services, how much
can we do?'' Hastert said in a news conference before the debate.
``If we buy into this, what do we do if something happens in Korea?
What do we do if something happens in Taiwan?''
</P>
<P>
   The House Democratic leader, Richard A. Gephardt, blasted the
GOP attack on Clinton's military policy as a reckless undermining
of the Kosovo peace talks, which are scheduled to resume in Paris
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is bloodshed, if there are more killings, if this
thing spreads to other countries, it will be because of the
irresponsible leadership in the House of Representatives in
bringing this up before it should have been brought up,'' Gephardt
said in a news conference after Hastert's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Although the House resolution on Kosovo is non-binding, the
Republican defiance of Clinton at a crucial phase of the peace
talks revealed the stark differences between the White House and
congressional Republicans over foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   The House majority leader, Richard K. Armey, decried the
proposed American role in Kosovo as ``poorly considered and
unlikely to achieve our desired ends.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the National Security subcommittee on military
readiness, Representative Tillie K. Fowler, a Florida Republican,
said the Kosovo peacekeeping mission is ``a recipe for resentment,
not reconciliation, and it will be our troops that are on the
ground and in the crosshairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler, like many other Republicans, said there was no
compelling reason to send American soldiers to Kosovo. ``Could I
tell someone that their loved one died in Kosovo in defense of
American vital interests?'' she said. ``The answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats lashed out at the reluctance among many Republicans to
help the peacekeeping effort in Kosovo. More than 2,000 people have
been killed in the year-long battle by the Kosova Albanians against
the dominant Serbs to regain their autonomy, lost in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Represenatative Tom Lantos of California, a Hungarian-born
Democrat who is Jewish and survived the Holocaust, said on the
House floor that ``isolationism is rampant in this body.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me glad some of my colleagues were not here when the
decision was made to participate in the Second World War,'' Lantos
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
