<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX HOTLY DENY HENRY CHARGES OF MISHANDLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Think it's easy being Dan Duquette? On a day
set aside to celebrate the signing of Ramon Martinez, the Red Sox
general manager found himself angrily denying charges that he and
physician/owner Arthur Pappas had mishandled pitcher Butch Henry
and several other Boston players.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time this spring, Henry, now with the Seattle
Mariners, criticized the Red Sox for the manner in which the team
dealt with him. Last month, Henry blamed his exit from Boston on a
$1 million paycut by an ungrateful team that penalized him for
getting hurt in 1998. Henry pitched only nine innings and two
games.
</P>
<P>
   Now word has come from the Mariners training camp in Peoria,
Ariz., that Henry is laying blame at Pappas, whom Henry says asked
him to work through a knee injury rather than have surgery. Henry
refused and says he might have lost a whole year had he taken
Pappas's advice and waited until the end of last season to have the
operation. Henry elected to have surgery in July, when doctors
found a partial tear of his left anterior cruciate ligament. Over
the winter, Henry signed a $1.5 million contract with Seattle and
may wind up in their starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Charges that Pappas, a limited partner of the Red Sox since
1977, faces a conflict of interest are not new. Second baseman
Marty Barrett sued Pappas and the Red Sox in 1992 and eventually
was awarded $1.7 million in a US District court. The topic
resurfaced last season in the wake of apparent misdiagnoses of
injuries to Brian Rose, Lou Merloni, and Reggie Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   But Duquette will have none of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is well-known that Dr. Pappas is considered one of the top
physicians in baseball,'' Duquette said. ``Why would the other 29
teams be coming to him regularly. If a doctor handles as many as
1,000 patients and you only hear complaints from three of them, I'd
say that's a pretty good record.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette's response to Henry's charges were stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it wasn't just a $1 million pay cut,'' Duquette
said. ``The truth is that at one point we offered him $2 million
for two years. He turned us down. Maybe we did mishandle Butch.
Every time I looked up he was on the disabled list.''
</P>
<P>
   At today's prices, Duquette said, players must contribute. Henry
was well paid in 1997 when he overcame a shoulder problem and had a
7-3 record in 36 appearences. In 1998, Henry collected $1.376
million for pitching nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   Henry's problems last season began when he pulled a hamstring
running the bases during an exhibition game against the Pirates.
After spending the rest of the spring in rehab, Henry came up to
Boston in May and made two starts before suffering an injury to his
left knee. As the days and weeks passed, Henry began to think more
about the 1999 season than trying to come back in '98. So he
elected to have the surgery, against the team's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surgery is always the last option,'' said Duquette. ``That is
why we recommend to players to try everything before surgery. At
the same time, we're not going to ask a player to go out there and
risk his career.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Duquette added, it's the players' responsibility to report
in good shape and stay that way all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what Bill Parcells said? Football players play during
the football season,'' Duquette said. ``In baseball, if you're on a
year-round conditioning program, you ought to be in shape so that
you can help your team. This is the same guy who pulled his
hamstring rounding third heading for home against the Pirates in a
spring training game last year. He did it on the bases. The last
time I looked a pitcher in the American League doesn't have to hit
or run the bases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
