<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-MARBURY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOCKBUSTER NBA TRADE BRINGS MARBURY TO N.J. NETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Minn., Wis.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With their team sputtering and their fan support on the wane,
the New Jersey Nets made a blockbuster three-team trade Thursday
that will bring the Brooklyn native Stephon Marbury, perhaps the
greatest player to come out of New York City in the past 20 years,
back to the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   The move should quickly and significantly improve the Nets'
on-the-court performance and perhaps enable them to legitimately
rival the New York Knicks for the hearts of basketball fans
throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   As the driving force behind the eight-player deal that included
the Minnesota Timberwolves, Marbury's former team, and the
Milwaukee Bucks, New Jersey sent Sam Cassell and Chris Gatling to
Milwaukee and Brian Evans and their 1999 first-round draft pick to
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Marbury, the Nets received Chris Carr and Bill
Curley, who they immediately waived, from Minnesota, and Elliot
Perry from Milwaukee. Minnesota received Terrell Brandon, a
two-time all-star point guard, from Milwaukee, in addition to
Evans.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Marbury is the latest bold move made by the
Nets' new ownership group, which is headed by Ray Chambers and
Lewis Katz and includes Bill Cosby. Since purchasing the club for
$150 million last fall, the group has paid an estimated $350
million to merge with the powerful New York Yankees and form a
groundbreaking partnership called YankeeNets; laid out plans to
build a new state-of-the-art arena in downtown Newark, N.J., to
help to revitalize the city's moribund infrastructure; and made
Jayson Williams, the club's charismatic center, the highest-paid
player in franchise history, signing him to a seven-year, $100.1
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' good fortune came at Minnesota's expense as the
Timberwolves only grudgingly traded Marbury, one of the most
exciting and talented players in the National Basketball
Association. Off to an impressive 12-6 start behind Marbury and
all-star forward Kevin Garnett, the Timberwolves parted with the
third-year guard because of his refusal to make a long-term
commitment to the club.
</P>
<P>
   The team offered Marbury a six-year, $70.875 million contract
extension, the maximum amount allowable under the league's new
collective bargaining agreement, but the player's aversion to
Minnesota's climate and lifestyle led him to reject the offer and
plan to test the free-agent market after the season. Given the
option of trading Marbury for the best possible player or losing
him for nothing in return at season's end, Minnesota took the best
deal available.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time since January that the small-market
Timberwolves lost a marquee player because of lifestyle
considerations. Before this season began, Tom Gugliotta, an
all-star small forward, left Minnesota and accepted less money to
play for the Phoenix Suns. While the club did fine in acquiring
Brandon, the breakup of Marbury and Garnett put to rest what could
have become the league's most outstanding guard-forward tandem of
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, who starred at Abraham Lincoln High School in Brooklyn,
leading it to three city championship appearances, is one of the
brightest young playmakers in the league, along with Philadelphia's
Allen Iverson. His unique combination of brashness, skill and
determination enabled him to lead the Timberwolves to their first
playoff appearance in franchise history last season. Built in the
mold of the new-generation, scoring point guards, Marbury shoots
the ball often, averaging 18 points, but also gets his teammates
involved and is third in the league in assists at 9.3 per game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
