<HEADLINE>
GERMAN FINANCE MINISTER QUITS; EUROPEAN MARKETS JUBILANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ After losing a power struggle over economic
policy that had sent tremors across Europe for months, Germany's
left-wing finance minister, who was also chairman of its ruling
party, abruptly resigned from both jobs on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation by Oskar Lafontaine marked a stunning new turn
for Germany's new chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, who defeated
Helmut Kohl in elections last September but whose government has
seemed confused and adrift ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation had implications well beyond Germany. As one of
Europe's most combative and ideological leaders, Lafontaine had
almost single-handedly talked down the value of Europe's new single
currency, the euro, with his loud and unrelenting demands on the
European Central Bank to lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   He had also shifted Germany, which accounts for more than
one-quarter of Europe's economic output, on a sharply leftwing
direction that frequently clashed with Schroeder's more pragmatic
and pro-business instincts.
</P>
<P>
   But Lafontaine has been unable to stimulate German economic
growth, which has slowed to a crawl while unemployment has remained
stuck at more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets in Europe reacted with thunderous approval
within minutes of the resignation. The euro scored its biggest
one-day jump in value since it was introduced in January. It jumped
from just below $1.08 to $1.10, as investors bet that German growth
could get a lift and that the European Central Bank would have more
freedom to steer its own course. It is widely expected that German
stocks will surge on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lafontaine gave no reason for his departure, and Schroeder
appeared as surprised as everyone else at the resignation. It was
still unclear whether the chancellor would end up a loser or a
winner after the dust settles.
</P>
<P>
   Lafontaine's resignation clearly reflected the disarray in
economic policy and Schroeder's own loss of credibility. German
business leaders have expressed outrage over Lafontaine's plans to
increase their taxes, with some big companies even threatening to
move operations out of the country. Lafontaine had also raised
hackles with American leaders, like Robert E. Rubin, the U.S.
treasury secretary, by campaigning for controls over exchange
rates.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Schroeder appeared to have eliminated a
powerful rival. Lafontaine, a burly and garrulous politician who
badly wanted to run for chancellor himself, wielded enormous power
until Thursday night as the head of Germany's ruling Social
Democratic Party. Although he could never match Schroeder's
charisma and flair for television, he commanded a loyalty among
party traditionalists and among Germany's powerful labor unions
that Schroeder could never hope to equal.
</P>
<P>
   Lafontaine deferred to Schroeder last year, recognizing that he
could never match Schroeder's popularity with voters. But as
finance minister, he then quickly dominated German economic policy
and muscled aside more pro-business moderates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between the two had been rising. Last week, Schroeder
bypassed his finance minister by pledging to German insurance
companies that he would limit their tax increase to about $5
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   He also began seeking out direct contacts with business leaders,
soothing their ruffled feathers in order to keep them from walking
out of talks with the government and unions.
</P>
<P>
   The hostility apparently erupted at a Cabinet meeting on
Wednesday. According to a report on Thursday by the newspaper Die
Welt, Schroeder obliquely hinted about resigning himself if the
government didn't stop antagonizing industry with tax increases and
demands to shut down nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   According to Die Welt, Schroeder railed at ``anti-business
policies'' that were ``against the majority of the people'' and
said he might reach the point where he would ``no longer assume
responsibility for such a policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But people who were in the chancellery Thursday said Schroeder
and his top lieutenants were genuinely shocked by Lafontaine's
decision, which he conveyed in an icy letter just one sentence
long.
</P>
<P>
   In a one-minute news conference Thursday night in which he
refused to take any questions, Schroeder said he was ``taken
aback'' by the decision while insisting that ``the stability of the
work of government is not in question.''
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders at both ends of the spectrum said they were
shocked, and both supporters and opponents speculated that
Schroeder might even seek out a new coalition, perhaps with
Germany's small libertarian party, the Free Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am shocked,'' said Peter Siegel, chairman of the Social
Democratic Party local branch in Limbach-Oberfrohna, near Berlin.
``It was evident that differences between Lafontaine and Schroeder
would eventually surface. But everybody in the party had hoped that
one could handle them in a professional way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hans-Olaf Henkel, president of the German Federation of Industry
and one of Schroeder's toughest critics, was elated. ``This will
give Schroeder the maneuvering room to come up with policies that
are more friendly to business and growth,'' he said Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   That view was largely echoed by Theo Sommer, co-publisher of the
liberal weekly newspaper Die Zeit, whose other co-publisher is
Helmut Schmidt, who was Germany's Social Democratic chancellor in
the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy to see this, because they had lost five months by
trying to do things without knowing how to go about it,'' said
Sommer. Much of the blame, Sommer said, went straight to
Lafontaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was steering the wrong course _ far too ideological, far
too left-wing and too removed from the economic realities of the
country,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joachim Fels, a senior German economist with Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter in Frankfurt, said Lafontaine's departure would be good news
for the euro as well as for German stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the euro's dramatic jump after the resignation provided
powerful testimony to the cloud Lafontaine had cast over the new
currency. When the euro was introduced on world markets Jan. 4, it
jumped immediately to about $1.19 and then began a long steady
slide to less than $1.08 in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that reflected the abrupt slowdown in European economic
growth, and more particularly the slowdown in German growth. The
German economy actually declined about four-tenths of a percent in
the last quarter of 1998 and many economists believe the country
will grow only 1.5 percent this year _ one of the slowest rates in
Europe, except for Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But Lafontaine contributed to the slide by raising doubts about
the independence of the new European Central Bank and perhaps even
backing it into an overly rigid policy just to prove its
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very good news for Germany markets,'' Fels said of
Lafontaine's resignation. ``Schroeder has won the power struggle
with Lafontaine. It now becomes easier for the European Central
Bank to concentrate on economic fundamentals without having to fend
off political calls for lower rates.''
</P>
<P>
   What most surprised political experts was that Lafontaine
resigned as head of the Social Democratic Party as well as finance
minister. But for all the heartburn he caused, some experts said
Lafontaine brought Schroeder invaluable political skills that he
may soon miss badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Lafontaine who held the party together,'' said Oskar
Niedermeyer, a political scientist at the Free University of
Berlin. ``Now there is a danger that the old fights between the
different party wings could surface again.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many politicians immediately began speculating that
Schroeder might reorganize his current political coalition between
the Social Democratic Party and the environmental Green Party.
Several experts said Thursday night that Schroeder might try to
shore up his support by teaming up with the small Free Democratic
Party, which represents a die-hard faith in laissez-faire
deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens have caused Schroeder numerous problems, the most
serious of which has been their demand for a rapid shutdown of
Germany's commercial nuclear power plants. The country's big
utilities have angrily charged that the rapid shutdowns would cost
them enormous sums of money and Schroeder has been openly
sympathetic toward them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Greens will be weakened by the resignation,
because Lafontaine tended to represent left-wing ideas,'' said
Jurgen Falter, a political scientist at the Gutenberg University in
Mainz. ``I would not exclude the possibility of a change in
coalition that would bring the Free Democrats into the government
within this session of Parliament.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
