<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATIC-CONVENTION-276&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ARE READY TO PICK LOS ANGELES FOR CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Mass., Pa.)   (rk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ending months of speculation, the Democratic
National Committee and Los Angeles civic and business leaders are
scheduled to announce on Monday that the party will hold its
national convention here next year, party officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The convention will be in the city for the first time since John
F. Kennedy was nominated in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that a
few, final financial details were being ironed out, but that
negotiations were expected to conclude over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A formal announcement, with the newly elected Democratic
governor, Gray Davis, and the Republican mayor of Los Angeles,
Richard Riordan, has been planned for 11 a.m. Monday at the
still-unfinished Staples Arena downtown, which will be the site of
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just back and forth over who's going to pay for the media
center, things like that,'' one party official said.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, party officials have made it clear that Los Angeles
is their top choice for the gathering Aug. 21-24, 2000. The city
beat out two other finalists, Boston and Denver, home to the
party's general chairman, Roy Roemer, and its outgoing national
chairman, Steve Grossman.
</P>
<P>
   But party officials had worried about who would guarantee the
financing for the convention because the city wanted the party to
sign a contract with the private citizens' committee that was
organized to sponsor the convention, instead of with the city
itself, as usually happens. Officials said Thursday that obstacle
had been overcome and that the party was willing to accept the host
committee's guarantee.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An unusual triumvirate of local leaders _ Eli Broad, a
billionaire businessman, David Geffen, the billionaire
entertainment mogul, and William Wardlaw, a prominent lawyer and
former partner of Riordan _ joined forces last year to head the
host committee seeking the convention, offering about $35.5 million
in financial backing.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the bid became an important element of Los Angeles'
effort to celebrate and show off its successful rebound from years
of economic, environmental and social disasters, and to profit from
the thousands of delegates and journalists the event will draw, and
the estimated $150 million in economic activity they generate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some initial worries by Vice President Al Gore that a
convention might be dominated by glittery celebrities who would
alienate swing voters, administration officials said that in the
end, the lure of California's 54 electoral votes proved too
appealing. California is vital to any Democratic candidate's
electoral strategy, and especially since Davis' election last fall
as the state's first Democratic governor in 16 years, Los Angeles
came to seem by far the most logical choice, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was said initially to favor Philadelphia, but when the
Republicans chose that city for their convention, that was no
longer a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, it's almost anticlimactic,'' said Rosalind Wyman,
the doyenne of the city's Democratic establishment and a member of
the party's site selection committee, reflecting on what has been a
foregone conclusion for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a national convention is such a positive for a city.
If your city shows well at all, it has an opportunity to really
show off. And televising west to east means the convention ends
early here, so delegates and journalists can go out and eat and
spend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
