</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BREAST-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DATA AWAITED ON TREATING BREAST CANCER WITH BONE-MARROW
TRANSPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cancer researchers have announced that by mid-April they will
make public the results of the first four large-scale studies
comparing standard treatment for advanced breast cancer to a far
more aggressive and controversial procedure involving bone-marrow
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   But the findings may well be equivocal, researchers caution,
even though they had hoped the studies would determine once and for
all whether the arduous bone-marrow treatment was worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to come out with a dogma?'' asked Dr. John
Durant, executive vice president of the American Society of
Clinical Oncology in Alexandria, Va., a group representing 12,000
cancer specialists. ``No. In all probability there will be
controversy. But there will be more information than there was.''
</P>
<P>
   Data from the four studies, two from the United States, one from
Sweden and one from South Africa, will be posted on the oncology
society's Web site (www.asco.org) by April 15, and formally
presented at its annual meeting May 15-18 in Atlanta. The four
studies included a total of about 2,000 patients.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the data are still being analyzed, there are hints
that the transplants have not had a dramatic impact. For one thing,
the American studies, which began 11 years ago, were periodically
evaluated by a data safety monitoring board, which would have cut
the experiments short if it had become apparent that one of the
treatments worked markedly better than the other. But the studies
were not interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the principal investigator of an American study of
553 women, Dr. Edward Stadtmauer, director of bone marrow
transplantation at the University of Pennsylvania cancer center in
Philadelphia, said that even though he had been involved in the
research for 10 years, he was still not sure whether one of the
treatments was better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm waiting with tremendous eagerness for the final
analysis,'' Stadtmauer said. In the meantime, he added, his center
is continuing to offer the procedure to appropriate patients with
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The studies, which could influence treatment decisions made by
thousands of women, have generated such intense interest and
speculation that groups representing patients and researchers have
taken the unusual step of issuing statements to explain why the
results have not yet been released. The organizations, including
the National Cancer Institute, which sponsored the American
clinical trials, said the data were still being analyzed and were
not being deliberately withheld.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors began offering bone marrow transplants to women with
advanced breast cancer in the 1980s, after the procedure had been
proved to help people with some forms of leukemia and other cancers
affecting the blood and immune system. The treatment involves
giving patients such extremely high doses of chemotherapy that the
immune system is virtually destroyed, and must be replaced with a
bone marrow transplant.
</P>
<P>
   For breast cancer, the procedure was recommended to patients who
had a poor outlook because the cancer had invaded many lymph nodes
or had spread to bones, liver or lungs. In most cases, instead of
using bone marrow from a donor, the patient's own marrow would be
harvested before treatment and returned afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure itself has risks: the toxic drugs can cause
bleeding and organ damage and leave a patient vulnerable to
dangerous infections. In its early days, as many as 15 percent of
patients died from the treatment itself. On Thursday, Stadtmauer
said, that figure is more like 1 percent to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The transplants became standard procedure for advanced breast
cancer in some medical centers, even though the technique had not
been tested in breast cancer using the gold standard of medical
research, a randomized, controlled trial in which patients with the
same disease at the same stage are assigned at random to one
treatment or another, and monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of hard data, many doctors and patients became
convinced that a bone-marrow transplant was the last hope for women
with aggressive breast cancer. In some cases when insurance
companies tried to deny payment for the procedure (which can cost
more than $50,000), calling it experimental, women sued for
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   It became difficult to study the procedure, because many women
wanted it and refused to enter a study in which they might be
picked for the standard treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Stadtmauer said he hoped the trials would help identify which
patients could benefit from transplants. ``Now, based on the best
possible experience, we know that of 100 patients with metastatic
breast cancer, maybe 20 will benefit from bone-marrow
transplantation,'' he said. ``I would like to make it so that we
only have to treat, say, 30, to get that 20, and we could treat the
other 70 with newer and perhaps better therapies that will help
them more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
