A7116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR-LEAKS-NYT &LR;      03-11 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-LEAKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR'S SPOKESMAN RESIGNS ABRUPTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chief spokesman for Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel who has been investigating President Clinton,
abruptly resigned on Thursday, as Starr asked the Justice
Department to look into unauthorized disclosures of confidential
material from his own office.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, Charles Bakaly, has resigned effective June 1,
but will cease his duties immediately and go on paid administrative
leave until then, Starr said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Although Starr said he accepted the resignation ``with regret,''
there was no doubt that Bakaly's departure and the unauthorized
disclosures were linked. Bakaly has retained a lawyer, Howard
Shapiro, who issued a statement that his client would cooperate
fully with the Justice Department inquiry and was ``confident that
he will be found not to have violated any statute, regulation or
court order.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said he had referred to the Justice Department the results
of his office's internal inquiry into possible unauthorized
disclosures that led to a front-page article in The New York Times
on Jan. 31. The Times reported on that day that Starr had concluded
that he had the constitutional authority to seek an indictment of
Clinton before Clinton left the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's new Washington spokeswoman, Elizabeth Ray, did not
return a telephone call seeking comment on Thursday's developments.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigation of Clinton's attempts to conceal his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky led to Clinton's impeachment. He
was acquitted in the Senate of obstruction of justice and perjury.
</P>
<P>
   The Times article said that Starr had concluded, after
conferring with two constitutional-law scholars in his office, that
he had the authority to seek an indictment of a sitting president,
but that he had not yet decided whether to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The article cited ``several associates'' of Starr as sources of
information and quoted Bakaly as saying: ``We will not discuss the
plans of this office or the plans of the grand jury in any way,
shape or form.''
</P>
<P>
   The article prompted Clinton's lawyer, David Kendall, to accuse
the independent counsel's office of leaking information on Starr's
thinking _ an accusation that Bakaly denied.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said he had no comment on Bakaly's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Oreskes, The Times' Washington bureau chief, said, ``We
do not discuss the sources of our stories.''
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokesman, Myron Marlin, confirmed that
Starr had notified the department that he would forward the results
of his internal inquiry. Marlin said the department had not
received the data pertaining to the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we receive it,'' Marlin said, ``we will determine how
best to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement on Bakaly's behalf, Shapiro said that, with the
``high-profile phase'' of Starr's investigation largely completed,
this was ``a logical time for Bakaly to make the transition back to
the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly, a lawyer from Los Angeles, joined Starr's office last
May. Before that, he was a spokesman for another independent
counsel, Donald Smaltz, who unsuccessfully prosecuted Clinton's
former agriculture secretary, Mike Espy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NKOREA-NUKE-460&AMP;ADD-N     03-11 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-NUKE-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADVISER SAYS NORTH KOREA IS ADVANCING ITS NUCLEAR PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ North Korea is working on its nuclear program,
despite Clinton administration statements that the program is
frozen, according to former Secretary of Defense William Perry, the
president's special adviser on North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing is moving forward on their nuclear
weapons,'' Perry said at a news conference today for the
publication of his book ``Preventive Defense,'' written with Ashton
B. Carter and published by the Brookings Institution. ``They seem
to have other programs under way that are part of a nuclear
effort.``
</P>
<P>
   This month Perry will submit a report to the president on the
effectiveness of U.S. policy toward North Korea, assessing whether
the North has complied with a 1994 agreement that guaranteed it
fuel oil and other aid in return for a pledge to freeze its nuclear
weapons effort.
</P>
<P>
   Last year U.S. spy satellites discovered several underground
complexes burrowed into the hillsides of North Korea near
Kumchang-ni, leading the Clinton administration to raise questions
about the site.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement Thursday the administration repeated its
conclusion that there was ``no basis to conclude at this point that
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea has violated'' the 1994
agreement and that it was pressing for inspections of the
suspicious site ``to be able to confirm that North Korea remains in
compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the North Koreans have refused to allow those
inspections. But the Clinton administration announced Thursday that
it had made some headway in talks with the North Koreans in New
York and that it believes the North Koreans may be persuaded to
allow the United States to inspect the site where North Korea is
suspected of constructing a nuclear reactor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some progress, some headway,'' said James
Rubin, spokesman for the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Since the new underground complex was discovered, the North
Koreans have alternately demanded money _ once asking for hundreds
of millions of dollars _ and food aid in exchange for inspection
rights. The United States refused both requests.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Perry was named special adviser on North Korea to
figure out how to save the 1994 Agreed Framework, which became
endangered not only by the discovery of the suspicious site but by
North Korea's launching last summer of a three-stage rocket over
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   That test caught Japan and the United States by surprise and
demonstrated the North Koreans' ability to launch missiles that
could threaten South Korea, Japan and the American troops stationed
in those countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is very serious,'' Perry said Thursday. ``The
long-range-missile program itself suggests in parallel the
development of a nuclear weapons program.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The rocket launching in turn helped spur the Clinton
administration's decision to set aside funds for the eventual
development of a limited missile-defense system and prompted
Congress to question why the United States should continue honoring
its part of the 1994 Agreed Framework.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated questioning, Perry refused Thursday to divulge
what he will report to the president. He did say he would present
the president with two separate recommendations: one road to follow
if the North agreed to cooperate and another road with ``sterner
measures'' if the North rejected the proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any recommendation that I give to President Clinton will deal
both with the possibility that North Korea will respond to positive
proposals and the possibility that they may not,'' Perry said. ``If
they do not, then sterner measures will be necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent trip to Asia, Perry said he received the necessary
backing of Japan and South Korea, both allies, for the proposals
and that in discussions with Chinese leaders he outlined why it was
in China's interest to find a peaceful solution to the North Korean
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   He said, though, that if the North Koreans refused to cooperate,
``We would expect to have the United States, Japan and South Korea
united in both the need for sterner measures and the way in which
we carry them out.''
</P>
<P>
   In private discussions, Perry has suggested that he will propose
a package deal for North Korea that could include more aid in
exchange for freezing nuclear production and imposing strong
restraints on ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   And if it were necessary, Perry said he would travel to
Pyongyang after delivering the report to Clinton to explain the new
American strategy to the North Koreans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm open to going to Pyongyang,'' he said, ``under the right
conditions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
