<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW VAULTS TO RECORD HIGH BEFORE FALLING BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dow Jones industrial average pushed within 65
points of the 10,000 mark Thursday before surrendering about a
quarter of its gains amid signs that the recent rally has widened
to include stocks that had been left in the wake of technology
shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index reached
records, but the Nasdaq market, which is dominated by
high-technology issues, managed only a slim advance after being in
negative territory for part of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow climbed 124.60 points, or 1.3 percent, to 9,897.44. The
high point was 9,935.46 at mid-session, when the gain was 162.62
points. The S&AMP;P 500 rose 10.84 points, or eight-tenths of a
percent, to 1,297.68. The Nasdaq index edged up 6.25 points, or
almost three-tenths of a percent, to 2,412.25.
</P>
<P>
   More evidence that the economy continues to surge helped fuel
the latest advance, which widened to include oil stocks,
Caterpillar, Coca-Cola and other issues that had been left behind
through a long period of enthusiasm for technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks also caught fire, with American Express pacing
the Dow with a jump of 5 7/8, to a record 123 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is a broadening of the leadership, which is
an encouraging sign,'' said Ned Riley Jr., chief investment officer
at BankBoston. He noted that major averages were setting records
even as popular technology issues like Dell Computer, Intel and
Microsoft remained well below their peaks.
</P>
<P>
   But the rotation of interest did not include small companies,
many of which have been selling at low prices relative to their
earnings. The Russell 2000 index of smaller-company shares was a
fraction lower Thursday and shows a loss of 4.95 percent so far
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be extremely difficult for them to rally until
we get a consensus that the next interest rate move will be down,''
a process that will take two or three months, said Robert Froelich,
vice chairman of the Kemper Funds Group.
</P>
<P>
   Among various unsettling factors during the day, traders said,
was a report that Microsoft would make an announcement at 5 p.m.,
with speculation about the subject ranging from possible good news
on the government's antitrust suit against it to bad news about
sales or earnings.
</P>
<P>
   With the market closed, Microsoft said it expected a $400
million revenue shortfall in the quarter ending March 31 because of
a delay in introducing the next generation of word-processing and
spreadsheet software. Shares of Microsoft fell 15/16, to 160 1/2,
in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really a rotation going on'' in the market, said
Richard Hoey, director of equity research at Dreyfus Corp. ``You
have a loss of energy in the old tech leadership and drugs while on
the other side there is a bounce in oils'' and other laggards, such
as DuPont and Goodyear Tire and Rubber.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts based hopes for higher oil prices on a possible
agreement by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to
limit output, as well as signs of economic recovery in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil rose 3 3/16, to 94 9/16, while Chevron advanced 1 13/16,
to 85 1/16, and Exxon gained 1 7/16, to 74 3/4. Drilling-company
stocks, however, were mostly lower after rising on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola jumped 3 11/16, to 66 3/8, after Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette raised it to ``buy'' and predicted a price of 79 within 12
months. Auto stocks also gained after an increasingly optimistic
Ford Motor said the industry could sell as many as 16 million cars
and trucks in 1999. DaimlerChrysler lifted its projection to 15.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers were mixed despite a strong government report on
retail sales for the first two months of the year, but Wal-Mart
Stores stood out with a gain of 1 3/4, to 95 5/16, nearly double
the 52-week low of 48 3/16 set last April.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage stocks and some banks were also strong after Warburg
Dillon Read recommended several companies including Merrill Lynch,
up 2 1/2, to 89 1/4; Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, up 2 11/16, to 101
3/4; Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, up 1 3/4, to 61 15/16, and
Citigroup, up 1 15/16, to 65 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange expanded to a hefty 909.6
million, with advancing issues outnumbering declining ones by 1,748
to 1,256. New highs, however, barely surpassed new lows _ 82 to 73.
</P>
</TEXT>
