</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKHILL12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The amazing exploits of Jack Hill
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Some would call them breasts and blood, camp and
come-ons. They are the ingredients Jack Hill was sure to include in
his legendary exploitation films of the 1960s and '70s. With a
poetic flourish, he calls them something else: ``The amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Things that were titillating,'' Hill explains. ``I hate to say
sex and violence because those elements are part of Shakespeare and
Greek drama as much as anything. But I had to deliver the goods in
the sense of stuff the audience would pay to see without big stars.
Instead of `Who's in it?,' it was 'What's in it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Quick answer: sassy girl gangs with switchblades, lusty
cheerleaders, cannibals, drug dealers, avenging prostitutes, women
in prison and bundles of crowd-rousing cat fights. And let's not
forget the Amazonian feats of blaxploitation queen Pam Grier, whom
Hill helped vault to '70s stardom.
</P>
<P>
   It's celluloid that unreeled at drive-ins and grindhouses, never
art houses. Ironically, art houses (and video shelves) are where
the visceral thrills of Hill and peers Russ Meyer, Roger Corman and
Herschell Gordon Lewis have been consigned today.
</P>
<P>
   The South by Southwest Film Festival _ itself a kind of
elaborate art house _ will honor Hill with an eight-film
retrospective Sunday through next Friday at venues around town.
Hill, camp crusader Quentin Tarantino and frequent Hill performer
Sid Haig will present the director's best-known works: ``The Big
Doll House'' (1971), ``The Big Bird Cage'' (1972), ``Spider Baby''
(1964), ``Switchblade Sisters'' (1975), ``Foxy Brown'' (1974),
``Pit Stop'' (1969), ``Coffy'' (1973) and ``The Swinging
Cheerleaders'' (1974).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of film festivals have these weighty tributes,'' says
Nancy Schafer, executive producer of the SXSW Film Festival. ``I
just like the idea of really showing off a guy who knows everything
about filmmaking and did a brilliant job and was not heavily
entrenched in the system doing serious, weighty films. He fits our
overall aesthetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Exploitation is cinema without guile, delivering vice and
vulgarity shorn of hypocrisy. Filmmakers such as Hill and his
mentor Corman offered a rebuke to Hollywood pieties, and, better,
satisfied audiences' unspoken yearnings. Like the freak-show
barker, the filmmakers did it to make a buck, and have some fun.
</P>
<P>
   So who was being exploited _ the stereotyped blacks and
half-nude women on screen, or us?
</P>
<P>
   Who cares? shot back the movies, as well as audiences. This was
outlaw entertainment _ frank, unaffected and gleeful, free of
pornography's icky anatomical specificity. Exploitation films
wallowed in their R-rated depravity, and beckoned us to skinny dip
with it.
</P>
<P>
   A KNACK FOR FILMMAKING
</P>
<P>
   A young, established classical musician, Hill went to the
University of California at Los Angeles with the intention of
making musical scores for films. He dabbled in film and writing
courses, discovered a knack, and was encouraged to continue on this
path. His 1962 student film was called ``The Host,'' a 30-minute
shocker based on James Frazer's ``The Golden Bough.'' Apparently,
classmate Francis Ford Coppola saw Hill's project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film became the basis for the third act of `Apocalypse
Now,' '' Hill says. ``My cameraman on my student film was the
second unit cameraman on `Apocalypse Now,' and he said they were
all laughing about how they were shooting Jack Hill's student movie
there. It's the part of the movie that didn't work in my opinion.
Nobody understood it. So if you see my student film, you'll
understand what the third act of Coppola's movie means.''
</P>
<P>
   (In 1996, Tarantino re-released Hill's ``Switchblade Sisters''
under the aegis of his Rolling Thunder Pictures label. The laser
disc and DVD versions contain ``The Host.'')
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s and '70s, schlock producer-director Corman used to
poach the best film students at UCLA and put them to work on his
outlandish pictures. Hill, Coppola and a New York University
student named Martin Scorsese all started under Corman's wing.
</P>
<P>
   Doing all manner of film work for Corman, from inserts to
writing and editing, Hill was suddenly in the epicenter of the
exploitation movie world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kind of fell into it,'' he says. ``I fell into the path
of least resistance doing whatever people hired me to do. But I
enjoyed working on those kinds of films. They were really fun to do
because you had a lot of freedom as long as you delivered the
necessary elements _ the amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill worked on such unabashed hokum as ``The Wasp Woman''
(1960), ``The Playgirls and the Bellboy'' (1962) and ``The Terror''
(1963). Then he was hired to finish Coppola's early directorial
effort ``Dementia 13,'' about an ax murderer in a spooky castle. In
those heady days, a longing to make high art never tugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt somebody was paying me good money to make a
movie and it was my duty to hopefully get their money back and make
a profit,'' Hill says. ``So I always wanted to make audience-appeal
movies, but I wanted to do more than that. I wanted the movies to
have audience appeal but at the same time deliver something on a
higher level, and I think I did accomplish that.''
</P>
<P>
   The first feature Hill called his own as writer-director was the
cannibal horror-comedy ``Spider Baby,'' starring Haig and an ailing
Lon Chaney Jr. Of his films, it's his personal favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chaney loved the script so much and really wanted to do a good
job. It gave him a chance to do comedy, which nobody else thought
he could do,'' Hill says. ``He stayed sober during the whole thing,
which was very, very difficult for him. It was really sad he died
before seeing that the movie would become an international cult
classic.''
</P>
<P>
   FINDING PAM GRIER
</P>
<P>
   It was during a cattle call for his girls-in-prison flick, ``The
Big Doll House,'' that Hill met Pam Grier. Famously, they would
make three more films together, including the blaxploitation
classics ``Coffy'' and ``Foxy Brown.'' The Afro-sporting Grier
packed sex and punch into one voluptuous package. Not until 1997's
``Jackie Brown'' would Grier be so on top of her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pam came in and I was immediately struck by her presence and
authority and personality and appearance,'' Hill says. ``I just
took a chance at giving her one of the leading roles, and she
almost stole the picture. She had a natural talent and so I adapted
the role for her. Of course, after that I wrote the scripts
specifically for her, with her personality very much in mind. She
was very hard working. She got better with each picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more over-the-top scenes and cheese-stuffed lines in
Hill's films elicit groans and giggles in our glibly ironic times.
Hill doesn't take it personally. ``Audiences laugh when they're
supposed to. My work cannot be trivialized,'' he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's intended to, in Shakespearean lingo, play to the
groundlings and also have some higher elements in it, and I think
it does that. As Quentin (Tarantino) says, it has some meaning once
you're willing to participate in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill's directorial career effectively died after 1983's
``Sorceress,'' with which he was so displeased that he removed his
name from it. Time rolls forward and exploitation, save for
inadvertent goofs like ``Showgirls,'' becomes arcana for driven
buffs. Hill still has two action-adventures he wants to make if
he's allowed to.
</P>
<P>
   And if he is, Hill says he will not forget what Corman always
told him, a reliable mantra for the exploitation aesthetic:
``Something has to happen every reel.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
