<HEADER>
A7126 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WING12-COX     03-11 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WING12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Director's first film to play up Austin's computer-effects
talent
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Yesterday, Chris Roberts was known only to PC
gamers. To them, he was a digital rock star, creating dynamic,
addictive computer games.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is the 30-year-old who created the ``Wing Commander''
game series, a series that sold more than 5 million units and made
Austin's Origin Systems an estimated $100 million. He is the man
who started his own game company _ Digital Anvil _ in 1997 and was
immediately given an undisclosed amount (some estimate the sum at
$80 million) by Microsoft, with carte blanche to do whatever he
pleased. He was king, a computer-gaming god.
</P>
<P>
   But that was yesterday. Tonight, everything changes.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight at 8 in the Paramount Theater, Roberts makes his
directorial debut with the Austin premiere of ``Wing Commander,'' a
$25 million science fiction extravaganza based on his game series.
Tonight, Roberts takes off his cloak and crown and puts on his
rookie cap as he introduces himself as Chris Roberts, filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   There's more at stake here than Roberts' ego and potential film
career. This premiere could add another facet to Austin's growing
reputation as an inexpensive filming alternative to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Wing Commander'' was shot in Luxembourg, the
computer-generated effects and much of the post-production work was
done locally, an Austin first. If ``Wing Commander'' is even mildly
successful _ producer Todd Moyer says pulling in even $35 million
would make it a ``huge hit'' _ it will prove that Austin can
produce a commercial film with locally produced high-grade special
effects for, in Hollywood terms, a pittance.
</P>
<P>
   A best-case scenario would result in a slew of new film
productions for the city as well as a reason to shoot effects-based
movies here.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Wing Commander' could be major,'' says Tom Copeland,
director of the Texas Film Commission, a state-funded office
responsible for bringing film crews to Texas. ``Nothing like this
has ever been done to this extent in Texas. Post-production and
special effects have always been done in L.A. This will say to
Hollywood: `If you don't believe things like this can be done in
Texas, take a look at this.' It really could start something new in
Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   GAMING WUNDERKIND
</P>
<P>
   Looking at Roberts, you wouldn't know he was carrying such a
burden. A couple of days before the ``Wing Commander'' premiere,
his attention is trained on one of his favorite scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Though he's seen the movie more than 40 times, Roberts still
giggles while describing the battle to save the main
spaceship.``You see it's like the settlers are circling the
wagons,'' he exclaims in his British-tinged Texas accent. ``The
(spaceship) Tiger Claw seems doomed! But then, the fighters return
and it's like the cavalry has returned to save the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, his brother Erin (a game developer at Digital Anvil)
and his mother and father moved from their native Manchester,
England, to Austin in 1988. The 17-year-old Roberts immediately
recognized Austin as ``really cool'' and wanted to stay. In
England, he had made a name for himself as a gaming Wunderkind,
making award-winning games since he was 13. He planned to continue
here.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts was working on a game called ``Wiz Adore'' in 1992 when
Richard Garriott wooed him to come work at Origin. Soon after,
Roberts began working on a game called ``Squadron.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I started off thinking about battleships in space and bought a
lot of World War II research books to help me get in the right
mind-set,'' Roberts said. ``I thought it would be cool to take the
war in the Pacific and put the fighters dogfighting in space.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting game was the first of five ``Wing Commander''
games. While the first two were action-based favorites, ``Wing
Commander III: Heart of the Tiger'' was a revolutionary
action-based game and computer-based interactive movie. It was
Roberts' first opportunity to display his talents as a storyteller,
a talent his mother says he had from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Chris was small, his father used to tell him and his
brother these fabulous stories and put the two boys in them,''
Susan Roberts said from her West Lake Hills home. ``And really,
when you look at it, that's what Chris does with his games. He puts
the person into the story. To a degree, he also does that with his
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, Roberts had completed five ``Wing Commander'' games and
built a mighty franchise.
</P>
<P>
   GOING SOLO
</P>
<P>
   That year, Origin was bought by gaming giant Electronic Arts.
Unhappy with the subsequent corporate bureaucracy, Roberts and his
colleague Marten Davies began their own company. In the first
attempt by someone in the gaming industry to cross over to film,
Digital Anvil was born with the intention of developing games and
creating movies based on those games.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was good enough to prompt software giant Microsoft and
local computer maker AMD to invest. Even local auteur Robert
Rodriguez bought a minor share of the company because ``it just
seemed right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We started a company on our core strength, which is games,''
said Davies, president of Digital Anvil. ``But we also wanted the
freedom to go into another medium _ the ability to go from silicon
to celluloid.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Roberts wrote a script for ``Wing Commander'' and kept
it for three years before meeting producer Todd Moyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time a game developer has crossed over to
director, and I think Chris has a great vision and, for the most
part, pulled it off,'' said Moyer, who also produced Jean-Claude
Van Damme's ``Time Cop'' and the Pamela Anderson movie ``Barbed
Wire.'' ``I've dealt with all these big money features. I wanted to
do a picture where we had a smaller budget, stick to it and still
come out with a quality product. I think we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   POST-PRODUCTION SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   In April last year, shooting for ``Wing Commander'' was
completed, and the film was brought to Digital Anvil. Here, 19
artists worked on more than 290 visual-effects shots. Though
significantly less costly than a Hollywood version, the film has an
impressively slick look to it. Spaceships and battles look more
like a $70 million production than the $25 million actually spent.
</P>
<P>
   While advance buzz and audience previews of ``Wing Commander''
range from ``flawed'' to ``visual achievement,'' no one has been
tougher on the film than Roberts. Known to be hypercritical of his
work, Roberts is a perfectionist, totally focused on his goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things I would have changed about the movie,''
he said. ``Like the Kilarathi, the bad guys. Next time I would have
done them digitally. It would have been great to have had a really
cool, scary bad guy. Next time I'll do it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts stops, realizing he is validating his reputation as a
perfectionist. ``I just hope people appreciate the production value
they are getting for budget of this film.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Schafer, director of the SXSW Film Festival, hopes the
film will bring some recognition for Austin and its ability to
provide an atmosphere and the talented artists that helped make
``Wing Commander'' a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wing Commander'' is also the first film to carry an actual
Austin brand in the end credits, reading ``Visual FX created in
Austin, City of Ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER BEGINNING
</P>
<P>
   For now, all Roberts can do is sit and wait for the reviews and
box offices numbers to roll in. In the meantime, he plans to go
back to developing games with his brother and the rest of the gang
at Digital Anvil. For the past two years, Roberts' pet game project
has been ``Freelancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Games, he says, are a great respite from making films, because
they contain no time limits. If it takes a few years, then it takes
a few years. Roberts, the digital rock star, doesn't have the time
pressures that Roberts the first-time director does.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, his mind remains focused on his movie. ``Ultimately,
what I'd like to achieve with this film is to see Austin grow as a
film community,'' Roberts said. ``It would be cool if someone was
talking about Austin film and mentioned `Wing Commander.' But as
far as Austin's filmmakers, like Robert Rodriguez and Richard
Linklater are concerned, I don't feel I'm a member of that club
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
