<HEADER>
A7131 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      03-11 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE MOVES AHEAD WITH KOSOVO DEBATE OVER WHITE HOUSE OBJECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is no longer a page 1 story.) 
(wg) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over the fierce objections of the Clinton
administration, the House moved ahead on Thursday with a debate
over whether U.S. troops should be sent to Kosovo as part of a NATO
peace-keeping force should a settlement be reached in the Balkan
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Although any House action on the issue would not be binding on
President Clinton, the debate came at a crucial diplomatic juncture
in the faltering peace effort as a new round of international
negotiations over Kosovo was scheduled to resume Monday.
Congressional officials of both parties said the vote on a
resolution authorizing troops was too close to call, raising the
possibility of a sharp foreign policy defeat for Clinton at a
moment when he is traveling overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution under consideration in the House notes that the
president is authorized to carry out the deployment of U.S. troops
to join a NATO peacekeeping force in Kosovo. But numerous
amendments were pending, including one offered by Rep. Tillie
Fowler, R-Fla., that would express ``the opposition of Congress''
to any deployment of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   Senior members of the president's foreign policy team _ many of
them overseas _ placed calls to lawmakers throughout the day. And
in Guatemala, President Clinton said, ``I do not believe that
Congress should take any action that will in effect pre-empt the
peace process or encourage either side to say no to it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright implored the
House to hold off, saying that a vote against troops at such a
delicate moment would be seen as ``a green light to resume
fighting.'' She was backed by Bob Dole, the former Republican
presidential contender and Senate majority leader, who warned
Congress that a no vote could ``throw cold water on any possible
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an aggressive assertion of Congress' role in foreign
policy, the new speaker, Dennis Hastert, refused to heed the call
for delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tried to be direct and honest with the president and
his secretary of state,'' he said in a speech on the House floor.
``I told them that I believed it was my duty as speaker to ensure
that members of the House of Representatives, Republican and
Democrat, have the opportunity to fairly and openly debate this
important issue before troops are sent into a potentially dangerous
situation. I believe Congress must have a meaningful role in this
decision, no matter how difficult our choice, nor how hard our
task.''
</P>
<P>
   The day was also a test of how Hastert would compare with Newt
Gingrich, a confirmed internationalist. Hastert, R-Ill., said in an
interview late Thursday afternoon that he had told Albright that
``probably my presumption would be I would be favorable to'' the
president's proposal to deploy 4,000 troops as part of a 28,000
NATO peacekeeping force. But he said he would not make a final
decision until he heard the debate.
</P>
<P>
   He was also unapologetic about his timing for forcing the issue
to the floor. ``We need to have an open debate,'' he said in the
interview. ``The White House, I'm just being perfectly honest about
this, was rather reticent to come up to Congress to try to sell
this thing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Rep. Dick Armey, the House majority leader and Rep. Tom
DeLay, the House Whip, opposed the deployment of troops. DeLay
called it a ``big dangerous quagmire'' and ``another bad idea in a
foreign policy with no focus.'' He said the Clinton administration
had become too dependent on air strikes or threats of air strikes,
speaking of bombings in Iraq, strikes against targets in Sudan and
Afghanistan and the threat of air strikes against Serbian targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bombing sovereign nations for ill-defined reasons with vague
objectives undermines American stature in the world,'' he said.
``The international respect and trust for America is diminished
every time we casually let the bombs fly. We must stop giving the
appearance that our foreign policy is formulated by the
Unabomber.''
</P>
<P>
   Through hours of sharp debate that stretched into the night,
House members clashed passionately over the role of the United
States in the post-Cold War world, as well as over the U.S.
leadership role in NATO. They argued over whether outsiders could
ever end the ethnic strife in the Balkans, where two world wars
began, and expressed misgivings about the length of the U.S.
peacekeeping mission in Bosnia which Clinton had once promised
would be of limited duration. The debate split the Republican
party, though most Democrats spoke out in support of the
president's policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recall Bosnia, my friends,'' said Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C.
``The president told us our troops would be back home, I believe,
by December of 1996. But when I last checked, December 1996 has
come and long gone and our troops are still there.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I don't mean to protray myself as an isolationist
but to suggest that Bosnia and Kosovo are European problems that
should be resolved by Europeans hardly constitutes isolationism.
It's isolationism-lite at its best, if that. I just believe we do
not need to insert our oars in those waters.''
</P>
<P>
   In disagreeing, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., argued: ``It boils down
to a simple proposition. Is NATO worthwhile?''
</P>
<P>
   Saying the western alliance was trying to ``stop genocide, to
stop slaughter,'' he said. ``There really is a moral obligation for
those who have the resources to intercede.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats spoke forcefully in favor of the deployment and
questioned why the Republican leadership had scheduled such a
debate when a new round of diplomacy was beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the height of irresponsibility,'' said Rep. Dick
Gephardt, the House minority leader. ``This should not be about
politics. It should not be about giving the administration a black
eye. This is about ending a humanitarian catastrophe and preventing
the slaughter of thousands of innocent people caught in a simmering
ethnic conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eliot Engel of New York said, ``If the United States
Congress votes against sending troops to Kosovo, Slobodan
Milosevic, the butcher of Kosovo, will laugh and laugh and laugh
because we will have given him cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats tried but failed to postpone the debate on two largely
party-line procedural votes _ 218-199 and 218-201.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
