<HEADER>
A7134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ART-NYT &LR;      03-11 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SERBIA: LESS DIPLOMACY, MORE FIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Fighting spread across southern Kosovo
Thursday and Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. envoy, left for Washington
empty-handed after his meetings here with the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But Holbrooke first met with representatives of other nations
involved in trying to bring peace to Serbia, then handed over the
negotiating to the Greek and Russian foreign ministers. The Greek
foreign minister, George Papandreou, arrived Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke failed to make any headway in meetings Wednesday with
Milosevic, who continues to refuse to accept foreign troops in
Kosovo as part of a peace plan. The troops' major function would be
to protect ethnic Albanians from Serbian and Yugoslav forces that
have been harshly suppressing a separatist militia.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, was quoted by the
Russian news agency Interfax in Moscow as saying the conflict in
Kosovo must be resolved peacefully, a reminder of Russia's
traditional sympathy for Serbia and its opposition to NATO's threat
of air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But hopes are thin that the representatives of two fellow
Eastern Orthodox nations, Russia and Greece, can sway Milosevic
before peace talks resume Monday in Paris. Russia has often offered
to intervene with the Serbs, to little effect.
</P>
<P>
   There is no apparent concern in Belgrade that the threat of
airstrikes is serious.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke seemed to acknowledge that Thursday. ``We don't like
to go around rattling rockets and making threatening gestures,'' he
said. ``Our positions are clear and President Milosevic knows them,
and we will be in continuing contact with him.''
</P>
<P>
   He said time remained for a compromise before Monday. ``I don't
want to leave you with a sense of optimism or pessimism,'' he told
reporters. ``We came out here to make clear what the American
position was. That has clearly and unequivocally been done.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Milosevic made clear that he would not accept
foreign peace keeping troops as a condition of the peace plan for
Kosovo, a province in Serbia that is 90 percent Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday his influential wife, Mira Markovic, depicted
America as the ``biggest bully at the end of the 20th century'' in
a speech at the University Left in Belgrade, the independent VIP
news agency reported here.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Markovic, the head of the Yugoslav Left movement and a
radical nationalist, defended Serbia's record, saying:
``Allegations that the interests and rights of minorities in Serbia
are not respected are untrue. These allegations are used by those
who invented them as an excuse to bring pressure and use violence
against disobedient Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbia and Montenegro are the last republics in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As diplomacy seemed to stall, fighting in Kosovo spread for the
first time to the southern region around Prizren, one of Kosovo's
most gracious towns and so far an example of peace and harmony.
Serbian forces shelled the region, near the border with Macedonia,
continuing the strategy of clearing this area of both rebels and
civilians. Thousands of residents have been forced to leave their
villages.
</P>
<P>
   Casualties reported Thursday from fighting on Wednesday were
some of the highest in recent weeks: six fighters of the Kosovo
Liberation Army and 20 Serbian soldiers were reported wounded in
fighting around Vucitrn, in northern Kosovo, according to the VIP
news agency.
</P>
<P>
   There were no casualty figures for the fighting Thursday in the
south.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
