<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEADHUNT-AIR-NYT &LR;      03-11 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADHUNT-AIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH FOR UAL CHIEF SAID TO NARROW TO GM EXECUTIVE AND UAL'S
PRESIDENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ending one of the most closely watched executive searches, UAL
Corp., the parent of United Airlines, has narrowed its hunt for a
new chief executive to two candidates, according to two people
close to the search.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates are James E. Goodwin, who has spent 32 years
at United and was promoted to president of UAL in September, and
Louis R. Hughes, a longtime executive at General Motors Corp., who
was passed over as heir apparent there in October.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the two men present UAL's board with a clear choice
between an airline industry insider and an outsider with a somewhat
similar background to UAL's 63-year-old current chief executive,
Gerald Greenwald, who plans to retire in July.
</P>
<P>
   The UAL board is expected to make its selection at its regularly
scheduled meeting on March 25, one of the people close to the
search said. But this person, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
warned that the decision could be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have been interviewed by the board's six-member search
committee, which will recommend one of them to the full board for
approval. Hughes was scheduled to meet Thursday with one member of
the committee who he had not yet met.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the search has been high because, in addition to
owning the world's largest airline, UAL is the country's largest
employee-owned company. Workers own about 55 percent of the
company's stock, with the unions representing United's pilots and
mechanics holding the lion's share. Each union also has a seat on
the UAL board and together they have veto power over who can be
named chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In September, John A. Edwardson, UAL's president and Greenwald's
chosen successor, resigned after the unions made clear they did not
want him to lead the company following Greenwald's retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever becomes chief executive will have to negotiate new
contracts with United's unions and decide whether to renew the
employee stock ownership program that expires next year. That
prospect in an industry with notoriously bitter labor relations was
said by some industry experts to limit the number of potential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But Madison Walton, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots
Association, whose leader is on the board's search committee,
disputed that. ``We have had many outstanding candidates express
interest in leading our employee-owned company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Plews, a spokesman for UAL, declined to comment on the
search other than to say that that the board ``continues to
evaluate a number of outstanding candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Goodwin and Hughes as final candidates was
first reported Thursday on the Web site Business Week Online.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes has followed a career path similar to Greenwald, who
spent most of his career at the Chrysler Corp. before joining UAL
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, 50, joined GM in 1966 and rose to head its international
operations in 1992. Their $36 billion in revenues last year were
roughly twice those of UAL. Though he was a close personal friend
of John F. Smith Jr., GM's chairman, Hughes was edged out of the
running to succeed him six months ago when the company named his
rival, G. Richard Wagoner, Jr., president and placed both GM's
domestic and international operations under his supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Because he spent most of his career outside Detroit, Hughes has
not been identified with GM's poor relations with the United
Automobile Workers, which has led to several costly strikes. Hughes
has also served on the boards of several European companies,
including Deutsche Bank AG and Saab Automobile AB, where labor
unions are also represented.
</P>
<P>
   But Goodwin, 54, has had a chance to impress the company's
unions since he was promoted to president at UAL six months ago.
Though not well known outside United, he has an encyclopedic
knowledge of its operations, having worked in virtually every
division over the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interaction with Jim Goodwin has been quite positive since
he has become president,'' Walton, the pilot spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the people close to the search said that Goodwin emerged
only recently as a candidate. The other handful of people
considered were all from outside the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin C. Murphy, an airline analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, said that choosing Hughes might make the most sense because
it was unlikely that Goodwin would leave if he were passed over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting a key labor practitioner like Goodwin to run the
airline as Inside and Hughes as Outside,'' he said. ``might be the
best situation of all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
