</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNINSURED-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP FOR THE UNINSURED MAY REST IN TAX CODE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not since the demise five years ago of the Clinton
administration plan to overhaul the nation's health care system
have Americans without health insurance, now more than 43 million
people, received so much attention.
</P>
<P>
   With the post-impeachment Congress determined to demonstrate
interest in domestic policy, and with lobbyists of all stripes
trying to influence the health insurance debate, the
long-overlooked uninsured are suddenly ``hot.''
</P>
<P>
   The road to any enactment of legislation providing them coverage
will be complicated, with many Republicans focused on marketplace
solutions, and some Democrats on marketplace shortcomings. But
across much of the political spectrum, a bit of consensus on an
approach is developing.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than start a whole new government insurance program or
expand the old ones _ Medicaid and the already overburdened
Medicare _ Republican leaders, a number of Democrats and an array
of powerful interest groups are looking for solutions in the tax
system. Proposals receiving serious consideration on Capitol Hill
would give millions of working families, which account for the bulk
of the uninsured, tax breaks or vouchers to buy health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year, Republicans and Democrats alike have
introduced at least six bills that would let the nation's three
million self-employed workers immediately deduct the full cost of
insurance. The bills would speed a phase-in that allows the
self-employed to deduct 45 percent of premiums this year, a break
that under current tax law escalates very gradually and does not
reach 100 percent deduction until 2007.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those measures, others now pending would offer
tax credits (distinct from a deduction in that they are subtracted
from the tax bill itself, rather than just from the income on which
the tax is based). For instance, Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the
House majority leader, plans to introduce legislation this spring
to give uninsured workers and their families an annual tax credit
tentatively set at $800 per adult and $400 per child, to a maximum
of $2,400, to buy insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Armey bill, the credits would even be ``refundable''
to the poorest workers, who earn too little to pay much or, often,
any income tax. With a refundable credit, an individual worker
whose tax would ordinarily be $500, for instance, would keep that
amount and be sent $300 more by the government, giving him $800 to
pay for all or a part of his annual premium.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Democrats who agree with Armey on little else are
prepared to go along with credits, hopeful that by extending
coverage to more people, they can move the nation a step closer to
the goal of universal coverage that eluded President Clinton in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   But others, like Rep. Pete Stark of California, the ranking
Democrat on the House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Health, are
skeptical that the proposals now under consideration offer
meaningful help. Armey's maximum credit of $2,400, for instance,
would pay less than half the annual premium that insurers require
of many families.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the merits of the proposals, there is little
disagreement that the issue's time has come. ``It's a very hot
topic right now,'' said Eugene Steurele, a tax policy expert at the
Urban Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the impetus to deal now with the problem stems from
projections of more than a decade of federal budget surpluses
ahead. ``Why not return some of it in a way that also helps
alleviate the crisis of the uninsured?'' Armey wrote to colleagues
in January.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing in with tax-break ideas of their own are a score of
prominent lobbying groups and policy research organizations,
running the gamut from the Heritage Foundation, the Cato Institute
and the National Center for Policy Analysis on the right to the
Progressive Policy Institute, a group of moderate Democrats.
Similarly, the American Medical Association (an emphatic proponent
of strictly regulating health maintenance organizations) and the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce (an emphatic opponent) joined last month
to promote the idea of tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   The concepts under discussion would be in keeping with a
longtime federal practice of using the tax code as an instrument of
social policy. A provision in Clinton's current budget proposal,
for instance, offers $1,000 tax credits to help pay for long-term
care.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics like Stark insist that the uninsured poor would
find the health care credits too small to be of much appeal _ to
say nothing of deductions, which favor people in high tax brackets
and are all but meaningless to those who earn so little that they
pay virtually no income tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're open to it,'' Chris Jennings, a White House health
policy official, said of the tax credit notion, but ``we have not
found the model'' that could be simply and fairly administered and
be generous enough to reach large numbers of people.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Congressional critics of the Armey approach are perhaps most
heatedly opposed to a Republican idea that would ultimately offer
tax credits to all, so that they could do their own health
insurance shopping. Stark says employers would use the availability
of those credits as a rationale to stop providing benefits, whichin
many cases would be more generous than those that could be bought
with the credits. ``Tell me,'' he said, ``why every employer
wouldn't drop health insurance in a New York minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Democrats who have little argument with ``targeted''
credits, aimed specifically at the poor, see broader credits that
might undercut the employer-based insurance system as a danger that
would leave workers vulnerable to the vagaries of the marketplace
free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   More generally, Henry J. Aaron, senior fellow and budget
economist at the Brookings Institution, finds little promise in
using the tax system to steer consumers into the marketplace for
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the Zeitgeist,'' Aaron said of the emerging
consensus. ``We are into market solutions _ vouchers in education,
privatizing Social Security. Not to be talking about tax credits
for health care'' would seem like ``a gross omission.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think it's got any future,'' he said, adding that
unless Congress created a big regulatory apparatus like the one
envisioned in the long-dead Clinton plan, insurers and HMOs would
pick and choose among consumers, setting premiums low to attract
the young and healthy and prohibitively high for older and sicker
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Ranit Schmelzer, a spokeswoman for the Senate Democratic leader,
Tom Daschle of South Dakota, agreed that ``a lot of things have to
be fixed in the individual market'' before a tax-break approach
could be enacted. She said she did not see tax credits or vouchers
``as something that has a lot of traction this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bills keep coming, and their details vary widely.
Rep. Jim McDermott of Washington, a doctor who is a Democratic
member of the federal commission on the future of Medicare, would
give tax credits to cover 30 percent of the insurance premiums of
individuals with incomes up to $25,000 and families with incomes up
to $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., has drafted a bill that would
allow a deduction of up to $2,000 to each working taxpayer who buys
health insurance privately.
</P>
<P>
   At the extreme is the legislation planned by Rep. Bill Thomas of
California, chairman of the House Ways and Means Subcommittee on
Health. He says he will offer a bill this year to jettison the
entire employer-based insurance system, which covers close to
two-thirds of all workers. Thomas' goal is shared by Armey, who
acknowledges that as a political matter, it is unattainable any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, Thomas complains, Congress gives tax
breaks to businesses that provide insurance benefits to their
workers, and the government allows the businesses to pass the
breaks on to their employees. (That is, the employees are not taxed
on the benefits.)
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, companies pay a worker's entire premium; more
often they pay 60 to 80 percent of it. But more than 18 percent of
all workers, 24.6 million of them, went without health insurance in
1997, according to the nonpartisan Employee Benefit Research
Institute. And about half of those 24.6 million earned less than
$30,000, leaving few with enough to buy insurance on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we provide 100 percent coverage for some workers,''
Thomas said, ``when others have zero? That's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   So he would take away the business tax break and build a new
system based on tax breaks to individuals, who would buy their own
insurance. ``I want to change the whole system,'' he said. ``You
have to go back to square one and rethink it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
