r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISA-SFCHRON &LR;      03-11 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Visa Takes Steps to Keep Big Customers Happy  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Visa's recent reorganization is aimed at making sure more of its
increasingly restive large-bank members don't jump ship, according
to credit card industry experts.
</P>
<P>
   Visa USA announced Wednesday that it has created a new position
overseeing relations with members and merchants, reporting to chief
executive Carl Pascarella. It hired Bond Isaacson, a 41-year-old
IBM executive, to fill it.
</P>
<P>
   The move was announced the same day Citigroup, the
second-largest issuer of Visa cards, said one of its executives
will join the board of MasterCard and that the bank is shifting
most of its credit card business to that association.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacson's appointment was the key move in a series of steps the
Foster City association has taken to shore up relations with the
giant banks that control more and more of its business, industry
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that they're taking their large customers very
seriously and don't want any more defections,'' said Anita
Boomstein, a New York lawyer specializing in credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   The banking industry's merger wave has created giant
institutions that dominate the credit card business, including
Chicago's Banc One, New York's Chase Manhattan and North Carolina's
BankAmerica. Their large market share puts them in position to make
unprecedented demands on Visa and MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, for example, demanded that Visa put its logo on the
back of credit cards so that the bank could use the front to
showcase its own brand. Visa agreed to move its logo but balked at
other Citigroup demands, prompting the bank to jump to MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacson is taking a job that the association eliminated as a
separate function several years ago. Now that function has taken on
new importance as the association's biggest members throw their
weight around.
</P>
<P>
   Visa's new executive will be based in Charlotte, N.C.,
headquarters for BankAmerica. He currently heads IBM's BankAmerica
sales team.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time the association has had such a senior
executive based away from the home office, evidence of how
important Visa considers its relationship with BankAmerica,
industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Visa said it chose to base Isaacson in Charlotte
because most of its members are in the East.
</P>
<P>
   William Stewart, the systems chief who before the reorganization
also headed member relations, said in an interview that Isaacson
brings ``the sales skills we need to go after the huge banks.''
Isaacson, he noted, ``is used to calling on very large customers.``
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of VISA12 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  At the same time, Stewart insisted Visa's reorganization isn't a
reaction to the way big banks are stepping up their demands.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacson said he ``is not being hired to soothe the feelings of
big banks.'' And Visa isn't reorganizing because of Citicorp's
defection, Stewart said, noting Isaacson was hired after a yearlong
search.
</P>
<P>
   As for Citigroup's defection, Visa ``is not agitated,'' Stewart
said. ``We gain customers and lose customers all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Visa's effort to put on a brave face, the association
was rattled by Citigroup's move and will bend over backwards to
keep big banks happy, industry experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They clearly want to work more closely with their key
players,'' said Robert McKinley, chief executive of CardWeb.com, an
Internet service tracking the credit card industry.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of VISA12 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
