</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AOL Will Open Faster Pipeline to Internet  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Californians who use America Online will soon have a faster way to
access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 online service provider is teaming up with SBC
Communications Inc., parent of Pacific Bell, to offer high-speed
Internet access via customers' existing telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5 million Pac Bell customers will have access to the
high-speed service by the end of the year, according to SBC and AOL
officials.
</P>
<P>
   AOL will use digital subscriber line technology, or DSL, to give
customers faster access. DSL is about 50 times faster than
traditional dial-up modems.
</P>
<P>
   The service, when it's rolled out this fall, is expected to cost
$20 per month on top of AOL's $20 per month fee for basic service.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell also offers its own branded DSL service via Pac Bell
Internet for about $40 per month.
</P>
<P>
   One benefit of DSL is that its users can remain on the Internet
without tying up their phone line. Also, they can access the
Internet as soon as they turn on their computers, without having to
wait for the modem to dial up the Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers will be able to upgrade their existing AOL service
and keep their e-mail addresses but get the benefits of DSL,'' said
Steve Dimmitt, Pac Bell's vice president of consumer marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is similar to one AOL signed with New York's Bell
Atlantic Corp. in January. By partnering with both Bell Atlantic
and SBC, AOL can now provide DSL service to 53 percent of its
customers, said AOL spokesman Tom Ziemba.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers said the deal with SBC is an important step
for AOL of Dulles, Va., which needs to give its customers more
bandwidth, or a faster pipeline to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   With competition from cable modem providers such as AtHome
Corp., AOL needs to provide DSL and other advanced services to
retain customers, said Blaik Kirby, who follows the industry for
Renaissance Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is a good thing for AOL in the sense that it gives
them a migration path for their existing customers to a higher
speed alternative,'' Kirby said. It's also important for SBC, he
said, because it makes the company a serious player in the DSL
market.
</P>
<P>
   While AOL wants to offer DSL, the company is continuing to look
at additional broadband services, such as fiber-optic cable and
satellites, Ziemba said .
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't decided that DSL is the only way to go,'' Ziemba
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few drawbacks to DSL.
</P>
<P>
   DSL is faster than a traditional modem but still slower than
cable modems, which access the Internet about 50 times faster. At
$40 per month, DSL is about the same price as cable-modem service,
which costs $40 to $50 per month.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of AOL12 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The service is also not available everywhere. More than 50
percent of Pac Bell customers should have access to DSL by the end
of the year. Customers have to be a certain distance from a Pac
Bell central switching office to get DSL service. Ziemba said AOL
customers who want the service should talk with Pac Bell to see if
their homes are capable of getting the technology. About 5 million
homes in California can get DSL service, according to Pac Bell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
