<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-SHOOTING-ART-N     03-11 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL TOWN SHATTERED BY BIBLE-CLASS KILLINGS OF 3 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GONZALES, La. _ In the seventh row of the New St. John
Fellowship Baptist Church, on the floor next to a viscous pool of
blood the full width of the pew, a Bible lay face up Thursday,
opened to a chapter of John that was spattered in red.
</P>
<P>
   Stained hymn books and notebooks were everywhere, diapers and
slippers and baby bottles, the frenzied residue of a moment of
chaos that occurred when a man kicked open the church doors during
a Wednesday night Bible class and started shooting, killing three
people and wounding four, two critically.
</P>
<P>
   Shon Miller, a 22-year-old homeless man, was charged by Gonzales
police with four counts of first-degree murder and three counts of
attempted murder. Among the dead were his estranged wife, Carla,
25, and their son, Shon Jr., 2, who had cried out to him in the
instant before the shooting. Police officials said that before
bursting into the church with his 9mm semiautomatic pistol, Miller
had fatally shot his mother-in-law, Mildred Vessel, 53, in a van
outside her home nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was shot in the back in a standoff with the Ascension
Parish sheriff's officers and local police after the church
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Any killing in this town of 7,000 people, 20 miles southeast of
Baton Rouge and so unassuming that no one can remember the last
major news story here, would shake the foundations of the social
structure. But to have a massacre in a simple white-brick Baptist
church, in the middle of evening Bible class, in a sanctuary
half-filled with children, was unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a small community _ stuff of this nature doesn't
happen in our quiet little town,'' said Darryl Hambrick, who went
to school with Mrs. Miller and had been her neighbor for years.
``When you go to church for serenity and prayer and for some kind
of peace in your life, and then you go there and something tragic
like this happens, it's sad that we live in a country like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Landry, the Gonzales police chief, said he could not
remember a crime so bloody and disturbing here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safest place in the world I always thought was a church,
and now that sanctuary has been broken,'' Landry told reporters.
``We'll all be a long time getting over this.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootings apparently stemmed from the stormy relationship
Miller had with his wife for the last two years, friends and family
members said.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrick said Miller burned the family's trailer two years ago
and slashed his wife's tires. He was arrested, accused of beating
her and knocking her tooth out in 1997, sheriff's officials said.
Last August, Mrs. Miller received a restraining order prohibiting
him from having contact with her, and he was jailed for 90 days
after violating it, officials said. He lived on the streets after
getting out of jail late last year, and a few weeks ago, Mrs.
Miller told him she was filing for divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told her from the beginning that he wasn't the right one,''
said Timothy Vessel, Mrs. Miller's brother. Vessel's wife,
Lequatta, described Miller as ``crazy'' and ``violent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they were getting a divorce,'' Mrs. Vessel said.
``He just couldn't take the pressure, so I guess he felt he had to,
you know, he had to kill her since he couldn't have her.''
</P>
<P>
   Other family members said that a few months ago, Miller was
dismissed from his job as a welder at an automotive machine shop
here because of repeated public arguments with his wife, and they
suggested that he blamed her for losing his job.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Miller apparently knew his wife and son
were going to Wednesday night Bible class at the church. Jeffrey
Wiley, the sheriff of Ascension Parish, and family members said
that before the class, Miller asked two friends to drive him to the
small wood-frame house on Coontrap Road where his wife was staying.
She wasn't there, but her mother was, and he walked up to the van
in which she was sitting and shot her in the head, Wiley said.
</P>
<P>
   The two friends, who saw the shooting, tried to drive away, but
their car stalled, officials said. Miller then got back into the
car and ordered his friends at gunpoint to drive to the church. The
pastor, Clarence Stephens, said the two men ran into the church and
told him that Miller had just shot someone and was approaching with
a gun. But it was too late to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   He burst into the church, where about 100 adults and children
were studying the third chapter of the Book of John, and fired two
shots into the ceiling, ordering everyone to get down, Stephens
said. As his son shouted, ``Daddy, Daddy,'' Miller shot his wife,
Stephens and police officials said, then reloaded his gun and fired
more shots, killing his son and Vaniaro Jackson, 19, who was
sitting beside Mrs. Miller.
</P>
<P>
   As Miller ran from the church, police and sheriff's officers,
who had been summoned by Stephens, surrounded the church and
cornered Miller in a dilapidated woodshed nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Officers tried to negotiate with him for about an hour, but in
frustration, Wiley said, he ordered a sharpshooter to shoot the gun
out of Miller's hand. He said another officer tripped and
accidentally fired a shot into Miller's back.
</P>
<P>
   The shot paralyzed Miller from the waist down. He was taken to
Louisiana Medical Center in New Orleans, where he was listed in
stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Jackson, Vaniaro Jackson's mother, said he was in church
every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it happened in the streets or in the church house, it
happened, and we can't change that,'' she said. But, added her
husband, William Jackson, ``it puts a big question in your head.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
