A7150 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEVRON-SFCHRON &LR;      03-11 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Chevron Unit Moving Base To Houston  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chevron Chemical, a division of Chevron Corp., told its employees
yesterday that it will move its headquarters to Houston from San
Ramon and eliminate 300 positions over the next year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring, which will reduce costs by $76 million, is
part of an effort to cut expenses at the company by $500 million
this year, Chevron spokesman Mike Libbey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are hard decisions to make but must be done if we are to
remain competitive during this severe petrochemicals downturn and
extended period of low energy prices,'' said Chevron Chemical
President Darry Callahan in a memo to the staff that was obtained
by The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surplus employees will be notified over the next few months
that their jobs will be eliminated,'' the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Maran, an analyst with A.G. Edwards, said many petrochemical
producers are cutting back these days. Chevron, whose revenues
plummeted to $29.9 billion last year from $40.6 billion in 1997,
``is not atypical of the industry at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, corporations stepped up construction of
petrochemical facilities during a commodity boom. But even as
production increased, the Asian economic crisis and weakness in
other economies has caused slumping demand _ and declining prices,
said Maran.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company memo, the headquarters move will occur
by September, and jobs will be cut in both San Ramon and Houston.
Human resources and finance personnel are safe for now, but the
company is studying what to do with those departments, it added.
</P>
<P>
   Production facilities and foreign operations will not be
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Libbey said it is not clear many people will be laid off because
much of the downsizing would be handled through retirement and
attrition. Workers will be offered incentives to retire early, and
some may be hired in other parts of the company, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical division headquarters, which currently employs
about 200 people, is being moved from San Ramon to be near the bulk
of the unit's 5,200 staffers in Texas, Libbey said.
</P>
<P>
   Petrochemicals, such as benzene and styrene, are used to make
plastics for both consumer and industrial use. Historically they
have accounted for about 10 percent of revenues for San Francisco's
Chevron, although that level has fallen recently, said Libbey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
