<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7151 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FACELIFT-SFCHRON &LR;      03-11 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACELIFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Professionals seek new profile with cosmetic surgery  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
It's not unusual for middle-aged executives in today's youthful
economy to feel their careers need some sort of a lift.
</P>
<P>
   How about a face-lift?
</P>
<P>
   A small but growing number of older managers and professionals
are turning to cosmetic surgery as a way to keep pace with their
twentysomething colleagues and competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Women make up the vast majority of cosmetic surgery patients,
accounting for about 85 percent of all procedures. But men are more
likely to cite career concerns as a reason for seeking surgery,
according to local doctors.
</P>
<P>
   For both genders, critics say, cosmetic surgery shouldn't be
taken lightly. Procedures can cost up to several thousand dollars
and, in some cases, can lead to life-threatening complications.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the drive for youth &LR;   &LR; often overpowers these
concerns, particular in Silicon Valley with its emphasis on
constant technological change and its legions of highly skilled
young workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fastest-growing segment of my practice is men in their
late 30s, 40s or early 50s,'' said Dr. Michael Rabkin, a San
Francisco ophthalmologist who performs a large number of laser
eyelid surgeries. ``Their main concern is the competitive business
environment today. They feel that if they're perceived as looking
old or fatigued, they'll be at a disadvantage in the workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 20,000 men underwent liposuction in 1997 _ triple the
number that did so in 1992, according to a conservative estimate by
the American Society of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of FACELIFT () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The number of men getting eyelid surgery rose from about 8,900 to
14,000. The number getting face-lifts rose from about 2,800 to
5,100.
</P>
<P>
   Some men _ even men under 50 _ single out career concerns as the
main reason they're seeking surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roger Greenberg, a San Francisco plastic surgeon, performed
a face-lift and liposuction last month on a 45-year-old salesman
who said his boss was favoring his younger colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though he felt very productive, he feared he was starting
to be treated as a senior citizen,'' Greenberg said. ``He wanted to
have a facial rejuvenation, so he could look as young as he
feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Affatato, a 61-year-old military adviser to the Saudi
government, had a complete face-lift last year primarily to make a
youthful impression on his Middle Eastern business contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think that if you're younger, you must have a lot on
the ball,'' said Affatato, who splits his time between Carmel and
Virginia. ``This is what the Bill Gateses and the Michael Dells of
the world have done. The moneymakers are no longer the
fiftysomethings of Wall Street; they're the young entrepreneurs who
buy stock online. That's why the young look is `in.'''
</P>
<P>
   Other men turn to cosmetic surgery from a combination of
concerns about their careers and general self-image.
</P>
<P>
   One 60-year-old high-tech CEO had surgery on his eyelids and
throat last December because he felt a little out of place among
his young employees.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of FACELIFT () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``I don't think anyone looked at me as being an old man,'' said
the CEO, who asked to remain anonymous. ``It was more internal
pressure. I'm in a business interacting with 35- and 40-year-olds
all the time. I was sensitive to that. ... When I'm interacting
with people now, I feel better, because we look like
contemporaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Some career experts are appalled by the idea of cosmetic surgery
as a solution to age bias in the business world.
</P>
<P>
   They acknowledge that age discrimination is a problem for many
older workers: More than 15,000 people filed age bias complaints
with the federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission last year.
</P>
<P>
   But these critics call surgery a shallow and potentially
dangerous response.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetic surgery typically costs anywhere from several hundred
dollars to $5,000 per procedure. The cost is rarely covered by
insurance. And if done badly, cosmetic surgery can cause
complications such as infections that threaten patients' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are doing this out of fear of aging, but it's a
superficial approach,'' said Ann Eichhorn, executive director of
the LifePlan Center, a San Francisco nonprofit that helps people
over 45 with personal and career transitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were working with these people, I'd try to help them
value who they really are,'' Eichhorn said. ``It's a sad state of
affairs when we get to a point where people take such dire measures
and expense to change the way they appear to others.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cosmetic surgery patients would disagree with Eichhorn's
description of their decision as ``sad.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of FACELIFT () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  They say it's part of a strategy to actively manage their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sato, 54, is a manager at a large Bay Area company who
had eyelid surgery last year to make himself more marketable if he
goes into business as a consultant. When he worked as a consultant
in the past, Sato saw clients reject some of his associates who
looked old in favor of younger but less qualified people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can say that our culture should value age and experience,
but people should also value themselves,'' Sato said. ``People get
caught up in feeling like victims. Taking proactive steps (like
surgery) can help you get over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Silicon Valley businessman who had anti-wrinkle
treatments with Botox and collagen described the procedures as just
one part of an overall effort to stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going hog wild and dying my hair,'' said this man, a
51-year-old telecommunications consultant who asked to remain
anonymous. ``But I have a number of quite important presentations
to give in the next three months _ one here, one in Japan, one in
Ireland. I wanted to do everything I could to make them as
effective as possible. I'd be naive to think this is the crucial
difference. But it's one piece of the overall package.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of FACELIFT () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
