<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7153 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEMPLETON-SUCCESS-NYT     03-11 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMPLETON-SUCCESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLDWIDE LAWS OF LIFE:
 FAILURE IS ONLY A DETOUR ON THE ROAD TO SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Sir John Templeton, the Tennessee-born billionaire and founder
of the Templeton funds, built his fortune on his legendary ability
to perceive value that others overlooked. In his column, he urges
us to recognize the value of spirituality in life.)
</P>
<P>
   (``You are on the road to success if you realize that failure is
only a detour.'' -- Corrie Ten Boom)
</P>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN M. TEMPLETON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. Templeton Foundation Press &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by N.Y. Times Special Features &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If success were easy, then it would not necessarily be true
success. Some of history's most successful people learned to cope
with failure as a natural offshoot of the experimental and creative
process and often learned more from their failures than their
successes.
</P>
<P>
   By taking the attitude that failure is merely a detour on the
way to our destination, hope can blossom into success.
</P>
<P>
   How can we best define success? Does it simply mean that there
was a task before us that we accomplished? If that is the case,
then we could call walking down the driveway and retrieving the
mail a success. Minor matters, regardless of how trivial, could be
defined as successes so long as they were completed. Yet, success
means so much more.
</P>
<P>
   Success comes when we face a challenge and struggle against odds
to succeed. Historically, success has often followed a series of
failures.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many of America's greatest heroes experienced their
share of failures. Abraham Lincoln suffered a staggering defeat in
the first election he ever entered, and was considered a poor and
bumbling speaker. Yet, he became one of our greatest presidents,
whose speeches are still regarded as masterpieces of political
persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   William Faulkner experienced a number of rejections as a young
writer by publishers who had no understanding of his innovative
narrative style, but despite repeated failures and impoverishments,
Faulkner went on to become one of the South's foremost novelists
and to win the Nobel Prize for literature.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Edison was another who struggled with failure.
Nevertheless, through hard work and the understanding that
``failure is only a detour,'' he invented the electric light bulb,
record players, and motion picture -- to name only some of his
inventions.
</P>
<P>
   Because learning is a process that may result in a failure of
one kind or another, failure can be essential to success. It is
important to study our failures, to learn from them, and then to
make a new attempt. Eventually this process can lead to success.
</P>
<P>
   However, if an individual gives up at the first failure, then
nothing has been learned, and no skill has been gained that can
improve our subsequent efforts.
</P>
<P>
   A person is seldom defeated by failure when he understands that
failure can be considered as part of a natural process leading to a
positive conclusion. He can then accept it as a mere detour and not
a dead end.
</P>
<P>
   Often success or failure, happiness or misery, in a situation
may be a matter of perspective. In her book ``The Hiding Place,''
Corrie Ten Boom described a discussion with her mother about Tante
Beb, the aunt who had lived with them for a number of years. Corrie
observed how unhappy Beb was, always complaining and comparing
their home to the ``Wallers,'' where she had been ``so happy'' as
their housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   But mother knew better. ``Corrie,'' she asked, ``Do you know
when she started praising the Wallers so highly? The day she left
them! As long as she was there, she had nothing but complaints. The
Wallers couldn't compare with the Van Hooks, where she had been
before. But at the Van Hooks, she'd actually been miserable.
Happiness isn't something that depends on our surroundings, Corrie.
It's something we make inside ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   If we want to succeed, we may consider blazing new trails rather
than going down the worn-out paths of former or accepted success.
Someone said that the difference between failure and success could
be doing a thing ``nearly'' right or ``exactly'' right.
</P>
<P>
   George Horace Lorimer offered, ``Because a fellow has failed
once or a dozen times, you don't set him down as a failure until
he's dead or loses his courage -- and that's the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Elbert Hubbard commented, ``The line between failure and success
is so fine that we are often on the line and do not know it!''
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Treasury,'' W. R. Beattie presents the idea that real
success can be enjoyed in the process of building-in the drafting
of the plans, laying the foundation, selecting the materials,
measuring the many parts, and then dove-tailing them together. He
felt a person's greatest joys often came from the anticipation of
each day's accomplishments and the satisfaction gained from a task
well done.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, consider a most important room in your ``house of
living'' -- the room of your mind. What you are can be dependent
upon what is in this room. You are -- first and foremost -- a
spiritual being, so the plan for your inner room should be
exquisite, comfortable, and satisfying. This place can represent a
sanctuary of loveliness and peace. Its furniture consists of your
thoughts. The walls must be sturdy in faith, with the colors
showing forth the beauty of strength and courage, joy and peace,
love and goodness, praise and thanksgiving, and positive,
confident, success.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, the light of wisdom must fully illuminate this
room, for it is in this inner room that you shape your world, and
it is here that you may fashion the self that you give to the
world.
</P>
<P>
   As Alexander Crummell, American minister and writer, said, ``All
real success springs from that inward might which we exert upon
society.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Excerpted from ``Worldwide Laws of Life'' by John Marks
Templeton. Published by Templeton Foundation Press)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-EU-NYT &LR;      03-11 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-EU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY BARRIER KEEPS EAST EUROPE OUT OF THE EUROPEAN UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See also NATO and EUROPE-FARMS)  
(DW) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Now that Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary are
joining the NATO alliance, perhaps the European Union might be less
afraid about letting them in too, President Vaclav Havel of the
Czech Republic observed during a recent swing through Western
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The curtain that came down 50 years ago was ripped away 10
years ago, but in certain respects, it still exists as a kind of
psychological barrier,'' he said recently. ``Admission into NATO is
a significant step, because we see that the West is not afraid of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after the collapse of the Iron Curtain, the most
important barrier still separating the east of Europe from the more
fortunate west is money.
</P>
<P>
   While the Atlantic alliance, led by the United States, is
willing to see the first three formerly Communist countries as full
partners, the European Union is still years away from admitting any
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most important reasons are the costs.
</P>
<P>
   According to the accession agreements they have worked out with
the alliance, Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary together will
be assessed only about $65 million a year for NATO programs,
according to allied officials in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   But offsetting this, the alliance plans to put $150 million a
year for the next 10 years into helping the three countries improve
military airfields, communications networks and air defenses they
had built as members of the Warsaw Pact.
</P>
<P>
   Poland plans to raise its military budget to $3.3 billion this
year, half a billion more than in 1997, while the Czech Republic
and Hungary plan to spend $1.2 billion and $745 million in 1999,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   All three new members might well have been tempted to spend more
on their militaries if they were not entering the collective
security of NATO, supporters of expansion say. Skeptics say that
NATO's cost estimates are much too low.
</P>
<P>
   But joining NATO looks almost easy compared with the costs and
the complexities of joining the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Letting poorer countries from Eastern Europe join the European
Union will cost both new and old members of that organization
money, though hardly as much as the United States spent after World
War II in the Marshall Plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West spent a lot on armament,'' Gyorgy Konrad, a Hungarian
writer, lamented at a recent gathering of central European and
western policy makers and intellectuals in Berlin. ``It appears not
to want to spend a lot on solidarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, starting with Germany, the cry from the rich but
unemployment-plagued European countries is to spend less, not more,
on items like farm programs, which cost Europe nearly $44 billion
last year, 45 percent of the total European Union budget.
</P>
<P>
   After wrangling all winter between Germany and France, European
agriculture ministers finally agreed Thursday, after negotiating
all night, to cut price supports for grain, beef and dairy products
by 15 to 20 percent over the next few years. But experts believe
more changes are necessary before countries like Poland, with tens
of thousands of small farmers, join the system.
</P>
<P>
   The agricultural policy was set up at the end of the 1950s, when
German leaders still felt guilty about what the Nazis had done to
France. The goal was to keep French farmers, then far more numerous
than they are now, prosperous while German industry got free access
to French and other European markets.
</P>
<P>
   But Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who was not even alive during
World War II, questions why Germany pays more in farm support
programs than it receives. Now, like many of his generation, he
does not see why Germany should be asked to foot more than its
share of the European bill.
</P>
<P>
   Spain, Portugal and Italy are fighting proposed cuts in European
regional infrastructure investment programs. Almost all countries
are fighting changes in cumbersome decision-making procedures that,
with 15 member states, often make European Union meetings last all
night.
</P>
<P>
   Without change, European leaders keep saying, new members could
bring only total gridlock or bankruptcy. But change will surely
take a few more all-night meetings like a special European summit
conference planned later this month in Berlin, the third such
meeting since last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Hans van den Broek, the European commissioner for foreign
affairs, said that the European Union was spending $1.6 billion a
year helping prospective new members get ready. ``The candidates
have to be able to adopt and, more importantly, implement some
80,000 pages of laws,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All this will take time, he says, time the formerly Communist
countries also need to make sure their economies are not
overwhelmed and crushed by more powerful Western ones when they
join the European Union and trade barriers come down.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, even Havel's target of 2002 for membership for the
Czech Republic looks optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``European leaders spent more time at their summit in Vienna in
December talking about ways to postpone abolishing duty-free shops
next year than they did about the prospect of admitting countries
from Eastern Europe,'' said the French philosopher Andre
Glucksmann. ``I think we have wasted 10 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 2141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RJR-NABISCO-540&AMP;ADD-N     03-11 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-NABISCO-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 FIGHTING RJR, ICAHN DEMANDS THAT IT SPIN OFF NABISCO STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two days after RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. announced that it was
splitting up its food and tobacco businesses, its biggest investor,
Carl C. Icahn, said Thursday that he was not happy with the plan
and would wage a proxy fight to get the company to create a
separate entity from its stake in Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn's decision came one day ahead of a deadline Friday for
filing an alternate slate of directors for RJR Nabisco two months
in advance of the company's annual meeting. In a telephone
interview, he said the board that he had assembled would include
himself. He refused to name the other members but was clear about
their agenda. ``It's going to be a board that will unquestionably
do the spinoff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, RJR said it would get out of the tobacco business by
selling its international tobacco business to Japan Tobacco for $8
billion and spinning off its domestic tobacco operations. Under the
plan, RJR's only asset would be the 80.6 percent of Nabisco that it
owns.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement Thursday afternoon, Icahn, who recently
acquired about 7.7 percent of RJR's shares, said he thought
shareholders would benefit more if the company spun off Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   Steven F. Goldstone, the chairman and chief executive of RJR
Nabisco, said in a statement that Icahn's idea would not work. ``If
I thought it was practical, I would have done it myself,'' he said.
``But a Nabisco spinoff can't get done, and we are going to do what
can actually get done.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the liability from lawsuits over smoking.
</P>
<P>
   RJR management has said that the company could not spin off
Nabisco without incurring more problems from critics who would
accuse it of a so-called fraudulent transfer of assets, stripping
away holdings that might otherwise be used to pay claims in
tobacco-related litigation. Experts say the company's new structure
means that plaintiffs could turn to the holding company to collect
their claims, should the assets of the tobacco company, to be
called R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, run out.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn said he and his lawyers disagreed. Jay Mayesh, a partner
in the law firm Stroock &AMP; Stroock &AMP; Lavan, who is advising Icahn,
said, ``There's a big difference between talking about a fraudulent
transfer and proving it.''
</P>
<P>
   RJR shares have been trading well below the price of Nabisco
shares that are held by the public. Thursday, RJR closed unchanged
at $30 a share, while Nabisco closed at $42.1875. Marginal movement
in RJR's share price since Tuesday was obviously a factor in
Icahn's decision to press ahead with his proxy fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Steve Goldstone I think you did the right thing in
selling international and you moved to enhance value,'' Icahn said,
``but if the stock went up on the news, I wouldn't win this proxy
fight and it would be stupid to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Wall Street had backed away from RJR stock in
recent days because of concern that his huge stake was about to be
sold, Icahn said such fears were misguided. ``I'm not going to sell
my stock until after the meeting, that's for sure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders will have to vote for either management's proposal
or Icahn's at the RJR annual meeting on May 12 in Winston-Salem,
N.C.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Continued worries about the effect of tobacco-related litigation
have kept many investors away from companies like RJR.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn said that if his plan was adopted, there would be no more
such ``tobacco taint.'' Indeed, he said he thought the price of
Nabisco would rise significantly over all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be no discount,'' he said. ``You'd go to the kinds
of multiples you see at other food companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Icahn has tried repeatedly to get the management of RJR to spin
off the food business, especially since a leveraged buyout in the
late 1980s left the company with a huge debt.
</P>
<P>
   One lawyer involved in tobacco litigation said that the point of
Icahn's plan seemed to be to avoid further liability on smoking
claims but that the move itself would probably stir lawsuits of
another kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do it Icahn's way, I am sure there would be people to
challenge it,'' said Joe Rice, a lawyer in Charleston, S.C., who
represents 25 of the state attorneys general who settled claims
against cigarette companies for $206 billion last year. ``The sole
purpose of the spinoff is to free it from tobacco liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Black, a tobacco analyst for Sanford Bernstein &AMP; Co., said
he agreed with Icahn's proposal because it would remove the risk of
liability from the Nabisco shares. At the same time, he added:
``He's got an uphill battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Icahn said he was hoping to keep the proxy fight focused on the
single issue of which entity to spin off. ``I'm not here to say
that Steve Goldstone is a bad guy,'' he said. ``I hope it doesn't
elevate to anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Goldstone offered some saber-rattling of his
own. ``My goal is to complete the sale of Reynolds International
and the spinoff of Reynolds Tobacco promptly after our annual
meeting on May 12th,'' he said. ``I want to assure our shareholders
that I won't permit our company to get diverted from that critical
objective by playing public proxy games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
