<HEADLINE>
UTAH EXCEEDS EARLY FORECAST BY MAJERUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ When the Utah basketball team arrived here
Wednesday, coach Rick Majerus promptly did the obvious thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the players out to eat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Majerus, whose success as a coach is matched only by his
legendary accomplishments in various buffet lines, also noted that,
``It wasn't really a place I would have picked myself, but it was
instructive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they can all say they've eaten alligator.''
</P>
<P>
   These Utes (27-4) can also say they've made the NCAA Tournament,
a notion that once seemed about as likely as the idea that they
would be dining on gator in the French Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After last year's team lost to Kentucky in the NCAA championship
game, Majerus gazed into the future and designated 1998-99 a
``rebuilding year.'' Actually, it's turned out fairly well.
</P>
<P>
   Utah will open play in the Midwest Region against Arkansas State
(18-11) at 11:30 a.m. today (KTVT/Channel 11) at the Superdome,
coming in as the second seed and riding a 22-game winning streak,
having finished the regular season ranked sixth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon's second game will feature Washington (17-11)
against Miami of Ohio (22-7). Kansas (22-9) will face Evansville
(23-9) at 6:50 p.m., after which third seed Kentucky (25-8) will
match up against New Mexico State (23-9).
</P>
<P>
   ``We began the season relatively young and inexperienced,'' said
Majerus, ``although some early notions of our strength may have
been a little harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``My original assessment was based not so much on losing Michael
Doleac off last year's team as it was on the fact that three of our
best players went off on missions for the \RMormon\S church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one kid who was a real gun, but he's now riding his
bike through Ecuador, proselytizing for the church. We have other
team members in Mexico City and Houston. We may be pretty good when
they come back.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Arkansas State coach Dickey Nutt is concerned, the
Utes look pretty good right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, for starters, they have the best coach in the country,
and maybe the best point guard in the country,'' Nutt said. ``Here
we are, in the tournament for the first time ever, living our dream
... and we draw Utah.''
</P>
<P>
   The point guard in question is Andre Miller, the Western
Athletic Conference Player of the Year and a man who is not
surprised at success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it a surprise that we've had this kind of
season,'' he said. ``In the past few years we've had teams that had
high-profile stars like Doleac and Keith Van Horn _ and maybe we
don't have that this year. But this is a team that does a lot of
things well.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah has not lost since Dec. 12, and Majerus credits much of the
growth to a killer road trip early in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a 15,000-mile round trip
\RHawaii-Chicago-California-Texas\S where we were on the road for
22 of 26 days,'' he said. ``We learned a lot about each other, and
when it was over we were a different team.'' \Ntagtop:Whit Canning,
(817) 390-7760
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
