<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRACUSE ENDS A DISAPPOINTING SEASON WITH LOSS TO OKLAHOMA STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BARRY JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The quality of Syracuse's season was reflected in
its seeding in the NCAA tournament: No. 8, the lowest of Coach Jim
Boeheim's 23-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen were inconsistent, failing to put together more
than two consecutive victories since the start of the season.
Despite one of the nation's better defenses, Syracuse lost five of
its last 10 games entering the South Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Oklahoma State ended those struggles, shrugging off
Syracuse's only serious threat to pull away to a 69-61 victory in
the opening round before a crowd of 27,184 in the RCA Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the case all year,'' Ryan Blackwell, a Syracuse
junior, said. ``We have the players, but we just don't put our
minds to it and go out and do what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, ninth-seeded Oklahoma State (23-10), an at-large
entrant from the Big 12, will face top-seeded Auburn, an 80-41
winner Thursday over No. 16 Winthrop.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen (21-12) trailed Oklahoma State from the outset, as
the game fell into a frustrating pattern for Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Big East club kept the Cowboys from building a
substantial lead, for more than 29 minutes the Orangemen could not
pull closer than three points. That is because Syracuse failed to
contain Oklahoma State's outside shooters, who made 8 of 18 shots
from 3-point range, many when the Orangemen mixed up their
defensive looks by going to a man-to-man alignment.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Adrian Peterson, who finished with 21 points, led Oklahoma
State's barrage by hitting 5-of-8 3-point attempts. The
6-foot-4-inch senior also had six offensive rebounds, all in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   When Syracuse employed its 2-3 zone, Cowboy playmaker Doug
Gottlieb repeatedly found open teammates, recording 11 assists
without taking a shot. His feeds helped forward Desmond Mason to a
28-point performance, his best showing in two months.
</P>
<P>
   Mason and Peterson scored all but two of Oklahoma State's points
as it led, 33-30, at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The game's single tie came on a baseline jumper by Damone Brown
with 2 minutes 51 seconds remaining. That was the closest Syracuse
had come since the game was about seven minutes old and Jason
Hart's 3-pointer had cut the Oklahoma State lead to 9-8. But 27
seconds after Syracuse caught up, Joe Adkins, a junior guard, made
his only shot of the game, a 3-pointer that pushed the Cowboys
ahead, 60-57.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse responded with a jumper from Blackwell with 1:59 left,
cutting the edge to 60-59. That would be as close as the Orangemen
came as the reserve forward Brian Montonati scored consecutive
baskets, sparking a 9-2 run to close the game for Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   Etan Thomas, showing no signs of the hand injury he sustained in
the Big East tournament, finished with 21 points for Syracuse. Hart
had 17.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was only the third in the opening round for a Boeheim
team in 19 NCAA appearances.
</P>
<P>
   AUBURN 80, WINTHROP 41
</P>
<P>
   Auburn (28-3) held Winthrop to the lowest point total in NCAA
play since 1996, when Mississippi State beat Princeton, 63-41, in
this same arena.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied, 13-13, midway through the first half when the
Tigers, winner of the Southeastern Conference, hit their stride.
They finished the half with a 24-5 rush, forcing nine turnovers and
holding Winthrop, the Big South Conference champion, to 2 of 13
shooting after it forged the tie on a free throw by forward Jacques
Vandescure.
</P>
</TEXT>
