<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, CENTRAL AMERICAN LEADERS SIGN AGREEMENT 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTIGUA, Guatemala - With President Clinton offering economic
incentives, the leaders of seven Central American and Caribbean
nations reaffirmed pledges Thursday to improve human rights, combat
crime and drugs, and clean up the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, hammered out over the past several weeks in
Washington, was signed in this historic city on the final stop of
Clinton's four-day tour of the region wracked 4-1/2 months ago by
Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Central America has had a long and difficult season aggravated
by the recent hurricanes,'' Clinton said against a backdrop of
stone buildings draped with bougainvillea. ``But we can truly
rejoice that the springtime of renewal and rebuilding is here.``
</P>
<P>
   The document was similar to an agreement the leaders signed in
Costa Rica two years ago. Although lacking historical drama, the
document signed Thursday served as a recommitment to programs
designed to strengthen the economies of the emerging democracies.
</P>
<P>
   On the outskirts of Antigua, the former capital of Guatemala, a
handful of protesters blocked a bus shuttling journalists and White
House staff members to the summit. It was the second demonstration
in two days against U.S. involvement in Guatemala's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton arrived in Guatemala City on Wednesday, he remained
aboard Air Force One for almost a half-hour until the Secret
Service determined that a demonstration outside the National Palace
was under control. Later, while Clinton was speaking inside,
several hundred protesters outside chanted anti-American slogans
and ``Viva Monica,'' referring to Clinton's ex-paramour, Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In the shadow of church ruins dating to the 18th century,
Clinton signed Thursday what is being called ``The Declaration of
Antigua.'' Also signing the document were Presidents Alvaro Arzu of
Guatemala, Arnoldo Aleman of Nicaragua, Carlos Flores Facusse of
Honduras, Armando Calderon Sol of El Salvador, Migues Rodriguez of
Costa Rica and Leonel Fernandez of the Dominican Republic, and
Prime Minister Said Wilbert Musa of Belize.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration included pledges from Clinton to forgive loans,
revise immigration laws and lower trade barriers to help stimulate
economic recovery for the emerging democracies, promises that hinge
on his ability to convince Congress to agree.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for a $956 million aid package Clinton wants
Congress to approve to help with storm recovery in Guatemala, El
Salvador, Nicaragua and Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's best chance to deliver on his end of Thursday's
agreement is the forgiveness of major portions of loans owed the
U.S. by Nicaragua and Honduras. Under the agreement, 90 percent of
Nicaragua's debt would be written off; 67 percent of what Honduras
owes Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In private meetings with Clinton earlier in the week, four of
the Central American presidents expressed disappointment in what he
has proposed in the Caribbean Basin Initiative he sent to Congress
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, said the
initiative falls short of the trade latitude given Mexico under the
North American Free Trade Agreement, which the Central Americans
see as vital to attracting investment necessary to provide jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, who was present during Clinton's meetings with the
presidents of Nicaragua, Honduras, El Salvador and Guatemala, said
damage from Hurricane Mitch has compounded the economic woes of the
four developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   Given organized labor's opposition to lowering trade barriers
that might threaten U.S. jobs, the limited trade package was the
best Clinton could hope to get through Congress, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   On immigration, Clinton has remained firm about enforcing U.S.
immigration laws and protecting the nation's borders. At the same
time, he has acknowledged the unfairness of regulations governing
legal migration from Central America and has promised to push
Congress to rewrite the laws.
</P>
<P>
   Already angry over Washington's plan to resume deporting illegal
immigrants back to their countries, the Guatemalan and Salvadoran
presidents reportedly balked over the weekend at signing the
document because of clauses seeking to end illegal migration and
exploitation of under-age workers.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's summit, Arzu, the Guatemalan president, said
Hurricane Mitch showed the need for ``an integral plan for
development'' in Central America, and predicted the area would
prosper if it is allowed access to world markets.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, he said, there will be less pressure on Central
Americans to seek jobs in the United States. ``If we want for
democracy to remain with us forever, we must be sure it is
translated into evident and tangible benefits for our people,''
Arzu said. ``If we want for our people to stay ... we need to offer
them the opportunities that we now only find abroad.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
