<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS LOOK INTO CRUISE-LINE TAX EXEMPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Miss.)  (mk) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying the United States could be losing billions of dollars
each year, two Democratic congressmen asked the IRS Thursday to
estimate how much foreign-owned cruise companies are saving because
of tax code provisions that exempt them from income tax and other
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The congressmen, Peter DeFazio of Oregon and Gene Taylor of
Mississippi, said in a letter to the IRS commissioner, Charles
Rossotti, that they wanted the assessment because Congress might
take up legislation later this year to expand access to U.S. ports
by foreign-owned passenger ships.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary estimates from the Clinton administration are that
the tax provisions allow the industry to avoid billions of dollars
a year in federal taxes, DeFazio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that a large, growing and very profitable
U.S.-based industry is escaping all of its federal tax burden,''
DeFazio said in a telephone interview. ``This is a basic issue of
fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the cruise industry, which has annual
revenues of about $10 billion, say that the unique tax exemption is
part of international transportation law and that the industry pays
millions of dollars a year in port fees and other charges. A new
study for the industry found that it bought $6.6 billion worth of
American goods and generated 176,433 jobs in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very proud of the contribution which the cruise
industry makes to the U.S. economy,'' said Cynthia Colenda,
president of the International Council of Cruise Lines, the
industry trade group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 17 major cruise lines are based in the United States
and rely on American passengers, they are exempt from U.S. income
tax and some other taxes because the companies are registered in
foreign countries and their ships fly foreign flags. The countries
in which those companies are registered do not have income tax.
</P>
<P>
   An article last month in The New York Times described the tax
benefits and said Carnival Corp., the world's largest cruise
company, earned $2 billion in the last three years yet paid less
than 1 percent in income taxes. Those taxes were on revenue from
hotels and tours in the United States. Carnival is based in Miami
but registered in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Under longstanding tax law, to qualify for the income tax
exemption, foreign cruise lines operating from an American port
must visit a foreign destination before returning to the United
States. But last year Congress debated relaxing the law to permit
foreign ships to transport passengers between U.S. ports without a
foreign stop.
</P>
<P>
   Some American port and tourism officials pushed for the change
to increase tourism. The domestic cruise industry opposed it,
arguing that American ships would have difficulty competing with
foreign vessels that pay no taxes.
</P>
<P>
   DeFazio, the ranking Democrat on the House Transportation and
Infrastructure Committee's Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation
subcommittee, said he expects the issue of expanding access to
American ports to arise again.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for taxing foreign cruise companies appear slim
despite some support. In January, the Senate majority leader, Trent
Lott of Mississippi, called on the administration to work with
Congress to re-examine tax policies that might stifle the domestic
cruise business.
</P>
<P>
   But DeFazio acknowledged that he faces a tough battle against
the foreign cruise companies, which lobby effectively. ``I've been
told I'm walking into a buzz saw,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7171 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETH     03-11 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT DENIES IGNORING EVIDENCE OF NUCLEAR SPYING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTIGUA, Guatemala _ President Clinton vigorously denied on
Thursday that the administration had minimized evidence of nuclear
spying by China and defended his policy of engagement with Beijing
as the only effective means of restraining Chinese behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he was under no illusions about China's covert
efforts to acquire American nuclear weapons technology. He said
that when he received persuasive evidence that highly classified
data about American nuclear weapons design had been leaked from the
Department of Energy's Los Alamos National Laboratory, he acted
aggressively to contain the damage and prevent further incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not ignore evidence. Quite the contrary, we acted on
it,'' the president said at a news conference at the conclusion of
a summit meeting with Central American leaders. ``I believe the
record is clear that we did respond in an appropriate way.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments on Thursday were his first public statements
since reports emerged over the weekend that a Chinese-American
scientist at Los Alamos might have been responsible for providing
information in the 1980s that enabled China to develop a
miniaturized nuclear warhead similar to the most sophisticated
weapons in the American arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has opened an investigation of the case, including
allegations that the administration sought to play down the
severity of the suspected espionage and delay the investigation so
as not to jeopardize its policy of reconciliation with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill on Thursday, Republicans toned down their fiery
criticisms of the administration's handling of the Los Alamos spy
case, perhaps sensing that undue hysteria was creeping into their
response.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert echoed Clinton's call to remain engaged
with Beijing. ``The more we're involved with China, the better off
we are _ for us and for China and the Pacific area,'' Hastert said
in an interview. ``It's also important that we stress our views on
human rights. If we aren't engaged, we can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he did not become aware of the potential scope
of the technology transfer until July 1997, when he was briefed on
a continuing FBI inquiry into a case of possible espionage at the
Energy Department laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   The initial investigation produced evidence not only of a hugely
damaging transfer of American nuclear technology, but of systemic
leakage of military secrets from the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, we moved quickly and decisively,'' Clinton said,
``not only with the continuing FBI investigation and a CIA review,
but also with an intense review of the counterintelligence
capacities of our Energy Department labs.''
</P>
<P>
   But American officials have said that the federal government's
drawn-out effort to track down the possible leak was plagued by
delays, inaction and skepticism _ even though senior intelligence
officials considered it one of the most damaging spy cases in
recent history. For instance, a recommendation by the FBI in April
1997 that background checks be reinstated on visitors to Los Alamos
was ignored for 17 months by the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly three years later, no arrests have been made. A
prime suspect in the case, a Taiwan-born scientist at Los Alamos
National Laboratory, was fired on Monday after three days of
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that beginning in early 1998 he had
significantly tightened security at the weapons facilities,
including requiring polygraph examinations for employees with
access to critical information.
</P>
<P>
   And he asserted that the intelligence committees of Congress
have received 16 briefings on the matter since 1997, despite angry
complaints from members that the administration kept them largely
in the dark about the alleged spying.
</P>
<P>
   He also rejected calls from some Republican presidential
hopefuls that he dismiss Sandy Berger, the national security
adviser, whom some have accused of foot-dragging in the spy case in
order to protect and justify his support for a policy of close
cooperation with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mr. Berger acted appropriately and therefore I would
not release him or ask for his resignation. I just don't think
there's any evidence to support that,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN BEGIN HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Craig Thomas, a conservative Republican from Wyoming who
heads the Foreign Relations subcommittee for Asia, dismissed as
``premature'' the demands for Berger's resignation. ``I've never
supported the idea that every time China does something we don't
like we ought to submit a thing to the Senate and get after them,''
Thomas told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met twice with Jiang Zemin, the Chinese president, in
the fall of 1997 and the summer of 1998, after Clinton learned of
the espionage charges but months before they became public. The
president plans to meet with the Chinese prime minister, Zhu
Rongji, in Washington in April.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that despite this case and other evidence of
Chinese acquisition of weapons-related technology from the United
States, it was in America's interest to remain engaged with the
Asian giant.
</P>
<P>
   He said that his policy of ``strategic partnership'' with China
had already brought benefits, including China's signing of the
Chemical Weapons Convention and the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   He also praised Beijing's cooperation with the United States for
progress in non-proliferation programs aimed at Iran, Pakistan and
North Korea. China has also played a constructive role in limiting
the damage from the Asian economic crisis of the past 18 months,
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would argue that our efforts to have an honest and open
policy with China, so that they don't think that we have made a
decision in advance to try to contain and limit them in their
economic growth and their development as a nation, has paid
dividends,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe those things would have occurred if we had
not had an open, candid, honest relationship with China, aware of
all the facts,'' he added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The president pointedly noted that the alleged transfer of
weapons technology to China occurred in the mid-1980s, when China
made rapid strides in its own nuclear program that were detected by
U.S. intelligence agencies. At the time, there was no clear
evidence that Chinese technological leaps were the result of theft
of American weapons secrets.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the current espionage case proves that Chinese spies
pilfered American weapons design, Clinton said, there remain
reasons to continue to work with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that the evidence justifies an isolated
no-contact relationship with China,'' he said, ``when we have
gotten the benefits not only to ourselves, but to the rest of the
world, of our engagement policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
