<SLUG> BC-MA-CASINO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDFALL FOR BAY STATE SEEN IN REPORT FUNDED BY CASINO BACKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Legalizing casino gambling in Massachusetts would
increase state revenue and boost annual Lottery sales by an
estimated $137 million, according to a study commissioned by casino
gambling supporters scheduled to be released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, commissioned by a group of businessmen seeking to
open a casino in Salisbury Beach, is the third progaming study
authored by professor Clyde Barrow of the University of
Massachusetts at Dartmouth released in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   The studies are intended to increase pressure on the Legislature
to expand gambling in Massachusetts. Lawmakers are scheduled to
take up the issue Tuesday, when the joint Committee on Government
Regulations considers a slew of bills to expand gambling.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, New Hampshire lawmakers will begin to vote next
week on a measure sponsored by Governor Jeanne Shaheen that would
place nearly 3,750 slot machines at the Granite State's four
racetracks, thereby increasing pressure on Massachusetts lawmakers
to expand gambling here.
</P>
<P>
   Barrow's new study focuses on a bill sponsored by state Senator
James P. Jajuga, Democrat of Methuen, that would allow the
construction of three casinos, located in Salisbury Beach and in
Bristol and Hampden counties, and authorize up to 200 slot machines
at each of the state's four racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   The study concludes that casinos would generate an additional
$150 million a year in direct local aid to Massachusetts cities and
towns. But it's the argument that expanding gambling will lead to
greater Lottery sales that's likely to catch the attention of key
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Barrow said his conclusions are based in part on the experience
of Connecticut, where state lottery sales increased after the
Mashantucket Pequots opened Foxwoods Casino in Ledyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fiscal year 1998, the Connecticut State Lottery contributed
over $264 million in revenues to the state's general fund,'' Barrow
said, ``an average increase of over $7 million annually since the
inception of casino gaming in 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Representative Daniel E. Bosley, Democrat of North
Adams, who as House chairman of the Government Regulations
Committee helped kill casino gambling in Massachusetts with a
scathing report on the ``false promises'' of casino advocates in
1996, said Thursday that Barrow's conclusions were a result of
``shoddy research.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Connecticut lottery increased sales because it expanded
its instant ticket games,'' Bosley said. ``We commissioned a very
expensive and exhaustive study two years ago which concluded that
you cannot draw any inference at all between the increase in
lottery sales and the introduction of casinos in Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien, who oversees the
Lottery and supported casino bills as a state senator, said she
will keep an open mind on the issue of expanded gambling in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   As The Boston Globe has previously reported, Governor Paul
Cellucci is in favor of allowing the Martha's Vineyard-based
Wampanoag tribe to operate a casino, and Senate President Thomas F.
Birmingham and Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly have declared they
``have no moral objections'' to expanded gambling in the state.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, who has opposed expanded
gambling in the past but signaled a willingness to take another
look at the issue, could not be reached to comment Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
