<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-TEXAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIHM'S ABILITY REACHING NEW HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you think you can take Chris Mihm on the tennis court? Think
again. He was ranked among the state's top players in his age group
as a 14-year-old growing up in Austin, Texas; you wouldn't stand a
chance of serving or volleying against him.
</P>
<P>
   So you think you can beat Chris Mihm in the swimming pool? You'd
lose again. The 7-footer would be capable of easily outreaching you
at the wall, even if you were leading by a full length.
</P>
<P>
   So you think you can post-up Chris Mihm on the basketball court?
That would be even more comical than ``There's Something About
Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   On all three counts, you'd be a triple (crowned) loser.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm will stand head-and-shoulders above everyone when the
multitalented 7-foot, 262-pound sophomore center leads Texas
(19-12), a seventh seed, against No. 10 seed Purdue in an East
Regional first-round game at the FleetCenter. At first glance,
Purdue's roster does not appear to have the personnel big enough to
challenge Mihm in the paint, let alone the tennis court or swimming
pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those players who's gotten better and better in
the last two years,'' remarked Purdue coach Gene Keady. ``He's got
long arms and he's got great hands, and he's big. He's got a good
touch and it looks like he might have a chance to move on to
another level. But it's one of those things where you see kids get
better, you know it took a lot of hard work. It just didn't happen.
I just think once he started to buy into Coach (Rick) Barnes's
system, he took off. And he's probably been the difference on their
team right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm earned a spot on the Big 12 media's All-Improved and
All-Defensive squads after averaging 13.4 points, a team-leading
10.9 rebounds, and recording 82 blocked shots. He says there are
two reasons he's improved. First and foremost, there was the
arrival of Barnes from Clemson, and, second, he was a devoted
participant in the Pete Newell Big Man Camp last August in
Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Pete Newell and the staff he has assembled there are
some of the best at teaching a lot of fundamentals and big-man
moves and techniques,'' said Mihm, who befriended Evan Eschemeyer
of Northwestern and A.J. Bramlett of Arizona during his Hawaiian
camping trip. ``That camp has helped me overall with just footwork
and my overall arsenal of different moves. But this year with Coach
Barnes coming in, I've learned so much. He's just a great teacher
and great coach, and he's really helped in a lot of areas of my
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them, I think, is the defensive end,'' he added. ``I've
really become a lot better defensive player and I've tried to
concentrate on other areas, like rebounding. My rebounding average
was up (from 8.0 to 10.9), and I was been able to average a
double-double.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Barnes, ``The first time I saw Chris, we had just gotten
here and we were doing our individual workouts and right off the
bat you knew this guy had great hands, great attitude, and was a
great guy who wanted to work. Then, as he started moving, you saw
he was a guy who had great agility. He's young, but as time went
on, he continued to learn a lot about himself but there is no doubt
in my mind that Chris Mihm is one of the best players in college
basketball tody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been as hard or harder on Chris Mihm as any player I've
coached, because when you look at him you see greatness and you
want to see it come out of him every day,'' Barnes added. ``He has
learned how to practice hard and he's raised his own bar, where now
some of the things I've told him he can do, I think he's realized
that he can do. He had truly a great, great year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Mihm's breakout games of the season came in a 76-65
victory over the University of Massachusetts Jan. 31 at the Frank
Erwin Center. In one of the few games he was not double- or
triple-teamed, Mihm dominated his one-on-one matchup with Lari
Ketner by scoring 20 points and grabbing a season-high 17 rebounds.
Afterward, UMass coach Bruiser Flint was left to state the obvious.
``(Mihm's) going to make a lot of money one day, I'll put it that
way. He was making baseline jumpers from 10-12 feet out with a guy
in his face. What do you do about that?''
</P>
<P>
   While Mihm would gladly sacrifice ``a flashy dunk'' for the
chance to swat someone's shot on the defensive end, Barnes hopes
Mihm continues to capitalize on his potential to become a
well-rounded player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want him just to be a block player, because he's too
good a shooter and his skills are too good to keep him down
there,'' Barnes said. ``I do want him to step out and face the
basket and play that way some, too. He's been a tremendous force on
the defensive end. We were able to extend our defense a little bit,
because we know we've got somewhat of a security blanket back there
that when players go in there they know there's a guy lurking back
there who can alter some shots and block some shots.''
</P>
<P>
   But, then again, those represent only a fraction of Chris Mihm's
abundant athletic talents.
</P>
</TEXT>
