<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIKE-LABOR-390&AMP;ADD-NY     03-11 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIKE-LABOR-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIKE CRITIC PRAISES GAINS IN AIR QUALITY AT VIETNAM FACTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A prominent critic who badly hurt Nike's image when he exposed
unsafe conditions at one of its factories in Vietnam in 1997 issued
a report Thursday that gave the footwear giant high marks for
improving air quality at the plant, although he said some
significant problems remained.
</P>
<P>
   After disclosing 18 months ago that the air in parts of the
plant had levels of cancer-causing substances that exceeded local
standards by 177 times, the critic, Dara O'Rourke, applauded the
factory for improving ventilation, reducing the use of hazardous
chemicals and training managers on safety issues.
</P>
<P>
   O'Rourke, an environmental researcher at the University of
California at Berkeley, praised Nike for a turnaround, noting that
it was substituting less harmful chemicals for dangerous ones and
had taken the unusual step of allowing a critic like him to inspect
the factory, which is outside Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
   Nike, the world's largest athletic shoe company, let O'Rourke
visit the factory in December while he was in Vietnam working as a
consultant for the U.N. Industrial Development Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been important improvements, but I don't want to
say Nike has solved all its problems,'' O'Rourke said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   O'Rourke criticized the factory, which is owned and operated by
a Korean contractor, for making insufficient use of protective
equipment like masks and gloves and for having excessive heat and
noise in parts of the plant, which has 9,200 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Kidd, Nike's director of labor relations, said in an
interview that the Tae Kwang Vina factory was an average factory,
not a model one, and that the improvements there were similar to
those at Nike factories throughout Asia. To prove that conditions
have improved at other Nike factories, Kidd said Nike would allow
O'Rourke to visit any of its 37 footwear factories in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Global Exchange, a human rights group that has been Nike's
harshest and most persistent critic, issued a statement Thursday
praising the company for improving conditions and for letting an
outside monitor inspect the factory.
</P>
<P>
   Medea Benjamin, the group's co-director, said, ``This is
certainly an astounding transformation for a company that once
treated independent monitoring as a public relations exercise,
limiting factory access to people they thought would write
favorable reports.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In November 1997, O'Rourke made public a damning inspection
report about the Vietnam factory, leaked to him by a disgruntled
employee, that the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young had prepared for
Nike's internal use. That report said that 77 percent of the
factory's workers reported respiratory problems in 1996 and that
employees worked 65 hours a week, far more than Vietnamese law
allowed. Hours have since been reduced to about 45 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Nike's effort to improve air quality has involved
reducing the use of petroleum-based chemicals _ known as volatile
organic compounds _ used in adhesives, solvents and primers. These
chemicals include toluene, which causes damage to the liver,
kidneys and central nervous system, and acetone, which causes
respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
   Nike is relying instead on water-based chemicals because they
are considerably less dangerous when they evaporate, although
O'Rourke called for studying the health effects of these chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's report, which was written O'Rourke and Garrett Brown,
an occupational safety expert, said the factory ``has implemented
important changes over the past 18 months which appear to have
significantly reduced worker exposures to toxic solvents, adhesives
and other chemicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd said Nike had cut its use of volatile organic compounds to
70 grams for every pair of shoes from 340 grams three years ago. He
said that converting to water-based chemicals had cost millions of
dollars but but that because 30 percent less of these chemicals are
needed than the petroleum-based ones, Nike's operating costs had
been cut by more than $10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   O'Rourke's report noted that 18 percent of workers at the
Vietnam factory reported nose and throat illnesses last year, down
from 86 percent in 1997 and 77 percent in 1996. But his report said
it was puzzling that the number of workers going to the factory's
clinic for what they said were respiratory problems was about the
same last year as in 1997. O'Rourke called on Nike to more closely
monitor how many workers have respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
   His report noted that several rooms with heavy equipment had
dangerously high noise levels and that the temperature in the plant
often exceeded 98 degrees. He complained that many workers did not
use ear plugs and that the cotton masks and gloves many workers
used were inadequate to protect them from the chemicals with which
they work.
</P>
</TEXT>
