<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HASTERT-REPUBS-ART-1S     03-11 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HASTERT-REPUBS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIVIDED PARTY GIVES NEW SPEAKER LITTLE ROOM TO MANEUVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to add extensive quotes from Hastert; complete writethru) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(wg) 
 KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dennis Hastert of Illinois, the new speaker of the
House, may be trying to shed all comparisons with his mercurial
predecessor, Newt Gingrich. But he cannot avoid one of the central
problems that Gingrich faced in trying to run the House: his party
appears hopelessly split, and with just a 10-vote majority, Hastert
has even less room to maneuver than Gingrich had.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert was overruled last week by party conservatives, who are
blocking aid to Central America unless it can be offset by cuts in
domestic programs, like food stamps. The week before, the speaker
signaled a compromise with moderates after they complained about
the proposed tax cut of 10 percent across the board, which had
become the party line, saying they wanted narrower tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert even seemed to be compromising with Democrats, who have
been pushing for an increase in the minimum wage. He suggested that
he did not have the power to stop it, only to shape the final
package.
</P>
<P>
   Two months into his accidental speakership _ he was catapulted
into the job after Robert Livingston's surprise renunciation of the
post after admitting extramarital affairs _ Hastert has shown
himself to be a pragmatic and cautious politician. He is mindful
chiefly that he needs to cement the political center if he hopes to
pass any legislation _ and keep control _ with his whisker-thin
majority.
</P>
<P>
   He is also more comfortable behind the scenes than on stage.
This has made it difficult for many outside of House Republicans to
get to know him and has raised an inevitable question: Are his
initial steps toward compromise the unintended result of an
inexperienced and tentative leader? Or are they the deliberate
strategy of a shrewd negotiator who knows how to piece together
legislation and will ultimately undercut Democratic accusations
that this is a do-nothing Congress?
</P>
<P>
   Hastert is the first to admit that he has no grand design.
``Three months ago, being speaker of the House was the farthest
thing from my mind,'' he said in an interview in his office
Thursday. ``I didn't expect it. You feel your way through this. The
best way for me to take this job is one day at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new speaker is slowly consolidating his power. One House
member who is sympathetic to him said: ``Unlike Newt, who got up
every day and told us how to save the world, Denny is calmly trying
to stake out a position where 218 will agree on taxes, 218 will
agree on health care, 218 will agree on education. It's not
glamorous, but he is dealing with congressmen one on one.''
</P>
<P>
   Every day, Hastert must confront the cold reality that five of
his 222 Republicans could abandon him on a vote and that, assuming
Democrats held together, his party's legislative agenda could
collapse. Then the Republicans could lose control of the House.
They could lose the House anyway, of course, but some legislative
achievements would help them gird against becoming known as the
party of impeachment, the party that could not govern.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes could not be higher. And the calculus _ to balance so
many competing interests and hold the majority _ must be precise.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this is bean counting, not vision,'' said Marshall
Wittmann, an analyst at the Heritage Foundation, a conservative
research group. ``Denny Hastert is meeting with everyone and going
over the schedule and counting heads. `How many do we have for this
rule? How do we calibrate this?' It's a green-eyeshade form of
legislating.''
</P>
<P>
   This plays to Hastert's strength. His previous role in the
House, as deputy whip, was to take the temperature of his
colleagues on bills coming to the floor and round up votes by
applying pressure to his colleagues and tinkering with the bills to
bring them into alignment. He used these skills most notably on
health care legislation in 1996, when Republicans got an experiment
in medical savings accounts added to the Kassebaum-Kennedy
legislation allowing workers to keep their health-care coverage if
they changed jobs. This took endless meetings and member-by-member
attention, a modus operandi that Hastert has taken to the speaker's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been counting votes for four years around here, and it's
a vote-by-vote situation, no matter how far-reaching you'd like to
look,'' Hastert said. ``You need to check where your folks are on
every vote and you never take anybody for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to sit down and listen to what people have to say and
at least try to accommodate what their concerns are. I think that's
why I'm here, quite frankly.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   He has also retained the instincts of the coach he once was. By
design and temperament, he shuns the limelight, preferring to
promote his team, not himself. Toward this end, he has reinvested
authority in his committee chairmen, defusing and decentralizing
the power that Gingrich had amassed in the speaker's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I've learned _ just because you're the speaker
doesn't mean you're the guru on every issue out there,'' Hastert
said, adding that he prefers to let the experts do the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will restore the speakership to the traditional mold,''
said Rep. J.D. Hayworth, a conservative Republican from Arizona.
``That means using the tools of the institution which over time
have worked rather than try to reinvent the process: Using
committees, spending time on the floor, reaching out on the
telephone, being accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has been accessible not only to members but also to
fund-raisers. He has been hobnobbing with Republican donors across
the country and lobbyists in Washington in an effort to keep
dollars flowing into the party's congressional campaign committee,
which plunged into debt in last year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   All of this private activity leaves little time for developing a
public persona, and Hastert remains relatively anonymous. This,
combined with his conciliatory style and his continued role as a
vote counter, has contributed to a perception that he has no
specific agenda of his own, beyond his oft-stated desire to make
the trains run on time. That in turn has raised some concerns
within the House that he has ceded big-picture decision making and
pre-eminence on Capitol Hill to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is getting up to speed every day,'' said Rep. Thomas Ewing,
a fellow Illinois Republican and longtime friend. ``When you're
working with such a slim majority, you really have to keep some
flexibility. If he had a 20- or 30-vote majority and a little more
experience, he would probably have more definite ideas, but his
strength right now is not being hamstrung by feeling `it has to be
my way.'''
</P>
<P>
   He is operating with virtually no margin for error, a task
complicated by the differences within his party. The moderate
Republicans in the House are flexing a new-felt power stemming from
their vote with conservatives on Dec. 19 to impeach President
Clinton, even though polls showed that a majority of their
constituents supported the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's next-to-impossible for leaders to go to the moderates and
say `You've got to cast a hard vote for me,''' Wittmann of the
Heritage Foundation said. ``They've already cast it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now those moderates need to assert their independence, and
Hastert appears sensitive to their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson, the moderate Connecticut Republican who led
a dozen of her colleagues against the 10 percent tax cut, praised
Hastert, calling him ``a good strategist.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert must satisfy the moderates while not antagonizing the
conservatives. There is a large reservoir of good will toward the
speaker. But privately, some conservatives say they worry that he
is making tactical blunders by ceding conservative goals too
quickly and that his conciliatory instincts will give them little
with which to distinguish themselves from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need definitional bills that pass but that Clinton vetoes
so we can say, `Here are the differences between us and Gore,'''
one conservative said, anticipating the presidential nomination of
Vice President Al Gore. ``That was the beauty of the 10 percent
cut. Now, Hastert has undermined it without even making an effort
to sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing his own majority is fragile, Hastert has been diligently
seeking Democratic support for various bills on taxes, education
and missile defense, hoping that for every Republican vote he might
lose, he can gain a Democrat one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly,'' he has said, ``with the margin of votes that
we have, we need to do as much stuff as we can on a bipartisan
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   But he cannot for a moment forget that the Democrats are
determined to retake the House and replace him with Rep. Dick
Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader. Despite Hastert's
friendly public overtures _ he has met not only with Democratic
leaders but also with the various Democratic factions _ the
Democrats smell blood.
</P>
<P>
   And many in the House expect that as election-year politics come
into focus, the Democrats will decide that they have little to gain
by helping Hastert and the Republicans look good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
