<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols won't look past Delaware
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ So, Tony Harris, what were you doing the last
time Tennessee won a game in the NCAA Tournament?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 4 or 5,'' said the Volunteer point guard. ``I was
probably breaking a bunch of toys.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the perspective of Tennessee's players on the school's
last NCAA Tournament win which, for the record, came over Marquette
(57-56) in the first round of the 1983 Mideast Regional. Since then
the Vols have been to the tournament only twice (1989, 1998) losing
both times in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   It is this piece of history, and Tennessee's (20-8)
disappointing play in last week's SEC Tournament, that has the
fourth-seeded Vols as an upset special on a lot of backets today as
they host 13th-seeded Delaware (25-5) in the first round of the
East Regional at the Charlotte Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question Tennessee has better athletes than the
America East champs, who had a 13-game winning streak earlier this
season. The question is, will Tennessee's talented athletes show up
to play?
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee entered this season with high expecations, ranked No.
9 in preseason.
</P>
<P>
   But since an opening-game loss to Arizona (73-72), the Vols have
shown a disturbing tendency to play up or down to the competition.
Tennessee swept Kentucky for the first time since 1979 to win the
SEC's Eastern Division. But the Vols also lost to Mississippi State
twice, the latest coming last Friday (62-56) in the second round of
the SEC Tournament. Tennessee was on a seven-game winning streak
when it inexplicably fell apart against the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   So inquiring minds want to know: Will Tennessee get caught
napping again, thinking Delaware can't play?
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, said coach Jerry Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we've been up and down at times this season but I feel
that we'll be ready to play,'' said Green, in his second season at
Tennessee. ``In fact, I had to cut practice short yesterday
(Wednesday) because I was afraid somebody might get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Tennessee's players thought they were ready to play a
year ago when they went to the West Regional, also as a No. 4 seed.
They now admit they did not take No. 13 Illinois State seriously
and lost 82-81 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we made a mistake of looking on and saying we could
play Arizona (in the second round),'' said guard Brandon Wharton.
``We're going to take it one game at a time this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite last week's loss to Mississippi State, Green has felt
pretty good about his team since losing back-to-back home games
against Arkansas (69-52) and Mississippi State (88-82) in early
February. He made some adjustments after those games to simplify
the offense and, except for the SEC Tournament, the Vols have
played well since.
</P>
<P>
   ``About eight games ago, I thought we might shooting our way out
of it (the tournament),'' said Green. ``But I don't think there is
any question that our kids are more comfortable being in this
position than we were a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all this team has accomplished _ 20 wins, the SEC East
championship, the sweep of Kentucky _ if it gets upset today for
the second year in a row, it will be labeled as a significant
underacheiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think about things like that. We came here to win,''
said Wharton, the team's leading scorer at 13.0 ppg. ``If you think
about being afraid to lose, you're in trouble. There's no time for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
