<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Apprentice' Blaney on Busch pole
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dave Blaney won't jump to NASCAR's Winston Cup circuit
until next season, but the former sprint-car standout beat 13 Cup
regulars in Thursday's qualifying for the Yellow Freight 300 Busch
race at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Blaney, 36, won the pole for Saturday's race with an average
speed of 186.755 mph, which broke AMS' Busch qualifying record of
186.673 mph set by Dick Trickle in November.
</P>
<P>
   Part-time Cup driver Jeff Green was second at 186.648 mph, and
Mark Martin, the two-time defending champion in the race, was third
at 186.322.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup drivers took eight of the 25 qualifying spots,
including five of the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I'm sitting, I need to learn as much as I can, as fast
as I can,'' Blaney said. ``I probably wouldn't be saying that if I
missed the race by a couple of spots, but from where I'm sitting, I
think it only helps me learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaney, a native of Hartford, Ohio, and father of three, spent
15 years driving sprint cars, winning more than 185 feature events
and $3.5 million in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Blaney was given a two-year ``apprenticeship'' in the
Busch series by his sponsor before entering the Cup circuit in
2000. Bill Davis, who owns Blaney's Busch team, also owns the Cup
venture of Ward Burton.
</P>
<P>
   While other Busch drivers are criticizing so many Winston Cup
regulars racing in the smaller series on a weekly basis, Blaney is
welcoming the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get close enough to them, you can learn where
they're hitting the brakes and where they're picking up the
throttle,'' he said. ``I'm out here trying to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS RATINGS SOAR
</P>
<P>
   Last week's Las Vegas 400 not only was the most-attended
sporting event in Nevada history, but it also was the second-most
watched race in NASCAR history, excluding the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   The second annual race at Las Vegas Motor Speedway, which
featured brothers Jeff and Ward Burton battling over the final 35
laps, had a 6.0 rating, marking a 3 percent increase over the
inaugural event, according to ABC. The 6.0 rating translates to a
15 share, which means the race was watched by an estimated 5.99
million households.
</P>
<P>
   ``Las Vegas performed exceptionally,'' Speedway Motorsports
chairman Bruton Smith said. ``The television rating is outstanding
given that 1998 was the inaugural year for the Las Vegas 400. With
this record-breaking event behind us, we will finalize plans for
further growth of this facility. We've got tremendous opportunities
in Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   THIS AND THAT
</P>
<P>
   Mark Stahl of Savannah qualified for today's Johnson Industries
300 ARCA race, joining local drivers Mark Gibson of Winder, Mike
Ciochetti Jr. of Clayton and Bill Flowers of Powder Springs. ...
Jason Jarrett, the son of Winston Cup driver Dale, wrecked during
practice Thursday and was unable to drive in first-round qualifying
for the Busch race.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
