<HEADER>
A7187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SADLER12-COX     03-11 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SADLER12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Declining legacy: Wood Brothers patient
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Perhaps only a fellow Virginian could understand the
burden that Elliott Sadler carries on his young shoulders, that of
trying to restore the Wood Brothers racing team to its former
glory.
</P>
<P>
   When he was hired to drive the No. 21 Ford this season, Sadler,
a rookie, gushed about the responsibility of sitting in the Wood
Brothers seat once warmed by some of racing's greatest names _
Yarborough, Pearson, Allison, Foyt, Bonnett, Baker, Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always kept a special eye on the Wood Brothers because we
were from Virginia,'' the 23-year-old Sadler said. ``To be able to
drive a race car for them at such an early age is very
overwhelming. Very flattering. I feel very lucky. I just want to do
what I can to make the most of it and repay those guys for giving
me the shot of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As a point of reference, history is a wonderful thing. But it
can also carry too much weight. After three races, the only
tradition Sadler can relate to is his newly established one of
getting in wrecks. Daytona: wiped out. Rockingham: wiped out. Las
Vegas: wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks into the season, he's mired in 43rd place (out of 49
drivers) in the points race.
</P>
<P>
   And Sadler is kicking himself. ``It looked like somebody might
have gotten in the back of Michael (Waltrip) and got him around,''
he recalled about the latest wreck. ``There was just so much smoke,
and I just panicked, I guess. I was trying to get slowed down in
time. I tried to go to the inside, and it just locked up on us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to apologize to everybody on this Wood Brothers
team. I've made a lot of bad mistakes the last three weeks, and I
just need to get a gut-check and turn this thing around.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's one nice thing about this racing business. There's a
fresh start just about every weekend. Sunday's Cracker Barrel 500
could be just that for the Woods and Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   While Sadler, who won five times in two full Busch seasons,
continues to define himself as a Winston Cup driver, the Wood
Brothers are trying to ease the burden of history. Forget about the
past, they're telling Sadler, just make notes about what you're
going through now and look ahead.
</P>
<P>
   As early as the 1980s, the words ``legendary'' and ``storied''
usually preceded references to the Wood Brothers teams.
</P>
<P>
   From 1973-79, the Woods, with David Pearson at the wheel, had a
stretch that forged their place in history: 43 victories in seven
years. Eleven victories in 18 starts in 1973; 10 victories in 22
starts in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The team was formed 49 years ago by Glen and Leonard Woods. Glen
drove; Leonard was the chief mechanic. The team is the all-time
Winston Cup leader in superspeedway victories with 80; its 96
victories since 1953 rank third all-time to Petty Enterprises and
Junior Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Woods are also credited with the first organized pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   But the team has won only twice in the '90s and not since Morgan
Shepherd's victory in 1993 at Atlanta, where the team has won a
record 12 times. Waltrip, the Woods driver the past three years,
had only one top-five finish in 95 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Wood Brothers in 1999 include two brothers (Len and Eddie),
a sister (Kim Wood Hall; they're all Glen's children) and uncle
Leonard. Glen is now retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a different era,'' said Len, the co-crew chief and
engine man. ``In the '70s, you would have us, the Pettys and Junior
Johnson winning about 10 races apiece. Nobody else would win. You'd
have seven cars to beat. Now, you've got 42, and it's much tougher.
Plus, add one Jeff Gordon into it and it makes it double tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today's pit crew could be intimidated by the history the
Wood Brothers created 35 years ago, when Ford brought them to
Indianapolis. They developed venters on the gas can to speed the
flow of fuel into the car and cranked out 18-second pit stops in
the Indy 500 that got the family's picture in True magazine. ``Had
them all in top coats and top hats in front of a tobacco barn,''
Len said.
</P>
<P>
   That also is stuff best left in the scrapbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, we try not to look at the past,'' Len said. ``The past
was different. It's like somebody racing their daddy, like Dale Jr.
Does he have to win seven championships and 80 races to be as good
as his daddy? It's a different time. He may win two championshps
and 40 races and still be one of the greatest drivers because of
the time and the competition level.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Woods are trying to be patient with Sadler. ``Obviously,
we're going to have a little bit tougher time with a rookie,'' Len
said. ``Working with him at each place, you take notes. This went
wrong this week or this went good this week. The next time we show
up there, we should be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
