<HEADER>
A7189 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-WEISS12-CO     03-11 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-WEISS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `There's a bigger picture out there'
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Walt Weiss is set to begin his second
season with the Atlanta Braves, and the 35-year-old shortstop knows
that it has to be better _ even though he hit .435 in his first
month as a Brave and was voted to his first All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, however, hamstring and quadriceps problems limited
him to 96 games, his lowest total since 1991. But none of that
mattered much next to the trauma he endured in nearly losing his
son Brody, then 3 years old, to e-coli poisoning in June.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As you look back, how would you describe last season?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's hard to sum up that year in a million words or less. So
much happened. When I was playing, I thought I played well, but I
missed so much time. And the thing with my son, it was eventful, to
say the least.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the worst moment in dealing with that?
</P>
<P>
   A: There was one day ... when it looked like he was headed for
the worst. There were two other little kids in there, they were two
days ahead of my son as far as all the symptoms and everything. He
was pretty much following suit.
</P>
<P>
   They ended up having to go on respirators and slipped into
comas; he looked like he was right behind them. ... He wouldn't
respond to anything that we said. When he looked at us, he would
kind of stare right through us. ... He was showing signs of it
affecting his brain. That was the worst day through the whole
thing. That next day, he just turned it around.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did going through all that change you?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's real easy to take things for granted. We get in our
daily routines. This game basically can consume you. There's a
bigger picture out there, you know? It just reaffirms what's
important.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did that affect your season?
</P>
<P>
   A: After the thing with my son, I felt like I was done. I was
emotionally and mentally spent. At times, it was difficult to
emotionally gear myself up, because it was like there was nothing
there. ...The first half (of the season) was special. The second
half was rough.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you expect from yourself this season?
</P>
<P>
   A: I just want to make sure I enjoy it, and I have fun here.
I've wanted to play ball my whole life, and I'm basically living a
dream, like we all are. Who knows how much more of it is left for
me?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was hitting leadoff comfortable for you last year?
</P>
<P>
   A: I enjoyed the challenge. It wasn't like I had to make a lot
of adjustments. That's my approach anyway at the plate _ I go deep
in the count. I try to have a high walk total, a high on-base
percentage. That's how I'm going to contribute offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Defensively, what do you pride yourself on?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just being reliable, which hurt last year because I was hurt
so much. That really bothered me more than anything, the fact that
I wasn't reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there anything you can do to stay healthy?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some of it may be luck. I'm getting to the point where I'm
pretty in tune with my body. There are just some things I have to
stay on top of, especially in my upper legs and my pelvis area.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
