<SLUG> BC-BKC-JIRSA-FIRED12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jirsa relieved of coaching duties at UGA
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three weeks after publicly stating that he had ``a
commitment'' to Ron Jirsa as head basketball coach, Georgia
athletics director Vince Dooley fired Jirsa Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a hastily called news conference Thursday evening, Dooley
cited ``no real hope or encouragement as we look to next year or
toward the future'' and Georgia's regression toward the end of the
season, as the main reasons the Bulldogs ``will be making a change
and searching for a new basketball coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs were 35-30 record in two seasons under Jirsa and
twice played in the National Invitation Tournament. But this year's
15-15 team, which consisted of five seniors and the 1998 freshman
of the year, was expected earn an NCAA Tournament berth. Instead,
Georgia lost 11 of its last 14 games, including an embarassing
77-57 loss to Clemson in the first round of the NIT on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose that, more so than anything, was the reason for the
change,'' said Dooley, who attended the Clemson game along with
President Michael Adams and associate AD Dick Bestwick. ``I got
very concerend with the (regular-season ending) loss to South
Carolina, then also concerned with the loss to Alabama as well as
the loss last night in Clemson. I started thinking about it
somewhat after the South Carolina game and it got a lot stronger,
of course, last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley gave Jirsa a firm vote of confidence following their
21-point loss to Kentucky on Feb. 17. But the Bulldogs lost four of
the next five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody in the media would give somebody the right to
change their mind,'' Dooley said. ``I'm sure everybody has changed
their mind at some point in time in their life. I meant what I
said, but I also said, if you go back and look, that the season is
not over yet. I was hoping the season would finish much better. As
it turned out, it was worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we ended poorly, didn't show any real
improvement. In fact, I felt like we went the other way. I didn't,
I suppose, see what you might say light at the end of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Jirsa did not attend the news conference and did not return
phone calls at his house. He issued a two-sentence statement along
with a notice asking media members to contact him for interviews
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very appreciative of the support of many friends both on
campus and around the state over the past two years,'' Jirsa said
in the statement. ``I'm disappointed things didn't work out
differently but I sincerely wish the players and the program every
success in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Jirsa, 39, has three years remaining on a five-year contract
that pays him approximately $350,000 a year, $111,300 in base
salary. Georgia is contractually obligated to pay Jirsa at least
$333,900, the remaining salary portion, and could provide
additional compensation in form of cars, tickets and country club
memberships.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia assistant coaches Michael Hunt, Reggie Rankin and Jerry
Waters all have one-year contracts that will be honored until their
June 30 expiration date or until they find other work.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley acknowledged that Jirsa had a difficult task in following
Tubby Smith, for whom he served as an assistant and succeeded at
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, Ron had a tough act to follow. His charge,
perhaps better than any one word, was continuity. That was the
object of hiring Ron, to keep the continuity that we had going
(under Tubby Smith).''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, now head coach at Kentucky, was not at all pleased to
hear the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed to hear Ron was let go after just two
years,'' Smith said in New Orleans, where Kentucky opens NCAA
tournament play today. ``It goes to show you what this business is
all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's players also were caught by surprise. Students are on
spring break and most of the players were out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shocked,'' said senior forward Michael Chadwick. ``He was
telling us to meet back with him on Monday and talk with him. I had
no kind of clue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' added D.A. Layne, who was informed of
the news while watching the NCAA tournament at his home in
Marietta. Dooley said the search will begin immediately for a
successor and he made it clear that he would prefer a Division I
head coach with a proven record of success. He gave no timetable
other than to have someone in place before the spring signing
period in April.
</P>
<P>
   Among the early names rumored to have interest include
Appalachian State's Buzz Peterson, Southwest Missouri's Steve
Alford, Seton Hall's Tommy Amaker and Leonard Hamilton of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
