<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Vols no shoo-in for fourth title in row
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It may have been inconceivable before the season
began, but Tennessee is not such an overwhelming favorite to win an
unprecedented fourth consecutive women's NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   While the Lady Volunteers are still a pretty good bet to be in
the winners' circle in the San Jose Arena on March 28, they haven't
been nearly as dominating as last season's dazzling 39-0 team. And
that gives others hope that the tournament, which begins today at
16 subregional sites, could be up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   But this is March, after all, and coach Pat Summitt has a
sterling 61-11 record in the NCAA Tournament. There's also the
individual pursuit by Tennessee seniors Chamique Holdsclaw and
Kelly Jolly to become the first Division I basketball players, male
or female, to win four national titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go out there and win our fourth championship, and
win it in style,'' Holdsclaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have left the second-ranked Lady Vols (28-2), who open
against Appalachian State on Saturday, with only one backup in the
low post and two in the backcourt. Also, Tennessee is not an
exceptional perimeter shooting team, and at times has not been able
to maintain its extremely intense defensive pace.
</P>
<P>
   However, the starting five, led by Holdsclaw, Jolly and
All-Americans Tamika Catchings and Semeka Randall, is clearly
better than anyone in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Half the 64-team bracket gets under way today, with featured
games involving Connecticut (27-4), the No. 1 seed in the Mideast,
against St. Francis, Pa. (6 p.m., ESPN2) and Louisiana Tech, which
lost to Tennessee in last year's title game, meeting Central
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Purdue (28-1), which snapped Tennessee's 46-game
winning streak in November, gets started on Saturday, as does
12th-ranked Georgia (23-6), which plays Liberty (21-7) at
approximately 8:30 p.m. in Athens in a Mideast subregional. That
game follows one between Toledo (25-5) and SMU (19-10).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
