u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HEAVYWEIGHT-TITLE     03-11 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HEAVYWEIGHT-TITLES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heavyweight unity
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man at the microphone bellows, ``You've got two
kings fighting for three kingdoms,'' which immediately tells you
this must be a boxing story.
</P>
<P>
   No other professional sport has three governing bodies all
crowning (rhymes with clowning) champions _ then strips two titles
away and distributes them elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen, the Denver Broncos now are only the Larry
Bowl champions. But the Falcons have been declared Curly Bowl
champs and the Vikings are winners of the Moe Bowl. We hope one day
to unify the Three Stooges.
</P>
<P>
   Despite itself, boxing will take a rare step forward Saturday
evening. Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis each will carry title
belts into the ring at Madison Square Garden. One will leave as the
sole heavyweight champion _ at least of the three most recognized
sanctioning bodies, the WBA, WBC and IBF.
</P>
<P>
   Something so simple has until now been so fractured. There
hasn't been a unified champion since Riddick Bowe, who defeated
Holyfield for the three belts in November of 1992. But shortly
after the fight, Bowe turned down the WBC's mandate that he make an
immediate defense against Lewis (then the No. 1 contender) and made
a show of it by holding a news conference and depositing the belt
into in a garbage can.
</P>
<P>
   ``That disappointed,'' Holyfield said. ``He made a big
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The championship has been in pieces ever since. In fact, there
have been 10 different champions in the last six years: Bowe,
Lewis, Holyfield, Michael Moorer, Oliver McCall, George Foreman,
Bruce Seldon, Frank Bruno, Francois Botha, Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Bowe's belief was that since he defeated Holyfield, he would be
the recognized champion. But in renouncing the WBC title, he
devalued his championship _ then lost all claim to it by losing the
rematch to Holyfield. Holyfield, who has never passed up a mandated
title defense or been stripped of a title, believes fusing the
three together will aid a sport that remains short on sanity. Those
who control the money agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a unified champion filters down to the extent that, as
the heavyweight division goes, so goes boxing,'' said Time Warner
Sports vice president Lou DiBella. ``Last year was a very dormant
year in heavyweight boxing, and the perception was it was a down
year for boxing in general. The truth is there were some pretty
decent fights, a lot of new young champions emerged, three Olympic
fighters won titles. It wasn't such a bad year for boxing. But
because of the heavyweight division, the perception was boxing
suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Dino Duva said, ``None of the top guys ever fight each
other any more. This fight is crucial and significant for boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBella already has asked WBC president Jose Sulaiman not to
dictate any ludicrous title defenses to Saturday's winner, but he
isn't terribly confident. The WBA wants the winner to fight Henry
Akinwande. John Ruiz is in line for a shot for the WBC. David Tua
is the IBF's No. 1 contender. Sanctioning bodies make most of their
money off fees in title fights, which they can more easily control
with lesser-known ``champions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The smart money would have to be that somewhere down the line
soon, the titles will splinter again,'' DiBella said.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Steward, Lewis' trainer and a longtime observer of
boxing's boardroom declarations, said, ``I don't think the title
will be together for longer than six months. It's all based on
politics and money. Until you see boxing regulated by a single
body, it's very hard for me to see things ever changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield hopes to do his part. If he defeats Lewis, he plans to
defend against Akinwande. But it's conceivable he would retire
either before or after that bout, leaving the three crowns in limbo
again. That's not Holyfield's immediate concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about this fight happening,'' he said. ``Only two
people have really set out to put the belts back together _ myself
and Mike Tyson. After Larry Holmes was champion for a while, we had
guys like Trevor Berbick and Pinklon Thomas, and none of those guys
would fight each other. Then Riddick won it and (his manager) Rock
Newman was like, `We're gonna do what we want.' I've had my mind
set on unifying since 1995 after losing to Bowe (in their third
fight). I've stuck to my guns. When I fought (then-mandatory
contender) Moorer (in 1994), they said, `Why don't you fight Lennox
instead and give up the belt?' It's because I've never been one to
go against the rules and regulations. Now I'm the guy they come
to.''
</P>
<P>
   The dearth of talent in the heavyweight division led DiBella to
say that the only other big fight out there is ``the rematch.''
That's assuming no sanctioning bodies gets in the way.
</P>
<P>
   For at least one night, one man can accessorize with three
belts.
</P>
<P>
   FUSING THE ALPHABETS IN BOXING
</P>
<P>
   The winner of Saturday's heavyweight title fight between Evander
Holyfield (WBA, IBF) and Lennox Lewis (WBC) will create the first
unified champion since Riddick Bowe. After taking the the belts
from Holyfield on Nov. 13, 1992, Bowe renounced the WBC portion a
month later rather than make a mandatory defense against Lewis,
then the No. 1 contender:
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBC) May 8, 1993: Lewis decisions Tony Tucker for the title
vacated by Bowe.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBA, IBF) Nov. 6, 1993: After two successful defenses, Bowe
loses a rematch to Holyfield by majority decision.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBA, IBF) April 22, 1994: Holyfield, in his first defense,
surprisingly loses a decision to Michael Moorer. He suffers from
severe shoulder pain and dehydration, eventually leading to a
misdiagnosed heart problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBC) Sept. 24, 1994: Lewis, after wins over Frank Bruno and
Phil Jackson, is stopped in two rounds by Oliver McCall in England.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBA, IBF) Nov. 5, 1994: Moorer dominates first nine rounds of
his first defense against George Foreman, but is knocked out in the
10th round.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBA) March 4, 1995: Foreman, ignoring the WBA's order to
defend his title against then-No. 1 ranked (again) Tucker, is
stripped by the WBA, which orders an elimination bout between
Tucker and Bruce Seldon.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBA) April 8, 1995: Seldon claims the WBA title with a
seventh-round TKO over Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   _ (IBF) June 29, 1995: Foreman is stripped of his second belt
when he declines the IBF's unusual mandate to fight a rematch with
Axel Schulz after Foreman's disputed win by decision April 22. The
IBF, like the WBA, orders a title elimination match between Frans
Botha and Schulz.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBC) Sept. 2, 1995: McCall, in his second defense, loses a
decision to Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   _ (IBF) Dec. 9, 1995: Botha decisions Schulz for title but tests
positive for steroids and is stripped. IBF orders a new title fight
between Botha and Moorer.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBC) March 16, 1996: Mike Tyson wins his first title since
his return from prison with a third-round TKO over Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   _ (IBF) June 12, 1996: Moorer decisions Schulz for title.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBA/WBC) Sept. 7, 1996: Tyson seemingly fuses two belts by
easily beating WBA champ Seldon with a first-round knockout. But
WBC belt is in limbo after Lewis goes to court to win a title shot.
Tyson chooses to bypass bout for more lucrative and perceived
easier fight against Holyfield. Courts mandate that WBC award its
belt to Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBA) Nov. 9, 1996: Tyson is stunned by a 12-to-1 underdog _
Holyfield, who wins by an 11th-round TKO.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBC) Feb. 7, 1997: Lewis, in his first ``title defense,''
avenges loss to McCall with a fifth-round TKO when McCall suffers a
nervous breakdown. He makes four more defenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBA/IBF) Nov. 8, 1997: Holyfield, after winning a rematch
with Tyson, unifies two of the belts by knocking down Moorer five
times and winning by eighth-round TKO.
</P>
<P>
   _ (WBC/WBA/IBF) March 13, 1999: Holyfield fights Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
