<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weigh-in: Lewis 246, Holyfield 215
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Evander Holyfield's proclamation that he is going to
knock out Lennox Lewis in the third round of Saturday's heavyweight
title unification is having a pronounced effect in Las Vegas,
prediction central.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield remains an overall favorite of about 7-5 at the
Caesars Palace Sportsbook. But the odds of him winning by
third-round KO have plummeted _ from 30-1 to open to 22-1 on
Wednesday to 15-1 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield smiled when informed of the odds at Thursday's
weigh-in, saying, ``I'm gonna do it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thomas, Holyfield's attorney, said, ``Wow! I guess people
are starting to wake up. Betting against Evander Holyfield is never
a smart thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lewis camp is not moved by the odds, and in fact felt buoyed
by the weigh-in. Lewis weighed in at 246 pounds, which is 31
heavier than Holyfield (215).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's too light _ Lennox will just destroy him,'' said Frank
Maloney, Lewis' manager, as Holyfield stepped off the scales.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-pound differential is not the greatest disparity for a
Holyfield fight. In 1991, Holyfield (208) weighed 49 pounds less
than George Foreman (257).
</P>
<P>
   At 246, Lewis was three pounds heavier than for his two previous
bouts against Zeljko Mavrovic and Shannon Briggs, but he has been
as high as 251 for Oliver McCall last year. Holyfield weighed 217
for his last fight against Vaughn Bean in September and was 214
previous to that against Michael Moorer. For what it's worth,
Holyfield also hadn't eaten lunch before the 4 p.m. weigh-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good at this weight,'' he said. ``I never worry about
what the other guy weighs; I only worry about what I weigh.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
