A7194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SABATES12-COX     03-11 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SABATES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sabates still revs up NASCAR
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ His stock-car racing team isn't doing much in points
or earnings at the moment, but car owner Felix Sabates still leads
Winston Cup in candor.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions _ he's full of 'em.
</P>
<P>
   On the delayed delivery of the new Chevrolet Monte Carlo:
``NASCAR doesn't want to give Chevrolet a great car right off the
bat, because then we have the crybabies of Ford doing the crying.
They're trying to make the Monte Carlo not as good as the Taurus at
the beginning, because they know we're going to make the car better
at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   On the crying by car owners: ``This is a game. The Chevy people
cry. The Ford people cry. We all cry. We're nothing but a bunch of
crybabies. You hope at the end, the one that cries the most ends up
with the breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   On minorities in racing: ``People say what is the average NASCAR
fan going to think if you have blacks in this sport? I saw
something (recently): Coors had a party, about a thousand people.
Jim Brown walked in there unannounced and 999 people went to him
for autographs. The women all wanted pictures with him. The guy's
63 years old, but he's still got the charisma.''
</P>
<P>
   On the chances of a rookie ever winning the Daytona 500:
``They're not going to let any rookie win Daytona. He'll be upside
down on the back straightaway, his roof flap would be digging a
trench on the race track.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ever-changing world of Winston Cup racing, he's still
Felix after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   This is the team owner who once celebrated a victory by
rewarding his crew chief with a motorcycle and the crew with a
boat. He once showed up at a speedway media center with two armed
guards and $1 million in cash, challenging Rusty Wallace to lap the
field in a Pontiac after the driver complained that the car Sabates
was running at the time had been given too much of an edge by
NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   In his 10th year as a team owner, Sabates still draws a crowd,
because he is perhaps the most entertaining owner in the garage.
One wonders what the size of his audience might be if his team
actually won a race, which hasn't happened since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Team Sabco tries again this week in the Cracker Barrel Old
Country Store 500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway. Sterling Marlin will
attempt to qualify the No. 40 Chevy, Joe Nemechek the No. 42 Chevy.
A season of anticipated improvement is enduring a slow start.
Marlin is 30th in points (242), Nemechek 34th (204).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working with the new Monte Carlo,'' Sabates said.
``The street car that we have is a race car. Unlike the Ford. They
came out with a four-door taxicab that they converted to a race
car.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Cuban-American, Sabates might be the only minority in
Winston Cup. He is asked often about the absence of minorities in
stock-car racing. He said it takes sponsorship and diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Julius Erving and (ex-NFL player Joe Washington, owners
of a Busch Series team) came in, they came in like, `I'm Julius,
come here and give me stuff.' They turned people off.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabates compared that to the style of former NFL stars Jim Brown
and Willie Lanier, who are considering starting a Winston Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way that Jim Brown and Willie Lanier are doing it, in a
very humble way, they're doing their homework and talking to
sponsors, talking to drivers; they're trying to start from the
bottom up rather than from the top down,'' Sabates said. ``We're
going to help them, car-wise and engine-wise. I might even invest
with them. I see the opportunities there to tap a whole new market
in NASCAR.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone appreciates Sabates' opinions. But that hasn't
slowed him from having them. Last year, he raised some tempers by
gushing about Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said if you took Jeff Gordon and put him on the Sabco team
he'd probably win 13 races, but you take Ray Evernham and put him
on the Sabco team, you might not win any races,'' Sabates said.
``It got a lot of people upset. I didn't mean that as a put-down to
my drivers or to Ray Evernham. But Jeff Gordon is an individual
that comes very few in a lifetime. I bet if you put him in a Jeep
Wagoneer with three wheels, he'd probably win nine races.''
</P>
<P>
   FELIX SABATES FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Age: 56.
</P>
<P>
   _ Residence: Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family: Wife, Carolyn; three children; six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   _ Years in racing: 10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best year: 1992, with Kyle Petty driving, won twice and got
four third-place finishes and three fourths.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other sports ventures: Original part-owner of NBA Charlotte
Hornets, sold interest in 1991. Owned Charlotte Checkers of East
Coast Hockey League, one of first investors in World Football
League. Helped start first professional indoor soccer league in
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   _ Background: Came to the United States in 1959 at age 16,
fleeing Castro's Cuba with only a few dollars and two boxes of
cigars. Sold cars in Charlotte, then was hired as a salesman for a
company that imported transistor radios and hair dryers. Eventually
bought the company and made a fortune marketing the Atari video
game Pong, and the talking Teddy Ruxpin doll. That company now has
six branches in the Southeast with more than $500 million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
