</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INMATE-FREED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER DEATH ROW INMATE IS EXONERATED IN TWO MURDERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Anthony Porter, who spent 16 years on death row for a
double murder before college journalism students found evidence to
clear him, was exonerated of the killings Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge Thomas Fitzgerald of Cook County Circuit Court
overturned both murder convictions against Porter, who came within
two days of being executed for the 1982 shooting deaths of a young
couple during a robbery in a South Side park.
</P>
<P>
   Porter, 43, was released from jail last month after a group of
Northwestern University students found evidence of his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald, thanking all of the participants in the case, said,
``I am personally profoundly grateful that we were spared the
unthinkable conclusion to this case.''
</P>
<P>
   He specifically cited ``those outside the system,'' referring to
the students and their professor, David Protess, who obtained a
videotaped statement from Alstory Simon, a Milwaukee laborer who
admitted killing the couple, Jerry Hillard and Marilyn Green.
</P>
<P>
   Protess, who assigns murder cases to his class each semester to
re-investigate, said this about the case: ``It is a great day when
a wrongful murder conviction is overturned. This just shows that
the machinery of death in this state is broken and there is no way
to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the death penalty was reinstated in Illinois in 1977, 11
inmates have been executed and 11 others have been released after
new evidence raised questions about their guilt, prompting calls
for a statewide moratorium on executions.
</P>
<P>
   Though cleared of the murder charges, Porter remains convicted
of armed robbery and related weapons charges that were also heard
at his 1983 murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State Attorney Thomas Gainer said that the reopened
investigation had led his office to believe that Porter was
innocent of the murders. But Gainer said the prosecutors still
believed that Porter was in the park that night and committed the
armed robbery against the couple.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing has been set for next month to determine whether those
convictions will also be vacated.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there is compelling evidence, both old and new, that
Alstory Simon committed these murders, there is nothing that
diminishes the evidence against Anthony Porter on the armed robbery
charge,'' Gainer said. ``A hearing must be held so that evidence
can be considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter's lawyer, Daniel R. Sanders, said that at the very least
there should be a new trial on the armed robbery charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony was convicted of the armed robbery in the same trial
that a jury was hearing incorrect testimony about a double homicide
which we now know didn't exist,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That had to have had a dramatic prejudicial effect on the
jury. But we maintain that Anthony Porter was not in the park that
night and he didn't commit any of these crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald suggested that even if the robbery conviction was
reaffirmed, Porter would very likely not return to prison because
of the time he had already served.
</P>
<P>
   Porter expressed relief Thursday as he left the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God I'm free,'' he said. ``I'm innocent of all these
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Four of the six students who helped free Porter attended the
hearing with Protess, who questioned prosecutors' motives for
maintaining the armed robbery conviction. After their
investigation, the students concluded that Porter was also innocent
of the robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case of this magnitude, where an innocent man was almost
executed, it would be too great of a leap for the state to vacate
all of the convictions at one time,'' Protess said. ``It would be
an acknowledgment that they were so mistaken right from the start,
which I don't believe they're ready to admit. It's an unwillingness
to apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon has been charged with the murders and remains in custody.
A lawyer for Simon has said his client shot the couple in
self-defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
