<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7198 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ILLEGAL-BANK-SCHEME-7     03-11 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILLEGAL-BANK-SCHEME-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKERS TRUST ADMITS IT MISUSED MONEY UNCLAIMED BY CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Germany)   (EDS: This is a late add to page 1 of The New York Times.)  
(js) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bankers Trust Co. pleaded guilty Thursday to federal
criminal charges that senior officers and employees had illegally
diverted $19.1 million in unclaimed checks and other credits owed
to customers to the bank's own books to enhance its financial
performance. The bank agreed to pay a $60 million fine to the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The bank also said it would pay a separate fine of $3.5 million
to New York state authorities for the illegal scheme. Some of the
unclaimed funds taken by the bank were to have been turned over to
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in Manhattan also charged that in the
scheme, which occurred between 1994 and 1996, the bank's officials,
including a partner and a managing director, had created a ``slush
fund'' of the unclaimed money that they used to supplement income
or offset expenses ``as needed'' at the end of financial reporting
periods, falsely enhancing the bank's financial results for that
period.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, called the senior
bank officials' behavior brazen and a ``willful disregard for their
legal obligations with respect to the proper handling of unclaimed
customer funds and abandoned property.''
</P>
<P>
   She credited other Bankers Trust officials with first uncovering
the scheme in 1996 and reporting it to the government, but she also
accused the bank of initially minimizing ``the extent of the
culpability of its officers and employees.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said that the scheme originated after Bankers Trust's
senior management had ``placed severe pressure'' on managers to
generate revenues and meet expense targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bankers Trust's guilty plea demonstrates the serious
consequences for all financial institutions that would violate the
law by misapplying their customers' funds in order to falsely
enhance their financial results,'' she said, adding: ``It is
conduct that will not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   At an evening court proceeding in U.S. district court in
Manhattan, David D. Brown IV, a managing director and counsel for
the bank, said that the bank had fired all the officers and
employees involved in the scheme. Court documents said 13 people
were involved.
</P>
<P>
   The document did not name the employees, and bank officials
refused to identify them. The plea bargain document explicitly
states that in accepting the bank's plea, prosecutors will continue
to prosecute people who may have been involved in the illegal
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bank acknowledges the violations of U.S. criminal law to
which it is pleading guilty,'' Brown told Judge John Koeltl. ``The
bank accepts responsibility for these transactions and the conduct
of its employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Newman, chairman and chief executive officer of Bankers
Trust, said by phone Thursday night that the bank had cooperated
fully with the authorities and would continue to do so as the
investigation continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unfortunate situation, no question about it,''
Newman said. ``On the other hand, it's something that's years old.
We pursued it actively. We launched an investigation. We reported
it to the authorities, and made the necessary changes and brought
in the right people.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Ms. White's characterization that bank officials had
initially minimized the responsibility of its officers and
employees, Newman said that it had taken the bank ``months and
months'' to uncover the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they are saying is that during that process, we
discovered that some of the people who we didn't know in the
beginning were involved in this turned out to be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   During the initial meetings with outside authorities, Newman
said, ``some of those people were there for the discussions. They
may not have said, `Hey, I was part of this.' They didn't hold up
their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank AG said in November that it would acquire Bankers
Trust for $10.1 billion. The acquisition is expected to result in
the elimination of 5,500 jobs, mostly in New York and London.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Bankers Trust would be the largest foreign
takeover of an American bank and would vault Deutsche Bank over UBS
AG of Switzerland and the new Citigroup as the world's biggest bank
in assets.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the acquisition is something that Newman had long sought to
avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust, founded in 1903 to handle the trust business of
other large banks, had transformed itself in the late 1980s and
1990s into one of the most aggressive and innovative trading shops
on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of derivatives scandals a few years ago wreaked
financial havoc on the bank. A handful of companies said they were
hit with large unexpected losses from complex deals with Bankers
Trust, leading to the departure of Charles S. Sanford Jr. as its
chairman and the ascent of Newman to that position in 1995. The
company was embarrassed when a court made public transcripts of
telephone calls between Bankers Trust employees gloating about how
much money they were making and how little their clients understood
the risk of the deals being made.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an uneven performance through the first half of 1998,
Newman was still well positioned to keep Deutsche Bank at a
distance until the torrent of ill will unleashed by the acquisition
of Alex. Brown &AMP; Sons, which was a regional brokerage firm, and
substantial trading losses in July and August combined to weaken
his standing.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Bankers Trust, posting its next-to-last earnings
report before the expected completion of its acquisition by
Deutsche Bank, said profit in its fourth quarter plunged 54
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
