<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, MARCH 12
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Mar. 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Mar. 9,
about a dispute between the Clinton Administration and
Congressional Republicans over what to make public from a
classified House committee report on China's acquisition of United
States military technology misstated a concern of Representative
Christopher Cox, the California Republican who is the chairman of
the committee. He said he feared that some of the findings would
not be disclosed in the declassification process, not that they
would be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NISSAN-ASSESS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Mar. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Mar.
10, about the financial difficulties faced by the Nissan Motor
Company misstated the amount of credit it has received from the
Japan Development Bank. It is $700 million, not $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SMALL-COLLEGES-EDUC-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Mar. 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Mar. 9,
about problems facing small private liberal arts colleges misstated
the percentage of admitted applicants to Ivy League colleges and
universities who ultimately enroll at Ivy League schools. The
highest percentage in the Ivy League last year was 79.2 percent, at
Harvard; the overall figure for the eight institutions was not
``well over 90 percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
