A7203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ORGANS-DONATE-NY     03-11 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ORGANS-DONATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MISGUIDED CHAUVINISM ON ORGANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Friday, March 12: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The way donated human organs are distributed to patients in this
country urgently needs reform. A report released by the Department
of Health and Human Services shows wide geographic disparities in
waiting times for livers, kidneys and other organs needed to save
lives. The median wait for patients with blood type O for a liver
transplant in New York City, for example, is 511 days, while the
wait a few miles away in New Jersey is 56 days. These irrational
differences arise from a system that often requires that organs be
used in the area where they are donated even though they might be
more urgently needed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has blocked an order from the Health and Human Services
Secretary, Donna Shalala, that might have produced reform. Last
year Ms. Shalala directed the United Network for Organ Sharing, a
private organization that distributes donated organs, to devise a
new allocation strategy. Her department outlined general goals,
such as establishing standards for ranking patients on transplant
waiting lists, but left the details up to the network.
</P>
<P>
   Many transplant centers lobbied vigorously against change,
however, fearing that new rules would reduce their current supply
of locally donated organs. Congress then inserted a provision in
last year's omnibus budget bill to delay the effective date of the
directive until this coming October, and asked the Institute of
Medicine to review the problem, which it is doing now.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile a handful of states have tried to pre-empt the entire
debate with laws designed to give top priority to in-state
residents, even though patients elsewhere may have more critical
needs. These misconceived laws reflect a dangerous parochialism
that, if copied in other states, can only threaten needy patients
everywhere by limiting the availability of organ donations to
increasingly smaller geographic areas.
</P>
<P>
   An important reason for the transplant crisis, apart from the
flawed delivery system, is that the nation as a whole faces a
severe organ shortage. More than 61,000 Americans are on organ
transplant waiting lists. Some 4,000 patients die every year while
waiting for an organ. The Clinton administration has taken some
remedial steps. For example, it has required hospitals to notify
organ procurement organizations whenever a hospital patient dies,
so that no potential donor is overlooked. The current budget
significantly increases funding for programs to encourage
donations.
</P>
<P>
   But increased donations alone will not eliminate the problem of
unfair geographic distribution. That can best be solved by uniform
medical criteria that give patients in all regions a fair shot at a
lifesaving transplant, regardless of where they live. This issue
must ultimately be addressed at the national level. Until it is,
state legislatures should resist passing laws that would make the
problem worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
