<HEADER>
A7209 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-1STLD     03-11 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE MOVES AHEAD WITH KOSOVO DEBATE OVER WHITE HOUSE OBJECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS with outcome of House vote; complete writethru) 
(EDS: This is once again a page 1 story.) 
(wg) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House rejected an effort to oppose the
deployment of U.S. troops in Kosovo as it debated Balkan policy
well into the night on Thursday despite the Clinton
administration's objections.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, 178-237, rejecting an amendment offered by Rep. Tillie
Fowler, R-Fla., left it quite likely, though still not certain,
that the House would ultimately vote on a resolution to endorse
sending troops to Kosovo as part of a NATO peacekeeping force, in
the event that a settlement is reached in the Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Passionate and sharply divided, House members argued throughout
the day and into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of deploying the troops argued that the United States
had to help stop a ``genocidal war'' that could ignite a broader
conflict. Opponents countered that Europe, not the United States,
should police a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Although any House action on the issue would not be binding on
Clinton, the vote was taken at a crucial diplomatic juncture in the
faltering peace effort, as a new round of international
negotiations over Kosovo was scheduled to resume on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The main resolution still under consideration in the House would
authorize the president to deploy U.S. troops to join a NATO
peacekeeping force in Kosovo. Congressional officials from both
parties said the vote on that resolution was too close to call,
keeping alive the possibility of a sharp repudiation for Clinton,
even as he traveled overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Senior members of the president's foreign policy team, many
overseas, called lawmakers throughout the day. In Guatemala,
Clinton said, ``I do not believe that Congress should take any
action that will in effect pre-empt the peace process or encourage
either side to say no to it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright implored the
House to hold off, saying that a vote against troops at a delicate
moment of western diplomacy would be seen as ``a green light to
resume fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   She was backed by Bob Dole, former Republican presidential
candidate and Senate majority leader, who warned Congress that a no
vote could ``throw cold water on any possible agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an aggressive assertion of Congress' role in foreign
policy, House Speaker Dennis Hastert refused to heed the call for
delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tried to be direct and honest with the president and
his secretary of state,'' Hastert said on the House floor. ``I told
them that I believed it was my duty as speaker to ensure that
members of the House of Representatives, Republican and Democrat,
have the opportunity to fairly and openly debate this important
issue before troops are sent into a potentially dangerous
situation. I believe Congress must have a meaningful role in this
decision, no matter how difficult our choice nor how hard our
task.''
</P>
<P>
   The day was also a test of how Hastert would compare with Newt
Gingrich, a confirmed internationalist. The Illinoisian said in a
late afternoon interview that he had told Albright a while ago that
``probably my presumption would be I would be favorable to'' the
proposal to deploy 4,000 troops as part of a 28,000-member NATO
force.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he would not finally decide until he had heard the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   He was also unapologetic about his timing for forcing the issue
to the floor. ``We need to have an open debate,'' Hastert said in
the interview. ``The White House _ I'm just being perfectly honest
about this _ was rather reticent to come up to Congress to try to
sell this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The House majority leader, Dick Armey, and the Republican whip,
Tom DeLay, opposed deploying troops. DeLay called the plan a ``big
dangerous quagmire'' and ``another bad idea in a foreign policy
with no focus.'' He said the Clinton administration had become too
dependent on airstrikes or the threats of airstrikes, speaking of
bombings in Iraq, strikes against targets in Sudan and Afghanistan
and the threat of air strikes against Serbian targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bombing sovereign nations for ill-defined reasons with vague
objectives undermines U.S. stature in the world,'' DeLay said.
``The international respect and trust for America is diminished
every time we casually let the bombs fly. We must stop giving the
appearance that our foreign policy is formulated by the
Unabomber.''
</P>
<P>
   Through hours of sharp debate into the night, members clashed
over the post-Cold War role of the United States, as well as over
the U.S. leadership role in NATO. The members argued over whether
outsiders could ever end the ethnic strife in the Balkans, where
two world wars began, and expressed misgivings about the length of
the U.S. peacekeeping mission in Bosnia, which Clinton had once
promised would be limited in time.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The debate split the Republican Party. Most Democrats spoke out
in support of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recall Bosnia, my friends,'' Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C.,
said. ``The president told us our troops would be back home, I
believe, by December of 1996. But when I last checked, December
1996 has come and long gone, and our troops are still there.''
</P>
<P>
   In disagreeing, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said, ``There really is
a moral obligation for those who have the resources to intercede.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats spoke forcefully for deployment and questioned
why the Republican leadership had scheduled such a debate when a
new round of diplomacy was beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the height of irresponsibility,'' Rep. Dick Gephardt,
the House minority leader, said. ``This should not be about
politics. It should not be about giving the administration a black
eye. This is about ending a humanitarian catastrophe and preventing
the slaughter of thousands of innocent people caught in a simmering
ethnic conflict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
