<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-REPORT12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    167 Texas counties declared at high risk for fires
 &HT;    By staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, citing an abnormally dry
winter, on Thursday declared 167 counties as emergency areas
because of imminent fire danger.
</P>
<P>
   The counties, including Travis, Bastrop, Williamson, Caldwell,
Hays and Burnet, are generally those west of and along Interstate
35 and Interstate 37.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious situation, and we must take steps now to
reduce fire risk, put firefighting equipment and personnel in
place, and conserve water.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the emergency declaration, Bush asked President
Clinton to make the state eligible for additional resources for
fighting wild fires. Bush also wants all counties to consider bans
on outdoor burning. Thirty-five counties, including Hays and
Caldwell, already have enacted such bans.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also asked all cities and water suppliers to
prepare water conservation plans to put in effect if the drought
predictions prove accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though many of us are having some cool and drizzly days,
we should not get a false sense of security,'' he said. ``The
drought has a head start on most of Texas this year, and we must be
prepared to conserve water and prevent fires today.''COMMITTEE
CLEARS HATE CRIME BILL
</P>
<P>
   A House committee voted 6-2 on the James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes
Act, named in memory of the black man dragged to his death behind a
truck in East Texas last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that if this bill is passed, it will not bring my
brother back,'' Louvon Harris, Byrd's youngest sister, told the
Judicial Affairs Committee on Thursday. ``But I have friends and
family who still have to live in this society. I want it passed for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting against the legislation were vice chairman Rep. Will
Hartnett (R-Dallas) and Rep. John Shields (R-San Antonio).
</P>
<P>
   ``A crime is a crime, and the fact that one child could be
killed and punished differently than another child because of the
motivation of the killer is not equal protection under the law,''
Hartnett said.SENATOR LINKS BILL TO SPEED TRAPS
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gregory Luna says a bill passed Thursday by the Senate
would encourage speed traps around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill by Sen. Teel Bivins (R-Amarillo), the state's 85
school districts that have police departments, including the Austin
Independent School District, would get half of the fines they
collect from Class C misdemeanor crimes committed on school
property or at school-sponsored events. Class C misdemeanors can
include motor vehicle crimes, such as speeding.
</P>
<P>
   Luna (D-San Antonio) said if schools know they will get some of
the money, they will push officers to issue more citations.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said he doubted that would happen but he will revisit the
issue if it does.
</P>
<P>
   DEADLINE TO FILE BILLS IS TODAY
</P>
<P>
   Today is the last day for legislators to file proposed laws.
</P>
<P>
   Already, thousands of bills are working their way through the
legislative process. Hundreds more could be filed today.
</P>
<P>
   After today, the 60th day of the session, lawmakers will have to
seek permission from their colleagues to file a bill. If that
fails, or if they want to go another route to get a late idea
through the process, lawmakers could attempt to rewrite a similar
bill with their unfiled proposals.
</P>
<P>
   That process is known as substituting a bill.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
