<HEADER>
A7213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DORM-CAMPUS-FIRES12-C     03-11 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORM-CAMPUS-FIRES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas universities' high-rise dorms don't meet fire safety
standards
 &HT;    By Angela Shah
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sixteen high-rise dormitories on Texas
university campuses _ in particular Jester Towers at the University
of Texas _ lack fire safety equipment like sprinklers and lighted
exits, a state fire marshal told legislators Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A yearlong inspection of 23 dorms at state universities
uncovered dozens of state fire safety code violations at high-rise
dorms at public universities. The inspections stem from by a 1997
fire in a 13-story Texas Tech dormitory that injured several
students. A parent's complaint about the fire led to the the state
fire marshal inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the inspections showed that many of the
``high-rise'' dorms had battery-powered smoke detectors _ some that
did not work _ lacked sprinkler systems and did not have
spring-loaded mechanisms to swing doors closed.
</P>
<P>
   Jester at UT, which houses 3,000 students, was at the top of the
fire marshal's list for needing attention. The 11-story, two-tower
dorm has no sprinkler system, no emergency lighting in its basement
and tower stairwells are not smokeproof, among other things. Some
fire safety improvements are not scheduled to be finished until
2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dangerous not to have sprinklers in the high-rises,''
said Wayne Smith, director of fire safety inspections for the fire
marshal's office. ``By definition, high-rises are above the level
that the fire department (ladders) can get to.'' Most fire
department ladders stretch seven stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a sprinkler system,'' Smith added, ``you can get
to a fire before it's out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings were reported to a higher education subcommittee of
the state House Appropriations Committee, which writes the state
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very concerned that the universities have not been more
timely on this, but I am encouraged by the timeline with the state
fire marshal,'' said State Rep. Dianne Delisi (R-Temple). ``But
this needs to be an ongoing effort. They need to inspect the
buildings on a regular basis. I'm surprised it hasn't already been
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The state fire marshal inspects government buildings on request
or when a complaint is made.
</P>
<P>
   State Fire Marshal Mike Davis told subcommittee members that the
23 universities plan to complete renovations by 2004. Some
improvements, which will cost millions, are contingent on obtaining
funding, state fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Until that time, Davis said the fire marshal's office will
inspect all the properties every four months. State lawmakers said
they will review inspection reports.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the buildings at the universities were built in the
1960s and 1970s before sprinkler systems and other measures were
required, administrators said. The Life Safety Code, which most
states around the country use as the fire safety code for all
public and private buildings, was not state law in Texas until
1995. Once it became state law, Smith said the fire marshal's
office had authority to cite state buildings for code violations.
</P>
<P>
   Universities say they understand the need for sprinklers and
other fire safety tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that fire safety is not a priority. The sprinklers
will be done in four phases during the summers,'' said UT vice
president for legal and administrative affairs Patricia Ohlendorf.
``We've made a number of improvements in Jester since it was built
in the 1960s.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlendorf said Jester has fire hoses on each floor, fire
evacuation maps on each resident door and hard-wired smoke
detectors _ which are still being installed. A new fire alarm
system will be operational next month.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Abboud a sophomore who lives on Jester's first floor, said
he feels safe without the sprinklers. But he moved from the third
floor last fall, in part, because his mother was concerned about
fire dangers. He added that the battery-controlled smoke detector
in his room was replaced with a central-system smoke detector and
UT checks it regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was concerned about the sprinklers, but she feels OK
about it now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Fire Prevention Association in Battery
Park, Mass., sprinklers reduce the chances of dying and the loss of
property damage from a fire by one-half to two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   Several universities say the improvements will take at least two
years primarily because of the cost of completing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about millions and millions,'' said Mike
Griffith, building safety director at Stephen F. Austin University
in Nacogdoches.
</P>
<P>
   SFA's 10-story, two-tower Steen Hall lacks a sprinkler system,
door closers and an emergency light at the main entrance. When fire
officials inspected it last year, they did not fidn a service
record for the fire alarm. Complying with the fire code will cost
about $1.8 million, Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're state-funded,'' he said, ``you can't just pull it
out of the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
