<HEADER>
A7217 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-PARIS12-COX     03-11 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PARIS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laroche misses mark; Rykiel hits pop spot
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Guy Laroche line, which hasn't packed much punch on
the American market for decades, did little to rise in the rankings
with its showing Thursday morning. At its trendiest, belts were the
focal point of this collection. Coats, sweaters, blouses and skirts
all featured a belt of some sort, most notably in snakeskin. Some
of these belts even seemed attuned to the ``utility'' phase fashion
is going through, given that they included zippered pockets.
</P>
<P>
   There were some nice, reversible sheared fur coats, and the
mohair dresses and jackets looked delightful to the touch. The main
colors in play _ green, pink and brown _ were indicative of how
mismatched this collection was to most women's needs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sonia Rykiel: The wiry-haired designer Sonia Rykiel has witty
ways of incorporating figments of pop culture into her collections.
</P>
<P>
   Last year during her spring/summer preview, she hitched a ride
on hip-hop's coattails and produced a bevy of ultrabaggy,
cargo-style pants and floppy hats; and for her fall/winter '99
collection shown Thursday, Rykiel culled the current kiss-and-tell
craze and adorned most of her clothes with lipstick prints of
Lewinskyan proportions.
</P>
<P>
   The embroidered, sequined or appliqued lip prints were placed on
all the imaginable/unmentionable erogenous zones. They were
disconcertingly prevalent distractions from the luxurious cashmere,
angora and alpaca separates Rykiel started her show with. Rykiel's
take on the ``sweater-dressing'' trend featured floor-length
pleated skirts with high splits, ribbed knit bathrobe-style coats
and long ski cardigans.
</P>
<P>
   All the knitwear in the collection realistically addressed
women's need for warmth, but with so many high-tech materials at
designers' disposal these days, Rykiel's clothes appeared rather
retro.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
