<HEADER>
A7222 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MINIREVIEWS14-CO     03-11 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MINIREVIEWS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robert enters a killer's mind with great insight
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  A Sight for Sore Eyes. By Ruth Rendell. Crown. $24.
</P>
<P>
   Fine writing, a hallmark of Ruth Rendell's mysteries, is matched
by her insight into sociopathology in one of the best of her 42
books. The lives of three characters are traced over two decades.
Teddy, product of an uncaring environment, develops into a
promising artisan with no conscience or comprehension of love.
Francine, 19, whom he loves instantly and obsessively, was a child
when she witnessed her mother's murder.
</P>
<P>
   The trauma left Francine temporarily unable to speak, but she
has since recovered and been accepted at Oxford. She is
overprotected by a batty stepmother, Harriet, the visionary beauty
featured in a painting on which the novel is based. Over the
decades she grows vain, faded and jaded. Trapped in a loveless
marriage, she seduces young handymen.
</P>
<P>
   The lives of the three converge tragically as Teddy finds that
murder does not mar his conscience. Rendell's tale is made more
spellbinding by well-drawn, Dickensian characters adrift in the
20th century. She explores class differences, family interaction,
useless lives, entrapment and the ways in which crimes mirror the
society that helped spawn them.
</P>
<P>
   The unsolved murder of Francine's mother hovers throughout. Less
crafty writers would have trouble tying up such complex factors,
but Rendell's ending is an ironic and elegiac variation of Poe's
``The Cask of Amontillado.'' The British author pays discreet
homage to her forebears and elevates mystery writing to literature.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hush Money. By Robert B. Parker. Putnam. $22.95.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Parker has been writing Spenser-Hawk novels for 25 years,
and the wear occasionally shows. But the shamus and his sidekick
still crack wise, Spenser's code of honor remains untarnished, and
he and Susan maintain a lusty relationship. Plus, Parker still
excels in creating timely situations. In ``Hush Money,'' Spenser
takes on two unrelated pro bono jobs for Hawk and Susan. Robinson
Nevins, a black conservative professor denied tenure, wants Parker
to find out why.
</P>
<P>
   The plot wends its way through gay society, academia and white
supremacist culture. Meanwhile, Susan talks Spenser into tracking
down the stalker of a divorced friend, who soon becomes as much
stalker as stalkee. The plots bump awkwardly _ it's almost as if
Parker combined two book ideas into one.
</P>
<P>
   One climactic scene is too contrived and the other
uncharacteristically tame: One hungers for a shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parker writes well about the complexity of relationships,
his portrayal of academic bureaucracy is on target, and he
struggles _ against a macho tradition _ to convey gender, sexual
identity and race issues with sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
