<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKNOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mickle gleans extraordinary from everyday lives
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Novels about divorce are as common as, well, divorces. But
Shelley Fraser Mickle's novel ``Replacing Dad'' (Algonquin Books of
Chapel Hill, $16.95) transcends the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to air at 9 p.m. Sunday (4608) as a CBS movie,
``Replacing Dad'' is a partly humorous, partly dramatic story of a
teenage son who tries to hold the family together after a messy
divorce in a small Florida town. To complicate matters, the father
not only leaves the family, he marries his daughter's fifth-grade
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The point of ``Replacing Dad,'' says Mickle, 55, is that he's
irreplaceable. ``Many fathers think they're valued only for their
economic contributions, but they are needed emotionally as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gainesville, Fla., author got the idea for the book from an
incident that happened to a friend whose husband had left her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She mentioned to me that her son, who was about 12, was having
trouble sleeping. She learned that he felt he was responsible for
the safety of the family and stayed up all night listening for
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Mickle has never been divorced is no handicap, she
says. ``Divorce is all around me, and I feel compelled to try to
address my friends' pain. The fact that I'm happily married and not
divorced anchors me emotionally. If I had been divorced, I wouldn't
have had the strength to write about what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   An Arkansas native, Mickle grew up determined to become a
writer. A turning point came in the 1950s when she contracted polio
and spent a year in wheelchairs and braces. ``It was like my mind
became crystallized in the sense that I was kept a child forever,''
she says. ``But I also became a very old person who understood what
was really important in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickle attended the University of Mississippi in hopes of
absorbing the Faulkner mystique, then devoted two years to reading
the classics and honing her writing skills. During the next 20
years she raised two children, published a few short stories, and
finally sold ``The Queen of October'' in 1989. It, too, was about
the effects of divorce on a family.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to get her most recent novel published, Mickle is
working on a collection of her National Public Radio essays and
another novel about a family changed by divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a subject that is endlessly fascinating to me,'' she
says. ``Real life is not necessarily great dramatic happenings.
People who lead ordinary lives can be extraordinary. That's what my
fiction is about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Deadly dosage: Reading Robin Cook is enough to make some
people avoid hospitals or at least wear a surgical mask whenever
they venture outside of their homes. Beginning with his novel
``Coma,'' which dealt with stolen human organs, Cook has turned out
a succession of medical thrillers about everything from plague to
genetic engineering.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest novel, ``Vector'' (Putnam's, $24.95), a
disgruntled Russian emigre teams up with a right-wing group in New
York to use anthrax as a way of exacting revenge on the United
States for the end of the Cold War and the breakup of the Soviet
Union. Only forensic pathologists Jack Stapleton and Laurie
Montgomery stand between the terrorists and disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Recent news stories about bioterrorism in Japan and anthrax
threats in Atlanta and other cities make such fictional scenarios
even scarier, Cook says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I finish one of these books I feel kind of
semi-responsible,'' says Cook, 57, an ophthalmologist who still
practices occasionally in Boston. ``But bioterrorism is not a
secret to the right-wing groups. These guys can get recipes for any
biological weapon off the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook will sign books at 7 p.m. Wednesday at Barnes &AMP; Noble, 2900
Peachtree Road N.E., 404-261-7747.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the news: Russell Banks' ``Cloudsplitter'' and Barbara
Kingsolver's ``The Poisonwood Bible'' are two of the nominees for
the PEN/Faulkner Award for fiction. Other nominees are ``Starting
Out in the Evening'' by Brian Morton, ``The Hours'' by Michael
Cunningham and ``The Doctor Stories'' by Richard Selzer. Winners
will be announced in April. . . . The 35th annual Georgia Author of
the Year Awards ceremony will be held Saturday at Mercer University
in Macon. The 86 nominees are Georgia residents who have published
a book in 1998. The all-day event will include three seminars about
writing, finding an agent and publisher and trends in publishing.
Information: 770-943-5699.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
