<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7228 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-GOODWIN14-COX     03-11 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GOODWIN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Godwin's women try to balance secular, sacred
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest challenge for any writer growing up in Asheville,
N.C., in the 1940s was avoiding the long shadow of Thomas Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Godwin had no problem meeting that challenge, because she
had a much more romantic role model: a mother who worked as a
newspaper reporter by day and wrote stories for pulp romances by
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was natural of me to want to do the same thing,'' says
Godwin, 62, who remembers her mother dashing off to her job in the
morning and returning after dark ``in elated exhaustion, wearing
the smoky, inky smells of her larger world.''
</P>
<P>
   As the child of divorced parents, Godwin's other role model was
her grandmother, who cooked and ran the household. ``She was a
remarkable woman, but as far as I was concerned, the choice was
simple. At 5, I allied myself with the typewriter rather than the
stove.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen books and numerous awards later, Godwin's choice
apparently was the right one. Critics from Joyce Carol Oates to
Kurt Vonnegut praised her debut novel, ``The Perfectionists,'' and
subsequent works for their portrayal of intelligent, creative
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godwin's great topic is woman's search for identity,''
novelist Lee Smith wrote in her review of ``Father Melancholy's
Daughter'' (1991) in the Los Angeles Times. ``Her literate, smart
women characters possess the free will to make choices, to take
responsibility for their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what Margaret Bonner does in Godwin's new novel,
``Evensong'' (Ballantine Books, $25). A young motherless daughter
of an Episcopal priest in ``Father Melancholy's Daughter,''
Margaret returns in this sequel as the pastor of a church in a
North Carolina mountain village. It is the eve of the millennium
and Margaret is married to Adrian Bonner, a much older man who
suffers from bouts of depression. Both are better at dealing with
the problems of others than with their stale marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview from her home in Woodstock, N.Y., where she
lives with her longtime companion, composer Robert Starer, Godwin
talked about her writing, her views on religion and the
autobiographical nature of her women characters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did you first begin writing?
</P>
<P>
   A: I sent my first story to Child Life when I was 9. It was
rejected, but they said to keep trying. It was about a man who was
henpecked by his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You wrote that your mother would ``read'' stories to you out
of a blank address book. Did that inspire you to be a writer?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was 4 or 5 then. This was before I could read fluently. I
knew there were no words in that little book, and I knew exactly
what she was doing. Seeing her do it made it possible to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Evensong'' and ``Father Melancholy's Daughter'' are
essentially about faith. People today seem to be concerned with
spirituality, yet novelists are reluctant to address this. Why do
you do it, and why do you think others don't?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Grace Mungers (a firebrand evangelist in ``Evensong'')
are in great excess. These are the people who want to accost you
with their own God-image. That's very off-putting. That's why
serious novelists veer away from the subject. The God image is an
ineffable thing, and it has to do with the individual and inner
life. The reason I wanted to write a book about a priest and a
woman of God is because I couldn't find one. The only character of
a woman minister that I could find in English was in George Eliot's
``Adam Bede.'' I wanted her to be married and have to deal with the
sensual side of life and those problems. I wanted to create a
female model of the spiritual life for myself.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do your women characters want?
</P>
<P>
   A: They used to want independence in my early novels. And
security. And they wanted to escape the cultural strictures of
their upbringing at the same time they wanted to be comforted by
the cultural aspects of their upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was a middle period when their vocation, their work
became very important. ``The Odd Woman,'' for example, was a story
about a young professor who gauged her life by what she knew of
literature. The character in ``Violet Clay'' was a young artist who
was trying to make the leap from talented illustrator to original
artist.
</P>
<P>
   In my last three books, my heroines are definitely being drawn
to the life of reflection _ the double life of being truly in the
world and truly in the spiritual sphere as well. They're trying to
find a balance.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have had many tragedies in your life. Your father
deserted your family when you were a child and later committed
suicide. Your half-brother committed suicide, and your mother was
killed in an auto accident. Does writing about them help? How?
</P>
<P>
   A: One way I handle tragedy is to distance myself. I created a
father for myself in ``Father Melancholy's Daughter.'' It was just
the kind of father who suited me yet had some of the
characteristics of my father. Both were depressed, but my father
was a playboy and Father Melancholy was a priest.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Southern Family,'' I wrote about a character who
committed suicide that was based on my half-brother. I just wanted
to write and follow it as closely as I could. It's left unsolved at
the end. As I wrote in ``Father Melancholy's Daughter,'' as long as
you still feel grief, they're still with you. You don't want the
ache to go away.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you sometimes feel you spend more time observing than
experiencing life?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm still working on enjoying the moment. I think that's
something very few people, writers included, achieve. I used to
have more of an ironic distance than I do now. I seem to be falling
in love with direct simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
