<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7229 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROADWAY-NEWSHOWS14-C     03-11 1835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-NEWSHOWS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With a dearth of pioneering new works, old guarantees gold on
the Great White Way
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Broadway has long feared the shock of the new. This
season, though, the Main Stem is doing quite well, thank you, with
the shock of the old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death of a Salesman'' is once again a Jovian thunderbolt under
director Robert Falls, perhaps even more searing than it was in its
legendary premiere 50 years ago. Ditto ``Electra,'' featuring a Zoe
Wannamaker with a punkish haircut and a bottomless tank of rage.
``Fosse,'' like ``Chicago,'' shows that the late choreographer Bob
Fosse's jaded joy in the human body is even more in tune with our
premillennial, no-more-secrets age than the decades when he created
the dances. ``Not About Nightingales,'' the lost melodrama by a
27-year-old Tennessee Williams making its American premiere by way
of London, has been mounted by Trevor Nunn to maximize the
existential chill of its prison setting.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for every bracing new Broadway entry there's a safer,
mushier one. ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' got mixed
reviews. ``Footloose'' was kicked around. Bernadette Peters brings
sensual warmth to ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' but almost everything
else about the revival is, as Irving Berlin wrote elsewhere, as
cold as yesterday's mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that Broadway, as it heads into the
seven-week gun lap before the cutoff (April 28) for Tony Award
nominations, is on track to top its record-setting mark of 11.5
million tickets sold in 1997-98. But the numbers really say more
about the hotness of long-runners (``Rent,'' ``Cabaret,'' ``The
Lion King'') than they do about the shows that have been added to
the Broadway lineup since this past June.
</P>
<P>
   The season's lack of good new works will be nakedly revealed
when the Tony Award nominating committee meets in May. Unlike the
revival categories (``Salesman'' vs. the Kevin Spacey ``Iceman
Cometh,'' opening April 8, will be in a tremendous face-off for
best revival of a play), the pickings for best play and musical
will be slim. Broadway has drifted so far from its role of 1949 _
when a ``Salesman'' could triumph as an unknown quantity _ that the
favorites for 1999's best play will be pre-heralded London imports:
Conor McPherson's ``The Weir'' (previewing March 23) and David
Hare's ``Amy's View,'' starring Judi Dench (April 3).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most bitter reminder of Broadway's commercial
realities was the untimely demise of ``Parade'' last month. The
daring musical by Alfred Uhry and Jason Robert Brown was undone by
its mixed reviews and unsparing sadness. Its short run makes it a
long shot for best musical. The favorite at this point would have
to be the red-hot ``Fosse'' (classified as ``new'' by the
Tony-nominating committee, even though it's old material). ``The
Civil War,'' set to Frank Wildhorn's country-western pop score and
opening April 22, shapes up as the only other contender. Here's a
rundown of what's new in New York:
</P>
<P>
   `Fosse'
</P>
<P>
   Watching ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' (1989) a few seasons ago
was like a trip through time, to a carefree New York of the 1940s
and '50s, when the mating dances of sailors and secretaries were
lighter than air and even the street gangs moved with balletic
grace.
</P>
<P>
   Watching ``Fosse,'' the new anthology of work by the late
choreographer, it's the dances that travel forward, leap into life
in our moment of time. The numbers are so amazingly contemporary
that you look at them and wonder how they could have been created
25 or 45 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fosse was often sexual (he worked many teenage hours in Chicago
burlesque houses) but never coarse; he discovered the elegant in
the blatant. Like a great playwright or musician, he made as much
from stillness as movement. His dancers wore pure black long before
it was the uniform of cool. They had attitude before anyone called
it that. They stalk downstage, like cats after prey, while the
snapping of fingers, the whisper of brushes on cymbals, creates the
charge of expectation that at any moment they will pounce upon some
note and brand the air with their fiery tableaux.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tremendously entertaining Broadway show. As conceived by
Richard Maltb Jr. (the director), Chet Walker (who re-creates the
Fosse choreography) and former Fosse girlfriend-collaborator Ann
Reinking (who assists them both), the show roams through the late
choreographer's entire canon _ from Broadway to TV specials to
films (``Cabaret,'' ``All That Jazz''). Pat Brady's orchestra, with
powerhouse brass, sounds terrific. At 2 1/2 hours, it's a bit too
much of a good thing, but the sheer variety ensures something new
for even the Fosse aficionado.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest number, ``Steam Heat'' from ``Pajama Game'' (1954),
is the most joyous. It places its dancers (led by Jane Lanier,
looking eerily similar to Fosse wife/interpreter Gwen Verdon) in
the baggy suits of vaudevillian clowns so that they can better
ambush us with endless inventions of athletic grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's Ruby''
</P>
<P>
   It's uncomfortable for any Atlantan who's enjoyed the work of
director Kenny Leon at the Alliance Theatre to see his long-awaited
New York debut production at off-Broadway's Joseph Papp Public
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Barely any of Leon's talent shines through, mainly because of
Thulani Davis' choppy script. Starting with the documented case of
Ruby McCollom (Viola Davis), a black Florida woman convicted in
1952 of killing a white doctor, and Zora Neale Hurston's (Phylicia
Rashad) attempt to revive her career by covering the trial for a
Northern newspaper, the playwright adds confusing layers of
speculation (including Hurston's ``visions''). Was Ruby raped by
the doctor? Did she then begin an affair with him, or was sex her
payment for morphine? Is the playwright stacking the deck to make
Ruby appear more of a victim?
</P>
<P>
   The story has the Grade B Southern gothic-ness of ``In the Heat
of the Night'' (the TV show, not the movie). Early scenes have an
awkwardness one never sees in Leon's Alliance productions. Davis is
a terrific choice for Ruby _ a woman who broods behind an invisible
steel visor _ but Leon's casting brilliance failed him in the
choice of the doctor. Beau Gravitte's ``dangerous good-ol'-boy''
seems like a slightly campy put-on.
</P>
<P>
   Even Rashad, looking overweight and unsure of herself, has an
off day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bright Lights, Big City''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, ``Rent'' is a hard act to follow, but just about any
new rock musical would have been better for director Michael Greif
and off-Broadway's New York Theatre Workshop.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``City'' deals with 20-something downtown types enjoying a
surplus of sex partners and drugs (``Cocaine: Dran-o for the
brain-o!''), but in every other respect, the 1984 Jay McInerney
novel is the anti-``Rent.'' It's cynical and intimately
confessional, where the late Jonathan Larson's musical was romantic
and larger than life. Yet Greif and adaptor/lyricist Paul Scott
Goodman attack the story of Jamie (the preposterously clean-cut
Patrick Wilson) with high energy and no irony, as if he were
another of ``Rent's'' idealistic bohemians instead of the
self-centered, darkly compulsive, blocked writer that he is. The
novel was redeemed by McInerney's sour wit, but the Scottish
Goodman translates almost none of it to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman is a good composer, however, nearly as good as Larson,
and ought to jump right back into a creative mode with a good
playwright and/or lyricist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashes to Ashes''
</P>
<P>
   What in the world has happened to Harold Pinter? Now 68 and one
of the master dramatists of the 1950s and '60s, he hasn't written a
satisfying full-length play in 20 years. ``Moonlight'' was
ballyhooed as his comeback play a few seasons ago but wasn't. He is
Britain's answer to Sam Shepard: the prematurely disappearing
playwright.
</P>
<P>
   Now from London comes the only slightly-less-ballyhooed ``Ashes
to Ashes.'' At 40 uneventful minutes, the production at the
Gramercy Theatre might be described as an unformed riddle not quite
wrapped in an enigma.
</P>
<P>
   In their coldly pristine English home, a man (David Strathairn,
too stiff) interrogates a woman (Lindsay Duncan, riveting) about a
former lover who may have been a sadist (``He put his fist against
my mouth . . . tore babies from the arms of screaming mothers . .
.''). She seems to be self-hypnotized. Whether she's aroused or
horrified, amoral or numb, fantasizing or channeling another
woman's traumatic memory, we do not know.
</P>
<P>
   Nor _ thanks to Pinter's chilly, quick-sketch approach _ do we
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie Get Your Gun''
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette Peters finally has the sun-splashed, melody-rich,
girl-gets-boy musical that she has always deserved. At
50-going-on-30, the pocket goddess has no trouble commanding the
boys' attention, and in the strapping baritone Tom Wopat, she
finally has one worth getting.
</P>
<P>
   And Broadway at last _ just two months before the Tony Award
cutoff _ will have its first bona-fide hit musical of the season,
if there's any justice.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big if, however, considering that some elements of this
revival don't come close to the stars' level. If Peters and Wopat
weren't onstage so much, this Graciela Daniele production might
seem plastic and pat. Aside from a few witty, athletic dance turns
(choreography by Daniele and Jeff Calhoun), the show behind the two
stars is merely OK.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on Broadway, and off-
</P>
<P>
   Recapping some long-running shows: The best ones that are still
relatively fresh (less than three years old) are ``Chicago'' at the
Shubert and ``Cabaret'' at Studio 54. Both are wittier,
sharper-edged and more sexually charged than their original
productions. ``The Lion King'' at the New Amsterdam is sheer joy.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``in-between'' category _ entertaining, though flawed _
is Warren Leight's ``Side Man'' at the Golden; a brooding,
intelligent new memory play about a struggling jazz musician.
Judging by reviews, Tennessee Williams' ``Not About Nightingales''
at Circle in the Square is similarly mixed, a youthful prison
melodrama saved by Trevor Nunn's powerful direction.
</P>
<P>
   Off-Broadway, there are hits for Generation X'ers or anyone with
a taste for the outrageous. ``This Is Our Youth'' at the Fairbanks
is the authentic, witty chronicle of drugged-out '80s kids;
``Killer Joe'' at the Soho is scary-funny, trailer-park gothic.
``Hedwig and the Angry Inch'' at the Jane Street is a transsexual's
saga set to surprisingly tuneful rock.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK THEATER
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Call 212-239-6200 for ``Fosse,'' ``Everybody's Ruby,''
``Cabaret,'' ``Chicago,'' ``Side Man,'' ``Nightingales,''
``Hedwig,'' ``Youth'' and ``Killer Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Call 212-307-4100 for ``Ashes to Ashes,'' ``Annie/Gun'' and
``Rent.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
