<HEADER>
A7230 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAMBERMUSIC14-COX     03-11 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAMBERMUSIC14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chamber music eyes what's next
 &HT;    EDs:Embargoed for Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixties cinema and '70s rock spawned ``new waves,'' pop culture
pundits claim to predict the ``next big thing'' and Brooklyn, N.Y.,
has its own Next Wave festival. Taking their cue from these
examples, Emory University and Thamyris, the Atlanta contemporary
music ensemble, are launching Next Fest.
</P>
<P>
   As its name suggests, the chamber music festival will focus on
contemporary trends. That means the work of living composers, sure,
but also livelier approaches to programs aimed at audiences more at
home in rock clubs than concert halls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had to expand our thinking to really embrace the music
that's going on right now,'' says Steven Everett, a Thamyris
co-founder and Emory music professor. ``You can no longer do the
kind of repertoire you did in the '60s or '70s. You don't have the
audience anymore. You have to find something that relates to people
more directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Next Fest takes several cracks at that goal.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Thamyris stages the 1969 music-theater piece ``Eight
Songs for a Mad King'' by British composer Peter Maxwell Davies.
It's a meditation on music and insanity as experienced by England's
King George III, who loses his grip as he tries to teach his pet
bullfinches to sing. The birds will be represented by the members
of Thamyris perched, symbolically and literally, in wire cages. The
king, portrayed by Canadian vocalist Tony Berg-
</P>
<P>
   aman, endures violent mood swings expressed through an intense
range of extended vocal techniques _ watch out, Yoko Ono.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing stays stable,'' Everett says of the piece, which deals
with the concept of distortion as a musical process and makes
parodic use of fox trots and Baroque themes. ``The shifts of
musical language are so sudden and so stark and so dramatic. I've
never met anyone who didn't come away mesmerized by this piece.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Mad King'' is designed to rattle the consciousness,
Saturday's show by Bang on a Can All-Stars promises an intriguing
dose of postmodern Muzak. The New York new-music group, which like
Kronos Quartet affects a stylish image, will play its ``Music for
Airports.'' Rock composer Brian Eno's 1978 album introduced the
term ``ambient music'' and anticipated the emergence of an entire
genre of electronic music.
</P>
<P>
   Bang on a Can, a six-member ensemble that uses electric guitar
and synthesizers in its arrangements, got its name staging
round-the-clock concert marathons.
</P>
<P>
   The rock connection isn't an automatic bonus, says Jeff Hunt,
founder of the Atlanta experimental music label Table of the
Elements. ``The rock audience is even more conservative and
reactionary than your most staid classical audience,'' he says.
``But there is a core audience of people coming from a rock context
that's been exposed to a lot of music and is well-educated about
it. That's a very receptive audience, coming from outside of what
would be the traditional context for new music.''
</P>
<P>
   In trying to make forward-thinking chamber music more appealing
to more people, the whole notion of what's avant-garde is up for
grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what was going on in the 1960s had a shock element
that had to be there in order to create something new,'' Everett
says. ``A couple of years ago I saw (performance artist) Laurie
Anderson in a production, and she said there is no avant-garde
anymore. You can't really shock audiences today. The only true
people who shock us are terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thamyris: ``Eight Songs for a Mad King.'' 8:15 p.m. Monday.
$15. Cannon Chapel at Emory University, 515 Kilgo Circle N.E.
404-727-5050.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bang on a Can All-Stars: ``Music for Airports.'' 8:15 p.m.
Saturday. $15. Performing Arts Studio at Emory University, 1804 N.
Decatur Road N.E. 404-727-5050.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
