<SLUG> BC-TRAILER-STARWARS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Star Wars' fans turn to Web for trailer peek
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ May the trailer be with you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' prequel fans got an early peek via the Internet on
Thursday at the new 2 1/2-minute trailer for ``Episode 1 _ The
Phantom Menace.'' And what did they see? Jedi knights battling
armored battle droids, the return of that nasty Emperor, blazing
light-saber duels, Jabba, vicious new devil-horned villain Darth
Maul and enough luscious sweeping landscapes from a world far, far
away to impress even David Lean.
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm Ltd. posted the full trailer, which hits theaters
today in metro Atlanta and across the country, on its official Web
site at http://www.starwars.com late Wednesday, not long after
George Lucas announced in Las Vegas that his fourth ``Star Wars''
film will be released May 19, two days earlier than previously
planned.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday night, the new trailer had been previewed on
``Entertainment Tonight'' and ``Access Hollywood.'' Today, CBS'
``This Morning'' will have cameras in the basement of 27-year-old
Carl Cunningham's home in Acworth (GA.). CBS plans to show the
trailer to Cunningham, an IBM staffer and Internet aficionado, and
about a half-dozen other Georgians for their comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm patient,'' Cunningham said Thursday when asked if he was
planning on downloading the trailer off the Internet before CBS
arrives. ``I'm going to wait till tomorrow so my comments will be
fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, however, won't be so willing to wait when the
complete ``Phantom Menace'' opens. ``We're getting a hotel room
overlooking a theater the day before,'' he said. ``That way we can
tell if the lines get too long at 3 a.m. We'll be able to react.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander on `Voyager'
</P>
<P>
   In his first series TV appearance since ``Seinfeld'' closed in
May, Jason Alexander _ sporting a hefty head of hair _ will play a
villainous alien on the March 31 episode of UPN's ``Star Trek:
Voyager.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's executive producer, Brannon Braga, said makeup
artists plopped ``Albert Einstein hair and a funny forehead'' on
Alexander for the role. Alexander's character offers to help Capt.
Janeway (Kate Mulgrew) out of a jam but then leads his fellow
aliens in an insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
