<HEADER>
A7232 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELLIST-HARRELL14-COX     03-11 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLIST-HARRELL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A handy feat as Harrell plays Rozsa with ASO
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last year was a memorable one for American cellist
Lynn Harrell. It was the year he lost his hands and got them back.
</P>
<P>
   And just in time, too, for playing and recording two works by
Miklos Rozsa with the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of carpal tunnel syndrome that may have been
building for 20 or 25 years, according to Harrell's British
neurologist, the cellist became aware of a growing numbness in the
first finger of his right hand (which controls the pressure on the
cello bow). As he investigated causes and remedies, he realized he
had lost sensation in his left hand as well. When his doctor
proposed surgery, Harrell decided to have both hands done at the
same time. The operation took place in June.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters more complicated, his surgeon did it the hard
way. Instead of arthroscopic surgery, with minimal cutting of
muscle and tissue, ``he wanted to see what he was doing rather than
using the little TV camera,'' Harrell said by phone from his home
in London.
</P>
<P>
   That meant a much longer period of recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell embarked on physical therapy with a sports medicine
clinic in Aspen, Colo., that normally works on Olympic skiers.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up taking five months off from playing. He reintroduced
himself to the cello with three minutes a day of practice,
increasing the time in tiny increments. He played open strings (no
left hand needed) and then slow scales. ``It was excruciatingly
painful,'' he said, ``because I had no calluses and no muscles. I
hadn't realized one could lose all that so quickly.'' By August, he
was ready to begin work on his concert repertory _ but even so, he
was forced to cancel some of his September engagements.
</P>
<P>
   As a further challenge, the Rozsa concerto is quite difficult,
and Harrell, 55, was learning it for the first time. ``There are
quite nasty things in it,'' he said cheerfully.
</P>
<P>
   The ASO will record a CD this weekend that will include the
violin concerto played by Robert McDuffie at last week's concerts
and the two works to be heard on this week's. It will be only the
third time the concerto has been recorded for commercial
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The recording follows a current interest in serious music by
Hollywood composers such as Erich Korngold, Franz Waxman and
Bernard Herrmann.
</P>
<P>
   When his agent first told him that the concerto had been written
by the composer who scored ``Ben-Hur,'' it raised his eyebrows a
little. Indeed, there is a little ``Ben-Hur'' in the cello
concerto.
</P>
<P>
   But ``I have great admiration for what he did in this piece,''
Harrell said. ``It seems well-written, and he obviously understood
the cello.'' For instance, Rozsa often has the cello line
duplicated by the xylophone _ a technique later borrowed by
Shostakovich in the second cello concerto he wrote for Mstislav
Rostropovich. ``It's a very clean sound, hard and energetic,''
Harrell said, ``but it doesn't sustain.'' So it doesn't cover the
cello.
</P>
<P>
   As for balance, a perpetual problem in works for cello and
orchestra, Harrell says, ``I don't know. I've never played it with
orchestra!''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
