<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7234 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-VENICE14-COX     03-11 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VENICE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Venice, a romantic tradition withstands changing currents
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By Holly Crenshaw
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Italy _ They are dream merchants, and they know it.
</P>
<P>
   Lounging along the Grand Canal in jaunty striped shirts and
broad straw hats with ribbons that flutter in the wind, the
gondoliers of Venice hold a monopoly on one of the world's most
enthralling experiences.
</P>
<P>
   But that experience _ a hallucinatory blur of iridescent green
water, dazzling pink and gold Renaissance palazzi and the gentle
lapping of the boatman's oar _ comes with a hefty price.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where reality and fantasy collide.
</P>
<P>
   To travel to Venice and not take a gondola ride seems
unthinkable, like sightseeing in San Francisco without hopping on a
cable car. In both locales, they're more than transportation:
They're the city's quintessence, an inseparable part of the
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   But as I studied my guidebooks and prepared for my first visit
to this most romantic of destinations, I felt a growing sense of
dread. Hiring a gondolier for a 50-minute ride sounded as stressful
and decidedly unromantic as negotiating a fare with a New York
cabdriver.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are posted rates _ 120,000 lira, or about $70,
during my November visit _ at Venice's 11 official gondola stands.
But my research warned me that those prices are virtually
meaningless, that gondoliers are free to charge double or more if
they choose and that they often will try to ditch their passengers
after a 15-minute ride while suddenly losing all ability to
understand English.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I wasn't sure I wanted to sully such a treasured
vacation by haggling over prices or caving in to extortion _ only
to fall victim to the gondolier's fast-running watch.
</P>
<P>
   Though the dishonesty is indefensible, it's only fair to
acknowledge some justification for the steep prices. Like the city
itself, gondoliers are perched on the edge of extinction, existing
in a watery netherworld of fading tradition and rising tides.
</P>
<P>
   Vastly outnumbered by Venice's vaporetti _ noisy public
transportation boats that ply commuters up and down the Grand Canal
_ the sleek, silent gondolas have dwindled from about 15,000 in the
17th century to a few hundred today. The gondolieri, who often
learn the trade from their fathers, must buy their own vessels and
pay for their upkeep at one of the city's five gondola yards. And
their entire yearly salary must be earned in a six-month tourist
season.
</P>
<P>
   So I decided to keep an open mind and gauge the scene when I
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   I started with an easy way to sample a boat ride: hopping on a
traghetto, a ferry gondola that does nothing but make quick trips
back and forth across the Grand Canal. Because there are only three
bridges across Venice's main waterway, locals pay 600 lira, or 34
cents, and use these gondolas as a short cut.
</P>
<P>
   But this, too, had its complications. Tradition dictates that
passengers remain standing, so I picked a spot in the crowded,
flat-bottomed boat and firmly stood my ground.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly a woman started pointing at the floor and saying
something to me in obviously irritated Italian. It took a minute to
understand that I needed to shift to a different spot to help
balance the boatful of commuters.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as we walked near the landmark Rialto Bridge _ one of
Venice's largest gondola stations _ I heard a voice cry out,
``Gondola! Gondola!''
</P>
<P>
   Hustling for passengers in this tourist-clogged area, a
gondolier offered a ride for 100,000 lira, or $57. For a moment, I
considered grabbing the cheaper fare but decided the price was
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   That night at our pensione, just off the Grand Canal, our
concierge unexpectedly volunteered to reserve a gondola for the
following day. For 120,000 lira _ the official rate _ a gondolier
would pick us up at our hotel at the appointed hour, with no
bargaining necessary.
</P>
<P>
   We reserved for 9 a.m., but when no one came, our concierge
phoned and was told someone would be there at 10 instead. When it
did arrive, it was wonderful to watch the gondola _ 36 feet long
and 5 feet wide _ pull into the little side canal and stop at our
front steps.
</P>
<P>
   The gondolier extended a steadying hand, helped us into our
seats and steered us out onto the Grand Canal. That first moment
was breathtaking. It was a brilliant Sunday morning _ cold but
sunny and clear _ with church bells pealing in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   When another ringing sound suddenly cut through the air, our
gondolier deftly grabbed his cell phone from his pocket and took
the call while still managing to keep our boat on a steady keel.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was into his well-rehearsed narrative in fairly fluent
English. ``On the right, you will see the home of Casanova, the
Venetian playboy,'' he said, gliding past the ornate palazzo.
</P>
<P>
   Slipping quietly past Ca' Rezzonico, where Robert Browning lived
out his final days, I paused for a moment to study our gondola's
gorgeous details. The black, eel-like boat was trimmed in the
traditional style _ with plush, fringe-lined seats, a bright red
floor and gilded sea horses mounted on either side. As the bow of
the gondola sliced through the water, its tiny Venetian flag
flickered in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look to your right side for the home of poet Lord Byron,'' our
gondolier continued. Just then, a vaporetto loaded with tourists
came chugging past, and I looked up to see three cameras pointed my
way.
</P>
<P>
   We turned into a moody side canal and enjoyed a few moments of
solitude. Every now and then, our fragile little boat would scrape
along some 500-year old stone wall, and our boatman would mention
that this had been Mozart's home or offer another historical detail
as we slipped through the shadowy alleys.
</P>
<P>
   The gondolier, a friendly young man with blond hair typical of
northern Italians, told us his father was a water taxi driver.
``But I don't like the engines. I like the silence,'' he said,
winding his way through the maze-like canals. ``And I like the
gondola history, the tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, we rounded a corner and were back in the
bright sun and midmorning traffic of the Grand Canal, where the
gondolieri shouted greetings to each other as they passed. Instead
of returning to our hotel a short distance away, our gondolier
asked if he could drop us off in front of the busy Accademia
Gallery, probably because he could find his next fare more easily
there, and we agreed.
</P>
<P>
   As he turned to tie up our boat, I quickly checked my watch: 40
minutes _ 10 minutes shy, but close enough, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   The boat pitched back and forth as we stood to climb out, and
our gondolier gallantly offered his arm. Still, I somehow managed
to crack my skull into his as I disembarked.
</P>
<P>
   A fitting end, I thought, for what had been a sublime journey of
otherworldly sensations, pierced with jarring reminders of ordinary
life.
</P>
<P>
   Information: The official rate for a Venice gondola is 120,000
lira for a 50-minute ride, with each additional 25 minutes costing
60,000 lira. After 8 p.m., the rate climbs to 150,000 lira, with
each additional 25 minutes costing 75,000 lira. But gondola fees
are set by each boatman, and prices can vary wildly. Singers and
accordionists can be prebooked, or sometimes hired on the spot at
the more touristy gondola stands, such as the one at San Marco, for
an extra fee. Gondolas can hold up to six people, who can split the
fare. Passengers may ask to ride to a particular destination or
visit a certain area; otherwise, the gondolier will take his
favorite route.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Crenshaw writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
