<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7235 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-VIENNA14-COX     03-11 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VIENNA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eye candy: Opulent Vienna a soaring Baroque confection
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By James D. Smith
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ What a wedding cake of a city this is.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's the soaring 450-foot Gothic spire of Stephansdom
cathedral or row upon row of intricately ornate Baroque facades or
the massive, overindulgent opulence of Schonbrunn Palace, this is a
city that looks like it was decked out by a cake decorator on a
binge.
</P>
<P>
   But what else would you expect in a setting whose history is
steeped in the soaring swells of Strauss waltzes, high-prancing
Lipizzaner stallions, an angelic boys choir, luxuriant coffeehouses
serving thick java laced with whipped cream and desserts designed
with nothing but sweet excess in mind?
</P>
<P>
   Vienna's intoxication with the frills and flourishes of Hapsburg
Empire court society has become an enduring love affair,
exemplified no better than by its unabashed fondness for the curved
lines and ornamental excesses of the Baroque.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise, then, that the New Town Hall, that most
mundane of edifices in most municipalities, resembles not so much a
pedestrian place of government as it does a civic cathedral, with
its 320-foot central clock tower serving as its secular spire.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a building that bristles with balconies, turrets, spires
and arched, ornamented windows, its numerous vertical lines giving
it the appearance of an oversize matchstick creation. At night, it
strikes an even more formidible pose as floodlights isolate its
pinnacles in stark relief against the surrounding darkness.
</P>
<P>
   And, for good measure, there's the Wiener Rathauskeller, a
popular wine cellar in the basement, serving up Austrian wines,
meals and traditional music.
</P>
<P>
   Just across the street stands the impressively stately
Burgtheater, a masterpiece in Italian Renaissance style that
features mirror-image, candelabra-lined grand staircases leading up
from the side entries to the main foyer. Just about everything
here, it seems, looks like a palace inside.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, amid all this splendor, it's the little things that stand
out _ the entertaining and sometimes amusing dollops of filigree
and folderol at every turn that leave a lasting impression.
</P>
<P>
   At the Burgtheater, sculpted cherubs adorn the balustrade, and
statues representing the muses of music and the dramatic arts
straddle the roof line. They're small details that can be easily
overlooked amid the overall grandness of the building's facade.
</P>
<P>
   And it's that way all over the city: little touches that force
you to crane your neck skyward and keep your eyes ever alert for
serendipitous surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you have to stretch some muscles to take in all of
Stephansdom, the city's landmark cathedral, its south tower
piercing the sky, as gray and daunting in reality as it is on
celluloid in the opening scene of the 1949 black-and-white classic
``The Third Man.''
</P>
<P>
   The massive interior of the 325-foot-long cathedral contains a
rich array of carvings, sculpture and ornate altars, all filtered
through the soft light of soaring stained glass windows. The
Pilgram's Pulpit (named after its creator, master craftsman Anton
Pilgram) is an intricate Gothic structure decorated with depictions
of four contemplative theological figures.
</P>
<P>
   On a clear day, one of the best panoramic views of the city and
the Danube (alas, it was blue only in the imagination of the
younger Johann Strauss) is from the viewing platform in the south
tower _ if you're up to climbing almost 350 steps to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, in the Hofburg Quarter, you'll find the former site of
the Hapsburg winter palace and the heart of Old Vienna. This
complex of imperial structures grew haphazardly over the centuries
as each new emperor sought to leave his mark. The result is a
hodgepodge of styles, not always in sync with one another.
</P>
<P>
   Along Naglergasse you can see some of the most representative
Baroque facades in the city. Yet only a few twists and turns of
streets away, facing the Michaelerplatz, is Loos House, which
outraged Archduke Franz Ferdinand with its simple modernistic lines
when built in 1912. Architect Adolf Loos despised ornamentation for
its own sake, which put him greatly at odds with conservative
Viennese society.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder, then, that in Vienna you can find horses stabled
in buildings that once served as the residences of royalty.
</P>
<P>
   At the Renaissance-style Stallburg Palace _ once the residence
of Archduke Maximilian and later home for an imperial art
collection _ are stables for the Spanish Riding School, which is
located in the building across the street. There you can watch the
specially bred Lipizzaner stallions go through their paces amid the
splendor of high columns, crystal chandeliers and an exquisite
coffered ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Even the city's major transportation artery is a jewel. To see
most of the major attractions, you merely follow the Ringstrasse,
the elegant boulevard built at Emperor Franz Josef's behest in the
late 19th century. The tree-lined thoroughfare drapes the confines
of the compact Old City like an empress' bejeweled necklace, with
major sights _ the State Opera House, the Museum of the History of
Art (as much an artwork itself as the collections it contains), the
Natural History Museum, the Parliament and so forth _ dangling like
shimmering baubbles along the way.
</P>
<P>
   But to fully appreciate the splendor that was once Vienna, you
need to leave the Old City just briefly to visit Schonbrunn Palace,
the imperial family's former summer residence _ now part of the
city but once a vacation refuge in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Though you're allowed to visit only a small portion of the 1,400
rooms, the areas on display are resplendent with Maria Theresa's
guiding touches _ rococo gilding, hand-painted wallpapers, wood
paneling from all over the world, antique furnishings and artwork.
Even the enormous iron stoves required to warm each room are
massive, ornate marvels that raise the potbellied stove to artistic
status.
</P>
<P>
   At the Orangerie, one of the magnificent outbuildings at
Schonbrunn, where imperial and royal celebrations were held and
Mozart conducted concerts, you can attend an evening's
entertainment that provides a sampler of the city's music and dance
history.
</P>
<P>
   With the music of Mozart and Strauss supplied by an ensemble,
the program includes vocal soloists and dancers. The finale, a
couple in period costume waltzing to the strains of ``The Blue
Danube,'' provides a fitting close to any journey to Vienna: the
icing on the cake.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: The round-trip fare to Vienna is $418 on
midweek departures through April on Lufthansa, United, Sabena,
KLM/Northwest, Delta, Alitalia and Austrian Airlines. Tickets must
be purchased by March 31. There are no advance-purchase
restrictions, but a Saturday stay is required.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting around: From the airport, the cheapest way into the
city is the Schnellbahn train (about $3.50). Other options include
city buses, which operate every 20 minutes (about $5.50), shuttle
buses (about $20) and taxis (about $40). You can get tickets from
the conductor. The train takes about 30 minutes to transport you to
Wien Mitte station, where you connect with the city's extensive
subway system. At the airport, you can pick up transit system maps
and buy the Vienna Card (about $24), which permits unlimited rides
on the city's transit system for 72 hours from its first use (it's
not good for the train ride into town). With the Vienna Card, you
can also get a coupon booklet that provides discounts or other
perks at many of the city's main attractions, shops and
restaurants. Several other discount fare options (day passes, etc.)
are available.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lodging: A good way to find reasonable accommodations is at
the Utell Web site, http://www
</P>
<P>
   .hotelbook.com/, which lists almost 50 properties in the Vienna
area. We selected the Hotel Savoy, a comfortable, small property on
a quiet street convenient to shopping, restaurants and public
transportation. For about $80 a night (taxes and service charges
included) we got a double bed with bath and continental breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dining: We sampled three eateries within walking distance of
our hotel. The small Stiftkeller offered traditional Viennese food
(Wiener schnitzel and beef-and-potatoes Tafelspitz for entrees;
Palatschinken _ Austrian pancakes _ for dessert) in a cozy setting.
Our tab for drinks, dinner and dessert came to $50 for two, service
included. We also enjoyed the busy Siebenstern Brewhouse (five
varieties brewed on site) and the Centimeter II (an excellent
potato soup comes served in a brown-bread loaf). You can find
coffeehouses and konditoreien (coffeehouses that also serve snacks
and alcohol) in most neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Austrian National Tourist Office, 212-944-6880;
http://www.anto.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ James D. Smith writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
