u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS &LR;      03-11 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (First lead writethru: Updates with House vote) 
 
HOUSE REJECTS GOP-LED EFFORT TO OPPOSE SENDING U.S. TROOPS TO
KOSOVO 
 &HT;    By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House killed a resolution Thursday aimed at
preventing the deployment of any U.S. forces to Kosovo as Congress
began an impassioned debate on the controversial issue of putting
U.S. troops in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Congress had defied a request from President Clinton to delay
debate on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton, backed by former GOP senator Bob Dole, pleaded
with Congress not to push ahead with a vote until a peace agreement
is completed between the Serbs and ethnic Albanian rebels in
Kosovo, Republican leaders said they were determined to consider
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Working late into the night, Congress gave tentative approval to
the deployment of troops to Kosovo if Clinton provides Congress
with specific details of the mission's goals.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 237-178 the House also rejected a call by Majority
Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, and others to prohibit the deployment of
any U.S. forces to the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., began the debate by
calling the ethnic conflict in Kosovo ``a great human tragedy,''
but said it was important for Congress to grapple with it before
the Clinton administration decides to commit forces as part of any
peace plan. He dismissed concerns expressed by Clinton and Dole
that a vote by Congress against deploying troops could undermine
any chance for a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   That view was echoed by Democrats who warned the Republican
leaders that a vote against deployment would give a green light to
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to continue his ethnic
cleansing in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said Hastert's decision to
go ahead with the debate was a clear signal that the GOP leadership
had chosen partisanship over a united U.S. front that could
encourage the ethnic Albanians and Serbs to sign a
Washington-brokered peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans opposed to committing U.S. forces argued that
any peace plan between the two warring sides likely would fail,
leaving U.S. soldiers in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is not a hopeful nation aspiring to democracy. It is a
big, dangerous quagmire,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   Calling U.S. soldiers ``warriors'' and not ``baby sitters,''
DeLay criticized Clinton for having no clearly defined mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has no plan to do anything but go to
Kosovo, hold hands with the two sides and hope they behave when we
leave. But of course they won't. The killing and the mayhem will
continue as soon as NATO pulls out,'' said DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   He joined with Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., in offering his own
resolution to bar the deployment of U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay used his floor statement to address the broader issue of
U.S. foreign policy and NATO's role in Europe. Referring to the
possible deployment of troops to Kosovo, he suggested that it would
amount to ``meddling in the internal affairs'' of a sovereign
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the historic mission of the alliance as defensive,
he declared, ``NATO is starting to resemble a power-hungry
imperialist army.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally designed to defend member nations from attack, it
is now setting itself up to be the attacker,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   While DeLay's comments struck a chord with a large number of GOP
colleagues who rose to applaud, some Republicans, who also oppose
sending troops, sided with Democrats in their support of the
administration's efforts to negotiate a deal between Milosevic and
the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him the authority to be the commander-in-chief and we
cannot deny him the authority granted to him in the Constitution,''
said Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala. ``It is irresponsible for Congress
to be debating this at this time while they are in negotiations
trying to negotiate an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to go ahead with the debate marked a setback for
the administration, which has failed so far to get Milosevic and
Kosovo Albanian separatists to sign an agreement that would invite
NATO forces onto Serbian soil to help keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Although the administration has yet to lay out a specific
deployment plan, Pentagon officials say the U.S. commitment to the
peacekeeping mission would comprise about 4,000 troops in a total
international force of 20,000-30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, traveling in Central America, reiterated Thursday that
U.S. and NATO forces would be deployed only if a peace agreement is
signed by Serbs and the Albanian separatists.
</P>
<P>
   He said the deployment plan would include a ``clear'' exit
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Although nonbinding, the resolutions offered in the House on
Kosovo gave members a chance to vent their frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on both sides of the aisle expressed horror at the
``slaughter and massacre'' of innocent civilians in Kosovo at the
hands of Milosevic, whom they referred to repeatedly throughout the
debate as ``a bloodthirsty ... brutal killer'' who should be be
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   But they disagreed on the best approach to ending the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to take up a resolution next week that
would authorize the deployment of forces. But several senators are
expected to offer amendments that would lay out specific conditions
governing any commitment of forces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
