<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7245 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UW-CAREY-SPI &LR;      03-11 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UW-CAREY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKY SUCCESS RIDING ON FRESHMAN POINT GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Slashing and distributing or scoring himself,
Senque Carey established the tempo for Washington when it won eight
of nine games during a month-long stretch.
</P>
<P>
   He was an impressive freshman, a one-time backup turning into a
prime-time force.
</P>
<P>
   But now he is five games and three weeks removed from those
sensational days, Carey's game becoming unusually average right
when the Huskies need it to be exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Bender says point-guard play is critical to a team's
success in the NCAA tournament. If that is the case, the Huskies
could be in trouble Friday afternoon at the Superdome when they
take on Miami of Ohio in a Midwest Region first-round game.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the production from Todd MacCulloch, Donald Watts and
Deon Luton, the Huskies need a stronger effort from Carey to
advance to the second round. His late-season difficulties coincided
with the Huskies', amplifying Carey's importance in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Stanford loss on Feb. 18, Carey has averaged 5.1
points, 10 below his output during the nine-game span. He has had
12 assists and 16 turnovers and shot 26.6 percent. He rarely
penetrates like he used to, evidenced by his sudden disappearance
from the foul line. Carey has not taken a free throw in the past
three games.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone _ from Carey to Bender to MacCulloch _ believes that a
crossover move is coming this afternoon, with the point guard
dashing off in a different direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in a slump or anything like that,'' Carey said. ``I
know what I'm capable of doing. I've performed in big games, I've
been bad in big games. You can't let the NCAA (tournament) stuff
get in your head. I'll just be myself and let the game come to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch thinks it will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in the tournament is not going to rattle him,'' the
Husky center said. ``It's just going to accelerate his play.''
</P>
<P>
   If MacCulloch is to be effective inside, he needs to get the
ball in scoring position. It's the same situation with Watts and
Luton on the wings. Carey must be a proficient director for the
halfcourt offense to run smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   He has proven capable against the country's best teams, sparring
with and even occasionally outplaying some of the marquee point
guards like Jason Terry and Baron Davis.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final stretch of the regular season, he lugged home,
using fatigue as a partial explanation. Bender said it was an
understandable development.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point every freshman hits the wall,'' the coach said.
``He hit his in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender said that Pac-10 teams became more familiar with the
freshman and took away his strengths. They kept the ball out of his
hands. They prevented him from playing in the middle of the floor.
They didn't leave him open on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   The adjustments left Carey searching for shots and teammates and
finding none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't gotten as many looks as I did in the past,'' he
said. ``I'm not taking the shots I was taking. I don't know for
what reason. But the season's not over. There's time to change
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey has been hesitant, making poor judgments instead of field
goals. He takes shots when he shouldn't and passes on others in the
open. He used to be confounding to the opponents instead of the
Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Bender saw a glimmer of the dynamic Carey in the final
regular-season game, claiming that the point guard regained his
confidence against Washington State. The observation sounded more
wishful than insightful.
</P>
<P>
   Carey had five assists and two steals but also committed five
turnovers and was 1-for-6 from the field, scoring three points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bothered by my lack of scoring and assists,'' Carey
said. ``We're not doing bad without me. But we do better when I
perform. I'll base myself on winning in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   If Carey ignites Friday, it will not be entirely surprising.
Miami of Ohio admits to be focusing on MacCulloch while also being
concerned with Watts and Luton on the perimeter. There was no
mention of a 20-year-old from East Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're loose,'' Carey said. ``I'm sure we'll be nervous, but
it's time to play now. This is what we've all been waiting for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
