<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ZIMMER-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE MAY BE OUT 3 MONTHS; ZIMMER TO TAKE HIS PLACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Yankee officials remain certain that manager Joe
Torre, who was told on Tuesday that he has prostate cancer, will
return to the dugout eventually. But the estimates of his absence
range from three weeks to three months, and on Thursday, Torre's
bench coach, Don Zimmer, said he would try to manage the team as
Torre would.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, who did not appear at the ballpark here Thursday and was
unavailable for comment, is leaning heavily toward having surgery
for the removal of his cancer, according to others in the
organization, and that procedure likely will occur at Washington
University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, acknowledged
that Torre was close to a decision. ``But I'm not sure it's been
finalized yet,'' Steinbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Fans here were asked to think of Torre for a moment before
Thursday night's exhibition with Texas, and they responded with
loud applause. Zimmer was in his customary spot, on a chair
adjacent to the Yankees' dugout, running the team with the special
assistant Stump Merrill and other Yankee coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer, who has spoken to Torre repeatedly in recent days,
suggested the Yankees' manager could come back perhaps as soon as
the first weekend of the regular season, when the Yankees play host
to Detroit at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Frank Torre, the manager's brother, and others in the
organization are suggesting that Torre might need as long as three
months to recover. Joe Torre must not only be well enough to make a
manager's decisions, but he must also be ready to handle the team's
rigorous travel and the intense scrutiny he will face when he
returns.
</P>
<P>
   And the manager's older brother made it clear that the lure of
baseball would not be a factor in determining when Torre comes
back; the only objective, Frank Torre said, is for Joe Torre to
regain his health. ``How long it takes is unimportant,'' Frank
Torre said. ``Managing is unimportant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have not formally announced that the 68-year-old
Zimmer will be the manager. But as Torre awaited the results of a
biopsy on Monday, he asked Zimmer to fill in if he had to leave the
team, and on Wednesday, Steinbrenner visited Zimmer at home, where
the coach was recovering from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden somebody pounded on the door and there was
Steinbrenner,'' Zimmer said. ``He said, `When the hell are you
going to get up? C'mon, let's go.' He said hopefully Joe won't miss
too much time, but you'll run the club.'''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer has 13 seasons of managerial experience, with San Diego,
Boston, Texas and the Chicago Cubs. But he sees no reason to change
the Yankees, who have won two championships in Torre's three
seasons. ``Joe and I sat side by side for three years, and I think
we kind of think alike,'' said Zimmer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Yankees' coaching staff will share the day-to-day
responsibilities of spring training: the pitching coach Mel
Stottlemyre will work with the pitchers; Willie Randolph, the
former second baseman, will oversee the infielders, etc. Once the
season starts, however, Zimmer will have full control, including
decisions regarding the pitching _ when to take out a pitcher, whom
to bring in from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to manage, I'm going to make the pitching
decisions, and that's taking nothing away from Mel,'' Zimmer said.
``Until Joe gets back, I will make the decisions. That doesn't mean
I won't discuss them with Mel.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cone said Zimmer would be fine as interim manager, and if
any group of players could be self-propelled, it would be the
Yankees, who are loaded with intense veterans. Before Torre left
Legends Field Wednesday, he told Cone and Roger Clemens and others
to take control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I just want you guys to be leaders, and not let
anybody stray, not let anybody slack off,''' Cone recalled. ``In
the midst of going through what he went through, he had the
presence of mind to tell us to not let anybody step out of line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
