<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7250 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI12-COX     03-11 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Haitian death toll now a mystery
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ One boat or two? Fifteen lost souls or
40?
</P>
<P>
   A relative claimed Thursday that at least one of the three
Haitians who survived Saturday's mass drowning off Palm Beach
County lied about the number of boats and people, adding to
confusion and doubt already surrounding the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents increased the mystery by removing another
survivor from Good Samaritan Hospital and saying they couldn't
disclose where he was being held, whether he was under suspicion of
being a smuggler or whether it was for his protection as a witness.
Yvon Pierre-Louis had been under 24-hour guard since Monday and was
not allowed to talk to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the jumbled stories of survivors and a report that two
boats were missing from the Bahamas, U.S. Border Patrol and Coast
Guard units thought they were searching for victims of a double
capsizing that threw 43 people into the water. Border Patrol agents
suspected the boats were run by smugglers who ferry desperate
Haitian immigrants to the United States from the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard rescued three men and picked up the bodies of
two women, leaving 38 presumed missing. No more bodies have come
ashore and no debris has been found, but the Border Patrol hasn't
ruled out the possibility of two boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, there still could have been two,'' said Dan
Geoghegan, assistant chief of the Border Patrol in Miami. ``The
good news is maybe there weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Two survivors, who gave their names as Carmel Auguste and Peter
Pierre, were taken to Krome Detention Center after leaving the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   When first rescued, the men said they were on a single boat,
though they weren't sure how many people were on board. As
investigators questioned them, their stories began to change and
contradict each other: two boats; one caught fire _ or took on
water _ and sank; one tried to help the other and both sank.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Pierre's real name is Wilner Casseus, and he made up the
story about the two boats, his brother said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Chavannes Casseus, a Palm Beach County resident, said he got a
call Saturday to visit his brother in the hospital. When he
arrived, Wilner Casseus told him there was only one boat with 18
people on board.
</P>
<P>
   Wilner gave authorities a fake name because he was scared of
being deported or charged with something, his brother said: ``If he
tell a lot of lies, it's because he's so scared. He don't know what
to do so he make up a lot of lies.'' Chavannes Casseus called
Daniella Henry, director of the Haitian American Community Council,
on Tuesday after she went on the air on WHSR. Henry had held a
lively discussion on Radio Haiti-Amerique Internacional with
callers.
</P>
<P>
   Chavannes Casseus said his brother is from l'Artibonite, a
grain-producing district in central Haiti hit hard last year by
Hurricane Mitch. Henry said the other two survivors, Pierre-Louis
and Auguste, are also from l'Artibonite. Marie Joseph of West Palm
Beach said she believes her young cousin, Elie Norelus, was on the
boat with the men and that the boy's mother lives in l'Artibonite.
</P>
<P>
   Henry said she interviewed Pierre-Louis in the hospital
Saturday, before he was placed under guard, and that he told her he
never saw two boats. But he also said that when everyone was
swimming around in the water, he talked with someone he didn't know
_ a man he believes could not have been on his boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a mystery somewhere,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no mystery about Haitians telling conflicting
stories about their perilous journeys to the United States. It's
standard procedure, according to the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every vessel that lands, whether there's a tragedy or no
tragedy, if 20 people are on that boat, I get 19 different
stories,'' Geoghegan said. ``They're instructed by the smugglers to
tell conflicting and confusing stories to stymie any
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Mary Lou Pickel and Joe Brogan contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
