<SLUG> BC-NATO-ALLIANCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYES OF WORLD TO BE ON MISSOURI CITY AS THREE NATIONS JOIN NATO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ The world map will be redrawn in
Independence today.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic will join NATO in
ceremonies beginning at 11:30 a.m. at the Truman Library in
Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will preside. She will be
joined by foreign ministers Bronislaw Geremek of Poland, Jan Kavan
of the Czech Republic and Janos Martonyi of Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Their aircraft is expected to arrive at Downtown Airport at
10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The event represents the first expansion of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion effectively redraws the boundaries of Europe,
pushing the alliance some 400 miles east toward Russia _
encompassing territory once controlled by the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also commits U.S. military forces to the defense
of Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic, as if they were any
other of the current 16 NATO member nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just absolutely astounding,'' said Robert L. Stockwell of
Overland Park, Kan., a former U.S. Army officer who worked for NATO
in the early 1990s. ``It's astounding to see where we are now, 50
years after the Cold War began.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO was created in 1949 to confront the Soviet Union in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of communism that began in 1989, however, left many
former Soviet satellites eager to join the alliance. In July 1997,
NATO invited Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic to represent
the first wave of expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Last April the U.S. Senate approved the expansion.
</P>
<P>
   For all its geopolitical import, the NATO ceremony should not
tie up traffic across Kansas City. The ceremony and ensuing
luncheon are private events, and the Truman Library will be closed
to the public for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ceremony will be big news around the world. About 30
print foreign correspondents are expected, and foreign television
broadcast crews will use as many as seven satellite trucks. The
first of those were pulling into place Thursday in front of the
library at U.S. 24 and North Delaware Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Each foreign minister will speak briefly, and Albright will
follow with about a 30-minute address.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Hackman, Truman Library director, understands that
Albright's remarks will be the first of three major NATO addresses
she will make in 1999, NATO's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   By holding today's event at the Truman Library, Hackman said,
the State Department is delivering a clear tribute to former
President Harry S. Truman and his secretary of state, Dean Acheson,
for their leadership in helping to found NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the focus of Madeleine Albright's comments is putting
NATO into historical perspective, it seemed to the State Department
that the library would be an appropriate place to look at NATO
until now,'' Hackman said.
</P>
<P>
   A 50th anniversary NATO summit, bringing together the leaders of
44 nations, is scheduled in Washington in late April.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of debate, however, whether expanding NATO is even
a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters have argued that the expansion promotes U.S. security
interests by nurturing new democracies in Europe and providing a
hedge against a resurgent Russia. Those supporters include Bill
Eckhardt, a lawyer and retired Army colonel who teaches at the
University of Missouri-Kansas City School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely in favor of this,'' said Eckhardt. ``NATO is
the linchpin alliance that we have had for this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckhardt believes, however, that not nearly enough debate
preceded NATO's decision to expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whates with NATO and its expansion is crucial,''
Eckhardt said. ``My frustration is is that there is an educational
process that goes along with this that was, in my judgment, absent.
This comes as close to committing us to war than anything else that
I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics, meanwhile, have maintained that NATO expansion will
dilute the organization's original mission of self-defense, and
also antagonize Russia. In fact, during a Munich, Germany,
conference last month, a Russian official declared that NATO was
intent on the ``destruction of the existing world order'' in its
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Everett of Independence, a former intelligence officer
with the CIA who served many years in Europe, believes NATO
officials want to aggravate Russia by expanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if we can irritate them enough, and maybe if we can get
enough rhetoric out of them in response, it will help to continue
the idea that we can have a potential resurrection of the `evil
empire' and that we must continue to support NATO,'' said Everett,
who also is executive director of the Kansas City Interfaith Peace
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Stockwell, the former NATO officer, believes expansion is in the
best interests of those nascent democracies eager to join.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that they are without the communist albatross around their
necks, they have to find the natural relationships with their
neighboring countries on both their west and east,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
