<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI SPELLS SUCCESS FOR REDHAWKS STAR SZCZERBIAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ One of the most traumatic moments in Wally
Szczerbiak's life came in first grade.
</P>
<P>
   Already it had been hard, because first grade was in Madrid,
Spain, where his father, Walter, was a professional basketball
player.
</P>
<P>
   Then his teacher dropped this assignment on the class: Write
your name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking, `You've got to be kidding me,'''
Szczerbiak said.
</P>
<P>
   Six consonants and a random vowel in the first seven letters was
graduate-school work, not something for kids. But the teacher
insisted. So Szczerbiak, tongue out, persevered.
</P>
<P>
   After about 20 minutes, he had strung it together.
</P>
<P>
   Whew.
</P>
<P>
   From there, life has been pretty much downhill.
</P>
<P>
   It's the rest of us who must now learn what he mastered in first
grade, including the Superdome's marquee for the Midwest Regional
in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the region's big-time programs such as Kentucky, Kansas
and Utah, the 6-8 senior forward might well be the best player
here. It is the Washington Huskies' misfortune to have drawn his
number, and the greater misfortune of the scribes who chronicle
them to have to type his name.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps through practice we would be better at it by now, had
Szczerbiak gone to a college more commensurate with his talents,
such as Iowa, or St. John's, or George Washington, to name a few
that recruited him out of Cold Spring Harbor, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But he chose to dwell in relative basketball obscurity by
attending Miami, a college that must be distinguished by the phrase
``of Ohio,'' because of confusion with the other school, Miami of
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Oops, sorry. I meant Boise of Florida. No, wait. Ohio of Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's not like I'm the only one messed up. One of Miami's
recent stars, Devin Davis, tells the story of getting his first
recruiting call from a Miami assistant coach. After about 20
minutes, he agreed to take a visit. But he couldn't figure out why
the guy wanted him to have a plane ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Davis lived in Miami, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   To confuse geographic matters further, Miami of Szczerbiak is
the name of the school, not its town, which is Oxford (not THAT
Oxford). Oxford is a little burg of 19,000 just inside the Indiana
border, about 35 miles northwest of Cincinnati, which you may
recall was the hometown of Xavier, the Huskies' first-round
opponent in last year's hoops cavalcade. (Ohio is full of obscure
Division I schools that annually fill out the fringes of the NCAA
bracket just to hassle Washington. Or have you forgotten that
Dayton upset the Huskies of Detlef Schrempf and Chris Welp in the
1984 NCAA tourney's third round?)
</P>
<P>
   Oxford isn't that far from Dayton, or Indianapolis, or
Louisville, but it isn't really anywhere in particular, either. The
school could just as easily be known as Miami of Nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that Miami is part of the Mid-America
Conference, which, despite being 52 years old, has hidden in the
Midwest more successfully than cutting-edge fashion.
</P>
<P>
   While having a fair reputation in football, the MAC in
basketball, aside from 1986 Miami graduate Ron Harper, the Chicago
Bulls guard, doesn't have much to recommend it. Miami has been as
successful in the tourney as any of the 13 MAC schools, and has a
4-17 record.
</P>
<P>
   Friday marks the RedHawks' fourth tourney appearance in the past
eight years. The most startling game came in 1995, when they beat
No. 5 seed Arizona 71-62 in the first round at Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   That may well represent 10th-seeded Miami's
once-every-hundred-years tourney lightning strike. Problem is, as
Szczerbiak noted, conferences such as the MAC, and schools such as
Miami, just don't see players such as UW's 7-foot Todd MacCulloch.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a midmajor conference, we get good guards, but the big
difference is we don't get the 7-foot shot blockers,'' he said.
``(Friday) will be different for us because in our conference, we
match up better using our smaller lineup. Here, we're going to have
to come up with something we've never done before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies, on the other hand, may not have seen anyone quite
like Szczerbiak, not even at Stanford. The MAC Player of the Year,
who led the conference in scoring (23.6 ppg, fifth in the nation),
was second in rebounding (8.6), fourth in field goal percentage
(52.1), third in free throw percentage (82.6) and ninth in 3-point
shooting (34.7 percent). He could well be the most complete player
in the tourney, and NBA scouts project him as a sure first-round
draftee, perhaps even a lottery pick.
</P>
<P>
   It might be that Szczerbiak's decision to attend a smaller
school where he stands out is paying off. It's safe to say that he
has more fame than consonants. After leading the 1998 U.S. Goodwill
Games team in scoring, he has been the darling of the national
media on its annual hunt for the obscure star.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak had a high school teammate who went to a big school
and became lost in the roster, a fate he wanted to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go somewhere where I wouldn't play,'' he
said. ``It's been fun having the attention, but we haven't had much
as a team, so this (game) will be great.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career is perfect, in my mind. There's no other place I'd
rather be.''
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak is among those rare people who got his tough stuff
done in first grade. Dunking over MacCulloch becomes child's play.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
