r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      03-11 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW'S HUARD RESTORING DRAFT STATUS AFTER TOUGH SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The reconstruction of Brock Huard has begun.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a total reclamation project. The University of
Washington quarterback does have NFL size (6-foot-5, 230 pounds)
and one of the strongest _ if not (start ital) the (end ital)
strongest _ arms of any passer in this year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   But there is definitely some patch work to do after Huard's
ill-fated junior season, when his struggles matched those of his
team and the blame was too often pointed at him.
</P>
<P>
   The process continued Thursday when scouts from more than 20 NFL
teams gathered at the UW to watch 17 draft hopefuls run and jump
and lift.
</P>
<P>
   Having already worked out at the scouting combine in
Indianapolis last month, Huard didn't participate in drills _ he
got drilled.
</P>
<P>
   Huard huddled with a scout from one team to talk about reading
defenses, then was whisked away by a scout from another team to
discuss just what happened to the Huskies last season and his role
in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reconstruction, that's a good way to put it,'' said Jon
Kingdon, a scout for the Oakland Raiders. ``Brock had a tough
season, but he'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   After his sophomore season, Huard was considered one of the top
quarterbacks eligible for the draft. Until, that is, he decided to
return for another season with the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a running game and too few NFL-caliber linemen left
Huard to throw and throw and throw, until he was battered and had
developed some bad habits.
</P>
<P>
   Huard didn't, and still doesn't, offer explanations. Instead, he
set about getting better by working with former Seahawks coach Tom
Flores and ex-UW quarterback Hugh Millen to correct some flaws that
developed during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm physically solid right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Huard was very accurate on his medium-range passes,
but still displayed the habit of throwing off his back foot when
serving up the deep ball. He did the same thing at the combine, a
reaction to being repeatedly blasted by blitzing pass rushers.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Demoff, his agent, likens Huard's situation to that of
Dan Marino in 1983. Marino's draft stock slipped his senior season
at Pittsburgh and he was the sixth quarterback selected in the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened to Brock has given him a quiet
determination,'' Demoff said Thursday. ``Some teams won't go past
the obvious. Other teams will. Those teams willing to take the time
to try to find out the answers to what happened to Brock last year
will be rewarded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
