<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GERMAN FINANCE MINISTER RESIGNS IN SURPRISE MOVE
</P>
<P>
   After losing a power struggle over economic policy that had sent
tremors across Europe for months, Germany's left-wing finance
minister and the chairman of its ruling party abruptly resigned
from both jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Oskar Lafontaine marked a stunning turn for
Germany's chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, but it had implications
well beyond Germany. As one of Europe's most combative and
ideological leaders, Lafontaine had almost single-handedly talked
down the value of Europe's new single currency, the euro, with his
loud and unrelenting demands on the European Central Bank for lower
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The euro rose against the dollar as traders said that the
resignation of Lafontaine would ease the economic change that
Europe needs to revive growth.
</P>
<P>
   NO DEAL YET ON OIL PRODUCTION CUTS
</P>
<P>
   Oil ministers from five major oil producing nations met in the
Netherlands in an effort to cut crude oil exports of up to two
million barrels a day, which is aimed at further bolstering the
recent modest recovery in crude oil prices. But the ministers broke
up without issuing a statement and will meet again Friday. Prices
of crude oil have rebounded by about $3.30 a barrel since
mid-February, and production cuts would most likely drive up
gasoline prices, which have been kept low by the oil glut.
</P>
<P>
   NIKE CRITIC APPLAUDS PROGRESS
</P>
<P>
   A prominent critic, who hurt Nike's image when he exposed unsafe
conditions at one of its factories in Vietnam in 1997, issued a
report that gave the footwear giant high marks for improving air
quality at the plant, although he said some problems remained.
</P>
<P>
   NO DEAL SIGNALS TROUBLE FOR NISSAN
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Nissan plunged and the automaker's credit rating fell
after the collapse of its merger talks with DaimlerChrysler. The
failure of the talks signaled serious problems not only for Nissan
but for other auto makers.
</P>
<P>
   Few car companies have been the object of as much unwanted
attention lately as BMW, but the company's executives say they want
to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   ANN TAYLOR PROFIT MISSES ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   Ann Taylor Stores, the women's apparel retailer, said that
fourth-quarter profits were nearly five times greater than a year
earlier but still missed Wall Street estimates. The company posted
net income of $11.8 million, or 42 cents a share, up from $2.4
million, or 9 cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier. Its
shares fell 87.5 cents, to $45.3125.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT TO SHIFT REVENUE
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said it expected to shift $400 million in revenue from
its third quarter to its fourth quarter because of a delay in the
introduction of the next generation of word-processing and
spreadsheet software.
</P>
<P>
   TAKEOVER BATTLES ON EUROPEAN FRONT
</P>
<P>
   Europe's three big hostile-takeover battles veered off into
different directions as investors viewed a three-way French bank
combination as increasingly possible, prospects for an Italian
telephone acquisition seemed to dim and signs of an amicable truce
emerged between two luxury-goods giants.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE SHARES FALL SHARPLY
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Oracle dropped in after-hours trading after the
company reported slower than anticipated software sales. The
company reported third-quarter earnings that essentially matched
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   National Semiconductor posted a less-than-expected loss for its
third quarter and expects a similar loss in the fourth quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
