<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROPAGANDA-POISON:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING AMERICA? TEN REASONS NOT TO INGEST THIS PROPAGANDA
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Gratuitous assertion is the term in English that appropriately
describes an anti-Hispanic video tape from the San Fernando Valley,
Calif.-based Voice of Citizens Together (VCT). It means a
declaration made to prove a point or to argue without objective
proof.
 &HT;    This method of public communication by VCT replicates the
one-sided assault on the senses of the German people during the
'30s by the Nazi Party of Adolf Hitler and propagandist Joseph
Goebbels.
 &HT;    VCT, of course, will cry foul of this comparison, but they can't
deny that their methods are identical, and that they are certainly
ethnically-phobic of Mexican-origin people, much like the Nazis
were of Jews. The proof is in their own words and in this video.
 &HT;    First, this homemade video from the computer of VCT founder,
Glenn Spencer, is a ripoff. Made from snippets of tape from
newscasts, taken out of context and without balance, it first cost
$25.00. The price then dropped to $14.95 and again to $9.95.
Perhaps they were experiencing difficulty selling their hateful
assertions.
 &HT;    Secondly, unsupported statements abound in this video.
 &HT;    For example, 1, we see a picture of an All-American Iowa boy
who, the narrator tells us, was bound for college, that 14 colleges
wanted him to play football, but because of Mexican drug dealers he
was now reporting to a probation officer, not school. Did a Mexican
drug dealer hold a gun to the boy's head to force him to abuse
drugs? No proof.
 &HT;    Example 2a: The narrator tells us that after the Tyson Foods
company of Arkansas posted billboards in Mexico about jobs in
Arkansas ``the illegal alien population (in Arkansas) exploded _
there were five drive-by shootings in one week.'' No numbers, no
arrest reports, nothing. Just the narrator's statement. Many of the
new Mexican-origin people in Arkansas are completely legal, many
born in the United States. They have saved dozens of factories and
revitalized Northwest Arkansas.
 &HT;    Example 2b: Drive-by shootings in the same breath with illegal
aliens, leading the listener to conclude that the shooting were by
these same illegal aliens. But where they? We don't know, because
there is no proof offered. Did Mexican kids shoot up an Arkansas
middle school last year, killing school children?
 &HT;    Example 3: The narrator says, ``The Mexican crime wave spreading
across the West is just a taste of things to come,'' but forgets to
tell us that all crime is down including that of Mexican-origin
people. Fast falling crime rates and a concurrent ``rise in illegal
immigration'' simply don't correlate.
 &HT;    Example 4: ``Mexican immigration is threatening California's
existence as part of America.'' Notice the constant referencing of
their enemies as illegal aliens, immigrants and Mexican immigrants
in an attempt to lump all people of Mexican-origin together into
one mass conspiratorial ``Mexican Nationalist'' cabal. There is no
distinction in the minds of VCT of native-born American citizens of
Mexican-origin, legal or illegal immigrants from Mexico. Moreover
they trash the Constitution by calling the 14th Amendment _ that
declares that all ``persons born'' in the United States are
citizens, regardless of parentage _ a ``legal loophole.''
 &HT;    Example 5: The narrator refers to a 1992 Los Angeles County
sponsored study about illegals as ``since suppressed.'' The truth:
The study was so poorly done (as are many government reports) it
was discarded. It wasn't suppressed.
 &HT;    Example 6: Hispanics (notice the change in label) kill cops just
to see how it feels, the narrator tells us, as we see two young men
with Spanish-surnames arrested for allegedly killing two police
officers. No mention if they were convicted; no mention of any
other cops being killed and by whom. Logical question: Have
non-Hispanic American citizens ever killed a cop? VCT doesn't say.
 &HT;    Example 7: Five million Californians voted to pass Proposition
187 in 1994, the narrator says. He forgot to mention that almost 5
million voted against it because of its fascist wording and
philosophy and that seven judges (six White males and one White
female) enjoined it or declared it unconstitutional.
 &HT;    Example 8: ``Art Torres (the State Democratic Chairman) is an
anti-American, pro-Mexican racist.'' Why? Because the narrator says
he is. Proof? His statement that Prop. 187 was the last gasp of
White America (VCT?) in California.
 &HT;    Example 9: ``Some in California say the term Democrat leader and
traitor are synonymous,'' solemnly declares the narrator. ``Some,''
clearly means Glenn Spencer and the VCT.
 &HT;    Example 10: Los Angeles State Sen. Richard Alarcon has ``very
close ties to the Communist Party,'' the video tells us. Proof: His
sister is a member of the Communist Party. Is he? No. But, thus, he
has ``close ties'' to the Party, according to VCT.
 &HT;    There are at least 50 more examples of deceptive and gratuitous
assertion techniques in this 45-minute videotape. The most
egregious is the constant lumping in together of anyone of
Mexican-origin into this ``invasion,'' as they call it. They
include all immigrants from Mexico, legal and illegal into a giant
invasion and conspiracy to take over California in alliance with
native-born Mexican origin people.
 &HT;    The video refers to all these people, American citizens
included, as a ``cultural cancer that is eating at the very heart
of our nation, American and Western Civilization.''
 &HT;    Substitute the word Jew for Mexican in this video and we
experience a horrible `deja vu' all over again.
 &HT;    VCT and its leader Glenn Spencer claim they will save America
from the ``cultural cancer'' with this videotape, at $9.95. Proof?
Ask them.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
