<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIC-PARTICIPATION-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CLINTON'S CALL FOR CIVIC PARTICIPATION
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By MARK L. KEAM 
 &HT;    (Mark L. Keam is a political observer based in Washington,
D.C.) 
 c. 1999 Koream Journal 
<TEXT>
 &UR; New America News Service &QC;
<P>
   It has been 38 years since John Fitzgerald Kennedy uttered that
famous phrase, ``Ask not what your country can do for you, ask what
you can do for your country.'' With his historic election as the
youngest president of the United States and the first to break the
WASP tradition the charismatic Kennedy inspired an entire
generation of Americans to public service.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1963, an Arkansas teenager had a fateful meeting on the
White House lawn with President Kennedy. That encounter and
handshake with JFK solidified William Jefferson Clinton's own
desire to pursue a career in public service.
</P>
<P>
   Like many baby boomers, President Clinton was strongly motivated
by a combination of his desire to change the world for the better
and to make history for himself. Unfortunately, his impeachment
will guarantee a place in history, even if it is not in the way
Clinton would have wished to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Looking beyond the scandals, however, I am drawn to an aspect of
Clinton's presidency that has often been overlooked: Clinton has
tried to inspire a renewed call for public service. Especially
considering the social climate in this generation of apathy,
cynicism and anti-government sentiment, Clinton strove to engage
all Americans to solve the nation's problems together. And at least
one positive contribution of his presidency will outlast the
negatives.
</P>
<P>
   Some might recall that Bill Clinton and Al Gore campaigned in
1992 on, among other issues, the need for change in the way our
government works. So, as the first baby boomer to reach the White
House, Clinton brought new ideas and energy to the way government
services were delivered to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton believes that the government should provide conditions
and tools to empower people to meet their own challenges.
Therefore, as chief executive officer of the nation, he indeed
tried to make the government a partner to the people, and over the
past six years, many of his cabinet and other agencies created
dozens of new programs to serve the people in ways that were never
tried before.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also knew how to capitalize on human resources. From the
beginning of his administration, Clinton tapped enormous talent
from the private sector, academia, and state and local governments
to bring their expertise and experience into the federal
government. He also placed Gore in charge of ``Reinventing
Government,'' reviewing the efficiency of every agency at the
federal level, and recommending major overhauls. As a result, the
federal government under Clinton became much smaller in workforce
and bureaucracy, but produced better service than before.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect of Clinton's rethinking on the role of government
involved active engagement of the citizenry. Starting with
AmeriCorps, like the Peace Corps, his Kennedy-esque call for
volunteerism; One America _ The President's Initiative on Race; and
his notoriously long, fact-and-data-filled State of the Union
lectures, Clinton has always attempted to nudge the American people
into action.
</P>
<P>
   He also traveled more than other presidents and held hundreds of
townhall meetings, connected with ordinary Americans from all walks
of life, and encouraged children and young Americans to dream big.
</P>
<P>
   Having followed this president closely over the years, I saw
that so much of what Clinton worked for simply did not resonate
with the Korean American (KA) community. Particularly frustrating
is that whenever the president engaged the government to develop
people-friendly programs or initiatives, the KA community failed to
live up to its end of the partnership, like participating in
townhall meetings, even in towns or cities with large KA
populations, or attended White House conferences on issues
important to Korean Americans, or appeared at briefings on the
President's Initiative on Race.
</P>
<P>
   Also, even though the administration appointed more Asian
Pacific Americans to important agencies and positions than any
other president in history, very few Korean Americans ever put
themselves forward to serve in Clinton's government, or even
volunteered in AmeriCorps or other public service programs.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't born when Kennedy was assassinated, so I never had the
opportunity to see or hear the man in person. The current president
of the United States, however, is still around, and regardless of
how some Americans feel, he is still our duly elected leader. And
this president has revived and reissued Kennedy's call for active
civic participation to our generation.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it time for each of us to ask, ``What can I do for my
country?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999 Koream Journal &QL; 
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
</P>
