<HEADER>
A7415 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAINO-INDIANS-NEWAMER     03-11 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAINO-INDIANS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``EXTINCT'' TAINO NATION RECOVERED AND RESTORED
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 By RICK KEARNS 
 c. 1999 Hispanic magazine 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Last November, Puerto Ricans on the island and in the United
States celebrated, protested, or ignored the 505th anniversary of
the ``discovery'' of Puerto Rico by Cristobal Colon (Christofer
Columbus). But on that Fall day in Brooklyn, N.Y.in a large
auditorium, a different gathering took place in contrast to the
controversial holiday.
 &HT;    Men, women, and children in traditional indigenous clothing came
together to sing, dance, feast, and pray as Tainos _ the same
people supposedly eradicated by the conquistadors.
 &HT;    Taino Nation of the Antilles (Nacion Taina de las Antillas) held
its Day of the Taino People to commemorate and celebrate the sixth
anniversary of the restoration of a people thought to be extinct by
most traditional scholars. But Nacion members from the Greater
Antilles and the Unites States feel far from extinct.
 &HT;    The Tainos are the indigenous people of the Greater Antilles _
Puerto Rico, the Dominican Republic, Haiti, and Cuba. According to
most scholarly accounts, the Tainos became extinct in the mid- to
late 16th century because of the genocidal wars of conquest, as
well as from disease and suicide. Some prominent anthropologists,
including Irving Rouse of Yale and Ricardo Alegria of the
University of Puerto Rico, concede that a few Tainos did escape the
Spanish invasion by fleeing to the mountains.
 &HT;    In the last few years, however, members of the Taino Nation and
a growing number of scholars have refuted the extinction theory,
known in Taino circles as the extinction myth. ``We purposefully
chose this day (November 19) for the declaration of the restoration
in 1992,'' asserted Rene Cibanakan Marcano, a chief [kacike or
cacique] of the Taino Nation. ``We are taking it away from Columbus
and using it for this special areito [celebration].''
 &HT;    At the areito held in New York, there were many people who had
never accepted the extinction stories and had kept their feelings
to themselves before finding one another. Nacion members like Nancy
Jawar Lion-Storm had been told as children of their ``Indio''
heritage. But she quickly discovered that there was no one to share
her feelings with. Most people dismissed the idea or were openly
contemptuous of such an assertion. Lion-Storm is the Walnut Creek,
Calif. field office representative of the Cultural Center of the
Taino Nation.
 &HT;    ``I always thought of myself as Puerto Rican Taino,'' Jawar
asserted. ``And throughout my whole life, when I mentioned to other
Puerto Ricans that I was part Taino, they replied that I couldn't
be. They said the Tainos are extinct and we're all a blend. This
same thing happened when I was in college, where professors told me
that I couldn't possibly be Taino. But I knew they were wrong,''
she stated. Jawar kept her eyes and ears open, and on a 1996
research trip to New York she came across a copy of the Nation's
newsletter at the National Museum of the American Indian in
Manhattan. In the Boletin Informativo, started in 1992, she found
her connection.
 &HT;    Announcements and articles published in the Boletin report news
of alliances with other tribes and native nations, and scholarly
articles on the recovery of ancient traditions and language. For
instance, anthropologist Lynne Guitar and archaeologist Peter
Ferbel have provided solid counterarguments to the Taino extinction
theory while writer/activist Jose Barreiro, of the American Indian
Program at Cornell University, emphasizes the living aspects of the
culture.
 &HT;    Ferbel, director of archaeological and anthropological studies
at the Historical Archives of Santiago, Dominican Republic, wrote
``The Politics of Taino Indian Heritage in Post-Quincentennial
Dominican Republic: When a Canoe Means More than a Water Trough''
for his 1995 doctoral dissertation at the University of Minnesota.
In an interview last year, Ferbel expanded on some of his main
points.
 &HT;    ``The indigenous heritage survived principally in the country
(el campo) ... so the culture is there, the race [or bloodline] is
there but not the identity. ... You have people in the Antilles who
live very similarly to Tainos even though they may not make casabe
(cassava bread), but they work the higuiro (calabash) and they
don't say, `I'm Taino,' they say, `I'm Dominican or Puerto Rican or
Cuban.' ... History is often written by the people who won the
wars. In this case it's the Spanish. ... Taino heritage still
exists, it is still strong in the face of incredible adversity,''
Ferbel asserted.
 &HT;    Nation members like Fernando Nixiwei Flores are working on
providing more proof and fortifying the living culture by studying
archaeology and scuba diving, among other things. ``We'll do what
is necessary and it will be a long journey,'' he stated.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Hispanic magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
