 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACK CHURCH: CALLED TO JOIN THE FIGHT AGAINST AIDS. The black
church, which is central to African-American life and historically
a house of refuge, states columnist Bill Maxwell, has turned its
back on one of the groups in greatest need _ people with AIDS.
``Instead of preaching sermons of understanding and compassion and
offering assistance, too many black pastors merely rail and
condemn,'' he writes. ``Simply stated, the black pulpit has
abnegated its responsibilities in dealing with AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-AIDS:BLACK-CHURCH:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   SAVING AMERICA? TEN REASONS NOT TO INGEST THIS PROPAGANDA. An
anti- Hispanic video tape from the San Fernando Valley,
Calif.-based Voice of Citizens Together (VCT) is a propaganda that
one can only compare to that seen and heard in 1930s Germany,
observes columnist Raoul Lowery Contreras. ``The video refers to
people of Mexican-origen, American citizens included, as a
`cultural cancer that is eating at the very heart of our nation,
American and Western Civilization,''' he writes. ``The VCT group is
certainly ethnically-phobic of Mexican-origin people, much like the
Nazis were of Jews,'' he writes. ``The proof is in their own words
and in this video.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-PROPAGANDA-POISON:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL JUSTICE AND ONE SCHOOL'S CATHOLIC CHARACTER. It was
already a done deal on Dec. 1, the day the Board of Fellows _ a
small group of Notre Dame officials entrusted with defining the
school's Catholic character _ unanimously decided not to add the
category of ``sexual orientation'' to the university's
non-discrimination policy, reports columnist Chuck Colbert.
``Nonetheless, more than 100 students staged a three-day hunger
strike, supporting a resolution before the full board of trustees
earlier this month, a proposed policy change that would have banned
discrimination against gays on the South Bend campus,'' he writes.
But they failed to sway the Board.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-NOTRE-DAME-GAY-POLICY:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT CLINTON'S CALL FOR CIVIC PARTICIPATION. Bill Clinton
believes that the government should provide conditions and tools to
empower people to meet their own challenges, notes Mark Keam in
KoreAm Journal. But ``I saw that ... the Korean American community
failed to live up to its end of the partnership, like participating
in townhall meetings, even in towns or cities with large KA
populations, or attended White House conferences on issues
important to Korean Americans, or appeared at briefings on the
President's Initiative on Race,'' he writes. ``Isn't it time for
each of us to ask, `What can I do for my country?'
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-CIVIC-PARTICIPATION-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   ``EXTINCT'' TAINO NATION RECOVERED AND RESTORED. Members of an
Indian Nation thought to be extinct, reclaim their heritage and
celebrate their culture and history. ``I always thought of myself
as Puerto Rican Taino,'' a Nation member told Rick Kearns of
Hispanic magazine. ``And throughout my whole life, when I mentioned
to other Puerto Ricans that I was part Taino, they replied that I
couldn't be. They said the Tainos are extinct ... .'' But the more
she researched, the more she discovered this was not so.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-TAINO-INDIANS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a'' general news
file.
</P>
