<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-MARBURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE COMFORTS OF HOME CAN BE CLINGING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The homecoming Stephon Marbury fantasized about did not include
a tunnel or a turnpike. Sometimes these things don't turn out
exactly the way you wish them to. Marbury, a Coney Island kid who
dreamed of being a Knick, leveraged his way out of Minnesota and a
sure-thing playoff run, and wound up Thursday with the Nets, in New
Jersey, in last place.
</P>
<P>
   He jumped at the chance, anyway, proclaiming on sports talk
radio that, in the final analysis, there's no place like home. ``I
will be signed tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is an emerging star stepping into a dowdy arena on a
shell-shocked team. His parents have a home he purchased for them
in a Baltimore suburb, near his mother's sister, but Marbury's
three older brothers and a sister remain in New York. His
4-year-old daughter lives with her mother in Brooklyn. He has
friends and acquaintances all over, and they will be close enough
to drop by now, to congratulate him on the $70 million he will sign
on for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Some will inevitably come with their hopes up, and hands out.
Queens' Kenny Anderson, who as a Net spent more time hanging out
than he did in midair, could tell Marbury that sometimes these
romantic notions of playing for the home folks don't turn out the
way you wish them to, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it's the best thing for him to come back East
right now,'' said Bob Hartstein, who handed Marbury the ball as a
14-year-old at Brooklyn's Abraham Lincoln High School and watched
him become the sport's purest young point guard. ``From a
basketball point of view, I thought Minnesota was a great place for
him, a good team on the verge of being very good. There were no
distractions. He flourished there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong. He's an intelligent kid, and he's always
been pretty good at blocking things out. But it's a concern. He's
22, with millions of dollars, and you know how many people there
are in this city who are thinking their man is coming home.''
</P>
<P>
   I mentioned to Hartstein that the best line I've ever heard
about those so-called distractions came from Len Elmore a few years
ago, on why he had quit the agent business. With no acknowledgments
to the creators of ``Star Trek,'' Elmore said, ``I got tired of
fighting the cling-ons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And those cling-ons,'' Hartstein said, ``never stop
clinging.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably with that in mind, Marbury's mother, Mabel, preferred
him to remain in Minnesota, with Kevin Garnett, whom he had
befriended a few years ago at a summer camp in Chicago. Garnett was
going straight to the pros from high school and helped talk Marbury
into joining him the following year after just one season at
Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett hooked Marbury up with his agent, Eric Fleisher, who
went to work on draft day and landed Marbury in Minnesota by way of
Milwaukee. Marbury was exultant that night, saying he and Garnett
were going to be the next Stockton and Malone, the brightest stars
in the northern sky, 21st-century money players.
</P>
<P>
   Except Garnett got $126 million and Marbury's hopes for a
competitive deal, an equal partnership, were crushed by the union's
lockout defeat. By the standard of who makes more, which is the
standard that translates to peer-driven status, Minnesota would
always be Garnett's team. So Fleisher was fired, David Falk hired.
Falk told Marbury he could move him to an endorsement-rich market,
and soon. Marbury decided not to wait around another month and a
half to see what the impressive young Timberwolves could become.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a couple of years, that team could have been one of the
best,'' Hartstein sighed.
</P>
<P>
   Falk told Marbury what he wanted to hear, the way Fleisher did
when Marbury was at Georgia Tech, the way Bobby Cremins did when
Marbury was at Lincoln. That is the way it is with the gifted
players. , Hartstein, who doesn't coach anymore, was settled in
front of his television, watching the other basketball madness,
when the news broke of Marbury's trade to the Netskees, partners of
George Steinbrenner, who will need some baseball financing to pay
Marbury, Kerry Kittles and Keith Van Horn. For now, Marbury has
come home to the most expensive 3-victory team in the history of
sports. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
