<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-MERGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MIXED VERDICT ON BIG EUROPEAN MERGERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Europe's three big hostile-takeover battles veered off
into different directions Thursday, as investors viewed a three-way
French bank combination as increasingly possible, prospects for an
Italian telephone acquisition seemed to dim, and signs of an
amicable truce emerged between two luxury-goods giants.
</P>
<P>
   On the Paris Bourse, shares in the three banks involved in a
now-$38 billion hostile bid by Banque Nationale de Paris for its
two French rivals, Societe Generale and Paribas, rose in heavy
trading, as investors appeared to give Banque Nationale's offer a
fighting chance.
</P>
<P>
   In Milan, Franco Bernabe, chief executive of Telecom Italia, the
nation's biggest phone company, announced defensive measures to
repel a $60 billion hostile bid by its major domestic rival,
Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   In the third corporate struggle, the month-old assault by the
big French luxury-goods group LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton for
control of Gucci, the fashion house, appeared headed toward
resolution. Next week, both companies will send representatives to
Amsterdam in an attempt to settle their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci said it was sending its chief financial officer, Robert
Singer, to meet Pierre Gode, a member of LVMH's executive board.
</P>
<P>
   Tempers flared in January, when LVMH, which makes such items as
Louis Vuitton bags and Moet &AMP; Chandon Champagne, amassed 34.4
percent of Gucci, but refused to bid for all the shares and
demanded a seat on Gucci's board.
</P>
<P>
   Defending itself, Gucci issued shares to an employee fund that
diluted the LVMH holding to 25 percent. LVMH took Gucci to court in
the Netherlands, where Gucci is incorporated. The court suspended
both companies' voting rights pending a decision in April.
</P>
<P>
   At next week's meeting, Gucci and LVMH are expected to discuss
ways to insure Gucci's independence. Gucci's chief executive,
Domenico De Sole, has said that a bid by LVMH for the rest of Gucci
would be the preferred solution; barring that, a noninterference
agreement might be negotiable.
</P>
<P>
   Any sign of friendly resolution appeared far off in the two
other takeover fights. In a surprise move on Tuesday night, Banque
Nationale de Paris made its offer for Societe Generale and Paribas,
which had agreed last month to merge.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken by the intrusion, the Paribas board met Thursday night,
reaffirmed its commitment to the Societe Generale merger and called
the Banque Nationale proposal unacceptable. But at least one board
member was known to have favored the Banque Nationale bid _ Claude
Bebear, chairman of the huge French insurance group AXA, which has
significant banking equity holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does an early solution appear likely in the battle by
Olivetti for control of Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts watched trading Thursday in five separate securities _
Olivetti, and ordinary and nonvoting shares in Telecom Italia and
in its mobile phone unit, Telecom Italia Mobile _ and said
investors seemed to be saying that while they were impressed by
Telecom's steps to block Olivetti, they would not be fully
convinced until Bernabe disclosed more details of his industrial
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Bernabe won approval from his board for a
plan to sell assets and raise fresh capital, in order to buy out
the mobile phone company and convert nonvoting shares to common
stock. Estimates varied, but analysts said the moves would raise
Telecom Italia's ordinary share capital to as much as 89 billion
euros, or $97 billion, from 53 billion euros now.
</P>
<P>
   The plan requires shareholder approval, but if successful it
would likely put Telecom Italia beyond the financial reach of
Olivetti. It provoked an angry response from Olivetti's chief
executive, Roberto Colaninno, the quarterback of the hostile bid.
Bernabe's actions, he told reporters, were the ``behavior of a
monopolist,'' and he implied that Bernabe's job would be at stake
if Olivetti triumphed. ``False promises can lead to people getting
fired,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti moved up its plans to next week to present its own
industrial strategy for Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the fireworks, Olivetti shares rose 2.8 percent,
while Telecom's common stock dropped 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Deirdre Ernest, an analyst at the Caboto brokerage house in
Milan, said investors needed ``more input'' from Bernabe about
Telecom's industrial strategy. And while the share price movement
could reflect technical factors, it could also mean that investors
were ``betting Bernabe doesn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, shares in Banque Nationale de Paris rose 7.2 percent
and in Societe Generale, 13.3 percent. The sharpest gains were by
Paribas, which rose 18.1 percent, to 101.55 euros. That evidently
reflected the 18 percent premium Banque Nationale said it would pay
above the offer for Paribas made last month by Societe Generale.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Pebereau, Banque Nationale's chairman, says he wants a
three-way combination to form the world's largest bank, by assets,
but Paribas and Societe Generale reject the offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
