<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-BMW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW CHARTS A NEW COURSE MUCH LIKE THE OLD ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ Few car companies have been the object of
as much unwanted attention lately as BMW AG, the Bavarian company
best known for its muscular but luxurious sedans and sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   First there were the continuing problems at Rover, the British
manufacturer of Land Rovers, MGs and Minis, which BMW bought in
1994 and which may have lost nearly $1 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the feuding and finger-pointing within BMW's top
management, which led to the surprise departures on Feb. 5 of its
chief executive, Bernd Pischetsrieder, and his chief rival on the
board, Wolfgang Reitzl.
</P>
<P>
   Last but not least, there has been the incessant speculation
about BMW as a takeover target. Despite repeated insistence by the
company and its biggest shareholders that the company wants to stay
independent, the conventional wisdom has been that BMW was simply
too small, too desirable and too rattled by management problems to
hold out for long. At a minimum, analysts have argued, the company
needs to trim back Rover or find it a partner.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in their first public appearances since last month's
shake-up, BMW's top executives are firing back. Their message,
delivered here this week at the annual Geneva Motor Show: No need
to change the basic strategy and no need to sell out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great strength of BMW is its independence,'' said Jochim
Milberg, the relatively unknown production chief who took over as
chief executive. ``BMW has the substance, the power and above all
the will'' to chart its own course, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milberg said BMW would continue to invest in Rover, even though
it has already consumed more than $4 billion. The plan assumes that
the British government will contribute more than $200 million to
modernize Rover's big factory in Longbridge, and BMW's total
investment is likely to be several times that much.
</P>
<P>
   BMW also plans to push ahead with new versions of Rover's
midpriced cars, the biggest source of the company's problems.
</P>
<P>
   The new boss did not open himself up to questions, and he left
some big ones unanswered. If BMW's board essentially dismissed
Pischetsrieder because of Rover, what is the new management going
to do differently?
</P>
<P>
   And if BMW wants to compete against the likes of DaimlerChrysler
on everything from subcompacts to luxury limousines, where will it
get the heft to do so? Many analysts have argued BMW is stretching
itself too thin, that it needs to be much bigger to survive on the
thin profit margins available in comparatively inexpensive
mass-market cars.
</P>
<P>
   Helmut Panke, a BMW board member in charge of research and
development, argued that the conventional wisdom was wrong. Rather,
he said, bigger is not necessarily better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about economies of scale,'' he said in an
interview. ``But tell me, where are they?''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Panke said, experts argued that manufacturing
costs were the main reason for companies to get bigger. Instead,
new technology has allowed companies to build factories that reach
their peak efficiency with smaller volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Painting shops used to be at peak efficiency if they had a
volume of about 200,000 cars a year, he said; today, the optimal
volume is less than half that.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is size an inherent advantage in procuring parts or
marketing, Panke argued. Companies use common parts in many
different models, but there are clear limits to the similarities
between a Chrysler Eagle and a Mercedes S-Class. And in marketing,
DaimlerChrysler has itself kept its Mercedes and Chrysler dealer
network separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the 1980s, the big story was diversifying into
aerospace or electronics,'' Panke added. ``But they found that
didn't work either.''
</P>
<P>
   BMW executives admit they have big problems. Though the company
has set a goal of making Rover profitable next year, they admit
that may not happen until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of Rover's current difficulties stems from exchange
rate differences. The British pound soared in value against other
European currencies last year. That made Rover cars much more
expensive in other European countries and severely hurt exports out
of Britain. It also drew in an avalanche of imports, driving down
British car prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Panke and other executives admit that is not the whole
story. So they have abandoned the old strategy of letting Rover
remain as ``British'' and as independent as possible. The new
approach calls for tighter integration of functions like body
design, research and information-processing.
</P>
<P>
   But those are tactical and managerial changes. On the more basic
questions, Milberg is veering little from the path charted by
Pischetsrieder. BMW will still try to offer a full range of cars
and it will not try to rearrange or consolidate its brand names.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that sense, the strategy has been confirmed,'' Panke said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
