<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH HEAVIER HEAVYWEIGHTS, HOLYFIELD'S NO SURE THING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ Even while steadfastly standing by his prediction that
he will knock out Lennox Lewis in the third round at Madison Square
Garden Saturday night, Evander Holyfield's ``the bigger they are,
the harder they fall'' approach doesn't seem to hold much weight.
</P>
<P>
   A look at Holyfield's record against heavyweight opponents who
substantially outweighed him and had a significant height advantage
indicates that Lewis has a good chance of remaining upright
throughout the 12-round bout for the undisputed heavyweight
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the 6-foot-5-inch Lewis can knock out the 6-2 Holyfield
or win a decision is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who has a 6{-inch reach advantage, weighed in Thursday at
246 pounds, against 215 for Holyfield. ``He's a big target,''
Holyfield said on Wednesday at the final news conference before the
fight. ``When a person is a target is when a person can get hit.
What to do? Hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   The 31 pounds is the most Holyfield has given up to an opponent
since he yielded 49 pounds to George Foreman (208 pounds to 257) in
April 1991. Holyfield won a 12-round decision over Foreman, who was
42 years old at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In heavyweight title bouts in which Holyfield (36-3) has given
up 15 pounds or more to his opponent, he is 4-3 with just one
knockout _ a third-round knockout of a grossly out of shape Buster
Douglas (246 pounds) in October 1990 to win the undisputed
championship. The three other victories were all in 12-round
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   One of Holyfield's three losses was an eighth-round technical
knockout to Riddick Bowe in November 1995. Bowe weighed 240 pounds
for that bout and Holyfield 213. It was the last time Holyfield
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's camp is not worried about the weight and size
differential against Lewis. ``Joe Louis gave up a lot of weight to
Primo Carnera,'' Don Turner, Holyfield's trainer, said. ``What does
it matter?''
</P>
<P>
   When boxing fans talk about Holyfield's trouble with larger
heavyweights, they typically refer to his bouts against Bowe,
against whom he went 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   In their first fight, in November 1992, the tall Bowe was a
young, strong heavyweight with an outstanding jab. The questions
about him involved his stamina and desire. This is the fight on
Holyfield's resume that most closely resembles his match against
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield weighed 205 pounds for that first Bowe fight and Bowe
235. Lou Duva, Holyfield's co-trainer at the time, said he and his
teammate George Benton had scripted the perfect plan for Holyfield,
which involved staying away from Bowe's strong jab.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told him to circle him, jab and move,'' Duva said. ``But as
soon as he got hit, he went toe-to-toe with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield lost a 12-round decision. But it was the fight that
defined Holyfield as a warrior. After getting pummeled by Bowe in
the 10th round and looking out on his feet, Holyfield rallied with
a barrage of punches that stunned Bowe.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' trainer, Emanuel Steward, who guided Holyfield to a
victory in his second fight against Bowe in 1993, said that he and
Lewis had not really concentrated on the Bowe-Holyfield fights,
because Bowe fought more of an inside fight against Holyfield.
Steward said he did not expect Lewis (34-1) to stay inside against
Holyfield.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990311.0484 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7434 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BOOKS-ART-2TAKES-     03-11 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO APPROACHES TO TAX RESENTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of business best-sellers is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14)  
 (af)  
 By DEBORAH STEAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One is respectable, one irreverent. But appropriately enough,
this being tax season, two quite different books are asking the
same question: How can we keep more of our money for ourselves?
</P>
<P>
   For one of the authors, Amity Shlaes, an editorial writer for
The Wall Street Journal, the answer is to reform the tax system.
For the other, a high-profile private investigator, the solution is
simpler: flee it.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Greedy Hand: How Taxes Drive Americans Crazy and What
to Do About It'' (Random House, $22.95), Ms. Shlaes argues that we
are being taxed as never before in peacetime history and are thus
hobbled both at home and at work.
</P>
<P>
   To show that the system is chaotic and burdensome, Ms. Shlaes
uses illustrations from everyday life, from marriage and babies to
schools and shopping. But despite her highly readable prose and a
good eye for historically interesting detail, the author often
fails to be persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that she is ideologically stubborn; conservative views
underpin the book, yet it is not a mere polemic. The problem is
that while Ms. Shlaes complains that the tax system is Procrustean,
she too often tortures her own examples into the service of a
point.
</P>
<P>
   In a chapter titled ``Your Clothes,'' for example, she cites the
crowds at Mall of America near Minneapolis, a tax-free shopping
center-cum-amusement park, as shocking proof of just how far people
will go to avoid a sales tax. But what about our well-known
national proclivity toward recreational shopping, which the Mall of
America surely satisfies?
</P>
<P>
   In ``Your Accountant,'' an otherwise interesting and unusual
glimpse into H&AMP;R Block, she charts the rise of this street-corner
chain and concludes that its success is a result of the hopeless
muddle of tax rules and the misery of the average taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with ``Your Baby,'' a chapter that discusses the
so-called nanny tax, the rule that people must make Social Security
and other payments on behalf of some household employees. It's one
thing to argue that this is an onerous, and widely ignored,
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Shlaes again stretches the point to conclude that the
reason day care chains like Kindercare Learning Centers have done
so well is that ``parents are so eager to shift the burden of the
nanny laws onto someone.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same reductionist manner, she blames the tax system for
the shortage of good day care centers in this country. Where some
might see the lack of a national consensus over child care's future
as the main cause, Ms. Shlaes sees a reluctance among potential
operators to ante up their share of Social Security and other
payments in a labor-intensive business.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean that Ms. Shlaes has no ammunition. She smartly
skewers the Internal Revenue Service for announcing last year that
any fan catching Mark McGwire's record-breaking home run ball might
be taxed on its hefty market value. (The IRS quickly backed off
what she calls this ``tax on joy.'')
</P>
<P>
   And she recounts, with appropriate revulsion, a grieving
parent's receipt of an IRS letter in the wake of his son's death in
the 1988 crash of a Pan Am jet in Lockerbie, Scotland. (The letter
was sent to alert survivors that any settlement award from the
airline would be taxed.)
</P>
<P>
   She also knows how to draw a wince, reporting that Americans on
average now have to toil until May 10 just to pay their taxes for
the year, according to the Tax Foundation, a research organization
based in Washington. (It was Jan. 31 in 1902, March 8 in 1940 and
May 2 in 1974.)
</P>
<P>
   Her chapters on ``Your Retirement'' and ``Your Death'' make some
solid points, too. Estate taxes _ even with the new $1 million
floor _ undermine family businesses, she asserts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she says, they rank second only to the death of the
founder as the main culprit in the failure of such enterprises in
the second generation, according to the American Family Business
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   And she has a flair for historical accounts, especially the
story of Beardsley Ruml, the former Macy's official who in 1942
came up with the idea of withholding income tax. A retailer at
heart, he called it a ``pay-as-you-go'' plan. Ms. Shlaes refers to
it as a ``bait and switch'' ploy that was aimed at masking how much
people were paying in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   We're still paying too much, she says, calling for self-managed
Social Security accounts and taxes that are easier on the
productive middle and upper classes. And, of course, individual tax
rates should be lower _ no higher than 25 percent at the federal
level.
</P>
<P>
   The second book rails against taxes, too. But its author, Edmund
J. Pankau, a high-profile private investigator, posits that the
choices are simply to ``pay up or bug out.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hide Your Assets and Disappear'' (Regan
Books/HarperCollins, $22), Pankau, who has had both the hunters and
the hunted as clients, gives detailed advice on everything from
getting a new identity to leaving the country without leaving a
trail.
</P>
<P>
   The book details how to change your appearance, in which
countries you can stage your phony death for a fee, complete with
newspaper coverage, and which financial trackers are to be feared.
(Hint: The private sector can be more relentless than government.)
</P>
<P>
   The author also offers a kind of Baedeker guide to potential
``host'' countries, complete with tables rating banking services,
extradition rules and weather. ``It's hard to beat Latin America,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Pankau warns that if you really intend to ``disappear'' into
another country with your assets, you can't give in to homesickness
and return _ or make long-distance calls to those you left behind.
The same goes for a new identity. Once you have it, you must live
it, he counsels.
</P>
<P>
   One way to get that new identity, he writes, is to visit a local
cemetery to find a dead soul who would be about your age if he or
she were alive today. The idea is to get a driver's license, Social
Security card and passport using a copy of the dead person's birth
certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the graveyard trick has been known and used for a
long time, many states will still send you a birth certificate
without trying to verify the identity of the person making the
request,'' the author writes. He does add a reminder that obtaining
government documents for fraudulent purposes is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   All the advice is backed by what seems to be field-tested
research. Pankau is experienced; he has hunted down white-collar
bank crooks and reached other criminals' hidden assets. But the
tough-guy tone deteriorates at times into immaturity. (Women are
either babes or hideous ex-wives; the IRS is the ``infernal''
revenue service.)
</P>
<P>
   And the numerous copy editing lapses are disconcerting. It's
difficult to take breathtakingly risky advice from a book that
refers to the Unabomber, Theodore ``Kazinsky,'' the South American
country ``Columbia'' and ``Jonny Cochoran,'' that famous lawyer who
defended O.J. Simpson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-99 2325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
