<HEADER>
A7436 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV14     03-11 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY BONUS IS SMALLER THAN YOURS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Ohio)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I am a manager at a company that regularly uses cash
rewards and other recognition to single out employees for
outstanding work. The program was a big morale builder in my group,
until word got around that the winners in the marketing department
received much more money than those in other departments, including
ours. (It was news to me, too.) Short of getting the president to
balance the awards, which he has so far refused to consider, how
can I relieve my staff's resentment and restore the incentives'
effectiveness?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Ouch. You have been put in an ugly, uncomfortable position _
and the damage control will probably require a combination of
sympathy, creativity and brutal honesty.
</P>
<P>
   First, the painful reality: ``The marketplace doesn't see all
functions as being equal in terms of bonus levels,'' said Kenan
Abosch, compensation business leader for Hewitt Associates, a human
resources consulting firm based in Lincolnshire, Ill. Bonuses tend
to vary among departments, just as budgets and salaries do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not feel good, but part of it has to do with the
company's philosophy,'' Abosch said. At a consumer products
company, for example, marketing often gets more attention and
resources than it does at an engineering firm.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure you understand the issue, sit down with your boss
and ask him to explain the reasons for the disparity. It may be
that marketing hands out fewer bonuses, or that its criteria are
tougher. Or the marketing staff may contribute so much to the
company's bottom line that the company will do anything to keep
them happy.
</P>
<P>
   Next, in the gentlest way possible, try to help your employees
see the logic of this policy. They may not necessarily agree with
it, but at least it won't seem so arbitrary.
</P>
<P>
   To help ease the sting, try to shift your employees' focus to
the broader marketplace, advised Jorg Kasparek, compensation and
benefits vice president for NCR in Dayton, Ohio. In other words,
forget what the clowns in marketing are making and ask a different
question: What kinds of bonuses are people receiving in departments
like yours at other companies?
</P>
<P>
   If you find that your employer lags behind the market norm, you
can use the research to lobby for more money. If your company isn't
behind the curve, you can try supplementing the rewards program
with other, though smaller, incentives.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Abosch said, the real value of periodic spot bonuses
lies not so much in their size as in their immediacy, as well as in
the recognition they confer. As such, rewarding employees with
pizza parties, movie passes or gift certificates can bolster morale
without breaking your budget.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, a free pizza can't take the place of an extra-fat bonus
check. Such a gesture could even be derided as a sop. But any
additional effort you put forth on your staff's behalf can help
soothe their wounded egos and show them that someone is on their
side. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y.
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
