<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CURRENCY-CONTROLS-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATAL ATTRACTION
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By JIM FREER 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MIAMI _ Imagine Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
piling stacks and stacks of dollars on the front lawn of the
Palacio de Planalto, his official residence in Brasilia, dousing
them with gasoline, and torching roughly US$35 billion. The scene
is a crass simplification of the country's mighty fight during the
past year to avoid a devaluation of the Real, but Cardoso had spent
that much of the country's reserves by the middle of January to
support an exchange rate policy that the market simply would not
buy.
 &HT;    Wrong move, say analysts and economists. As Brazil and other
Latin American nations brush up on their crisis management skills,
financial professionals who monitor Latin America say the key to
minimizing future outbreaks lies in establishing sound economic
policies, such as a realistic exchange rate. Above all, the pundits
say, governments should avoid the temptation to try to control
capital flows with restrictions on foreign currency transactions.
 &HT;    Regional riptide. Such steps do not contain all outflows and
they can scare domestic and foreign investors, says Bertus Meins,
the Inter-American Development Bank's regional economic adviser for
Mexico and Central America. Latin America is unable to
realistically impose controls because the region has ``become more
and more a part of the world's trading environment,'' he says.
 &HT;    Moreover, the region cannot afford to put obstacles in the path
of capital flows. According to the Institute of International
Finance, a research group based in Washington, D.C., net capital
flows to Latin America will fall by roughly a third to just under
$70 billion in 1999. The group expects private creditors, such as
banks and other financial institutions, to pull back in a big way
to reduce exposure, slowing lending down from to an estimated $42
billion in 1998 to little more than $10 billion this year.
 &HT;    To turn the tide, Latin American governments will have to woo
investors back with privatizations, independent central banks, and
reductions in budget and trade deficits to a point where they can
be financed domestically, says Thomas Trebat, managing director of
emerging markets at U.S. investment bank Salomon Smith Barney. He
says that the cycle ``begins with Latin American governments taking
measures to please domestic investors.'' He adds, ``You need
capital from abroad, but if we see Brazilians moving money out of
the country, not buying stocks and not rolling over government
bonds, why should foreigners not do the same?''
 &HT;    Foreigners, especially the so-called ``hot money'' managers who
deal in assets like stocks that are easily sold, may be just doing
the same as the locals, but their actions tend to do more damage
and receive more attention.
 &HT;    Chilean controls. The IDB's Meins and numerous other analysts in
the United States and throughout Latin America feel that some
countries could lessen the boom-bust cycle by setting reserve
requirements on inflows.
 &HT;    The most cited example is Chile, which in 1991 began requiring
foreign investors to put $20 in a one-year, non-interest bearing
account with the Central Bank for each $100 invested in Chilean
stocks and bonds. Investors who sold securities in less than a year
would receive their gains but would forfeit the funds in the
account. For most of the 1990s, capital flowed into the country
without huge, abrupt ebbs.
 &HT;    The lack of major bouts of capital flight, however, may have
more to do with Chile's strong and orderly economic performance
than the reserve requirements on inflows. When the economy stalled
last year, some $975 million fled the country through the first 10
months of 1998, according to Chile's Central Bank.
 &HT;    Foreign investors leaving the country accounted for about 95
percent of the capital flight, says Valentin Carril, Santander
Investment's chief economist in Santiago. In September, the
government finally scrapped the reserve requirement for foreign
investment. While Carril believes that the requirements did help to
prevent large swells in capital flows to some degree, he notes that
even well-run Chile cannot afford to put any obstacles in the way
of investment. ``There has been a need to attract capital,'' Carril
says.
 &HT;    For countries, like Brazil, where authorities are still
struggling to get the basic macroeconomic indicators under control,
instituting any sort of restrictions on foreign currency
transactions would probably be as effective as trying to put out a
fire with gasoline. As ably demonstrated by Brazil's President
Cardoso in recent months, when policymakers try to control capital
flows or exchange rates, they usually get burned.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</TEXT>
