<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST GAMBLES ON RICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Sixty-one wins and the wrong end of a playoffs sweep
wasn't good enough for the Lakers, so they traded their starting
point guard and hired a veteran replacement. That wasn't enough, so
they hired the best rebounder in the NBA and fired their coach.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't enough either, nor was a nine-game winning streak,
so on Thursday, the Lakers introduced the next (and final?) piece
of their drive for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all the pieces to the puzzle, we just have to go out
and do it,'' said new Laker and puzzle solver Glen Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-changing face of the Lakers morphed once more with the
swap of All-Star Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell to Charlotte for
sharpshooter Rice and J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   It was, even in the words of Lakers executive vice president
Jerry West, a risk.
</P>
<P>
   Starting tonight, the Lakers will see what that gamble nets
them. They have exchanged Jones' defense and transition-game
fireworks for Rice's dead-on 3-point shooting, instantly improving
their half-court game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to bring us a dimension that we feel we have not
had here in a long, long time, maybe since Byron Scott,'' West
said.
</P>
<P>
   And although this was not a trade players enthusiastically
embraced when it was announced 24 hours earlier, still stung by the
loss of Jones, the Lakers are hopeful Rice will open up the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought (O'Neal) was definitely one of the big
guys in the league that is pretty much impossible to stop,'' Rice
said, ``and teams have been double-teaming. Now I don't think
they're gonna want to do that as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kobe Bryant, a slasher who should also benefit from Rice's
presence, ``what that does is it makes us even more dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   For O'Neal, it's another wish come true. He demanded a
``thuggish rebounder'' and got Dennis Rodman. He ached for a
3-point shooter to draw away the extra defenders, and now he has
Rice.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't already true, anything short of a championship now
will certainly be deemed a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ain't no excuses now,'' O'Neal said. ``Now we should
really push to go all the way. We've got a lot of veterans here, so
everybody's hungry. We have a lot of great players, a lot of great
talent, we've got some deadly shooters. There should be no excuse
now.''
</P>
<P>
   And no competition for the ball, vowed Rice, Bryant and O'Neal,
the three top offensive threats. O'Neal said he'll gladly give up
shots, Bryant said he's not worried and Rice said he's fine
dropping from the first to third option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very comfortable with that,'' Rice said. ``I'm comfortable
with the thought of my chances of getting a ring as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte came calling with this trade weeks ago, but the Lakers
did not immediately jump on it, despite Rice's status as one of the
league's top shooters. And with the optimism surrounding his
arrival, there remain legitimate concerns over what they gave up in
continuity, chemistry and Jones' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I wouldn't say (all the changes are) necessary
because we got to the Western Conference finals, but to get over
the hump, to be a championship team I guess they felt we needed to
make the changes,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   So a different team, yes. And improved one?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be debated, for the rest of the season,'' said
Rick Fox. ``We won't drop off, if anything. Whether we are better
remains to be seen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
