A7455 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN     03-11 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE WON'T HAVE TO ELBOW FOR TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Glen Rice practiced with his new teammates for the
first time Thursday, and there was only one word to describe the
hailstorm of 3-pointers he poured through the Forum nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pure,'' Derek Harper said. ``He looked like a pure shooter. He
can shoot the ball, man. You enjoy watching a guy like that shoot.
I like to think I'm a pretty good shooter, but I'm a poor man's
version of Glen Rice.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice will be in uniform tonight and playing significant minutes,
though not necessarily starting yet. He hasn't played since last
season, but Rice said he's kept in shape by running, and his elbow
is 100 percent healed after undergoing arthroscopic surgery in late
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked very good,'' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``I don't think
he's in game shape, but with the time he's gonna be getting, he
soon will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Here to stay: Rice was only the latest star to leave Charlotte
over money, the Hornets unwilling to pay him the $10-$14 million he
wants in a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Rice and Lakers executive vice president Jerry West both
said the plan was for Rice to retire a Laker.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers will pay him their share of a prorated $5.4 million
this season and have a $7 million option for 1999-2000, but figure
to give him a contract extension this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Laker, and I would like to hang my shoes up here,'' the
31-year-old Rice said. ``This is a great organization, and I would
love to be a part of that until it's time to call it quits. And
hopefully get a couple rings in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice admitted he initially wanted a trade to Miami, his original
team, or Orlando, in order to remain close to his wife, newborn
daughter and extended family. But he dropped his opposition to
playing in California in exchange for the shot at a title, then got
extra encouragement when Shaquille O'Neal called a couple weeks
back and lobbied for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``(That) made me feel more comfortable,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Missing: Robert Horry didn't make it to Thursday's practice in
order to fly home to Houston and attend to undisclosed personal
matters. He is expected back in time for tonight's home game
against Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had permission from me,'' Rambis said. ``He told me he had
some stuff he needed to do. I believe in that, if a player's got a
lot of business to take care of and family matters to take care of,
if they can go see their family, I think that helps free up a
player's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Reid, traded with Rice, missed his morning flight and did
not make practice. He was expected in town by late afternoon and
will be in uniform tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
