<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WEST-NYT &LR;      03-11 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL HITS MINNESOTA AND GONZAGA PROVIDES THE KNOCKOUT PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Minnesota's 75-63 loss to Gonzaga officially occurred
mid-afternoon Thursday here, but the fate of the Golden Golphers
might have been determined several hours earlier when the school's
basketball program imploded because of an academic scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Back east in Minneapolis five hours before game time, four
Golden Gophers players _ starters Kevin Clark and Miles Tarver and
reserves Antoine Broxsie and Jason Stanford _ were declared
ineligible by the university president, Mark Yudof, in response to
academic misconduct allegations.
</P>
<P>
   In an article published in Wednesday's editions of The Saint
Paul Pioneer Press, a former university employee said that she had
written papers for past and current athletes, with four former
players confirming her story.
</P>
<P>
   Tenth-seeded Gonzaga, the West Coast Conference champion from
Spokane, can now celebrate its first tournament victory and prepare
for second-seeded Stanford, which struggled before pulling away
from Alcorn State, 69-57. Minnesota and its coach, Clem Haskins,
now go home to face the investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``You prepare all week and all of a sudden they slap you in the
face and you can't play your starters,'' Haskins said after the
loss. ``To me, life goes on. You make adjustments. Our team played
hard and I'm proud of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss concluded a trying 48 hours for Minnesota. Clark, a
senior guard and the team's No. 2 scorer at 14.7 points a game,
suffered a seizure on the flight to Seattle on Tuesday. On
Wednesday, the day the allegations were published, Kyle Sanden
sprained his ankle in practice. By the time the game started,
Minnesota was down to eight players.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the bench in warm-ups were Clark, Tarver, a senior
forward who led the team in rebounding at 7.1 per game; Broxsie, a
sophomore center who had played in all 27 games this season, and
Stanford, a senior reserve forward. By game's end, two more
Minnesota players had fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with Minnesota's Quincy Lewis, the Big Ten scoring champion,
swarmed by Gonzaga's defense, a redshirt walk-on freshman helped
put the Golden Gophers back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Rychart, who averaged only eight minutes a game during the
season, finished with a team-high 23 points as Minnesota cut the
lead to 2 points with 1 minute 43 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The players were ruled ineligible Thursday following an
investigation by the university's general counsel and its NCAA
compliance officer.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's article in The Pioneer Press quoted a former office
manager, Jan Gangelhoff, as saying she wrote papers, did take-home
exams and other course work for the four current players and at
least 16 former players. The newspaper also quoted four former
players as confirming that work was prepared for them in possible
violation of the student code of conduct and NCAA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   STANFORD 69, ALCORN STATE 57
</P>
<P>
   Second-seeded Stanford withstood a furious second-half rally by
undersized but persistent Alcorn State. Forward Mark Madsen led the
Cardinal with 23 points and 13 rebounds, 16 of the points in the
first half when the Cardinal appeared headed for an expected rout. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA 75, PENN 61
</P>
<P>
   Florida, seeded sixth in the regional, methodically erased a
13-point deficit and pulled away to defeat the Ivy League champion.
The youthful Gators utilized a balanced scoring attack, led by the
freshman forward Mike Miller's 15 points. Freshman guard Teddy
Dupay had 13 and the junior guard Kenyan Weaks had 11. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
