<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-11 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NISSAN-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-11 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES OF NISSAN PLUNGE AND ITS CREDIT RATING FOLLOWS SUIT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Shares of Nissan plunged Thursday and the automaker's
credit rating fell after the collapse on Wednesday of its merger
talks with DaimlerChrysler AG. The failure of the negotiations
signaled serious problems not only for Nissan but also for many
other automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in the Nissan Motor Co. fell 11 percent in Tokyo
Thursday, while shares of its truck-building unit, Nissan Diesel,
dropped 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Service downgraded Nissan's credit rating
Thursday to junk-bond quality while Standard &AMP; Poor's, another
rating agency, said it was prepared to lower Nissan's rating to
junk-bond status, too, but would wait for the outcome of Nissan's
efforts to raise money by selling a stake to Renault of France.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of Nissan's merger talks with DaimlerChrysler
underlined how difficult it was to achieve real consolidation in
the global automotive industry and made it likely that the industry
would continue to be plagued by excess factory capacity for years
to come.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the talks said Thursday that a key sticking
point was Nissan's reluctance to give full management control to
DaimlerChrysler, which might have allowed it to close excess
factories in Japan, lay off workers and drastically cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   The big mergers that have taken place over the last year _
Daimler-Benz AG's takeover of the Chrysler Corp. and the Ford Motor
Co.'s pending purchase of the car operations of Volvo AB _ have
combined successful automakers that did not need to close any
assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   But these transactions did nothing to address the auto
industry's biggest problem: the world's consumers buy only 50
million cars and light trucks a year, yet there are enough assembly
plants worldwide to build 75 million vehicles a year. And new
factories are opening practically every month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deals that have occurred so far are really to grow the
business and not to pare the business,'' said Michael E. Robinet,
the director of forecast services at CSM Worldwide Inc., an auto
consulting firm in Farmington Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Without commenting on the details of DaimlerChrysler's aborted
plans for Nissan, Juergen E. Schrempp, DaimlerChrysler's
co-chairman, hinted in an interview Thursday that the resistance of
Nissan's managers to losing control had been an issue.
DaimlerChrysler had been reluctant to accept a compromise that
would have given it only 25 percent of Nissan now and deferred any
DaimlerChrysler control of the company until later, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempp also said that DaimlerChrysler had become concerned
about the difficulties of embarking on another big merger so soon
after last November's combination of Daimler-Benz and Chrysler.
``We would have been overstretched,'' Schrempp said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   International auto industry mergers face huge political and
cultural obstacles because automakers tend to be symbols of
national strength. The political obstacles can become
insurmountable when, as in the case of DaimlerChrysler and Nissan,
the merger is likely to entail closing factories and dismissing
thousands of workers.
</P>
<P>
   While Nissan has also been in talks with Renault, those talks
have reportedly involved a smaller equity stake in Nissan and
relatively little loss of control for its Japanese managers.
</P>
<P>
   Even when weak automakers are bought, few factories are closed.
Korea's Kia Motors was auctioned last year after its excessive
expansion and factory construction left it insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   But while Ford bid for Kia and would have been likely to cut its
costs somewhat, the winning bidder was Hyundai, another Korean
automaker that has emphasized rapid growth, sometimes ahead of
profits.
</P>
<P>
   European automakers are not immune. BMW of Germany is struggling
because it did little to cut costs in Britain's struggling Rover
unit after taking it over in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a merger with DaimlerChrysler increases the pressure
on Nissan to undertake a more ambitious cost-cutting program than
anything it has tried so far. Nissan said in a statement Thursday
that it was ``taking additional measures such as reviewing and
cutting domestic production capacity'' in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto analysts think that DaimlerChrysler would also have
found it hard to reduce Nissan's costs. ``You can't rule out the
possibility that if less equity is given to Nissan, they'll have to
close capacity quicker because they'll have more financial
distress,'' said Scott F. Merlis, an auto analyst at Wasserstein
Perella Securities Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's distress could become worse in the coming months. David
S. Andrews, a senior vice president for corporate finance at
Moody's, said that Nissan's debt might be downgraded even further
if it did not reach an alliance with Renault.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, Nissan said the downgrading would not pose a
problem because the company had increased its cash on hand and had
set up lines of credit, including a $700 million line extended by
the Japanese government, which is worried about the problems at one
of Japan's biggest employers. The company criticized Moody's
decision, saying that it would have no problem financing its
activities even in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrews said that competition was so tough in the auto
industry that it would be hard for an already weakened automaker
like Nissan to improve its profitability.
</P>
<P>
   The world has too many factories making small and midsized cars,
and Nissan and Renault mainly compete in these overcrowded and
usually unprofitable segments. Nissan has been weak in the world's
two strongest auto market segments _ sport utility vehicles in the
United States and luxury cars worldwide _ while Renault does not do
business in the United States and is only just now entering the
luxury market.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly because of the strength of sport utility vehicle and
pickup truck sales here, Ford and DaimlerChrysler separately raised
their forecasts Thursday for total car and light truck sales in the
United States this year, predicting that this would be one of the
strongest years ever. DaimlerChrysler's profitable Jeeps and
Mercedes cars would have made it a financially stronger potential
partner for Nissan than Renault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
