<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS FAIL TO MAKE DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NBA's trading deadline rolled past Thursday,
and the Clippers avoided driving away with a lemon off the NBA's
used player lot.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not like that 0-17 start failed to remind them that a
change or two wouldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   One league source said the Clippers attempted to close a deal
that would have sent Lorenzen Wright and Pooh Richardson to
Portland in exchange for deluxe shooting guard Isiah Rider. The
Blazers, looking for inside depth from Wrigh, have Jim Jackson
playing behind Rider. But Rider stopped being trade bait when his
inspired play helped Portland rise to the top of the Pacific
Division. The Blazers changed their minds about that deal 10 days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another near-miss trade would have delivered power forward Chris
Gatling and salary-cap throw in Brian Evans from New Jersey. But
that pair joined Sam Cassell in a three-way deal that sent them to
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The next deadline arrives Saturday, when teams either must have
offered contract extensions to their own players or wait until July
1 to tender an offer. (Or not make an offer.) Clippers currently
cashing paychecks in the final year of their contracts include
Wright, Lamond Murray, Rodney Rogers, Eric Piatkowski, Stojko
Vrankovic, Darrick Martin, Sherman Douglas and rookie free agent
Tyrone Nesby.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers are not expected to offer any extensions this week.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead `Mo' money
</P>
<P>
   One Clipper who will have a year remaining on his current deal
when this season ends is second-year forward Maurice Taylor.
Taylor, who has played his way up to the status of
star-on-training-wheels, hasn't ruled out re-signing with the
Clippers when they make their re-enlistment pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not exactly a lock to stay put, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be against that,'' said Taylor when presented with
the hypothetical prospect of signing a six-year deal for maximum
loot. ``A lot depends on what other changes are made between now
and then. I'm still going to keep my options open, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was referring to roster adjustments that could make
winning a bit easier than it is now. At their current rate, the
Clippers should have a lovely shot at the first pick in this year's
draft. And while underclassmen aren't eligible for selection until
they declare themselves available by sending a letter to the
league, Taylor's vote goes to Rhode Island freshman Lamar Odom.
</P>
<P>
   Odom is a 6-foot-10 playmaking southpaw best classified as a
``point forward.'' According to scuttlebutt around the league, Odom
is expected to enter the draft, despite recent reports that he
hasn't completely ruled out staying at Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clippers' personnel team continues to evaluate
potential lottery selections, they are committed to retaining
Taylor ... owner permitting.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead Old hands for Kings
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento Kings brought several familiar faces to the
Sports Arena. The active roster included center Vlade Divac, who -
prior to duty with the Charlotte Hornets - bridged the Lakers'
center gap between Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Kings assistant coach Byron Scott was drafted by the Clippers in
1983, pouted his way into a trade to the Lakers, and now has three
NBA championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   Two other assistant coaches became popular thanks to March
Madness. Steve Fisher directed Michigan to the NCAA crown in 1989
after Bill Frieder was chased off the bench for having agreed to
coach at Arizona State the following season.
</P>
<P>
   Former Princeton coach Pete Carril is remembered for leading the
Tigers through the back door and into a first-round upset of UCLA
in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
