<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE CALLS PLAYERS-ONLY MEETING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ROGER PHILLIPS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ In nine seasons with the Kings, Rob Blake
had never called a players-only meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With the Kings coming off an important victory over Detroit two
days earlier but still seven points behind San Jose and Edmonton
for the final Western Conference playoff berth with 17 games
remaining, the Kings' captain concluded the time was right.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Blake declined to discuss details of the
meeting, saying, ``What happens in the room belongs in the room. It
really concerns the 25 guys in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake admitted calling the meeting was difficult, and added,
``It's probably 50 games too late. We won a game, but we might as
well have lost because we didn't move anywhere in the standings
(San Jose also won Tuesday night). I'll tell you at the end of the
year if I was too late or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Tuesday morning's skate before the Detroit game, Blake
approached Coach Larry Robinson and told him he wanted to call a
meeting. Robinson said he was pleased to see Blake take the step.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unlike myself in that we don't like doing those
things, yet it's our job to sometimes stand up and maybe hurt a few
feelings, say what you really feel,'' Robinson said. ``You're put
in a position of taking responsibility and giving responsibility.
I've said all along that I thought he's matured more this year than
he has in the past few years and this is just another example of
his maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first thing is to get over the fear of hurting
somebody's feelings or the fear of maybe not thinking you're worthy
of doing what you're doing. I think that's all part of maturing and
becoming a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 17 games will reveal whether Blake was able to get
through to his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a speech like that,'' center Ian Laperriere said.
``We know we've been playing awful for most of the year. Blakey
said, `Great game against Detroit. But we didn't win the Stanley
Cup, we didn't get back in the playoffs, and it doesn't mean
anything if we start losing again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Peter Demers said wingers Vladimir Tsyplakov (knee
injury) and Steve McKenna (abdominal injury) have medical clearance
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Status quo (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Steve Duchesne, who has struggled most of the season
after signing a three-year, $11.25-million contract as a free
agent, was a healthy scratch Tuesday against Detroit, and may not
be in the lineup for Saturday's home game against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're asking me right now,'' Robinson said after
Thursday's practice, ``I'll probably go with the same lineup (as
Tuesday). You're not going to get a better 60 minutes than we
played the other night. If it ain't broke, don't fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked following Tuesday's game why he'd scratched Duchesne,
Robinson said, ``He's still not willing to pay the price to make a
play. We can't afford to wait. We've got to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
